<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMP-DAVID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RENDEZVOUS AT CAMP DAVID  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, July 6:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's convening of a summit meeting between
Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak, and the Palestinian leader,
Yasser Arafat, next week will usefully quicken the pace of Mideast
peace negotiations two months ahead of the deadline both sides have
set for a final agreement. As Clinton noted Wednesday, standing
still is not an option in the quest for Middle East peace. Like
Prime Minister Menachem Begin of Israel and President Anwar Sadat
of Egypt when they gathered at Camp David at President Carter's
invitation 22 years ago, Barak and Arafat must summon the courage
to make difficult compromises or risk losing a historic opportunity
to end the half-century-old conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has long sought such a meeting, believing it could help
hold together his fractious Cabinet and revive a negotiating
momentum that has been ebbing. Wednesday's resignation threat by
Interior Minister Natan Sharansky underscored Barak's problems.
Arafat also recognizes that only the two top leaders can make the
decisions necessary for peace. But he had argued that more
groundwork needed to be laid in lower-level talks before a useful
summit meeting could be held.
</P>
<P>
   Those lower-level talks have now reached their limit. Forward
movement has stalled, leaks about possible Israeli territorial
concessions have raised resistance and both sides have resorted to
strident rhetoric over a possible Palestinian declaration of
statehood. Under these circumstances, the White House was right to
move for an early meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The main issues to be resolved are competing claims to
Jerusalem, borders between Israeli and Palestinian territory, the
future of Jewish settlements and the rights of Palestinian
refugees. Settling them will require compromises that will leave
neither side happy but that both sides can live with.
</P>
<P>
   The Camp David meetings begin next Tuesday and could run
anywhere from a few days to a few weeks, with President Clinton
participating on a regular basis. Any peace agreement between
Israel and the Palestinians produced under his auspices would
enhance Clinton's place in history. But the importance of achieving
Mideast peace should transcend personality or partisanship. Gov.
George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee,
would be wise to give full support to Clinton's peacemaking
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving a final agreement between Israel and the Palestinians
would crown decades of Mideast diplomacy and resolve the central
conflict between Israel and its Arab neighbors. Much of the
preliminary work is done, but the remaining issues are
excruciatingly difficult. The passage of time is unlikely to make
them easier to resolve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
