<SLUG> BC-DISPARITY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NONPROFIT PAY REFLECTS MALE-FEMALE DISPARITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. - Average earnings for women are 73 cents on
the dollar compared with men, the National Committee on Pay Equity
said in April.
</P>
<P>
   That's an unfair use of total pay figures, countered the
Employment Policy Foundation in May: Compare earnings of full-time
workers 21 to 35 - especially single women - and there's no pay gap
at all.
</P>
<P>
   While advocacy groups played a statistical tug of war about
whether men earn more than women, the new ``2000 Salary and
Benefits Survey of Greater Kansas City Area Nonprofit
Organizations'' pulled together some interesting numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The data tend to endorse the Pay Equity group's contention.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, commissioned by the Center for Management
Assistance, collected compensation data from 251 area nonprofits of
all sizes and purposes. The center's executive director, Carol
Suter, was surprised at the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``On average, there is very competitive pay for men working in
nonprofits compared to those working in the for-profit sector,''
Suter said. ``But that's not so for women.''
</P>
<P>
   The center, which provides management assistance to area
nonprofits, found that men made an average of 21 percent more than
women in directly comparable positions. Some examples of mean
salaries:
</P>
<P>
   Executive director: $70,164 for men, $50,138 for women.
</P>
<P>
   Associate director: $69,100 for men, $42,285 for women.
</P>
<P>
   Development director: $51,823 for men, $40,972 for women.
</P>
<P>
   Finance director: $49,091 for men, $36,366 for women.
</P>
<P>
   In only one nonprofit job category - human resource director -
did women's salaries equal or exceed men's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps,'' Suter theorized, ``women working in that capacity
know better than people in other kinds of positions what
competitive rates of pay are, so they know what to ask for when
they're hired.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Management Assistance is not a political group,
and it takes no formal position on gender equity. But its survey
results speak volumes.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit industry traditionally is dominated by women
employees. While the American work force is 44 percent women, the
Kansas City area nonprofit sector work force is 66 percent women.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one percent of area nonprofits are headed by women; 67
percent of their upper management teams are women. Apparently, the
``sisterhood'' isn't powerful enough to elevate its members' pay to
the level of male counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity raises questions.
</P>
<P>
   Is employment in nonprofits consciously or unconsciously viewed
as an extension of the volunteer work that so many women do without
pay?
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter that it's a nonprofits survey? Would the pay
disparity look the same in the for-profit sector, but we just don't
know it because we don't see the numbers?
</P>
<P>
   And, if nonprofit pay is competitive with for-profit pay for
men, why does the industry appear willing to hang the old
``sackcloth and ashes'' expectation on women who choose careers in
nonprofits? Why are women not worth market value, too?
</P>
<P>
   The apparent inequities deserve scrutiny by nonprofit boards
that set compensation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 0028EDT &QL; 
