<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO TALK ABOUT HEALTH CARE AT UNIVERSITY OF
MISSOURI-COLUMBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - President Clinton will give Missouri a warm
endorsement as a model for health-insurance reform Thursday and
indirectly, at least, turn up the political heat on Sen. John
Ashcroft a notch.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will tell a University of Missouri-Columbia audience
that Congress must pass a patients' bill of rights, which gives
consumers more choices in health care and gives them authority to
sue their insurance providers for bad service.
</P>
<P>
   The House last fall passed a bill Clinton backs, but the Senate
is a vote short of following suit. Supporters saw Ashcroft, a
Missouri Republican, as a key swing vote, although Ashcroft voted
for a different plan last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president wants to do everything possible to highlight the
importance of this issue and to swing a few votes,'' said Chris
Jennings, deputy assistant to the president for health policy.
``Missouri has taken a leadership role in the patients' bill of
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Tim Harlan, a Columbia Democrat who sponsored a 1997
Missouri law similar to the bill that passed in the U.S. House,
said, ``He clearly wants to get some grass-roots support for the
bill and we've had three years experience with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will share the speaking platform at Jesse Auditorium
with Harlan and Gov. Mel Carnahan, who is trying to unseat
Ashcroft. The president's appearance may prove to highlight the
difference between Ashcroft and Carnahan on the issue. Last week,
Carnahan's campaign blasted Ashcroft for not backing a ``real''
patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the president's trip, the Missouri Republican
Party said it smacked of using public dollars for political gain.
It is a private event, with tickets distributed by Carnahan,
Clinton and the university, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a quick political hit intended to benefit Mel
Carnahan and any other Democrat willing to participate in the
charade,'' state party Executive Director John Hancock said in a
press release late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political party that illegally used a Buddhist temple to
shake down campaign contributors in 1996 is using the University of
Missouri to shake down taxpayers this year,'' Hancock said,
referring to Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan spokesman Jerry Nachtigal said that Republicans ``were
looking for a parade to rain on,'' and that nothing is improper
about the president's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding is this was a White House call on where this
would be held,'' Nachtigal said. ``They looked over sites and liked
the size of this one. This is not a campaign event for the
governor. He is here to talk about health care and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Farinella, manager of Carnahan's campaign, said they had
nothing to do with Clinton's appearance. ``They announced it to
us,'' he said. ``I'm sure it's about trying to pass a strong
patients' bill of rights. It's important in our view, too, to get
that bill passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hilton, spokesman for Ashcroft's Senate office, said that
``bipartisanship and constructive effort are indispensable'' to
enacting a patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Partisan pep rallies, closed to the public, won't get the job
done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft is one of three senators whom the American Medical
Association announced last month it was focusing on as the 50th and
deciding vote to pass the House bill. The proposal failed by three
votes in the Senate on June 8.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ashcroft voted instead for an amendment that critics
said doesn't give patients much leverage to sue their insurance
carriers. Ashcroft disagreed, saying it sets a $10,000 penalty for
carriers that fail to meet obligations and permits recovery of up
to $350,000 in damages in federal court only.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the House bill, however, want lawsuits handled in
state courts and want unlimited damages. Critics say that would
lead to excessive and expensive lawsuits, with costs passed on as
higher premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan signed the 1997 Missouri law that removed immunity that
health-maintenance organizations had from lawsuits. Harlan said
there has been only one apparent suit in Missouri since the law
passed.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri law also required HMOs to give patients more
options on getting tests and seeing specialists. It set up a
third-party review process to resolve disputes over health-care
decisions. In the past three years, about 300 appeals have been
filed and the outcome has been split about evenly in favor of
patient and insurers, Harlan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri law applies to people who are covered by
health-maintenance organizations, which Harlan said amounts to
about 40 percent of all insured state residents. The other 60
percent, not covered by the state law, are in self-insurance plans
in which employers pay medical bills directly.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate versions of proposed federal laws would cover people
in self-insurance plans but not those in traditional insurance
programs. The House bill would cover both, which the insurance
industry opposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the critical question,'' AMA chairman Ted Lewers said
late last week. ``Who do you want in charge of your health
insurance? Big insurance, which is more interested in profits than
in patients. Or your own physician, who you know will put patients
first?''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Cohen, at the Health Insurance Association of America,
responded that it is doctors who are concerned about making money.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is being sold in the guise of patient rights is really
about other issues, such as reimbursements to providers,'' Cohen
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the House bill would duplicate and complicate state
laws that already exist in Missouri and some other states: ``The
bill has a number of onerous, redundant and unnecessary
requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   While much of the concern centers on insurer restrictions on
patient and doctor options in making health-care decisions, Cohen
said overall service remains very high.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this perception that insurance companies deny care,
but 97 percent of claims submitted are paid right off the bat,''
Cohen said. ``It's hard to see how reality and myth line up here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
