A4120 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GAS-PRICES-LADN     07-06 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA MAY MISS OUT ON GAS PRICE BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 &HT;    By BRENT HOPKINS AND ERIK NELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gasoline prices in the Los Angeles area could soon
hit $2 a gallon, even as much of the rest of the nation enjoys
relief, analysts who follow the petroleum industry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With prices now averaging $1.68 a gallon in Southern California,
any disruption - such as a refinery fire like one last year in
Torrance - would shoot prices to $2, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any hiccup at all in the production pipeline, we're
going to see an effect on pricing,'' said Jeff Spring of the
Automobile Club of Southern California. ``There's very little
margin for error.''
</P>
<P>
   Burgeoning demand for gas by cash-flush California vacationers
and the rising price of crude oil have driven up pump prices,
despite recent increases in foreign oil production, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   And gas supplies that would otherwise go to California have been
siphoned to the Midwest, where federal regulatory action has
mandated the switch to cleaner-burning fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Some motorists seem resigned to paying the price, especially
those who drive for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prices go up, but our wages don't, so it's putting a
strain on us. I have to continue, I have no choice,'' said Jonathan
Marquez, 39, who sometimes has to fill up his Ford Aerostar twice a
day while working as a messenger.
</P>
<P>
   The pump price increase has crept up on the Southland because
highly competitive gas station operators have taken only bare-bones
profits, or none at all, said Tom Kloza, publisher of the New
Jersey-based Oil Price Information Service, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very quietly the West Coast wholesale price has advanced 15 to
20 cents since June 15,'' ``The wholesale cost at terminals is
about $1.25 (a gallon) in California right now. When you add on
taxes and freight and whatever, it's close to $1.70.''
</P>
<P>
   But station operators no longer will forgo profits, predicted
Tim Hamilton, franchise issues director for AutoCal, a nonprofit
trade association for Southland gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has got about 6 more cents right now that they
haven't seen yet. These dealers have eaten it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tajinder Chahal, general manager of the Woodland
Hills Carwash, a Union 76 affiliate, the profit on gas is minor.
``What we make on gas is really low,'' Chahal said. ``It's only a
couple cents a gallon.''
</P>
<P>
   That number is borne out - to the penny - in the most recent
weekly survey by the state Energy Commission, which found that
dealers were making 2 cents on a gallon of gasoline, while
refineries were making 36 cents. The rest goes to taxes and other
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are out-of-business numbers. Unless you're Amazon.com,
you can't run a business that loses money. They're going to be
forced by economics to raise prices,'' Kloza said.
</P>
<P>
   Refineries producing California's unique summer blend of
cleaner-burning gasoline - formulated to meet state and federal
air-pollution regulations - are operating at full tilt and reaping
profits, Kloza said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every refiner is doing very, very well and every oil producer
is doing very, very well,'' Kloza said.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline producers defended the increases, saying they are
responding to rises in the price of crude oil and the demand for
cleaner gas. ``There's just not that much supply available,'' said
Cheryl Burnett, a spokeswoman for London-based BP Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   However, Barnett conceded that gas prices are higher in areas
where there are relatively fewer stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oftentimes the prices between areas of the state are related
to competition,'' Barnett said. ``Los Angeles has more stations,
there's more competition, therefore the prices are lower.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, where stations tend to be fewer and more
isolated from each other, consumers already pay more than $2 a
gallon for grades except regular unleaded, which costs about $1.90,
Kloza said.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron's Frank Gorell wouldn't predict where prices were
headed, but described current price pressures, such as the price of
crude oil, the output of refineries, demand from vacationers and
farmers doing summer planting, as a layer cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The layers of this cake all push in the same direction,'' he
said, ``upward.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also said that a little longer than a year ago, prices
were lower than those during the Great Depression, when adjusted
for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   And Claudia Chandler, assistant executive director of the
California Energy Commission, disputed dire price predictions
because of Saudi Arabia's promise to increase production, thereby
driving down the cost to refiners. She said Saudi price cuts would
be followed by price cuts of Alaskan crude, which supplies 41
percent of California's oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the factors right now are not pointing to $2 per gallon,
barring any serious refinery problems,'' she said, such as those
that caused Northern California prices to jump 15 cents
``overnight'' last week.
</P>
<P>
   Some San Fernando Valley motorists said higher prices had
compelled them to be more selective in their buying habits,
including whether they will continue to drive sport-utility
vehicles and pickups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably get a diesel the next time I'm in the market,''
said Jim Rodnumsky, 43, as he paid $60 at Novak's Chevron to fill
up his Ford F-350, which he uses in his work for Cablecam Systems.
``It's less convenient, but I need this for my job, so I can't do
anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kloza said most motorists aren't matching their words with
actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angry motorists railing against high prices ... just has not
been followed by real action,'' he said. ``So far, it hasn't had a
significant impact on demand. People are driving just as much as
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone has benefited from the up-swing in gas prices, it is
bulk-retailer Costco, which offers gas to its members. Though lines
are long at the Van Nuys location, customers keep coming, snared by
the low prices - $1.53 per gallon for regular unleaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best deal I can find in L.A., so it's worth the
extra five minutes,'' said Brad Pressman, 33, of Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Like most customers, he's unhappy about the increase, but
willing to ride it out until the price drops down again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until they can invent an electric car that can go as fast as
my Corvette, I'll keep paying for gas.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
