</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLICS-LATINOS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC CHURCH LOOKS TO HIKE NUMBER OF LATINO PRIESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
 &HT;    By STEVE CARNEY  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Catholics from throughout the United States
gather in Los Angeles today for an unprecedented cross-cultural
get-together, they're concerned that the explosive growth of their
Latino membership isn't reflected in their priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 40 years, Latinos have accounted for 71 percent of
the growth in the Catholic Church in the United States. More than a
third of the church's total membership is now Latino, as compared
with only 4 percent of priests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth in the last 10 years has been so great, we haven't
been able to keep up with it,'' said Ronaldo Cruz, executive
director of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops'
Secretariat for Hispanic Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the average ratio of priests to Catholics is 1 to
1,200, while for Latino priests and parishioners it is 1 to 9,900.
</P>
<P>
   Serving that burgeoning and vital minority is only one of many
topics on the menu for Encuentro 2000, a four-day gathering that
starts today at the L.A. Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, subtitled ``Many Faces in God's House,'' and
expected to draw 4,400 church leaders and members, is the only
national gathering of its kind planned for 2000, a pivotal Jubilee
Year for the church, as decreed by Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique moment in the Catholic Church,'' said Sister
Mary Ann Walsh, spokeswoman for Encuentro 2000. ``It's the first
time we have called Catholics of all races and all ethnic
backgrounds together. It's a chance to look at the church and where
we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   And Los Angeles is the ideal place for that self-examination
because it's such a cross-cultural crossroads itself, with
Catholics from Cambodia, Egypt, Samoa, the Philippines, Central and
South America, Syria, Lebanon and other points around the globe all
residing here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have just about every ethnicity and every language and
every type of Catholic here,'' said Tod Tamberg, director of media
relations for the Archdiocese of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very proud of our ethnic makeup. It's a strength, and
it's really a skill to master to live as one Christian family, to
say, How do we work together, and how to we become one family?''
</P>
<P>
   Because of its large Latino Catholic population - by far the
largest in the country - Los Angeles does better than most dioceses
in serving Latino immigrants, Tamberg said. Officials from dioceses
nationwide have come calling for advice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz said the church has three main approaches to recruit more
Latino priests: have current priests mentor potential Latino
seminarians, ask Latino families to encourage their children to
consider the priesthood, and reach out to young men directly at
colleges and high schools.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new study by the National Conference of Catholic
Bishops, 83.5 percent of church leaders surveyed said their
dioceses ``have yet to develop effective programs to reach Hispanic
youth.''
</P>
<P>
   And though Spanish-language services and Latino cultural
programs are increasing, church officials say more are needed, as
are more Latinos in leadership positions.
</P>
<P>
   If the Catholic Church doesn't cater to immigrants' needs, then
there are plenty of small evangelical churches sprouting in ethnic
communities that will - and already are.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way of telling how many immigrants who were
practicing Catholics in their home countries joined storefront
churches upon arriving in the United States. But more than half of
the bishops and other church officials surveyed in the Latino study
in 1998 called proselytism a ``very significant'' challenge,
compared with only 11.5 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
