A4125 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLA     07-06 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KREUTER BEGINS HIS SUSPENSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The two-month saga that began when Chad Kreuter
entered the stands and took part in a May 16 fight at Wrigley Field
took a major step toward a final resolution Wednesday when the Los
Angeles Dodgers catcher dropped his appeal and began serving his
eight-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter, through the players association, filed his second
appeal of the suspension when Paul Beeston, chief operating officer
for baseball, upheld Frank Robinson's original ruling last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to drop the appeal was Kreuter's, though it was
something the Dodgers wanted him to do for the past week. The
timing makes sense because of the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Todd Hundley had Monday and Tuesday off to rest him for
the five games that remained heading into the break. Kreuter will
finish serving his time by sitting out the three-game series with
the Angels after the break. He'll return July 16.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kreuter, who is also facing a civil suit, said he
believed the suspension was harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I needed to appeal it because I wasn't happy with
the outcome, in the first place, but I felt I needed to (serve the
suspension) because I want to be a team player and do what's best
for this ballclub,'' Kreuter said. ``I'm not happy with what has
gone on. I was on a baseball field, playing baseball, and I was
struck in the back of the head and my cap stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the victim in this thing and I've been made out to be
more of the villain. So I'm not too thrilled with how the
circumstances have turned out, especially since the guys that have
come to my aid, not all of them have been vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   By dropping the appeal, it leaves three Dodgers with appeals
pending in Gary Sheffield, F.P. Santangelo and Carlos Perez, each
suspended five games.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield remains adamant about appealing his suspension, which
he'll do next week while he's in Atlanta at the All-Star game.
Sheffield's appeal will be heard by commissioner Bud Selig.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the players association continue to speak with
Santangelo and Perez about dropping their appeals. Two Dodgers
sources said it's likely Santangelo would drop his appeal as early
as today. A baseball official said Perez will likely drop his
appeal because he's a pitcher, and it would only cost him one
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (Kreuter's decision) has any affect on anyone
else,'' said Gene Orza, associate general counsel for the players
association. ``My suspicion, and it's really nothing more than
that, is the Dodgers want to move on, and I think the players want
to move past it. I think Carlos and F.P. will drop their appeals,
but in Sheffield's case, he fully plans to follow through.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the reason Kreuter appealed Beeston's decision last week
was to protect himself against a civil suit that's been filed. The
wording of the decision caused some concern, but Orza and Robert
Manfred, executive vice president of labor relations and human
resources for baseball, will meet today to change the wording.
</P>
<P>
   But Kreuter said that dropping his appeal in no way means he
agrees with the punishment. It was handed down May 24 after Kreuter
was allegedly struck in the back of his head and had his cap stolen
by a fan.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter says he went into the stands to hold the person until
security arrived. The episode exploded into a melee for which 16
players and three coaches were suspended by Robinson, vice
president of on-field operations. Eleven players and coach Glenn
Hoffman had their suspensions overturned by Beeston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that we have a position in baseball where we
have a Hall of Famer (Robinson) that should be respected by all of
us players, who is respected as a baseball player, that he's put in
position to be a bad guy,'' Kreuter said. ``It's unfortunate
because you don't want a guy that's done what he's done in this
game to be put in that position of being the cop, or the judge and
jury of any of the things that (happen) on the field. You hate for
a guy of that stature to be in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz will act as Hundley's backup, and Dave Hansen is the
emergency catcher. Hundley should be aided in that he just had two
days off and the All-Star break will give him three more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to have a whole bunch of suspension dates after
the All-Star break,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``If
Hundley wasn't healthy, I'd postpone it (by continuing the appeal).
If you have to serve it for eight days, and there's not much chance
for redemption, then you need to serve it and get it past you. I've
made no secret of that to Chad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
