<SLUG> BC-NH-IMPEACH-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE PANEL RECOMMENDS IMPEACHING NEW HAMPSHIRE CHIEF JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (RECASTS with other articles of impeachment, comment from Brock's
lawyer)   
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A committee of New Hampshire lawmakers voted Wednesday
night to recommend that Chief Justice David Brock of the State
Supreme Court be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to recommend impeachment of Brock on accusations
that he had committed perjury as he defended himself against
charges of ethical improprieties came on a 17-5 vote of by the
Judiciary Committee of the State House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also endorsed two other articles of impeachment
charging that Brock called a lower-court judge in 1987 in a case
involving a powerful state senator, something Brock has denied, and
that he solicited comments from a fellow justice about that
justice's divorce case, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   The full House is scheduled to decide on the committee's
recommendations on July 12. If the House votes for impeachment, the
trial, which would be the first such Supreme Court impeachment
proceeding in New Hampshire since 1790, will begin in the state
Senate in August.
</P>
<P>
   Two other articles of impeachment against Brock, one accusing
him of letting disqualified justices take part in deliberations and
the other saying the sum of his actions warranted impeachment, both
failed, The AP reported.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Brock's lawyer, David Barry, said Wednesday night that the
committee had lowered the threshold for impeachment too far.
Historically, he said, officials have been impeached for willful
misconduct, not poor judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``An impeachment of the chief justice based on the evidence
found will stand out as a historical aberration,'' Barry was quoted
by The AP as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also decided against impeaching or reprimanding
two state Supreme Court justices, Sherman D. Horton Jr. and John T.
Broderick Jr., who were also accused of ethical missteps.
</P>
<P>
   The committee voted 19-3 against impeaching Horton and 16-6
against admonishing Broderick. Both had been accused of failing to
turn in the colleague who tried to intercede in his own divorce
case and of discussing cases from which they had recused themselves
because of possible bias.
</P>
<P>
   But state Rep. Cynthia J. Dokmo, a Republican who is one of
several lawyers on the committee, said, ``Whether we impeach them
or not, their reputations are forever damaged by this process.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire judicial crisis began with an ugly divorce,
the split between a state Supreme Court justice, W. Stephen Thayer
III, and his wife, Judith, a former chairwoman of the state Board
of Education. Judith Thayer appealed aspects of the case up to the
very court on which her former husband sat, and its justices,
unable to rule on their own colleague, had to appoint a special
panel of other judges to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 4, according to a report by the state attorney general,
Thayer, who has since resigned, vehemently objected to the choice
of a particular judge for that panel. In response, Brock tried to
prevent the court clerk from calling that judge but was too late.
</P>
<P>
   That incident, which the court clerk reported to a judicial
conduct committee, prompted a broader inquiry into the court's
practices by the state attorney general, Philip T. McLaughlin. It
found a worrisome pattern of justices' being allowed to comment on
cases even when they had excused themselves because of potential
conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Although the court had already issued new rules on recusals, the
incident also raised strenuous protests from court critics across
the state, many of whom were already contending that the court
overstepped its bounds in a major 1997 ruling that revamped the
state's heavily local system of financing schools. Lingering anger
among lawmakers over that decision could mean trouble for Brock as
the Legislature decides his fate, political analysts here say.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the court in the Legislature moved this spring for an
inquiry into whether any justices should be impeached, and the
Judicial Committee of the House took up the question in April. It
has since heard testimony laying bare some of the innermost
workings of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Another, somewhat dusty case figured prominently in the
discussions: accusations that in 1987, Brock intervened in a case
involving a powerful state senator and commented that the senator
held some control over justices' pay raises. Brock denies making
the call.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
