<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-A'S-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS COMPLETE SWEEP OF A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Oakland Athletics starter Mark Mulder threw
32 pitches in the first inning last night, and most of them were
pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   He walked David Segui after getting ahead 0-2 in the count, but
other than that, he pretty much had the Rangers off-balance for the
entire inning. Only a couple of balls were hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop the Rangers from putting together one of the
weakest seven-run rallies imaginable and riding it to a 9-4 victory
over the Athletics at The Ballpark in Arlington. The victory
allowed the Rangers to sweep the three-game series and improved
their season record to 7-2 against the second-place Athletics. The
Rangers are 33-40 against everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good start, being able to sweep these guys,'' first
baseman Rafael Palmeiro said. ``It gives us hope. It gives
everybody hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also finished 6-3 in a nine-game stretch that
consisted of six against Oakland and three against the Seattle
Mariners, keeping alive their flickering hope of remaining in
contention in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had periods like this all year,'' manager Johnny Oates
said. ``What we're looking for is two months like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Kenny Rogers took advantage of the early support
to run his winning streak to six games. Rogers, who hasn't lost
since May 24 in Kansas City, allowed four runs on 10 hits in
eight-plus innings and threw 114 pitches. He's still hoping to
pitch Sunday on three days' rest against the San Diego Padres, but
Oates isn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the victory, Rogers was unhappy with the way he pitched.
A foot through a wall in the clubhouse emphasized that displeasure,
even though he raised his record to 9-5 with a 4.13 earned-run
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt terrible out there,'' Rogers said. ``But the offense
gave me room for error. I struggled with my location on anything I
threw. It was more them making outs than me making good pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulder threw 131 pitches. Despite the rough start, he still
managed to hang around for 62/3 innings and give up 15 hits, the
most in one game by a pitcher in the major leagues this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mulder, after striking out Luis Alicea to start the first, got
himself into trouble on what should have been a routine out. Rusty
Greer hit a grounder to first baseman Jason Giambi, who flipped to
Mulder covering the bag. But Mulder somehow barely missed stepping
on the bag, and first base umpire Brian Gorman ruled Greer safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got it with the side of my foot,'' Mulder said. ``But at the
last minute, I said, let's make sure, and when I went back to hit
it again, I missed it. So the umpire, of course, is going to think
I missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro followed with a soft single into center that sent Greer
to third, and Ivan Rodriguez brought him home with a sacrifice fly.
Chad Curtis followed with a grounder off the third-base bag that
went for a run-scoring double. Gabe Kapler was walked
intentionally, but Mike Lamb, starting a 3-for-4 night, blooped a
single to left, scoring two runs. Scott Sheldon doubled off Jeremy
Giambi's glove in deep right to score two more. Alicea made it 7-0
with a solid double into the left-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt good,'' Mulder said. ``I was hitting my spots,
but I still gave up a seven-spot in the first inning. All I needed
was one out, and I couldn't get it. That's tough to come back from
with Kenny out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Greer, ``We hit some balls, but I don't know if more than
one or two of them were right on the screws. We had good placement
out there, but right now we'll take anything we can get.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
