<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     07-06 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY, THE YANKEES FIND THEIR LAUGHER ISN'T SO FUNNY
</HEADLINE>
  By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The domination was clear and seemingly complete after
six innings Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees had taken a 10-0 lead over the Baltimore
Orioles, which was refreshing for a team stumbling through a summer
swoon, a team that had gone 10-15 in June and had lost its last
five games at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a 10-0 lead was like diving into a swimming pool on a
steamy day. But the Yankees lingered too long in the shallow end,
and by the end of the seventh inning, they were sweating again,
their lead down to just 10-6. But the Yankees bounced back to score
two runs in the eighth, and they eventually wiped their brows with
a 12-6 victory over the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Yankees desperately needed the victory, which put
them four games above .500 at 41-37 and moved them within a
half-game of first-place Toronto in the American League East, the
Orioles' six-run seventh inning exposed their weaknesses in the
bullpen again.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' newly named All-Stars Derek Jeter and Bernie
Williams were scorching. Williams extended his hitting streak to 15
games and instigated the scoring barrages with leadoff doubles in
the second and sixth innings. Jeter made typically astounding
throws from the shortstop hole and then homered in the fifth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte (9-4), who pitched a complete-game shutout against
Detroit in his last outing, was dominating Wednesday night through
six shutout innings. Pettitte, who has won four of his last six
starts, left with one out in the seventh, but not before he had
given up a two-run home run to Charles Johnson, a triple to Luis
Matos and a walk to Brady Anderson. That was enough for manager Joe
Torre as he took Pettitte out to the roar of the 40,031 fans who
appreciated the value of a solid outing.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander Jason Grimsley, whom Torre had mentioned as a
strong possibility to start Saturday's day game against the Mets at
Shea Stadium, relieved Pettitte. But Grimsley heard a much
different reaction when he walked off the mound after recording
just one out, hanging his head to boos.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley gave up a run-scoring single to Mike Bordick, the first
batter he faced, then outfielder B.J. Surhoff cracked a double that
scored Bordick. Albert Belle drove in a run with a groundout and
Jeff Conine singled Surhoff home for the sixth run of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Torre called for the left-hander Mike Stanton. Will Clark
singled on his only pitch for his second hit of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander Jeff Nelson finally snuffed the rally. Johnson
slapped a ground ball that ricocheted off Nelson's foot, and Jeter
collected it and rifled to second for the force.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth inning, Pettitte escaped the only other danger he
faced. He walked Johnson, and Mark Lewis slapped a ground ball deep
into the hole at shortstop. But Jeter was there, and he threw
across his body to get Johnson at second.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
