A4132 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-ALGAE-INVASION-SFCHRO     07-06 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALGAE-INVASION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLER ALGAE BLOOMS IN SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA LAGOON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ A noxious species of ``killer algae'' that has
destroyed marine life across thousands of acres of the
Mediterranean seabed has now invaded a coastal lagoon near San
Diego and threatens to spread swiftly unless the fast-growing pest
can be controlled.
<P>
   A task force of scientists from federal and state wildlife
agencies, joined by other environmental specialists, is testing
techniques to wipe out the invading algae before the dangerous
bright green weed spreads along the California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have compared the spread of the invading algae to
``unrolling a carpet of Astro Turf across the bottom of the sea,''
causing ``ecological and economic devastation'' in its path.
</P>
<P>
   The deadly pest was detected last month by divers monitoring the
growth of transplanted eel grass in a program to restore a lagoon
beside the Cabrillo Power Co. plant in Carlsbad, about 20 miles
north of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe that a strain of the nasty plant, known
scientifically as Caulerpa taxifolia, was first cultivated years
ago by biologists at the Stuttgart zoo aquarium in Germany because
it made a highly decorative cover for the aquarium's artificial
ocean bottom.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, the evidence indicates, clones of the same invading
species apparently were dumped into the Mediterranean from the
Monaco aquarium, and the algae began its swift attack. From an
original patch of less than a square yard, the infestation spread
wildly, covering more than 1,000 acres by 1992 and 10,000 acres by
last year, with patches of the weed established along the
Mediterranean coast of France, Spain and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Before the lagoon invasion was discovered in California three
weeks ago, the aggressive weed was unknown anywhere along the
coasts of North and South America, according to Andrew N. Cohen, a
marine biologist at the San Francisco Estuary Institute in
Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   The importation or sale of the invasive algae was banned last
year in an executive order from President Clinton. But in a
telephone briefing from San Diego Wednesday, Robert Hoffman of the
National Marine Fisheries Service warned that clumps of the algae
are still being sold to hobbyists by aquarium dealers. Dumping the
contents of home saltwater aquariums into storm sewers _ a common
practice _ could threaten to spread disaster for coastal marine
life, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 letter to Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt that
triggered the federal ban _ two years before the plant was first
detected in the Carlsbad lagoon _ nearly 100 environmental
scientists warned Babbitt that the algae can grow almost anywhere
in the ocean down to depths of 250 feet and on sandy and rocky sea
bottoms in both protected bays and along rocky coasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allowing the release of this organism into the Mediterranean
was an act of environmental mismanagement that threatens
catastrophic changes and the loss of biological diversity in one of
the most valued marine ecosystems,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This killer algae smothers local aquatic plants just as
effectively as if we had bulldozed them out,'' said Linda Sheehan,
Pacific region director of the Center for Marine Conservation, a
national environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   In the Carlsbad lagoon, one thick patch of the invading algae
now covers an area about 30 by 60 feet, while nine other small
patches are growing around it, according to Hoffman. The thick turf
covers all kinds of bottom-dwelling life _ including native
seaweeds, corals, sponges, and many species of clams, shrimp and
small fish, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the seaweed is harmless to humans, it contains a toxin
that can interfere with the eggs of many marine animals and can
kill many microscopic marine organisms.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists from the government and private agencies working
now to wipe out the invasion in the Carlsbad lagoon are testing
several chemicals they hope will work, Hoffman said. The plan is to
cover each of the nine small patches of algal turf with tarpaulins
and then drench the area with either copper sulfate or chlorine.
</P>
<P>
   The attack will kill everything living within the patch, Hoffman
said, but just how the larger invaded area can be cleansed remains
a question. In any event, he said, the team hopes to start
attacking the invasion within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Caulerpa invasion in the lagoon was first identified by
marine biologist Rachel Woodfield, who works for Merkel &AMP;
Associates, a San Diego environmental consulting firm employed by
the power company to oversee the lagoon restoration project.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mediterranean, fishing nets and boat anchors have spread
the invasion. ``Even a tiny piece of the algae broken off can
regenerate a new plant, making eradication by mechanical means
nearly impossible,'' Woodfield said.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition of agencies trying to stem the invasion in the
Carlsbad lagoon urged the public Wednesday to notify any local
office of the California Department of Fish and Game if the algae
species is observed anywhere along the coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
