<HEADER>
A4133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OPSAIL-TURNAROUND-1ST     07-06 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPSAIL-TURNAROUND-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNAROUND OF PARADE SHIPS IS DEFENDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (CORRECTS to OpSail in grafs 2,3,7)  
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An official of the Fourth of July Parade of Sails on
Wednesday defended decisions by two captains to turn 27 tall ships
around before reaching Upper Manhattan, a move that disappointed
thousands of eager spectators.
</P>
<P>
   The defense came as Mayor Rudolph Giuliani suggested that the
organizers of OpSail may have barely managed to execute the whole
event.
</P>
<P>
   The captains of the Eagle, from the U.S. Coast Guard, and the
Cisne Branco, from Brazil, led separate turnarounds of two lines of
ships on the Hudson River, said Gregory Perrin, vice president of
OpSail, the nonprofit group that put on the event.
</P>
<P>
   Both captains turned around farther south than scheduled to make
sure their ships had time to dock safely, before the tides changed,
he said. The other tall ships followed their lead.
</P>
<P>
   But one OpSail executive, Paul Welling, a retired Coast Guard
vice admiral, said that while the dozen ships docking on the East
River had to turn around early to take advantage of ideal tidal
conditions, those docking on the Hudson should not have had to turn
around.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people in Upper Manhattan and northern New Jersey
were let down when the full parade did not go all the way up to the
George Washington Bridge as they had expected. Most of the
four-masted Class A ships measured more than 300 feet in length and
were the most impressive in the parade.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at P.S. 48 in the Washington Heights
section of Manhattan, Giuliani declined to address the turnaround,
but said that there were tensions between the city and OpSail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not have the greatest relationship with OpSail, so I am
not about to defend them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did note from the complaints that I got from the people who
worked with OpSail that this was not a terribly well-managed
operation. Now, they pulled it off, it worked. But there were times
in which it almost looked like it wasn't going to work at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But Perrin said that ``all the operations went off without a
hitch.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the turnaround, the captains could have been reacting to
a number of variables, including currents and wind conditions, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The captain of a vessel is ultimately responsible for the
safety of that vessel,'' Perrin said. ``Whatever variables came
into play, OpSail is not in a position to question the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The captains wanted to get their ships to their berths during
slack water, an eight-minute window of time when the tide is not
coming in or going out, Perrin said. On the East River especially,
the water can be treacherous at other times, and tall ships cannot
be maneuvered easily into the narrow piers.
</P>
<P>
   Welling said that if the dozen ships docking on the East River
had missed slack water, they would have had to wait several hours
for the tide to shift and then use tug boats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
