<HEADER>
A4138 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-MEXICO-ENVIRONMENT-SF     07-06 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ENVIRONMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FOX URGED TO PLACE ENVIRONMENT HIGH ON AGENDA  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Earlier this year, as Vicente Fox revved up his
campaign for president, few people paid attention to his
increasingly frequent promises to include ecological considerations
at nearly every stage of government.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative, pro-business candidate who is also an
environmentalist? Ridiculous, just empty rhetoric, more of Fox's
usual moralizing, critics said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after Fox's surprise victory in Sunday's election, Mexicans
are taking a second look _ and many are concluding that he may turn
out to be the country's most green-friendly president ever.
</P>
<P>
   Since his triumph, Fox has repeated and expanded on his pledges
to end Mexico's severe problems with air and water pollution,
making mention of the issues in nearly every speech and interview.
</P>
<P>
   But a backlash has started _ ironically enough, from some
environmental groups, while business leaders, who would stand to be
hurt by stepped-up enforcement of pollution controls, have been
virtually mum on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Harsh criticism is raining down on the small Green Ecologist
Party, which joined with Fox's National Action Party (PAN) to form
the Alliance for Change that swept him to victory. The Green
Party's leader, Jorge Gonzalez Torres, has long been controversial
among Mexico's small yet vocal environmental community, and
speculation that Fox might anoint him czar of Mexico's
environmental ministry disturbs some.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez Torres was almost inseparable from Fox on the campaign
trail, appearing at countless rallies. At Fox's victory celebration
Sunday night, the Green leader was at his elbow and gave his
introductory speech.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the key advisers who have influenced Fox to adopt
an environmental stance that advocates:
</P>
<P>
   -- A substantial increase in funding and new policing powers for
PROFEPA, the agency that investigates and enforces pollution laws.
</P>
<P>
   -- A sharp reduction in logging of old-growth forests, and an
increase in commercial reforestation.
</P>
<P>
   -- Inclusion of pollution as a negative cost when calculating
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   -- Special tax breaks to industry for installing environmental
controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make Mexico's environment, its water and forests, a
national-security issue,'' Fox said Tuesday. ``We will turn around
the concept of development to include the environment as a factor
in economic and social decisions _ not as a separate sector, but as
an essential element in creating sustainable economic and social
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gonzalez Torres says he maintains close links with the
U.S. Green Party and praises its presidential candidate, Ralph
Nader, his party is much more centrist and cautious than its
northern counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Many critics say Gonzalez Torres _ who ran for president in 1994
but received only 1.5 percent of the vote _ is more small-time
political operator than environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
   There have been suspicions for years that the formation of the
Green Ecologist Party was aided and abetted by former President
Carlos Salinas as a tactic for dividing voters opposed to the
long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI). Gonzalez
Torres also has been criticized for running his party in an
authoritarian manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Party has never been known for taking strong
ecological stands, and for that reason no major Mexican
environmentalists are members,'' said Alejandro Calvillo, director
of Greenpeace Mexico. ``If Gonzalez Torres is given a major role in
the government it will be a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, a coalition of 65 environmental groups went further,
calling Gonzalez Torres an ``opportunist'' and warning that his
party had ``usurped'' the environmental cause.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez Torres is highly controversial even within Fox's inner
circle, with some advisers trying to veto him from any job in the
new government. ``It would be a tragedy if he is named to any
important position,'' one top Fox adviser, who requested anonymity,
said last night.
</P>
<P>
   Others defend him, arguing that many of his critics have tight
links with the PRI and with government environmental authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Party is not perfect, but it has played a
constructive role in many issues,'' said Homero Aridjis, president
of the Group of 100 and Mexico's best-known environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
   Aridjis cited the role of Green Party congressional legislators
in forcing President Ernesto Zedillo to halt a controversial salt
extraction project by Mitsubishi Corp. in whale wintering areas in
Baja California.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening now is a political offensive, as many people
are fighting over government power in the new administration _
keeping their jobs, getting new ones, getting a piece of the pie,''
Aridjis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what's important now is that Fox has shown a real
sensitivity toward environmental issues,'' he added. ``I'm very
enthusiastic about the new administration. Fox could really help
solve Mexico's horrible pollution problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez Torres said he is being attacked merely because his
often-lonely, 20-year campaign to inject environmentalism into
mainstream politics has finally been successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been at the forefront of these issues for many years,
and now there is a great possibility that Mexico will have its
first environmentalist government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he hopes to influence the Fox administration to
increase support for mass transit, electric vehicles, environmental
education in public schools and cooperation with the United States
to clean up pollution along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez Torres rejects the charges of political opportunism,
noting that his party has never flinched in its animal-rights
crusade to stop bullfighting and hunting. The crusade has been
highly unpopular in macho Mexico, and Fox has declined to endorse
it _ although his coalition's congressional candidates reluctantly
agreed to forsake bullfight appearances during this year's election
race.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Gonzalez Torres gets a top job in the new regime,
his Green Party will likely have considerable influence. By running
on the same parliamentary election list as Fox's PAN, the Green
Party will reap a big harvest of seats in the new Congress _ five
in the Senate and 16 in the Chamber of Deputies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
