<SLUG> BC-CAR-CART-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TMS EXPECTED TO ADD CART RACE TO 2001 SCHEDULE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The addition of a Championship Auto Racing
Teams open-wheel race to the 2001 schedule at Texas Motor Speedway
will be announced Tuesday, an industry source said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   TMS has booked a news conference for a ``major announcement''
regarding next season at The Movie Studios at Las Colinas in
Irving. Bruton Smith, the owner of TMS and chairman of Speedway
Motorsports Inc., is scheduled to attend. The source said that
Bobby Rahal, CART's interim president and chief executive officer,
also would attend.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Gossage, vice president and general manager of TMS, would
not confirm that CART was poised to join the track's lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of weeks ago, I said the next time I had anything to
say on the record \Rabout CART\S, it would be that they're either
coming or not coming here,'' Gossage said. ``So, we'll be on the
record Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of CART to the TMS schedule would make it the first
facility to play host to both the FedEx Championship Series and the
rival Indy Racing Northern Light Series. The Indy Racing League has
competed at TMS since its inaugural season of 1997. Last month,
Gossage and IRL founder Tony George signed a sanctioning agreement
that will continue to give TMS the first race after the
Indianapolis 500 in June and the season finale each year through
2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have one of the busiest schedules in the country
that any superspeedway has,'' Gossage said. ``As we sit here, we
already have announced our Winston Cup weekend \Rfor 2001\S, two
IRL dates and the American Le Mans Series. We've got four major
weekends already. It goes back to what we've always said, that this
wasn't going to be just another speedway.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of a race in this market, CART historically has
posted strong TV ratings in Fort Worth-Dallas. Gossage and former
CART president and CEO Andrew Craig negotiated on a CART date in
the summer of 1996. But a variety of issues _ including the extreme
speeds generated by CART's turbocharged V-8 engines through TMS'
24-degree banked turns _ prompted Gossage to go with the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between TMS and CART accelerated after Craig's resignation
from the post of president and CEO on June 16. Rahal, a team owner
and member of CART's Board of Directors, was appointed Craig's
interim replacement by his fellow board members. Rahal could not be
reached for comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after taking over for Craig, Rahal said, ``Job one is
the schedule. Job one, day-to-day, is to raise the level of
awareness of open-wheel racing in this country, especially CART
racing.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day Rahal replaced Craig, Gossage said he would contact
Rahal and extend an invitation for CART to race at the 1.5-mile
quadoval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not had any meetings with Rahal or anybody in CART. I
haven't been up there \RTroy, Mich.\S and they haven't been down
here,'' Gossage said yesterday. ``That does not mean that I haven't
had telephone conversations. I'm trying not to say anything. But
it's just a real exciting time right now for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahal said last month that he wanted to have the series' four
engine manufacturers look into ways of reducing horsepower to
provide a better show on the series' oval tracks.
</P>
<P>
   CART currently races on a temporary 1.527-mile street circuit in
downtown Houston. The Texaco Havoline Grand Prix of Houston is
scheduled for Oct. 1 as Round 18 of a 20-race schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Rahal announced last month that CART would not return in 2001 to
either the Homestead-Miami Speedway, near Miami, or Gateway
International Raceway, near St. Louis. Both are oval tracks.
</P>
<P>
   An industry source said CART was looking to schedule an early to
midseason date at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   Homestead served as the 2000 season opener, on March 26. But
such a late-March date would put a 2001 CART race into close
proximity to the NASCAR Busch Grand National and Winston Cup
weekend at TMS. Those races are scheduled for March 31-April 1,
2001.
</P>
<P>
   This year's final CART event at Gateway International Raceway is
scheduled for Sept. 17. While that would fit TMS weather-wise, a
mid-September date would put a CART race in proximity to the 2001
IRL season-ender, scheduled for Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   CART also has announced the addition of a race in Mexico for
next season, and is rumored to be heading to Germany and England
for oval-track events. With those additions and that of TMS, CART
could operate with a 22-race schedule next season.
</P>
<P>
   That would be consistent with the plan Rahal outlined last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the need to go beyond 20 races,'' said Rahal, a
three-time series champion and winner of the 1986 Indy 500. ``I
think ultimately 20 to 24 races is possible. A lot of good circuits
are interested in hosting us. We have to start aligning ourselves
in stronger markets here and overseas as well.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
