<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-JULY4-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A FINE FOURTH, WITH ONE FLAW  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, July 6:
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of tall ships, mighty explosions and big numbers.
To begin with, there were more than 30,000 craft of all sizes in
New York Harbor and adjoining waters, including 300 military
vessels and 27 spectacular tall ships that a lot of people did not
get to see. There were a million spectators, thousands of sailors,
12,000 cops, and one president. At the end of the day, 60,324
shells _ 150 tons of pyrotechnics in all _ were fired into the air
on both sides of Manhattan Island, providing a deafening
exclamation point to the biggest Fourth of July celebration the
city has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   There were some touching moments. On the carrier John F.
Kennedy, Attorney General Janet Reno swore in 19 new U.S. citizens,
including Rosa Norales-Nunez, a crew member and native of Honduras.
Norales-Nunez was chosen to introduce President Clinton, who then
reciprocated with a message of welcome and a plea to all Americans
``never to close the golden door behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   As was true of earlier OpSails, the tall ships provided the
day's centerpiece _ and, this time around, its biggest
disappointment. The Indonesian barque Dewaruci reached New York via
the Indian Ocean, the Red Sea, the Mediterranean and the North
Atlantic _ but, like the rest of the really big ships, could not
muster the energy to make it as far as the George Washington
Bridge. The bridge had been widely advertised by the organizers of
OpSail as the flotilla's eventual destination, and thousands of
people gathered in Harlem and at upriver locations on the New
Jersey side to see these majestic giants sail by. But many of the
big ships, led by the Eagle, a U.S. training vessel, began turning
around at about 47th Street. Some went farther, but none reached
the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   OpSail officials said that the prospect of unfavorable tides had
raised fears that the big ships would not make it back to their
berths. But tides are not all that difficult to predict. In the
future, the organizers should either start the procession at a
different time or be a bit more honest in their advertising. It was
one glitch in an otherwise glorious day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
