<HEADLINE>
THE SPORTING MUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know that baseball has expanded too much when you can fill a
32-man All-Star roster and still leave quite a few worthy players
off the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre was able to swell his American League
roster for Tuesday's game to 32 by selecting replacements for the
injured Pedro Martinez and Manny Ramirez, yet he still couldn't
find a way to get the White Sox's Frank Thomas, armed with a robust
.340 average, 25 home runs and 75 runs batted in, on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the requirement of at least one player from each team,
Torre gave berths to Tampa first baseman Fred McGriff (.272
average) and Minnesota outfielder Matt Lawton. First base is a deep
spot in the A.L. this year, which makes one wince at McGriff's
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Giambi deservedly won the fan voting and becomes the
second former Dirtbag in the game (Steve Trachsel was the first),
and Toronto's Carlos Delgado and Kansas City's Mike Sweeney are
also having big years. Jim Thome, who finished second in fan
voting, wasn't selected, and Mo Vaughn and Rafael Palmeiro were
also bypassed.
</P>
<P>
   With Cal Ripken's status for the game undecided, Torre handed
two reserve spots to the Angels' Troy Glaus (deserved) and the
Indians' Travis Fryman (marginal). Toronto's Tony Batista might
have been more deserving than Fryman.
</P>
<P>
   Torre also selected his own catcher, Jorge Posada, when the
Orioles' Charles Johnson might have been more deserving.
</P>
<P>
   The N.L. decision-making reflected the game's locale, Atlanta,
and the person doing the picking, Braves manager Bobby Cox. It's
safe to say there were pitchers more deserving of a bid than Tom
Glavine (Florida's Alfonso Alfonseca) and outfielders more
deserving than Andrew Jones (Steve Finley).
</P>
<P>
   Four players earned berths by nature of the must-have team rule:
Mike Lieberthal (Philadelphia), Ryan Dempster (Florida), Shane
Reynolds (Houston) and Bob Wickman (Milwaukee). The Padres' lone
bidwent to Trevor Hoffman, who was deserving.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest oversight was Florida second baseman Luis Castillo,
who is hitting .351 with 35 steals, but there's a logjam of great
N.L. second basemen this season. Jeff Kent, Edgardo Alfonzo and
Jose Vidro are all deserving. It would have been nice to see the
Padres third baseman and ex-Fullerton star Phil Nevin make the
team, but he hit under .200 in June. ...
</P>
<P>
   The fans deserve a lot of credit for voting non-traditional
candidates like Giambi and Dye into the A.L. starting lineup. Cal
Ripken and Ken Griffey Jr. earned spots on their rep, which is
understandable and tolerable. ...
</P>
<P>
   Glaus and Darin Erstad deserve their berths on the A.L. team,
but it's still amazing to realize all-time Angel Tim Salmon has
never been on the A.L. All-Star team. ...
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield and Kevin Brown of the Dodgers are also
deserving, especially Sheffield, who is having a career season. But
he also isn't turned on by these things (neither is Brown), and it
would have been nice to see Eric Karros, who has comparable power
numbers, make his first All-Star team. ...
</P>
<P>
   One way to get around this problem is to eliminate the one
team/one-man concept when it comes to selecting the 30-man roster.
One player from each team without a representative could then be
added. Who cares if that causes a 35-man roster? Not me. ...
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Dodgers/Angels report: Mike Piazza was selected to start at
catcher for the seventh consecutive season, and Pedro Martinez is
only skipping the game and the starting nod because the Red Sox are
paranoid about his health. Meanwhile, the two big names that left
the Angels in the offseason were named to the team, St. Louis
outfielder Jim Edmonds and Cleveland pitcher Chuck Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping Edmonds gets to bat against Finley and Disney
execs are forced to watch. ...
</P>
<P>
   Cox took only two relievers and only has one shortstop, Barry
Larkin. Torre took four closers. Giambi's election was the first
for an A's player since Mark McGwire and Jose Canseco were elected
in 1992. Royals outfielder Jermaine Dye will be the first Royals
starter since ... George Brett? No, Bo Jackson. ....
</P>
<P>
   Hoop buzz: Grant Hill is leaning toward signing a free agent
deal with Orlando. But Spurs' free agent Tim Duncan hasn't
committed whether that will play a part in his decision to play in
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The real hot talk is the status of Tracy McGrady and Eddie
Jones. McGrady is the guy most G.M.s want most, and Jones' name
seems to pop up in every trade rumor. The latest has him being
traded to Chicago, but Miami's interested, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers would like to obtain Miami's P.J. Brown and/or
Portland's Brian Grant. But a Brown-for-Glen Rice deal, or any
other, isn't likely until Hill, Duncan and McGrady have landed.
Boston also wants Indiana's Austin Croshere. ...
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams is in agony because daughters Venus and Serena
must play each in the Wimbledon semis. Better he should look
forward, because both of his daughters are playing better than
Lindsay Davenport, who plays Jelena Dokic in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The problems with men's tennis are underscored by the fact Pete
Sampras didn't face a single seeded player enroute to the men's
semifinals, and semifinal opponent Vladimir Voltchkov isn't seeded,
either. Andre Agassi gets the difficult Pat Rafter in the other
men's semifinals. ...
</P>
<P>
   The anti-all-star? Kenny Lofton got the most votes of anyone not
on the team, with 1,126,846. McGriff, Lawton and
man-without-a-position DH Edgar Martinez didn't make the top 10 (or
20) at their positions.
</P>
<P>
   The N.L. player with the fewest votes? Lieberthal with 282,695.
And what does it say that Sheffield had the second-fewest with
292,277? ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
