<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT PADRES, PLOT A DIRECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Los Angeles Dodgers managing general partner and CEO
Bob Daly will be at his Dodger Stadium office in late July, talking
with the team's hierarchy about a trading-deadline move.
</P>
<P>
   The move figures to involve a starting pitcher, but whether one
is coming or going could depend heavily on the next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   If the path of the Dodgers' 7-5 win against San Diego on
Wednesday at Qualcomm Stadium is any indication, the Dodgers will
be looking to acquire a pitcher to make a playoff push. They
rallied from a five-run deficit thanks to four homers to end a
losing streak at three games, and they still believe the postseason
is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Darren Dreifort and Mark Grudzielanek began the comeback
with home runs in the fifth inning. Todd Hundley tied the game 5-5
with a three-run homer (No. 16) off reliever Carlos Reyes in the
sixth inning, and San Diego-raised Eric Karros broke the tie in the
top of the eighth with a two-run homer off Matt Whiteside.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, who played at Patrick Henry High here, has 24 homers and
69 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers possess that type of comeback ability, but their
play remains inconsistent. A loss would have put the Dodgers
(42-40) at .500 for the first time since April 8, but the recent
poor play hasn't made Daly ready to restructure the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't contemplate making any changes, not as far as
personnel (front office and on-field staff),'' Daly said. ``I'd
like to win some more games. We may make some player moves that
(general manager) Kevin (Malone) is working on, but for every 10
players discussed, you're lucky if you make one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody on the Dodgers, as far as personnel is
concerned, that has to worry about their jobs. We're going to
finish out the year and hopefully do a lot better. I'd like to see
everybody kick a little more butt. That would be nice, to get
everybody fired up a little bit, but not for threatening anybody.
After the All-Star break, everybody gets their juices going, and I
think it would be good to get them going a little faster.''
</P>
<P>
   How the Dodgers decide to attack the last week of the month,
leading up to the July 31 trading deadline, could hinge heavily on
whether the right-handed Dreifort turning things around.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Dreifort is having a miserable time heading into his
free- agent season. He's 1-6 with a 7.03 ERA in his last 10 starts
after beginning the season 3-1 with a 2.59 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, the Dodgers have been determining the
market value of the 28-year-old, though a deal isn't imminent.
They're also analyzing whether they can compete for the division or
wild-card spot with Dreifort, Eric Gagne and Carlos Perez in their
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make player changes if the right changes come along,
and they're hard to make because everybody wants the same thing _
pitching,'' Daly said. ``They either want starting pitching or
relief pitching, and very few teams want to pick up money so you
have to creatively figure outa way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we thought we could bring the right player to the Dodgers
who could help us this season and give us a much better chance to
finish first or in the wild card, would we (add payroll)? The
answer is yes. But we have to find that player, and what are we
giving up in return? We would make a move and add payroll if we had
to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
