<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL'S THREE-RUN SHOT RINGS UP ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Alex Rodriguez is the glitz and glamour of the Seattle
Mariners, and he threw in some pop with two home runs in their 6-4
victory Wednesday night over the Anaheim Angels before 17,369 at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's second homer of the night _ off losing pitcher Brian
Cooper (3-3) _ was estimated at 455 feet, but the home run that
made the difference did not come from Rodriguez, who will start at
shortstop next week for the American League in the All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell's three-run homer off Cooper in the fifth inning
turned a 3-2 game into 6-2 and propelled the Mariners to their
second win in three games with one to go in the series. Mariners
starter John Halama (8-4) improved to 3-0 lifetime vs. the Angels,
including 2-0 with a 2.31 ERA this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was coming off his first major-league shutout over the
A's, but couldn't make it out of the fifth inning Wednesday. He
went 4 innings and gave up six runs and nine hits.
</P>
<P>
   The victory increased the Mariners' lead in the AL West to
three-and-a -half games over Oakland and seven over the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez hit his first home run in the first inning and might
have received an indirect assist from Rickey Henderson. Henderson
singled to open the game and was on first with one out and
Rodriguez at bat.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's first pitch to Rodriguez was a pitch-out, but
Henderson, always a threat to steal, stayed put. On a 2-2 pitch,
Rodriguez went the other way, hitting the ball over the fence in
right-center field for a 2-0 Mariners lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got it back an inning later when Darin Erstad, one of
two Angels All-Stars, ripped a two-out, two-run double down the
right-field line to tie the game at 2. Both runs were unearned
because second baseman Mark McLemore dropped Bengie Molina's popup
earlier in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, however, knocked Cooper out of the game in the
fifth. First, Rodriguez hit a 455-foot home run on Cooper's first
pitch of the inning. Then, after singles by Edgar Martinez and John
Olerud, Bell hit a three-run homer for a 6-2 Mariners lead,
spelling the end of the night for Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Halama found a groove. After allowing a leadoff
single to Vaughn in the third inning, Halama retired the next 10
Angel batters, the streak ending on Garret Anderson's broken-bat
single to center with one out in the sixth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
