<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANZIA-WINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WINEMAKER WINS RIGHT TO LABELS  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Wine brands that suggest the contents of a
bottle come from Napa, Calif., when they actually come from
elsewhere may be perfectly legal, according to a key ruling handed
down Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   An administrative law judge for the Treasury Department's Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms dismissed charges by the bureau
that Bronco Wine Co. violated the law by putting ``Rutherford
Vineyards'' and ``Napa Creek'' brand names on wines that did not
necessarily contain grapes from either area.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ruled that Bronco Winery, which is based in Ceres,
Calif., only used labels that were approved by ATF.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for the industry,'' said Fred Franzia,
co-owner and chief financial officer for Bronco Winery. He said
there is an obvious distinction between a brand name or trademark
and a contents label: ``No one assumes Hawaiian Punch is from
Hawaii or London Fog raincoats are from London.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was sharply criticized by many Napa winemakers. ``It
is fundamentally unfair to use a brand name with viticultural
significance on a bottle of wine where the grapes do not come from
that area,'' said Tom Shelton, CEO of Joseph Phelps Vineyards in
St. Helena, Calif., and chairman of the Napa Valley Vintners
Association's Winegrowers Appellation Committee. ``In my mind, it's
consumer fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Wineries cannot make up potentially misleading monikers for
their wines today. To qualify as Napa Valley wine, at least 85
percent of grapes must come from the valley. To qualify as Napa
County wine, the percentage is 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is a loophole for geographic brand names that
existed prior to 1986 before rules were revised to make wine
labeling and advertsing more accurate. As a result, hundreds of
labels with geographic connotations were grandfathered. These
include Bronco's ``Rutherford Vineyards,'' ``Napa Creek,''
``Domaine Napa'' and ``Napa Ridge'' brands.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Bronco paid more than $40 million to Beringer for
its well-known Napa Ridge brand, which for at least 15 years has
produced wine with little or no Napa grape content.
</P>
<P>
   Franzia said the main attraction is the name, not the inventory,
and the price would have made no sense if Bronco were required to
bottle high-priced Napa County Chardonnay or Cabernet instead of
similar varieties from Lodi, Calif., and elsewhere that cost
one-half to one-quarter the price.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the favorable ruling by the administrative law judge,
Bronco's wine labeling battles are not over. The ATF director could
have a different view of the case or the ruling could be appealed
in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The issue also is subject to proposed California legislation.
Last Thursday, Assembly Bill 683, backed by the Napa Valley
Vintners Association, was proposed to require wine bearing a Napa
appellation to contain at least 75 percent Napa-grown grapes.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation ``is designed to correct what we view as an
oversight in BATF regulations and is not a vendetta against Fred
Franzia,'' said the association's Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   Vintners association attorney Richard Mendelson added, ``We
believe the California Legislature has the authority if not the
responsibility to protect consumers from misleading or deceptive
labels.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Governmental Organization Committee voted 8 to 1 for
similar legislation. But dissenter Don Perata (D-Oakland) said
there could be problems as a result of the administrative law
judge's ruling Wednesday and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   He believes federal laws take precedence over California law on
wine labeling, noting that some wineries in other counties view
Napa County vintners' legislative efforts as a push for ``unfair
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All sides agree this is prologue to a protracted `Falcon
Crest'-style court fight,'' Perata said.
</P>
<P>
   Bronco and Franzia are no strangers to court contests. In 1993,
Franzia plead guilty to federal fraud charges over passing off
about 1 million gallons of inexpensive wine as premium zinfandel.
</P>
<P>
   Bronco produces 44 million gallons of wine a year and sells much
of it to other bottlers. Recently, it has been buying brands and is
about to open a huge bottling plant at the Napa County Airport to
increase its Napa Valley capacity.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
