<SLUG> BC-MACQ&AMP;A-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MAC Q&AMP;A: UPDATES MAY THAW COLD IMAC  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: My iMac with Mac OS 8.6 often freezes up solid; the only way out
is to turn off the power. I can prevent the problem by
disconnecting both the printer (an HP LaserJet 6L) and the Imation
SuperDisk floppy drive, but of course this rather sharply limits
what I am able to do. When I reconnect either peripheral, I must
accept the likelihood of a hard freeze and loss of data since the
last save, or loss of a Web connection.
</P>
<P>
   Are there patches that might resolve this problem?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: For starters, a simple suggestion: Save your work before you
connect either of those peripherals!
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there better be a way to resolve your problems _
they sound intolerable. The first step is to make sure you have the
latest software for both the peripherals and the iMac. You can find
the latest drivers and firmware updates for the Imation drive at
 &LR; www.super &LR;   &LR; disk.com/sc/scdl.html &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The LaserJet model you mention was designed for use with Windows
PCs, not Macs. It connects to the computer via a parallel port,
something Macs have never had. If you're really using a LaserJet 6L
with your iMac, it must be via Infowave Software's PowerPrint USB
adapter and software. And lo and behold, a quick trip to Infowave's
download page ( &LR; ftp.infowave.com/pub/UPDATES/powerprint &LR; ) reveals a
file called OS8.6-USBfix, which sounds as if it could be just what
you need.
</P>
<P>
   As for the iMac, Apple has released several updates that might
also be relevant to the problems you're experiencing. Which one you
should install depends on the iMac model and Mac OS version you
have. There's a guide of sorts at
 &LR; til.info.apple.com/techinfo.nsf/artnum/n58174?OpenDocu &LR; 
 &LR; ment&AMP;software &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   If I'm reading it correctly, though, the only thing you might
need to add, because Mac OS 8.6 includes most of the other fixes,
is something called Mac OS ROM Update 1.0, which you can read about
at  &LR; til.info.apple.com/techinfo.nsf/artnum/n60408 &LR;  and download
from  &LR; asu.info.apple.com/swupdates.nsf/artnum/n11476 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   If you happen to be connecting the printer and floppy drive via
a USB hub connected to your iMac, you should also check the hub
vendor's site to see if a software or firmware update is available.
Several early hubs had problems with Apple's implementation of USB.
</P>
<P>
   If the problem persists after you've updated all your software,
let me know and I'll go over some basic troubleshooting techniques
in a future column.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'm running Mac OS 8.5 on a Power Mac G3 with a 15-inch display.
Is there any way to enlarge an Internet screen even though it may
require scrolling? Too much stuff, too small type and wrong
contrast turn me off on many Internet sites that I would like to
pursue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You've got several problems wrapped together there. To fix
``wrong contrast,'' all I can suggest is that you try fiddling with
your brightness and contrast settings, either on the monitor itself
or in the Monitors control panel.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``too much stuff,'' you can always tell your browser not
to display graphics and other non-text items. In Netscape Navigator
or Communicator, go to the Edit menu, choose Preferences, click on
the Advanced category and uncheck ``Automatically load images and
other data types.'' In Internet Explorer, go the Edit menu, choose
Preferences, click on the Web Content category (under Web Browser)
and uncheck pictures and other items you want to eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   If you also want to block banner ads (as well as cookies and
other stuff), try WebFree ($20 shareware from
 &LR; www.falken.net/webfree &LR; ) or WebWasher (free for home and education
use, $29 for business users after 30-day evaluation, from
 &LR; www.webwasher.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Too-small type also has several solutions. If you use Internet
Explorer, go to Preferences again, choose the Language/Fonts
category and increase the point size. In the Netscape browsers, go
to Preferences, then choose Fonts under Appearance and increase the
size for both variable- and fixed-width fonts.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, you can leave the font size as is and instead
switch your monitor to a lower resolution, which will make
everything on screen look bigger. Just open your Monitors control
panel or click on the Monitor Resolution tile in the Control Strip
(the one with the black-and-white checkerboard icon) and choose
lower numbers than what you have now.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TIP OF THE MONTH
</P>
<P>
   You may have heard about the Hunger Site
( &LR; www.thehungersite.com &LR; ), a Web site where you can, in effect,
donate food to the hungry just by clicking on a button. (The site's
sponsors contribute enough money to pay for a quarter of a cup of
food to the United Nations World Food Programme for every click on
the button, except that only one click per user per day counts.)
Now, several similar sites have sprung up: The Rainforest Site
( &LR; www.therainforestsite.com &LR; ), WebReLeaf ( &LR; www.webreleaf.com &LR; ) and
the multi-cause FreeDonation.com.
</P>
<P>
   The operators of these sites apparently hope to make money for
themselves with these schemes, but their business models also
produce real help for good causes. My only problem is that too
often I forget or never get around to visiting these sites and
making my daily clicks.
</P>
<P>
   Now that problem has a solution _ a free utility called iDonate.
You click once on its Donate button, and it automatically makes a
virtual click at the appropriate spot on any or all of the sites
mentioned above (or so the developers say _ I can't verify exactly
what the program does). Best of all, you can set it to run
automatically every time you start up your Mac.
</P>
<P>
   You can download a copy at
 &LR; www.donation-manager.com/download.html &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; mac(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
