<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4153 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EMULATORS-GAMES-SFCHR     07-06 1651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMULATORS-GAMES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SMALLER GAME FIRMS SCORE IN COURT AGAINST SONY  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One might expect two tiny software firms facing
a snarl of million-dollar lawsuits from Japanese electronic titan
Sony to buckle under.
</P>
<P>
   But armed with a spate of recent legal victories and millions in
sales, two California companies that make programs that ``emulate''
Sony's PlayStation on a PC are emerging from the fringes of the
video-game industry and gaining palpable respect in the process.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's Electronic Entertainment Expo, the video-game
world's premier trade show, ``everything was whispered,'' said
David Herpolsheimer, president of Hollywood softwaremaker Bleem
Inc. Video-game developers ``would come up to us and say, `This is
really cool.' But they didn't say it too loud because they (were)
afraid of Sony. This year (at E3), it was incredible to see how
things changed. We were welcomed and accepted and these companies
were seeing that we're not pirates or hackers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bleem's eponymous product and the Virtual Game Station, from San
Mateo's Connectix Corp., let consumers play select PlayStation
titles such as Grand Turismo on their PCs at one-third to one-half
the price of the PlayStation console (Connectix also makes a
version for Macs).
</P>
<P>
   Video-gamers have welcomed the products with open arms,
according to the companies. Since its launch last year, Bleem has
sold about 300,000 units. Connectix would not disclose an exact
sales figure but said its Virtual GameStation has sold between
66,000 and 110,000 units.
</P>
<P>
   Sony, worried that its intellectual property may be on the line,
has filed a slew of lawsuits against the firms. But so far, the
courts have sided with the Davids, not Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a judge in U.S. District Court in San Francisco tossed
out seven of the nine counts in a copyright suit Sony filed against
Connectix in January 1999. In that suit and in others, Sony claims
emulators cheapen its brand and infringe on its copyrights because
the software is ``reverse engineered'' _ created by taking apart
Sony's hardware and examining how it functions.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are still wrangling over the remaining trade
secret and unfair competition claims. Last Thursday, Sony dropped a
separate patent suit against Connectix, filed in February, but then
refiled six of the 11 claims the next day to avoid ``procedural
issues that may have been appealable.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the flip-flop, Pamela Samuelson, a law professor at the
University of California at Berkeley, says there is marked momentum
in favor of Connectix _ and by extension, Bleem. Much of it stems
from the early 1990s, when many of the so-called ``interoperability
wars'' were originally fought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts over the years have said that if all you're trying
to do is allow people to play games they already own on their own
machines, that's good for consumers and that's good for
competition,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sony, known for fiercely guarding its technology, doesn't see it
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to assert that we have a legal obligation to
protect our intellectual property,'' said Sony spokeswoman Molly
Smith, ``and we're going to continue to move forward with this type
of litigation to make sure we're doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   The company did not respond to repeated requests for a more
in-depth interview about the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the company has filed so many, however, ties directly
into the ubiquity of its signature gaming machine.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated that 1 in 5 U.S. households has a PlayStation.
And with hundreds of titles on the market for the machine, Sony has
become a ripe target for the emulator companies.
</P>
<P>
   While most of Sony's games start off tied to the PlayStation
console, many end up on computer desktops because developers make
versions playable on PCs. Regardless of the eventual format, Sony
wants the PlayStation disks to run only on the PlayStation console.
</P>
<P>
   Sony and some outside developers say that stance benefits
consumers because the games are built for the console, which means
seamless function and better customer support.
</P>
<P>
   But others say that strategy, and the lawsuits, are Sony's
attempts to dominate video gaming as the company positions its
PlayStation 2 _ due out this fall _ as the Internet and
entertainment hub for the home.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Funk, editor of Electronic Gaming Monthly, notes Sony is
trying to block emulators and simultaneously expand the reach of
the PlayStation hardware. Earlier this month, the company said it
would license the PlayStation 2 ``chip sets'' to third-party
hardwaremakers.
</P>
<P>
   If the initiative goes as planned, PlayStation games could
surface on TV set-top boxes, Internet appliances or wireless
devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to broaden the accessibility of their platform, but
only on their terms,'' Funk said. ``The emulators simply take the
ball out of their court.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuelson is even more blunt. ``Sony is essentially trying to
create a monopoly position for themselves,'' the law professor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Others say Sony has cause for its rash of legal filings.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bleem and Connectix say their products require an original
PlayStation title for play on the PC. But Silicon Valley
intellectual property attorney Rich Gray says copying a PlayStation
CD is a relatively easy endeavor once it's loaded onto a PC. The
next step is a rash of counterfeit games that threaten the
company's software sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Sony, (the lawsuits) are not so much about making a lot of
money as it is keeping the games tied to a platform where it's
difficult to make and use illegal copies of the games _ which are
the real cash cows,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, ``Sony has the right to enforce their copyright,''
Gray said. ``If that means they're preventing someone from playing
it on another platform, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Herpolsheimer and Connectix chief executive Roy McDonald
deny the piracy charge and say their products actually stimulate
Sony sales. The theory goes that if someone has a PC, likes
PlayStation games, but doesn't want to buy the console, they'll buy
an emulator (Connectix's Virtual Game Station sells for $50; Bleem
is priced at $30; PlayStation sells for $99) and some Sony titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our product contributes to Sony's profitability,'' McDonald
said. ``It's generally understood in the gaming industry that
virtually all the profit is in the software, not the platform
itself. Our product creates new consoles for Sony.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony might dispute that. But one thing is for sure: Emulators
threaten the fees Sony garners from outside game developers _ one
of the most lucrative sources of revenue for the company, which
enjoys $63 billion in worldwide sales a year. About 11 percent of
that figure comes from PlayStation-related hardware, software and
licensing.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated that companies like Redwood City's Electronic
Arts Inc. pay a $10-per-game licensing fee to Sony. For that, their
games are played on a console that has sold more than 25 million
units in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   If more consumers buy emulators, developers might switch
allegiance to Microsoft _ which doesn't charge licensing fees for
PC games and is trying to recruit developers for its X-box console,
due out next year.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an issue of quality.
</P>
<P>
   Not all emulated games look the way they do on the PlayStation.
Both Bleem and Connectix have a list of recommended titles that
have been tested with the emulator. While the recommended
PlayStation games look similar to, and in some cases better than,
those played on the console, those not recommended can look blocky
and have glitches in the sound effects. And customer support, for
Bleem anyway, is funneled mainly through its Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Though some expect Bleem and Connectix to prevail in their legal
skirmishes with Sony, the prospects for Bleem and Connectix in the
video-game arena are clouded. Though Virtual Game Station isn't
Connectix's main focus (the company also makes PC emulators for
Macs), a Sony restraining order tied it up in legal limbo for a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Herpolsheimer says the lawsuits cost Bleem its profits last year
_ about $1.5 million _ and ``poison pilled'' the company with
video-game developers in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most video-game developers are cagey when the topic of
emulators comes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ain't got a dog in that fight; that's a hardware battle,''
said Jeff Brown, spokesman for Electronic Arts.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, editor Funk says emulators aren't likely to top
any software best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   But he says emulation technology is another step toward a gaming
world where the game itself, not the device, takes center stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a point where you turn the hardware into the
equivalent of a telephone and what matters is the content on the
other end of the line,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until that happens, the legal death match will continue. At E3,
Bleem unveiled an emulator that will let gamers play PlayStation
titles on the Dreamcast console from Sega _ Sony's archrival. The
Bleem product for Dreamcast is due out later this month. Nintendo,
the gaming giant behind the Pokemon phenomenon, has avoided the
fray by sticking to a cartridge format for its N64 console.
Cartridges are generally trickier to emulate or copy.
</P>
<P>
   Sega has remained mum on the topic. And though Sony will not
comment on whether it will take legal action, many video-game
insiders expect it.
</P>
<P>
   For Herpolsheimer, who thinks one of these emulator cases will
eventually end up in the U.S. Supreme Court, even the rumor of
another Sony lawsuit is reason enough to continue pumping out
Bleem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd probably be done with PlayStation if Sony didn't keep
suing us and costing us money,'' Herpolsheimer said. ``It's almost
like we have to keep selling it.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
