<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CHANGES IN MEXICO MAY HURT U.S. FIRMS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ President-elect Vicente Fox's pledge to improve
the livelihood of workers in Mexico played well with voters, but
the promise could have a serious impact on the many U.S. companies
with manufacturing facilities south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   If Fox succeeds in boosting Mexican workers' wages, U.S.
manufacturers, including a number of Silicon Valley technology
enterprises, may be forced to look elsewhere for the cheap labor
that helps keep their products competitive on store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long run, though, higher pay for Mexican workers may
end up expanding the market for U.S. goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that changes the economic status quo would be a
challenge,'' said Ruben Barrales, chief executive of San Jose,
Calif.'s Joint Venture: Silicon Valley Network, a coalition of
local companies and governments. ``It may mean that for really
cheap labor, companies will have to go to other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive, has said he will strive to
ensure that incomes rise higher than the rate of inflation _ now
running about 10 percent _ during his first year in office.
</P>
<P>
   However, this may be easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still Mexico,'' said John Schick, director general of the
Mexico Consulting Group, a San Francisco firm that advises U.S.
companies on investing in the country. ``Things are not really
going to change for another generation.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he predicted that Fox will offer a variety of
incentives to woo U.S. high-tech firms, and that Mexico may
eventually prove to be a more-attractive overseas outpost for
Silicon Valley than low-overhead rivals like China and India.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things change fast in the Valley, and Mexico allows people to
just hop on a plane and get down there,'' Schick said. ``Compared
to China or India, it is so much easier to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Exports accounted for nearly a third of Mexico's gross domestic
product last year, up from 13 percent in 1993, before the North
American Free Trade Agreement with the United States and Canada was
implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican government officials say that about half the 3.3 million
jobs created since 1995 are export-related and that such jobs
usually pay better.
</P>
<P>
   The tech boom in the United States has not been lost on
growth-hungry Mexico's economic planners, and there has been a
concerted effort in recent years to attract more technology
enterprises to the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very aggressive about it,'' said Douglas Smurr,
director of the California Office of Trade and Investment in Mexico
City. ``And people have been very impressed with the amount of
skilled labor in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of these skilled workers _ young, well-educated people in
their 20s and 30s _ are now flocking to Guadalajara, where what
some call a ``Little Silicon Valley'' has taken root as an
increasing number of tech companies open plants in the area.
</P>
<P>
   In just one example of Guadalajara's attractiveness to U.S. tech
manufacturers, Milpitas, Calif., electronics-maker Solectron Corp.
said recently that it may hand pink slips to as many as 850 of the
1,500 workers at its Georgia plant as it expands operations in the
Mexican city.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which produces cellular phones as a subcontractor
for other manufacturers, cited cheaper labor as being its chief
reason for the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a difficult decision driven by changing market
conditions,'' Fred Forsyth, president of Solectron Americas, said
in a statement. ``Simply put, most of our competitors and customers
have already moved cell phone manufacturing to lower labor-cost
geographies, and we must take this action to remain competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Higher wages in Mexico would undercut this advantage. But Andrew
Rose, a professor of international trade at the University of
California at Berkeley's Haas School of Business, said it would
ultimately be a plus for the United States if Fox prevailed in
raising Mexican wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Higher wages mean higher demand for our products,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he dismissed the suggestion that Mexico can compete
with the likes of China and India for the lion's share of excess
tech production from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's economy, Rose said, is simply too well-developed to
allow creation of the sort of tech sweatshops that have popped up
in China and India.
</P>
<P>
   He and other observers agreed that the most likely scenario is
that Mexico will continue the economic reforms begun under previous
presidential administrations, and that Fox will probably succeed in
attracting more foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man is a businessman,'' said the Mexico Consulting Group's
Schick. ``He thinks as an entrepreneur. This is bound to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
