 VISA USA MOVING HEADQUARTERS TO SAN FRANCISCO  &HT;     By KELLY YAMANOUCHI 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Visa USA announced plans Wednesday to shift its
headquarters to downtown San Francisco from Foster City, Calif., in
a move designed to bring it closer to member banks and ease
commuting problems for its employees.
</P>
<P>
   The new office, which will take up four floors at 123 Mission
St., will house 200 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The first contingent of employees is expected to move into the
new headquarters in November with a second and final group
scheduled for April.
</P>
<P>
   The giant financial services company said it is making the move
in anticipation of rapid growth and worsening traffic conditions
around the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the chief executive officer and executive management,
six other departments will make the move: advertising and brand
management, consumer products, corporate relations, emerging
technologies, e-Visa and smart cards.
</P>
<P>
   Some Visa USA and Visa International employees will continue to
work at 900 Metro Center Blvd. in Foster City.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is leasing the new office space for seven
years through real estate agency Michael Lydon &AMP; Co., says that the
addition of the San Francisco location may lead to a regional
network of work sites from which employees can choose.
</P>
<P>
   Visa USA, which also has offices in San Mateo and Hayward,
employs about 710 in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a presence in San Francisco really helps us,'' said
Susan Forman, a vice president at Visa USA and head of the
transition efforts. ``We're really behind in this move. It will
make us a better employer in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   With Caltrain, Muni, Muni Metro and BART transit locations
nearby, Visa USA hopes that the office will be more convenient to
employees who are fed up with rush-hour traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't improve the commute for everyone, but it will improve
for some,'' Forman said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the San Francisco move, the company is
considering options to ease the commute for employees _ including
carpools and vanpools, telecommuting, alternative work schedules,
and a satellite office outside San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really doing this because we want to retain and attract
talent to Visa,'' Forman said. ``With the current pressures of the
new economy, with the commute becoming worse and worse in this
area, we feel that we need to become a more flexible employer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Hauptman, spokeswoman for the San Francisco Chamber of
Commerce, said Visa's move makes sense. ``San Francisco is the
leading financial center on the West Coast,'' she said. ``The
public transportation systems are getting better and better all the
time. Muni is showing vast improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Yamanouchi at  &LR; kyamanouchi(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
