<HEADLINE>
MEDIA BYTES: HEAR THE ONE ABOUT THE COMEDY WEB SITE THAT MADE
A  PROFIT?
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How many comedy sites does it take to make money
on the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   Ummm ...
</P>
<P>
   Why did the comedy site try to turn a profit when it knew Net
content was a hopeless business?
</P>
<P>
   Come on, these are the jokes, folks _ and while they may not get
me a job with Jay Leno, they're at least as funny as some of what's
passing for humor online these days.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't really laugh too much while I surfed around
 &LR; www.comedyworld.com &LR; , the site started by San Francisco's Comedy
World. The company announced last week that Sandra Bernhard and the
Canadian comedy troupe Kids in the Hall will participate in the
site, so maybe things will get funnier.
</P>
<P>
   But the business plan has raised some serious money _ $10
million from the venture capital firm Attractor and private
investors, including ZDNet chief executive officer Dan Rosensweig
and Cnet CEO Shelby Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   That business plan, like many of the new content plays, involves
distributing the content over not only the Internet, but also
television, radio and even wireless devices like cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really building a Web site,'' Comedy World CEO Jody
Sherman said. ``We're building a media network.''
</P>
<P>
   But he does acknowledge that the Web stands at the core of the
operation. And that makes sense: Comedy World hopes to use the low
cost of Web distribution to create a cult hit online. If it can do
that, it could then sell that hit to television at much more
favorable terms than if it started shopping untried concepts to
entertainment execs.
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting idea, but it may have trouble working.
``It's a way to blow a lot of money on a Web site, or not much
money on a production company,'' said Malcolm Maclachlan, a media
and e-commerce analyst for IDC. ``Web economics are not working out
too well in the entertainment space, so they're looking at the Web
as a tool, rather than their main means of distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Other sites are making it work on a smaller scale. For instance,
the Onion ( &LR; www.theonion.com &LR; ) _ a truly funny satire of newspapers
_ has ads on its site, and also has off-line counterparts, like a
print edition and a book. A relatively new site, Modern Humorist _
at  &LR; www.modernhumorist.com  &LR; _ also has plans to branch into other
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to create a brand, more than create hits,'' said
Michael Colton, Modern Humorist's co-editor and co-founder and a
former reporter for Brill's Content and the Washington Post. The
company is seeking book deals, putting pieces online and on the
radio, and writing funny pieces for hire that run in magazines and
other Web sites (such as a parody that Fortune magazine ran called
``MisFortune'').
</P>
<P>
   His model is the old National Lampoon, which used a print
magazine to launch radio, stage and screen ventures in the 1970s.
He hopes to build a similar stable of talented humor writers, using
the Web as a base.
</P>
<P>
   Colton said Modern Humorist has venture backing in the ``low
seven figures.'' He was on the road covering the presidential
primaries for Brill's when his partner had the meeting with Carlin
Ventures; Colton listened in ``from a cell phone in the bathroom of
John McCain's campaign bus. I could barely hear as I rocked back
and forth on the Straight Talk Express.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more popular sites for humor is at
 &LR; www.comedycentral.com &LR; , the Web home of the cable channel Comedy
Central. But that's a different proposition, using the Web to
promote a broadcast property by, for example, allowing users to
download previews of ``South Park'' bits.
</P>
<P>
   The Humor Network operates online only, but it takes advantage
of the Internet's biggest killer app: &QL; 
e-mail. With its flagship site at  &LR; www.joke-of-the-day.com &LR; , the
New York company sends out a joke to more than 1 million people
every day. The way I figure, the Internet became popular in no
small part because of people e-mailing each other jokes (usually
dumb ones, but that didn't stop many of my friends).
</P>
<P>
   Comedy World has about 45 people working in its Financial
District office, primarily in Web development, marketing and
business development, and it has a studio in Los Angeles where it
creates and produces the content. And it's a lot of content: 18
hours a day of live programming, much of it featuring comics like
Bobby Slayton, Sue Murphy and CEO Sherman's favorite, the duo of
Travis Clark and Greg Behrendt, who host ``The Manversation'' every
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It also has a variety of other jokes and gags, many sorted by
topic. And how's this for a Web advantage: You can search for a
word, like ``lightbulb,'' and find 16 relevant jokes.
</P>
<P>
   So to share Comedy World's sparkling wit, and leave you
laughing, here's a short sample: Why did the spider cross the road?
</P>
<P>
   To get to another Web site.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you do the same.
</P>
<P>
   HAIL TO ``THE CHIEF'': Because I'll someday be working for the
Hearst Corp. _ assuming, of course, that Hearst's deal to buy The
Chronicle goes through, maybe even during my lifetime _ I found it
worthwhile last week to meet with David Nasaw, author of ``The
Chief,`` an acclaimed new biography of William Randolph Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to know: Did Hearst ``horse-trade'' his editorial pages
for business or political favors, as the publisher of the San
Francisco Examiner, his once-flagship newspaper, is now accused of
doing? Nasaw's answer: Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chief was above that,'' Nasaw said. ``He didn't do favors.
He expected politicians to do favors for him. He wouldn't have sold
his editorials to anybody. They were his pages. He would not have
engaged in this kind of horse-trading.''
</P>
<P>
   I was also interested in Nasaw's analysis of Hearst as the
builder of the first true media powerhouse, the forerunner of
today's megamedia operations. In his heyday, Hearst boasted 20
million readers for his newspapers, magazines, news services, radio
shows and newsreels _ 1 out of every 5 Americans. By comparison, a
combined 7 million people watch network anchors Dan Rather, Peter
Jennings and Tom Brokaw each night _ and the population has doubled
since Hearst's day.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hearst's attempt to use that media power to foster his own
ambitions and promote his own opinions changed the shape of the
media forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't interested in objectivity. He was interested in
advocacy journalism,'' Nasaw said. ``If you didn't like it, you
could read another newspaper. ... He wrote and signed his own
editorials, and put them on the front page.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst took many unpopular views. ``He was against American
involvement in World War I, and he was against the New Deal,''
Nasaw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the negative poster boy for advocacy journalism,'' Nasaw
said. ``It's totally gone because of him. You don't see (Rupert)
Murdoch writing editorials. You know there's strong opinions there.
You know Ted Turner has strong opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   But the modern moguls keep their views out of their
publications, Nasaw said: ``They all learned from Hearst.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Dan Fost at  &LR; fostd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
