<HEADLINE>
NO DEALS ON TABLE, SAYS DALY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The Los Angeles Dodgers have a $90 million payroll,
are two games above .500 and certainly are not playing up to
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodgers managing general partner and CEO Bob Daly is a
patient man who doesn't make changes without putting loads of
thought into it.
</P>
<P>
   So before the Dodgers rallied to score the final seven runs in a
7-5 win at San Diego on Wednesday to end a losing streak at three
games, Daly spoke about the club's plans for the second half of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   And he said the only changes coming during the season would be
in player personnel and not in the front office or with the
on-field staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't contemplate making any changes, not as far as
personnel (front-office and on-field staff),'' Daly said. ``I'd
like to win some more games. We may make some player moves that
(general manager) Kevin (Malone) is working on, but for every 10
players discussed, you're lucky if you make one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody on the Dodgers, as far as personnel is
concerned, that has to worry about their jobs. We're going to
finish out the year and hopefully do a lot better. I'd like to see
everybody kick a little more butt. That would be nice, to get
everybody fired up a little bit, but not for threatening anybody.
After the All-Star break, everybody gets their juices going and I
think it would be good to get them going a little faster.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' win against the Padres could be the spark that
ignites a nice run to the break, especially with all-star
right-hander Kevin Brown closing out the series today.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Darren Dreifort and Mark Grudzielanek began the comeback
from a 5-0 deficit with solo homers in the fifth inning and
switch-hitting catcher Todd Hundley, who's started three of the
five games on the road trip, tied it 5-5 with a three-run homer
(No. 16) off reliever Carlos Reyesin the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego-reared Eric Karros broke the tie in the top of the
eighth with a two-run homer off Matt Whiteside. Karros, who played
at Patrick Henry High, has 24 homers and 69 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big hit was Hundley, tying the ballgame and giving us an
opportunity to win,'' Karros said. ``He's got to be in the lineup
every day. That's the bottom line. What he provides for this
offense, and that's not to take anything away from Chad (Kreuter),
but Hundley can turn the game around with one swing. He can do it
any at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (42-40) possess that type of comeback ability, but
their play remains inconsistent. They avoided falling to .500 for
the first time since April 8. Even so, the Dodgers are six games
behind Arizona and in fourth place, and team officials plan to add
a starting pitcher at the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make player changes if the right changes come along,
and they're hard to make because everybody wants the same thing _
pitching,'' Daly said. ``They either want starting pitching or
relief pitching, and very few teams want to pick up money so you
have to creatively figure out a way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we thought we could bring the right player to the Dodgers
who could help us this season and give us a much better chance to
finish first or in the wild card, would we (add payroll)? The
answer is yes. But we have to find that player, and what are we
giving up in return? We would make a move and add payroll if we had
to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
