<HEADLINE>
SONICS GO INTO FULL-COURT PRESS TO RETAIN LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is good to be able to concentrate on the topic of
Rashard Lewis' future.
</P>
<P>
   At 20 years old, Lewis is the best example of what can happen to
a talented high school basketball player when he is drafted by an
NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   If the league is in trouble because Michael Jordan is playing
golf and the incoming rookies have little or no college experience,
watching a player like Lewis flower isn't a bad alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The fresh legs. The willingness to put your head down and learn.
</P>
<P>
   The games when suddenly _ even in playoff contests featuring
Karl Malone, John Stockton and Gary Payton _ Lewis' bounce and
promise are the most impressive things to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just shows you what a lot of hard work can get you,''
Lewis said Wednesday at the Sonics training facility. ``Not being
drafted right away, being drafted in the second round, people
saying you weren't going to make it, a lot of the negative things _
it just shows you how much hard work can help you. Being a nice guy
and being yourself helps in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got the game to play in the NBA, if you've got the
heart and the work ethic, you can make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years into his pro career, Lewis emerged last season as
something just short of the Sonics' saving grace.
</P>
<P>
   In a sketchy second half of the season, just around the time
when nearly every other Sonics player was in a huff, confused,
depressed, playing poorly, not talking or throwing VCR remote
controls, Lewis soared.
</P>
<P>
   We are not talking about ignorance is bliss.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is a sharp guy. He's also nice, hard-working and, as much
as he might hate the reputation, sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   His quiet resolve has helped him grow and improve at a rate that
critics of the NBA's youth movement never dare predict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I played at the end of the season, a lot's going to be
expected of me this season, so that's the reason I'm working out. I
feel like I could have done better,'' Lewis said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is working out with the Sonics' L.A. summer league squad.
Everyone hopes that Lewis' willingness to play this summer is an
indication that the coveted free agent will re-sign with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis places great importance on the chance to play, to be a
starter, to be a star.
</P>
<P>
   His primary consideration will be ``where would I be playing the
most, where would I be starting. It won't be totally financial. No,
I wouldn't say that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are desperate to re-sign Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   A host of NBA teams, depending on which way the free-agent
dominoes fall, will call with offers _ some, no doubt, offering
more than the Sonics' initial $3.9 million bid.
</P>
<P>
   If Tracy McGrady leaves Toronto, the Raptors might come up with
as much as $5.5 or $6 million. Now that Detroit appears about to
lose Grant Hill, the Pistons might ante up. Same with the Bulls.
Maybe even the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the teams with salary cap room will call, and probably
everyone else who doesn't have cap room, too,'' Sonics president
Wally Walker said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone understands what Lewis has done for himself since being
drafted by the Sonics with the 32nd overall pick in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's paid his dues, and now all the people who missed the boat
want to jump on the bandwagon,'' Sonics assistant coach Dwane Casey
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has proved everyone wrong. He has worked hard. He's gone
from being a second-round pick to being the kind of guy people talk
about as a franchise player.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of a full-court press to make sure Lewis understands how
much he is wanted in Seattle, Sonics owner Barry Ackerley took
Lewis out for a private talk the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only other player Mr. Ackerley has ever done that for is
Gary Payton, so I think Rashard understood how important he is to
the entire organization. He is the top priority,'' Casey said.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, although he has not called Lewis like he said he was
going to, has been a strong advocate. Payton has said Lewis is a
main option on the team, a 6-foot-10 small forward who should be
scoring 20 points and getting marquee billing in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone worried that the All-Star point guard's volatile
nature has negatively impacted the soft-spoken Lewis, Lewis has
grown up enough to be able to handle Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just Gary being Gary,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearing him say I can score 20 and play 30-plus minutes does
make a difference. He is our leader. He's the captain of this team.
We are going to follow him. He's going to be the one who leads us
to wherever he's going to lead us to,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes Gary a while to respect a lot of young guys. Toward
the end of the year, he gained a lot of respect for me, and that
was a good feeling, and very important for me. That helped me play
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis also has a great rapport with Casey and Nate McMillan, two
teachers who have helped Lewis accelerate his NBA learning process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nate and Dwane are the big part of this team. Without them,
I'm not sure what would have happened. They're great assistant
coaches. They're here for you and help you in any way you need.
They're always addressing things,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have identified Lewis as an emerging star with a
limitless future.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, they might be able to convince Lewis that they can
do as much for him as he can for them.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
