<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ HOMERS TWICE TO POWER MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ There's nothing like being picked the creme de
la creme.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seems for Alex Rodriguez, whose bat had looked just a
little sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Tuesday, when he was named the starting
shortstop for the American League All-Star team. Once again
recognized as the best of the best, Rodriguez has celebrated with
typical Rodriguez fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   He had two homers Wednesday night to help carry the Mariners to
a 6-4 victory over the Anaheim Angels at Edison Field. The night
before, he homered in his first at-bat and added a sacrifice fly
later in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been feeling pretty good about what I'd been doing for a
week or two now,'' Rodriguez said after homers Nos. 23 and 24.
``The last couple of days, though, it all came together.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night he homered with a man on in the first, then hit
a solo shot in the fifth that was the trigger for a four-run
inning, the bigger blast being a three-run bomb by David Bell.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the solo homer to left that had the Mariners talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might be the longest ball I've seen hit all year,''
manager Lou Piniella said. ``That was huge. But what we've seen the
last two nights is why Alex is an All-Star. He's a good player, and
tonight was a great example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, Rodriguez and Bell got starter John Halama (8-4) out
to a 6-2 lead. And the long ball helped the Mariners add another
game to their lead in the AL West. With Oakland losing in Texas,
Seattle has a 3{-game lead over the A's, the Mariners' biggest lead
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't only the long ball that proved the salve for the
wound left by the late loss to the Angels on Tuesday. The Mariners
got a nice game from Halama, who allowed just two earned runs, and
terrific relief work from Brett Tomko (21/3 innings) and Kazuhiro
Sasaki, who put the Angels away with a big ninth inning, cutting
through the heart of the Angels offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the two relievers did was huge,'' pitching coach Bryan
Price said. ``Tomko came in with the bases loaded (in the sixth
inning) and went right after the hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomko induced a popup from Benji Gil, and that was the last best
chance for the Angels to strike. Anaheim got almost nothing against
Tomko in the seventh and eighth, and Sasaki retired Scott Spiezio,
Mo Vaughn and Tim Salmon, each as the potential tying run, in the
ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen has been our backbone here all year,'' Rodriguez
said. ``You can't say enough about what they've done for us.
They're a big reason why we're where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki did walk the first man he faced, Darin Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need to know about Kaz you can get by watching his
mound demeanor,'' Price said. ``He's comfortable in what he does,
and he's doing it extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, so is Halama. Wednesday night was one of those times.
He might have been pitching to stay in the rotation. If so, he did
a creditable job. The two runs he allowed in the second inning were
unearned, thanks to a dropped pop fly by Mark McLemore. Halama
wasn't threatened again until the sixth, when all manner of hits
cheap and freakish showed up to chase him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched the game I had to pitch; I threw strikes, made them
swing,'' Halama said. ``In the sixth, they had to swing, and some
of the balls they hit just found the holes. There's nothing I can
do about that.''
</P>
<P>
   With Seattle holding a 6-2 lead entering the bottom of the
sixth, bad luck caught up with Halama. Garret Anderson singled, and
from that point on, the Mariners' lead began to burn off faster
than sunscreen on a 90-degree Southern California day. Benjie
Molina singled to left with two outs. Then Adam Kennedy beat out a
single to shortstop, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Edgard Clemente singled to right, bringing home one run. And
Erstad chopped a grounder that hung in the air like a balloon left
over from the Fourth of July, refusing to come down until another
run had scored and Erstad was safely at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only walked one man all night,'' Halama said. ``I'm happy
with the job I did. Some of those infield hits and choppers no one
can do anything about.''
</P>
<P>
   Price went a step further, saying ``with any kind of luck at
all, that might have been the best inning John pitched the entire
game. But the bounces don't always go your way.''
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded and the game on the line, Tomko took over.
He got Gil to pop out _ to McLemore, who squeezed this one good.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth inning, Sasaki struck out Vaughn on a high
fastball, then got Salmon to pop out to McLemore.
</P>
<P>
   The M's are a season-best 16 games over .500 (49-33) and the
winners of four of their past five, 12 of 15 and 22 of 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 0240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
