<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4160 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGEL2-LADN-(SLAN     07-06 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGEL2-LADN-(SLANG)...WRITETHROUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ, BELL RING UP ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Alex Rodriguez is the glitz and glamour of the
Seattle Mariners, and he threw in some pop with two home runs in
their 6-4 victory over the Anaheim Angels on Wednesday night in
front of 17,369 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's second homer of the night _ off losing pitcher Brian
Cooper (3-3) _ was estimated at 455 feet, but the home run that
made the difference did not come from Rodriguez, who will start at
shortstop next week for the American League in the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell's three-run homer off Cooper in the fifth inning
turned a 3-2 game into 6-2 and propelled the Mariners to their
second win in three games with one to go in the series. Mariners
starter John Halama (8-4) improved to 3-0 lifetime vs. the Angels,
including 2-0 with a 2.31 ERA this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A-Rod (Rodriguez) is a good hitter and he's going to hit
pitches,'' Cooper said. ``I looked at the tape and the first homer
was a good pitch. The next homer was a first-pitch fastball....
I'll give up a solo homer. But I hung a change-up to Bell and that
really killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the first home run he's hit in his life,'' Angels
manager Mike Scioscia said of Bell, who has six homers this season
compared to 24 by Rodriguez. ``It's not like saying the sky fell
because he hit a homer. (Cooper) made a mistake and when you make a
mistake it can hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was coming off his first major-league shutout in a win
over the A's but couldn't make it out of the fifth inning
Wednesday. He went 4 innings and gave up six runs and nine hits,
but after the game he said he felt as good as he has all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference was when I made good pitches, they fouled them
off, and when I made a mistake, they didn't miss many,'' Cooper
said. ``I wasn't concerned about the three runs because I know we
can score and the bullpen's solid. I thought I could get into the
sixth or seventh giving up three or four runs. But then Bell hits
the home run ... you can't give up three-run bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory increased the Mariners lead in the AL West to
three-and-a-half games over Oakland and seven over the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez hit his first home run in the first inning with Rickey
Henderson on first for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got it back one inning later when Darin Erstad, one
of two Angels All-Stars, ripped a two-out, two-run double down the
right-field line to tie the game 2-2. Both runs were unearned
because second baseman Mark McLemore dropped Bengie Molina's popup
earlier in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper escaped trouble in both the second and fourth innings
despite a couple of errors _ one physical and one mental _ by
second baseman Adam Kennedy. In the second inning, the Mariners'
Mike Cameron hit a grounder to third baseman Troy Glaus that might
have started an inning-ending force play at second. Glaus' throw
was slightly to Kennedy's right, and Kennedy dropped the ball for
an error. However, Cooper was able to escape by striking out
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, with Bell on first base, Robert Machado bunted to
Glaus, who fielded the ball cleanly with his bare hand. But he
didn't throw to first because Kennedy was late getting to the base.
First baseman Mo Vaughn had come toward the plate when Machado
squared to bunt.
</P>
<P>
   But Cooper got out of that jam, too. He made a diving stop on a
grounder by McLemore, then threw out McLemore at first for the
first out. With the runners now on second and third, Henderson his
a sharp one-hopper to Benji Gil at shortstop. The runners had to
freeze and Gil threw out Henderson for the second out.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper got out of the inning when Cameron flied to center.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, however, knocked Cooper out of the game with four
runs in the fifth, all four coming on the home runs by Rodriguez
and Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``His command was good, he just lost it for a time,'' Scioscia
said of Cooper. ``He's gone through stretches where he gets out of
whack, but he's been able to make adjustments and get out of it.
Unfortunately tonight he couldn't make adjustments before they had
six runs on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got a pair of RBI singles by Edgard Clemente and
Erstad in the sixth, but Brett Tomko (2 scoreless innings) and
Kazuhiro Sasaki (scoreless ninth, 18th save) closed it out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
