<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 08:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4206 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN09-COX     07-06 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Hero of Mexican election was Ernesto Zedillo
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big winner in the Mexican election was Mexico itself, but
the hero of the election was not the successful presidential
candidate, Vicente Fox. It was the outgoing president, Ernesto
Zedillo, whose party's nominee got walloped.
</P>
<P>
   Candidate by default six years ago when the anointed nominee of
the Institutional Revolutionary Party _ PRI in its Spanish language
acronym _ was assassinated, straight-arrow Zedillo stuck to reforms
already tentatively under way and added more, in the end securing
the means and atmosphere that could lead to a peaceful transition
of power.
</P>
<P>
   Could, and did.
</P>
<P>
   Thus ends 71 years of sham democracy, in which PRI come to
perpetuate itself in power through bribery, fraud and simple
muscle, all behind a gloss of democratic forms. In recent years,
that patina has looked more like the sheen of flop sweat.
</P>
<P>
   PRI has long been far more institutional than revolutionary. The
no-succession constitution, in practice, failed to prevent the
entrenchment of power represented by the previous, open-ended reign
of Porfirio Diaz. The party's inner circle hand-picked presidents
who differed in appearance but not in purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Among the results: a stymied economy shuddered by periodic
crises, police and court systems funded under the table and endemic
patronage corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and his National Action Party face formidable challenges in
untangling economic, social and political systems in which PRI and
the state have become so intertwined that often only the subtle can
tell where one ends and the other begins.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, voters outfitted the nation with a Congress in
which power is split among three parties, and while the electorate
was choosing the presidential candidate of a conservative party,
Mexico City voters elected the candidate of the leftist Democratic
Revolutionary Party to their powerful mayoralty.
</P>
<P>
   The only coherent command from that muddle is ``change.'' It
will take an exceptional leader to define the change and assemble
and sustain a constituency for it.
</P>
<P>
   It is promising that all early indications point to a civil
transition, as Zedillo has promised. (And maybe even one less
marred than usual by outgoing retainers grubbing pesos at every
political checkpoint.)
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, little has become the PRI so much in recent years as
the manner of its leaving. Zedillo's predecessor, Carlos Salinas de
Gortari, though he fled into exile from financial corruption
charges, initiated electoral reforms, responding to domestic and
international pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo added political and judicial reforms and used the 1994
financial crisis to install structural economic changes that have
stabilized the economy, making political change more possible and
its promise more credible.
</P>
<P>
   The risk now is that Fox has raised popular expectations so high
the inevitable shortfalls will be disillusioning rather than just
disappointing. A wise U.S. policy will calculate what it can do to
help reduce that risk.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
