<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-CO     07-06 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-COX-1STLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RESENDING TO CORRECT FOURTH PARAGRAPH FROM BOTTOM
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: An apology for everything
 &HT;    For release July 9, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With each passing day, we are exposed to newer and more
imaginative forms of political correctness. It is obvious that
there are no bounds, no time limits. Last week, the Hartford
Courant, the nation's longest continuously published daily
newspaper, apologized in a front page story for accepting
advertising from 1764 until 1823 for the sale of slaves and the
capture of runaways.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's discovery of its past, it said, was rooted in an
apology earlier this year by Aetna, the Hartford-based insurance
company, for selling policies to slave owners.
</P>
<P>
   This is but another in a growing series of apologies for
centuries- and millenniums-old abuses of people because of their
race, their religion or their thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody seemingly is demanding of everyone else some sort of
apology, certainly due but somewhat outdated. If it makes the
Hartford Courant feel good about apologizing, then more power to
them. Same for Aetna.
</P>
<P>
   So let's talk about getting some more apologies. Take runaway
slaves. It would be nice for the descendants of Andrew Jackson to
apologize for his military forays into then Spanish Florida in 1818
to capture slaves who had run away from Georgia and Alabama
plantations and been accepted by the Seminole Indians.
</P>
<P>
   His high success rate got him a military governorship of Florida
once Spain ceded it to the United States and, eventually, the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   I have first-hand knowledge (and microfilm printouts) of
newspapers in Miami in the 1920s and 1930s accepting advertising
for apartment houses and hotels that included the language
``restricted'' or ``Gentiles only.'' Is an apology due for that as
well?
</P>
<P>
   There are as many apologies due for wrongdoing as there probably
are days remaining in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Truman, when he died in 1972, still was waiting for the
Japanese to apologize for Pearl Harbor, and so are the rest of us
to this very day.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has apologized to the Jews for earlier Christian
targeting of them in the betrayal of Jesus Christ, the Germans have
apologized (and paid dearly in cash) for the Holocaust, Bill
Clinton has apologized to us for being caught lying and to Monica
for taking advantage of her misplaced passion, Bill Buckner has
apologized a thousand times to Red Sox fans for letting that ball
slip through his legs in the 1986 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's John Rocker who, no matter how many times he
apologizes for his stupid remarks, will not find redemption because
people won't let it happen. And, besides, he's a blockhead.
</P>
<P>
   I would imagine the Hartford Courant stirred the pot more by
admitting its old role than cooled it.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine those staid Connecticut Yankees being told in
the year 2000 that slaves once were hawked through their daily
newspaper? They probably thought they were clean of the filth of
slavery, that only the South had its hands dirty. And now the local
newspaper exposes them and itself!
</P>
<P>
   Likely, similar advertising was taking place in newspapers all
over the North then, but those papers haven't survived to
apologize. Let's find out who they were, anyway. Let's expose some
more of those Yankees for their hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   I will assure you that apology is not what today's
African-American population is most in need of. Yes, it's
politically correct to cleanse yourself of assumed earlier sins _
even if your antecedents still were in Europe or Latin America
during the American slavery era, and being periodically bopped over
the head themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But ghettos replaced slave plantations (in the North, too) and
they, like the old plantations, didn't alter too much the
lifestyles of the people who live there, except on paper.
</P>
<P>
   As a people, we constantly are angry with each other over
something and insistent on apology as if that can correct the
previous wrong done. I'm not contending that an apology is a
complete waste of time but I recommend as a better way of
correcting things, the motto of my old (Southern) high school: Non
verbis sed operis (not words but deeds).
</P>
<P>
   (Gee, I hope I got that right. If not, I apologize.)
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
