<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A trip to the vet leaves the cats stressed
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cats are in dire need of psychological counseling. They have
post-traumatic stress syndrome after a recent foray to the
veterinarian, a trip that's been delayed far too long because I
knew it would be unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Otto, the 13-pound street tomcat who adopted me three years ago,
and Kiki, the 5-pound Siamese step-cat who regards me as the evil
step-owner, are confirmed homebodies. I can predict almost to the
minute where you will find either of these cats at any given time:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  6 a.m. They are on the back porch impatiently waiting for me
to get my lazy rear up and feed them their allotted can of cat
food. Kiki will be at the door, nudging it with her pea brain in
vain hopes it will somehow miraculously open. Otto will be
stretched out in my Adirondack chair.
</P>
<P>
   If I sleep in on a weekend until, say, 7 a.m., I still often
must get up and feed the cats or they'll meow and raise a ruckus
until sleep is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  7:30 a.m. Kiki will come inside to eat dry cat food while Otto
will go on an early morning rat-hunting expedition.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lunchtime: Both cats will come inside as soon as somebody
comes home to let them in. Otto will sleep the rest of the
afternoon in my desk chair. Kiki sleeps in the game room on the
futon. There are slight variations in sleeping spots, but only
slight.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dusk: Both cats sleep on the back porch, with occasional bouts
of chasing each other around the yard, interspersed with serious
snoozing and occasional bug-catching.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NIghttime: Otto hunts rats while Kiki sleeps on top of the
fence, safe from predators. She doesn't weigh much more than a fat
squirrel.
</P>
<P>
   If we leave town, we must make arrangements for someone to house
sit the cats, even if children are still home. We made the mistake
of leaving the cats inside with a litter box once. They went nuts
trying to get outside, clawing up carpet by the doors. Similarly,
they go nuts trying to get inside after a day or so if we're gone,
scratching the paint. A house sitter is cheaper than new carpet and
paint.
</P>
<P>
   These cats are Republicans. They don't like change. That is my
only excuse for having gone two years without taking them to the
vet. The only thing worse than a mad cat is a mad woman, and it's a
close call. Besides, they're both healthy as can be, which was
confirmed by the vet once I finally got them there.
</P>
<P>
   Kiki went first. I snatched her up and wrestled her into the
cat-carrier, with a loud wailing and gnashing of teeth. Hers, too.
By the time I picked her up at lunch (I actually took a vacation
day to deal with hauling cats to the vet), she had turned into a
feline version of Linda Blair in ``The Exorcist.'' The assistant at
the clinic informed me I would have to help get her out of their
cage and into mine, because she was hissing and clawing at
everything in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, Kiki does not like me, either. We have an uneasy
relationship. She loves my wife, tolerates Otto, but has little use
for any other living creature in the world. So it did not reassure
her to have me saying, in that stupid kitty voice you have to use,
``That's OK, Kiki, we're just going to go home, now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rrreahhhh! I don't know how to spell that sound cats make when
freaked, but you get the idea. I asked if the clinic had any thick
gloves. Kiki would rip me apart just as quickly as a stranger.
Another employee took charge and cornered her and had her in my
cat-carrier in no time. I got home, gave her some more canned food,
and she has spent the last several hours sleeping in the garden and
casting a baleful eye in my direction.
</P>
<P>
   Otto, on the other hand, acted like this was a day in the park.
I put him in the cage with no problem. He meowed a few times on the
way to the clinic, but nothing untoward. He stood on the table,
took his shots and happily accepted ear scratching from all the
two-legged creatures in the room with him. Then he got back in the
cat-carrier, came home, ate some lunch and crashed. But he's still
a bit miffed and cool toward me, whom formerly he thought of as
king of the world _ at least as much as any cat does of its owner.
</P>
<P>
   Both cats were pronounced fit and healthy, though Kiki has a
tartar problem with her teeth, making another appointment
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   I guess Otto has done a better job flossing. Probably it's all
those rat bones.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches (Texas)
Daily Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
