<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERNIEMURRAY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Are you missing a beagle?
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was sitting in my recliner Sunday afternoon trying to decide
what was the most important task at hand; clean out the car or mow
the backyard. Neither one of the these chores should be tacked
without a fair amount of thought. Sometimes, if I think about them
long enough, it's time for bed.
</P>
<P>
   The wife was in the kitchen mopping the floor (obviously unaware
that such jobs need hours of study before diving into them) when
she called me in a tone that could only mean one thing: She wanted
me to do something that involved work.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that when she opened the door into the garage, there
on the mat was a dog. But not just any dog, a beagle, a beagle with
no collar. I've had beagles all my life. I've raised beagles. I
have two beagles in the backyard right now. Now a beagle with no
collar is not surprising. The breed is known for slipping collars.
What was out of character was that she wasn't running, nose to the
ground. Obviously, this beagle had run until she couldn't run
anymore and ended up in our garage.
</P>
<P>
   She gladly came inside, checked out every room, and decided she
would bed down in the den. Trying to move a beagle is like trying
to move a towsack with two pigs in it. Try to pick her up and she'd
roll over onto her back. Finally, we were able to get her out the
door into the backyard so she could meet her dog hosts.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest daughter made a sign that said; ``Found, one
beagle,'' and taped it to the mailbox. Beagle owners spend a good
deal of their time tracking down their wayward dogs. We figured it
wouldn't be long until the owner showed up.
</P>
<P>
   I was about ready to settle back down into mentally debating the
finer points of car cleaning verses mowing when the youngest
daughter brings me what looks like a tiny black pebble. She says
it's a bug. I smushed it and the blood that oozed out left no doubt
that what we had here was a tick. Our beagle visitor must have
picked up a load of them on her run and now she had spread them
into every room of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Quick as a flash I jump into action. I have the girls start
vacuuming. Tell the wife to redouble her efforts on mopping and I
got out the flea and tick powder.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs hate to be dusted almost as much as I hate to do it; I
usually end up with more powder on me than on the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   So the house is covered in ticks, I'm covered in flea power and
our dogs are wondering why there's a strange animal in the
backyard.
</P>
<P>
   I'm beginning to wonder if her owners are out of town for the
weekend. The beagle, however, seems to be perfectly content to
sleep and eat.
</P>
<P>
   Check and see if you're missing a beagle. If so, I think I may
have yours, ticks and all. This whole episode has put me way behind
in fully understanding the merits of car cleaning and grass mowing.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin (Texas) Daily
News.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
