<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4285 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN07-COX     07-06 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exposing the flaws in the system
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If he had been an upstanding citizen, Ernesto Miranda would
undoubtedly have passed through life with little notice.
</P>
<P>
   Because he wasn't, Miranda, a repeat offender, lent his last
name to a litany repeated nightly on television and in real life.
``You have the right to remain silent,'' it begins.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, Miranda, who dropped out of school in the eighth grade,
was arrested on a charge of rape. The victim was an 18-year-old
woman in Phoenix with mild mental retardation. Two hours after
entering a police interrogation room, Miranda signed a confession.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, no one bothered to tell Miranda what people with
money to hire a good lawyer would have been told: He didn't have to
talk.
</P>
<P>
   At trial, Miranda's lawyer objected to the admission of the
confession, but was overruled. Sentenced to 20 years, Miranda
appealed. In 1966, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that if criminal
defendants are not properly advised of those rights, any statements
they make are inadmissable.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda was not carried out of prison on anyone's shoulders. On
retrial, he was convicted on evidence other than the confession.
Paroled in 1972, he wore out the revolving door on Arizona's
prisons. Miranda died in a bar fight in 1976, having wasted most of
his 34 years of life. What survives him is the warning that bears
his name. That fundamental right was upheld last week by the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Earl Gideon was the kind of fellow most of us would
avoid if we saw him on the street. Gideon had seen the inside of a
lot of jail cells since running away from home at 16 to become a
hobo.
</P>
<P>
   Like Miranda, he dropped out of school in the eighth grade. And
like Miranda, Gideon cast a long shadow over the nation's criminal
justice system. He contributed this piece of the litany: ``You have
the right to an attorney. If you cannot afford an attorney one will
be appointed for you''
</P>
<P>
   Arrested in 1961 on a charge of breaking into a Florida pool
hall, the 51-year-old Gideon told the judge he wanted a lawyer but
couldn't afford one.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, the judge said. Guilty, the jury said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Gideon's handwritten petition, U.S. Supreme Court
ruled that ``in our adversary system of criminal justice, any
person hauled into court, who is too poor to hire a lawyer, cannot
be assured a fair trial unless counsel is provided for him. This
seems to us to be an obvious truth.''
</P>
<P>
   On retrial, Gideon was acquitted. Later, Gideon _ who obviously
had no trouble overcoming humility _ told a judge: ``I believe I've
freed more people than Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   This savior, however, died in obscurity in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   David Ruiz is a career armed robber who first ran afoul of the
law at 16. Like Gideon and Miranda, Ruiz is no candidate for
citizen of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Ruiz, a native Austinite, distinguished himself by
being the lead plaintiff in the longest-running prison reform
lawsuit in the nation. As a result of that suit, the courts ruled
that even convicts have fundamental rights.
</P>
<P>
   Released in the mid-1980s, Ruiz came home to something
resembling a hero's welcome. He found honest work for a while, but
evidently couldn't stay away from his former life. He took part in
the armed robbery of a bar in East Austin, was convicted and sent
back to prison. He is still there.
</P>
<P>
   No, these aren't heroes. The cracks and fissures in the criminal
justice system, however, are usually exposed by people you wouldn't
invite to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to Gary Graham, whom some are naively painting as
some kind of hero. He wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Graham shot people and he robbed and he raped. But he protested
to the last that he didn't commit the murder that landed him on
death row.
</P>
<P>
   He went to trial five months after arrest and the trial that
cost him his life lasted less than week _ start to finish. It is
highly doubtful that the defense investigation was either vigorous
or thorough in that short a time.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Graham execution note that his conviction was
reviewed by 20 different courts and upheld. That kind of unwavering
faith in the infallibility of the criminal justice system demands
belief that O.J. Simpson is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   A society's values are reflected in the way it metes out justice
to its poorest and even its most loathsome citizens. To turn a
blind eye to the brutal realities of the system's imperfections is
to lower ourselves to the level of those who don't blink an eye or
feel the least bit of remorse for the damage they do.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin (Texas)
American-Statesman. He can be reached at (512) 445-3667 or at
agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
