<HEADLINE>
WHEN CELEBRITIES ARE PILOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, July 6, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever a celebrity is involved in a small aircraft crash or
even a scare in the skies, a journalistic colleague of mine
displays none of the semi-authentic empathy you'll see oozing from
other media types.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, my friend snorts and raises an I-told-you-so eyebrow, and
puts a new twist on a familiar quote:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another example of the self-cleaning oven of
Darwinism, taken to its highest level,'' she says matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to dehumanize these talented if self-indulgent
artisans and their propensity for zooming around in their own
flying machines. When someone like singer John Denver dies in a
bizarre flying accident, it's obviously the most terrible,
unspeakably heartbreaking tragedy for these immensely talented
individuals and for anyone who knows them and cares about them _
not to mention the millions of fans who feel the loss on some
level.
</P>
<P>
   But let's be honest; let's admit that when famous people have
these kinds of mishaps, some of us withhold at least a portion of
our sympathy because we believe that only odds-defying daredevils
and reckless thrill-seekers will repeatedly take to the skies in
relatively tiny toys that seem to burn and crash with more
regularity than, say, 747s.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the stories of two machismo-tinted actors who recently
had to make emergency landings _ Mr. Dirty Dancing, Patrick Swayze,
and Harrison Ford, he of the deadpan delivery, steadfast reluctance
to talk to the media (a personality trait he's revealed in perhaps
300 interviews with the media) and the mysteriously goofy and quite
butch haircut and earring.
</P>
<P>
   Short guys first. In June, Swayze was flying his 1978
twin-engine Cessna 414-A from Van Nuys, Calif., to Las Vegas when
he was forced to make an emergency landing in a half-finished
subdivision in central Arizona, hitting a light pole and tearing
off part of a wing.
</P>
<P>
   Swayze walked away uninjured _ but the story didn't end there.
</P>
<P>
   First we heard reports that Swayze was engaging in ``erratic
behavior,'' that he had bloodshot eyes and that police were unable
to question him for 12 hours after the crash-landing.
</P>
<P>
   Then three men who at first denied witnessing the crash said
they actually helped Swayze remove a half-consumed 30-pack of beer
and a nearly empty bottle of wine from the plane before they all
went to a hotel. The men were charged with failing to tell police
about this alleged behavior, but as of this writing Swayze hasn't
been charged with anything.
</P>
<P>
   And now we've been told Swayze's seemingly befuddled condition
could have been caused by a broken clamp on a pressure hose in the
cabin, combined with his habit of chain-smoking. God, don't tell
the kids about this or they'll start simulating it at rave parties.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, Harrison ``Han Solo'' Ford was flying his
Beechcraft Bonanza over Nebraska when he encountered dangerous wind
shear and had to make a quick landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was potentially a very dangerous situation,'' said an
official at the Lincoln Municipal Airport. ``He's either very
experienced or darn lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   (The airport official's name: John Kennedy if you can believe
it. Which brings to mind another celebrity pilot, JFK Jr., whose
inexperience possibly cost him, his wife and his wife's sister
their lives in a plane crash.)
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Ford has been ``lucky.'' Last fall,
he was learning how to fly a Bell 206 JetRanger helicopter at the
Van Nuys airport when it went down in a dry riverbed about 45 miles
northwest of Los Angeles. Neither Ford nor his instructor were
harmed.
</P>
<P>
   And while Swayze and Ford were breathing sighs of relief from
their near-tragedies, two well-known horse racing jockeys in Great
Britain were doing the same. Italian-born racing legend Frank
Dettori and Ray Cochrane were in a Piper Seneca aircraft when it
crashed at Newmarket and burst into flames near a racetrack. The
pilot was killed, but the jockeys managed to escape with cuts and
bruises and some broken bones, but no life-threatening injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The beloved John Travolta, who for years has talked about his
passion for flying his own planes, has been equally fortunate on at
least two occasions.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1999, Travolta's plane was forced to make an
emergency landing at Logan International Airport in Boston when an
engine on his Boeing 707 overheated.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years prior to that, Travolta was in the vicinity of
Washington, D.C., at the controls of a Gulfstream II turbojet
carrying a half-dozen passengers when the electrical system failed,
the lights went out and the radio died. Air traffic at four
airports was suspended as Travolta tried to rendezvous with a USAir
Boeing 727 to follow it ``home.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Transportation Safety Board, the
planes narrowly avoided a midair collision. Finally Travolta
managed to navigate his way to safety, making an emergency landing
that did some damage to his plane but left him and his precious
human cargo intact.
</P>
<P>
   Other celebs who have survived emergency landings: Rod Stewart;
Jimmy Buffett (who actually swam to safety after his plane went
down); Kirk Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the list of famous figures who weren't so fortunate in
(mostly) small planes and helicopters is much longer. It includes
the aforementioned Denver, Collins, and JFK Jr.'s three-person
party, as well as Payne Stewart; Otis Redding; Hale Boggs; Rick
Nelson; John Tower; Knute Rockne; Buddy Holly, Ritchie Valens and
the Big Bopper; Rocky Marciano; Thurman Munson; Sen. John Heinz;
eight members of Reba McEntire's band; Will Rogers; Stevie Ray
Vaughan; Patsy Cline; Jim Croce, and several members of Lynyrd
Skynyrd.
</P>
<P>
   Some celebrities, including Aretha Franklin and John Madden,
refuse to fly commercial airlines, let alone small aircraft.
Others, e.g., Wayne Gretzky and Luther Vandross, hate flying but
endure it because they have to. Of course that's irrational and of
course they're more at risk on trains or on the highways, but you
consider the above roster and you wonder if the grounded
celebrities are the ones exercising true logic.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
