<SLUG> BC-WACHNER-COUNTERSUES-KLEIN-FAIRCHILD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINDA BITES BACK: SUES CALVIN FOR $500 MILLION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By VICKI M. YOUNG 
 From DNR 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ Judicial resolution of the nasty brawl between Calvin
Klein Inc. and The Warnaco Group Inc. can be reduced to just one
key central issue: Did CKI's biggest licensee have any rights to
sell CK trademarked products to off-price membership clubs?
 &HT;    On June 26, Linda Wachner's Warnaco Group filed a countersuit in
Manhattan federal court against Calvin Klein Inc. seeking $500
million in damages, charging Klein with an ongoing and intentional
breach of its obligations to Warnaco, under several licensing
agreements.
 &HT;    Warnaco is suing both CKI and Calvin Klein, personally, for
defamation and trade libel, seeking at least $50 million in
compensatory and punitive damages.
 &HT;    The libel and defamation claims arise from the designer's June 5
appearance on ``Larry King Live.'' The suit says that during the
Larry King show, Klein attacked ``the quality of the (jeanswear)
product'' produced by CKI, asserting that it had been
``compromised'' and announced that ``we want our license back, and
we want it to be in the hands of a responsible manufacturing
company.''
 &HT;    CKI, in its original lawsuit, claimed that Warnaco was eroding
the Calvin Klein jeanswear and underwear lines through a flood of
discounting and other unauthorized sales and practices ``that are
the equivalent of counterfeiting.''
 &HT;    Warnaco, however, claimed in the court filing that CKI has no
right under any agreement with Warnaco to approve channels of
distribution, and that Warnaco has every right to sell Calvin Klein
jeanswear through its distribution channels.
 &HT;    ``CKI and Warnaco agreed that each would utilize distribution
outlets that were consistent 'with the reputation and prestige of
the trademarks.' In fact, CKI expressly reserved the right for it
or any of its licensees to sell Calvin Klein trademarked
products... 'in the mass merchandise market and channels of
distribution.' Warnaco expressly reserved the right to sell certain
Calvin Klein trademarked underwear in the mass merchandise
market.''
 &HT;    According to Warnaco, the warehouse membership clubs such as
Costco sell high-end fashion and accessories designs by Prada,
Gucci, DKNY, Cartier, Movado, among others.
 &HT;    In fact, Warnaco's answer to the CKI lawsuit contains 18 pages
showing the breadth of products being sold on Costo.com, including
those by Coach, Prada, Gucci Rush, Tag Heuer, Movado, Chanel, DKNY,
Tommy Hilfiger, Ralph Lauren, in addition to Calvin Klein Jeans,
cK1, Eternity by Calvin Klein and Escape by Calvin Klein.
 &HT;    The firm also said that these stores also sell and continue to
sell an array of CK-branded products made and distributed by other
licensees.
 &HT;    Warnaco is seeking a declaratory judgment to confirm those
licensees' rights to distribute CK product in the membership clubs.
 &HT;    A spokesman for CKI said, ``As the CKI complaint lays out, the
company believes that product was sold to a number of unauthorized
channels and the company believes that the evidence will show that
Warnaco knew it was unauthorized.''
 &HT;    In the original May 30 complaint by CKI, the company charged
that except for a one-time deal in which Warnaco was given the okay
to sell at a membership club to clean up inherited problems in the
distribution channel, ``since 1997, CKI has never approved Costco,
BJ's or Sam's Club as appropriate channels of regular distribution
for close-outs, seconds, or irregulars of Calvin Klein goods _ much
less sales of first-quality goods.''
 &HT;    Also in the Warnaco countersuit, the company charged that a
proposed sale on June 8, 2000, of almost $400,000 of CK jeanswear
to Mode Shirmax Fashions, a Canadian retail chain, fell through
``specifically because of statements'' made by the designer during
the Larry King interview.
 &HT;    Shirmax, Warnaco said, had projected that it would order $1.15
million in jeanswear in 2001. Another customer in Venezuela,
Warnaco said in the suit, ``reduced its order for Calvin Klein
jeanswear from $1.5 million to $500,000.''
 &HT;    The suit also charges CKI and the designer with timing the
filing of its lawsuit to coincide with a speech he gave last month
at the Fairchild CEO Summit, a gathering of fashion industry and
press planned months in advance, where, the suit claims, he
``falsely accused'' Warnaco of counterfeiting CKI apparel.
 &HT;    And, in an apparent attempt to show that CKI officials had no
prior problems with Warnaco's distribution practices _ a key
complaint and a major focus of CKI's own suit against Warnaco _ a
Warnaco press release describes a letter that Klein and his
partner, Barry Schwartz, wrote to Warnaco Oct. 6, 1999, thanking
Warnaco for its ``efforts to make our projects with you so
successful and to ask for your continued support as we move on to
the next level of creativity, productivity and rewards.'' The
letter was referring to the strategic options CKI was about to
explore in its attempt to sell or find a partner.
 &HT;    In response, CKI issued a statement saying: ``Warnaco's
announcement is a thinly veiled attempt to divert attention from
the fact that Warnaco has been systematically violating its
agreements with Calvin Klein Inc. In fact, the letter Warnaco
distributed today to substantiate its claims of support for its
activities by Calvin Klein was a courtesy form letter sent to
dozens of people on the same day last fall announcing Calvin Klein
Inc.'s exploration of strategic options _ a weak reed, indeed, on
which to base a counterclaim.''
 &HT;    The legal jab arises from the May 30 lawsuit filed by CKI and
the Calvin Klein Trademark Trust against it biggest licensee,
Warnaco, and Wachner. Warnaco and CKI are co-owners of the Calvin
Klein Trademark Trust, which owns the Calvin Klein marks.
 &HT;    The main thrust of the CKI suit _ which alleges federal
trademark violations and breach of fiduciary duty and contracts _
centers on CKI's allegations that Warnaco infringed upon and
diluted the Calvin Klein underwear and jeanswear trademarks in the
U.S. by selling unauthorized CKI goods to off-price warehouse
clubs, such as Costco, Sam's Club and BJ's Wholesale.
 &HT;    And the battle apparently is raging outside the courthouse, as
well. According to sources, CKI is trying to stop a multimillion
dollar order that Costco placed with Warnaco this spring. The
Calvin Klein Jeans order is reportedly about to go into production.
 &HT;    Warnaco also disclosed that it and CKI reached a tentative
agreement in April on a $900 million purchase price for the
company, but that Warnaco withdrew because of disagreements over
the scope of the acquisition agreement.
 &HT;    Since then, Warnaco charged, ``Mr. Klein and CKI embarked on the
inconsistent and self-destructive strategy of attacking The Warnaco
Group _ the very same entity that had once saved them from
financial ruin and now provides them in excess of $85 million
annually.''
 &HT;    The Calvin Klein jeans and underwear business under Warnaco's
umbrella represent about $1 billion in sales. Last year the
jeanswear license generated revenues just under $700 million.
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Vicki M. Young is a writer for Fairchild Publications.)
