<HEADLINE>
EYE SCOOPS!  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 COMPILED THE EDITORS AT FAIRCHILD PUBLICATIONS 
 From WWD, W magazine and DNR 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 DONNA'S NEW CAMPAIGN FULFILLS HER DREAM  
 &HT;    ``It's always been a dream of mine to do movies,'' said Donna
Karan, describing the cinematic quality of her fall Collection
campaign.
 &HT;    ``I've always seen my company as a moving experience, as opposed
to a still, from the very first (campaign) shot of a moving car.''
 &HT;    For fall, Karan returns to storytelling in her new ads that
feature actors Milla Jovovich and Gary Oldman, who appeared
together in the film ``The Fifth Element.''
 &HT;    The ads focus on the relationship, emotions and lifestyle of the
couple, unlike recent campaigns that were more product-focused,
said Trey Laird, executive vice-president and corporate creative
director.
 &HT;    ``It's been good that we've done it,'' said Laird of his past
campaigns, ``but sometimes you need to step back and give a healthy
dose of good brand imagery.''
 &HT;    For fall, the company hired Mikael Jansson to photograph, got
the assistance of creative director Fabien Baron and stylist Karl
Templer, hired the actors and headed to France.
 &HT;    ``We set it up like a movie and shot it in Paris. We tried to
capture a relationship between these two characters and what was
going on in their lives,'' Laird said.
 &HT;    ``They make you think, `Do they really get along?''' said Karan.
``Definitely, it's intense. It's like any relationship today. I
wish I had more photographs to show all the aspects of their lives.
The two of them have a chemistry.''
 &HT;    Eight-page inserts will break in the September issues of Vogue,
W and Vanity Fair, and spreads will run in the New York Times
Magazine, Harper's Bazaar, Wallpaper and V. Ads will also appear in
the October issue of Details.
 &HT;    
 SPARKLING DONATION  
 &HT;    Because Elizabeth Taylor was recently proclaimed a Dame of the
British Empire, her fragrance licensee, Elizabeth Arden, is
celebrating by making a donation to her AIDS foundation.
 &HT;    Through August, the company will donate a portion of the
proceeds from sales of Elizabeth Taylor Sparkling White Diamonds.
 &HT;    ``We wanted to honor Dame Elizabeth with a meaningful gift,''
said Susan Taylor, managing director, Elizabeth Arden, U.K. ``We
believe we will be able to donate a substantial sum by the end of
the summer.''
 &HT;    Elizabeth Taylor Sparkling White Diamonds, which launched in the
United States last year, is now available at the 90 branches of
Debenhams throughout the United Kingdom.
 &HT;    
 Golden Greek  
 &HT;    Several biographers have tried in vain to figure out Stavros
Niarchos, the Greek shipping tycoon who died in 1996. But an
upcoming memoir by John Frangoulis, the longtime captain of
Niarchos' yacht, the Creole, should shed more light on the
reclusive billionnaire.
 &HT;    Frangoulis details many of Niarchos' eccentric habits, including
his insistence that his favorite van Goghs be on board the boat
whenever he was _ never mind that they'd be ruined by the sea air.
 &HT;    Then there was Niarchos' habit of swimming nude while an armed
guard stood on deck, checking for sharks.
 &HT;    The book, due out later this year in Europe, also has photos of
the Creole's many illustrious guests _ including the Duchess of
Windsor, who clearly wasn't the type to pack light. For one brief
stay on the boat, she showed up with 12 Vuitton steamer trunks.
 &HT;    
 MANHATTAN TRANSFER  
 &HT;    One of Los Angeles' reigning nightlife impresarios, Sean
MacPherson, is heading to New York.
 &HT;    The man behind such haunts as Smalls, the Olive, Swingers and
Bar Marmont plans to open his first New York restaurant next year
at an unspecified downtown location.
 &HT;    To help him navigate the local terrain, he'll be partnering with
Eric Goode of Bowery Bar fame.
 &HT;    ``I have a good feeling about this one,'' MacPherson says.
 &HT;    
 ROYAL BABES  
 &HT;    Prince William isn't the only pinup in the British royal family.
In the past few months, two of William's female cousins have been
setting male teens' hearts aflutter with their blond looks and
trendy fashion sense.
 &HT;    Gabriella Windsor, the 19-year-old daughter of Prince and
Princess Michael of Kent, had the British tabloids panting when she
appeared at the Badminton Horse Trials in a tight-fitting sweater
and leather Stetson. (Windsor's good looks are shared by her
brother Frederick, a model featured in the latest Burberry
campaign.)
 &HT;    Meanwhile, royal rebel Zara Phillips, 18, delighted the
paparazzi at a recent horse race by wearing a chic jacket and
thigh-high skirt.
 &HT;    Phillips, the daughter of the Princess Royal and Mark Phillips,
is dating jockey Richard Johnson; she has agreed to remove her
tongue stud in exchange for his vow to give up smoking.
 &HT;    
 FIELD DAY  
 &HT;    It's no secret that Hollywood movie stars have been earning
extra cash by appearing in ads on Italian TV: Harrison Ford has
plugged Fiat, Catherine Zeta-Jones has campaigned for Alfa Romeo
and even Brad Pitt has deigned to promote Damiani jewelry, secure
in the knowledge that the commercials would never be shown
Stateside.
 &HT;    But Kevin Costner has reportedly broken a longstanding taboo by
allowing his upcoming shoe commercial to appear in the United
States.
 &HT;    In fact, the new ad, for the mid-range Italian shoe company
Valleverde, will reportedly debut in America this fall and air
later in Europe. The commercial shows Costner walking in a field,
helping a child take its first steps.
 &HT;    
 FETISH SCENT RELAUNCHED  
 &HT;    NEW ORLEANS _ Grammy-award-winning singer Christina Aguilera is
expanding her range with a line of color cosmetics.
 &HT;    The 19-year-old international pop star is partnering with the
Boca Raton, Fla.-based New Dana Perfumes Company on a relaunch of
its teen brand Fetish.
 &HT;    The collection, expected to rollout in January, has been renamed
Fetish by Christina Aguilera. Packaging will carry the slogan
``What a Girl Wants,'' after her hit single.
 &HT;    Aguilera snagged the Grammys' ``Best New Artist'' award earlier
this year and also appeared in the Super Bowl half-time show with
Enrique Iglesias.
 &HT;    Aguilera also has promotional contracts with Levi's and recently
inked a deal with Coca Cola. With Fetish, however, she is directly
involved in product design and packaging.
 &HT;    ``I am definitely going to have a say in the products,''
Aguilera said. She has already swapped the brand's lavender
packaging for black with silver components. ``I've always been a
lover of fashion, and I enjoy playing with makeup.''
 &HT;    This time last year, as part of the Renaissance Cosmetics
Company, Fetish was in Chapter 11. p 
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
