<HEADER>
A4313 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-WHERE-GODS-ARE-NEIGHB     07-06 2874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHERE-GODS-ARE-NEIGHBORS-TRAVEL-FARE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE GODS ARE NEIGHBORS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES 
 By NICOLE KRAUSS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    The first time I was in the Peloponnesus, it was midwinter, and
out of the low fog that was everywhere goatherds seemed to appear
and dissolve as if in a Theo Angelopoulos film. The narrow roads
etched into the mountainside threatened to fall off into clouds.
 &HT;    At every switchback turn, a small, mailbox-like shrine with
faded icon, biscuits and half-empty bottle of Fanta seemed placed
to ensure safe passage.
 &HT;    Despite the cool air, the orange groves along the roadside were
fragrant, and as I walked between the rows of trees, the silence
was punctuated by the thud of ripe oranges dropping. The
archaeological sites _ and often it seemed the peninsula itself _
were empty of people.
 &HT;    Aside from the phantom goatherds and the men in the kafeneia
smoking and fingering their knotted worry beads, the most evident
signs of life were the occasional smoldering heaps of rubbish that
slid down the mountainside like scree.
 &HT;    In that strange weather there was something almost threatening
about the loom and lunge of the mountains. Alone among the ruins of
Olympia or Epidaurus, I couldn't shake a feeling of eerieness and
half expected, at any moment, to encounter some ancient shade
walking among the broken columns.
 &HT;    It's no surprise that at times the Peloponnesus seems haunted.
The Isle of Pelops is named for the boy slaughtered and cooked by
his father, Tantalus, and served to the gods. Brought back to life
by the outraged Zeus, Pelops eventually became a king.
 &HT;    Later a curse was put on him by a man he tricked, so that for
generations the House of Pelops was plagued by murders and
vendettas, by the same grisly plots compulsively repeated.
 &HT;    But in spring the Peloponnesus changes. It is as if the curse
lifts with the fog and the valleys and hillsides suddenly flower.
With 6,000 species of flowering plants, Greece has some of the most
extensive flora of any European country. The fields fill with
larkspur, anemones and asphodel, with stalks of giant fennel in
whose slow-burning pith Prometheus brought fire to the Earth. Pink
and white oleanders hem the roads, and house fronts are decorated
with shocks of bougainvillea.
 &HT;    But despite the abundance of flowers and the bright sun, much of
the Peloponnesus retains a kind of severity year-round: even in
that fabled idyll, Arcadia, the barren mountain peaks are always
present. The occasional monasteries built into sheer cliff faces
remind the traveler of the isolation of the place.
 &HT;    This time I returned to the Peloponnesus in June, to rent a
house with a friend on the beach with no address or phone. Aside
from this, its most remarkable detail was the blowzy red lampshade
that hung, with its delusions of grandeur, over the kitchen table.
Everything else about the house was simple and rustic.
 &HT;    Its only luxury was the garden, so packed with oleanders, lemon,
fig and pomegranate trees that it threatened to engulf the cottage
in its green embrace. In Greece it is impossible to forget that
everything must eventually fall to ruin; what little remains
depends on freak chance or the serendipity of archaeologists.
 &HT;    Behind the garden walls that backed up onto a grove of
lime-washed olive trees, Ben and I spent whole days reading.
Clothes became mostly useless. Even as we read about ancient
Greece, civilization seemed to stall or slip a notch.
 &HT;    We told time by the constantly changing light or the sounds
around us: the clatter of cicadas or the bells from the small
church where the priest sang his drafty evensong, the doors on all
sides of the cruciform church thrown open to his congregation of
zero. Only in the evenings, when the stubborn heat finally began to
give in, would we venture out to swim in the clear Ionian Sea.
 &HT;    Our house was on the western coast of the Mani, the middle of
the three southern switchblades of land that jut into the sea. It
was partly Patrick Leigh Fermor's exhaustive book ``Mani,''
published in the 1950s, that originally drew us to the place; the
house we rented outside the little town of Stoupa was only a few
miles away from his.
 &HT;    Mr. Fermor describes the map of the southern part of the
Peloponnesus as ``a misshapen tooth fresh torn from its gum with
three peninsulas jutting southward in jagged and carious roots.''
The middle carious root _ a description that conjures not only its
shape but also its character _ is the Mani.
 &HT;    The sharp spine of the Taygetos mountain range rips down its
length, and on its hard, boulder-strewn plateaus a fierce and
passionate race of people lived in a perpetual state of war.
 &HT;    Descended from Spartans, Slavs, and Frankish crusaders, the
Maniots' way of life revolved around bloody family feuds waged with
yataghans (short Turkish sabers with double-curved blades), axes
and muskets; when a feud was on a Maniot could not leave his house
without dodging a volley of bullets.
 &HT;    The Maniots lived in austere stone tower houses, the better to
aim at and pick off a neighbor. They were feared by other Greeks,
many of whom still keep a wide berth of the peninsula. Not much
remains of the Maniots now, having killed off or tired each other
out, and their surviving progeny packed up and moved to Athens. The
wrecks of their domestic fortresses _ sometimes whole villages of
them _ seem outcroppings of the very rock that forms the wild and
lonely hills.
 &HT;    On weekends we explored the Peloponnesus _ often on overnight
trips _ in a car we rented in Stoupa, the town where Kazantzakis
created the larger-than-life character Zorba. On our first
excursion we headed south, deep into the Mani. We stopped for an
early breakfast at the Krifos Kipos taverna in the tiny fishing
village of Agios Nikolaos and watched the caiques come in, hung
with kerosene lanterns and laden with the morning's catch of fish.
 &HT;    The serenity was only occasionally punctured by cries of the
ubiquitous traveling salesmen who advertise their wares, whether
watermelons or plastic chairs, from megaphones mounted on the roofs
of their trucks.
 &HT;    After Agios Nikolaos the road climbs inland into the mountains
before cutting back to the coast to descend on the Bay of Limeni,
where the white-capped sea bites deeply into the cliffs. In the
Maniot town of Areopolis (named, appropriately, for the god of war)
the cobbled streets are lined with tower houses whose whitewashed
rooms look out onto slopes of prickly pear.
 &HT;    Nearby are the caves of Pirgos Dirou where, for less than the
mythical gold coin, a gruff Charon punted us on a skiff through the
miles of stalactite-hung grottoes said to extend inland as far as
Sparta.
 &HT;    After Areopolis the Mani becomes more desolate; this stretch of
the Taygetos is dubbed the Kakovounia, or Evil Mountains. In
summer, the temperature rises until it reaches the sort of heat
that breeds hallucinations or madness. Nothing much grows there
except for scrub or scorched grass, yet it is tremendously
beautiful.
 &HT;    At the highest points clusters of tower houses still stand vigil
above the sea. And everywhere the ruins of stout stone walls
criss-cross the plateaus: surreal boundaries that mark one share of
nothingness from the next. We passed a dust-covered mason breaking
stones by the roadside in the noonday sun, but he spoke no English
and we spoke little Greek and so we couldn't extract from him the
reason for that infinite network of senseless walls. But he happily
posed for a picture.
 &HT;    After the ghost town of Vatheia _ whose tower houses have been
converted into an eccentric hotel _ the peninsula narrows toward
its end, Cape Tainaron, the location of the mythical gates to the
Underworld. The beaches widen (Marmari is one of the most
beautiful) and the sea, surprisingly warm, breaks in tremendous
waves. By the time we arrived at the very tip of the cape it was
already evening.
 &HT;    Around the ruins of the Temple of Poseidon the wind bent the
gold grass toward the sea; directly above us the sky was stamped by
the first sliver of moon. Somewhere nearby was the cave where
Hercules supposedly descended to the Underworld to bring back the
three-headed dog, Cerberus. But we stopped short of finding it,
feeling some things are better left to the imagination.
 &HT;    The Peloponnesus has some of the finest classical ruins in the
world. The acoustics in the amphitheater of Epidaurus _ one of the
greatest sites _ are so perfect that even from the uppermost tier a
whisper from the stage is audible.
 &HT;    When I brushed my foot along the circle that marks center stage
a twang rang out as from an amplified steel guitar. Behind the
theater are the vast ruins of the spa where invalids came from all
over the Hellenic world to convalesce with the aid of therapeutic
baths, poultices and miraculous cures.
 &HT;    In the mountains of Arcadia, up a winding road of treacherous
hairpin turns, is the limestone Temple of Bassae, erected around
420 B.C. _ in the middle of nowhere _ by Ictinus, the architect of
the Parthenon. In Pylos, in the remains of Nestor's Palace, you can
stand in what's left of the great hall where Telemachus came to ask
for news of his father. The most remarkable surviving detail of the
ruins is an intact terra-cotta tub, last bathed in some 3,000 years
ago.
 &HT;    In the northeast region of the Peloponnesus is Mycenae, first
excavated in the 19th century by Heinrich Schliemann, the
indigo-merchant-turned-archaeologist who discovered Troy. Upon
opening the most elaborate of the royal tombs, he wrote to the King
of Greece, ``I have stared into the face of Agamemnon.''
 &HT;    From 1400 to 1200 B.C. Mycenae was the most powerful kingdom in
Greece. In the rooms of the ruined palace there, Clytemnestra and
her lover, Aegisthus, murdered her husband in a bath to avenge the
sacrifice of her daughter; her children Orestes and Electra, in
turn, murdered Clytemnestra.
 &HT;    To me, the most moving ancient site in the Peloponnesus is
Olympia. The first time I was there it was February and raining,
and I was alone in the place. It made such an impression on me
that, as the summer was running out, I insisted on a last trip to
see it again. Every four years, for almost 1,200 years, athletes
made a pilgrimage to this quiet grove of pines to strive to achieve
the heights of human strength, grace, speed and agility.
 &HT;    Although the hippodrome has long since sunk into the silt of the
Alfios River, the temples and most of the buildings remain, as does
the short-distance track. It is around 600 feet long, with hills
for specta tors on either side and stone slabs cut with grooves
where the runners crouched before the start signal. No one else was
around when we were there so we took our sandals off and raced each
other barefoot, neck and neck, pounding the ground packed down by
time and countless ancient races.
 &HT;    But history did not end on the Peloponnesus with the fall of
Greece. The landscape is scattered with signs of all who followed
the invasion of the Romans: Goths, Avars and Slavs, the Byzantines,
Franks, Turks and Venetians. After the perfection of Praxiteles'
sculptures or still-extant geometry of a Grecian temple, these
medieval ruins may seem crude and insubstantial.
 &HT;    But atop the rock of Monemvasia, inside the 13th-century
Byzantine church with its humbled frescoes, one suddenly feels the
illumination of those dark ages, sensing the very pattern of
history itself with its endlessly repeating eras of chaos and
order.
 &HT;    And even as one is constantly aware of all that has been lost,
there are also reminders of what is continuous: the
thousand-year-old monastery of St. John the Baptist outside the
mountain town of Stemnitsa, for example, where the monks waved down
to us from their hawk's perch to offer us coffee and a bowl of
Turkish de light.
 &HT;    At the end of each of our weekend excursions _ to the southern
tip of the Mani, to Monemvasia, Olympia, Arcadia _ we found
ourselves eager to return to our small house. After such a close
study of the ravages of time, there is a certain comfort in a place
where nothing seems to happen.
 &HT;    The day's only events were the start or finish of a book, the
evening baptism in the Ionian, and our meals at the house or our
favorite taverna, Agrogiali, usually accompanied by a carafe of
retsina, the local wine made with pine resin.
 &HT;    Under the influence of that good drink, with the sun gone down
leaving the houses glowing like lamps, a poem by Constantine Cavafy
came to mind.
 &HT;    ``That we've broken their statues,/that we've driven them out of
their temples,/doesn't mean at all that the gods are dead.'' The
poem ends with an ethereal figure in rapid flight, winging across
the hills: a further explanation, perhaps, for the occasional
ghostliness of the place.
 &HT;    -----
 SIDEBAR: IN A LAND HAUNTED BY A LONG HISTORY  
 LOGISTICS  
 &HT;    The airport at Kalamata, around 30 miles from Stoupa, has
flights from Athens on Olympic Airways. Travelers can also fly into
Athens, then take a bus or rent a car. There are frequent (if
rickety) buses to all major towns. A hydrofoil connects Piraeus and
Monemvasia.
 &HT;    Some of the classical sites in the Peloponnesus can be reached
on a day trip from the Mani, but an overnight stay is needed for
Epidaurus and Mycenae.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    The Peloponnesus is largely untouched by tourism, which means
there are almost no luxury hotels. Renting a house is probably the
best option. We found ours advertised in The New York Review of
Books.
 &HT;    There are also a number of small, charming and relatively
inexpensive inns. The Thomeas Travel Agency in Stoupa, (30-721)
77689; fax (30-721) 77571, can help with accommodations. A studio
for two people with bath and cooking facilities runs about $42 a
day in high season (July through September); a two-bedroom villa,
around $70 (at 360 drachmas to the dollar). Ask for Bob Barrow, an
English expatriate who published his own book about the Mani.
 &HT;    In the Mani, Limeni Village, near Areopolis, (30-733) 51111, fax
(30-733) 51182, perched on a cliff overlooking Limeni Bay, has
spectacular views. Its 35 rooms are in replicas of tower houses; a
restaurant with a terrace overlooks the sea. There is also a
swimming pool. Doubles cost $64 in July and August, with buffet
breakfast, $50 the rest of the year.
 &HT;    In Vatheia there are lodgings in restored ruins of tower houses
atop a rocky escarpment, with sweeping views down to the ocean.
Information: (30-733) 55244. A double is $44 in summer, $39 in
winter.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    Lela's Taverna in Kardamyli, (30-721) 73541, is run by a
wonderful woman (and an excellent cook) who used to be the
housekeeper for Patrick Leigh Fermor, author of the fascinating
book ``Mani.'' The tables are under a grape arbor overlooking the
sea. Dinner for two with house wine, around $20. Dinner nightly;
open all day on weekends in summer.
 &HT;    The Rapteas family run Agrogiali, (30-721) 77335, formerly a
taverna and now an ouzeria serving drinks, snacks and sweets. It's
on the southern end of the main beach. At the Krifos Kipos taverna
in Agios Nikolaos, you can sit at a table on the marina or under
the enormous plum tree in the back garden.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    The amphitheater at Epidaurus, built in the 4th century B.C., is
spectacularly well preserved, and the site also includes the ruins
of an ancient therapeutic center. Open daily from 8 a.m. to 7 p.m.;
admission $4.15. There are also concerts in the theater during July
and August. Call (30-753) 22009 for a schedule.
 &HT;    Near the west coast of the Peloponnesus, the ruins at Olympia,
(30-624) 22517, are open 8 a.m. to 7 p.m. daily except Monday, when
hours are noon to 7 p.m. The museum is also excellent. Combined
ticket, $5.55.
 &HT;    The site at Mycenae, (30-751) 76585, is open 8 a.m. to 7 p.m.
daily; admission $4.35.
 &HT;    One of the most unusual medieval ruins is Monemvasia, built on a
massive rock that rises dramatically from the sea, off the east
coast of the Peloponnesus. For information, call the local tourist
agency, Malvasia Travel, (30-732) 61752.
 &HT;     
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Nicole Krauss lives in New York.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Nicole Krauss 
