<HEADLINE>
THAT FLYING SENSATION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Free to clients of Way to Go!) 
 (FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES) 
 BY JERRY HAINES  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    However unfashionable it may be to admit it, I like to fly on
commuter airlines. I like to feel the water when I swim, I like to
taste the food when I eat, and I like to feel as if I'm flying when
I fly.
 &HT;    This is not a knock on the big airlines or their efficiency in
transporting billions of passengers or their safety records. But,
really, as you pass from the passenger lounge to the ``people
eater'' to the plane, and then back again at your destination, can
you really say that you have flown? Wasn't it more like being in a
series of large rooms?
 &HT;    It's just that in one of them they project movies of aerial
scenery outside the windows, and once in a while a burly stagehand
bounces the room on the director's cue of ``Looks like we're gonna
have a little turbulence, here, folks.''
 &HT;    Personally, I am delighted when I note on my itinerary the
asterisk that leads me to the footnote, ``Operated by
Somebody-You-Never-Heard-Of Airlines'' _ notwithstanding the big
corporation's logo on the plane or the masthead on the in-flight
magazine.
 &HT;    My expectations are validated when, at some stopover, I am
advised that my connecting flight is at D-78. At the very end of
the concourse, I take the escalator down, and suddenly it's as if
I'm in a different airport. There are no admirals' clubs or sports
bars here; the ceilings are low, and there is no music system. In
contrast to the gates upstairs, which are city blocks apart, the
gates here are all in one big room.
 &HT;    The boarding announcements override one another, like competing
rug merchants shouting out bargains in a bazaar. (I expect them to
try to talk me out of my destination: ``You don't want Duluth, my
friend. Evansville is right for you. I could take 30 percent off
that fare.'') There are no monitors or electronic signs. Rather,
gate agents manually insert cardboard numbers on a display board.
 &HT;    The only available food here is from vending machines. But the
food upstairs is overpriced, underseasoned and hyperfatty _ even if
it does come on a lettuce leaf. Eat your Cheez Doodles and drink
your Dr Pepper.
 &HT;    Passengers in the bullpen seats strain to sort out the
information about their respective flights. (``Did she say,
'Wichita' or 'Wichita Falls'?'') When we do board, there is little
ceremony. There is no separate loading of celebrities into first
class (indeed, the concept of first class on a commuter flight
would provoke giggles), and the entire process takes only about 10
minutes. Often the gate agent will walk us to the plane. I wonder
whether the agent is going to fly the plane, too.
 &HT;    I love these walks out to the plane. Like kindergarten kids on a
field trip, we stay close together as we follow our agent across
the Tarmac. And we're actually on the Tarmac. Little tractors and
baggage carts zip around us like deerflies as we keep a wary eye
out for approaching Airbuses. We can hear the plane engines and the
yelling of crew members. We can smell the jet fuel and feel the
prop wash. It's a sensory experience that has all but disappeared
as the airline industry strives to make air travel as
nonthreatening as possible.
 &HT;    The seating inside the plane is cramped, but at least it makes
sense to have 20 cramped seats on a small plane instead of hundreds
of them on a 747. And there are no middle seats; in fact, sometimes
a seat is both ``aisle'' and ``window.''
 &HT;    It is true that there is less space for carry-on luggage and
that we'll end up checking it. But, unlike passengers on the big
planes, I can see the guys loading it. And they can see me seeing
them. Further, when I get to where I'm going, I will just pick up
my luggage at planeside and roll through the terminal to the taxi
stand, while the people from those big planes stare at the empty,
revolving carousel and curse.
 &HT;    Many of the planes are prop jets, so that I actually can see the
engines start and the propellers begin to spin. (I wish they were
real propeller engines, though, so that starting them would sound
like that climactic moment in ``Casablanca,'' where the plane
engine starts with a whining kick.)
 &HT;    Like their counterparts on the airborne cruise ships, flight
attendants on these planes (usually only one) do the little drill
about seat belts and emergency exits and seat cushions that are
usable as flotation devices, but people actually pay attention
here. The attendant then plops into the jump seat and the plane
taxis out toward the runway.
 &HT;    As with the boarding, the taxiing seems more efficient. This
plane doesn't need help pushing back from its parking space any
more than a cabdriver needs help pulling away from the curb. The
pilot just puts down the flag on the meter and we're off for a
drive across the concrete.
 &HT;    A lot of the passengers appear to be regulars _ sales
representatives, tech reps and other itinerants who have gotten to
know the flight attendants and who kibitz with them. The plane
shudders in the backwash of a launching wide-body, then it's our
turn, and we are effortlessly airborne.
 &HT;    The flight itself is closer to the ground, and we can see the
scenery. (I had flown dozens of times into Ronald Reagan National
Airport, for example, but not until I flew there by commuter plane
was I truly impressed by Washington's memorials, the Pentagon and
those bobsledlike turns that planes must take as they approach
along the Potomac.)
 &HT;    Of course that same low altitude means that in bad weather, the
pilot can't get us above it. We are simply in it, and we can only
endure it. We macho types pretend not to be alarmed as the contents
of our soda glass hover above the glass momentarily when we hit an
air pocket.
 &HT;    ``Hey, at Busch Gardens you'd have to pay 10 bucks for a ride
like this,'' we joke (and then resume mumbling prayers). I try to
think of it as my Authentic Flying Experience. Real mashed potatoes
have lumps; real flying has bumps.
 &HT;    Soon we sense the impending landing (in our ears --
pressurization sometimes is a scarce commodity), and we return our
seat backs to their full upright position (as opposed to the
91-degree position we used for relaxing).
 &HT;    We're down quickly, the pilot does that little prop-reversal
thing that halts the plane on a dime, and we chug over toward the
terminal, where we stop several yards from the building. I expect
the pilot to caution, ``Now, everyone remember where we parked.''
 &HT;    I wonder whether the pilots, flight attendants and gate agents
are happy here in the farm club. Do the pilots dream of setting
down a 747 at Narita or Charles de Gaulle or Leonardo da Vinci? Do
the flight attendants look enviously toward the big ships that have
entire teams to do all of the things that one person does on a
commuter flight? Do the gate agents aspire to a life upstairs where
one might see the sun and buy $6 pizza slices?
 &HT;    I surely hope not. I hope they enjoy it as much as I do. Now if
they'd only let me sit up front with the pilots.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Jerry Haines is a lawyer in Washington, D.C.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Jerry Haines 
