<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASK THE TRAVEL EXPERT 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: The word AT in parentheses has been used in an e-mail
address instead of the symbol, which many computer systems at
newspapers can't interpret.)  
 &HT;    
 By WILLIAM T. TOMICKI 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;     Q:  My wife and I are headed to Melbourne, Australia. Can you
recommend a culinary hot spot there?
 &HT;     A:  You couldn't find a more popular restaurant than the sleek
Radii at the Park Hyatt Melbourne, where chef Paul Wilson is
earning rave reviews.
 &HT;    This vibrant, multilevel experience with an open kitchen has a
wood-fired oven, bar and cigar lounge. Chef Wilson prepares what he
calls ``modern cuisine'' using quality produce true to its natural
flavor.
 &HT;    This is exciting food of superb quality. Expect dishes such as
scallops in a citrus beurre blanc; cassoulet of blue eye and clams;
and sauternes custard. There's also rotisseried leg of lamb,
risotto, roasted trout, grilled chicken and duck. The menu is
brave. Wines are fairly priced at Radii and service is impeccable.
All dishes are designed to share. Desserts are extravagant.
 &HT;    For more information, call 9224-1211.
 &HT;     Q:  I am planning a three-week trip to China in September. I am
having trouble finding anyone who understands the exchange rates
and how to do it. I am aware that you can bring a limited amount of
money in or out, but where do you get it? I am trying to avoid long
lines and hassles at the airport, and my bank tells me they do not
trade in this currency. Help!
 &HT;     : . Regarding the pre-purchase of Chinese currency, there are
two official names for the currency, renminbi (RMB) and kuai.
 &HT;    Our sources at Export International Currency Express do not
advise on pre-purchasing large amounts of RMB because the rate is
not very favorable compared to exchanging in China. The CITIC bank
in Beijing, on Jiangguomenwai Street, is very efficient.
 &HT;    However, Export International Currency Exchange can arrange for
a smaller amount to be made in advance to hold you over until you
can reach a proper bank. You can contact them at (888) 278-6628.
Best wishes for a wonderful trip through China.
 &HT;     : . My husband and I are looking for a quick getaway to the
Arizona desert. Do you know of any value-priced packages at nicer
resorts?
 &HT;     A:  The Royal Palms Hotel and Casitas is offering a variety of
well-priced packages for those seeking some rest and relaxation in
the desert. The Phoenix property is managed by Destination Hotels
and Resorts and is part of a collection of distinctive upscale
hotels and resorts known for their luxurious standards and
exceptional recreational opportunities.
 &HT;    The Royal Romance package, which costs $279 for two days and one
night, includes Plaza Suite accommodation and sensual amenities
such as champagne and chocolate-covered strawberries.
 &HT;    The Royal Tee, which starts at $269 for two days and one night,
includes daily breakfast and a round of golf at one of several top
golf courses in the area.
 &HT;    The Royal Treatment, $399 for two days and one night, includes
Plaza suite accommodation, and an in-room or cabana massage for
each guest, as well as complimentary use of the fitness center.
 &HT;    For those looking for accommodations only, the Royal Palms is
offering a summer promotional rate of $149 per room, per night. For
reservations or more information, call (800) 672-6011.
 &HT;     Q:  I've been to Africa once before, but I felt very much like
a tourist the entire time and left feeling unsatisfied. I'd like to
try again, but I really want to get a feel for the various local
cultures and really experience Africa. Any suggestions?
 &HT;     A:  The best way to experience local culture anywhere is to
just immerse yourself in it. Bush Homes of East Africa offers a
``true African experience'' by housing guests at private residences
and ranches so they can experience the personable hospitality of
Kenyans and witness their lifestyle.
 &HT;    Visitors get the chance to mix with villagers by learning about
local farming customs, regional wildlife, and join in with the
daily life of the nomadic Ndorobo people. This is definitely NOT
your average safari trip.
 &HT;    For more information on prices and locations, visit
www.bush-homes.co.ke on the Web.
 &HT;    This trip _ and more like it _ can be found in the Spring/Summer
2000 Specialty Travel Index, $10 per year for two issues. Send
orders to info(AT)specialitytravel.com.
 &HT;     Q:  My niece has been working at a quality golf resort, but she
feels her career is stalled. She has an excellent eye for design
and loves the sport. Any suggestions on how she might kickstart her
career and remain in this exciting industry?
 &HT;     A:  Your niece may be a perfect candidate for the new Master's
Degree in Golf Course Architecture at Edinburgh College of Art in
Scotland _ see www.eca.ac.uk. The one-year program has the full
blessing of the Royal and Ancient Golf Club. With St. Andrews just
one hour from Edinburgh, students will carry out fieldwork at the
Old Course and many of Scotland's hidden gems. Tuition is
approximately $12,175.
 &HT;    Contact Edinburgh College of Art, Edinburgh, Scotland. telephone
44 131 221 6091, fax: 44 131 221 6005. E-mail:
landscape(AT)eca.ac.uk
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions to William Tomicki, P.O.
Box 5148, Santa Barbara, Calif. 93150. Although he cannot answer
each query individually, selected questions will be included in his
column. Mr. Tomicki, who logs over 150,000 miles each year, is the
publisher of ENTREE, a travel newsletter. 
 &HT;    
 c.2000 William T. Tomicki 
