<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACATION LEAVES UNWELCOME LEGACY
</HEADLINE>
  By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   My malady didn't hit until the return trip. Over there I was
unfazed, body and brain automatically tuned into European time.
Over there it was my husband staring into the TV at 3 a.m.,
watching a French documentary on fish.
</P>
<P>
   Now he sleeps and I wander the house like an intruder, bumping
into walls, rebuffed by my own pillow. Goodnight moon. Goodnight
chair. Hello strange zombie woman. It is 2:30 in the morning, and
lack of sleep is my new obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the price for getting away for three weeks and crossing
too many time zones? Is this what our mothers meant by burning the
candle at both ends?
</P>
<P>
   In the past weeks I have fallen asleep to the high-pitched whine
of motor scooters and screeches from soccer fans. Here, where all
is calm under a silk cover of fog, I am bejangled. My brain is
saying, ``Hey mama, let's party.''
</P>
<P>
   Le lag from the jet is not a pretty creature. She looks to be
roughly 109. Her eyelids are heavy, but her eyes dart back and
forth, perhaps scanning for one more museum, one last cute little
cafe. Look into those eyes, if you dare. They resemble that
delicacy of central France, poached eggs in red wine sauce.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the refreshed image I was hoping to come home with.
</P>
<P>
   If science can figure out how cells combine to make a person
crave spinach and want to play the piano, why can't it let us fly
around the world and come back with the same brain attached to the
same body? The legs ache, the throat burns, the brain thinks it's
time for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Don't advise melatonin. It gives me weird dreams. Of course,
this is pretty weird reality.
</P>
<P>
   It's good to be home. Home is where the heart is, where the cat
is brooding, where the tomato crop appears doomed and where the
phone company has delivered equipment nobody ordered. But one must
slumber first to cope with these things.
</P>
<P>
   Jet lag is as common a travel affliction as poison oak and
sunburn. I know this because I have been looking up information on
the Internet, which is the only number I dare to dial in the middle
of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants suffer from it, you know. You would think
they'd have learned all the tricks. I always envy them stretched
out behind their curtained-off seats while we wrap our knees into
our armpits for 11 hours, but they, too, complain of altered
states.
</P>
<P>
   Some high-flying business executives aren't allowed to sign
contracts the first 24 hours after landing because of potential
brain impairment.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing you can't sleep creates the same anxiety I get while
waiting to give a speech. I have tried doing yoga breaths, drinking
mint tea. I have thought kind thoughts. I have banished all care.
Aargh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a long flight,'' said the attendant, placing
four tiny drink bottles of golden liquid in front of us somewhere
off the coast of England and before Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding alcohol while flying will help to prevent jet lag, they
say. However, many people who pay lots of money to fly think they
deserve at least one celebratory drink. After all, we're on
vacation. It is also easier to get alcohol than water on a plane.
You can bring your own, of course, but how many quart bottles can
you lug on board?
</P>
<P>
   No coffee, either, they warn. But the time I tried flying
without any coffee at all I was punished the next day with a
caffeine withdrawal headache.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly you get less jet lag flying east to west, although
some say just the opposite. You are also less prone if you fly in
daylight and if you're middle-aged or older. Bingo on all the
above, but here I am with my motor running.
</P>
<P>
   NASA says you need one day of recovery for every time zone
you've crossed. That gives me until the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Travel guru Rick Steves says to take two days before traveling
and just relax. Leave for a flight well-rested. Try to have two
orderly and peaceful days before taking off. What a kidder, that
Rick.
</P>
<P>
   Most people I know maximize their vacation time by working up
until the day they leave and going back to work the day after they
get home. It is, however, one of my 2:30 a.m. vows. Next time I
will come home one day early simply to catch up on sleep.
</P>
<P>
   No, I won't.
</P>
<P>
   That's the other thing about jet lag. Like childbirth, you
forget the inconvenience, which allows for repeats.
</P>
<P>
   As we filed off the plane and into the airport, we looked like
detainees, shuffling in swollen feet toward the baggage carousel.
An animated group was coming our way. They were smiling and
fresh-faced. Their hair was combed and they had crisp boarding
passes in hand, on their way to fun and adventure, with hours to go
before they turned into aliens. I envied them.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
