<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, July 6, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL-STRIKE (San Francisco) _ One of the largest health care
worker strikes in recent history forced nine Bay Area hospitals to
operate with skeleton crews, as 4,000 union members walked off
their jobs and onto the picket line. By The San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKER-DEATH (San Francisco) _ Leslie Whiteley, a former smoker
who received $21.7 million in damages from a San Francisco jury
against the nation's two largest tobacco companies in March, has
died of cancer at age 40. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE-CHEMICALS (San Francisco) _ A Las Vegas couple says a
Royal Caribbean Cruises ship returning from an 11-day Alaska voyage
last September dumped chemicals into the San Francisco Bay so
noxious that the concoction chased away the sea lions. The cruise
company denies the accusations made by the couple and an
environmental organization that is threatening to sue. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LAKE-GEORGE (Lake George, N.Y.) _ Divers in Lake George looked
deep into the water and found pieces of whole worlds: more than 60
shipwrecks lay forgotten in the lake's southernmost tip alone, and
elsewhere under the 32-mile length of clear water, submerged
vessels remain to be counted. The discoveries were made by divers
taking a first-ever inventory of the lake bottom _ an effort to
catalog the historic treasures before they are picked over by
adventure seekers and disappear. By LORI SODERLIND.
</P>
<P>
   LAKE-GEORGE-RELICS (Lake George, N.Y.) _ Among the wreckage
found at the bottom of Lake George is a 15-foot homemade submarine
built to study French and Indian War wrecks. It was stolen from its
dock in 1960 and was one of the lake's big mysteries until 1995,
when divers found the rusted hulk in deep water. By LORI SODERLIND.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICORPS-RECRUITS (San Antonio) _ It may not have any snap,
crackle or pop, but the makers of an organic breakfast cereal are
delivering a pitch to millions of young adults in an effort to
recruit them into the volunteer organization AmeriCorps. Cereal
maker General Mills has teamed up with the government to call
attention to the 5-year-old volunteer corps which is competing with
a strong economy to get young people involved. By MATT FLORES.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA-MEXICO (San Antonio) _ Supporters of the North American
Free Trade Agreement touted the pact as a boon to U.S., Mexican and
Canadian economies. But it may have had another, unintended
consequence: political reform in Mexico. Political and economic
analysts say the steps that led to the historic presidential
election of Vincente Fox of the National Action Party, the first
president from outside the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party
in 71 years, can be directly traced to NAFTA. By BILL DAY.
</P>
<P>
   ATM-FEES (San Francisco) _ U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker's
decision to strike down local ordinances banning extra bank ATM
fees came as no surprise to lawyers defending the laws, but his
failure even to mention in his ruling an appellate case that seemed
to allow local regulation of automated teller machines left them
baffled. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
