<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4387 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-CHOCOLATE-HNS &LR;      07-06 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOCOLATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHOCOLATE LOVERS GET SWEET REVENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A chocolate bar a day will keep the doctor away?
Well, maybe not, but research conducted over the past several years
indicates that chocolate isn't the guilty pleasure we thought it
was.
</P>
<P>
   Much ballyhooed research on fruits and vegetables, red wine and
green tea suggests that the antioxidant compounds found in those
foods in abundance provide protection against cancer and heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   To explain the theory very loosely and in non-scientific terms,
free radicals are rogue molecules with a spare electron. Since
electrons like to live in pairs, the free radicals are constantly
looking for a mate for their spare electron. In the process, free
radicals can rob an electron from another molecule, damaging the
molecule. Free radicals reacting with DNA can cause cancer, lipid
and protein damage leads to atherosclerosis (hardening of the
arteries), diabetic complications and the bane of us all, aging.
Antioxidants, on the other hand, generously lend free radicals an
electron and render them impotent.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate, too, contains antioxidants. And, as it turns out, a
lot of them.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate is made by fermenting, roasting, and pressing the
beans of the cocoa tree to make ``chocolate'' liquor. This liquor
is then pressed to extract more cocoa butter, leaving a paste that
is ground and sifted to make cocoa powder. The primary nutrients in
cocoa powder include carbohydrates, proteins, mineral salts,
theobromine, caffeine, polyphenols and water.
</P>
<P>
   And polyphenols are a kind of antioxidant.
</P>
<P>
   Polyphenols protect plants from diseases and ultraviolet light
and help prevent seed damage. They also give fruits, vegetables,
wine and chocolate their color.
</P>
<P>
   Studies at Scranton University in Scranton, Pa., indicate that
gram for gram, chocolate has more polyphenols than kidney beans,
Bordeaux wines and even the much-lauded blueberry.
</P>
<P>
   Chemist Joe A. Vinson, who directed the Scranton study, says
chocolate hasn't received the hoopla of blueberries and broccoli
because other studies concentrated on foods with a lot of other
nutrients such as fruits, vegetables and beverages. Vinson's tests,
however, measure all the polyphenols in 100 grams (3.2 ounces) of a
specific food.
</P>
<P>
   To make the various forms of chocolate, the cocoa powder is
remixed with cocoa butter, diluting the concentration of the
polyphenols. Therefore, by weight, cocoa powder contains the most
polyphenols of all chocolate products. Dark chocolates, since they
contain additional cocoa butter and sugar, contain a lower
concentration of polyphenols, milk chocolate (which is made by
adding in milk, contain even less). Since white chocolate doesn't
contain cocoa powder but is a combination of cocoa butter, sugar
and flavorings, it contains no polyphenols at all. (Remember,
polyphenols give foods their color and white chocolate isn't very
colorful).
</P>
<P>
   In terms of serving sizes, a standard 1.5-ounce chocolate bar
contains about the same amount of polyphenols as a 5-ounce glass of
red wine, according to studies conducted at the University of
California at Davis. The advantage to red wine is that it contains
fewer calories and no fat. But then again, you can't be convicted
for driving under the influence of a Hershey bar.
</P>
<P>
   And remember, it's the chocolate that had been counted, not
crisped rice, caramel, flour sugar or any of the other things that
are mixed with chocolate to produce candy, cookies, cakes or even
mole sauce.
</P>
<P>
   And what about all that fat?
</P>
<P>
   Stearic acid, one of two saturated fatty acids in chocolate does
not raise total plasma levels or LDL (that's the ``bad''
cholesterol) levels like other fatty acids according to studies at
Pennsylvania State University. Also, Penn State found that
consumption of chocolate raised the HDL (``good'' cholesterol) and
protected the LDL from oxidation, both of which are factors in
decreasing the risk of heart disease
</P>
<P>
   In addition, further studies at UC-Davis indicate people who
were given cocoa beverages to drink had less clumping of blood
platelets for two to six hours after drinking the beverage.
</P>
<P>
   As for the calorie count, ``There's no arguing that chocolate is
a calorie dense food,'' Vinson says. ``And no one's recommended you
eat chocolate all the time. But if you're going to have a snack,
wouldn't you want one with some health benefits as opposed to
something, like say, potato chips, that are just as high in fat and
calories but don't contain as many polyphenols?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
