<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4389 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-COLD-SOUP-HNS &LR;      07-06 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLD-SOUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SOUP: A COOL WAY TO ENDURE THE SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE WALKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Cold soup. Words that sound like an oxymoron in
January turn into a far more tantalizing proposition when July
rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   Deceptively simple to make, a chilled soup can be delicious and,
yes indeed, comforting when those temperatures start to climb into
three digits. Making it does present a few challenges, though.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the fat problem.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you can put cream into some cold soups, but forget butter,
shortening or vegetable oil. Fat that is absorbed in a hot soup,
adding all that delicious flavor, turns into unappealing little
pools on top of a soup that is cold. (All we can say here is, thank
heaven for olive oil.)
</P>
<P>
   Second, there is that thing that happens to flavors when food is
chilled. It is quite capable, when you least expect it, of pulling
a disappearing act.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there is the pesky matter of thickening. Make a fruit
soup, for example, thicken it up with a little roux, chill it down
and voila! You have a dull, icky mess on your hands.
</P>
<P>
   It might be enough to make us give up on the whole, chilly task,
but then we remember classics like iced consomme, or gazpacho,
Spain's delicious cold tomato and garlic soup. It's thickened to
just the right consistency with breadcrumbs, cooled, and served
garnished with all manner of crunchy and savory things _ chopped
olives, croutons, cold shrimp or crab.
</P>
<P>
   Or, a fruit soup with chunks of summer's best berries or peaches
drowned in a thick matrix of pureed fruit, sugar, white wine and a
thick drizzle of cream decorating the top.
</P>
<P>
   These cool soups are classics, meaning someone else has
surmounted the inherent difficulties for us. But anyone can create
a successful cold soup, quite simply, by adhering to a few
tried-and-true methods.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Blank, chef/owner at Hudson's on the Bend in Austin, Texas,
doesn't even think about the fat or thickening aspects of cold
soups. His colorful soup duo, chilled Poteet Strawberry and
Fredericksburg Peach Soup, is thickened by simply pureeing the
fruit with cream in separate blender batches and flavoring them
simply with a little sugar, white wine and lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fun dish. We put the strawberry and peach soups into
different glass pitchers or carafes. Then _ you have to have some
hand/eye coordination for this _ pour them into one bowl. Then, we
leave about a half-cup of one of the soups in the blender and whirl
in some blueberries and use (the mix) to paint the top of the
soups. You can really release the Picasso in yourself that way,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   This soup, he says, is Hudson's ``Tool Time Special'' _ ``the
best excuse there is for having duct tape and a blow torch in the
kitchen,'' says Blank. These tools aren't for making the soups, but
for fabricating a fancy iced flower bowl to serve it in.
</P>
<P>
   A sweet cold soup, such as this, can serve as either an
appetizer or a dessert. As an appetizer, a fruit soup piques the
appetite without overwhelming the palate. As a dessert, it provides
a light, refreshing finish that showcases summer's best produce.
</P>
<P>
   A savory cold soup is similarly flexible. It can serve as
appetizer, second course or main course. It just depends on how
it's presented.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Cohen, executive chef at La Mansion del Rio, tops his
gazpacho with a hearty mound of chilled fresh crabmeat. David Levy,
chef at the Westin Hotel's Caliza Grille, has a new summer item on
his menu _ a chilled calabaza (squash) soup with rock shrimp relish
and cinnamon cilantro oil.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Pedregon, cookbook author, chef and owner of the Peach
Tree Tea Room in Fredericksburg, Texas, has a recipe called Fiesta
Gazpacho that adds a Nuevo Latino touch to the classic recipe by
including black beans.
</P>
<P>
   Creamy cold soups are possibly the most popular at Pedregon's
restaurant, however. Her Chilled Avocado Soup, for instance,
doesn't lose flavor with chilling because the recipe calls for a
dash of Tabasco, some green onion and jalapeno. It gets its
thickness from buttermilk and sour cream and it is far and away the
most demanded cold soup on her summer menu, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kitchen gets so tired of making it they call it ``the
green menace,'' says Pedregon, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few points to remember about making a chilled, or
room temperature soup:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ingredients for cold soups are practically limitless. Use
fresh tomatoes and other seasonal produce, such as bell peppers,
onion, garlic. Roasted vegetables, such as squash, onions, pureed
cooked carrots, beets, zucchini, eggplant and so forth are good
seasoned with garlic and a little olive oil, pureed with fresh
herbs, fat-free chicken or vegetable stocks and so forth. Fruits,
such as avocado, mango, strawberries and peaches make good chilled
soups. Thin with a little wine, add a squeeze of lemon or lime for
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go light on sugar in fruit soups _ you want to taste
raspberry, strawberry or cherry, not sugar. Taste it as you make it
and leave it a little tart rather than too sweet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thicken fruit soups with reduced purees of fruit, thick cream
or sour cream. Don't use flour, as it will give the soup a duller,
opaque finish rather than a bright, shiny one. If you are
thickening a fruit soup by cooking it before chilling, thicken with
cornstarch or tapioca mixed with a little cold liquid, then add to
soup and cook to desired thickness.
</P>
<P>
   _ After you've chilled your soup, taste it once again before
serving. If the chilling has dulled the flavor, add another pinch
of fresh herbs, spices, a splash of wine, lemon juice or other
flavoring.
</P>
<P>
   _ Garnish with fresh chives, thin slices of scallion, tiny
pieces of diced red, orange and yellow pepper, a dab or drizzle of
sour or fresh cream, croutons, slices of cucumber, carrot, celery
stick and so forth. Bright soups, such as berry soups, will show
off their colors best in a clear bowl or even a stemmed glass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Bonnie Walker by e-mail at
bwalker1(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
