<HEADER>
A4414 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-GOP-CONVENTION-HNS &LR;      07-06 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOP TAPS THREE LAWMAKERS TO LEAD CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GARY MARTIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders have tapped three lawmakers _ a
black a Hispanic and a woman _ for high-profile roles at the GOP's
presidential nominating convention that begins July 31 in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Henry Bonilla of Texas, Jennifer Dunn of Washington and
J.C. Watts of Oklahoma were selected by the Bush campaign and
advisers with the Republican National Committee to serve as deputy
permanent co-chairmen during the weeklong event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taking a while to sink in,'' said Bonilla, reached by
telephone in Laredo. ``It's a tremendous honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Naming a Hispanic, a woman and a black to the posts underscores
Texas Gov. George W. Bush's effort to reach out to ethnic
minorities and bridge the gender gap in this presidential campaign
against Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is a different kind of Republican,'' said Scott
McClellan, a Bush spokesman in Austin. ``This is going to be a
different kind of convention, that reflects his positive and
inclusive agenda for America.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Allbaugh, the Bush campaign manager in Austin, notified
Bonilla of the selection earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The three co-chairmen will emcee the 37th Republican National
Convention. Bonilla, Dunn and Watts will introduce a cast of
Republican speakers and oversee the formal nomination of Bush as
the GOP presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same role held by Bush and New Jersey Gov. Christie
Whitman in 1996 when Republicans nominated Bob Dole as their
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla's stature within the party has continued to rise this
year, first as an adviser to Bush's campaign. He was later named
co-chairman of the RNC's Victory 2000 effort to reach out to
minority voters, a post that former GOP spokesman Mike Collins
called ``a major step'' in Bonilla's career.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn also was appointed to Victory 2000 in April.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla has been touted as a candidate for an administration
post if Bush is successful this November in his race against Gore.
The San Antonio congressman serves as a member of the powerful
House Appropriations Committee, a position that has helped him in
raising funds for the RNC and the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Watts, a former college quarterback, is a popular member of the
Oklahoma congressional delegation who was elected in 1998 to the
House leadership role of Republican Conference chairman. He is one
of several black Republicans advising the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn led an unsuccessful challenge to House Majority Leader Dick
Armey of Texas in 1998. This year she served with Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, R-Texas, as a co-chair of the Republican Women Leaders
Forum attended by more than 1,000 GOP leaders nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Gary Martin by e-mail at gmartin(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
