<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4430 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-0707-COX     07-06 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-0707-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIAN-CHECHEN WAR THREATENS REGIONAL SPILLOVER
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHATILI, Republic of Georgia _ At first glance, this fairy
tale-like medieval village perched halfway up a mountain slope
above the banks of a rushing mountain stream hardly seems like a
flashpoint for war.
</P>
<P>
   But almost every night, villagers say, explosions echo through
the craggy, snowcapped passes that mark Georgia's border with
Chechnya, as nearby Russian forces try to destroy the Chechen
separatist army that has enmeshed them in a nasty, brutish war of
hit-and-run attacks and suicide bombings.
</P>
<P>
   These battles have spilled into Georgia on at least three
occasions, with Russian helicopters bombing homes in Shatili and
wounding six people, and Russian forces occupying a Georgian
hamlet, according to the villagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really afraid the war will come across the border.
Twenty-four hours a day we wait for Russian planes to bomb us,''
said Mikhail Tshintsharauri, a 64-year-old geography teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces have inflicted thousands of civilian deaths in
their 10-month-old war against Chechen separatists, ignoring
international condemnation of what the Kremlin calls a ``domestic
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   However, fresh evidence shows that rebels pass back and forth
across the porous border just as Russian forces have undertaken
secretive incursions into Georgian territory itself. These actions
belie Moscow's insistence that its military campaign in Chechnya is
an internal matter. They also threaten to expand Russia's backyard
war into a regional conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Although badly outnumbered and outgunned, Chechen rebels have
evaded Russia's full-frontal assaults over the winter by holing up
in secret headquarters in the Caucasus mountains, whose snow-capped
9,000-foot peaks are virtually impenetrable except to the Chechens
and Georgians who have lived in the remote region for generations.
</P>
<P>
   The slower pace of fighting through the spring led Russian
generals to boast that organized Chechen resistance had been wiped
out and the war was over. Yet, rebels continue to inflict mounting
casualties against them, often spectacularly. The fighters' new
tactic _ suicide bombers _ killed and wounded more than 150 Russian
servicemen last week alone.
</P>
<P>
   Such repeated debacles have frustrated and embarrassed Russia's
top brass and led to a steady stream of Kremlin vitriol against the
usual scapegoat for the persistence of the Chechen rebellion:
international Islamic terrorist organizations. But recently, the
Kremlin has found a new whipping-boy in Georgia, Russia's southern
neighbor located between the Caspian and Black Seas where some
7,000 Chechen refugees live.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Yastrzhembsky, Russian President Vladimir Putin's
spokesman for Chechnya, told reporters on June 23 the Kremlin had
intelligence that more than 800 Chechen fighters were in Georgia,
and that rebel commanders were using refugee camps located in
Georgia's Pankis Gorge, some 31 miles from the border, as a supply
base for weapons and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know of a wide network of Chechen terrorists and
separatists (in Georgia),'' Yastrzhembsky said. The situation there
is ``getting out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgian officials say the 50-mile border separating the two
countries is effectively sealed, with more than 2,000 Russians
guarding passes on their side, and about one-third of that number
deployed on the Georgian side.
</P>
<P>
   While conceding that a few people may slip through the
cordoned-off frontier, Georgian border guards insist that large
groups of fighters have not used their land either as a safe haven
or for transshipping supplies or weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could anyone except an experienced mountain climber scale
that?'' said Col. Irakli Kopadze, standing in the narrow dirt path
leading to Shatili and waving an arm at the surrounding
mountainsides dotted with scrubby grass and treacherous footpaths
more fit for goats than humans. ``They may be passable for one or
two people, but not people loaded with heavy weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to the Pankis, a lush, agricultural region in
eastern Georgia, the well-equipped, highly-organized network of
fighters alleged by the Kremlin was not readily visible.
</P>
<P>
   But hints of rebel sympathies were abundant in the regional town
of Duisi as well as in Tbilisi, the Georgian capital, where the
self-described Chechen ambassador to Georgia _ a man branded by
Russia as a war criminal and living with a Russian arrest warrant
over his head _ keeps a highly public profile despite the Georgian
government's denials of support for the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   In Duici, a group of 13 Chechen men, the majority of whom were
large, fit and in their mid-20s, were mingling and smoking near the
central outdoor market. All said they had fled homes in Chechnya
and lost family members to Russian attacks. None admitted to being
rebels themselves, but a few said they knew of fighters in the
village.
</P>
<P>
   A grizzled, unshaven 45-year-old man who identified himself as
Abu pointed out a house where he said four fighters wounded by
Russian land mines in Chechnya were recuperating under the care of
their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif Sharip Djibrailov, a 52-year-old father of two from
Grozny, the Chechen capital, said men routinely slip across the
border from Georgia to return to Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young guys leave and go back to Chechnya,'' Djibrailov said
matter-of-factly. ``No one sees where they go. But they aren't
going back to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts in Tbilisi say the presence of a few fighters doesn't
prove Georgia's participation in the war. Still, they said, stories
like this fuel Russia's propaganda fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians aren't winning and they need someone to blame. So
they create rumors in Moscow (about rebel infiltration here). At
the same time, the Georgian government is weak. It doesn't control
what is going on either at the border or in the (Pankis) valley,''
said political analyst Sergi Prangishvili.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's belief that Georgia is indeed harboring terrorists has
led to multiple incursions by Russian forces into Georgian
territory, according to Georgian border officials.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic of these attacks occurred late last year. On
Nov. 17, 1999, three Russian helicopters bombed the pass between
the Russian and Georgian border posts, hitting the village of
Shatili. On Dec. 22, Russian helicopters again crossed over into
Georgian territory, shooting two rockets at houses in Shatili and
wounding six villagers.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow officially apologized for this incident, saying it had
intelligence that a home was being used as a Chechen communications
center _ an allegation Shatili residents deny.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Russian border guards have taken over a village
above Shatili higher in the mountain pass, which Georgian villagers
say is located in Georgia but the Russians say is located on their
side of the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Georgian officials have lodged no official protest about the
incursions, much to the dismay of the local population, most of
whom believe their government is too weak to stand up to Russia
while international support for Moscow is unwavering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very angry my government speaks nothing of it,'' said
Tshintsharauri, the schoolteacher. ``We villagers saw it as a
provocation. Russia wants to start a war.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Kremlin denied that its forces crossed into
Georgia and insists it is not in its interest to antagonize its
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fighting a war with a clever enemy. We are taking
precautions against this enemy. However, we would never violate
another country's border in pursuit of this,'' Kremlin spokesman
Yastrembsky said. ``This would make us equal to the terrorists whom
we are fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   On the web:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.rferl.org
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
