<TEXT>
<P>
   DIGITAL-MEMORIES: Will Digital Photos Last for Years? (UNDATED)
Across the nation, shutter clicks are giving way to the beep of
digital cameras. Shipments of digital cameras are expected to rise
over 60 percent this year over last, one research firm says. The
average price will drop 8 percent by year's end and is expected to
plunge another 16 percent by the end of 2001. Lured by ever better
and cheaper cameras, more consumers are going digital. No waiting
(or paying) for processing, pictures can be posted to a Web page,
printed out an unlimited number of times, or sent to friends and
relatives by e-mail almost as quickly as they can be taken. But
there may be a hidden cost: Even as they snap away, most consumers
have given scant thought to archiving their growing store of
digital photos. By Margie Wylie. About 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-POLITICS: GOP Resists Using Sampling as Census Fight
Continues (WASHINGTON) The 2000 census is ahead of schedule, on
budget and mired in politics and controversy. Despite an impressive
string of successes since it began in earnest on April 1, the
national head count has come under relentless attack from
Republicans over a plan to adjust the numbers to try to account for
millions of Americans who were missed. At stake is fair
representation in the nation's state legislatures and the House of
Representatives, along with billions of dollars in federal aid that
will be doled out over the next 10 years based on census data. By
J. Scott Orr. About 1,200 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
