<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SAFETY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPER FOOD HANDLING PREVENTS PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after June 8, 2000 by NYTimes News Service clients. A copy
is being transmitted to both food and lifestyle wires.) 
 
 
By ANGELA LEMIRE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Health officials estimate that more than 85,000 food-borne
illnesses occur during the summer months in Los Angeles County _
about half the cases for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   To kill food-poisoning bacteria when grilling:
</P>
<P>
   --Cook meat, poultry and fish thoroughly until well done, and
serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   --Never consume raw meat.
</P>
<P>
   --Reheat cooked food until very hot _ about 165 degrees
Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   --Refrigerate, or store in an ice chest, uncooked chicken in
plastic food storage bags or containers until ready for cooking or
marinating.
</P>
<P>
   --Store food containing eggs, poultry, meat or dairy products
separately to avoid cross contamination.
</P>
<P>
   --Do not allow other foods or cooking surfaces to touch raw
poultry or its drippings.
</P>
<P>
   --Likewise, do not reuse utensils, plates or bowls that have
been in contact with raw chicken, fish or meats for other raw or
cooked foods.
</P>
<P>
   --To prevent bacteria from multiplying, keep hot food hot and
cold food cold until ready to eat: Store uncooked or cold foods in
safe zones below 40 degrees and store freshly cooked foods in
warmers at a minimum of 140 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms of food-borne illnesses like salmonella can show up
from 30 minutes to three days after eating the contaminated food.
Vomiting, nausea, cramps, diarrhea and sometimes fever are common
symptoms. For more information on food safety, visit the Los
Angeles County Web site at www.lapublichealth.org or call the
County Food Safety Hotline at (888) 700-9995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4454 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CAR-BURTON-BOS &LR;      07-06 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BURTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURTON SEEMS TO BE ON THE RIGHT TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Jeff Burton will be the first to admit his
luck has been extraordinarily good at New Hampshire International
Speedway, where the NASCAR Winston Cup driver has won the last
three July races at the 1.058-mile oval in Loudon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's been a good one for us,'' said Burton, driver of
No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford Taurus, who won the Pepsi 400 at
Daytona International Speedway last Saturday night. ``It's pretty
strange that we've won the same race that many times. You see
people who go to a racetrack and they have it figured out and run
well there a lot, but to win that many times is unusual, especially
when it's the same race and there's two races there a year.''
</P>
<P>
   So, it is not an understatement when Burton says of NHIS, ``We
like the racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like? For the last three Julys, it has been
Burton's personal playground, where he has recorded a quarter of
his 12 career victories on the Winston Cup circuit. Although Jiffy
Lube has pulled out as the primary sponsor of Sunday's race, which
for now will be called the New England 300, it wouldn't be
far-fetched if it were renamed the ``Jeffy Lube 300,'' in honor of
Burton's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first two, we just had the better car; we were just
faster,'' Burton said. ``We drove away from the people we needed to
beat. We had a better-handling car than most people and we had
track position when it counted, and we got our deal done.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton pointed to a number of factors for his success at NHIS.
First, there is his crew chief, Frank Stoddard, of North Haverhill,
N.H., who has developed quite a dossier on the track. Then there is
the support of car owner Jack Roush, whose deep pockets have always
provided Burton with the best equipment. And, finally, there is
Lady Luck, who certainly smiled upon Burton in last year's race.
</P>
<P>
   Burton qualified poorly and started 38th. After Saturday's Happy
Hour practice session yielded few results, Stoddard made
significant adjustments to the springs, shocks, and track bar _ on
the morning of the race, no less _ that enabled Burton to motor to
the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of major changes, but we felt we had enough
experience there that we could make some of the right calls,'' said
Stoddard, who masterminded the two-tire pit strategy that enabled
Burton to win at Daytona last week. ``I wasn't worried about us
getting to the front, but I was concerned after Happy Hour that we
didn't have a fast enough car to get to the front. But with all the
changes we made, it turned out right.''
</P>
<P>
   The adjustments put Burton in position to win his third
consecutive Jiffy Lube 300 when Tony Stewart fell out of the lead,
running out of gas with 11 laps remaining. Burton pitted for a
quick splash of fuel with two laps to go and made a return visit to
Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we've won there, we've generally had a better-handling
car than most people,'' Burton said. ``We had the second-best
handling car last year, but the 20 car made a mistake and we were
in a position to win. You win a lot of races like that and you lose
a lot of races like that. You lose races where you had the best car
and something didn't go right for you, and you win races when you
had the next-best car and something went right for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the best car doesn't always win. And on that day, the best
car didn't win; the best strategy won.''
</P>
<P>
   As he sat in his hauler in the garage at Daytona last Friday,
Burton expressed some concern about going to New Hampshire because
``we have struggled at places that we've never struggled before,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth in the point standings, Burton said he hoped a return to
Victory Lane at NHIS would be the spark, the momentum boost, his
team needed at the start of the second half of the grueling Winston
Cup season.
</P>
<P>
   That was, of course, before Burton recorded his first
restrictor-plate victory at Daytona, where he finished runner-up to
Dale Jarrett in the Daytona 500. However, he held off Jarrett in an
exciting shootout with three laps to go to win the Pepsi 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really big for our race team,'' said Burton, who earned
$152,450 but remained fifth in points (2,314) behind leader Bobby
Labonte (2,527). ``We needed a kick in the pants and we got it. I
did a great job of driving and Frank did a great job of making some
calls and setting the car up.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Burton will try to make it four in a row. Lest
you think it has never been done in NASCAR, think again. Darrell
Waltrip once won seven consecutive races at Bristol, Tenn.,
including four Valleydale 500s from 1981-1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about New Hampshire is that the race is long and
there's enough places to pass,'' Burton said. ``If your car is
driving well, there's places to pass, but if your car is not
driving well, you can't pass _ anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do qualify poor, it's the type of racetrack that will
allow you to get some moves made, but you've got to have everything
good go your way when you start in the back. You've got to have
good pit stops, you've got to make the right move at the right
time. It's a tough racetrack, but it's a fun racetrack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
