<SLUG> BC-GRILLING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THRILL OF THE GRILL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after Sat., June 8, 2000 by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: This story is being transmitted to both lifestyle and food
wires. Goes with sidebar on food safety.) 
By ANGELA LEMIRE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
So you can't stand the heat and want out of the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise some grill power.
</P>
<P>
   No longer just a knockabout accessory for the occasional picnic
or poolside barbecue, today's outdoor grills have sophisticated
features, heating elements and accessories that make the grill an
all-purpose mega appliance for year-round cooking _ let alone a
great excuse to spend more time in the yard this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor set-ups can be nearly as versatile, functional and
efficient as indoor kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   And rest assured, grills offer plenty of variety to one's diet _
given the right equipment and, of course, the right chef at the
helm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make it as kitchenlike as possible, but only as
much as you need it to be,'' says Dan Cannon, an Agua Dulce
resident and Southern California Barbeque Association president,
who rarely tires of grilling. ``I barbecue one to two days each
week year-round. I don't even let the rain stop me.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's grills smoke, steam, roast and rotisserie everything
from burgers, steaks and lobsters to leg of lamb, whole chickens
and turkey. Add-ons and side burners make it possible to serve up a
veggie saute, stir fry, pasta or sauce on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the variety of food, limits are non-existing,''
agrees Ken Ostrander, manager of Barbeques Galore in Tarzana, which
sells grill accessories, parts, flavored wood chips and grills for
every price range.
</P>
<P>
   Accessories that adapt the grill to various cooking styles take
many forms: Skillets, smokers and adjustable baskets keep fish,
skewers and other meats from falling apart on the grill; Another
gadget resembling a slotted hub cap even bakes potatoes on the
grill.
</P>
<P>
   Steam trays are great for cooking seafood such as shrimp and
mussels, or vegetables like asparagus spears.
</P>
<P>
   And side burners _ which can be purchased separately, or found
attached to grills within most price ranges _ are handy for boiling
corn or beans, frying up peppers, mushrooms and onions as meat
toppers, heating sauces or cooking chili.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter the dinner menu, setting up an efficient barbecue
and work station is very important in creating complete meals
outdoors, notes Frank Boyer of the California Barbecue Association.
</P>
<P>
   Safety and location should be primary considerations, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor grills should be placed away from flammable objects like
houses and lawn furniture, combustible materials such as backup
barbecue fuel canisters, and _ for the grill master's sake _
preferably in shady areas where tree branches have been pruned and
won't catch fire.
</P>
<P>
   Metal pans should be kept near the grill to dump hot coals, as
well as a fire extinguisher for grease fires.
</P>
<P>
   The next consideration should be an ample work space to prepare,
cut or marinate foods, especially when the main grilled entree is
accompanied by grilled side dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A prep area can be anything from a patio table that everyone
eats at to a special prep table used just for grilling,'' said
Cannon. ``And if you don't have those things, you can cut your
vegetables or season your meats in the house and carry them
outside, ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Many grills come with prep areas.
</P>
<P>
   On the top end, you can spend more than $6,000 for a permanent
backyard setup like a DCS natural gas-powered model at Barbeques
Galore that comes with stainless steel casing for its appliances,
twin burners, preparation counter, storage cabinets and
electrically charged refrigeration. Drawers make it easier to keep
grilling tools and accessories within reach.
</P>
<P>
   Less expensive charcoal and propane-powered grills also come
with preparation areas, though much smaller and shelflike, plus
tool racks and side-burners. Grills with these basic features run
as low as $150 to $200.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cannon and Boyer suggest other must-haves: Fresh water for
washing and rinsing hands and utensils, long tongs, separate
thermometers to measure food and heat source temperatures, separate
cutting boards and knives for poultry and meat, thermal gloves to
prevent burns, a good grill brush, spray bottle or brush and bowl
to baste food, and separate food storage areas for both cold and
hot food.
</P>
<P>
   Cannon also suggests installing Plexiglass walls around grill
areas or barbecue pits as shelter from the wind, and using large
weatherproof rubber containers to store wood and unused charcoal
between uses to keep them dry.
</P>
<P>
   And for maximum enjoyment, always treat your barbecue grill like
the great outdoor entertainer that it is, says Boyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep it social. Keep it fun,'' says Boyer. ``You don't want
the head chefs standing off to the side by themselves. You want
them to be part of the party, and the grill area large enough for
people to help out. Most people just naturally congregate around
cooking areas, whether it's the kitchen in the house or outdoors.
That's just a fact of life.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
