<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLYWOOD SIDING COULD BECOME SHEATHING FOR CEDAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My house has T-1-11 plywood siding, and I would rather use it
as sheathing to put new cedar siding on. Is that practicable? Also,
along the gable ends, where there is a trim board following the
slope of the roof, should I remove that board before putting up the
siding, then put the board back over the siding? Or is it better to
leave the board in place and trim the siding so that it abuts the
sloping board?
</P>
<P>
   MIKE LYON, Canton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is practicable to put cedar clapboards or shingles over
the T-1-11, but there is one important thing to be aware of. If the
windows and their frames are flush with that T-1-11, the new siding
will have nothing to butt against when it hits the frames of
windows and doors. So, you must nail a piece of trim or other
molding on the sides and tops of all windows and doors to provide
something for the siding to butt into.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rake board (the trim board that follows the slope of
the roof at the gable), the lazy way to do it in new construction
is to put up the siding, then put on the trim board. This results
in little openings at each row of clapboard or shingle, and these
openings are often used by nesting wasps. It's not a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   The other way is to put up the rake board (yours is already in
position), then trim the siding to butt against the rake board as
you apply it. This is fussy work, and takes time, and that is why
professionals don't like to do it. But it is much better, gives a
neater appearance (if you trim the siding for a snug fit), and
leaves no openings for critters.
</P>
<P>
   Since your rake boards are already in position, take the time to
trim the siding to fit the slope.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My finished-basement walls are covered with plasterboard. I
don't know how long the plasterboard has been up, but it was there
when I bought the house in 1987. The basement is dry. I would like
to paint those walls. Is there anything extra I have to do because
the walls are in the basement?
</P>
<P>
   STEVE POWERS, Kingston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If there are no signs of wetness from the past, there is is
nothing extra you have to do. The standard procedure is to apply
two thin coats of a latex wall paint; it will be good for years.
But you can do one extra thing that will not take any extra work or
paint, to make sure you get a good bond on the plasterboard. And
that is: Apply one thin coat of a latex enamel undercoater, then
one coat of the latex wall paint. If your finish coat is white,
then one coat is needed. If the finish coat is a different color,
apply two coats.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that thick coats fail, but thin coats work most of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I can't find anyone who will wash and polish my mahogany
ceiling beams. They were polished and quite shiny, but they have
gotten dull. Where can I find a person who will do this?
</P>
<P>
   SARAH AGABIAN, Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If it entails cleaning the beams, why not a housecleaning
service? Some services may say they don't do beams just as others
say they don't do windows. I have no answer to that. I doubt if the
beams were polished; the shine probably came from the varnish.
Cleaning them may dull them even further, but the shine can be
restored by buffing with a dry cloth.
</P>
<P>
   And why not leave well enough alone? They might benefit from
dusting, but even dull beams look good on a ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My roof is 75 years old with two layers of shingles on it.
The top layer is in good shape, and I know both layers must come
off. Trouble is, one roofer said he would not do anything unless I
strip the board planking and put in 3/4-inch plywood. Is that
necessary?
</P>
<P>
   DAVE CRISTMONT, Salisbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Whoa! It probably is not necessary, and if it were, the
roofer should do it. A roof 75 years old is unlikely to have bad
planks, but stripping the shingles will reveal any bad planks,
which can then be replaced. And certainly not everything's needs to
be covered with 3/4-inch plywood. At best, with some planks
replaced, 3/8-inch plywood is all you need to smooth everything
out.
</P>
<P>
   Find another roofer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a nice Shaker bench that is painted with latex paint.
Can I paint it over with oil? If I can, how?
</P>
<P>
   CONNIE ANDREWS, Yarmouthport, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes you can, but why? Is the latex finish peeling? Is it
wearing off? OK, there must be a reason, so this is what you can
do: Sand the bench lightly to reduce gloss and roughen the finish,
apply an oil primer or a latex enamel undercoater (either will work
well), and finish with two thin coats of the oil enamel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4461 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-06 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MANHATTAN DISCOVERS THE LEFT COAST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The New York Times just discovered that
California is no longer predominantly white, or as the Times put
it, ``the California of postwar popular imagination, of the Beach
Boys and the John Birch Society, of Disneyland and monochromatic
Pleasantvilles.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah yes, remember the days when everyone in California was blond,
even Annette Funicello.
</P>
<P>
   The Times breathlessly reported this week that sometime in the
next year ``California will become the first big state in the
nation in which non-Hispanic whites are officially no longer a
majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that news? And what's a non-Hispanic white? I always thought
people from Spain were white, or as close to that color as any of
us get.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind San Francisco and Oakland. When was the last time a
gentleman or gentlewoman from the Times visited the Santa Monica
Pier, the Santa Cruz Boardwalk or even the beaches of La Jolla or
Del Mar? It's been years since the average surfer girl or beach
boy, not to mention hodad, has been blond.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, it's been years since any blonds really have been blond.
</P>
<P>
   California dreaming always has been a pipe dream, and finally
the powers that be at the New York Times managed to take their eyes
off Al Gore and the Clintons and notice the reality of the state
where politicians raise much of their money. Maybe all those
fund-raisers in Beverly Hills and Woodside are a bit on the
monochromatic side.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with being white. It's not right
to pick on minorities, especially a minority whose members
elsewhere in the country may be a self-satisfied majority. The
Times didn't directly address some of the questions Rush Limbaugh
might raise for a national audience upon reading the story.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever someone makes a joke about white men not being able to
jump, can we jump up in anger (well, a little way) instead of
having to force a smile?
</P>
<P>
   Can we have our own special programs to raise test scores so
white kids can get into the University of California?
</P>
<P>
   Can we start pronouncing our names with English, Norwegian or
Polish accents (particularly when signing off news reports) to
celebrate our heritage?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is no. Sorry, Rush. By the way, does
Limbaugh still have a show, or did all the angry white men turn
into resigned or guilt-ridden white men?
</P>
<P>
   There are bigger questions, ones for all Californians, not just
its newest minority:
</P>
<P>
   _ Will Woody Allen stop picking on California now that this
isn't the land of shallow blonds?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will the Eastern media ever look at California as something
other than a freak show? Once this was the land of surfers, hippies
and religious cults. Now it's the land of youth gangs, illegal
immigrants, techie weirdos and fat liberation.
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern establishment needs California the way Freud needed
an id, as a place to blame for all weird, powerful or unexplainable
impulses. Pardon the Woody Allenish invocation of Freud.
</P>
<P>
   First, Eastern snobs said the country was tilted to the left and
everything that wasn't tied down rolled in. Then they said all
strange ideas start in California and move east. Now they're saying
that everyone who isn't tied down in Latin America and Asia is
moving to California, as if that's a strange idea.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted to get out of Latin America or Asia, wouldn't you
want to come here? California dreaming is done in all colors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
