<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING A VOCABULARY FOR SEXUAL ORIENTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents around the country owe a debt of gratitude to David
Gaita, the gay first-grade teacher in Newton, Mass. who made
headlines after he came out to his students in May. Thanks to him,
we all have a reason to talk to our children about sexual
orientation, a subject we tend to avoid even though our culture,
not to mention our children's playground talk, is full of it.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind, we're talking about sexual orientation, not sexual
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not appropriate to talk to 6- or 7-year-olds about the
intimate acts two consenting adults engage in. It's confusing, not
something they can process,'' says San Francisco family therapist
Kevin Gogin, director of that city's public school health education
program, the most comprehensive in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations about the mechanics of sex are better suited to a
slightly older child; in San Francisco, it's part of the fifth- and
sixth-grade health curriculums. Even then, Gogin says, teachers
simply provide definitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't talk about personal sexual practices,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual orientation, on the other hand, is a concept children are
exposed to from birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual orientation explains family diversity; it's just that
we tend not to think of it that way,'' says clinical psychologist
April Martin of New York City. She says when we say things like
``Daddy loves Mommy'' or ``Mommy loves Daddy,'' we are teaching
about heterosexuality; when children observe our affection,
loyalty, and trust, they are learning about the partnership that
goes on between parents.
</P>
<P>
   By 4 or 5, most children notice on their own that there are
differences between families. In today's world, it's hard for them
not to: The typical day care or preschool has its share of children
raised by stepmothers, stepfathers, grandmothers, grandfathers,
parents of different races, two mothers, or two fathers. Despite
the differences, however, preschoolers are able to see that all
families are still basically the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as they understand that the Great Dane and the cocker
spaniel are both dogs, they know that two women raising a child and
a man and woman raising 11 children are both families, regardless
of how many people there are or the sex of the parents,'' says
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   To preschoolers, the differences are neither good nor bad; they
just are. This changes in elementary school, however. Kids begin to
hear things.
</P>
<P>
   From news headlines and local events like gay pride parades,
television shows with gay and lesbian characters (``Will and
Grace,'' ``Friends,'' ``Ellen,'' ``Spin City''), movies (``Ace
Ventura''), and magazines that trumpet the lifestyles of
celebrities such as Melissa Etheridge and Ellen DeGeneres, children
hear words such as ``gay,'' ``lesbian,'' and ``homosexual.''
</P>
<P>
   Do they know what the words mean?
</P>
<P>
   They don't at 4 or 5 or even 6 or 7, says developmental
psychologist Karen Anderson, but they attach values to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids pick up words: `gay,' `dyke,' `fag,' `homo.' They hear
them used on the playground and in the culture as put-downs, so
they attach negative stereotypes to them and hurl them without
really knowing what they mean,'' says Anderson. She is director of
the Center for Psychology in Schools and Education at the American
Psychological Association in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   This can be particularly hurtful to boys who don't fit the mold
of what a boy is supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gender rules are very powerful and rigid for kids 5 to 10,''
says Anderson. ``If you're a 7-year-old boy who doesn't like sports
but likes to read and play the cello, that's atypical gender
behavior, and you're likely going to be rejected because of it and
called fag or gay.''
</P>
<P>
   By middle school and often sooner, the stereotypes become the
foundation for confusion, discrimination, and violence.
</P>
<P>
   It's with this developmental background in mind that San
Francisco developed a health curriculum that includes ``My Family''
for kindergarteners.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they draw a picture of their own families, there's a
discussion of what other kinds of families there might be that
aren't already represented,'' for instance, two dads or two moms,
says Gogin. Teachers define heterosexual as ``a person who is
attracted to and falls in love with a person of the opposite sex''
and homosexual as ``a person who is attracted to and falls in love
with a person of the same sex.'' They also say homosexuals are
known as gay men and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a conversation about sex,'' says Gogin. ``It's
about the way people are in our community. For 5- to 8-year-olds,
this is a source of comfort and safety: They see the diversity
around them, they may even live it.''
</P>
<P>
   For child psychologist Dan McPherson of San Francisco, getting
stereotypes out in the open when children are young can go a long
way to making the world easier and safer for them as they grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most kids develop odd notions unless we clear up their
language and their stereotypes,'' he says. Questions and comments
he typically gets from young children include: ``What do gay people
eat?'' or ``I don't think I can be gay because I want to be a
doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the San Francisco curriculum is the idea of
respect and tolerance for all differences. Gogin describes an
activity for fifth-graders that drives it home graphically:
</P>
<P>
   Each child creates a cutout of him/herself that the teacher
links to form a paper people chain. She asks the students to keep
track of the name-calling they hear in a day. As they share the
insults with the class, she breaks one link in the chain for every
slur, demonstrating how damaging insults can be. Then the class
talks about how to repair the hurts.
</P>
<P>
   This, obviously, is not just about homosexuality, but about
accepting all diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very powerful,'' says Gogin.
</P>
<P>
   Once the subject of homosexuality is raised in the classroom,
parents, of course, have an opening to talk about their own values,
says sexuality educator Debra Haffner, author of ``From Diapers to
Dating'' (Newmarket) and former executive director of the Sexuality
Information and Education Council of the United States. For
instance, ``In our family, here's what we think about this . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, this is what Newton parents did after David Gaita
sent home a letter detailing the conversation he had in his
classroom May 17. According to reports, as the class discussed
biographies and families, students asked about his family. He told
them that if he had a partner, it would be a man, and he defined a
partner as ``someone you love the way your mom and dad love each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaita's principal and Newton schools superintendent Jeff Young
were supportive of Gaita, as were most parents. Psychologist
Anderson says Gaita handled the situation ``beautifully. It's what
every parent should hope for in a teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
AGE-APPROPRIATE INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Questions 10- and 11-year-olds tend to ask, with suggested
answers: &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. ``How do you become gay?'' &QL; 
A. ``Nobody really knows, but it isn't something you catch, and it
doesn't come from hanging out with someone.'' &QL; 
Q. ``What if I'm gay?'' &QL; 
A. ``Many people your age wonder about this. What's important is
for you to be who you are, whatever that is, and to know that I'll
love you any way you are.'' &QL; 
Q. ``What do gay men/lesbians do?'' &QL; 
A. ``There are different ways people give each other pleasure,
sometimes genital to genital, sometimes hand or mouth to genital''
or ``When I grew up, people didn't talk about these things, so I
never got comfortable talking about it. Who can we think of for you
to talk to?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Messages for 5- to 8-year-olds, recommended by the Sexuality
Information and Education Council of the United States: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Everyone is born a boy or girl and grows up to be a man or
woman. Human beings experience different kinds of loving. Most men
and women are heterosexual. Some men and women are homosexual. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Messages for 9- to 12-year-olds, also from the council: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sexual orientation refers to whether a person is heterosexual,
homosexual, or bisexual (a person attracted to both men and women).
Heterosexual, homosexual, and bisexual people are alike except for
their sexual attraction. Homosexuals and bisexuals are often
mistreated, called hurtful names, or denied their rights because of
sexual orientation. Some people are afraid to admit they are
bisexual or homosexual because they fear they will be mistreated.
Homosexual love relations can be as fulfilling as heterosexual
relationships. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Instead of pointing out to your child only the
times he doesn't meet your expectations, catch him in the act of
doing something right and make it a big deal. For instance, brag to
someone about it when you know he'll overhear you. From ``Boost
Your Child's Self-Esteem: Simple, Effective Ways to Build
Children's Self-Respect and Confidence,'' by Karin Ireland (Berkley
Books, 2000).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz welcomes letters and comments and can be reached
via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
