<HEADLINE>
PALMTOP SUFFERS; MICROSOFT, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since Microsoft Corp. found itself ensnared in the federal
antitrust lawsuit, industry mavens like me have been on the lookout
for signs that the software titan was going soft under the strain.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few: Microsoft's inability to quash the
growing popularity of the Linux operating system, and the
retirements and departures of many of the firm's key executives.
Now I think I've stumbled across yet another sign of corporate
decay _ a good Microsoft product that would probably have been
better, if the company had been able to pop the whip as it did back
in the day.
</P>
<P>
   I refer to one of the latest palmtop computers running
Microsoft's Pocket PC software. I've spent a month using the
Hewlett-Packard Jornada 540, and the glitches and imperfections
I've stumbled across prove that Microsoft and Hewlett-Packard
aren't singing from the same hymnbook.
</P>
<P>
   I figure the antitrust case is partly to blame. Among other
things, Microsoft was condemned because it wouldn't let desktop
computer makers change the look and feel of the Windows operating
system. In the view of the US Justice Department, Microsoft's
tactics deprived the public of countless innovations in computer
user interfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But consider the alternatives. Apple Computer Inc.
makes both the hardware and software for the Macintosh computer;
Palm Inc. makes the hardware and software for the Palm Pilot.
Because of this total control, both companies produce products that
are elegant and easy to use. Microsoft doesn't make computer
hardware, so it tried to keep it simple for consumers by ordering
PC makers not to touch anything. Looks like they can't do that any
more.
</P>
<P>
   And so we end up with the user interface of the HP Jornada. It's
like trying to use two computers at once; both HP and Microsoft
have installed their own menus, each with a different layout. There
are two places where you can reset screen contrast, but only one
for adjusting screen brightness. There are two places for checking
available memory; one lets you adjust memory levels, while the
other does not.
</P>
<P>
   In the good old days, Microsoft would simply have told HP to sit
down, shut up, and do it their way. Unfair, perhaps. Nasty?
Definitely. But it would have made the Jornada a lot easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another irksome example. The Jornada has a built-in
digital voice recorder that I used to record a half-hour interview.
I dumped the file onto my desktop computer, only to discover that
it could only be played back on the Jornada. Nobody has written PC
software that'll play back this sound format. I could have reset
the device to use a PC-compatible format if I'd known. But once
upon a time, I wouldn't have had to know. Microsoft would have
insisted that HP make its sound files PC-compatible or else. Ah,
those were the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a bruised, demoralized Microsoft is also easing up on its
own employees. That might explain the Jornada's most inexcusable
flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Like any good palmtop, the Jornada can store your personal
address book. During a road trip, I needed to look up a contact at
IBM Corp. I couldn't remember the name; I just knew he was at IBM.
And that meant the Jornada was useless, because the
Microsoft-designed contact program won't let you search by company
name.
</P>
<P>
   Every other palmtop I've ever seen has this feature, including
previous Pocket PCs. But out of carelessness or laziness, Microsoft
has left it out. It's an astonishing lapse, and I couldn't imagine
buying a Pocket PC until it's fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a pity, because there's much to like about the $500
Jornada. It's smaller and lighter than previous Pocket PC models,
weighing and costing about the same as a Palm Pilot with a color
screen. And it boasts features that Palm Pilot users can only dream
about. There's the built-voice recording, for instance, and the
ability to play MP3 music files. Microsoft Reader, the company's
new electronic book software, is excellent; small enough for a
jacket pocket but clear enough to let me read the latest Michael
Crichton bestseller during a plane ride to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with the Jornada that couldn't be fixed by
a ruthless, aggressive corporate bully that would ride roughshod
over its partners and employees to get the product right. There
used to be a company like that in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
