<HEADER>
A4465 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-GENETIC-TESTING-ART-B     07-06 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENETIC-TESTING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 GENETIC CODE MAPPED, DRUG MAKER SEEKS NEW PREDICTIVE TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before the first drugs derived from the human genome
project ever reach pharmacists' shelves, gene-based diagnostic
tests will emerge to assess a patient's chances for a complete
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Medicine has begun a major shift, toward being able to remedy
the underlying causes of diseases and away from relying on the
diagnosis and treatment of symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, scientists are developing tests to predict
whether a patient will suffer a relapse and require more radical
treatment, or enjoy a speedy and complete recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Initially focused on cancer, these diagnostic and genomic tests
are aimed at recovering patients who want to know whether the
disease is no longer active or will pose problems down the road.
The results could lead to more aggressive medical treatment and
counseling, or provide the relief of knowing that a tumor is
benign.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc. has developed such a test for
melanoma patients, based on a gene that produces melastatin. Tumors
removed from under the skin would be tested at a laboratory by
pathologists. Tumors containing melastatin are most likely to be
cancer-free, while those with little or no melastatin could cause
more serious skin cancer problems, said Dr. Michael Kaufman, vice
president of medicine at Millennium's Predictive Medicine group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are measuring the distribution of melastatin in a tumor,
and from that determining how the cancer has spread,'' said
Kaufman, noting there are 44,000 new cases of skin cancer annually
and that 1 in every 75 Americans will get skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium's skin cancer test, which will be marketed by Becton
Dickinson &AMP; Co., a supplier of medical devices, diagnostic systems
and equipment, is one of six diagnostic genomic cancer tests being
developed based on Millennium Predictive Medicine's gene
discoveries. The company's president, Kenneth Conway, expects the
skin cancer test to be on the market this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to change the practice of medicine,'' he said, ``with
tests based on our knowledge of cancer genes that enable people who
have a problem to do something positive about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Details about the test, which was developed and tested at
Massachusetts General Hospital, are expected to be published by
fall, said Dr. Lyn M. Duncan, an assistant professor of pathology
at Harvard Medical School and a Mass. General pathologist who
worked closely with Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the tools we use for skin and many other cancers
are largely based on physical observations,'' Duncan said. ``I
think the public and cancer patients can expect a wealth of
information from the human genome project.''
</P>
<P>
   The Millennium/Becton Dickinson tests are considered the first
wave of a new generation of gene-based predictive tests. Within the
next 10 years, geneticists say researchers will create genetic
tests that will be able to predict babies' predisposition for
breast, colon, and prostate cancer, heart disease, and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   The use of patient information from such genetic tests raises
some ethical and legal questions. Despite federal laws including
the Americans with Disabilities Act that bans the use of genetic
tests to discriminate in the workplace, the extent of consumer
protection has yet to be tested in court.
</P>
<P>
   From the inception of the human genome projects, ethicists have
warned that genetic knowledge might be used against people as it
relates to insurance coverage and employment. In February,
President Clinton issued an order barring genetic discrimination in
the hiring of federal workers. He also endorsed legislation now
pending in Congress that would prohibit enrollment restrictions and
higher premiums for health and life insurance policies based on
predictive genetic information or genetic services.
</P>
<P>
   While several states have already added genetic privacy laws,
Massachusetts is now looking to develop one that would protect
against the dissemination of genetic test information.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a survey of the American Management Association found
30 percent of large and mid-sized firms seek some form of genetic
information about their employees, of which 7 percent used that
information in awarding promotions and hiring.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Millennium/Becton Dickinson genetic skin cancer test
stands out because of its predictive capabilities. The exam _
expected to be performed as an adjunct to the standard tumor
thickness measurement exam by pathologists _ is different from the
more than 200 genetic exams now on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tests currently available can cost between $800 and
$2,500 each. They range from determining genetic diseases in
newborns to learning whether an individual has a mutated gene and
is a carrier of a disease, such as cystic fibrosis, Huntington's
disease, or sickle cell anemia.
</P>
<P>
   Other genetic tests can determine whether there is a family
history of disease even without any current symptoms or calculate
the probability that a healthy individual with or without a family
history will develop that disease.
</P>
<P>
   Exact Laboratories Inc. of Maynard is developing a colon cancer
test that measures the abnormal amount of DNA in a person's stool.
Currently, colon cancer is evaluated through sigmoidoscopies and
colonoscopies _ devices that physicans use to visually examine the
colon.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our test you either have colon cancer or you don't,''
said Stanley Lapidus, Exact's chief executive, noting the proposed
test is currently undergoing a pivotal clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium's entry into the diagnostic market with Becton
Dickinson follows several companies developing breast cancer tests.
One of the first genetic cancer exams came from Myriad Genetics
Inc. of Salt Lake City, which found two specific genes, BRCA1 and
BRCA2, that are linked to breast cancer. However, its genetic
predisposition test is limited, since fewer than 8 percent of women
with breast cancer have mutations in these genes.
</P>
<P>
   And there are many nongenetic tests that identify whether a
person has a certain disease ranging, from pap smears that women
have annually to detect signs of cervical cancer, to a simple urine
test developed by Matritech Inc. of Newton, Mass. for diagnosing
bladder cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see ourselves as complementary to what Millennium has,''
said David L. Corbett, president and chief operating officer of
Matritech, which is developing a series of other cancer tests based
on its patented nuclear matrix proteins.
</P>
</TEXT>
