<HEADLINE>
AT 175 MPH, 911 TURBO CAUSES EARTH TO SHIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACK ROCK DESERT, Nev. _ We are strapped tightly into the 2001
Porsche 911 Turbo as it reaches 150 miles per hour and sizzles
across the cracked desert floor.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two of us we have five wins at the 24 Hours of
Daytona, three wins at the 24 Hours of Le Mans, two wins at the 12
Hours of Sebring, and four good wrecks at the Hopkinton, N.H.,
State Fair Demolition Derby.
</P>
<P>
   All the endurance wins belong to the great Hurley Haywood. The
demolition derby wrecks were mine.
</P>
<P>
   I am driving as we head to 175-plus miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The surface over which we race is the hard, dried silt of a
playa (Spanish for intermittent lake). In 1997, a jet car broke the
sound barrier on this surface. But it is not stable. Cracked in the
sun, it resembles an unassembled jigsaw puzzle. Even light cars
leave shattered tracks. In some places, the pieces shift beneath
your feet.
</P>
<P>
   The effect can be disconcerting. In a test run parallel to the
main track on which we go for a top speed, the car had wiggled its
rear steadily as the surface shifted beneath it. Like driving in an
inch of snow.
</P>
<P>
   Haywood's advice? Let the car go where it will go. Use the wheel
ever so delicately. Half-inch turns in either direction are plenty.
But that is not your instinct when, at 125 miles per hour, the car
hints at slipping sideways. There is a danger of overcorrecting.
That would be a bad thing, especially at higher speeds. Delicate
steering takes some time to get used to when your head screams
``countersteer.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, I have had two days and more than 300 miles in this
marvelous new car, which is the fastest, most stable street machine
Porsche has ever built.
</P>
<P>
   It is an all-wheel-drive, road-eating beast powered by an
all-new Porsche engine based on the power plant from the Le
Mans-winning GT1 race car. With two intercooled turbochargers and
24 valves, the 3.6-liter engine packs a walloping 415 horsepower
and 413 lb.-ft. of torque.
</P>
<P>
   Most impressive is the peak torque band, which runs from 2,700
to 4,600 rpms. Even in sixth gear with the manual transmission, the
car picks up and goes like a rocket.
</P>
<P>
   It does 0-62 in 4.2 seconds. Top speed can be around 190 miles
per hour. Air dams with channeled flows, spoiler lips at the front
of the wheel arches, and a hydraulic rear wing (it pops up at 75
m.p.h.) provide down force to keep the Porsche hugging the road.
</P>
<P>
   And hug it it does, as those 300 miles proved.
</P>
<P>
   There are places in Nevada where undulating roads stretch as far
as you can see. A tempting place to let it rip. And it's clear that
this Porsche could go from top speed limit well into triple digits
in seconds.
</P>
<P>
   There are places in Nevada where roads climb up to 9,000 feet _
roads that twist and turn and switch back again and again.
Sometimes there are guardrails, sometimes there are not. In some
places, you round a corner and are looking out over an endless
valley 4,000 feet below. It's as if you're looking out the
windscreen of an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   One of these snakes runs up to Virginia City, the old mining
town. It is here they hold the Virginia City Hill Climb. A tempting
place to see how the Porsche corners at speed.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear the 911 Turbo could rip the brief straights in triple
digits, take the corners and hairpins and switchbacks at four times
the posted limit, and feel as if it's riding on rails.
</P>
<P>
   The faster these cars go, the more stable they become, one
Porsche executive said at the car's introduction in Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Back out on the Black Rock Desert Playa, stability was just what
I was looking for.
</P>
<P>
   The acceleration run was to be made along a 3-mile course.
Orange cones marked its edges. In the distance, mirages that looked
like silver clouds danced along the horizon. The curvature of the
earth was evident.
</P>
<P>
   The speed test 911 was the European model _ 20 millimeters lower
than the US model. Its Pirelli N3 tires had been X-rayed to check
for defects.
</P>
<P>
   For safety equipment, it had an elaborate roll cage, racing
seats, and five-point safety harness. It also came equipped with
Haywood.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to speed up through the first mile, hit the second
and critical measured mile at high speed, put the gas pedal to the
floor and keep it there as the United States Auto Club recorded
average speed for the mile and top speed. The third mile would be
used to slow down. It was this last, frankly, that worried me more
than running the middle mile at speed. How do you stop smoothly on
this surface? Let's find out.
</P>
<P>
   We took off gradually, then worked our way up through the gears,
the familiar wiggle setting in at about 100 miles per hour _ the
last time I looked down at the speedometer.
</P>
<P>
   I looked only straight ahead and well down the race course. At
high speed, looking out the side or too close to the front of the
car can induce dizziness.
</P>
<P>
   The cones seemed to rise out of the desert floor straight ahead,
popping up for split seconds and disappearing. I don't know what
speed we were doing when we hit the measured mile, but everything
seemed to smooth out. Later I was told the surface was a bit
smoother there.
</P>
<P>
   I never saw the monitors at the beginning or end of the measured
portion. I was too busy looking far out and straight ahead. Haywood
did, though, and once we were through talked me into a graceful
slowdown _ backing off slowly on the gas, not touching the brake
until we'd dropped to 100, and then only touching it softly.
</P>
<P>
   I'd averaged 169.411 through the mile. Top speed was 175.438.
The Porsche could go faster, but Haywood said later that was plenty
fast on that surface.
</P>
<P>
   For my run, I got a plaque. Haywood got to survive. He's got
plenty of plaques and trophies.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
