<HEADLINE>
WHEN MEN'S BODIES AREN'T UP TO BUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women aren't the only sex that suffers from Bad Body Fever, the
pressure to conform to a body image that is, for most, unrealistic.
The authors of a recent book, ``The Adonis Complex,'' contend that
millions of insecure American men are linking their self-worth to
body image. Guess who's to blame? Women. Guess who can help? Women.
Because guess who'll read this book? That's right. Women.
</P>
<P>
   Men of all ages ``in unprecedented numbers'' are preoccupied
with the appearance of their bodies, according to the authors,
Harrison G. Pope, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical
School, Katharine A. Phillips, an associate professor of psychiatry
at Brown University, and Roberto Olivardia, a clinical fellow in
psychology at Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of boys and men exercise compulsively, gobble
``muscle-building'' food supplements and diet aids, take anabolic
steroids and other dangerous illegal drugs. Increasing numbers of
men develop eating disorders. A million or more suffer from ``body
dismorphic disorder,'' an excessive preoccupation with perceived
flaws in their appearance that leads many to undergo cosmetic
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all their efforts, they feel like failures because they
don't resemble pumped-up Hollywood stars like Arnold Schwarzenegger
and Mel Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   The Adonis Complex has reached plague proportions only in recent
years. In one 1972 survey cited by the authors, only 15 percent of
men said they were dissatisfied with their bodies, compared with 25
percent of women. A follow-up survey in 1997 indicated that 43
percent of men were dissatisfied, compared with 56 percent of
women. While the percentage of both sexes saying they disliked
their bodies rose dramatically from 1972 to 1997, women's body
problems have gotten most of the attention. Men have been
overlooked, largely because they don't want to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   The authors contend that at the core of the problem is
``threatened masculinity.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, they note, women can do just about anything men can
do. Fly combat aircraft. Work as police chiefs. Operate heavy
machinery. Become CEOs of big corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What then do men have left to distinguish themselves, to mark
their masculinity?'' the authors ask.
</P>
<P>
   OK, they've got that. But what else?
</P>
<P>
   Muscularity, the authors say. It's one of the few areas in which
women can never match men: ``No matter what crowning achievements
women accomplish, they will never, ever be able to bench-press 350
pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   But what accounts for the startling increase in the last 25
years in the percentage of women who are unhappy with their
appearance? You might think they'd be too busy flying combat
aircraft and becoming CEOs to anguish over the size and shape of
their bodies. But of course they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Threatened masculinity'' may explain why some boys and men are
obsessed with their appearance, but it seems clear that the most
potent influence is popular culture. Hollywood, advertising, the
music and fashion industries, the popular media have conspired to
bamboozle women and men alike into believing that a perfect form
equals a perfect life.
</P>
<P>
   Women, the authors write, are at an advantage because they have
already been learning how to ``confront'' the media's impossible
ideals of beauty. They urge women to help the men and boys in their
lives by talking with them about the hollow promises of the Adonis
Complex. But will talking help? Or will it threaten their
masculinity?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
