<HEADLINE>
NOW, REDO SOME BAD OLD FLOORS WITHOUT SANDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millions of words have been written about floors, most of them
about wood floors: installing, sanding, staining and finishing. And
resanding, restaining and refinishing.
</P>
<P>
   Hardwood or pine? The treatment for hardwood _ oak, cherry,
birch and maple _ is the same as for pine.
</P>
<P>
   And if someone says you cannot sand a softwood floor because it
is too soft, tell him to back off; any wood floor can be sanded
unless it it has been sanded so many times that the boards are
paper thin, and nails are showing through.
</P>
<P>
   That's the beauty of wood. While the finish lasts for decades,
when it gets beat up and worn, it can be sanded, up to three or
four times, extending its life to generations. In this age of
throw-away floors with guarantees of a piddling 15 years, being
able to resand a floor is a plus.
</P>
<P>
   You'll know when your floor needs resanding and refinishing. The
finish is worn in places _ maybe the whole floor _ to the bare
wood, and some of those bare areas are weathered. In short, it is a
mess, scratched, pitted and gouged.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Old Aches and Pains
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For many years, refinishing a floor was hard, muscle-pulling
work. You rented a floor sander, a 200-pound monster with a sanding
drum that could pull you right across the room if you didn't hold
on for dear life. You also rented an edger because that big sucker
could not reach corners and edges. And, you had to sand three times
(with coarse, medium and fine paper).
</P>
<P>
   When you were through, you knew where every one of your muscles
were in your raggedy old body, because every one of them ached.
You'd agree if someone called you Old Aches and Pains.
</P>
<P>
   Then you applied three coats of varnish. With luck, results were
spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Today, things are easier. You still have to sand three times,
but with a square-plate sander. It's as heavy as the old drum
sander, but it can be maneuvered virtually with one hand, with that
square plate vibrating, orbit-style. And, it can do edges and
corners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just a little work . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes your floors look a little beat up, dull and worn, with
a few light scratches and scuff marks. That is the floor you can
refurbish or renew, without competely sanding and refinishing.
</P>
<P>
   The time-honored way is to sand the floor by hand, with a medium
sandpaper to reduce gloss and roughen the finish, so a new coat of
varnish will adhere. Then wash with paint thinner. Finally, apply
one or two coats of a semigloss or high-gloss oil-based
polyurethane varnish.
</P>
<P>
   If you sand the floor by hand, it will look horrible, with all
kinds of sanding marks on it, but with a new coat of varnish, those
marks will disappear and (with luck) it will look great.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new, easier way
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a new way to restore and renew your floors if they are
not too far gone. It is called the Varathane Renewal Wood Floor
Restoring System, sold as a kit at home centers and hardware and
paint stores.
</P>
<P>
   The kit allows you to restore worn and dull floors just as some
of us did the old way, but there is an important difference: no
sanding, which is a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find the kit, call 800-635-3286 for a source near
you.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, the kit is good for floors that are not too far gone,
those that are worn and dull, with scuff marks and light scratches
on the finish. The only prep work needed is to remove any wax by
washing with paint thinner.
</P>
<P>
   Floors with water stains, urine stains, pit marks, depressions
from table and chair legs, deep scratches and gouges in the wood,
not the finish, require complete sanding and refinishing.
</P>
<P>
   The Varathane kit costs $69.99 (good for a 15- by 15-foot room).
It's a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How it works
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The kit contains a quart of No-Sanding Formula solution, a quart
of Interloc Bonding Formula solution, Catalyzed Diamond Wood Finish
(124 ounces of topcoat and 4 ounces of catalyst), a scrubbing pad,
applicator block, and a synthetic lamb's wool pad.
</P>
<P>
   Step One uses the No-Sanding Formula, a liquid sandpaper that
conditions any finish, including polyurethane and other varnishes,
giving the finish ``tooth'' for other finishes to adhere to.
</P>
<P>
   Step Two uses the Interloc-Bonding Formula, which further
conditions the finish, to permanently bond with the new top coat.
</P>
<P>
   Step Three uses the Diamond Wood Finish, a water-based
polyurethane varnish strengthened by the addition of a catalyst
just before using. It hardens the finish and makes it more durable,
said Kristy Mayers, company spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   You have to be careful with the water-based polyurethane, she
said, because it looks milky in the can and must be carefully
applied so it will not stay cloudy.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is water-based, the finish will not darken or yellow
over time
</P>
<P>
   Persons who prefer using a brush can do so in peace, said
Mayers.
</P>
<P>
   You can walk on the new finish in eight hours. You can return
furniture in three days. Heavy furniture should be kept off for
seven days until the finish is compeltely cured.
</P>
<P>
   And, contrary to many opinions, there is no need to add wax,
polish or anything else to this finished floor. Like any other
varnished floor, it is finished.
</P>
<P>
   By that time your floor will be good for lots more years, and
you can roll up your sleeves and do another room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
