<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIEMAN A BATTLEGROUND OF DETROIT NEWSPAPER WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In November 1995, a New York Times story on the early days of
Detroit's bitter newspaper strike warned that it had already
created ``immeasurable losses in diminished good will and growing
hard feelings.'' Nearly five years later, former Detroit News
editor and publisher Robert Giles can vouch for that.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, sources say Harvard University was ready to
name the 67-year-old Giles _ now vice president at the Freedom
Forum _ as the long-awaited successor to Nieman Foundation curator
Bill Kovach. But a concerted lobbying effort to derail his
candidacy by the unions and some journalists who joined the July
1995 strike appears to have delayed his appointment and perhaps
even caused a reassessment of that candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Although he left the News in 1997, the key issue is Giles's role
in Detroit's five-year labor battle and his fitness to run the
nation's most prestigious journalism fellowship program. If chosen,
Giles follows the much-admired Kovach, who ruffled corporate
feathers with his aggressive investigative instincts as former
editor of the Atlanta-Journal Constitution and who used the Nieman
post as a bully pulpit to loudly advocate for core journalistic
values. Neither Harvard nor Giles would comment Wednesday on the
specifics of the Nieman search.
</P>
<P>
   Giles's foes _ who accuse him of deliberately provoking the
unions as well as slanting the News' coverage of the strike _ say
his selection as curator would be an ``affront'' to those values.
Supporters see the former president of the American Society of
Newspaper Editors as the victim of a simmering vendetta, a sound
news executive who did his job under nearly impossible
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any personal feelings about any of the
individuals involved,'' although ``the strike was a very difficult
thing for me . . . very tough, very hostile,'' says Giles. Yet, he
was ``very surprised'' when the strike issue resurfaced in
connection with his Nieman candidacy because ``the issue of my role
in the strike has never been raised,'' in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   A Detroit reporter who is familiar with the situation but
requested anonymity is less stunned by this resumption of
hostilities. ``There's a great deal of ill will toward Bob Giles,''
he says. ``I don't know if it's justified. But I know it's real.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Mather Jenkins, a former News food editor who went on
strike, says the idea of Giles getting the Harvard job is ``just
too disgusting . . . As the curator of the Nieman Foundation, he
represents the best and brightest in American journalism. His
actions during the strike indicates he's not the best guy to be in
that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles ``has a great reputation in the journalistic community and
deservedly so,'' counters Sandra Mims Rowe, editor of The
(Portland) Oregonian. ``For the Guild to organize an attack on his
candidacy based on the known difficulties of labor and management
disputes is unjust, given Giles's sustained and substantial
contributions to journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the old wounds and animosities at play here, the most
serious journalistic charge levelled is the fairly widespread
sentiment that the News produced biased, antiunion strike coverage
on its news pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We paid a lot of attention to how the strike was being
covered,'' Giles says. ``I thought (other media outlets') coverage
was focused mostly on coverage of people on the picket lines. . . .
But there was more to the story than that. In the early days of the
strike, there was a great deal of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles notes that striking workers made the News' job tougher by
declining to talk to the paper. But in 1995, The Columbia
Journalism Review gave the News (and its sister paper, The Detroit
Free Press) a ``dart'' for ``strikingly tilted'' coverage of the
strike. ``What readers got,'' the magazine said, ``were daily
bundles of stories, editorials, columns, photos, and ads pushing
the management line.''
</P>
<P>
   In a March 1996 Editor &AMP; Publisher story in which several
observers criticized the News' coverage as biased, Giles complained
that local broadcast outlets were guilty of pro-striker coverage
and acknowledged that ``to some extent, we feel the newspaper has
to balance the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Gonyea, the Detroit correspondent for National Public Radio,
says Giles ``was definitely very aggressive on making sure the
newspaper management's spin was out there on this . . . Giles was
the one to pick up the phone. He was definitely a lightning rod.''
</P>
<P>
   In temperament, the soft-spoken Giles doesn't seem much like a
lightning rod. And he says that ``a lot of decisions that were made
about the management of the strike,'' did not involve him. ``My job
was to keep producing a newspaper for those who wanted it'' and to
``preserve a professional'' environment for those who returned to
work, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Critics see it differently. During his ``tenure in Detroit,''
wrote Newspaper Guild President Linda K. Foley in a letter to
Harvard President Neil Rudenstine, ``Mr. Giles showed himself to be
committed not to high journalistic standards, but instead to the
corporate agenda of the Gannett Co.''
</P>
<P>
   Union members say their battles with Giles predate the 1995
strike. And a number of sources indicate that union-managment
relations began souring after the 1989 Joint Operating Agreement
that created a single business entity out of former rivals, the
Free Press and News.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man presided over the dismal decline of the Detroit
News,'' even before the labor strife, says Newspaper Guild of
Detroit president Lou Mleczko, who spent two dozen years as a News
reporter. One harbinger of the strike was a nasty 1994 battle
between the union and Giles over whether management could order
reporters to appear on a local television news show without any
agreement over compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry that we couldn't make it work better,'' says Giles
of the TV experiment, issuing what could pass as a post-mortem on
the larger labor war that raged at his paper.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Lacy, director of Michigan State University's School of
Journalism director, says Giles ``gets a lot of mixed reaction and
I have mixed reactions. Bob and I have disagreed on the strike. I
think it was a mistake on both sides (but) I suspect there are
people in the industry who have done things far worse than what Bob
did . . . It would not bother me as an academic to see Bob run that
(Nieman) program.''
</P>
<P>
   Like others, Lacy hints that Giles may not have been an ideal
fit ``at a big paper with a union'' at ground zero of the organized
labor universe. Now, with the unions galvanized and Giles's allies
organizing, the pressure intensifies on Harvard to determine
whether he's the right fit at the Nieman Foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
