<HEADER>
A4473 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-MAO-BOS &LR;      07-06 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MAO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDING THE TIGER TO POWER: A TALE OF MAO'S WIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AMY GRAVES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BECOMING MADAME MAO 
By Anchee Min 
Houghton Mifflin, 320 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Madame Mao Jiang Ching took a strange, often sad, and
unpredictable path to her role as the most powerful woman in
communist China.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Becoming Madame Mao,'' Anchee Min's second novel, she
starts as Yunhe, a girl of every possible disadvantage of poverty
and social ostracism. She is the daughter of a concubine, deepening
the difficulties she faces as a female in Chinese culture.
</P>
<P>
   At 18 Yunhe escapes an arranged marriage and runs away to
Shanghai, where she struggles to find work as an actress. She
finally stars in Ibsen's ``A Doll's House,'' and looks for more
acting jobs, but because she won't sleep with the directors she
gets nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   After two more failed marriages and a stint in jail for her
communist leanings, she takes a new name and gives up on acting. As
Lan Ping, she leaves Shanghai on a train bound for Mao's stronghold
in the remote countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Lan Ping pursues the communist leader when he's still hiding out
in Yenan, building his power base. It doesn't take long for Mao, in
turn, to pursue her. Mao is married, but he doesn't let that stand
in the way. Lan Ping has no sense of foreboding that what Mao did
for her he would be capable of doing again for the love of someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   She ends as Mao Jiang Ching, the ruler's wife compelled to
``ride the tiger'' _ the dangerous life she's chosen with Mao, who
turns out to be as elusive and contradictory in private as he is in
public.
</P>
<P>
   With letters, documents, and characters drawn from real life,
Min conjures a lyrical story that serves as an interpreted history
of Jiang Ching's rise and fall. Mesmerizing from page one, this
story neither romanticizes nor demonizes Jiang Ching, a compelling
character for whom it's hard not to feel sympathy, despite the
horrors she inflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Many passages are beautiful, and the ones describing her romance
with Mao suggest that long before Jiang Ching assumed power of her
own and began exacting revenge on her foes, she was a girl in love:
``It is the third time they meet privately. The stars look like
voyeurs' eyes opening and closing. Mao Tse-tung and Lan Ping stand
in the descending darkness, shoulder to shoulder. The day has begun
to cool. Weeds bend lazily over the riverbank. The reflection of
the moon trembles in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can tell this story, it's Anchee Min. Having escaped
her fate as a worker on a Red Army farm to become an actress in one
of Jiang Ching's opera companies, and having escaped again to the
United States in 1984, Min knows her subject. Min gave her own
story in the 1994 ``Red Azalea,'' an autobiography that recounts
the hardships and deprivations that millions like her suffered in
the turbulent years during and after the Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Becoming Madame Mao'' opens with Jiang Ching awaiting her
death after 14 years in prison. She's telling the story of her life
to her daughter, Nah. ``Well, I won't surrender. When I was a child
my mother used to tell me that I should think of myself as grass _
born to be stepped on. But I think of myself as a peacock among
hens. I am not being judged fairly. Side by side Mao Tse-tung and I
stood, yet he is considered a god while I am a demon.''
Interspersed with passages from Nah's view (often contradictory to
her mother's), the narrative offers insight into Jiang Ching's
refusal to see her own shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Min adeptly links Jiang Ching's passion for theater to her
passion for the real drama of her public life. Jiang Ching sees
herself as an embattled heroine whose enemies are obscurity, the
comrades of Mao who tried to silence her, and finally Mao himself.
As Mao's power grows, he pushes Jiang Ching away and refuses to
grant her any status within his government. And then she learns
that Mao has syphillis from one of his many other sexual partners.
As her life with Mao proves lonely and difficult, her motivation
changes to consolidating power, imprisoning and executing her
opponents, and achieving immortality.
</P>
<P>
   She finally gets her opening after the debacle of the Great Leap
Forward, an effort launched in 1958 to industrialize China that
instead resulted in widespread famine, when Mao turns to his wife
for help. They work together to foment the Cultural Revolution, the
years of upheaval that cement Mao's grip on the nation in the late
'60s and early '70s. But Jiang Ching's own position remains
precarious, and she never overcomes detractors within the shifting
circles of power.
</P>
<P>
   Without ignoring her crimes, Min never lets go of the image of
Jiang Ching as a vulnerable woman. The result is a testament to the
complexity behind even the most brutal characters, and a lesson in
the soul's potential for shaping its destiny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
