<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS JESUS READS NIETZSCHE, PLACES PERSONAL ADS ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big surprise. There's a guy on the Internet who calls himself
Jesus and is advertising for a mate. He sports golden locks,
dresses in a flowing robe, and claims to have ``a lean swimmer's
body and a six pack.'' On his Web site, www.jesus.com, he's
offering ladies a chance to shower with him as a ``lasting tribute
to. . .cleanliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. So is this the work of a pornographer, a performance
artist, or a postmodern poseur?
</P>
<P>
   This much we know. When ``Jesus'' returns queries, he calls back
collect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a joke,'' says the fellow calling collect from Falls
Church, Va. He describes himself as a 26-year-old college graduate
who changed his name to Jesus a few years ago. He claims to be
gainfully employed _ ``I generate intellectual property'' _ and
swears that the Web site is ``totally legitimate.'' He also attests
that he has no interest in money or organized religion, for that
matter.
</P>
<P>
   So what's up with the Web site? ``I love women immensely, and
I'm looking for a good one,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon the skepticism, Jesus, but there have been too many
online hoaxes for anyone to believe unconditionally. Who are you?
What is your motive?
</P>
<P>
   ``I experiment with various things,'' he says. Well, so did
Timothy Leary. Can you be a little more specific? ``I don't want to
get into past projects.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about all you're going to get from the self-described
spiritualist who favors long romantic walks and the philosophy of
Nietzsche and Schopenhauer. (Nothing like a little nihilism on the
beach!) His ``sermons'' are semi-coherent, anti-corporate screeds,
although the site also boasts pictures of ``Jesus'' endorsing
Starbucks, Guinness, and Barbie. (Go figure.)
</P>
<P>
   In this age of privacy violation, a guy who goes around dressed
as Jesus is paranoid about revealing personal details: ``I don't
want people showing up at my house in the middle of the night,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't the only cryptic fellow associated with the site. The
domain name is registered to Tor Manders, a 34-year-old
Washington-based programmer who says he registered the name several
years ago. Manders says he leases the site to Jesus. A few months
ago, the site featured chat and discussion boards for Christians;
the personal ad went up last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything to do with the content,'' says Manders,
not once but twice. ``I'd actually prefer not to have anything to
do with it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Manders can confirm that the photos on the site are real and
that the fellow looking for a mate does have a full-time job,
doesn't smoke, and only drinks socially. (He can't comment on the
``six-pack,'' though.) As for the shower offer, he's not sure what
that's all about. ``The shower thing seems to indicate, um, that
it's humor.'' A pause. ``On the other hand, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Wong,'' an animated Web series on www.icebox.com, is
generating a fair share of controversy online. The title character
is a slant-eyed, buck-toothed butler who works for a self-centered
society girl, stereotypical enough to draw the ire of
Asian-Americans and members of the Junior League alike. In fact,
the show has been excoriated on the community site,
www.asianavenue.com, and the Icebox message boards have been
bombarded by fans and critics of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, the most offensive thing about ``Mr. Wong'' is
that it's just not funny. Unlike the hilariously irreverent ``South
Park,'' whose politically incorrect characters are rooted in
contemporary life, ``Mr. Wong'' seems to take place in a time warp,
featuring a bumbling majordomo obsessed with Bing Crosby. The first
two episodes, titled ``Urine Trouble'' (get it? ha ha), are about
the valet's exploits at Graceland. See Mr. Wong urinate on Elvis
Presley's grave. Hear him mix up his l's and r's. Watch him teeter
around on little feet. Are we supposed to be laughing? And what's
up with that accent? It makes Charlie Chan sound downright British.
</P>
<P>
   The show does have one genuinely uproarious moment; too bad it
comes in the opening disclaimer that warns audiences about
offensive content, including ``racially inflammatory material. . .
tired vaudevillian schtick, vomiting, and rude nicknames.'' It does
promise that there are ``almost no portrayals of cannibalism.''
Maybe that would have been funny.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most recent wrinkle in the recording industry's battle
against online music piracy is a lawsuit against www.mp3board, an
MP3 search engine. But after a visit to the site, it's hard to
imagine what all the fuss is about. The links on the site lead to
other MP3 sites that display an endless series of pop-up windows,
similar to those that show up on porn sites. The pop-up windows
make it nearly impossible to download music. ``That's probably a
bug,'' says Ira Rothken, MP3board.com's attorney. ``It's not the
intention of the design to make it an annoying experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You heard it here first: Musicbank.com may come up with a whole
new concept _ the instant bootleg. The company, which sells custom
compilation CDs, is sponsoring the summer tour of The Who and Jimmy
Page and The Black Crows, which play the Tweeter Center next week.
Recordings of the shows may end up on musicmaker.com, says Larry
Lieberman, the company's president of global marketing. ``We could
take a concert by any artist and put it up on the site the next day
for sale anywhere in the world,'' he says. ``The concept is, `Leave
your microphones at home. We'll get the board mix for you.' '' But
that would be legal, and that wouldn't be any fun at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week, a coalition including Blockbuster, MP3.com, and Yahoo
launched www.whowantstobeamoviestar.com, a scheme that would allow
regular Joes and Judys to bid for the chance to play roles in a
yet-to-be-scripted movie. Under the original plan, aspiring stars
would bid for the roles on Yahoo's auction site; the winning
bidders would be appear in a film by screenwriter Adam Rifkin. The
film will be distributed by Blockbuster, and MP3.com will select
the bands for the soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   After folks began placing bids, the California Labor Commission
intervened. It turns out that it is illegal to require a fee from a
job applicant. Whoops. The group revised its plan; now actors must
have others (like proud Aunt Selma) bid for them, acting as
sponsors. The film hasn't been named yet. How about: ``Who Wants to
Be a Labor Lawyer?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of reality programming, the Net is abuzz with theories
on who is going to be the winner of ``Survivor.'' One fan site,
www.survivorsucks.com, claims to have the inside dope on the show.
Who knows who their ``sources'' are, but one thing is clear: These
people have way too much time on their hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
