<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4476 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WHALE-BONES-ART-BOS &LR;      07-06 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALE-BONES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MUSEUM TO EXHIBIT RARE BLUE WHALE SKELETON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Texas)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMAL E. WATSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BEDFORD, Mass. _ The scene was remarkable, as hundreds of
camera-toting spectators and scientists gathered on Second Beach in
Middletown, R.I. to watch history unfold.
</P>
<P>
   A giant blue whale sat impaled across the bow of a ship, its
eyes bulging and skin torn away. The 66-foot whale _ so rare that
one like it hadn't been seen on the East Coast for 100 years _ had
been struck by a tanker in a wild ocean storm and dragged hundreds,
if not thousands, of miles across the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Even as gawkers approached the carcass, officials at the New
Bedford Whaling Museum began an intense battle to claim the bones.
Under pressure from US Sen. Edward M. Kennedy and US Rep. Barney
Frank, the National Marine Fisheries Service awarded care of the
whale's skeleton to the museum, over other institutions including
the Smithsonian Institution and the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were extremely excited,'' said Anne Brengle, executive
director of the Museum. ``New Bedford is a major whaling center so
it makes sense that the whale is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a painstaking two years spent piecing the bones back
together, the mammal's skeletal remains will be on display at the
museum beginning Friday _ making it one of only three locations in
the country where the public can view a complete blue whale.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-ton species, which scientists believe was between four
and six years old when it was killed, was towed to a Middletown
beach by bulldozers in March, 1998. Its ribs, vertebrae and
shoulder on the left side were broken, apparently from the impact
with the tanker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many people at the beach it was incredible,''
said Lee Heald, director of programs at the Whaling Museum who
first pitched the idea to Museum officials about requesting the
skeleton. ``I took my children. It was something that was important
for them to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven scientists huddled around the animal to take
samples of blood, skin, organs and other tissues for future study.
</P>
<P>
   The whale's carcass was then taken to a New Bedford landfill
where volunteers and city crews guarded the skeleton throughout the
night until the flesh and blubber could be stripped from the bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was amazing. Everyone came together to make sure this
would happen here in New Bedford,'' said New Bedford's Mayor
Frederick M. Kalisz, Jr. ``It was a fantastic feeling.'' The whale
- which has been named KOBO - King of the Blue Ocean - by sixth
grader Katie Hallett, has rallied the city, which has seen some
hard financial times over the past few decades. ``The city is
really undergoing a renassiance,'' Kalisz said. ``This exhibit was
a public-private partnership. It was a phenomenal achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   The skeleton's debut comes just as museum officials are
celebrating an $11 million renovation and expansion project of its
current facility, and as 50,000 tourists stream through the city
for the annual Summerfest weekend.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second whale that adorns the two-and-a-half story
gallery of the museum. Next to the blue whale skeleton, which is
suspended from the ceiling, is a 33-foot humpback whale skeleton
which has been housed at the facility since the mid-1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Konnerth, a biologist and expert in the field of mammal
skeleton rearticulation, worked with his wife Jean to reassembled
the blue whale skeleton.
</P>
<P>
   The process, somewhat akin to constructing the world's largest
jigsaw puzzle, took more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the eighth whale that I've done,'' said Konnerth, who
was commissioned by the museum from his home in Texas. ``What was
important, was that we had to make sure that we kept everything
intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists estimate that there are only about 300 blue whales in
the North Atlantic and 4,000 in the whole world. They can swim as
fast as 22 mph. But they don't reproduce very often _ every two to
three years at most.
</P>
<P>
   The heart alone weighs three-quarters of a ton.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials estimate that the entire display cost about
$350,000. That investment is worth it, they say, because of the
thousands of new visitors they expect to lure into the facility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
