<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4477 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SHRINERS-CELLIST-ART-     07-06 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHRINERS-CELLIST-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 A BOY, A CELLO AND A DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Wis.)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By REGINA MONTAGUE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ His every note a triumph over disability and fate, Tad
Lietz brought tears to the eyes of Shriners Wednesday as he gently
played the theme from the film ``Titanic'' on his cello, drawing
the bow across the strings with his left foot because he was born
without a left arm.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve-year-old Lietz, who played for the Shriners at their
national convention in Boston, was abandoned shortly after birth
and left on the steps of a crowded orphanage in Ho Chi Minh City in
Vietnam. He spent the first three years of his life there.
</P>
<P>
   He moved from a crib resting on a dirt floor to Appleton, Wis.,
at age 3, when he was adopted by Mary and Jeffrey Lietz.
</P>
<P>
   The Shriners, an international fraternity that supports a
network of hospitals offering free care to patients, have helped
Tad Lietz to begin to realize his lifelong dream of becoming a
famous cellist, his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you Shriners for believing in children, and helping us
to teach our children to believe in themselves,'' Mary Lietz told
the crowd at the Hynes Memorial Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our minds, angels wear red fezzes.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tad Lietz first came to the United States he weighed 16
pounds, had trouble seeing, couldn't sit up or walk, and screamed
through the night, his mother said. His ear was infected due to
insect bites.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Shriners read a story about Tad in the Lietzes'
local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we knew it, men came to our door and said they
represented the local Shriners,'' said Mary Lietz. The men told her
and her husband they could help their son.
</P>
<P>
   The Lietzes accepted the help and Tad's father is now a member
of the Shriners.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Tad Lietz has gotten free treatment and therapy from
a Shriners Hospital in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But he cannot use his prosthetic arm to play the cello. So Lietz
had to learn to finger the instrument's strings with his right hand
and move the bow with his foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look inside,'' Tad Lietz said after the concert
Wednesday, ``you really don't have a disability.''
</P>
<P>
   Lietz is now enrolled in programs for gifted and talented
children. He is an accomplished soccer player and chess teacher.
``You only have one life,'' he said. ``Make it useful.''
</P>
<P>
   Lietz's performance was a surprise gift to the Shriners, many of
whom were moved by the presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Knauss, 66, the wife of retired Shriner Earl Knauss of
Buffalo, N.Y., said the sweet cello tones of the song ``My Heart
Will Go On'' made her feel proud of the work the Shriners do. She
was so filled with emotion that tears streamed from her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it's all about _ helping kids,'' she said.
``We're part of a great organization that helps these children.''
</P>
<P>
   After Lietz finished playing, another Shriners patient,
18-year-old C.J. Williams from Panama City, Fla., thanked the
organization for giving her life.
</P>
<P>
   She had suffered burns over 70 percent of her body in a fire
when she was a young girl, but was treated at the burn unit of a
Shriners Hospital in Galveston, Texas. Now she leads an active
life, physically and socially.
</P>
<P>
   Shriners president Ralph Semb said Lietz and Williams are living
examples of the miracles the organization makes happen.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the pair, Semb said: ``Those are our stars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
