<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-WORKERS (Tulsa, Okla.) _ American business is rushing
into China, and Marilyn C. Grant, a 56-year-old widow who drives a
forklift for a fishing reel company, is being left behind. Ms.
Grant's employer, Zebco, plans to move much of its fishing reel
production to China, just a month after the House passed a measure
that would end cold war restrictions on China trade. At least 240
local Zebco workers will lose their jobs. As China modernizes and
loosens controls, its lure as a manufacturing base, which has been
growing since the early 1980s, is proving irresistible to many
multinationals. For every jumbo jet Boeing sells China, it seems, a
Zebco sends a production line there. By Joseph Kahn.
