<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKE-GEORGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORK LAKE PROVIDES A FRAGILE RECORD OF COLONIAL WARFARE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDs: With: LAKE-GEORGE-RELICS)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LORI SODERLIND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE GEORGE, N.Y. _ Can you judge a lake by its surface?
</P>
<P>
   Divers in Lake George looked deep into the water and found
pieces of whole worlds: more than 60 shipwrecks lay forgotten in
the lake's southernmost tip alone, and elsewhere under the 32-mile
length of clear water, submerged vessels remain to be counted.
</P>
<P>
   The discoveries were made by divers taking a first-ever
inventory of the lake bottom _ an effort to catalog the historic
treasures before they are picked over by adventure seekers and
disappear. Volunteer divers, part of Bateaux Below Inc. of Saratoga
Springs, began the formal inventory five years ago, inspired by the
region's Colonial history and by several significant discoveries
made in the past three decades. The work is expected to take
another decade or more.
</P>
<P>
   Along the lake bottom divers have already found a collection of
French and Indian War remains rivaled in the Northeast only by the
shipwrecks of Lake Champlain. And one of Bateaux Below's recent
discoveries _ a British warship known as a ``radeau'' _ is so rare
that it is now among just six shipwrecks registered as National
Historic Landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   When their inventory is complete, Bateaux Below divers hope to
find wrecks spanning the history of European wars and fresh-water
recreation that has long centered on Lake George. But they also
hope their work will foster a new respect for submerged
archaeology. With discovery comes increased curiosity. And that,
combined with the growing popularity of diving, is bringing
increased threats to the remains in this watery grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inventory will help us manage what's down there,'' said
Joe Zarzynski, executive director of Bateaux Below and a diver who
has spent countless hours in Lake George. Something needs to be
done, Zarzynski said, ``to take the diving pressure off'' the
popular wrecks and help preserve them for the next few centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Long as they have been there, the artifacts in New York's famous
lake were mostly undisturbed until the past three decades and the
advent of modern scuba diving in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Some early finds were recorded: in 1903 a slooplike vessel was
found in 15 feet of water off a steamboat dock. It was hauled out
of the lake and cut up for souvenirs, according to written
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   With scuba gear, divers could look deeper _ and stay longer.
Anyone could join the adventure just by learning to dive, so there
was less incentive to raise the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   The first major discovery was made in 1960 when two teen-age
divers found what turned out to be 14 British bateaux _
flat-bottomed vessels that were used in the French and Indian War
to move troops fast. The British Army had developed a practice of
building boats and then submerging them with rocks, hiding their
fleet from any French marauders who might raid Fort William Henry
over winter. In the spring, the vessels would be raised from their
``wet storage'' by divers.
</P>
<P>
   In the winter of 1758, however, some of the 260 submerged
bateaux slipped out of reach. The 14 boats found in 1960, each
about 30 feet long, were in neat rows as if deliberately placed,
but forgotten or lost in 25 to 50 feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the British were hiding more than bateaux. In 1990,
Zarzynski led a group of divers into 107 feet of water to the wreck
of a British radeau _ a seven-sided floating fortress armed with
cannons. Radeaux were used almost exclusively as artillery ships,
and fewer of them were built.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-foot wreck of the radeau _ known as the Land Tortoise _
that Zarzynski's team found is the oldest completely intact warship
ever found in the Western Hemisphere and the only radeau known to
exist.
</P>
<P>
   The last historic reference to the ship was made in October
1758, when it was taken for a test sail shortly after it was built.
The ship was then submerged, but apparently its size made it
difficult to control. It slipped under the surface and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the biggest `Oh no!' ever heard,'' said
Zarzynski, who has pieced together a story that the Colonials
failed to record.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists have made careful studies of the 18th-century
ships found in Lake George, and have learned over the years that
preservation beats raising the wrecks piecemeal.
</P>
<P>
   A 1965 State Police dive to the bateaux site, for example,
raised boxes of relics, but they weren't properly recorded and
documented.
</P>
<P>
   Some wreck divers have piracy on their minds. Lake George
attracts divers accustomed to the rules of the ocean, where,
outside a three-mile limit, any wreck is fair game for looting.
</P>
<P>
   Inland, the law forbids removing artifacts from the water. But
archaeologists say looting has nonetheless caused irreversible
damage to the historic sites, which are well-preserved in cold
water but are extremely vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early days of diving it was pretty much an accepted
fact that people could go down there and take what they wanted,''
said Bob Benway, a Bateaux Below diver. ``It was very common for
people to just take a piece of railing off the wreck'' or some
other piece of rigging, even a section of wood, as a souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   More often, though, the wrecks are simply loved to death.
</P>
<P>
   The bateaux and radeau were stripped of most articles before
they were deliberately scuttled. But it doesn't take much to harm
242-year-old vessels: Divers who try to get an underneath-look at
the radeau can disturb the wood simply with their bubbles. Anchors
have been dropped on the wrecks. A diver's momentary loss of
control might mean bumping into the gunnels, and just that can be
jarring enough to cause damage.
</P>
<P>
   Bateaux Below divers believe the best way to preserve the wrecks
is to create a series of educational sites, or ``submerged heritage
preserves,'' to attract divers and to educate and train them. So
far three such sites have been established: The ``Underwater
Fleet'' site (where the bateaux lay alongside one submerged
replica) was opened in 1993, along with an ``underwater classroom''
set up at the site of a sunken tour boat, known as the Forward,
that is believed to have been scuttled in the 1930s. The radeau
site (for advanced divers because of its extreme depth) was opened
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Each site is marked with buoys and provided with moorings to
protect the wrecks from anchors. Underwater informational signs
lead divers through the sites and, in the Forward underwater
classroom, stations provide experiments and training exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to set up scenarios where divers practice before
diving on sites,'' Zarzynski said. That takes the pressure off
historic landmarks that can't be guarded by rangers, watched in the
busy season or closed off with gates after hours.
</P>
<P>
   Bateaux Below hopes to create more submerged preserves. The
group is entering the fifth year of its mile-by-mile inventory with
the help of grant money, sonar and global positioning equipment,
and hopes to find an appropriate site for a new park somewhere
midlake.
</P>
<P>
   They want another site because, in history book drawings, the
ships look old. But to come upon a radeau sunk in 100 feet of fresh
dark water feels, to some, like finding God.
</P>
<P>
   A thin light grazes the mossy beams of the warship, long settled
in the mud and silence. ``It's like diving in a cathedral,''
Zarzynski said. ``It's religious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
