<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4506 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-NAFTA-MEXICO-HNS &LR;      07-06 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAFTA-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRADE OPENED DOOR FOR POLITICAL REVOLUTION IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BILL DAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Supporters of the North American Free Trade
Agreement touted the pact as a boon to the Mexican, Canadian and
U.S. economies. But it may have had another, unintended
consequence: political reform in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Mexican voters elected as president Vincente Fox of
the National Action Party, the first president from outside the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party in 71 years. Political
and economic analysts believe the steps that led to Fox's historic
election can be directly traced to NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government slowly began to realize they can grow the
economy much faster if they gain the confidence of foreign
investors,'' said Alejandro Velez, a professor of economics at St.
Mary's University. ``To do that, you have to open politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's election was a dramatic shift in Mexican politics. Many
institutions were firmly controlled by the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, known by its Spanish acronym, PRI. Previous
elections had signaled voter dissatisfaction with the PRI, but one
way or another _ fraud I soften alleged _ the PRI always managed to
win the top office.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1994, the implementation of NAFTA coincided with the
election of the PRI's Ernesto Zedillo and an economic crisis.
Zedillo, an internationally trained economist less beholden to PRI
bosses than his predecessors, began pushing for reforms within the
party and in Mexico's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, a NAFTA-induced economic boom began boosting people into
the middle class, and people began migrating from the countryside
to the cities to seek jobs. The cities became strongholds of power
for National Action, known as PAN. Meanwhile, political reforms
like this year's first-ever primary elections were being
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not having NAFTA probably would have condemned (Mexico) to
more years of darkness,'' Velez said. ``Instead, it has heralded a
new era in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   By last week, with the Mexican economy growing quickly, trade
with neighboring nations to the north and no signs of a peso
devaluation that often accompanies presidential elections, the
electorate decided to dump the PRI and take a chance on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of who won, either Fox or (PRI candidate Francisco)
Labastida, people knew that the economy would continue to expand,''
said Jorge Gonzalez, chairman of the economics department at
Trinity University in San Antonio. ``That gave them the freedom to
vote for whomever they wanted politically.''
</P>
<P>
   That freedom, Gonzalez maintains, emanates directly from NAFTA's
economic benefits. He said that is a lesson for those who criticize
open trade with countries like China or Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once people see the freedom we have in the world, there's no
way they'll stay with a system that won't allow them to speak their
mind about politics.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trade advocates will likely cite the Mexican transition as an
example of how open markets can spawn open governments. But Rep.
Ciro Rodriguez, D-Texas, who supported NAFTA and trade with Cuba
but opposed normalized trade relations with China, says each
country must be considered separately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba is not a national threat to us, and its proximity to us
has a bearing, like with Mexico,'' he said. ``It's also not a
nuclear threat to us, and it's not been stealing secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, countries like China are likely to draw lessons from how
quickly _ and orderly _ Mexico changed once NAFTA was implemented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade is not simply exporting tomatoes or jalapenos, it's also
about change in ways you produce things and involving investors
from abroad,'' Velez said. ``To do that, you have to have a
political system that's not going to collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Day can be reached by e-mail at wday(at)express-news.net)
</P>
