   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHRINERS-CELLIST (Boston) _ Born without a left arm, Tad Lietz
was abandoned on the steps of a Ho Chi Minh City orphanage, adopted
by a Wisconsin couple and treated at a Shriners' Hospital. Now 12,
Lietz has played the cello for 2,000 Shiners at their national
convention, fingering the instrument with his right hand and using
his foot to drag the bow across the strings. By Regina Montague.
590 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   WHALE-BONES (New Bedford, Mass.) _ The Smithsonian wanted it. So
did the National Museum of Science. But the New Bedford Whaling
Museum got it. It's a 66-foot skeleton of the juvenile blue whale
that was killed by a tanker in Rhode Island in 1998, the first blue
whale brought ashore on the East Coast in 100 years. By Jamal
Watson. 900 words. (Resending from Spot News budget, with photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE &LR;   &UR; (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHILDCARE-COLUMN (Undated) _ To preschoolers, sexual differences
are neither good nor bad; they just are. This changes in elementary
school, however. By Barbara Meltz. 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-PROJECT (Undated) -- A new product offers a way to restore
your hardwood floors, if they are not too far gone. By Peter C.
Hotton.
</P>
