<HEADLINE>
WITH NEW CABRIOLET, PORSCHE SAYS: LEAVE THE CORNERING TO US 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENO _ There's great variety in driving a different car every
week. But there can also be a certain sameness _ same commute into
the city; one dirt road's another dirt road; tree-lined country
lanes blur even in their beauty.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it's good to get away and drive once in a while. It's
why taking the 2000 Porsche 911 Cabriolet on a run from here to San
Francisco and back _ and later playing on the mountains and deserts
that surround Reno _ was such a recent treat.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 911 descended from a long line that began in 1965.
Its latest incarnation was given to us for the 1999 model year and
has been tweaked just a bit for 2000. In the Porsche world right
now, the basic 911 does not have the buzz that surrounds other
models _ Boxster and Boxster S, the Carrera 4, and the hot new
all-wheel-drive 911 Turbo. But the 911 is, after all, the spine of
Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   So we drove it up and over the mountains, Reno to the City by
the Bay, up steep Interstate 80, down winding Interstate 80,
through the valley at Sacramento, and to the sea. Back in the
Reno-Tahoe area, we climbed on tortuous roads to 9,000 feet in a
curving ascent that would give angst to acrophobes. And we rolled
across remote stretches of desert (carefully obeying traffic laws
on Indian reservations where, we were told, even three miles an
hour over the speed limit meant a $500 fine, payable on the spot).
</P>
<P>
   It was easy spending hours at a time in this car, just enjoying
its power, its handling, its comfort.
</P>
<P>
   It surged along the highway, charged up the steepest stretches
the Nevada-California border could offer.
</P>
<P>
   On rolling desert highway, with visibility as far as the eye
could see, it was obvious you could run in the 911 Cabriolet for as
long as you wanted at speeds well into the triple digits.
</P>
<P>
   On those hairpinned and switchback climbs and descents on lesser
roads _ and we're talking no guardrails sometimes _ it cornered on
rails of its own. It's rear-wheel drive, and even without Porsche
Stability Management, it felt as though you'd have to try real hard
to shake the rear end loose or to induce terminal understeer.
</P>
<P>
   In short, superb, solid handling.
</P>
<P>
   The multi-layered suspension includes independent struts,
aluminum lower control arms, coil springs, stabilizer bar, and
gas-charged twin tube shocks up front and, in the rear, an
independent five-link setup with coil springs, single tube shocks,
and stabilizer bar.
</P>
<P>
   You get no body roll, no sense of the torsional twist you might
expect in a drop-top. You might be able to induce a touch of the
latter on a racetrack, but not many of us will be driving a
Cabriolet there.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of Porsche, the braking was superb: Set weight to the
front wheels to enter a fast corner and it took only the slightest
touch. Try to bring it down from high speed in a desert experiment
and it will track true to a belt-tightening stop.
</P>
<P>
   The ride was exceptionally quiet for a convertible, the seats
low and firm (Porsche-like again), though I'd question whether you
could fairly call this a 2x2 since any two adults in the rear would
be chewing on their knees. Of course, we could just pretend it's
still the '60s and that's just part of the adventure.
</P>
<P>
   If I had one complaint to make from the driver's seat it would
be that a big swath of canvas at the rear corners of the roof
blocks the view.
</P>
<P>
   For safety, it's got airbags all around and a roll bar that
automatically deploys once the car tilts to that certain scary
angle.
</P>
<P>
   In 911 fashion, the engine is a horizontally opposed
six-cylinder (hey, Subaru likes the idea so much you'll see one in
the new Outback). This helps keep the center of gravity low. It's a
3.4 liter that, because of an improved exhaust system, gives four
more horsepower (300) than the '99 model. You can have a six-speed
manual or the five-speed Tiptronic.
</P>
<P>
   The test model had the Tiptronic, with wheel-mounted controls.
Working the gears was a lot like playing a video game.
</P>
<P>
   Also helping boost performance for 2000 is an ``E-throttle.''
You may think you're stepping on the gas and causing direct action,
but as a Porsche guy explained to me, what you do with the pedal is
merely a suggestion to the car's control center, which then uses
cams, valves, and the air and fuel supply to do that job best for
you.
</P>
<P>
   I put about 800 miles on the Cabriolet, much of it at high
altitude and on steep grades, and got 19 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   This is a superb car, but here would be my dilemma: I haven't
driven the Boxster S, yet I've heard great things about its
performance. Before I'd drop $80,000 on the 911, I'd want to know
one thing: Is it $30,000 better than the Boxster S?
</P>
<P>
   I'll get into the latter real soon.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The one-touch operation of the convertible top. Fifteen
seconds and it's tucked away under a big smooth crescent.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --They sell you a convertible for $80,000 _ and then want $250
for a rear wind deflector? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
