<HEADER>
A4517 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SCARYMOVIE-COX     07-06 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCARYMOVIE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Scary Movie' the new champ in bad-taste derby
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We can probably all agree that ``Scary Movie,'' the Wayans'
brothers' spoof of teen slasher films, is stupid and gross. The
problem is that a large segment of the movie-going public considers
those adjectives to be compliments, not put-downs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a parody of these
someone-is-out-there-stalking-and-killing-teens movies is hardly a
new idea. Kevin Williamson already claimed that territory with his
substantially more clever ``Scream'' franchise. At least the first
two installments self-referentially noted the cliches of the genre,
kidded them, yet still made them work. Now comes ``Scary Movie,'' a
spoof of the spoof ``Scream ``(whose original title, as trivia fans
know, was ``Scary Movie''). Got it?
</P>
<P>
   Whole scenes here are lifted from ``Scream,'' then warped and
broadened into crude comedy by TV's Shawn and Marlon Wayans,
working with their older brother, director Keenan Ivory Wayans.
With a committee of gag writers, they also send up ``I Know What
You Did Last Summer,'' a mere ``Scream `` wannabe. Eventually,
after they exhaust all the jokes in these two movies, they cast
their nets wider and kid any recent hit, from ``The Blair Witch
Project'' to ``The Usual Suspects'' to ``The Matrix.''
</P>
<P>
   The tradition of these parody movies goes back at least as far
as the Zucker brothers, who demolished disaster movies _ a category
every bit as silly as slasher films _ with 1980's ``Airplane!''
Through the ``Naked Gun'' series and beyond, they wavered in
quality, but remained sufficiently amusing. Now come the Wayans
brothers in that Zucker mold, but grafted onto the brazenly bad
taste of the Farrelly Brothers (''There's Something About Mary'').
</P>
<P>
   It begins promisingly enough, spoofing ``Scream's'' opening.
Carmen Electra as the slyly named Drew Decker is home alone popping
popcorn, when she gets a terrifying phone call, followed by a visit
from a knife-wielding specter in a Halloween costume.
</P>
<P>
   She escapes his clutches, strips down to her undies for reasons
that are unclear (but who's arguing?), then runs through lawn
sprinklers for an even more alluring wet look, before being caught
and bludgeoned in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   When they learn of Drew's demise, her high school pals _ all way
beyond student age _ fret they will be next, fearing that the
killer knows they ran over a guy in the road last Halloween and
left him for dead. That is about as far as the plot goes, for
``Scary Movie'' gives up on story in favor of unconnected sketch
vignettes built around slasher movie archetypes.
</P>
<P>
   There's the virginal heroine, Cindy Campbell (Anna Faris), who
is busy keeping her horny boyfriend at bay, the obnoxious
television reporter Gail Hailstrom (Cheri Oteri) busy cashing in on
the mayhem, and the slow-witted deputy sheriff Doofy (Dave
Sheridan), who is busy drooling.
</P>
<P>
   Off in their own world, a kind of ``In Living Color'' but
without the inhibitions of network television, are Shawn Wayans as
a gay football jock in deep denial over his orientation and Marlon
Wayans as a horror movie junkie obsessed with getting high. Their
acting style could best be described as indulgent.
</P>
<P>
   In the all-time bad-taste derby, ``Scary Movie'' takes the lead,
just weeks after ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' became the new crude champ.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, if stupid and gross is what you're after, the Wayans
clan is gleefully eager to accommodate. Warning: If ``Scary Movie''
turns into a hit, it will encourage someone to make a film even
more stupid and gross. That would be a truly scary prospect.
</P>
<P>
   SCARY MOVIE
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   Rated R: Prosthetic private parts, comic violence, crude sexual
situations, language
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 28 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Broad, obvious parody of teen slasher movies and
other genres.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
