<HEADER>
A4518 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-THEKIDREVIEW-COX     07-06 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEKIDREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man-child reunion too dull for kids, too artless for adults
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's an interesting Freudian premise in the new Bruce Willis
movie, the name-branded ``Disney's The Kid'':
</P>
<P>
   What if, by a primal fluke of nature, you met yourself as an
8-year-old child? What if the tot reminded you of everything you
disliked about your youth, while your adult achievements greatly
disappointed your younger self?
</P>
<P>
   The ramifications are enough to keep a swarm of psychotherapists
busy for years. But remember whose Kid this is, so wipe away any
thoughts of analytic depth and replace them with gooey Baby Boomer
feel-good vibes. Never fret that you may not know what to think
about image consultant Russ Duritz's personal quandary, for Marc
Shaiman's treacly, sitcom-music score tells you how to react at
every moment.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may not be obvious to a youngster, Russ has a great
job. He gets to insult politicians, television news anchors and
baseball team owners in the guise of helping them, and then he
bills them for his public relations advice. But in the eyes of
pudgy 8-year-old Rusty (certifiably adorable Spencer Breslin, a
veteran of commercials), Russ is a loser _ with a capital ``L'' _
because he is not married, doesn't pilot jets and he doesn't own a
dog. Sure, we could add that he also makes movies like ``Hudson
Hawk,'' but why rub it in?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that Russ wears $2,000 suits, has an
extraordinary bachelor pad and plenty of other adult toys
signifying material success. Yet it doesn't bring happiness,
because _ as Dr. Freud might put it if he worked for Disney _ he
has lost touch with his inner child. Oh, and he's a rotten person.
</P>
<P>
   He ignores his aging father, is brusque with his tirelessly
efficient assistant (a droll Lily Tomlin, who must not realize she
has mistakenly gotten involved in kids' stuff) and is downright
insensitive to his British sidekick (a waifish Emily Mortimer, who
looks disconcertingly like Demi Moore at times).
</P>
<P>
   Although the screenplay by Audrey Wells (''Guinevere'') is said
to be an original, someone should check her library records to see
how recently she checked out Charles Dickens' ``A Christmas
Carol.'' You know the book: well-heeled curmudgeon is visited by an
apparition from his past, is guided through telling moments from
his life, learns the importance of stopping and smelling the roses
and makes an astonishing conversion to generous lovability by the
fade-out. Far be it from me to give away the ending, but do not be
surprised to see Willis clutching a puppy before the final credits
roll.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine that an A-list star yearned to be in a
sentimental, family-friendly comedy, but then things did work out
well for him the last time he teamed up with a small boy.
Personally, I have a sixth sense that ``Disney's The Kid'' will not
fare as well with audiences, mainly because it cannot decide whom
it is aimed at. Youngsters are bound to be bored at Russ'
midlife-crisis angst, and adults should find Jon Turteltaub's
rose-colored, forced comic tone too simplistic to be taken
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there are lots of precious child actors hanging out on Los
Angeles street corners, but young Breslin more than meets the
movie's requirements. He has a handful of hang-dog expressions,
talks like he has a mouthful of spit and delivers lines with deadly
comic timing. Like Haley Joel Osment before him, Breslin steals all
of his scenes with Willis, which, in this case, is hardly grand
larceny.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer also comes off well, even if her chief assignment is to
look longingly and admiringly at Willis, only to be crushed each
time he acts heartlessly. Jean Smart has a couple of nice scenes as
the newscaster in need of a makeover, but her presence only cements
the movie's sitcom feel.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Disney's The Kid'' catches on with audiences, it will be
because it stands out in this summer's sea of testosterone and
tastelessness. In fact, it is one more lame Disney live-action
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY'S THE KID
</P>
<P>
   Two stars
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG: Mildly rude behavior
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 44 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Willis meets his 8-year-old self in a midlife-angst
comedy not quite suited for either kids or adults.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
