<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA LOSES TO GERMANY AS SITE FOR SOCCER'S 2006 WORLD CUP
 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soccer's international body Thursday awarded the 2006 World Cup
finals to Germany over South Africa in a close vote that dashed
hopes that the world's most popular sporting event would be held
for the first time in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-11 vote by the executive committee of the body, known as
FIFA, came as a shock to South Africans and to many in the soccer
world. In recent weeks, vote-bargaining had appeared to make South
Africa the favorite. The nation had a boost from the beginning when
the president of the soccer body, Sepp Blatter, first expressed the
desire for Africa to be named as the location for the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup finals draw billions of television viewers and
billions of dollars in revenue when they are staged every four
years, most recently in France in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Blatter had argued that the World Cup should rotate from
continent to continent. The 2002 World Cup competition will be held
in Asia, with South Korea and Japan as co-hosts. Four World Cup
finals have been held in South America _ in Uruguay, Brazil, Chile
and Argentina _ and three in North America _ two in Mexico and one
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The 2006 World Cup finals will be Europe's 10th, and Germany's
second. The last one there was in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   For South Africa, the chance to become the site of the finals
was more than just a question of wealth. The country's bid
organizers argued that the West had a moral obligation toward a
nation emerging from decades of apartheid, where soccer is the
passion of the long-oppressed black majority and where sports have
been seen in the post-apartheid era as an engine of racial healing
and a symbol of the once-isolated country's return to the
international fold. They also argued that soccer is the continent's
sports passion, and that Africa has fueled European clubs with
players for years now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course the disappointment we're experiencing today is a
setback to our efforts at gaining the recognition that Africa
deserves in the international sporting community,'' President Thabo
Mbeki said in a live broadcast on South African television.
</P>
<P>
   Germany was awarded the World Cup games on the third round of
voting.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the first round, Germany received 10 votes; six went to South
Africa and five went to England. Morocco received three first-round
votes and was eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   In the next round, Germany and South Africa tied at 11 votes
each, and England _ which suffered an image problem because of
recent incidents of soccer hooliganism _ was cut, with only two
votes.
</P>
<P>
   In the third round, one of the two people who cast votes for
England, Scotland's David Will, threw his lot to Germany. Charles
Dempsey, the New Zealand delegate, abstained. If he had voted for
South Africa, creating a 12-12 tie, Blatter would have cast the
deciding vote, presumably for his longtime favorite, South Africa,
The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey's abstention stunned the South Africans.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the German bid group, Franz Beckenbauer, said he
was surprised by the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not prepared for this because you can't be prepared for
this,'' he said. ``It was a very close result. We'd hoped for this
but we couldn't expect it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The South Africans argued that they had the infrastructure to
stage a successful World Cup final. One of the obstacles that South
Africa had to overcome was worries about its severe crime problem.
The nation has one of the highest crime rates in the world, and
visiting sportsmen have fallen victim in the past. Stadium security
is also not the strictest, given that the apartheid-era security
forces gave it scant attention.
</P>
<P>
   Other marks against South Africa were a poor public
transportation system and the country's distance for European fans.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa had promised to devote 10 percent of its budget to
security, and it pointed to previous international events it had
hosted _ the 1995 rugby World Cup, the 1996 Africa Cup of Nations
soccer tournament, the 1998 track and field World Cup and the 1999
Africa Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
