<HEADER>
A4534 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-AMERICORPS-RECRUITS-H     07-06 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICORPS-RECRUITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CEREAL MAKER TO PROMOTE VOLUNTEER PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT FLORES  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ It may not have any snap, crackle or pop, but the
makers of an organic breakfast cereal are delivering a passionate
pitch to millions of young adults in an effort to recruit them into
the AmeriCorps volunteer organization.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to dramatically increase the organization's ranks to meet
membership goals during the next few years, General Mills has
teamed up with the government to call attention to the 5-year-old
volunteer corps.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this month, the company's top-selling organic
breakfast cereal, Sunrise Organic, will feature three AmeriCorps
members on its boxes, and the company has pledged to donate $1 to
AmeriCorps programs for every cereal box sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be as recognizable as the Peace Corps,'' said
Harris Wofford, a former Democratic senator from Pennsylvania and
current chief executive officer of the Corporation for National
Service, which oversees AmeriCorps.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program with Sunrise Organic breakfast cereal reaches
more people than we've ever been able to reach in the past. You
could say we were looking for something to give our recruiting more
bite,'' Wofford said.
</P>
<P>
   AmeriCorps is a government-sponsored volunteer organization
whose members work in a variety of service projects across the
country. Members receive a stipend to cover living expenses and
health insurance and, after a year of service, an education award
to pay for college or pay back student loans.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its recruiting campaign, the cereal company will
feature three AmeriCorps volunteers on the back panel of the box. A
brief text describes their current service projects, which include
organic farming and national park restoration. The box also offers
a Web link where monthly updates and photographs of each of the
volunteers will be provided.
</P>
<P>
   One of the volunteers, Juliet Schraeder, 24, of Madison, Wis.,
teaches organic gardening at the Austin Community Gardens in the
Texas state capital.
</P>
<P>
   The gardens grow vegetables for food banks and homeless
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how fulfilling this experience would be, but
working for AmeriCorps has turned out to be one of the greatest
experiences of my life,'' Schraeder said.
</P>
<P>
   AmeriCorps is hoping to recruit 50,000 volunteers this year. Its
current membership is 40,000. Clinton has proposed that the
organization enlist 100,000 new volunteers each year by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150,000 mostly young people have served in AmeriCorps
since it was launched in 1994. Besides park preservation and
organic farming, AmeriCorps volunteers coordinate disaster relief,
fight forest fires, build homes and tutor, mentor and help
vaccinate children.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (More information about AmeriCorps is available at
www.americorps.org.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
