<P>
   HUDSON-SHAKESPEARE (Undated) _ In the theater it isn't always an
encouraging sign when the audience leaves humming the scenery. But
at the Hudson Valley Shakespeare Festival, it's all but inevitable.
The festival, one of the best-kept theatrical secrets of summer in
the gentrified outer reaches of the New York metropolitan area, is
ensconced in the most lyrical of settings for open-air theater: the
grounds of the Boscobel Restoration, a historic house and gardens
on a promontory overlooking the Hudson River across from West
Point. The plays change each July and August, but the magnificent
backdrop is immutable. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   VANGOGH-PORTRAITS (Boston) _ Despite a reputation for antisocial
behavior (the episode of the amputated earlobe looms large),
Vincent van Gogh was a people person. He was an avid talker and
letter writer, fluent in four languages. Early in his short life he
held a series of face-the-public jobs, as an apprentice art dealer,
a schoolteacher and an evangelical preacher. Van Gogh is surrounded
by people, and very much part of the crowd, in ``Van Gogh: Face to
Face,'' a show devoted to his portraits, at the Museum of Fine Arts
here. Among the 80 entries are paintings and drawings of friends
and neighbors, lovers and strangers, and repeatedly, magnetically,
of the artist himself. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   NY-AUTOMOBILE-ROW (New York) _ Given New York's hate-hate
relationship with motor vehicles _ on the one hand, their numbers
and bulk make the streets impassable; on the other hand, their
fumes and noise foul the atmosphere _ it is hard to imagine a day
when mid-Manhattan was the automotive Acropolis of America. But
there was such a time. And there was such a place: Automobile Row,
a one-and-a-half mile stretch of Broadway from the 40s to the 70s,
lined with car makers, tire companies and dealerships by the
dozens. Bedazzled buyers could find the ``Three P's'' of luxury
motoring _ Packard, Peerless and Pierce (makers of the Arrow) _
jostling for attention with Babcock Electrics and White Steamers,
Hupmobiles, Loziers, Overlands, Reos and Speedwells. By David W.
Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   RUSCHA-RETROSPECTIVE (Washington) _ If you can catch the
traveling retrospective of Ed Ruscha's 40-year career, now here at
the Hirshhorn Museum, you should do so. Ruscha's scrutiny of the
world is truly American, and his art hovers tantalizingly on the
edge of slapstick, with enough intimation of melancholy to keep you
guessing. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   RAUSCHENBERG-NEW-WORK (New York) _ Continuing his long-running
game of ``Anyone Can Be an Artist as Long as I'm in Charge,''
Robert Rauschenberg has unveiled his latest enterprise at the
Whitney Museum of American Art. By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
