<HEADER>
A4541 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-REVISITING-NUREM     07-06 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-REVISITING-NUREMBERG-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTING THE UNIMAGINABLE: TELEVISION REVISITS NUREMBERG 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of scenes from the
television miniseries ``Nuremberg.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Modern-day Hollywood has a strict hierarchy: Those who make
feature movies, however trite, are the elite, while network
television people are considered lesser artists. As for those who
toil for cable television, well, they are so low on the totem pole
that the others often won't even acknowledge their existence.
 &HT;    It's an attitude which makes no sense at all, and no greater
proof is needed than ``Nuremberg,'' the two-part miniseries airing
on Turner Network Television July 16 and 17.
 &HT;    ``You're never, never, never in a thousand light years, in the
current universe, going to get the networks to make the Nuremberg
trials for television,'' says star Alec Baldwin, a veteran of
feature films. ``I've pitched relevant, historical dramas like
this, and the networks just completely glaze over.''
 &HT;    Their loss, then. This account of the 1945 Nuremberg trials, in
which 21 Nazi leaders were tried on war-crimes charges, is a
remarkable achievement. It stars Baldwin as Chief Justice Robert
Jackson, the lead prosecutor, with Brian Cox as the Nazi Field
Marshal Hermann Goering, Christopher Plummer as the British
prosecutor Sir David Maxwell-Fyfe and Jill Hennessy _ best known
for ``Law and Order'' _ as Jackson's assistant, Elsie Douglas.
 &HT;    This capable cast, plus an absorbing script by David W. Rintels,
add up to some of the most compelling hours of film seen in a very
long time, on the big screen or elsewhere.
 &HT;    It's 1945 and the victorious Allies _ the United States,
Britain, France and Russia _ are struggling to deal with the
mounting evidence that the atrocities committed by Hitler's Third
Reich are the most heinous in the history of the civilized world.
It's difficult to put an entire nation on trial, so the four
occupying powers decide to charge 22 members of the Nazi high
command with war crimes and ``crimes against humanity'' _ the first
time that term has ever been used.
 &HT;    One of the accused, German Labor Front boss Robert Ley, hangs
himself before the trial, leaving 21 men to face an international
team of prosecutors at Nuremberg _ an ironic venue, since it was
from Nuremberg that Hitler's mammoth Nazi Party rallies broadcast
the ``glory'' of his Reich to the world.
 &HT;    Hollywood has told this story before, in Stanley Kramer's
``Judgement at Nuremberg'' (1961), with an all-star cast that
included Spencer Tracy, Burt Lancaster, Marlene Dietrich and Judy
Garland. Though sober and well-intentioned, it was a
once-over-lightly look at the trial as melodrama, without too much
concern for historical accuracy.
 &HT;    This version, on the other hand, takes accuracy very seriously.
Based on Joseph E. Persico's book ``Nuremberg: Infamy on Trial''
(Viking Press, 1994) and made by a French-Canadian company in
Montreal, it goes for the historical truth, which turns out to have
plenty of drama for even the most restless viewer.
 &HT;    ``The overwhelming majority of what is said in the film is
excerpted from the actual trial transcripts,'' Baldwin says, ``but
in the case of Jackson's opening argument, the actual document was
somewhere between 40 and 60 pages in length, which would have been
a miniseries in itself. So we had to abbreviate.
 &HT;    ``We also had to telescope the number of principal roles for
dramatic purposes,'' he adds, ``so we wound up bringing four or
five people to the fore, so that we could attract good actors who
wanted to play those roles.''
 &HT;    The story focuses primarily on the battle between good and evil,
as personified by Brian Cox's Goering, who is the rallying point
and cheerleader for the imprisoned Nazis, and Baldwin's Jackson,
terrified of not having the legal skills to make history.
 &HT;    But the villains are anything but cardboard bad guys. Goering in
particular is shown in many dimensions, and the heroes understand
that, had the war gone differently, they themselves might have
ended up on trial for war crimes.
 &HT;    Even the back stories are fascinating. They include the
political maneuvering between the French, American, British and
Russian judges, the posturings of a vain American justice (Len
Cariou) with a chip on his shoulder and the paternal relationship
between the suave British prosecutor (Plummer) and his
less-seasoned American colleague _ for once, it is the American who
is the most cautious of the group.
 &HT;    There's also the relationship between Goering and the
Jewish-American military shrink assigned to psychoanalyze the
defendants, as well as a fascinating, crucial piece of theater as
Goering uses his Machiavellian powers to woo the young American
lieutenant sent to guard him.
 &HT;    These later scenes are in some ways the most chilling of all,
because they show the seductive power of the Nazi mentality, even
to people who know to what horrors that mentality can lead.
 &HT;    In the courtroom _ an exact replica of the room where the trials
took place _ actual concentration-camp films are shown as part of
the prosecution's case. They are hideous enough viewing today, and
one can only imagine what they must have been like for those
assembled in Nuremberg 55 years ago, viewing the evidence for the
first time.
 &HT;    ``Everyone was crying _ the extras who were on camera and even
one man who wasn't,'' Hennessy says. ``He was sitting beside me,
and I could hear him sobbing. At least I was allowed to cry _ the
actors portraying the Nazis could not permit themselves to do
that.''
 &HT;    Just as affecting, however, is a scene in which Plummer reads
the testimony of an ordinary German witness to a horrendous mass
murder. It was that scene, the veteran actor says, that persuaded
him to take the part.
 &HT;    Some of the highest drama took place offscreen. The parents of
actor Sam Stone _ who portrays Julius Streicher, Hitler's
hate-literature publisher _ survived a death camp near the
Russian/Romanian border. The actor had difficulty getting through
the showing of the real-life camp footage.
 &HT;    ``I was on the witness stand at the time and I was weeping,''
Stone says. ``One of the actors came over and put his hand round me
to comfort me. He was very kind. As it turned out, as a teen-ager
he had been in the Hitler Youth Movement.''
 &HT;    Everyone in the cast was mindful of their enormous
responsibility in bringing this story to a new generation who may
not have heard it.
 &HT;    ``The Nazis on trial at Nuremberg were like the New York Yankees
of bad guys,'' Baldwin says, ``and the legal team set out to have
the first war-crimes tribunal in history. Many legal scholars found
overwhelming flaws in the way the cases were handled, but, as much
as they were criticized, in the end the Nuremberg trials were an
incredibly important contribution to civilization.
 &HT;    ``What they did there was profound.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Nuremberg,'' consult the TNT
Web site at www.turner.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on Hollywood Stars and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
