<SLUG> BC-TREK-KEVIN-BACON-IN-HOLLOW-MAN-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVIN BACON FLESHES OUT A `HOLLOW MAN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Kevin Bacon
with Elisabeth Shue in a scene from ``The Hollow Man.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Kevin Bacon disappears into his roles, but he's hardly an
invisible actor.
 &HT;    Though he jokes that it may be his downfall, Bacon likes to err
on the side of acting big, of pushing a performance a tad too far.
Anyone who saw last year's ``Stir of Echoes,'' or the earlier ``The
River Wild'' or ``A Few Good Men,'' can attest to Bacon's sizzle.
 &HT;    ``I think, oftentimes, film actors were just told to `Dial it
down, dial it down, dial it down,''' Bacon says. ``I'll look at a
performance and think, `Wake the f--k up! Do a little acting. Do
something!'
 &HT;    ``I want to see some semblance of a performance if I'm paying my
money to see something,'' Bacon says. ``I tend to appreciate actors
who go over the top, (even if) they don't always hit.
 &HT;    ``Nic Cage is a good example,'' he says. ``James Woods, Dustin
Hoffman. It doesn't always work, but at least they are going for
it.''
 &HT;    Bacon goes for it again with his latest film, ``Hollow Man,'' a
variation on the ``Invisible Man'' saga directed by Paul Verhoeven.
Verhoeven previously helmed such high-adrenaline genre epics as
``Total Recall'' and ``Starship Troopers.''
 &HT;    ``Hollow Man'' will materialize on August 4, starring Bacon as
Sebastian Caine, a cocky scientist working with colleagues Linda
McKay (Elisabeth Shue) and Matthew Kensington (Josh Brolin) on
clandestine government research into invisibility. After
successfully testing a vanishing serum on animals, Caine ignores
protocol and injects himself with the serum.
 &HT;    ``The catch is that I am predisposed to a touch of evil,'' Bacon
says over lunch in a conference room at his publicist's Manhattan
office. ``That gets amplified, to say the least, when I become
invisible.
 &HT;    ``I start causing trouble, and I make life hell for Elisabeth
and Josh,'' he says. ``It's very bizarre and very cool. For
instance, a sprinkler system will come on and the water will cling
to my form. The movie is going to be good.''
 &HT;    Bacon spends a great deal of time offscreen, and thus had to
make his presence felt early and powerfully. All the thrills and
chills that follow Caine's invisibility are the combined result of
Bacon's voice, more than 500 special effects, the performances of
Shue and Brolin, and of course the virtuosity of director
Verhoeven.
 &HT;    As a filmmaker, Verhoeven is known as much for his hard-driving
directorial style as for the brutal violence and stark sexuality
depicted in his films. Bacon acknowledges that Verhoeven was not
one to fade into the woodwork.
 &HT;    ``Paul is very, very passionate,'' Bacon says, a wicked grin
crossing his face. ``He's kind of like a mad scientist himself _
he's got a brilliant mind and is just full of this incredible
energy. He gets very amped.
 &HT;    ``We got along really well,'' the actor adds. ``He can be
explosive and I'm not, but it seemed to work OK.''
 &HT;    Bacon's career might best be described as OK, too. Though he's
not a pack-'em-in megastar like Tom Cruise or Jim Carrey, the
42-year-old actor is in constant demand for both mainstream and
independent features. His genre pictures alone prove the point, as
they include ``Flatliners,'' ``Tremors'' and ``Apollo 13.''
 &HT;    Still, Bacon is not satisfied.
 &HT;    ``Never,'' says the actor, who lives with his wife, actress Kyra
Sedgwick, and their children in Connecticut, and will next be on
view opposite Helena Bonham Carter, Laura Dern and Steve Martin in
the dental comedy ``Novocaine.''
 &HT;    ``I don't know where I want to be,'' he says thoughtfully. ``I
feel that with `Stir of Echoes,' `Skip the Dog' and `Hollow Man,' I
am at a point again where things could be really good. `Hollow Man'
is a great part, a big part in a big film. It's a role where I get
to be a little evil, and those tend to be noticed by people.
 &HT;    ``If this period leads to anything for me, I'd love to get to do
a character that also happens to be the hero,'' Bacon adds. ``So
often in movies, especially the ones that get seen, the really
interesting roles are the bad guy, the goofy best friend and the
gay next-door neighbor. The hero usually isn't that much of a
character.
 &HT;    ``I want to play an interesting hero.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Hollow Man,'' consult the Sony
Pictures Entertainment Web site at www.spe.sony.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
