<HEADER>
A4553 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-SCAREMOVIE-TEX     07-06 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SCAREMOVIE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NOT MUCH ABOUT `SCARY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to be a splatter-flick buff to know that ``Scary
Movie'' was the original title of ``Scream,'' Wes Craven's smart,
suspenseful spoof of slice-and-dice films. Now, there was a movie
that managed to slash its cake and eat it, too, reviving an
all-but-dead genre while mocking its conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Because ``Scream'' _ not to mention ``Scream 2'' and ``Scream
3'' _ was used instead of the original title, the door was left
open for Keenen Ivory Wayans to call his spoof ``Scary Movie,''
which lampoons ``Scream'' and its countless ripoffs. In other
words, it's a parody of a parody, and despite some chuckle-worthy
moments, ``Scary Movie'' is just as redundant as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   It starts well enough, with a sharp takeoff on ``Scream's''
bravura prologue, this time featuring Carmen Electra as the young
woman whose plans for a quiet night alone are interrupted by a
series of increasingly terrifying phone calls. Wayans and his
battery of writers come up with clever gags about Electra's
``Baywatch'' past and her one-time association with Prince, but
somehow miss out on a joke about her on-and-off marriage to Dennis
Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   But the prologue includes an unnecessary _ although perhaps
inevitable _ flatulence joke, and that's an indication of things to
come: For every clever little riff the writers concoct, there's a
huge gross-out moment that would make the Farrelly brothers blush.
This is the type of movie where when the filmmakers say, ``Let's
just throw things at the wall and see what sticks,'' they mean it
literally.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the antics surround poor Cindy Campbell (Anna Faris),
the archetypal virgin-who's-stalked-by-the-killer. Among Cindy's
buds are her increasingly libidinous boyfriend (Jon Abrahams), a
jock who shows every indication of not realizing that he's gay
(Shawn Wayans), and the school vixen (''American Pie's'' Shannon
Elizabeth, scoring the movie's one comic bull's-eye in an
evisceration of Rose McGowan's vampish screen persona). They and
the others in their crew (Lochlyn Munro and Regina Hall) evidently
kill a pedestrian, and begin receiving threatening notes, a la ``I
Know What You Did Last Summer,'' the title of which is continually
ridiculed. No one's ever done that before, huh?
</P>
<P>
   And therein is ``Scary Movie's'' other principal problem _ it
comes at least three years too late, when the slasher genre is
wheezing again and its internal parodies are once more
unintentional. Hence, many of ``Scary Movie's'' best riffs are on
non-slasher movies such as ``The Matrix,'' ``The Blair Witch
Project'' and ``The Sixth Sense.'' It does manage the occasional
savvy jab at the ``Scream'' series, including a funny twist on the
ol' the-killer-is-in-the-house bit and a gag about noisy audience
members that will have every polite movie fan silently cheering.
Marlon Wayans, as a gleeful pothead who parties with the killer,
also earns some laughs.
</P>
<P>
   If you've seen the trailer for ``Scary Movie,'' you'll note that
much of what's mentioned in the previous paragraph is included in
the preview. That's good marketing, but it's not necessarily good
moviemaking. What you won't see in the preview are the scenes that
put various bodily organs, functions and fluids on display.
Director Wayans relies too heavily on these grossout gags, which
inspire groans of disgust rather than howls of laughter. The truly
frightening thing about this is that, given our increased tolerance
for lowbrow humor during the past couple of years, the grossest
stuff is likely to make ``Scary Movie'' a hit. Even more
frightening is that it could merit a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Scary Movie''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Keenen Ivory Wayans
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Anna Faris, Shannon Elizabeth
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, sexual situations, violence, drug
abuse and various types of goo
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1535EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
