<HEADER>
A4568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-POPULATION07-COX     07-06 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPULATION07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AN AGING AMERICA FACES BROAD CHANGES, STUDY PREDICTS
 &HT;    580&AMP;add. With POPULATION-DATA-1STLD.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's aging population will force policy makers
to change everything from retirement benefits to the lettering on
traffic signs, presenting one of the key challenges in the 21st
century, a study predicted Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As the country's population grows, the proportion of old people
to young is growing, in large part because of better health care
that helps people live longer and the trend toward families with
fewer children.
</P>
<P>
   The median age of the population was 35.5 years in 1999,
compared to 22.9 in 1900. By 2100, the median age is projected by
the Census Bureau to be 40.3.
</P>
<P>
   ``This realignment has the potential of being more politically
challenging than anything we've seen before,'' said Martha
Farnsworth Riche, a population researcher and former Census Bureau
director who authored the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scares politicians because it is such a big political
task,'' she said at a news conference presenting the study,
``America's Diversity and Growth: Signposts for the 21st Century.''
</P>
<P>
   To visualize the problem, imagine a pyramid, with a wide base
representing children and gradually diminishing by age group to the
point at the top. That was the profile of the country's population
in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   By 2020, as the crest of post-World War II baby boomers reaches
retirement age, the model looks more like a pillar, with an almost
equal number of people in each age group from birth through age 70.
</P>
<P>
   Riche said the emerging population profile already has begun to
shape policy changes, from larger and easier-to-read lettering on
highway signs to the ongoing debate about Social Security and
retirement benefits. Housing traditionally designed for families
raising children will be revamped to accommodate people who want to
live in their own homes until very late in life, the study
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   The aging population will place new demands on the health care
system, and may stir political tensions between the generations as
younger people are taxed to finance the benefits of their elders.
</P>
<P>
   It also will influence the traditional notion of retirement,
with people continuing to work well beyond the age of 65. It will
open more opportunities for women who, because they are living
longer, have more time to begin or revive a career after their
childbearing and child-raising years, Riche said.
</P>
<P>
   The study notes that when the age threshold of 65 was set for
full Social Security benefits when the system was created in 1935,
average life expectancy at birth was about 62. Today it is 77, but
the age for full benefits is rising only to 67.
</P>
<P>
   Better health care and public-safety laws have Americans living
longer, what Riche called ``the success story of the 20th
century.'' Half of America's current population would not be alive
today had the advances not been made, the study shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the large growth of the older population, Americans will
no doubt revise their assumptions about what 'old' means for
individuals and institutions,'' the report concludes. ``Assumptions
that people will spend their entire work life in one occupation, or
that career ladders can be climbed in only one direction, may prove
ill-suited to a potentially longer work life.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on Census Bureau data and published by the
non-profit Population Reference Bureau, a Washington-based research
group.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In general, this century will be marked by robust population
growth and immigration, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration will continue to make America more diverse, the
study said. In 1999, 72 percent of Americans were white, with
blacks and Hispanics each making up 12 percent of the population
and Asian-Americans 4 percent. By 2050, the white population e
best. That's not stopping, and it shows no sign of stopping,''
Riche said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.prb.org
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
