r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     07-06 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING A COMFORT ZONE WITH CHILDREN'S TV VIEWING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A longtime reader, first-time caller is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got a question,'' she starts. ``Um, er, hmmm ... don't know
how to ask this without sounding really, really stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask. I'll be gentle.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK ... what's a v-chip?''
</P>
<P>
   A v-chip?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah. The television device thingie that keeps certain
programs from coming on. I saw a news program the other day, which
talked about parents not using it. How do I know I have one?''
</P>
<P>
   If you had one, you'd know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's not something the government or whomever just puts in
your house without you knowing it?''
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it sold door to door?''
</P>
<P>
   If someone tries, slam the door, lock it, and call 911.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you get it, how?''
</P>
<P>
   Televisions come equipped with the device. If you haven't bought
a new set recently then you don't have a v-chip, or any other
device, designed to keep your kids from watching stuff you don't
want them to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, if that's the case, why are we being scolded for not using
it if we don't have it?''
</P>
<P>
   You're being scolded?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, not personally, but they're saying something about a lot
of parents whining about adult TV but this study they've done shows
that many parents aren't using the v-chip thingie that would give
them control over what their children watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Two out of five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two out of five?''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah. Two out of five parents, according to researchers, aren't
bothering to use the tools available to them, according to the
Annenberg Public Policy Center. Not because they don't care about
them. Most are simply uninformed. The television industry has done
a poor job telling us that the v-chip is available. And hype over
TV violence has slowed, once again, since no one in Washington is
trying to use it for political brownie points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know that television stations must air three hours a
week of educational children's programs. Is that true?''
</P>
<P>
   True, but their version of educational TV is scary. I mean,
``Saved by the Bell'' or anything animated counts, but these shows
are hardly educational.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, how do you know what's educational and what's not?''
</P>
<P>
   They're labeled on the screen with an ``E/I,'' which means
``educational and informative.'' Although, they've got to be
laughing at that themselves. It's ludicrous. Just like the other
labels on episodes of shows like ``Friends.'' I don't know of a
single person who actually uses them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, are those labels in your paper, in TV Guide?''
</P>
<P>
   Nope. And nope. And there's more. The networks are routinely
taking advantage of FCC rules that now allow them to pre-empt
Saturday morning E/I shows with whatever they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can they do that?''
</P>
<P>
   It's TV. They can do anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   It's all-powerful and all-knowing. And guess who gave them the
power? We did. Hate to put you on the spot, but how many TVs are in
your house?
</P>
<P>
   ``Four.''
</P>
<P>
   Where?
</P>
<P>
   ``Living room, three in bedrooms, one in the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   That's five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh ... five.''
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to watch while I cook, wash dishes. It's more like
background noise, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Three bedrooms?
</P>
<P>
   ``My son has one. My daughter has hers. And we have one in our
bedroom. It sounds like a lot but I don't know what we'd do with
only one TV. I guess it's not a good thing, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly gives your children a sense of what you consider
important. Plus, you can't watch what they watch when they're in
their rooms alone, their doors closed, the sound down. But you're
not alone. In the survey you speak of, while parents expressed
concern about their children's viewing habits, as you do, more than
half of the kids surveyed have TVs in their rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, it's a matter of just turning the thing off? Or just
making sure only family-oriented shows are shown?''
</P>
<P>
   How to protect a child from the rude shocks of the tube is a
question answered in each household, depending on what your kids
watch and for how long. Forcing all TV to conform to a
safe-for-kids standard seems unfair to adults. Advisories that warn
of excessive violence are fine, but who guarantees what kids will
do when they're alone in their rooms? This is what prompted the
whole v-chip thingie you speak of.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what's the answer? I feel like we're talking in circles
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Look, violence and sex are enduring parts of popular culture,
and nobody would be worrying all that much about them if daily life
weren't so filled with both as well. As long as there are buyers
for sex and violence, there will be sellers of it. Want my advice?
Find your personal comfort zone, whether it's the v-chip or simply
limiting TV watching in your house. Or how about simply getting
those TVs out of your kids' rooms?
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds like the toughest one. Got any ideas on how to
break it to them?''
</P>
<P>
   Bribery?
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
