<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BET-STUDIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE NETWORK CHOOSES HARLEM FOR OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Black Entertainment Television, the nation's only
24-hour cable network meant for African-Americans, has selected an
East Harlem office building for the location of a New York office
and studio, company officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company's long-awaited New York office will be a production
operation and headquarters for its music division, which is one of
three divisions that provide original programming for the network.
It will be in a former office building on East 106th Street, near
Park Avenue, and is scheduled to open in September, in time for the
beginning of the fall television season.
</P>
<P>
   Officials did not disclose the cost of construction of the
facilities or the price of the lease.
</P>
<P>
   Black Entertainment Television, a subsidiary of Washington-based
BET Holdings II, is the latest in a long list of large corporations
to make substantial investments in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Magic Johnson Theaters, Harlem's first multiplex,
opened in the six-level $66 million Harlem USA shopping and
entertainment complex at 125th Street and Frederick Douglass
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The complex is the home to stores for several national chains,
including HMV records, Disney, Old Navy and Modell's Sporting
Goods.
</P>
<P>
   Other developments in the area include a new retail complex
planned between Adam Clayton Powell Jr. Boulevard and Malcolm X
Boulevard and a new 50,000-square-foot shopping market planned for
145th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``By transferring much of our music-oriented programming to New
York City, we put BET right in the center of the music universe,''
Curtis Gadson, the network's vice president for programming, said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give us greater access to the top talent for both
appearances and performances on our shows.''
</P>
<P>
   A 10,000-square-foot office space and 7,000-square-foot studio
are expected to be completed by the end of the summer, officials
said. There will be 10 to 15 full-time workers housed in the
complex, and dozens of other contract employees, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the NBC, CBS and MTV studios with windows that overlook
Times Square and allow for participation from audience members on
the street, BET's studio will be entirely enclosed, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is different from what our counterparts have done in Times
Square,'' said Michael Lewellen, a spokesman for BET.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not have windows that look out on a New York vantage
point, but the flavor of the shows will be New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said that several of the shows, including new
music programs for the fall season called ``106th and Park'' and
``BET in NY,'' will take on a New York setting, with video disc
jockeys getting outdoors and using the city as a backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to bringing new jobs, Lewellen said that the company
also hopes to provide work to television and music contractors now
in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   The move to New York is a part of a three-pronged strategy in
which the company will put its music division in New York, its
entertainment division in Los Angeles and its news programming in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In June, BET announced plans to cut approximately 50 positions
in its network operations, programming and production departments.
The cuts were attributed to technological upgrades and the
network's decision to open the New York office.
</P>
</TEXT>
