<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNERFALLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALLING IN LOVE, ALL OVER AGAIN, WITH TURNER FALLS IN OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by TURNER FALLS-HOW TO) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIS, Okla. _ There is no slow-moving Lazy River inner-tube
ride at Turner Falls. No twisty-turny, high-speed fiberglass water
slide; no imported fake-sand beach fronted by an automated
artificial wave pool.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what you get at this city park just miles across the
Oklahoma-Texas border, is what nature intended.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of this park, the oldest in the state, is the
graceful 77-foot-tall waterfall, created where the sweetly named
Honey Creek cascades over the Arbuckle Mountains. In the park's
1,500 wooded acres, visitors can wade in the clear creek, clamber
across boulders and follow gentle paved trails, explore caves and
splash around in two natural swimming holes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there have been improvements over the years _ a
playground, campsites, rustic cabins, concession stands selling
snow cones and corn dogs and sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   But coming here, you get the sense that Turner Falls hasn't
changed in decades. And that no one especially wants it to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the diamonds in the rough of Oklahoma,'' says
Jerry Fullerton, the Turner Falls park manager who was Davis city
manager when the city took over the park's management in 1975. The
city government ``has done a lot to keep it up over the years. But
we don't want it to ever get too big or too fancy.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   After the two hours' drive up the largely flat Interstate 35
from Dallas-Fort Worth, the terrain changes as you approach the
falls, past Ardmore and Lake Murray, and into the rolling
tree-covered hills of the Arbuckle Mountains. Just after the first
turnoff to the falls on U.S. 77 _ a road built, according to an
aged plaque, by prison labor in 1925-26 _ there is a pullout for a
paved lookout area.
</P>
<P>
   Step out of your car here in the morning, and the air is cool,
smelling slightly of cedar. Walk down a few steps to the fenced-off
lookout, where, even without paying 50 cents to peer through the
bolted-down binoculars, you can get a great view of the waterfalls,
cascading into a small green-blue pool.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the falls have been a tourist attraction of sorts for
more than 100 years. Though some accounts have it that soldiers
from nearby Fort Arbuckle visited the site as early as 1851, the
more accepted story goes that in 1860, an Anglo settler named
Mazeppa Turner married a Laura Johnson, who was a Chickasaw.
Because of her heritage, he was allowed to claim some land north of
the falls, and the family built a cabin there. Impressed by the
beauty of the falls, Turner would take all the family's visitors to
see them up close.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, people would just say, let's go see Turner's
Falls,'' Fullerton says. ``That just became what everyone called
them.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1900s, the area around the falls, including the
gently flowing Honey Creek and the swimming holes it created, were
a popular summer destination. Privately owned resorts and cabins
were built, including a small rock ``castle,'' the remains of which
loom over Honey Creek today. The park switched back and forth
between being managed by private operators and the city of Davis
until 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Though the city has modernized and maintained the park
infrastructure, much of it looks like it must have 40, 50 or even
75 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the roads and buildings, such as the rock bathhouse and
the trading post, were built in the 1930s by WPA workers, and they
still have the look of an old-fashioned summer camp. Where
structures have been rebuilt _ like a bridge repaired by a
volunteer group of Vietnam veterans after a flood in '90 _ the
original style has been followed.
</P>
<P>
   A playground is outfitted with old-style metal equipment, the
kind that was a fixture on schoolyards in the '60s. There's a tiny
chapel, with a stained-glass cross and four curved wooden pews just
big enough to seat four families; devotionals are held each Sunday
morning. Wooden picnic tables are scattered around the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The nearest town is Davis, a community of about 2,500 just a
couple of miles from the park's entrance, and the other amenities
in the area are strictly small-town. Local motels and cabins are
definitely on the rustic side, with simple furnishings; these are
not the types of luxurious bed-and-breakfasts where you'll find
Egyptian cotton sheets or marble bathroom counters. Dining options
tend toward family-style barbecue and catfish places; you can find
good food, but it's far from fancy.
</P>
<P>
   But then, that's not why you would come to this corner of
Oklahoma. The draw is the water, cool and crisp.
</P>
<P>
   The most-photographed and prettiest swimming area is the natural
pool into which the falls empty. You reach it by walking less than
a quarter of a mile into the woods on a paved path, below an old
stone castle and other abandoned cabins perched on the low cliffs.
But all along the way, you'll see kids and adults playing in the
slow-moving Honey Creek, wading or swimming or simply sitting in
the shallow water, absorbing the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Day visitors and campers _ and the park may get 20,000 daily on
a summer holiday weekend _ tend to be repeat guests, some of them
replicating the family vacations they enjoyed as kids 20 or more
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago, park manager Fullerton says, he met a
couple visiting the park for the day, happy to explain why they'd
chosen this spot for a day trip: They'd been married at the park 50
years earlier, and thought it would be fun to see it again.
</P>
<P>
   They probably thought it hadn't changed a bit.
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
