<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNERFALLS-HOWTO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU GO TO TURNER FALLS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TURNER FALLS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GETTING THERE: From Fort Worth, Turner Falls is a two-hour
drive, straight up Interstate 35; take the U.S. 77 exit.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WAY: Pie for breakfast? That's practically required at
the Fried Pie Co. and Restaurant in Gainesville (202 W. Main St.;
(940) 665-7641). Deep-fried crescents packed with apple, peach,
cherry or one of several other flavors are $1.65 each and go down
perfectly with hot coffee.
</P>
<P>
   THE MAIN ATTRACTION: Turner Falls is open year-round; there's
swimming, hiking, a playground, and camping and picnic areas. Day
admission during the summer is $6 ages 13 and over; $4.50, children
ages 7-12.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ELSE TO DO: Several local outfitters offer horseback riding
and canoe trips.
</P>
<P>
   Arbuckle Wilderness is a 400-acre park with an eight-mile
drive-through safari, small zoo, paddleboats, go-carts and other
rides and games. Open daily; admission is $14.99 adults, $12.99
children. (580) 369-3383.
</P>
<P>
   In Davis, the Arbuckle Historical Museum, housed in an old Santa
Fe depot, offers a well-organized display of antiques shedding
light on local history, including the interior of a reconstructed
pioneer cabin.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO EAT: Turner Falls is a perfect destination for packing
your own picnic. Several small stores in the area are stocked with
picnic supplies, and inside the park, stands sell snacks, ice cream
and snow cones at the park.
</P>
<P>
   In Davis, try the meaty, satisfying ribs or brisket at Willie's
Bar-B-Q ( (580) 369-3551) or go for perfectly fried catfish filets
or chicken-fried steak at the Dougherty Diner ( (580) 369-5119).
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY: Camping is allowed on a first-come, first-served
basis at the Turner Falls park, with RV hookups and screened-in
shelters available. Camping rates are $4.50 per adult plus $10-20
for hookup or shelter fees.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of small, modest motels and cabins nearby.
Some of the most pleasant are those operated by Cedarvale Garden &AMP;
Restaurant, which also has a popular trout restaurant about a mile
from the park entrance. Cabins, with grills, kitchens and
air-conditioning, start at $85. (580) 369-3224;
www.cedarvale-gardens.com. The newest motel in the area, the
Arbuckle Mountain Motel, has 24 clean but basic rooms, a hot tub
and some kitchenettes. Rooms start at $48; (580) 369-3347. There's
also a reservation service representing more than a dozen larger
homes and cabins; call (580) 369-5453 or visit
www.brightok.net/homesweethome.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Turner Falls Park, (580) 369-2917;
www.brightok.net.davis/turner.html. Davis Chamber of Commerce,
(580) 369-2402; www.brightok.net/davis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Rodriguez
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
