<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-POPLIFE-SENOR-COCONUT     07-06 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPLIFE-SENOR-COCONUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT FUSION? TO SAY THE LEAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL STRAUSS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Senor Coconut, the truth is stranger than the fiction,
which is pretty strange itself. Released this week on the record
label Emperor Norton, the second album by Senor Coconut, ``El Baile
Alleman'' (Spanish for German Dance), masquerades as a collection
of songs by the pioneering German electronic band Kraftwerk as
performed by a Latin-music combo led by an eccentric South American
composer, arranger and dancer known as Senor Coconut.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that Senor Coconut is an alias for an innovative
German producer who decided that engaging in the usual electronic
dance-music tradition of obscuring his identity by releasing albums
and singles using more than two dozen pseudonyms still wasn't
affording him enough privacy. Then, while in bed with the flu in
1996, he had a vision.
</P>
<P>
   Born Uwe Schmidt but best known for the music he has been
releasing since 1990 under the names Atom Heart and Lassigue
Bendthaus, he was trying to think of ways to blend Latin music with
electronic dance when he suddenly awoke with the image of an album
cover with the name Senor Coconut in his mind. He began working on
the album in Frankfurt, Germany, but soon decided that he might as
well move to Latin America, for both the new cultural experience
and the additional cloak of privacy. So he told his friends he was
moving to Chile. None of them believed him until he actually packed
his bags and left for Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in Chile, I'm not getting too many phone calls from
press and record labels and distributors,'' he said by telephone
from his home there. ``It's a different life here. And being in a
different culture changes your perception of things. Things are not
as precise and tight as in Germany, for example, and because of it
I'm making different music.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the beauty of Senor Coconut's ``Baile Alleman.'' Where
his previous Coconut record, ``El Gran Baile,'' was a frenetic
Latin-tinged take on drum and bass, this one uses an opposite
approach. The rigidity and technological precision of the
electronic dance music that Kraftwerk helped invent in the '70s has
been removed, as if it were the spine from an animal, causing
machine-deifying songs like ``The Robots'' and ``Trans-Europe
Express'' to collapse into fun, loose cha-chas, merengues and
cumbias.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could listen to the album just as entertainment and
nothing too profound,'' Schmidt said. ``But at the same time
there's the idea of a fake Third World band covering First World
avant-garde music. What does it mean? I always refer to it as a big
absurd question mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know Latin music, you know that the people making it
don't have any connection to the whole history of electronic music
like in Europe. A Latin musician would never make a Kraftwerk
cover: There's no compatibility. So a person in Europe like me had
to move here to make an artificial connection with Latin music to
do it. And it works musically, but at the same time it seems so
bizarre: A German living in Chile programming Kraftwerk.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most interesting juxtapositions on the album is his
version of ``Autobahn.'' In the original, Kraftwerk took a Beach
Boys-like refrain and mechanized and streamlined it for the
automobile, droning, ``Fun, fun, fun on the autobahn.'' In Senor
Coconut's laid-back cumbia version, the sand and sun return to the
refrain, mixing now with the tire rubber and pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said that when he sent out early demo versions of the
album, an unmarked copy fell into the hands of Kraftwerk members,
who thought at first that a Latin band was actually performing
their music. When Kraftwerk learned the truth, its members, known
for being extremely reclusive, critical of cover versions, and
somewhat litigious, actually liked the music and struck up a
dialogue with Schmidt. They had only one demand: That Senor
Coconut's version of ``Radio-Activity'' be dropped from the album.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought my version was too happy for the content, which I
didn't think was the case,'' Schmidt said. ``Because a Latin band
could only cover it that way. I told them that this means that a
First World band would prohibit a Third World band from covering
its song because the versions are too light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to have a discussion to explain that it's a First
World stereotype to think that Latin music is a joke and that
nobody would think bad about Kraftwerk even if they do see the song
in a funny way, but they insisted.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt released two other recommended albums last year: One of
more traditional cover songs, ``Pop Artificielle,'' under the name
Lassigue Bendthaus and an electro-acoustic emulation of a jazz
trio, ``Templates,'' under the name Flanger (a collaboration with
Burnt Friedman). But for the rest of this year he is focusing on
Senor Coconut, hoping to take it on the road if he can get
financial support. As if the album itself wasn't already enough of
a mishmash, he has a six-piece Danish band learning Latin dances to
back the Venezuelan singer who learned German lyrics for the album.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
