u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-800&AMP;A     07-06 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-800&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN WANTS PRO-RUSSIA CHECHENS TO JOIN POLICE FORCE IN CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Stung by rising casualties, President Vladimir Putin
promised Thursday to reduce the use of Russian policemen in
Chechnya and turn over more law enforcement responsibilities to
pro-Moscow Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's pledge followed a recent string of bombings that killed
at least 33 Russian troops and policemen, including members of a
police unit from Chelyabinsk, a city in the Ural Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third major attack in recent months against the
special Russian police units, known as OMON, that have been
dispatched to Chechnya to keep order in towns and cities seized by
the Russian army.
</P>
<P>
   The assaults have brought the cost of the war home to the
Russian heartland and created a potential political problem for the
new president, who was elected largely because of his forceful
policy toward Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Yegor Stroyev, the governor of the Oryol region who is known for
his loyalty to the Kremlin, summed up the sour mood Thursday.
``What is going on in Chechnya is more than a tragedy,'' Stroyev
said. ``The military is telling us that large-scale operations are
over, but why then do so many of our boys die there? How did the
death of police officers from Chelyabinsk become possible in Argun?
These questions must be answered.''
</P>
<P>
   During a surprise visit to the Mozdok military base near
Chechnya Wednesday, Putin reviewed the deteriorating situation with
his top security aides. The Mozdok meeting _ Putin's first visible
move on Chechnya since the Sunday bombings _ was broadcast on the
television news Thursday night and appeared to be a piece of
political theater intended to repair the president's image as a
decisive leader.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Putin sat behind a desk, flanked by Akhmad Kadyrov, the Chechen
and former religious leader whom Putin appointed to administer the
republic. Putin's top military aides and commanders sat in front of
him like a group of errant schoolboys.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, Putin called them to account. Putin began by
addressing his minister of defense, Igor Sergeyev, who snapped to
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has released you from your duties as chief of the
anti-terrorist operation,'' Putin said sternly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' Sergeyev responded.
</P>
<P>
   Then Putin turned to Vladimir Rushaylo, the interior minister,
whose forces include the police units that were the targets of
recent attacks.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Chelyabinsk militia, which was hit by the
Sunday bomb attack, police units from the town of Sergiyev Posad,
near Moscow, and from the Perm region in the Ural Mountains have
suffered high casualties in deadly ambushes.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to these attacks, Putin said that Russia must
``gradually stop sending scores of law-enforcement people to
Chechnya.'' Instead, he ordered the interior minister ``to involve
local citizens in the work of law-enforcement bodies in Chechnya
more boldly and energetically.``
</P>
<P>
   Putin noted that the Chechen public has a better idea than the
Russian troops of who was loyal to Moscow and who supported the
rebels. Or as Putin put it, ``the latest events have shown that
large-scale tragedies did not happen in those places where local
police officers were working.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of turning over responsibility to pro-Russia Chechens
is much easier said than done. Russian authorities have long sought
to develop a Chechen militia.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent effort involved a Chechen paramilitary unit
controlled by Bislan Gantermirov, the former major of Grozny who
was jailed for embezzlement but released and appointed to a Russian
government post so that he could fight on the Russian side.
</P>
<P>
   Gantamirov's men, however, played only a minor role in the
capture of Grozny, the Chechen capital. He and his men were
recently discharged from their posts after Russian authorities in
Chechnya charged that his 300-odd man force had failed to carry out
its duties and had vanished along with their weapons. Gantamirov is
also a rival of Kadyrov. Still, Gantamirov was at the Mozdok
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rising Russian death toll _ more than 2,300 Russian
troops have died during the conflict, 61 just last week _ there is
no mass anti-war movement in Russia, and much of the public seems
to despise the rebels more than ever. Still, there is a growing
unease over the way the war is being fought and a sense of
pessimism that a decisive victory can ever be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to win the public relations battle at home, the Russian
military has sought to portray the Sunday bombings, which involved
five trucks loaded with munitions and operated by suicide drivers,
as the desperate acts of militants who are on their last legs.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officials vowed to wipe out the last remnants
of the rebel resistance in special operations mounted by the
Russian military.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The situation in Chechnya on Thursday, however, remained tense.
Gudermes, the administration center of the republic, was closed to
civilian traffic. Only military convoys and police units were
allowed to enter and leave. And the Russian media reported that
Russian checkpoints and outposts came under fire 14 times Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kremlin says that more emphasis should be placed on
special operations,'' said the newspaper Nezavisimaya Gazeta, which
is controlled by the tycoon Boris Berezovsky. ``This is something
we have been hearing for months already, with nothing to show for
it. The situation is further damaged by the military's inability to
defend itself.``
</P>
</TEXT>
