<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM-TERRY-NYT &LR;      07-06 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-TERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIMMER REDISCOVERS TRANQUILLITY IN THE POOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 ATTN: Tenn., Calif. )  (EDS: Note the harsh language in graf 7.)  
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next month, Alison Terry will try to become the first black
swimmer to make the American Olympic team, having already made the
more important splash of self-discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Earning an Olympic berth as a freestyler would affirm the
rejuvenation of a career that began with great promise, ended in
abandonment and the despair of a suicide attempt, then re-emerged
after five years with her racial awakening and a personal mission
to bring the sport to inner-city neighborhoods where opportunities
long have been denied or dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has been able to redefine herself as a swimmer, a mentor,
a leader,'' said Alan Voisard, who is both Terry's coach and her
fiance. ``She has a great understanding now of who she is.''
</P>
<P>
   Born 26 years ago to a black father and a white mother, Terry
said she felt as a teen-ager in San Diego the societal tug of war
to declare herself one race or the other. She had little contact
with her father when she was younger, and as she began to excel at
swimming, a world as white as a bathing cap, she entered private
school and began to change the way she dressed. She said she became
ashamed of her frizzy hair, hiding it under a cap or a hooded
sweatshirt, and using products to straighten her wavy locks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really started to lose who I was,'' Terry said in a recent
interview. ``I think I was trying to emulate more the white person
and really thinking it was more important to move out of my
community. Now I've come full circle. I think it's very important
for kids to realize that opportunities can be available to them
right there in the black community, and that being successful
doesn't mean you have to move out.''
</P>
<P>
   This self-realization was not easily achieved, however, and her
swimming career was nearly drowned.
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, Terry had become a national junior freestyle champion.
A year later, she graduated from high school and intended to delay
college for a year to compete in the Olympic trials for the 1992
Summer Games in Barcelona, Spain. But her coach quit unexpectedly
before the trials. Stunned, untethered, she relocated up the
California coast to Mission Viejo, but she was unhappy and
indifferent about training. While her brimming talent and light
coppery skin had allowed her comfortable entry into the swimming
world, Terry met crude resistance when someone scrawled
``nigger''on her car, according to her mother, Debra Terry. Alison
moved back to San Diego and attended the 1992 Olympic trials as a
spectator, not a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally devastated,'' Alison Terry said. ``I was just
trying to hang on, dealing with other things, trying to find my own
identity.''
</P>
<P>
   She entered the University of Tennessee in the fall of 1992 on
scholarship, but she was still unnerved from losing her club coach
and her chance at the Olympic trials. She said she clashed with her
college coach, began skipping classes and training, and was kicked
off the team. She left school in February 1993. For five years she
would not compete.
</P>
<P>
   She began bartending, smoking, hanging with a rough crowd. She
said she felt depressed, guilty about leaving swimming, but not
strong enough emotionally to return. ``I felt like I had let
everybody down,'' Terry said. She entered a relationship that she
described as abusive, and her self-esteem plummeted. At her lowest
moment she said she used a razor blade to slice her left wrist,
which still bears a scar after six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so sorry for myself, and at the time I was so weak I
didn't think there was a way out,'' Terry said. ``I can't imagine
being that sad now. I look back, and I don't know if I really
wanted to commit suicide. If I wanted to go, I would have. Maybe it
was my way of asking for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother said she was hospitalized briefly to treat the wound
and received counseling. Trying to regain her personal ballast,
Terry enrolled in San Diego's Mesa College to study black history.
She would be greatly influenced by Starla Lewis, the chairwoman of
the school's black studies department, who persuaded Terry to
decide her own identity, not one that society would decide for her.
Lewis also told her not to frustrate herself by trying to adhere to
white standards of hair, beauty and physical appearance. Where she
once hid her hair under a cap, Terry now lets it cascade off her
shoulders and she has an endorsement for hair-care products that
enables her to train fulltime. She has also mended the broken ties
to her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``She changed Alison's life,'' said Debra Terry, a budget
officer for the San Diego Lifeguard Service and a community
activist who had taken her daughter to anti-apartheid rallies as a
girl but who admittedly had not fully recognized her identity
struggles later on. ``Sometimes it takes the right person saying
the right thing at the right time. From black history classes, she
learned about her ancestry, which gave her better perspective and
pride and some justifiable anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Alison began to embrace her black heritage and, along with her
mother and others, she began to develop swimming programs at San
Diego's inner-city high schools, to recruit members of minority
groups as lifeguards, to teach beach safety at elementary schools
and to assist in learn-to-swim courses. This year, San Diego has
agreed for the first time to keep inner-city pools open year-round,
Terry said. These are small victories in a much larger battle that
she believes should be waged against a lack of facilities,
insufficient programs, a lack of interest and discouragement that
linger from the days of segregation and persistent racial myths
that blacks somehow lack the physical capabilities to be good
swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't give the kids a chance to participate, you'll
never know how much talent is out there,'' Terry told the officials
at Lincoln High in San Diego as she encouraged them to start a
swimming program, which they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really important to have a black swimmer on the
Olympic team,'' Terry said. ``That inspires me, to be in a position
to be a role model for a lot of kids that just don't see swimmers
every day, or don't see the sport as being a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, inspired by coaching high school swimmers, she
realized that if she was encouraging them to pursue their own
passions, she should pursue hers as well. She began swimming again,
with the idea of making the 2000 Olympic team in Sydney, Australia.
Only two Americans will qualify in the open 100-meter freestyle,
but the top six finishers at the trials will qualify for Olympic
relays. An outside chance is a chance worth taking for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have that perfect race inside me,'' Terry said. ``I
believe in myself. That's the No. 1 thing, believing you are going
to be there. If you have any doubts, forget it. I'm not doubting
myself. I did for way too long. And I'm not anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
