<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4590 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CRUISE-CHEMICALS-HNS &LR;      07-06 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-CHEMICALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CRUISE LINE ACCUSED OF DUMPING IN SAN FRANCISCO BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Royal Caribbean Cruises ship returning from an
11-day Alaska voyage last September dumped chemicals into the San
Francisco Bay so noxious that they chased away the sea lions,
according to a Las Vegas couple who were passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Only two months earlier in July, Royal Caribbean agreed to pay
$18 million after pleading guilty to dumping oil and hazardous
chemicals from nine ships into U.S. coastal waters.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, prompted by the new charges by Alan and Maxine
Silver of Las Vegas, environmentalists began legal proceedings to
sue Royal Caribbean under the federal Clean Water Act.
</P>
<P>
   Earthjustice Legal Defense Fund, representing the Bluewater
Network in San Francisco, sent a letter of intent to file a
lawsuit. The 60-day notification period gives government regulators
an opportunity to act, if they wish.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentalists also sent the Silvers' allegations to
Kimberly Brandon, president of the San Francisco Port Commission.
The group asked the commission to enforce violations of the San
Francisco Municipal Code and state codes relating to resources,
fish and game, and harbors and navigation.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sheehan, a spokesman for Royal Caribbean, a Liberian
corporation based in Miami, said the company ``flatly denies all
allegations by the Bluewater Network that its ship, Mercury,
discharged illegally and/or polluted San Francisco's harbor in any
way on Sept. 21, 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan said Royal Caribbean's Celebrity Cruises, which operates
the Mercury, maintains ``a strict no-discharge policy for all of
its operations within 3 miles of shore, including while its ships
are in port.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``the ship's operations are recorded and verified
in a series of logs, maintained and reviewed by an environmental
officer on board the ship. These records were reviewed earlier this
year by an independent, external environmental auditing firm, with
no irregularly being found.''
</P>
<P>
   But one environmentalist disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous that a company with so many felony convictions
for illegal dumping thinks it can continue this activity in the San
Francisco Bay,'' said Russell Long, executive director of Bluewater
Network, a project of the San Francisco-based Earth Island
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Silvers, on Sept 21 the Mercury docked at San
Francisco's Pier 35. As the passengers disembarked, the Silvers
stayed on their veranda watching sea lions playing nearby. They
smelled a strong, noxious chemical odor emanating from below, they
said in a written account to Bluewater Network.
</P>
<P>
   They looked down at the water and saw the source - a white,
frothy liquid being discharged from the ship, accompanied by a
rainbow sheen of an oil slick, they said. The discharge continued
for 30 minutes or more and was so caustic that the sea lions
scattered, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The Silvers say the chemicals smelled like perchloroethylene, a
solvent used by the ship's on-board dry cleaning operation.
</P>
<P>
   Incensed by what they saw, they photographed it. They called
governmental environmental agencies, and when they couldn't get a
satisfactory response, they called Bluewater Network.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations came two months after Royal Caribbean settled
criminal charges against it by paying the $18 million fine. Royal
Caribbean pleaded guilty to 21 felonies, six of which were for
illegally discharging perchloroethylene at several U.S. ports. The
other felonies had to do with routine illegal dumping of oil and
lying to government officials.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Jack Williams, president of Royal Caribbean
International, another company owned by Royal Caribbean Cruises
Ltd., signed a statement admitting to dumping by the Song of
America ship in New York harbor. Every week in the summer and fall
of 1994 and 1995, he said, the ship drained about 50 gallons of
photo lab chemicals, including toxic silver. Once a month, the ship
dumped 20 gallons from the dry cleaning shop, including
perchloroethylene.
</P>
<P>
   While discharging certain toxic chemicals in ports is clearly
illegal, environmentalists are at odds with state and federal
governments over regulation of a whole range of wastewater. Many
regulations offer exemptions to ships that aren't available to land
sources.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Bluewater Network asked the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency to reconsider these exemptions and enforce the
Clean Water Act as strictly for ships as for factories and public
water treatment systems.
</P>
<P>
   The group argued that ships were ``floating cities, no different
from any municipality that has numerous streams of pollution
including sewage, hazardous waste, garbage and gray water.''
</P>
<P>
   The California Legislature is considering a bill that would
require cruise ships to report monthly discharges to the state
Water Resources Control Board, which would release the findings in
three years. The bill was passed by the Assembly and goes to the
Senate Environmental Quality Committee for a hearing in August.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise line industry opposes the bill, saying monitoring
would be expensive, burdensome and unnecessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
