<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DECLINE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DECLINE OF WESTERN CIVILIZATION, PART III': MINOR BUT
TELLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I wasn't born yet,'' says Why-me, the first interview subject
of ``The Decline of Western Civilization, Part III,'' Penelope
Spheeris' latest installment in her documentary series on the
social trajectory of the Los Angeles punk scene.
</P>
<P>
   In the first ``Decline'' (1981), the curdled fomentation of punk
was young and looming. In the second (1988), she spun nasty jokes
on rock 'n' roll, and in this third episode, which is minor but
telling, the movement has become an institution. Many of the young
punks interviewed _ many in their teens, like Why-me _ are
inheritors of a movement that existed before they did and has
calcified into what can only be called ritualized anarchic
behavior. One of them, caught in a crowd scene, says, ``I know a
guy that can suck an Icee through his nose,'' and seconds later, we
see it.
</P>
<P>
   The grand old punk Keith Morris, once part of the most ferocious
Los Angeles punk band, Black Flag (which was a big part of the
first ``Decline''), notes the prevalence of punk nowadays. ``There
was a lot of energy and a lot of anger,'' he observes. ``It wasn't
like it is today, where you could go out on any corner and see punk
rock people.''
</P>
<P>
   Those current punk youths are what the film calls gutterpunks,
who inhabit the streets of Hollywood looking for handouts to live
on. When asking for money, one of the spike-haired panhandlers
says, ``I swear I won't waste it on food.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an air of resignation about punk today. Pain is still a
constant, and it is bewildering to hear the punkers, with piercings
through the bridge of the nose, talk about being beaten by two
types of skinheads, the Nazis and the anti-hate punks, who also
travel in gangs. The anti-hate punks call themselves SHARP _
Skinheads Against Racial Prejudice _ and they practice their own
brand of oppression. Ezzat Soliman talks about the only condition
for admission at the club he owns: no politics. (He also talks
about the kind of music he plays at home. ``I listen to Frank
Sinatra, Tony Bennett, Louis Armstrong,'' he says with a laugh.)
</P>
<P>
   Spheeris often places her interview subjects in front of a gray
wall, with a single light bulb to illuminate the camera setup. One
wishes she had pulled away a bit because in some instances
``Decline'' comes off as the essay of a punk mom worried about her
charges, babyfaces with Mohawks and tattoos that make them look
like Maoris. That feeling also gives the movie a full-on sadness
not found in the previous chapters, and her curiosity and maternal
instinct mitigate some of the plus ca change resonance, especially
since there is less of a community this time around. The little
punkers are mostly loners who don't fit in.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd to see such feelings of naked aggression setting off a
wave of nostalgia. Naked Aggression also happens to be the name of
one of the bands, and its members are interviewed. They are trained
musicians _ one is shown playing classical guitar; the vocalist
noodles on a French horn _ and they are trapped in a paradox. They
talk about the exploitation of punk bands at the hands of indie
labels, which is actually more pronounced than they would receive
from a major recording label. Yet if the bands signed to a major
label, their fans would ignore them. ``That's the irony of it
all,'' one responds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decline'' is best and most touching when it shows how willing
punk is to eat its young. The anecdotes build momentum and power.
``It certainly hasn't gotten more beautiful,'' Morris muses,
matter-of-factly, ``but the punk rock thing was never a beautiful
thing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE DECLINE OF WESTERN CIVILIZATION, Part III'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Penelope Spheeris; director of photography, Jamie
Thompson; edited by Ann Trulove; score by Phil Suchomel; produced
by Scott Wilder; released by Abbey Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   With: Why-me, Keith Morris and Ezzat Soliman, with performances
by Final Conflict, Litmus Green, Naked Aggression and the
Resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 88 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
