<HEADLINE>
A RISK FOR PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton took a risk worth taking when he invited
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat to Camp David next week for intensive negotiations on the
crucial issues standing in the way of a framework peace accord
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation is a gamble because, after years of dialogue and
negotiation, the Palestinian and Israeli positions on the issues _
borders, Jerusalem, refugees, and settlements _ remain so far apart
that it is hard for each side to imagine making the compromises a
final-status agreement will require.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few days, distinguished Israeli and Palestinian
voices have warned their leaders against the very compromises that
Clinton is gambling he can persuade Barak and Arafat to make.
Israel's interior minister, Natan Sharansky, said he would resign
because Barak would have to concede too much at a Camp David
summit.
</P>
<P>
   A group of eminent Palestinians _ including the human rights
campaigner Hanan Ashrawi, former Palestinian negotiator Haidar
Abdul Shafi, and Dr. Eyad Sarraj, the child psychiatrist who has
been jailed by Israel and by Arafat's security forces _ signed a
statement calling for ``a final and just settlement, guaranteeing
the right of return and self-determination in a Palestinian
sovereign and independent state with Jerusalem as its capital in
the territories occupied after the fourth of June, 1976 . . .''
</P>
<P>
   These positions have tremendous emotional force among
Palestinians, emanating from a communal narrative about their
history of displacement, deception, and suffering since 1948. There
are also Israelis within their nation's mainstream who approach
these same issues with a fear that even partial concessions to the
Palestinians will expose Israel to intolerable existential threats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was alluding to such apprehensions when he spoke
Wednesday of how both parties harbor ``intense fears and emotions
and a deep-seated commitment to defend their people's interests.''
Nonetheless, Clinton has done the right thing in summoning Barak
and Arafat to make the ``historic decisions'' that only they can
make and probably only he can cajole them into making.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
