<HEADLINE>
GIVE A PINT, HELP YOUR HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best reason for donating blood always was and always will be
that it can help save a life. But in recent years evidence has
mounted that, for adult males at least, there might be a side
benefit as well: The gift of blood appears to reduce the risk of
heart disease in the donor.
</P>
<P>
   That likely extra benefit was mentioned in a TV interview last
week by Dr. Harvey Klein, chief of the Department of Transfusion
Medicine of the National Institutes of Health. He pointed to a
comprehensive study of this done in Finland under the auspices of
the University of Kuopio and reported in the American Journal of
Epidemiology.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers followed 2,862 men aged 42 to 60 for an average of
nine years. Of the men in the group who donated blood in the two
years before the study began, just 0.7 percent had a heart attack.
Of the nondonors, 12.5 percent did. The researchers knew that
donors tend to be in better overall health than nondonors, so they
controlled for the risk factors that would vary between the two
groups and still found that donors had an 88 percent reduced risk.
</P>
<P>
   The most commonly accepted theory explaining this is that
donating blood periodically does for men what monthly menstruation
does for women _ it gets rid of excess iron, a suspected risk
factor for heart attacks. After menopause, women's heart attack
rates resemble men's.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory is that the heart benefits because occasional
blood donations spur bone marrow to produce new red blood cells,
which are more flexible than old ones and deliver oxygen better. Of
course, it may be that both phenomena are at work or that other
factors are involved. It is also possible that women benefit from
donating _ it is hard to pin down because heart disease among
pre-menopausal women is so rare.
</P>
<P>
   Blood supplies across the country are perilously low these days
for a number of reasons, including a rise in utilization, which
Klein said may be linked to more frequent surgery in an aging
population. Still, organizations that collect blood are cautious in
describing the secondary benefits of donation _ they are afraid
would-be donors offering their blood strictly for the heart-disease
benefit might lie about aspects of their medical history that would
disqualify them. But the important word is ``strictly.'' If a
healthy but slightly lazy or needle-phobic individual gets an extra
push into a donor center because he wants to do his heart a favor,
that is a benefit to all of us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0158 </DOCNO>
