<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FRANCAIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH REASONING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is something spectacularly idiosyncratic about France's
refusal to join 107 other countries in signing a document called
the Warsaw Declaration _ a statement of principles meant to unite
diverse nations in a community of democracies.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, where nonconformism boasts a long and honored
history, it should be possible to admire the courage to stand alone
displayed by France's foreign minister, Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
   The bemusing aspect of the French decision to stand apart from
the other 107 democracies last week, however, is less the
theatrical gesture made by Paris than the reasons given for making
it.
</P>
<P>
   Other statesmen and stateswomen gathered in the chamber of the
Polish parliament spoke of their declaration on the universal
principles of democracy as a text they hoped would have the same
potent effect as the 1975 Helsinki Accords enshrining human rights
as an entitlement of all human beings under all political regimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the United Nations can truly call itself a community of
democracies,'' UN Secretary General Kofi Annan told the conferees,
``the charter's noble ideals of protecting human rights and
promoting `social progress in larger freedoms' will have been
brought much closer.''
</P>
<P>
   But France, rejecting this vision of democracy triumphant, gave
reasons that reason itself would hardly recognize. The French
ambassador to Poland, Benoit d'Aboville, warned against the
creation at the UN of a new, exclusive bloc of democratic states,
one that recapitulates the global divisions of the Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
   Vedrine lectured the 107 countries that failed to follow the
lead of France. ``In Western countries,'' he said, ``the thinking
is that democracy is like religion, and all you have to do is
convert people.'' As an example, he cited America's failure to
convert Saddam Hussein. Sigmund Freud, who has been enjoying a
revival in France, might theorize that French leaders feel a trifle
guilty about their continuing collaboration with the unconverted
Saddam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
