<SLUG> BC-SMOKER-DEATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FORMER SMOKER WHO WON $21.7 MILLION FROM TOBACCO FIRMS DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Leslie Whiteley, a former smoker who received
$21.7 million in damages from a San Francisco jury against the
nation's two largest tobacco
</P>
<P>
   companies in March, has died of cancer at age 40.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whiteley, of Ojai in Ventura County, died Monday in a
Ventura hospital, her attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's verdict was the first in the nation in favor of a
smoker who
</P>
<P>
   took up the habit after 1965, when the federal government first
required
</P>
<P>
   warning labels on cigarette packages. The companies, Philip
Morris and
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds, plan to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whiteley testified that she had started smoking in 1972 at
age 13, using her lunch money to buy cigarettes. She said she had
paid little attention to the warning labels because tobacco
companies promoted the benefits of cigarettes and the government
permitted their sale.
</P>
<P>
   She smoked Marlboros and Camel Lights, averaging two packs a
day, until she quit in 1998, shortly before being diagnosed with
lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco companies attributed Mrs. Whiteley's illness to her
voluntary choice to smoke, despite the warnings, and to her
admitted use of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   But after reviewing internal industry documents, the jury, in a
9-3 verdict, found that the companies were to blame because they
designed cigarettes negligently, then made false or misleading
statements to the public and concealed information about the
dangers of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors awarded Mrs. Whiteley and her husband $1.7 million for
pain and suffering and medical costs, and awarded $10 million in
punitive damages against each company. Superior Court Judge John
Munter upheld the verdict and denied the companies' request for
reduced damages or a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leslie was the unfortunate victim of the tobacco companies'
intentional targeting of children with their addictive and deadly
products,'' said her attorney, Madelyn Chaber.
</P>
<P>
   She said Mrs. Whiteley's estate was entitled to the same damages
she would have received. If a plaintiff dies before the trial ends,
her heirs cannot seek damages for her pain and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Another San Francisco jury awarded $51 million last year to a
former smoker in a suit against Philip Morris. Munter, who also
presided over that trial, cut the damages in half. The company is
appealing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0160 </DOCNO>
