<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PLAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST PLAIN ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest dispatch from the can't-leave-well-enough-alone front
is the news that ``plain'' M&AMP;Ms will now be called ``milk
chocolate'' M&AMP;Ms. M&AMP;M/Mars is spending $10 million on this name
change because, a spokesman said, ``for a long, long time, our
chocolate has been too good to be called plain.''
</P>
<P>
   The long, long time has been 46 years. In 1954, the basic
chocolate-covered treat, which had been called ``plain chocolate
candies'' since coming on the market in 1941, was switched just to
``plain'' as the peanut version was being introduced.
</P>
<P>
   The company made the switch to ``milk chocolate'' just before
the Fourth of July, when our nation honors its democratic roots. As
the M&AMP;M case illustrates, we may lack a titled aristocracy in this
country, but we throw the verbal equivalents of baronies around
with abandon when we think we can make a buck by gussying up a
workaday product. Vanilla ice cream becomes ``French vanilla.''
Realtors turn porches into ``verandas.'' Used cars are
``pre-owned.''
</P>
<P>
   Something there is in salesmen that can't abide the ordinary.
M&AMP;M spokesman Michael Tolkowsky says calling the candies plain
``never really fit the eating experience of M&AMP;Ms,'' as though that
dreaded word was ever supposed to signal to buyers anything other
than the fact that they weren't getting any of the nutty M&AMP;Ms.
</P>
<P>
   There are, happily, refuges of the generic, including hardware
and building supply stores. To the horror of the Michael Tolkowskys
of the world, such stores stock common nails, No. 2 pine,
carpenter's glue, and flat paint. One suspects that the word
``common'' fits the hammering experiences of carpenters just fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
