<HEADLINE>
`LONGITUDE' IS SPLENDID, JUST LONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: A-  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The coldly cynical will see A&AMP;E's decision to air ``Longitude''
in a four-hour block as a crass attempt to persuade the bum-weary
masses to order the film from A&AMP;E Home Video ($59.95, plus shipping
and handling) instead of sitting in front of the television from 8
to midnight Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But if A&AMP;E makes a little money on video orders for
``Longitude,'' who am I to complain? Especially if they pour the
money into other productions of such elegance and splendor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Longitude'' would work better as a two-night presentation. But
A&AMP;E will rebroadcast the film at least four times, making a split
viewing quite possible for the VCR-challenged.
</P>
<P>
   John Harrison and Rupert Gould would have had no trouble
programming VCRs. Harrison, a carpenter born in 1693, was the sort
of self-educated genius who could see possibilities where others
see only problems. Gould, born almost 200 years later, was an
emotionally unstable intellectual with a knack for explaining
complex and abstract concepts in simple terms.
</P>
<P>
   In Dava Sobel's celebrated book ``Longitude,'' on which the film
is based, Gould is an extremely minor player. But director Charles
Sturridge wisely elected to place Gould's contemporary story in
parallel with Harrison's all-consuming effort to solve the great
scientific riddle of his time: how to to determine one's position
at sea.
</P>
<P>
   It was a life-and-death problem equivalent to the modern
challenge of making space travel safe, and most seafaring countries
of the time offered prizes to anyone who could come up with a
reliable way of allowing a sea captain to know precisely where he
was when he was on the bounding main.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gambon is magnificent as Harrison, the unsophisticated
but brilliant carpenter who created a succession of
weather-resistant, motion-proof clocks, each smaller than its
predecessor, to solve the navigational conundrum. A roiling mixture
of ambition, emotion and determination, Gambon's Harrison is easy
to root for when stacked mercilessly against a roomful of stuffy
astronomers and admirals who controlled Britain's Longitude Prize,
equal today to millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Gould isn't as easy to cheer, but he is no less fascinating in
Sturridge's film. A man whose obsession with restoring Harrison's
clocks ruined his marriage and his health, Gould is played with icy
intensity by Jeremy Irons, who is careful never to upstage Gambon
as the parallel stories move back and forth between 18th and 20th
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Though the film is fairly light on the scientific aspects of the
story, it manages to convey the importance of the quest to
calculate longitude precisely. An almost endless parade of
Englishmen in powdered wigs makes it tough to keep track of certain
characters, but ``Longitude'' remains a triumph of filmmaking that
would play as well on the big screen as on a small one.
</P>
<P>
   Longitude. Four-hour movie about an 18th-century man's attempt
to solve the problem of determining one's position at sea, and a
20th-century man's attempt to bring his achievement to light.
Starring Michael Gambon and Jeremy Irons. Sunday at 8 p.m., A&AMP;E.
Repeating July 13, 8 p.m.; July 15, 1 and 8 p.m., July 16, 3 p.m.
Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
