<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ There is a go-for-broke quality to
the Israeli and American approach to the coming Camp David peace
summit, which starts Tuesday with the stated goal of ending a
52-year-old blood-steeped conflict. But for the Palestinians, whose
participation is more reluctant, there is at best an aspiration
that the three-way, retreat-style meeting will serve as a stop-gap
measure to keep alive the stalemated peace process so that a
partial deal can be achieved by September. A news analysis by
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S.-MILITARY (Tokyo) _ The top U.S. military official in
Okinawa made an unprecedented apology Thursday for an incident on
Monday in which an American Marine was accused of entering a
private residence on the Japanese southern island and sexually
molesting a 14-year-old girl. The display of remorse, which
included a bow of Japanese contrition, was the first time that a
senior U.S. military official had made such an apology, government
officials said. And it came after numerous accusations in recent
years that U.S. soldiers stationed in Okinawa had been involved in
cases of violence and sexual misconduct. The general's apology was
seen as an effort to smooth relations with the people of Okinawa,
who have held angry rallies and protests over the incident in
recent days, just as island officials prepare for a July 21-23
summit meeting of world leaders that President Clinton is scheduled
to attend. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-NAZI-LABOR (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The German parliament
approved legislation Thursday that will govern a $5 billion
humanitarian fund for Nazi-era slave workers and other victims of
the Holocaust. The measure, passed by an overwhelming majority of
556-42, is intended to bring legal closure on the most brutal
chapter in German history. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
