   GORE (Chicago) _ Asking repeatedly ``whose side are you on,''
Vice President Al Gore on Thursday drew a sharp contrast between
his proposals for Medicare and those of Gov. George W. Bush, and he
branded his Republican opponent as the candidate of powerful
industries. Gore lectured with charts and bar graphs at a suburban
senior citizens center, seeking to put a debate over the popular
Great Society health insurance program for the elderly at the
forefront of the presidential agenda. By Alison Mitchell.
