<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4610 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CHEAPTRICK-COX     07-06 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEAPTRICK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ron Rollins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - If nothing else, the band may have the coolest
logo in rock 'n' roll history: that double-struck,
bleeding-typeface that has been with Cheap Trick since its 1977
debut album.
</P>
<P>
   There is more to the band than only that, of course, which is
why Cheap Trick has been kicking around on stages and in studios
pretty much nonstop since that first record.
</P>
<P>
   But even after two more albums, those of us who live outside the
immediate Chicago-Rockford, Ill., region that was the band's home
didn't know much about the power-pop quartet until a few years
later. In 1979, it released ``Live at Budokan'' _ which went down
as Cheap Trick's biggest and best album and which may well be one
of the two or three best live rock albums ever.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those rare records that nailed a good band on a
great night, when all cylinders were firing and when the crowd was
in sync with the action onstage. Cheap Trick had caught on in Japan
before it caught on here. After this record, the States were on
board. ``Budokan'' went multiplatinum and introduced many Americans
to an unusual-seeming cast of musical characters.
</P>
<P>
   Out front were the handsome ones, singer Robin Zander and
bassist Tom Petersson, both of whom made the girls swoon. Behind
them was Bun E. Carlos, the mustachioed, pudgy drummer who looked a
bit like your band teacher on a smoke break. Off to the side was
Rick Nielsen, who wore funny little ballcaps and checkered
cardigans, played half a dozen guitars all slung around his neck at
once and never seemed able to stand still.
</P>
<P>
   The odd quartet broke out of the late-'70s cookie-cutter
hard-rock image and backed it up with hard, hooky, power pop driven
by huge, crunchy rhythms, brick-wall guitar riffs and Zander's
silvery voice. Between Nielsen's off-center lyrics (does anybody
know exactly what ``Surrender'' is about?) and well-chosen,
spiffed-up covers (''Ain't That a Shame,'' etc.), the band enjoyed
a good ride.
</P>
<P>
   It never soared quite as high again, though it scored hits from
1980's ``Dream Police'' and with ``The Flame,'' included on a '91
best-of disc. Changing labels and producers through the years, the
quartet has never stopped working, though _ and, except for a
seven-year break by Petersson, it has kept the original group
together through commercial highs and lows.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the highs, incidentally, have had to do (again) with
Budokan. ``Budokan II,'' with extra cuts from the original show,
came out in 1993, and a remastered combination of both discs came
out in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Courthouse Square probably won't be jammed with thousands of
screaming Japanese teen-agers tonight when Cheap Trick brings its
once-upon-a-time-hysteria-inducing show to Dayton for Fox Rox the
Square. But then, you never know.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
