<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARGARET CHO'S FILM PROVES HER METTLE AS A COMIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B+  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Korean American comedian Margaret Cho made headlines in 1994 by
jumping from a successful stand-up career to fronting America's
first Asian-cast sitcom ``All-American Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   After a solid launch, the show's numbers slipped and a frantic
network tried to redefine the show (``It's too Asian ... no, it's
not Asian enough'').
</P>
<P>
   Cho hit the depths of depression when it was canceled in its
first season. She sank into alcohol and drug addiction before she
pulled herself out of the pit of self-pity and turned her harrowing
experiences into a scathing stand-up act turned one-woman show,
something akin to Julia Sweeney's ``God Said Ha!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the One That I Want'' is a kind of comic healing, a
hilarious yet pointed self-affirmation. The backbone of the show is
her nightmarish experiences with television and her harrowing
efforts to conform to the network's definitions of their ideal
all-American girl _ including launching into a crash diet and
exercise program that came close to killing her _ while denying her
own identity.
</P>
<P>
   It creates a narrative through-line for the act, but the show is
fleshed out with her experiences growing up in San Francisco
``raised by drag queens'' and her trademark impressions of her Old
World, but unexpectedly hip Korean mother.
</P>
<P>
   Lionel Coleman respectfully preserves this triumphant hometown
performance of her 1999 show. Comedy concert films are tricky
things to get right; they rely on delivery, pacing, often subtle
body language, and a responsive crowd, yet they need to play to a
theater audience. Coleman smartly gives us an intimate and up-close
look at Cho's show and keeps the cameras trained on her. We don't
need an audience reaction shot to know she's funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the One That I Want'' is at its best when her rhythm
carries the film, and Coleman's technique is invisible. Only rarely
does he get in the way, such as a few lovely but unmotivated
gliding moves that draw the camera out to long shot. It's pretty
but works against her timing.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the film seamlessly captures the arc of her stories
and her easy connection with the audience. Her liberal use of
profane language doesn't seem at all shocking in this context and
her comic insights are delightfully affirming, a celebration of
difference that skewers stereotypes of all kinds. Her act has
earned her a loyal gay following (``Fag hags are the backbone of
the gay community!'' she deadpans to her appreciative San Francisco
audience) but her humor is universal. ``I'm the One That I Want''
is the funniest thing I've seen this summer.
</P>
<P>
   I'm the One That I Want. Directed by Lionel Coleman. Written by
Margaret Cho. Cast: Cho. Cho Taussig Productions. 96 minutes. No
rating, contains offensive language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
