<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-KID-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KID' PLAYS TO THE HEART BUT THE TUNE IS A TIRED ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C-  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the summer of 1999, Bruce Willis played on the softer side of
his persona for a story about love, loss and acceptance. ``The
Sixth Sense'' came out of nowhere and both thrilled and moved
audiences used to slam-bang action and funhouse horror roller
coasters, and Willis delivered one of the quietest performances of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect a return engagement in 2000. Willis retunes the
heartstrings for Walt Disney's ``The Kid,'' a cloying family comedy
as distinctive as a TV movie, but this time he's off-key.
</P>
<P>
   He plays a boorish workaholic image consultant who gives his
advice with a sarcastic sneer. Willis does such a good job playing
an arrogant, insolent jerk that he's instantly unlikable, only
barely funny, and hardly worth saving.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow he has earned the loyalty of a small but faithful staff.
Sardonic secretary Lily Tomlin puts up with his mercenary nature
with a steady stream of retorts, and his perky assistant Emily
Mortimer (``Love's Labour's Lost''), a smart little British cookie,
keeps the idea of romance alive for no apparent reason.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's another chapter in Hollywood's unending saga, ``Smart,
sensitive women who stay with complete jerks hoping they'll
change.'' This being Hollywood, he does.
</P>
<P>
   A time warp twist on ``A Christmas Carol'' delivers Willis his
own Jacob Marley: a nerdish, clumsy kid with unlimited affection
who turns out to be himself at age 8. Spencer Breslin, who plays
the kid, is reminiscent of Charlie Talbert from ``Angus,'' a
fumbling but well-meaning adolescent just trying to find his way in
the world with all the dignity he can muster, but all Willis can
see is the echo of a miserable childhood he's drummed out of his
memory.
</P>
<P>
   Will he succeed in turning his mini-me into a hardened, no-fun
workaholic, or will the little guy melt the big guy's heart and
heal his emotional scars?
</P>
<P>
   Willis can do this part in his sleep and at times he does,
falling back on familiar smirking retorts and lazy saccharine
versions of soulful sincerity. To be fair, he's not given much help
by Audrey Wells' (``The Truth About Cats and Dogs'') utterly bland
script or Jon Turteltaub's (``Instinct,'' ``Phenomenon'') vague,
generic direction, which manufactures its sense of wonder with
orchestral flourishes and swooping camerawork.
</P>
<P>
   The time-travel fantasy is the least of their worries: Willis
and Breslin are stuck in a charmless, predictable picture they
can't escape.
</P>
<P>
   The Kid. Directed by Jon Turteltaub. Written by Audrey Wells.
Cast: Bruce Willis, Spencer Breslin, Emily Mortimer, Lily Tomlin,
Chi McBride, Jean Smart. Walt Disney Pictures. 101 minutes. Rated
PG for mild language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
