<SLUG> BC-TRENDS-NEXTGEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT GEN INTERNET SHOPPERS LOAD UP 
</HEADLINE>
  EDITORS: Subs to change wording in first sentence of second
paragraph. It should read: ``teens and twentysomethings.''  
 (For release July 5, 2000.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's TRENDS-NEXTGEN column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of TRENDS-NEXTGEN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shopping on the Internet. People talk about it, but are they
really doing it? Or are these shoppers like Internet millionaires _
people we've heard about but don't really know.
</P>
<P>
   We recently asked groups of teens and twentysomethings if _ and
where _ they were shopping. Most tend to browse rather than buy,
others browse and then head to the old brick-and-mortar for the
deal, but a few revealed some of their favorite sites for shopping.
And while we can't guarantee the sites will last forever (little
does on the Web), here's a good start if you're up at 2 a.m. and
desperate to spend.
</P>
<P>
   REFLECT.COM
</P>
<P>
   One of the things our respondents claim to like the most about
the Internet is its ability to allow them to customize products to
feel more special. Reflect.com lets surfers select ingredients to
make shampoos, cleansers and other body products. On top of that,
they can name the product after themselves _ or someone else.
That's one way to make sure that your medicine chest is unique!
</P>
<P>
   PURPLESKIRT.COM
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has watched Tracey Ullman's comedy routines might
question her fashion sense. But clearly she was acting. This
somewhat limited site offers some of the coolest fashion trends at
reasonable prices. The picks tend to be on the cutting edge,
offering even the funniest fashionista a chance to upgrade her
look.
</P>
<P>
   THEHOMEBISTRO.COM
</P>
<P>
   We've been hearing a great deal about the trend toward cooking
at home. Xers who grew up on microwave feasts and fast food are
returning to the kitchen in droves. The one catch _ they don't know
how to cook! And while some are content to learn as they go, others
are looking for short cuts. Enter Thehomebistro.com. This site
offers pre-prepared meals, with ingredients, cut, measured and
bagged so that the recipient has only to follow some simple
directions and whip up a masterpiece. Thehomebistro.com also allows
you to select the number of portions, avoiding that ever-present
fear of running out, or (even worse), having leftovers that last a
week.
</P>
<P>
   CNET.COM
</P>
<P>
   According to our respondents, the Web can be just that _ a maze
of choices that snag and snare. When it comes to electronics at
least, Cnet.com untangles the mess. This site provides its own _
and customers' _ ratings on electronics, comparing at least 10
stores on price, availability and shipping. While it won't
guarantee that you'll know how to use what you purchase, at least
you'll feel like a smart shopper.
</P>
<P>
   NETAPORTER.COM
</P>
<P>
   Did we say shop? We meant lust. This site is one of the most
fashion-forward sites around, with high-end brands like Jimmy Choo,
Vanessa Bruno and Anya Hindmarch. In addition, netaporter.com,
which is headquartered in London, assembles some of the hottest
European brands. What makes this site so appealing is its magazine
approach. Photos feature put-together outfits that entice the
viewer to click further. Be warned, though, prices are in British
pounds, so you might want to visit oanda.com first to exchange
currency.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINESCLOSET.COM
</P>
<P>
   For our respondents who love the look of vintage clothing but
hate sorting through the remnant bins, this site offers some of the
coolest classics around. From Pucci to Pulitzer, Sergio Valente to
sneakers from the 1970s, this site has all the stuff you wish you
hadn't let your mother throw out. Each piece is rated, reasonably
priced and ready to take you back.
</P>
<P>
   ALLOY.COM
</P>
<P>
   What started as a teen catalog has morphed into a teen community
center. But what smart shoppers have discovered is the site's
auction area where everything from beanie babies to action figures
to hard-to-get Pokemon cards can be found. Alloy.com feels like a
less intimidating E-bay, where you won't get carried away with the
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   LUXURYFINDER.COM
</P>
<P>
   This site should be used only in emergencies _ like when you
forgot your dad's 60th or your partner's passing the bar. This
amalgamation of high-end products assembles the best of the best.
From Porthault sheets to more moderately priced Frederic Fekkai
hair-care products, you'll know you're buying the top of the line.
And for those pesky times when you find yourself in immediate need
of your own personal jet, look no further.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPASSURED.COM
</P>
<P>
   Before you shop anywhere, check out this site that warns you
when you've entered a site with a bad reputation. It's a free
plug-in; it won't have info on every site, but since the Web will
be won by word of mouth, this is a resource you should take the
time to install.
</P>
<P>
   BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR:
</P>
<P>
   Technomarine watches
</P>
<P>
   Lambertson truex handbags
</P>
<P>
   Lipgloss kits
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on
CENTERPIECE and other features. &QL;
</P>
