u a BC-COLO-GOD-TRUST-NYT &LR;      07-06 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-GOD-TRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO BOARD RECOMMENDS THAT SCHOOLS DISPLAY `IN GOD WE TRUST' 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Asserting that public schools have a duty to teach
moral rectitude, the Colorado State Board of Education on Thursday
passed a resolution that encourages schools to display the national
motto, ``In God we trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the measure passed with five Republicans on the board
voting in favor and the lone Democrat dissenting, supporters
insisted that the motto reflects a founding principle of the
country, not any religion, and, therefore, does not blur the
constitutional line separating church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation has lost its way on the road to virtue and moral
character,'' said Clair Orr, the board chairman and sponsor of the
resolution, who characterized the motto as no less sacred than
words he quoted from the Declaration of Independence, Lincoln's
Gettysburg Address and the pledge to the flag. ``We have a moral
obligation to educate our children in the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   As the only opponent to the resolution, Gully Stanford, said he
agreed with the majority's view that ``In God we trust,''
introduced on currency in 1864 and made the national motto in 1956,
conveys the vision of a country founded on Judeo-Christian values.
</P>
<P>
   But in an increasingly diverse society that includes followers
of other religions, as well as nonbelievers, he said the resolution
is insensitive, divisive, distracting and ill-timed in light of the
recent Supreme Court decision that affirmed the unconstitutional
nature of student-led prayers at high school football games..
</P>
<P>
   The resolution may not be intended as ideological, he told his
colleagues, ``but it will be interpreted that way at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford also said that the values embraced by the national
motto, religious or otherwise, can be taught just as effectively
and more appropriately in history and civics classes.
</P>
<P>
   The board heard no public comments before the vote. Lynn M.
Fontanier, a spokeswoman for the board, said the public had several
months to submit comments and only two opponents emerged. She said
the board received arguments against the measure from Robert R.
Tiernan, a Denver lawyer who has been involved in several federal
lawsuits challenging the constitutionality of the motto's use on
currency, and the Mountain States chapter of the Anti-Defamation
League of B'nai B'rith, which characterized the resolution as
unconstitutional, insensitive and exclusionary.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Armstrong, executive director of the Denver office of the
American Civil Liberties Union, who attended Thursday's meeting,
said she had been unaware that the board had scheduled a period for
public comment. Speaking to reporters after the vote, she echoed
many of Stanford's concerns and questioned the constitutionality of
the measure, saying, ``Each argument they made was a religious
argument that reflected a strong religious bias.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry W. Lynn, executive director of Americans United for
Separation of Church and State, a Washington-based organization,
agreed, accusing the board of ``trying to meddle in the religious
lives of young children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no business doing that and should, in fact, just
butt out,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1708EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4631 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-BROTHER-REVIEW-NYT     07-06 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BROTHER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: `BIG BROTHER' PROFFERS HOURS OF GUILT-FREE
SNOOPING
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CBS-BIG-BROTHER, being filed in category ``f'')  
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was in college my boyfriend and I were baby-sitting for a
neighbor and had just put the children to bed. We were both
reporters for the campus newspaper and somehow decided our right to
know extended to the private papers on the desk of the people who
had trusted us to watch their children.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes we hit pay dirt: a letter from the husband to his
wife, confessing adultery after she had found incriminating hotel
bills.
</P>
<P>
   But our successful snooping didn't feel rewarding or even
titillating. Instead we felt ashamed. We tried to arrange the
papers exactly as we'd found them and hoped our employers didn't
see the guilty look in our eyes as we rushed out the door at the
evening's end.
</P>
<P>
   That's the seamy beauty of CBS's ``Big Brother'': voyeurism
without guilt. We've all been invited to peep at 10 people who have
volunteered to live together nonstop for three months, under
constant surveillance by 28 cameras and 60 microphones. Not only
must they endure one another, they must live without many creature
comforts (dishwashers, clothes dryers) and without contact with the
outside world (no computers, television, telephone or newspapers).
They can swim in the backyard pool, grow vegetables in the garden
and gather eggs from their CBS-supplied chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Already a hit in Europe, ``Big Brother'' originally was
scheduled to begin Thursday night. But CBS advanced the premiere
one day to take advantage of the popularity of its other
``reality'' show, ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' however, is shown only one night a week. We can
watch people in the ``Big Brother'' house constantly: five nights a
week on television, in both live and taped broadcasts, and nonstop
on the Internet. But the producers have assured viewers in advance
that the bathroom camera will not be part of the live broadcast, to
prevent reoccurrence of an embarrassing moment in the Netherlands
version.
</P>
<P>
   We can even participate. Every two weeks the home audience votes
(by telephone) to evict one of the residents and ultimately
determines which of three finalists wins the $500,000 grand prize.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the end of civilization as we know it?
</P>
<P>
   Hard to tell from the Wednesday night one-hour premiere, which
was a giant tease. The contestants spent most of the hour traveling
on the streets of Los Angeles in a caravan of identical white SUVs,
conjuring a memory of O.J. Simpson's Bronco. While waiting for
their arrival at the house, the hostess-anchor, Julie Chen,
explained and exclaimed with relentless enthusiasm. (Chen is a
newscaster on ``The Early Show''; her credibility may never recover
from this.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The show has already rocked several countries in Europe,'' she
hyperbolized. Then she presented a montage of video clips from the
European editions. Judging from these, here's what we have to look
forward to: conga lines, deodorant spritzing, leg shaving,
smooching, fighting, more smooching, pillow fighting, X-rated
smooching (under wiggling comforters).
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for the caravan to arrive, Chen introduced the
contestants, who appear in brief taped biographies, with commentary
from friends and family. Her co-host, Ian O'Malley, gave a tour of
the house and its hidden cameras. While Chen seemed ready to pop
through the screen with excitement, he'd barely shaken himself
awake.
</P>
<P>
   But neither host is nearly as odd as the people who have
volunteered to lock themselves in the house for national
exhibition. There's Jamie, crowned Miss Washington, USA, (described
as ``a beauty queen with a 4.0 average''), who declares that she
was sorry to miss ``community service and things like that.'' If
there were a choice, however, between relinquishing her crown and
participating in ``Big Brother,'' she says, the title would just
have to go.
</P>
<P>
   From the Midwest comes George, seen posing in the snow in boxer
shorts and nothing else. He says that if America can get a thrill
at looking at an overweight, hairy guy walking around in his
underwear, ``have at it!''
</P>
<P>
   One young man lost his leg to cancer as a child; another lost
his mother. A buff-looking woman competes in triathlons and is
writing a book, but she earns her living as an exotic dancer. As in
``Survivor,'' one contestant is pierced: this one in the nose
rather than the nipple. She lets us know that she's a virgin.
</P>
<P>
   A mother of four says she needs a break from her kids. Hasn't
she heard of a spa?
</P>
<P>
   Finally the contestants arrived. The annoying Chen herded them
to the front of the house, through a cheering gaggle of friends and
family. As the ``Big Brother'' group awkwardly kissed loved ones so
long and blinked at the lights, it became apparent that this show
will be tackier and creepier than ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the night I peeked at the contestants on the
Internet, at bigbrother2000.com, to see if any comforters were
rustling suspiciously. After a half-hour, I was rewarded only by a
shift in position by one of the men. It's just the beginning, but
so far there's more Web action on www.stinkymeat.net, the Web site
that follows the decomposition of various meat products, day by
day.
</P>
<P>
   This bizarre gimmick illustrates yet again how desperate the
networks are for ratings. It's a brave new world in television
land, because even couch potatoes can summon the energy to click
through dozens of channels.
</P>
<P>
   How big is ``Survivor's'' much-vaunted success? Preliminary
ratings show that ``Survivor'' was watched in about 15.1 million of
the country's 100.8 million television households this week. On its
first night ``Big Brother'' was seen in about 13.9 million
households. Compare those numbers with the highest-rated episode of
the ABC miniseries ``Roots,'' also a special event, which in those
network-dominated days of January 1977 was seen in 36.4 million of
the 71.2 million television households, more than half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' continues a CBS tradition. A half-century ago,
on ``Truth or Consequences,'' another CBS game show, the host,
Ralph Edwards, brought onstage the mother of a (real) soldier
stationed in Korea. They chatted, and then she was taken offstage,
while Edwards prepared a surprise for her.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the critic Jack Gould reported the event in The New
York Times:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Edwards, with an air of triumph, brought out Mrs.
Cunningham to see her boy, upon whom she had not laid eyes for 31
months. Across her face in a flash there came that heart-rending
combination of anguish and relief any woman would show upon seeing
a son or husband returned from war. It was an intensely private,
personal moment, which no outsider had the right to share. The
sensitive viewer could not help but be embarrassed and ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the sensitive viewer. Does he exist anymore? Did she ever?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
