<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MCMURTY-BOOK-REVIEW-N     07-06 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMURTY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ROADS': A LONESOME DRIVER ON THAT ANONYMOUS RIBBON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bittersweet scent of loss has always wafted through Larry
McMurtry's fiction, creating a mood of wistful melancholy. Whether
writing about the waning of the Old West in ``Lonesome Dove'' and
``Streets of Laredo'' or simply chronicling an aging woman's
reminiscences and regrets in ``The Evening Star,'' he has always
been acutely attuned to the wages of time and change. His latest
book, ``Roads,'' is no exception. Though the volume is simply an
account of his desultory travels through the United States, it
leaves the reader with a haunting sense of how the country has
changed in the last half-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roads'' traces a series of drives that McMurtry took in his
spare time along America's great interstates: from Baltimore to
Burlington, Colo., on I-70; from Los Angeles to Albuquerque on the
10, the 15 and the 40; from Washington to Dallas via the 66, 81, 40
and the 30, and so on, from East to West, from North to South.
</P>
<P>
   The trips were made with no real destination in mind: the routes
chosen by whim, the direction by impulse and intuition. McMurtry's
one aim, it seems, was to avoid traffic congestion, roads under
repair and heavily traveled truck routes while also renouncing the
sort of small picturesque roads that William Least Heat Moon
traversed in his 1983 book ``Blue Highways.'' As a result ``Roads''
has a decidedly improvisatory air: It lacks the obsessive quality
that McMurtry himself says distinguishes the best travel writing,
and it often suffers, like ``Flim Flam,'' his 1987 book on
Hollywood, from a curiously perfunctory tone.
</P>
<P>
   In his restless drive to keep moving, McMurtry often passes by
the oddest, most interesting sights. He toys with stopping at a
roadside attraction that features a 500-pound man-killing clam but
when he notices that the site is closed he makes no effort to
return. He similarly bypasses the famed Meteor Crater in Arizona
because he doesn't want to contend with the traffic. As for his
views on the shortcomings of Texas cities like Austin and San
Antonio, he simply refers the reader to one of his earlier books.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Roads'' is not without its modest pleasures: It's like
a long, meandering road trip with an affable raconteur who likes to
comment on the landscape glimpsed through the windshield while
reminiscing about earlier visits to the region and books he once
read. Visits to northern Michigan and Key West, Fla., of course,
elicit riffs on Hemingway while Mississippi evokes memories of
books by Faulkner and Eudora Welty. Works by lesser-known writers
are cited as well, most notably ``We Pointed Them North'' by Teddy
Blue and Helena Huntington Smith, a book McMurtry hails as ``the
single best memoir of the cowboy era.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to writing novels, McMurtry has long had a second
career as an antiquarian bookman, and that job has taken him over
the years to remote corners of the country. This volume attests to
his easy familiarity with a plethora of regions and roads _ the
sort of familiarity that has helped him lend the sprawling country
the intimate feel of a small town in novels like ``Buffalo Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the days in West Virginia before the interstate
highways were built, when he ``crawled painfully across the state,
usually on mountain roads that offered no opportunities to pass the
many under-powered coal trucks that would be groaning up the hills
at two or three miles an hour, in their lowest gear.'' And he
remembers commuting between his two homes in Washington and Archer
City, Texas, a route he has driven some 60 times, ``enough to have
acquainted myself with virtually every gas station and convenience
store along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving that route today, he observes, ``it occurs to me that my
effort was obliquely Proustian, a retracing of my past that is
analogous to the many rereadings I've done in the last few years''
of favorite books. After heart surgery left him feeling alienated
and ghostly, it was a way to reconnect with his former self, to
reacquaint himself with ``elements of my old personality that are
still unaccounted for.''
</P>
<P>
   In this volume, however, McMurtry does not dwell on his own
feelings but focuses rather on the changes in America he observes
as he retraces favorite roads. He notes the proliferation of
casinos and outlet malls across the country and comments on the
arrival of ``nouveau ranchers'' in Texas who decorate the entrances
to their spreads with statuary modeled on the Arc de Triomphe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The development of credit-card gas pumps, microwaves, and
express motels has eliminated the necessity for human contact along
the interstates,'' he writes. ``It is now possible to drive coast
to coast without speaking to a human being at all: you just slide
your card, pump your gas, buy a couple of Hershey bars, perhaps
heat up a burrito, and put the pedal back to the metal.'' The most
eloquent chapter in this slender book deals with McMurtry's
memories of the ranch he grew up on in Texas, and the small,
unnamed roads he traversed as a boy _ on horseback, by mule cart
and later by truck. McMurtry recalls the waning days of the trail
drive (soon to be replaced by the advent of big cattle trucks) and
the squabbling produced by the county's decision, in the centennial
year of 1980, to name some local roads in honor of prominent
pioneer families. Some residents who did not like the name given to
the road past their homes just cut down the sign, he recalls;
``some roads had to be named two or three times before the citizens
who lived along them'' felt that ``the committee of road namers had
finally got it right.''
</P>
<P>
   In this chapter the hasty travel chat of the book's earlier
portions gives way to something deeper and more moving. The reader
only wishes that McMurtry had spent more time in this volume on the
dirt roads of his youth than on the impersonal interstates of
today.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `ROADS'
</P>
<P>
   By Larry McMurtry
</P>
<P>
   206 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
