<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CONVENTION-PROTESTS07     07-06 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTION-PROTESTS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROTESTERS SAY THEY'LL BE ACTIVE OUTSIDE POLITICAL CONVENTIONS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Promising a pox on both political parties, an array
of activists warned Thursday that they will take over the streets
outside the Republican and Democratic national conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had enough,'' said Margaret Prescod, a leader of the
R2D2K Coalition of protest groups. ``Get ready for a democratic
intervention on both coasts of the United States this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement includes many of the anti-globalist militants who
disrupted the World Trade Organization conference in Seattle and
besieged the World Bank meetings in Washington this year.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference, they outlined plans for similar actions
when the Republicans meet in Philadelphia from July 31 to Aug. 4
and when the Democrats convene in Los Angeles from Aug. 14-18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for a change,'' said Lisa Fithian, who wore a ``Shut
It Down'' T-shirt from the Direct Action Network. ``In Philadelphia
and Los Angeles, we say, 'No more business as usual.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The organizers said both major parties are controlled by
multinational corporate interests, and neither is accountable to
poor and working people. While representing causes varying from
labor unions to homeless mothers, they said they were unified in
demanding a political system ``based on human need, and not on
corporate greed.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizers predicted tens of thousands of activists will
take part in demonstrations ranging from marches to street theater.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, where the Republicans will nominate Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas for president, poor people will camp out in a
``Bushville'' modeled after the ``Hoovervilles'' of the Great
Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Convention Center in Los Angeles, thousands of
people will bang on drums, paint buckets, pots and pans during Vice
President Al Gore's acceptance speech for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take to the streets because they still belong
to us,'' said John Hogan, a Philadelphia labor organizer and
spokesman for the R2D2K Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   However, law enforcement agencies have formed their own
coalition to preserve order in Philadelphia and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service and FBI have helped local and state police in
planning security. In both cities, there will be buffer zones
around the convention sites where demonstrations are banned. Police
hope to confine protests to a designated and guarded area. Similar
restrictions were imposed around previous political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   But protest leaders said they won't be penned in.
</P>
<P>
   The ``protest pits'' established by police ``are like prisons,
and none of us intend to go there,'' said Prescod, co-founder of
International Black Women for Wages for Housework.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both permitted and non-permitted events will be taking
place,'' said Cheri Honkala, a formerly homeless single mother and
co-chair of the National Welfare Rights Union.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the street protests, ``shadow conventions'' will be
taking place in auditoriums several blocks from the Republican and
Democratic sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The official conventions ``will be boring, scripted
coronations,'' said Chuck Collins, co-founder of United for a Fair
Economy, (cq) which advocates redistribution of wealth. The shadow
conventions will feature ``real debate'' and ``substantive forums''
as well as parody and humorous commentary on the actual
conventions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said about 3,000 people will take part in the shadow
conventions. R2D2K Coalition leaders predicted at least 10 times
that many protesters will be on the streets of Philadelphia and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Since hotels are already booked by Republicans and Democratic
conventioneers and by the news media, organizers said the
demonstrators will be staying in churches, private homes, parks and
campgrounds. Labor unions are providing some of the funding.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers promised their protests will be peaceful, but
said they are worried about violence by police.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia has already enacted ``an anti-mask ordinance'' and
police are clearly targeting the black-clad anarchists who
protested in Seattle and the capital, said Susan Whitaker, an
activist leader.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers said they are equally disgusted with both
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to set up a radical participatory democracy _ a
political system where we all participate in decisions that affect
us,'' said Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.unity2000.com, www.D2KLA.org, www.R2Kphilly.org,
www.shadowconventions.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
