<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-06 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD'S PLAY THE WAY IT USED TO BE 
</HEADLINE>
   By WENDY MOONEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   R2D2, meet Barbie. Vintage toys and dolls are in, not that they
ever went out. There are specialty auctions, Web sites, collector
clubs, swap meets. There are sales four times a year in
Gaithersburg, Md., as well as the twice yearly Atlantique Fairs,
sales that attract tens of thousands to Atlantic City. There are
more than 80 dealers on nadda.org, the Web site of the National
Antique Doll Dealers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a baby boomer thing,'' said George Glastris, head of the
toy and doll department at Skinner, the Boston auction house.
``It's about nostalgia and recapturing our youth, even for
35-year-old yuppies like me. The robots are a guy thing. Dolls are
for girls.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Saturday's auction at Skinner, with 694 lots, is its
biggest toy sale to date. The sale includes wind-up toys,
lithographed tinplate vehicles, dolls, 18th-century Neapolitan
creche figures, toy soldiers, cast iron banks, board games, puzzles
and robots.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage toys are evaluated according to rarity and condition.
``Great age is not important for toys, dolls and collectibles,''
Carol Prisant writes in the ``Antiques Roadshow Primer.'' ``Toys
made before World War II are considered `antique,' while toys made
after the war are `modern.'''
</P>
<P>
   Old toys need not be expensive. Skinner has given many lots $200
estimates, though not the star ones. These include rare robots like
the Robby Space Patrol. (The word robot, coined by the Czech writer
Karel Capek, comes from the Czech word robota, meaning compulsory
labor like that of a serf.) Robby the Robot was made famous by the
classic 1956 science-fiction film ``Forbidden Planet.'' A robot who
drove a space vehicle across a windswept alien planet, he has
become an icon among robot collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's also rare,'' Glastris said. ``I've never sold one
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bergin, a private dealer in New Hampshire who specializes
in vintage robots and space toys (www.bergintoys.com), said:
``Today, kids and Generation X, at least the 15- to 20-year-olds,
are turned on by them. They are even showing up in MTV videos.''
</P>
<P>
   To Bergin, robots represent not nostalgia but the future and the
unknown. ``These robots are futuristic in form and design,'' he
said. ``The toys are 50 years old, and we still don't have real
robots yet. We are just on the verge.''
</P>
<P>
   Robots are also popular among graphic artists. ``It's because
they have a `Pulp Fiction' kind of art,'' Bergin said. ``Robots and
robot boxes probably have better graphics than any other toy.''
</P>
<P>
   This may explain the astronomical prices robots can fetch.
Sotheby's London has sold a rare Robby for $74,000. That set a
record for a robot sold at auction, but Bergin said he had sold
robots for more. At the moment he has a red Robby Space Trooper in
its original box for $7,500 and a black Robby Space Trooper without
its box for $1,500. He recommended that would-be collectors read
``Future Toys,'' by Antoni Emchowicz and Paul Nunneley (New
Cavendish Books).
</P>
<P>
   A quick survey on the Web proves you can also buy other
movie-star toy robots made more recently, including a robot
inspired by the Maria in Fritz Lang's 1926 German film
``Metropolis''; Hal 9000, from ``2001: A Space Odyssey''; both 3CPO
and R2D2 from ``Star Wars''; and Vanessa Rembot from ``Austin
Powers.'' Robots rule!
</P>
<P>
   Dolls have been cherished since men lived in caves. ``Dolls are
the second most highly collected antiques, after stamps and
coins,'' said Dorothy McGonagle, the doll specialist at Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   They tend to be classified according to the material used to
make the head: wood, china, cloth, wax and plastic, among others.
``The head is 90 percent of a doll,'' McGonagle said. ``Some
manufacturers made only heads, and others made the bodies. Then
dolls were sent off to the couturier for dressing. In the late
1800s, Paris shops like Au Nain Bleu acted as a middleman. It would
have samples, so the customer could specify what head and dress she
wanted. They must have had teams of seamstresses making the
outfits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dolls are a mirror of society,'' McGonagle continued. ``Dolls
reflect what is going on in a culture at a given time. In the 19th
century, for example, France was the fashion capital of the world,
and costume was an important part of French life and the French
economy. So the French produced fashion dolls, dolls depicted as
upper-class ladies in couture. They are the predecessors of Barbie,
the fashion doll of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan specialty shops like Second Childhood on Bleecker
Street and Iris Brown Antique Dolls on East 57th Street sell such
dolls. Richard Wright, a dealer in Birchrunville, Pa., also has a
selection of rare European toys and dolls.
</P>
<P>
   There are two schools of thought about fashion dolls, said
McGonagle, author of ``The Dolls of Jules Nicolas Steiner.'' ``Some
say they were a way France exported its fashions. I think these
dolls were to play with. They were made at a time when the middle
class was burgeoning and people had money. It was the right time
for a huge development in doll making. Such dolls came with
accessories: crosses, enameled watches, rings, rosary beads and
necklaces, to name a few.''
</P>
<P>
   Iris Brown disagrees. ``These dolls are not really for
children,'' she said. ``They have survived because they were put on
shelves. Girls just looked at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the 19th century, dolls tended to look like miniature
adults. They probably look like adults because children were
expected to act like adults, McGonagle said. ``Early dolls were
also very pale, because ladies stayed inside,'' she added. ``Later
on you see healthier coloring.'' Dolls were adults dressed as
children until the 1870s, when the child began to be glorified and
doll forms were rendered as babies and children.
</P>
<P>
   French companies like Bru, Jumeau and Steiner all produced fine
child dolls. Lot 171 in the Skinner sale is a rare French Bru Bebe
doll called Zepherine from the late 1870s. Her beautifully modeled
head and delicate (repainted) hands are bisque, while the body is
made of kid leather. She looks very grown up, with protruding
breasts and a (replacement) blond wig framing her face. She has
enormous cornflower blue eyes made of paperweight glass, arched
eyebrows and long eyelashes that have been painted on. She wears
her original cotton chemise underdress, which originally would have
had a fabulous outfit over it. The estimated selling price for the
doll is $8,000 to $12,000.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors have arcane criteria when judging dolls. ``A good
doll, like a good woman, keeps her eyes open and her mouth shut,''
McGonagle said, quoting an adage.
</P>
<P>
   To Bergin, a robot is really an industrial doll. ``They mesh the
computer age with the human age,'' he said. For him, the only good
doll (or robot) is one that can move in mysterious ways. To each
his own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4642 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-AMTRAK-FREE-RIDE-390&AMP;     07-06 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-FREE-RIDE-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMTRAK IS OFFERING EVERY DISSATISFIED RIDER A FREE TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amtrak said Thursday that it would offer every
dissatisfied customer a free repeat trip, even if the problem was
not the railroad's fault.
</P>
<P>
   The new program is part of its campaign to build ridership and
revenues by reducing the number of disgruntled passengers, before
Congress cuts off operating subsidies in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``This grabs people's attention in the marketplace,'' said
George Warrington, president of Amtrak, who added that no other
national carrier offered a similar program. This one is retroactive
to July 4.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak's reputation among potential passengers has historically
been poor, Warrington acknowledged, because of trains that are late
or in poor condition. He said the new program was intended to
demonstrate ``Amtrak's ability, desire and fixation about putting
guests at the center of everything we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also revealed a new logo, to replace the ``pointless
arrow,'' as it is known, that has served for the last 29 years. The
company plans to redesign waiting rooms, ticket booths, platform
displays and schedules themselves, to match.
</P>
<P>
   To exercise the new guarantee, Amtrak is asking its customers to
call their complaints to the attention of any employee. If the
employee cannot solve the problem Amtrak will issue coupons for
repeat travel.
</P>
<P>
   The company anticipates, for example, issuing coupons to
individuals for a problem with a seat or a sleeping compartment or
to all passengers onboard if a train is extremely late. Amtrak
promises to provide the free ride coupon even if the problem is an
ice storm, or derailment of another train. ``Regardless of fault,
in the end, it's Amtrak that's responsible,'' Warrington said
during a meeting with reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak estimates that for every 100 people who try the railroad
for the first time, 15 percent never ride again. If Amtrak can
raise that rate by 1 percent, its revenues would rise by $13
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad has also trained on-board personnel to help
passengers if a train is going to be late, by telephoning ahead to
relatives who were planning to pick them up at the station, for
example, or re-booking connections and hotel accommodations.
Company officials said they were taking cues from what travelers
expect from airlines under similar circumstances.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the last three years Amtrak has been offering a similar
satisfaction guarantee on a single train, the Coast Starlight,
which runs daily in each direction between Seattle and Los Angeles,
and has issued one coupon good for a free trip for each 107,000
passengers carried, Warrington said.
</P>
<P>
   But the railroad expects a much higher rate of complaints and
refunds on other trains. It has told its 25,000 employees that if
the rate of complaints runs better than one in 1,000 trips during
any given month, each of them will get a bonus for that month equal
to the average price of an Amtrak ticket, which is now about $50.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad, created by Congress in 1971 as a way to preserve
the passenger service that the investor-owned railroads were
closing down, said that ridership was up 7 percent in the last four
months compared with the previous year, and that in June, for the
first time ever, it had revenues of $100 million. Passenger loads
on its four daily all-electric ``Acela Regional'' trains running
between Washington and Boston are up 40 percent over the older
trains they replaced, the railroad said.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad intends to introduce its high-speed Acela service,
with a top speed of 150 mph, later this summer. That had been
scheduled for last year, but problems were found in testing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
