<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4643 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-CAR-NASCAR-HNS &LR;      07-06 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NASCAR RACES AHEAD AS A FAVORITE PASTIME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL PARKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the fastest growing sport in America. Thousands of
spectators flock to the main event each Sunday, and millions more
watch on television. Marketing executives covet the biggest stars
as product endorsers. Fans adore them.
</P>
<P>
   This not the NFL. This not the PGA tour.
</P>
<P>
   This is the National Association for Stock Car Auto Racing. This
is NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   While other sports plateaued or declined in attendance during
the 1990s, NASCAR boomed, nearly doubling in on-track spectators
between 1990 and 1999, when more than 6.6 million people attended
the 34 Winston Cup events.
</P>
<P>
   But attendance only begins to tell the story of NASCAR's
meteoric rise. Television ratings are up in recent years, and sales
of licensed merchandise have skyrocketed more than 1,400 percent in
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have contributed to NASCAR's rise, not the least
of which is a shrewd and thorough marketing plan that relies
largely on the athletes themselves to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when the sports section is littered with reports of
athletes behaving badly, ask yourself this: When was the last time
you read, saw, or heard anything about a NASCAR driver running
afoul of the law or displaying contempt for fans or the media?
</P>
<P>
   ``They are heroes to their fans,'' said Brett Yormark, NASCAR's
managing director of corporate marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The hero, however, isn't always the guy in the white hat. This
is NASCAR, remember, an organization that traces its roots to
Southern bootlegging, and there's no one in the game today who
conjures that image more than hard-driving Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt is a roguish figure with a brush-like mustache and a
fondness for mirrored shades, the kind through which you can smirk
at the world and never meet an eye in return. Don't look for him to
teach your local defensive driving course. He'll bump, nudge, test
your mettle and your metal _ all at 150 mph _ if that's what it
takes to get his car under the checkered flag first.
</P>
<P>
   He does it all in a big black Chevrolet, the No. 3 car. His fans
know it as the GM Goodwrench Chevrolet, just as Dale Jarrett's fans
know he drives the Quality Care Ford and Jeff Gordon's fans know he
drives the DuPont Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt and NASCAR have grown together, the popularity of one
no doubt fueling the rise of the other. In many ways, Earnhardt
epitomizes the NASCAR ideal _ tough and uncompromising on the
track, human and approachable off it. He signs autographs and poses
for pictures with fans in wheelchairs. And, like any ordinary
father might, he cried the first time his son, Dale Jr., won a
Winston Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like the Pettys. Earnhardt equals NASCAR,'' said
Sally Chittenden, the general manager of ``Victory Lane,'' a
NASCAR-themed cafe and store in Queensbury, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's appeal, too, is its familiarity. It's possible for the
fans to imagine themselves in the driver's seat, because these are,
after all, souped up Fords, Chevys and Pontiacs, not the low-slung,
open-wheeled speed machines of the Indianapolis 500 and Formula
One.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike other sports, the entire NASCAR season is one large
playoff for the championship. Every race counts, and every driver
who wants to win the championship shows up to compete. The driver
who starts the race gets credit for the points, so it's not
uncommon to see a driver with bone fractures of one kind or another
gut it out for a lap or two before handing the wheel to a
substitute, all in the name of staying in contention for the points
title.
</P>
<P>
   The foreseeable future looks as bright as the recent past for
NASCAR, which will begin the 2001 season with a new television
contract and two new race venues. The first half of the season will
be aired on Fox, the second half on NBC. This year, as in years
past, a handful of marquee races were on network television,
including Saturday night's primetime broadcast of the Pepsi 400 on
CBS. The rest are on cable, primarily ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be going from 70 million homes to 100 million homes,''
Yormark said. ``Add in the new racetracks near Chicago and Kansas
City, and we see only continued growth for NASCAR and its
sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of the Winston Cup series to those major
Midwestern cities will give NASCAR a strong foothold in all the
regions of the United States, including the Northeast, where tracks
in Watkins Glen, Loudon, N.H., Dover, Del., and Long Pond, Pa., are
filled to capacity when the series comes to town.
</P>
<P>
   The broad national appeal also is reflected in the demographics
of the fans. NASCAR research shows that more 40 percent of those
who identify themselves as fans went to college, and that more 37
percent earn more than $50,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dover Downs International itself offers a snapshot of NASCAR's
surge. The track, which hosts two Winston Cup events each year, had
22,000 grandstand seats in 1986. Today it has 133,000, with a goal
of 170,000. Every race is sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket costs are rising to help pay for expansion at Dover and
elsewhere, but so far the sport hasn't seen the backlash that
accompanied price increases in the other major U.S. sports. At
Dover, you can expect to pay between $60 and $90 for bleacher
seats. If you don't want to have the person in front of you sitting
in your lap, you'll need to pay the higher price.
</P>
<P>
   One of NASCAR's next big targets is New York City, and though
nothing concrete is being proposed, Yormark said, ``it's on our
radar screen.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, NASCAR fans will have to be satisfied with the
2,000 races a year in 13 series that NASCAR oversees. Those in
search of a quick fix can visit www.nascar.com, which gets about
300,000 visits a day, according to Yormark, more than any other
sport-specific site on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who go on-line or tune in looking for the sport's next star
needn't look far. Dale Earnhardt Jr. has Gordon's clean image _ an
image that has made Gordon a lightning rod for the wrath of fans
who prefer drivers with grease under their nails _ and an
organization that has the financial wherewithal to produce
immediate success. Coming off back-to-back championships on the
Busch Grand National circuit, NASCAR's minor league, Earnhardt Jr.,
at 25, already is on his way to the most impressive rookie campaign
in Winston Cup history. He was the first driver this year to
collect two Winston Cup wins. Two more would give him the rookie
record.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR does have its drawbacks. Huge crowds mean long waits and
lots of traffic. Once inside, be prepared to shell out 10 bucks for
a program, and 20 for a shirt or hat with your favorite driver's
name on it. Add another five for a beer brought to you by Earnhardt
Jr. and his Budweiser racing team, but don't expect it to be all
that cold.
</P>
<P>
   Once in your seat, don't get up or you'll miss the show. Things
happen fast in this sport. If you miss a lap, though, there's no
need to worry; they come around 400 more times before it's over.
And even then, you can still tune in next Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
