<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV wrapup
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Big Brother'' (8 p.m., CBS, 4674) _ Episode 3 of a projected
gazillion episodes, and already a national groundswell is ready to
vote the two most annoying people out of the house. That, of
course, would be hosts Julie Chen and Ian O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Jerry Springer'' (11 p.m., WAGA, 72262) _ I just noticed
that TV Guide lists Springer's show as ``Discussion.'' Apparently
the analyses of the disputants are not rarefied enough to qualify
it as a salon.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Biography: Ernest Borgnine'' (8 p.m., A&AMP;E, 593755) _ Summer
is traditionally the time when cable puts on snappy new programming
to lure viewers away from the broadcast networks. And nothing says
snappy like an hour on Ernest Borgnine.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The 1900 House Marathon'' (3-7 p.m. , WGTV, 28408, 12083,
7335, 16373) _ No, it doesn't get the ratings of CBS's ``Survivor''
(but then again, you never had to watch Richard get naked). ``The
1900 House,'' however, got big ratings for PBS. An interesting
wrinkle in the current voyeur-vision craze, it followed a real
British family trying to live exactly as their ancestors did 100
years ago and not always real happy about it. WGTV reruns the four
hours as a block.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Longitude'' (8 p.m., 571847 A&AMP;E) _ A four-hour docudrama
about scientific efforts to improve maritime navigation? Whoa,
baby, dibs on the Barcalounger!
</P>
<P>
   All scoffing aside, ``Longitude'' has an excellent pedigree,
most notably its two stars, Jeremy Irons (``The French Lieutenant's
Woman,'' ``Lolita'') and Michael Gambon (``The Singing
Detective),'' and writer-director Charles Sturridge, who did the
great ``Brideshead Revisited'' so many years ago. Gambon plays John
Harrison, the 18th-century tinkerer whose solutions to the problem
of mapping longitude were mocked, and Irons plays Rupert Gould, the
early 20th-century British Navy officer who reconstructed
Harrison's work.
</P>
<P>
   Movies
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Fled'' (8 p.m. Saturday, WATL, 427137) _ Laurence Fishburne
and Stephen Baldwin star as escaped cons in a flick notable mostly
for scenes shot at Stone Mountain Park.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dirty Dancing'' (8:05 p.m. Saturday, TBS, 1583205) _ While
America waits for the we'll-believe-it-when-we-see-it rumored
remake with Ricky Martin and Britney Spears, you can still get down
with the original with Patrick Swayze and Jennifer Grey.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Great Escape'' (2:30 a.m. Saturday, TBS, 717868) _
``Chicken Run,'' but with people. Cool idea.
</P>
<P>
   Best Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Freaks and Geeks Marathon'' (8-11 p.m. Saturday, NBC, 33601,
20137, 23224).
</P>
<P>
   Talk about bittersweet. ``Freaks and Geeks'' was a real
heartbreaker of a series, the intricately interwoven tales of
various high school losers, circa 1980. Funny, poignant, brutally
real at times, it had a grasp of high school hierarchies (of any
era), of petty rivalries and soaring moments of triumph that
bordered on the poetic.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, NBC didn't schedule it well, hardly anyone watched,
and the network axed it before its first season was even over. Now,
as a sort of penance (or the ultimate in chutzpah), NBC is airing
three unseen episodes.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Smooching and Mooching'' at 8 p.m., sweet geek Sam (John
Daley) plans to go to a makeout party with cheerleader Cindy
Sanders. ``The Little Things'' at 9 p.m. guest stars Ben Stiller as
a Secret Service agent advancing a visit to the high school by Vice
President George Bush. And in ``Discos and Dragons'' at 10 p.m.,
the episode that would have For Use By Clients of the New York
Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
