<HEADER>
A4651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMANY-NAZI-LABOR-49     07-06 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-NAZI-LABOR-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPENSATION FOR NAZI-ERA LABORERS APPROVED BY GERMAN PARLIAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ More than a half-century after the end of
Hitler's Third Reich, the German parliament approved legislation
Thursday that will govern a $5 billion humanitarian fund for
Nazi-era slave workers and other victims of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, passed by an overwhelming majority of 556-42, is
intended to bring a close, at least legally, to the most brutal
chapter in German history.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's vote was not surprising, because it essentially
ratified an agreement reached after more than a year of grinding
negotiations between representatives of German industry, the German
government and the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   But the new law now sets the stage for payments to Holocaust
survivors before the end of the year. It thus ends a half-century
of denial of responsibility by German manufacturers including the
German subsidiaries of Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Inc.
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned, former slave laborers _ prisoners in
concentration camps who worked without any pay and under
nightmarish conditions _ will be entitled to one-time payments of
up to 15,000 marks, or less than $7,500. Former forced laborers _
people who were dragooned into factories but may have received some
payment _ will get as much as 5,000 marks or about $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Though the German government has paid out more than $50 billion
in compensation to various groups and to the state of Israel since
World War II, the vast majority of former forced laborers have
received nothing.
</P>
<P>
   German manufacturers argued that they had been forced by the
Nazi regime to use the workers. Under former Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, the German government argued that it had already paid out
full compensation and would not contribute anything more.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate was changed by two things. The first was a new
wave of class-action lawsuits filed in the United States, which
could have potentially inflicted billions of dollars in liabilities
on German companies. The second came when Gerhard Schroeder
replaced Kohl in late 1998 and immediately began pushing for a
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, German industry and the government will
each contribute about $2.5 billion to a fund that will pay
compensation to as many as 1 million former forced laborers. Most
of the victims are in Central Europe and Russia, although many
others are scattered around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The fund will also be used to compensate people who endured
medical experimentation at the hands of Nazi scientists and some of
those whose property was confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have responsibility, because we cannot disclaim the past,
the good much less the bad,'' Hans Eichel, Germany's minister of
finance, told members of the parliament Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate resolution, the parliament formally apologized to
Holocaust victims for taking away their rights, displacement,
maltreatment and exploitation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But despite the lofty goals of reconciliation, sourness also
permeated Thursday's debate in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Otto Lambsdorff, who represented German industry in the long
negotiations with survivors' organizations, U.S. class-action
lawyers and the U. S. government, lashed out angrily at German
companies that refuse to contribute to the new fund.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of fund-raising, German industry has thus
far pledged only 3.1 billion marks, or about $1.5 billion from
about 3,000 companies, about $1 billion short of its obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a public offense that the majority of companies have not
yet joined up,'' said Lambsdorff, the former German finance
minister. ``All German companies, including those formed after the
war, should contribute to the fund. Those not burdened by the past
should think about reshaping the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of companies that have already joined the humanitarian
fund includes most of Germany's big corporate names _ Siemens A.G.,
DaimlerChrysler A.G., Volkswagen A.G. and Deutsche Bank. It also
includes the German subsidiary of General Motors, Adam Opel, as
well as the German subsidiary of Ford.
</P>
<P>
   But many smaller companies have refused to contribute. Many
argue that they did not use forced labor and were themselves
bankrupted during the war.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Manfred Gentz, the chief financial officer of DaimlerChrysler
and leader of the German industry initiative, has recently said he
is confident that the foundation will collect all the money needed
within the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the sluggish progress prompted heavy criticism
from many members of the parliament. ``The behavior of industry is
and remains a scandal,'' said Ulla Jelpke, a member of the Party of
Democratic Socialism, the successor to East Germany's old Communist
Party.
</P>
<P>
   One lingering uncertainty is whether the agreement and the new
law will shield German companies from future lawsuits stemming from
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Legal immunity from future claims was the central demand by
German corporations, who only began negotiating after being
confronted with a wave of class-action lawsuits filed in the United
States on behalf of former forced and slave workers around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the Clinton administration has devised a
legal declaration urging courts to dismiss any future Holocaust
claims on the grounds that they are best dealt with through the new
humanitarian fund.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials argue that the declaration, which will be
submitted to any court where new lawsuits might be filed, should
provide German companies with the assurances they demand.
</P>
<P>
   But German negotiators have been far less sure, and continued to
demand stronger wording long after both sides announced their basic
agreement last December.
</P>
<P>
   At least one German attorney for Holocaust survivors said on
Thursday that opportunities to file lawsuits still remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``A statement of interest is no guarantee, just a strong
recommendation to a U.S. court,'' said Michael Witti, who has
collaborated with the American class-action lawyer Edward Fagan in
representing many former forced laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Witti said he continued to believe that victims of various
Aryanization programs, used to expropriate property from Jewish
citizens, may still have claims.
</P>
<P>
   Another discordant note to Thursday's proceedings came from a
handful of politicians in Germany's center-right parties, the
Christian Democratic Union and the Christian Social Union, who
voted against the law.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents said Germans had already paid out more than $50
billion in compensation to various groups as well as to the state
of Israel after World War II. They also demanded that the law be
coupled with demands for compensation to German prisoners kept by
Russia at the end of World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4655 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-DIGITAL-MEMORIES-NEWH     07-06 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-MEMORIES-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL PHOTOS WILL PROVIDE YEARS OF MEMORIES, BUT ONLY IF
PRESERVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attention editors: For information about purchasing this article
as a separate-buy, contact Debra Weydert of the New York Times
Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail:
weyded(at)nytimes.com.)
 (Note to editors: Material at bottom is suitable for graphic
treatment or sidebar)
 By MARGIE WYLIE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) On the Fourth of July, 8-month-old Rose Mendell took
part in a family tradition for the first time: a community
Independence Day parade in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Rose won't remember the marching bands or riding in a stroller
draped with red-white-and-blue bunting, but the snapshots taken by
her mother, Miriam Lewis, will tell her the story someday -- that
is, if they survive.
</P>
<P>
   Lured by ever better and cheaper cameras, more consumers are
going digital. No waiting -- or for that matter, paying -- for
processing. Pictures can be posted to a Web page, printed out an
unlimited number of times, or sent to friends and relatives by
e-mail almost as quickly as they can be taken.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be a hidden cost. Even as they snap away, most
consumers give scant thought to storing their growing collections
of digital photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we need to deal with greater archiving issues,'' said
Lewis, little Rose's mom. ``We just haven't researched what's best.
It's our intention to do that, but we all know what path good
intentions can take us down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all irreplaceable, little bits of her life, and I'd
really hate to lose them,'' she said of her 300 megabytes of photos
-- about 214 floppy discs' worth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet lose them she may, if she's not careful.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike conventional photos stuffed into shoeboxes and stashed in
the closet, digital pictures won't survive benign neglect. The data
that make up a digital photo can be easily lost, corrupted, or
simply become obsolete and unreadable. The medium is so new that
there is no tried-and-true method for preserving it for decades,
much less hundreds of years, say experts dealing with this problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you exactly how to store silver gelatin
(black-and-white) photos ... for the next 50 or 100 years,'' said
Andrew Robb, senior photograph conservator for the Library of
Congress in Washington. ``We just can't do the same for digital
images.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the best anyone can do is try to keep moving digital
data to newer media, a process called migration.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's both costly and scary,'' said Kenneth S. Weissman, head
of the Library of Congress Motion Picture Conservation Center in
Dayton, Ohio. ``Once you go digital, you've committed yourself to
constantly migrating your collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists like Robb say that optical media -- for
instance, DVD, CD-ROM and magneto optical discs -- are the most
stable. And recordable CDs, or CD-Rs, are the cheapest and most
available optical storage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nobody really knows how long CD-Rs will last. Industry
groups and CD-R manufacturers say the discs can last anywhere from
50 to 300 years based on artificial aging -- a testing process in
which they subject the discs to high heat, radiation and other
destructive forces. Others contend that CD-Rs might last as little
as 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even a disc that lasts five years might outlive the
operating system or file format with which it was created, Robb
warns. That's a predicament akin to reading hieroglyphics without
the Rosetta stone. It can't be done. So data have to keep moving.
</P>
<P>
   And that brings on another hazard. Over the course of years, the
digital language of photography can change. Merely translating
degradation, Weissman warned.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say the best way to save a digital shot is to
convert it back to analog: Print it out.
</P>
<P>
   Many manufacturers make color inkjet printers that create
near-photographic-quality prints, depending on the quality of
photos your camera is capable of taking. Yet, even when printed
out, images can fade in two years if produced with poor quality
paper and ink.
</P>
<P>
   Low-acid and acid-free papers are becoming increasingly
available, Robb said. And inks are improving, too.
</P>
<P>
   While most inks are still based on organic dyes, they fade much
less than they used to. Some printer manufacturers, Epson for one,
are also offering super-stable mineral-based inks or pigments for
their inkjet printers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many inkjet prints should last as long as, if not
longer than, traditional color film prints, according to a study by
Wilhelm Imaging Research of Grinnell, Iowa. That means, under
normal household conditions, 10 to 50 years before significant
fading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most archivists consider color images temporary,'' Weissman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Making a lasting image is only half of it.
</P>
<P>
   Robb also advises consumers to apply some professional
archivists' methods to their collections as well: cull and
organize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't try to save everything or you might get overwhelmed and
save nothing,'' he advised. ``What would you take if you had to
grab only a few
</P>
<P>
   The other trick? Save ``meta-data,'' or information about the
</P>
<P>
   ``The information on a disk might be useless if someone doesn't
understand how you've organized your file hierarchy or who is in
the picture or what they are doing,'' Robb said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL LIST OR SIDEBAR MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, shutter clicks are giving way to the beep of
digital cameras. Shipments of digital cameras are expected to rise
more than 60 percent this year over last, according to
International Data Corp., a Framingham, Mass.-based market research
firm. The average price will drop 8 percent by year's end, compared
with a year earlier, and is expected to plunge another 16 percent
by the end of 2001, according to IDC.
</P>
<P>
   But even professional preservationists don't have foolproof ways
of ensuring that digital photos survive for the long run. Here are
tips that will improve their chances:
</P>
<P>
   1. Cull and organize. Don't try to save everything. Identify
only your best or most meaningful photos for serious preservation
and concentrate your efforts on those. Be sure to find a place to
put ``meta-data,'' such as information about how the photographs
are organized, the dates on which they were taken, and any
descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   2. Print. Make archive photos on the best-quality paper you can
afford with the most stable inks possible. Choose mineral-based
inks over organic dyes where possible. Put those copies away in
light-tight boxes. (Check this Web site for a name-brand comparison
of papers and inks: www.wilhelm-research.com/1/1.html.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Save. Optical media is the most stable and long-lasting. If
you can afford to, save your digital photos on CD-R (recordable
CD-ROM). A CD ``burner'' runs about $300. CD-R discs are only about
$2 each and hold 650 megabytes of data. Magnetic media like hard
discs, Zip discs or backup tapes are less reliable but viable
options. Whether saving on magnetic or optical media, use an
application-neutral format, such as JPEG, and try to make at least
two copies to store in different places.
</P>
<P>
   4. Migrate. Whether you store on optical or magnetic media,
you'll probably face losing your data to changes in computer
systems long before the medium itself will degrade. Mark backups
with an ``expiration date'' -- five years at the outside -- when
you will copy (or migrate) the contents to the new disc, tape or
medium of your choice. If at all possible, don't change data
compression formats. Each time a file is translated, it loses data.
Over time, the loss will cause the image to degrade. LF END WYLIE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
