<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4656 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-CENSUS-POLITICS-NEWHO     07-06 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-POLITICS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP RESISTS USING SAMPLING AS CENSUS FIGHT CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
 -NEWHOUSE   (Attention editors: For information about purchasing this article
as a separate-buy, contact Debra Weydert of the New York Times
Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail:
weyded(at)nytimes.com.)
 By J. SCOTT ORR  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The 2000 census is ahead of schedule, on budget
and mired in politics and controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an impressive string of successes since it began in
earnest on April 1, the national head count has come under
relentless attack from Republicans over a plan to adjust the
numbers to try to account for millions of Americans who were
missed.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is fair representation in the nation's state
legislatures and the House of Representatives, along with billions
of dollars in federal aid that will be doled out over the next 10
years based on census data.
</P>
<P>
   But fueling the fight are lofty political stakes that include
control of the House -- where Republicans, with a slim six-vote
majority, are worried that the adjusted numbers will wrongly boost
the count of traditional Democratic constituencies like minorities
and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans point to errors in adjusted figures in the 1990
census in arguing that the risks of using sampling techniques to
tweak the figures are just too great. They want the Census Bureau
to use only figures compiled the old-fashioned way: through
questionnaires, door-to-door canvassing and telephone interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once states draw their district lines, you can't come back a
year later and say, `Sorry. We made a mistake. We added or
subtracted too many people,' '' said Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla. As
chairman of the House subcommittee on the census, Miller is leading
the Republican fight against sampling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about control of the House,'' said Rep. Robert
Andrews, D-N.J., who estimates that the city of Camden was
undercounted by nearly 10 percent in the 1990 census, when adjusted
numbers were calculated but not used.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican arguments have been indefensible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 census has exceeded expectations and overcome obstacles
on a number of fronts as the data collection portion of the task
winds to a close. Of the 120 million questionnaires sent out to
homes in March, 66 percent, about 78 million, were returned. That
figure is up from 65 percent in 1990, reversing a 30-year decline
in response rate.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Weeks before a self-imposed July 7 deadline, census workers had
completed surveys in 99 percent of the 42 million homes that did
not return their census questionnaires. The bureau also overcame an
expected shortage of workers, recruiting 2.6 million qualified
applicants.
</P>
<P>
   And the agency's telephone assistance program aided more than 6
million callers; more than 546,000 people took advantage of walk-in
questionnaire assistance centers.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Census 2000 `The Good Census,' and I believe that
accurately describes what the Census Bureau has achieved,'' Census
Director Kenneth Prewitt told Congress.
</P>
<P>
   However, the question of using sampling techniques to adjust
census numbers to make up for the inevitable undercount looms
heavily.
</P>
<P>
   The fight must be settled by April 1, the deadline by which the
Census Bureau must make available to state legislatures the figures
they will use to redraw legislative and congressional district
lines.
</P>
<P>
   State legislatures will then have the option of using the
unadjusted -- or enumerated -- data or the adjusted numbers, if
they are released, in redrawing district lines for the decade.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   In at least six states, legislatures are moving to ban the use
of adjusted numbers for redistricting purposes. In one of those
states, New Jersey, the state Assembly voted last month to require
the use of only enumerated data.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Menendez, D-N.J., the third-ranking member of the
House leadership, said House Democrats are planning a challenge to
the first such state law to pass on the grounds that it violates
constitutional guarantees of equal protection under the law.
Virginia is expected to lead the way in enacting a ban on the use
of adjusted numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt, meanwhile, has expressed confidence in the sampling
technique devised for the 2000 census and said he hopes it will
help avoid the undercounting of African-Americans and other
minorities that took place during the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   Without adjusting the data, he admitted, ``neither the overall
coverage, nor the differential undercount rates in Census 2000 will
show improvement over 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The sampling technique planned for the 2000 census, called the
Accuracy and Coverage Evaluation, involves the use of a separate
minicensus of 314,000 randomly selected households nationwide.
Those results will be compared with figures from the regular census
to determine factors to adjust the counts of 448 demographic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The evaluation might determine, for example, that non-Hispanic
black males, age 18 to 29, living in their own home in a
metropolitan area where census return rates are low were
undercounted by a factor of ``x.'' That factor would then be added
to the count of all such men across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the survey will make the census more
accurate,'' said Howard Hogan, the chief of statistical design for
both the census and the evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't believe that, we wouldn't be doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hogan said, the Census Bureau will examine its results
before deciding if the adjusted figures will be released next
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we've run the survey, we're going to take a look at the
results and decide whether in fact it has been carried out
properly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on whether to release adjusted figures is expected
to be made in February. The Clinton administration has drawn
criticism in recent days for its plan to push the decision making
from the secretary of the Commerce Department, which oversees the
Census Bureau, down to Prewitt.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Secretary William Daley, who subsequently left the
department to take control of Vice President Al Gore's presidential
campaign, said the decision was moved downstairs because ``politics
shouldn't play any part in this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans saw the move as an effort on behalf of Gore to
distance the administration from a controversial census decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transferring of decision-making authority from the
commerce secretary to the Census Bureau director doesn't make the
decision to release manipulated numbers any more palatable or less
political,'' Miller said, pointing out that Prewitt was appointed
by President Clinton. ``This decision was political from the
beginning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on releasing adjusted figures may actually be made
by voters in November. If Texas Gov. George W. Bush is elected
president, he will likely name a new commerce secretary and census
director who will block the release. JL END ORR
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
