<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RAUSCHENBERG-NEW-WORK     07-06 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAUSCHENBERG-NEW-WORK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING A CARD TRICK INTO CELEBRITY `SHUFFLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Continuing his long-running game of ``Anyone Can Be
an Artist as Long as I'm in Charge,'' Robert Rauschenberg has
unveiled his latest enterprise at the Whitney Museum of American
Art. Called ``Synapsis Shuffle,'' the new divertissement _ if one
may use that word for such a dull performance _ is a group of 52
panels, the number alluding to a full deck of cards.
</P>
<P>
   Each panel bears a characteristically disparate mix of
photographic images taken by Rauschenberg around the globe and
transferred to the panels' polylaminate surfaces. The paintinglike
photographs include objects, street scenes, people and natural
phenomena, along with snippets from advertising, magazines and
newspapers. Interspersed with abstract passages from paintings,
these seemingly stream-of-consciousness images are played off
against one another in arrangements that allow for multiple
readings on the part of the viewer. It's an old Rauschenberg idea
that has become very, very tired.
</P>
<P>
   Involved with the notion of audience participation in his art
for many years, Rauschenberg invited 12 fellow celebrities to
shuffle the panels for public presentation. That is, each was given
a chance to ``compose'' his or her own work, selecting from three
to seven of the panels and placing them in whatever juxtaposition
came to mind. A Whitney press release states portentously that
``the singular nature'' of ``Synapsis Shuffle'' dictates that its
52 components be rearranged by different people each time it is
installed, ``so that new works are continuously created from it.''
But it's a little hard to buy the premise that anyone can create a
new work simply by pushing around the artist's components.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, using the maximum of seven panels, the artist Chuck
Close selected those with images ranging from a cherub sitting on a
cornice to a tiny man on a scaffolding painting a large orange
wall. Martha Stewart, the lifestyle entrepreneur, picked three
panels that included one with a photo of elephants' rear ends
placed next to a cartoon of a giant lobster on the back of a truck.
In his five-panel arrangement, Mike Wallace, the television
journalist, included one that bore an image of a fire plug and
another showing a photograph of an American Indian brave.
</P>
<P>
   Mathilde Krim, chairwoman of the board of the American
Foundation for AIDS Research, defied convention by turning one of
her three panels back to front, so that only its bare frame shows.
The soprano Renee Fleming impishly decreed that her four panels
should appear sideways. Other shufflers included Michael Ovitz, the
talent agent and art collector; the art critic Robert Hughes; the
museum director and curator Walter Hopps; the musician and
photographer David Byrne; the choreographer Merce Cunningham; the
designer Edwin Schlossberg; and the art dealer Ileana Sonnabend.
</P>
<P>
   A long video loop displayed with the show details the selection
procedure on May 15 (at a Long Island City warehouse). It has all
the pumped-up gaiety of a celebrity fund-raiser. What's truly
amazing is how Rauschenberg managed to get this high-powered group
together in one space on one particular day to participate in this
hollow exercise. That is really the most successful accomplishment
of the show.
</P>
<P>
   It is also amazing how Rauschenberg himself has kept shuffling
the same ideas, more or less, into larger and larger projects that
take up enormous gallery space at the country's museums. He started
out as a bombshell in the early 1950s, a young, hugely talented
artist with an open, experimental approach to techniques and
materials. He anticipated the transition from Abstract
Expressionism to the emerging Pop Art movement by using
Expressionist gesture with everyday objects and images. It was a
giant, fresh leap.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years his work has sadly lapsed into some of the
most boringly predictable cliches of the art world. For the last
decade and a half he has been assembling his repertory of images
taken from here, there and everywhere around the globe, into
endless epics, like his 1984-1991 ROCI project (Rauschenberg
Overseas Cultural Interchange), covering his exposure to cultural
traditions in each of 11 countries, among them China, Mexico,
Japan, Venezuela, Cuba and others, using materials and images from
each country's culture. This giant piece was presented in full at
the National Gallery of Art in 1991 and in part at the traveling
Rauschenberg retrospective organized by the Guggenheim in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A precursor to the present ``Shuffle'' is ``The \ Mile or 2
Furlong Piece,'' a continuing extravaganza that at last count had
more than 200 painted and sculptural elements, extended more than
1,000 feet and was still growing. It was exhibited in 1987 at the
Metropolitan; 10 years later with add-ons as part of a Guggenheim
retrospective, and this year at the Massachusetts Museum of
Contemporary Art in North Adams. Like ``Furlong,'' Rauschenberg
considers ``Shuffle'' a piece ``in perpetual evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   The pretentiousness of ``Synapsis Shuffle,'' the
celebrity-kissing self-promotion it has involved, and the wasteful
allotment of nearly 6,000 square feet of gallery to it at the
space-challenged Whitney are not cause for celebration. Neither is
the sheer chutzpah of calling these hoary Rauschenberg cliches ``a
new masterwork'' and proclaiming that the participation of people
other than the artist in arranging them gives the project ``an
element of chance.'' (About as much an element of chance as in
three-card monte.)
</P>
<P>
   It won't go away: ``Shuffle'' has been promised as a gift to the
Whitney by Leonard A. Lauder, chairman of the Estee Lauder
Companies, who is also chairman of the Whitney's board, a diligent
fund-raiser for the museum and a prime donor of art and money
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Synapsis Shuffle'' turns out to be the same old Rauschenberg
deal. It's a pity that the Whitney has all but turned itself into a
Rauschenberg coliseum. It seems that as museums expand their
capacity, Rauschenberg's work expands to fill it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
