<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A KILLER SHARK IN RETROSPECT
</P>
<P>
   The screenwriter Carl Gottlieb tells a story about Steven
Spielberg, then a young director making ``Jaws,'' and a very small
backyard swimming pool. In the film a man's head suddenly and
shockingly appears in an underwater hulk. After the movie was shot,
the editor, Verna Fields, was working on it in her garage when
Spielberg became dissatisfied with the scene and decided to shoot
it again in Fields' pool. He would pay for it himself if need be.
</P>
<P>
   The boat remains were retrieved from the prop department and
sunk. The pool was lined with black plastic, and milk was dumped in
the water to make it opaque. An underwater cameraman descended and
kept shooting the rubber head. Eventually the studio agreed to pay
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Next week much old ``Jaws'' lore will resurface in a
25th-anniversary edition on tape (two cassettes) and DVD from
Universal. In 1975, the movie was a sensation, the first of the big
mass-audience action films that would take over the industry. In
its first two months, it brought in $90 million at the box office,
passing ``The Sting'' and ``The Exorcist'' and posing a threat to
``The Godfather'' as the biggest money-maker ever.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics were shocked at what they saw as the film's blatant
attempt to exploit and manipulate. ```Jaws' is so shabbily
constructed that audiences don't even pay attention during the
quiet intervals,'' Stephen Farber wrote in The New York Times.
``They're just waiting to see if the director can top the last
spectacular death or dismemberment.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg, as explained in a 75-minute making-of documentary on
tape and disc, was waiting for the shark. In those days the
monsters were hydraulic, not digital. ``The shark didn't work very
well,'' Gottlieb said in an interview. ``Storms trashed the
mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb got the writing credit, along with Peter Benchley, on
whose novel the film was based. In an early memo to Spielberg, he
recommended losing a proposed Mafia subplot and getting rid of the
sexual tension between Hooper (Richard Dreyfuss) and the wife of
the police chief, Brody (Roy Scheider).
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the film, the shark had to get in the boat with
Brody and Quint (Robert Shaw), the hard-bitten captain. Until then
it was a work in progress. ``I told Steven, `If you don't have a
shark, let's shoot stuff without one,''' Gottlieb said. While the
movie has plenty of gore in the water and yellow harpoon barrels
tearing here and there along the surface, the beast rarely exposes
more than a fin and some teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our model was `The Thing,' a low-budget black-and-white
thriller,'' Gottlieb said. ``The key element there was that you
didn't see the monster, just the effects.'' Also known as ``The
Thing From Another World,'' the film, made in 1951, is regarded as
one of the best in its genre.
</P>
<P>
   Most critics now say the same about ``Jaws.'' And what's wrong
with a little manipulation? ``It's what Hitchcock did better than
anybody,'' Gottlieb said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricane
</P>
<P>
   Telling the story of Rubin (Hurricane) Carter (Denzel
Washington), Norman Jewison's stirring but schmaltzy film lands
every emotional jab and hook. Carter, the boxer who served 20 years
in prison for murder, makes a brainy advocate for his own release.
A book he writes about himself attracts a young reader (Vicellous
Reon Shannon), who in turn interests three investigators from
Canada (Liev Schreiber, John Hannah and Deborah Kara Unger) in
taking up Carter's cause. Washington is powerful, but, Stephen
Holden wrote in The New York Times, ``his performance only partly
camouflages the glaring flaws of a movie that is as blatantly
manipulative as a pep rally.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Universal. $107.37; DVD, $26.98. 120 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: July 11.
</P>
<P>
   Boiler Room
</P>
<P>
   Beer-swilling Long Island boys in a cacophonous investment
trading room pitch customers looking for fast killings and try to
figure ways to spend all their own money. But there is a personal
story, too. Seth (Giovanni Ribisi), a college dropout and former
casino operator, strives to reconnect with his father (Ron Rifkin),
a judge who disowns him. Written and directed by the 29-year-old
Ben Younger, the film ``reflects the sensibility of the generation
it holds up to critical scrutiny, and it's a cunningly ambiguous
act of self-portraiture'' (A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. New Line. $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 110 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: July 11.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield Park
</P>
<P>
   The setting in Patricia Rozema's adaptation of Jane Austen's
novel seems familiar, but her smart, politically pointed screenplay
features a protofeminist heroine and includes such modern touches
as lesbianism and blatant drug addiction. Sir Thomas Bertram
(Harold Pinter), a slave trader, rules his estate with pompous
authority while young Fanny Price (Frances O'Connor), a poor
relative who is treated like a servant, persists in a film that
``is determined to invest Austen with as many prickly resonances as
it can'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 110 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: July 11.
</P>
<P>
   My Dog Skip
</P>
<P>
   Far from the typical high-tech kiddie adventure, Jay Russell's
leisurely, beautifully atmospheric film recreates the world Willie
Morris wrote about in his book about his Mississippi childhood. The
setting is a small town during World War II, and the action strays
no farther than across the railroad tracks as a boy (Frankie Muniz)
and his pup grow up together on leafy streets and in the embrace of
loving parents (Kevin Bacon and Diane Lane). Yes, it gets gooey,
but locations and performances ``help to make the film's relentless
sentimentality more bearable than it otherwise might have been''
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. Warner. $22.96; DVD, $24.98. 95 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG. Release date: July 11.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   THE AUDREY HEPBURN STORY. Wearing her hair in a huge French
twist popular in the early 1960s, Hepburn (Jennifer Love Hewitt)
shows up on the set to play Holly Golightly, a sort-of call girl,
in ``Breakfast at Tiffany's.'' Marilyn Monroe would have been
better for the part, grumbles a man who looks like Truman Capote,
author of the novella on which ``Breakfast'' is based. Roughly the
same misgivings might be expressed about Hewitt in the role of
Hepburn, who moved from a lonely upbringing to stardom on the stage
and screen. Chronicling the Hepburn career, this film, made for
ABC, never rises above its genre. But Hewitt, Anita Gates wrote in
The New York Times, at least gets Hepburn's voice right and ``is
not the disaster many people expected.'' 2000. Columbia Tri-Star.
$19.96; DVD, $24.95. 133 minutes. Closed captioned. Release date:
July 11.
</P>
<P>
   UPSTAIRS, DOWNSTAIRS: THE FIFTH SEASON. Thirteen episodes from
the last season of the acclaimed ``Masterpiece Theater'' series
follow the Bellamy family and those who toil in their service from
the start of the First World War to the confusing years after the
Armistice. Seven cassettes, $99.95. 663 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON POLLOCK. A BBC documentary treats the artist's life and
work with archival film and includes interviews with Lee Krasner,
Pollock's wife, and Ed Harris, who directs and stars in the new
feature film ``Pollock.'' 1999. $29.95. 46 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4662 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-HOSPITAL-STRIKE-HNS &LR;      07-06 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-STRIKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STRIKING HOSPITAL WORKERS DEMAND JOB SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL YI,  
 &HT;     MICHAEL DOUGAN and PIA SARKAR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One of the largest health care worker strikes in
recent history forced nine Bay Area hospitals to operate with
skeleton crews Thursday as 4,000 union members walked off their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The unions delivered on their promise of packed picket lines,
while the hospitals appeared to be handling the work shortages with
no serious problems.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Service Employees International Union Local 250 _
representing technicians, licensed vocational nurses, respiratory
therapists, clerical employees, dietary and food-service personnel
and housekeeping workers _ started picketing at 6 a.m. Thursday.
The strike was scheduled to last 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the dispute, which has been fought bitterly through
radio and television advertising, is not about wages and benefits,
but about staffing, union representatives said.
</P>
<P>
   The union charges the hospitals have not been staffing adequate
numbers of workers, often resulting in work-related injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be normal when a worker is sick, injured on the
job, that worker is replaced, but it's not the case anymore,'' said
union President Sal Rosselli. ``Our folks are frightened. ... It's
escalated the work-related accidents ... all caused by short
staffing. Our workers are being rushed.''
</P>
<P>
   The union is demanding the hospitals form committees _ made up
of workers and management _ to set staffing levels. The union also
wants better job security for its members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking that no matter what our wages are, what
difference does it make if they shut our facility next month?''
said Susan Zupko, a respiratory therapist at St. Mary's Medical
Center in San Francisco. ``Job security is a big issue in health
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical center officials criticized the strikers for leaving the
hospitals with smaller staffs for a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're having a picnic and a parade and putting patients
last,'' said Sutter Health spokesman Bill Gleeson.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals tried to make it as easy as possible for patients
and employees who reported to work. In some hospitals, where the
cafeterias closed, workers received free food and patients were
given catered meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a crisis, no question about it,'' said Trisha Barrett, a
director in nursing for Alta Bates Medical Center. ``With nine ...
hospitals in one region ... it has a widespread effect. It's just
one day, but that could be an important day for some people.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Kemp, spokeswoman for Sutter Health's Alta Bates and
Summit medical centers, said there were no serious problems to
report, with doctors staffing all of the ``most critical areas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very heartening to see the physicians working so hard to
compensate for the staff we don't have today,'' Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials acknowledged the strike inconvenienced the
hospitals and their patients, and would continue to affect service.
</P>
<P>
   Alta Bates and Summit officials said they canceled elective
surgeries a week ago and that it will take a few days to get the
hospitals' schedules back in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing as a one-day strike,'' said Maggie Gerk,
vice president for patient care at Alta Bates and Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Picketers were joined by members of the California Nurses
Association, which had approved a sympathy strike.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Moore, a CNA member who has been a nurse at Summit Medical
Center in Oakland for 22 years, said the hospital called the nurses
individually and asked them to report to work Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said she declined the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to support your co-workers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the union has accused the hospitals of hoarding
profits, Harry Joel, Catholic Healthcare West's vice president of
human resources and chief negotiator for the hospitals, said that
was not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we break even, we're happy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel added the management has a contract offer on the table,
including 12 percent pay increase over four years plus added health
and pension benefits, but the union hasn't responded.
</P>
<P>
   Strikers also said wages weren't the prime issue _ one of the
few things both sides seem to agree on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here because we're fighting for safe staffing and
patient rights,'' said Deborah Covington, who works at Summit in
the food service area and is the chief shop steward there. ``Sutter
has gobbled many hospitals in the Bay Area. They care about
profits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
