<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4669 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      07-06 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVER THE TOP AND PROUD OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The unexpected success of ``American Pie'' last
summer, in which a fresh crop of young actors obsessed about losing
their virginity and an apple pie was rudely disturbed in the
process, has accelerated the trend toward vulgar,
borderline-tasteless comedy that has some shaking their heads. How
low will Hollywood go to lure young people into theaters? The most
recent flurry of tsk-tsking occurred with the release of ``Me,
Myself and Irene,'' a Jim Carrey comedy that pokes fun at mental
illness and the disabled and does brazen things to a cow and a
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   But a fresh wave of scorn may well greet the release Friday of
``Scary Movie,'' a gleefully over-the-top satire of teen-slasher
flicks including the ``Scream'' series and ``I Know What You Did
Last Summer.'' The film, directed by Keenen Ivory Wayans, focuses
less on the horror aspects than the sexual ones and includes digs
at ``The Sixth Sense,'' ``The Usual Suspects'' and a host of more
mainstream films. No baked goods or poultry were violated in the
making of the film, but there are plenty of sex scenes, sex talk,
sex satire and pot-smoking, and one particularly rude, up-the-dress
shot that involves prosthetics of a type not seen since Mark
Wahlberg unzipped in ``Boogie Nights'' in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do our bad taste in good taste,'' promised Bob Weinstein,
one of the brothers who runs Miramax Films, distributors of both
the ``Scream'' series and this satire. ``What you do is you look at
the barometer of where the other guys have gone and then you try to
go a little further. The bottom line is, if it's funny, it stays;
if it's not, it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the pre-release tracking _ a series of surveys to monitor
audience awareness of a movie _ that precedes the opening of
virtually every new film in Hollywood these days, ``Scary Movie''
has been doing very well, indicating that there is a good deal of
pent-up demand to see the film. (That is, if the polling is
correct, which it isn't always; last week ``The Patriot'' was
tracking much better than ``The Perfect Storm,'' yet the latter did
twice as well at the box office over the holiday weekend.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tracking through the roof,'' Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about tracking is almost pathological in Hollywood these
days, despite its spotty history. It gives marketing executives
some idea of how well their campaigns are working and has a jargon
all its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 15 percent overall first choice a week before the
release,'' Weinstein said. ``And in the quadrants, the news is even
better. For males under 14, we're 24 percent; for females in that
age group, we're 29. For the same two categories, `Perfect Storm'
was 9 and 9. For all teen-agers, `Patriot' was 9, `Perfect Storm'
was 5. We're 34.''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the two big holiday films, which had budgets of more
than $100 million, ``Scary Movie'' was made for a relatively
minuscule $19 million and makes no effort to disguise the fact.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Miramax intended to open the film in about 2,000
theaters, wedged two weeks after the release of the Carrey movie
and three weeks before the release of Eddie Murphy in ``Nutty
Professor 2: The Klumps.'' As some summer films have faltered,
especially during a late-June slump at the box office, Miramax has
grown more aggressive about expanding the movie's release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we'll be on close to 4,000 screens,'' Weinstein said.
``We picked up 800 in the last two weeks alone. Basically, based on
this tracking, we're taking any theater we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   CAMP FOR 60-YEAR-OLDS
</P>
<P>
   Harry Shearer sat in the crowded set in Hollywood _ meant to
resemble a television station's control booth _ surrounded by the
bare-bones crew of a new movie he has written and is directing. In
the scene, Howard Hesseman, remembered by many as the disc jockey
Johnny Fever on the 1970s television series ``WKRP in Cincinnati,''
is playing a television producer trying to work out the details of
a new commercial for adult diapers. Shearer, tugged at his Spy
magazine T-shirt as he watched the scene unfold.
</P>
<P>
   The film, ``Call o' the Glen,'' is from a script Shearer began
six or seven years ago, he said, and is based on his fascination
with Bohemian Grove, the super-private power retreat in Northern
California where leaders from business and politics regularly
gather in a kind of summer-camp bonding experience. Famous for
guarding the privacy of its powerful guests and for forcing them to
do some of their own cooking and cleaning, the whole idea seemed
ripe for satire, said Shearer, who was actually invited to visit
the camp while he was doing research for the script. ``There is
just something that seems so goofy and sweet about men 60 and up
reliving their sophomore days at college,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Hesseman and Shearer (who plays the camp's chief cook),
the cast includes TV series survivors like Morgan Fairchild, George
Wendt, Alan Thicke, Kenneth Mars, Henry Gibson, Kurtwood Smith and
Ming-Na. It is being shot on newfangled digital cameras for a
budget of less than $600,000 by Visionbox Pictures, a new
production company hoping to exploit this less expensive digital
technology that theoretically will make it possible to make more
movies more cheaply. The entire shooting schedule is three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, Shearer said, is to take his time editing the film but
to try to have it ready for the festival circuit, perhaps as early
as the Sundance festival in January, and from there, to attract a
theatrical distributor. ``I knew this was a picture that no one
could really understand until they saw the performances,'' he said.
``You can't just read the script; you have to see Kenny Mars
reading the line. So we're hoping we'll get a better price by
presenting distributors with a finished film than by selling off
the rights beforehand to raise production money.''
</P>
<P>
   Shearer has been a steady presence in radio, television and
films for a quarter-century, as a regular on ``Saturday Night
Live'' in the late 1970s and early '80s, one of the writers and
stars of Rob Reiner's classic 1984 rockumentary, ``This Is Spinal
Tap,'' and one of the main voice-over artists behind ``The
Simpsons.'' In recent years, he has made a kind of cottage industry
out of playing fatuous television journalists, including a
talk-show moderator in last year's ``EdTV'' and, in 1998, an
interviewer in ``The Truman Show'' and a bone-headed anchorman in
``Godzilla.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Call o' the Glen'' script is one of just two he has
rattling around in his desk. He said he shies away from churning
out scripts for recreation or in hopes of raising his odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refuse to have more than two unproduced scripts at any one
time,'' Shearer said. ``I feel that my role in life is not to
produce something that will only end up as decoration in some
agent's office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
