<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably cool air will plunge into New England on Friday as
low pressure slides southward from Quebec. Puffy clouds will
proliferate in the afternoon as air heated near the ground ascends
into chilly air. A few light showers will dampen the high ground of
interior New England. Farther south and west, high pressure will
bring mostly sunny skies to the Great Lakes, northern Middle
Atlantic States and Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptional heat will occupy the central and southern Plains as
abundant sun propels temperatures past 100 degrees in many places.
Potent thunderstorms will erupt in the northern Plains and upper
Mississippi Valley near the edge of the hot air as a jet stream
disturbance intercepts a conveyor belt of humid air.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, clouds and a few claps of mountain thunder will
accompany low pressure moving into Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DELAYED HEAT
</P>
<P>
   Summery heat has been slow to come to Indianapolis, where the
temperatures has not yet reached 90 degrees this year. The average
date of the first 90 degree reading in the city is June 12, and
during a typical summer, the mercury reaches or exceeds 90 degrees
on 18 days. Heat has been suppressed, in part, because ample rain
since early June has kept the ground and vegetation moist. Part of
the sun's energy has been used to evaporate the moisture rather
than heat the air.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
