<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION-PROTESTS _ WASHINGTON _ Activists ranging from
card-carrying union members to the masked anarchists who besieged
the World Bank meetings announce their plans to protest at the
Republican and Democratic National Conventions. Charging that
neither political party is responsible to its constituents, the
disidents will hold shadow conventions in Philadelphia and Los
Angeles. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-COSTS _ Humans pay more for drugs than animals _ even when
it's the exact same medicine, according to a survey U.S. Rep. Lloyd
Doggett unveils today. High drug costs are an issue nationally,
especially for uninsured seniors, low-income families and others
who cannot afford their prescription medicines. (Roser, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-TEACHERS _ CHICAGO _ Spot story on Democratic presidential
hopeful Al Gore's appearance Thursday at the annual meeting of the
National Education Association, after speaking earlier in the week
to the American Federation of Teachers. Both teacher groups will
have formally endorsed him by the time he speaks. (Mollison, Cox
News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEYHOME _ John and Patsy Ramsey are selling their Atlanta
house, and gearing down their lavish lifestyle to pay off their
legal debts. (Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POPULATION _ WASHINGTON _ A report released Thursday examines
the record U.S. population growth and its effects on how Americans
live, including increased life expectancy, immigration, social
trends and information technology. The report's author is Martha
Farnsworth Riche, former director of the U.S. Census Bureau, and a
founding editor of American Demographics magazine. (Holmes, Cox
News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN-TRIAL _ Davidian wrongful death lawsuit trial
continues. Developing. (England, Waco Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   UTLAW _ Free airfare and a good time apparently worked in favor
of the University of Texas Law School. The number of
African-American students who plan to attend UT in the fall is
double the number from last year and officials believe it's because
of an outreach effort this spring that brought accepted students to
campus for a look-see. They want to expand to hispanic students
next spring. (Jayson, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA _ SHATILI, Republic of Georgia _ Destroying the
credibility of Russian generals who repeatedly issue statements
that the war in Chechnya is over, Chechen rebel leaders have
launched a new round of deadly attacks on the Russian army.
Throughout the 10-month-old war, the rebels have evaded Russian
attacks by holing up in secretive headquarters in the snow-capped
Caucausus mountains and escaping over the porous border with
Georgia. New evidence shows that rebels are taking refuge in
Georgia, while the Kremlin has undertaken a handful of incursions
into Georgian territory itself, threatening to turn what Moscow has
called a ``domestic conflict'' into a regional one. (Coker, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving on the NYT wire in the (i) International category
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   MILLIONAIRE _ Austin's recent spate of acquired companies has
left the rest of us wondering what it's like to be suddenly very
rich. How do these nouveau millionaires' lives change? Do they run
right out and buy cars? Toss in the hat for early retirement? Or
are they more conservative, knowing the money's just on paper?
Let's find a suddenly ricution)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving in Sports (s) category.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT _ While BellSouth ponders a renewed bid for Sprint, the
company keeps working to launch its wireless joint venture with SBC
by summer's end. But if Deutsche Telekom does bid for Sprint,
BellSouth is more likely to hold on to its wireless holdings and
make a play for Qwest. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DATA-STORAGE _ IBM Corp. and Compaq Corp. are joining forces in
an assault on the lucrative and growing market for data storage
that many see as the Holy Grail of the Internet for computer
companies. In a partnership valued at about $1 billion, IBM and
Compaq each will cross-sell a limited amount of the other's
products. Pletz, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   POTTER _ ATLANTA _ FedEx hopes the latest Harry Potter book will
work magic for its new home delivery unit. The Memphis-based
delivery giant has a special deal to deliver the first books for
Amazon.com starting Friday. It hopes the deliveries will raise the
profile of its new Home Delivery ground unit, aimed at competing
with Atlanta-based UPS. (Hirschman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
