<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, July 7 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Pristina, Kosovo) _ Kosovo's capital today is a
chaotic noisy town, but the hubbub scarcely speaks of solution of
Kosovo's many problems: A year after the end of the war here, chaos
and dislocation continue, manifested in the doubling or even
tripling of the population of this ramshackle town, now home to
more than half a million people. Mostly people from the villages,
they are refugees who have abandoned their burned out homes and
have sought work and shelter in the capital. The Kosovo war forced
about two-thirds of the province's 2 million people from their
homes. Hundreds of thousands remain displaced, living in tents and
shacks in villages, in drab and despondent refugee centers in
towns, or doubled up with relatives in cramped and unhealthy
surroundings in the cities. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map and photos, NYT6-9.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ There is a go-for-broke quality to
the Israeli and American approach to the coming Camp David peace
summit, which starts Tuesday with the stated goal of ending a
52-year-old blood-steeped conflict. But for the Palestinians, whose
participation is more reluctant, there is at best an aspiration
that the three-way, retreat-style meeting will serve as a stop-gap
measure to keep alive the stalemated peace process so that a
partial deal can be achieved by September. A news analysis by
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-B2B-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ As companies in practically
every industry rush to join business-to-business exchanges on the
Internet, regulators are growing concerned that they will face a
rash of new antitrust questions for which they are not prepared.
Known as B2B Web sites, these business-to-business exchanges create
a place for companies in the same industry, be it automobiles or
grain, to buy and sell goods, potentially saving millions of
dollars in back-office costs by setting up a national marketplace
online. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-HIGHSCHOOL (Weaverville, Calif.) _ When it learned last
year that a private company was offering college-level Advanced
Placement courses over the Web, the lone high school in this remote
gold-rush town thought it had finally discovered a perfect way to
mine the genuine academic potential of the Internet. It took the
Clinton administration up on its pledge that there was educational
salvation in new technology, and that the Web could help the
poorest schools approximate the offerings of the wealthiest. But so
far the results here and elsewhere have been ragged, suggesting
that a computer can be a crude substitute for a live teacher,
particularly when the students are so young, the stakes for them
are so high and the technology is so new. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-FAMILIES (New York) _ They fill the courtrooms and
hallways of the city's courthouses each day. In some cases they
arrive in force: siblings, children, friends, all there to show
support for a loved one. In other instances, they are women who
arrive alone, a solitary mother, wife or girlfriend there to
support a scorned defendant or bring to life a murder victim. They
are the families of accused criminals and crime victims, and they
are all in some form of mourning. They often display remarkable
grace and loyalty, but in just as many instances, those families
that show up show a more fallible side. Fights break out.
Relationships in the process of coming apart unravel completely in
public. Still, the families who fill the courthouses in ever
increasing numbers are not anonymous, and they very often have
impact _ great and modest _ in the outcomes of the trials they have
come to witness. By David Rohde.
</P>
</TEXT>
