<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4682 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CONNECT-WEB07-COX     07-06 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONNECT-WEB07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet site helps former Athens High students hook up and play
catch-up with old friends
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Michael Barnett sends e-mails to ``the first girl I
ever kissed'' 38 years ago. He's pals with his old flame's
boyfriend, who doesn't know that the woman in question and the
52-year-old Barnett once shared a memory and are talking again _
via a Web site for Athens High School, Athens, Ga., which ceased to
exist in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Athenshigh.com was the brainchild of Bobby Prince, 55, of
Venice, Fla., who graduated from AHS in 1963 and created the site
for all members of the classes of 1927 through 1970 to reconnect
with old friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like a visit home to a past that has been lost,'' says
Barnett, an official with the state Department of Corrections in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Prince, a professional musician, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone ever has friends as close as those of
their childhood,'' he says. ``Adults usually cannot open up to one
another and take risks like children can. The site equalizes the
ground for everyone, unlike in high school where the most popular
kids received the lion's share of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The site provides names, phone numbers, street and e-mail
addresses, personal comments, photos, a list of 20 Athens, Ga.,
boys who died in Vietnam, announcements and questions, such as ``do
you know where Betty Lou is,'' and links to information about
upcoming reunions. With a mouse click, users can even listen to the
Athens High fight song.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 1,200 people have registered at the AHS site, and the
number grows by 20 a week. It's averaging 1,300 hits a day.
</P>
<P>
   The site has even been a boon to reunion committees. Last week,
a reunion of the classes of '50 through '70 drew a capacity crowd,
thanks mainly to the Web site, says Frances Hoge Harper of Athens
who graduated in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard from a classmate named Jimmy Ashley,'' says Harper, of
Athens. ``He was so funny. He said, `Tell me what you've been doing
for the past 40 years.' We weren't even good friends then, but now,
what's great is that everybody is like a cousin to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Web sites for those who want to reconnect reflects a
burgeoning trend, especially among baby boomers, to find others who
came of age during the '60s. People 50 and older account for 23
million of the 132 million Americans who use the Net, the largest
of any age segment, according to Jupiter Communications, a net
research firm in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   So the Net is loaded with people finders, many with message
boards, like the AHS site and the Virtual Wall
(thevirtualwall.org). New sites pop up daily, now numbering in the
hundreds or thousands. Some cost nothing, but many charge fees. A
few will dig up almost any kind of info _ such as an FBI file on a
neighbor _ for fees up to $500. They offer the advantage of the
Internet's warp speed, with links to databases. There's even a site
for now-grown kids who moved every few years with their parents
from one military base to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 40,000 registered `brats,''' says Vann Baker, 43, who
runs Military Brats Online in Atlanta. ``There's a growing desire
to reconnect, and if you can go online and find an alumni group,
that's a good starting point.''
</P>
<P>
   Social changes since ``Leave It to Beaver'' days have dispersed
old chums, and hectic lifestyles keep most boomers too busy to form
bonds with neighbors or colleagues. Plus there's the tug of
mortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a vast conspiracy to keep us isolated from
one another,'' says Michael Dean Murphy, an anthropology professor
at the University of Alabama. ``This produces great nostalgia for
the intense, multifaceted friendships of our younger days. The
American high school is just the kind of medium in which intense
relationships can form.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are feeling our mortality, which forces us to look back to
a time when our whole lives were still in front of us,'' says
Gerald Celente, head of the Trends Research Institute in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy says millions of boomers have turned into ``cyber
gumshoes'' in the past few years. The Web offers them an anonymous
way to be nosy and to see who married whom, who's divorced, who's
dead, who made it financially and who didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Net also has proved a boon in finding family members for
reunions. Farley Daniel-Cottrell of Athens began researching her
family names of Maxwell, Audley and Couper on line and soon found
cousins stretched from Florida to Texas. Some 75 descendants of the
families that had once resided along the Georgia coast gathered on
St. Simons Island last month to meet each other and explore family
history. They toured old homesteads and gathered for a picnic,
where bagpipers provided the entertainment as an homage to their
Scottish roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just fell into place,'' said Daniel-Cottrell. ``We even had
a couple from Canada come to meet the 'American' Maxwells.''
</P>
<P>
   The net has fostered connections for such diverse folks as:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jennifer McCormick, 22, of Sterling, Va., who had been
separated from her father since her parents divorced 20 years ago.
Three weeks ago, her husband contacted US Search.com, and knowing
only her dad's Social Security number found the right guy. When he
heard from her via email, Richard McILvenna, 50, says ``it blew me
away. I'd just accepted she was gone forever.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thomas Marr, a 71-year-old Emory University law professor, who
used the Net to return a canteen once owned by a now-dead GI held
as a prisoner of war in Japan. He'd inherited the relic from his
dad. The only marking on the canteen was a name, Minini, scratched
on its side with a nail. Then he found in his late father's papers
a reference to a Carlo A. Minini. Using geneology software, Marr
found Minini's widow Bertha in Gallup, N.M. ``I looked up Carlo
Minini and there he was, with an address and a telephone number his
widow had never changed. So I called her, then mailed it. She was
very grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Rev. Ron Baskin of St. David Episcopal Church in Roswell,
who posted a message on the Virtual Wall (thevirtualwall.org)
trying to find friends he served with in Vietnam. Baskin, 71, who
became a priest after the war, found one close buddy, and ``it felt
great, special. You have a closeness and it's great to be able to
do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Vietnam vets use the Virtual Wall to search for buddies,
says Alan Greilsamer of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund, which
built the Wall in Washington. So do relatives of men who died, such
as Grace Walsh, 43, of Boston, who posted a message asking for
anyone who knew her brother to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard back immediately by email from my brother's lieutenant
who was with him the day he died. He said he'd always wanted to get
in touch. It's brought as much peace to him as it has to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, ex-Lt. A.T. ``Doc'' Stevens, 53, of Baker, La., met
Walsh at Atlanta's Hartsfield Airport and the two drove to her
mother's home in South Carolina. She also met Atlantan Ray Barnwell
at the airport, who was in her brother's unit, too.
</P>
<P>
   It's been cathartic for all concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grace was my saving grace,'' Stevens says.
</P>
<P>
   But many have used the net to recapture happier times.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Terry Vennes, a '62 Athens grad who lives in
Lawrenceville, for example, made contact with her best high school
chum, Emily Hoge Waldron, now of Richboro, Pa., after three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like the years have just fallen away, and I am so
grateful to be reconnected with old friends,'' says Vennes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have taken up where we left off some 30 years ago.''
Waldron says. ``We email each other at least twice a week and find
instead of discussing which boy we are now dating, we discuss how
to deal with aging parents and news of our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince says, ``This site has shown me that the Internet is far
from impersonal.'' It's a point well illustrated by Barnett, whose
journey on the Net helped him rekindle memories of that first
smooch, long before Athens High became Clarke Central after it was
consolidated with an all-black high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was at one of the dances at the YMCA when I was 13 or 14,''
he says. ``Guys don't forget things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   _Staff writer Reagan Walker contributed
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
