<SLUG> BC-CHRONIC07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women hold heavy advantage in overall health
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women continue to lead the way in healthier lifestyles over men
by smoking and drinking less and wearing seat belts more often.
</P>
<P>
   But they still don't exercise as often as men, results from a
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention national telephone
survey found. The survey, with more than 100,000 adult Americans
polled in 50 states, was conducted in 1996 and 1997; results were
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and public health educators use the results as a
barometer for how Americans are doing _ or not doing _ in efforts
to keep healthy and avoid the big killers: heart disease, cancer,
diabetes and other chronic diseases. Researchers said they found no
surprises in the latest survey that has been conducted since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the categories of overweight and obesity have gone
up in all states, all genders and all races,'' said Deborah
Holtzman, epidemiologist with the CDC's Chronic Disease Prevention
&AMP; Health Promotion center. ``But we knew that would be a trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, about 61 percent of men and 44 percent of
women reported being overweight, even though men were slightly more
likely than women to engage in leisure-time physical activity.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia in 1997, almost 10 percent more women reported being
overweight than the previous year, from 40 percent to 49 percent.
Some 69 percent of Georgia men described themselves as overweight
in 1997, up from 66 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, 300,000 Americans die prematurely because of being
overweight and not getting any exercise, second only to
tobacco-related deaths, according to the CDC.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released last October that included some of the
1996-1997 telephone survey data, the agency labeled obesity an
epidemic, holding the same potentially deadly threat as an
infectious disease. In that report, Georgia had the weightiest
problem of all states with a whopping 101 percent increase in
overall obesity among its residents from 1991 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone survey also found that more men than women in
Georgia smoked cigarettes, 25 percent to 20 percent, and that three
times as many men as women reported binge drinking, defined as five
or more drinks on one occasion (15 percent of men and 4 percent of
women).
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, more men than women reported going in for
colon-cancer screening, while women were more likely to have their
blood cholesterol checked.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more information:
www2.cdc.gov/mmwr/mmwrss.html
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
