<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE-TEACHERS-0707-CO     07-06 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEACHERS-0707-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE TELLS TEACHERS BETTER SCHOOLS WILL LEAD TO HIGHER PAY
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Vice President Al Gore repeatedly brought delegates
and guests to their feet as he outlined his education agenda
Thursday at the annual convention of the National Education
Association.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic hopeful also irritated some of them by
predicting that higher pay for teachers will require visible
improvements in the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are not going to lift the compensation for
teachers if they feel they aren't getting more than they're getting
now,'' Gore told the 2.5-million-member group, which includes 1.8
million active teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Several teachers said after his speech that Gore seemed to be
signalling that _ like Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
hopeful _ he had refused to rule out reliance on merit pay or
performance-based pay for teachers and other public school
employees. In the past, Gore has endorsed a limited experiment in
Denver with performance-based pay for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Revelling in the warm reception from delegates who had endorsed
him 7,553 to 889 in a secret-ballot vote on the Fourth of July,
Gore inspired many rounds of applause as he itemized the main
features of his education agenda without mentioning its price tag
of $115 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Summing up his views, he said he favors bringing a populist
``revolution to our schools, treating teachers like the
professionals that they are, reducing class sizes, modernizing our
classrooms and connecting them to the Internet, (and) giving
teachers the training and the professional development
opportunities that are needed.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the euphoria wore off, some NEA members said they were
miffed by the way in which Gore qualified his support for raising
the pay of teachers to the level of other professionals in other
fields with the same education and hours of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like he wasn't admitting that we already aren't
being paid enough now,'' said Lianne R. Bennett, a 7th-grade
language arts teacher in Medford, N.J. ``But I don't suppose the
other gentleman (Bush) is any better on performance-based pay, so I
guess we're stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Sullivan, a Bush campaign spokesman, said later that, while
Bush hasn't explicitly endorsed linking the pay of individual
teachers to their performances, he advocates local control, ``which
would let localities choose to do that, if they decide that's best
in their locality.''
</P>
<P>
   Linking performance to pay is a touchy issue with teachers in
the NEA. The day before Gore spoke, the convention turned down a
suggestion by its reform faction that it allow local affiliates to
negotiate such agreements with their districts.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two hours before Gore spoke, the convention
overwhelmingly adopted a resolution that satisfied both reformers
and traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
   The two-sentence policy statement said: ``NEA shall not promote
or in any way advocate merit pay or pay for performance. If,
however, an affiliate should be forced to negotiate or accept a
merit pay or pay for performance plan, the NEA shall provide
assistance to that local to protect the rights and benefits of its
members and will work to insure that any such proposed plan will
not be adopted unless agreed to by that local.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   National Education Association: www.nea.org
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore on Education: www.algore2000.com/speeches
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush on education: www.
georgewbush.com/issues/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's email address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
