<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4702 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      07-06 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG SISTER WINS IN WIMBLEDON MEGA-MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The big sister was still watching out for the little
sister.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that they no longer were alongside the
dilapidated hard courts of a Compton, Calif., slum with
neighborhood toughs trying to shove them out of line for the ice
cream truck. It didn't matter that they were standing on the
elegant lawn of the All England Lawn Tennis &AMP; Croquet Club,
engulfed by 13,812 gawkers and the world watching on television.
</P>
<P>
   The maelstrom had changed but the instinct hadn't. Surrounded by
interlopers, they pulled together. Venus Williams, 20, reached
across the net to clasp the hand of Serena Williams, 18, embraced
her as if to form a protective cocoon, and whispered words only
they could appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the pained epitaph to an occasion trumpeted all over
the planet, the Wimbledon War of the Williamses. To onlookers, it
was an event; to the participants, it was an ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, the big girl occasionally had picked on the little
girl because she wanted to protect her turf. This time she was
forced to.
</P>
<P>
   Venus's 6-2, 7-6 (7-3) semifinal victory over Serena Thursday
was utterly joyless. It earned Venus a shot at tennis's most
coveted title in Saturday's final against defending champion
Lindsay Davenport, who took care of Jelena Dokic, 6-4, 6-2, in the
near seclusion of the second semi while the press was busy poking
at and probing the sisters one more time.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little sense of accomplishment for Venus. Despite
their prematch claim that they're all smiles and no competition can
intrude upon their solidarity, the Williamses acted as if they'd
been ordered to clean their rooms and do the dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really bitter,'' conceded Venus.
</P>
<P>
   But it was business. Family business, perhaps, so delicate that
the girls' father, coach, and mentor, Richard, claimed he couldn't
bring himself to come to the grounds and watch. But business
nonetheless, a necessary evil dictated by the random heartlessness
of the draw and the sisters' spectacular success. The precious spot
in the final came down to Williams vs. Williams. Like it or not.
They insisted they would like it; they acted as if they most
definitely did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone had to move on,'' said Venus. ``It was either going to
be me or Serena. In this instance, it was me.''
</P>
<P>
   And Serena took it hard. She was curt with the press, in
contrast to her spontaneous eloquence in previous postmatch
sessions. Asked to assess the impact, she said, ``I don't know. I
lost in the semifinals at Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was a shock to many, except those conspiracy theorists
who believe that Richard rigs the results of his daughters'
confrontations and that he had declared this was Venus's turn to
sparkle. Asked about such a sub rosa subplot, Venus said, ``Not
that I'm aware of.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than predestination, the outcome was attributable to
Serena's inexplicable collapse. The effervescent sensation of the
women's draw through five rounds and owner of the only Grand Slam
crown in the family _ the 1999 US Open _ she was considered the
overwhelming favorite against Venus, whom she had beaten in their
last meeting, the 1999 Grand Slam Cup final, after losing their
first three at the Australian and Italian Opens in 1998 and the
Lipton last year.
</P>
<P>
   But sometime during the one-day interim between their
quarterfinal wins and their semifinal showdown, Serena's ebullience
disappeared. She came onto the court a step ahead of Venus, but
that was the last time she would maintain the lead all day. Her
performance was listless, her body language downcast. And Venus
looked no more enthused. The sisters had come out for warmups five
minutes early, but it was immediately evident that they weren't
eager for the celebration to begin but anxious to get the nuisance
over with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult,'' said Venus, ``because the pressure
was always on.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure surrounding the first semifinal sister act in a
Grand Slam event since tennis let professionals onto the property
in 1968. The pressure of trying to become the first
African-American woman to win Wimbledon since Althea Gibson in
1958. And the subsidiary pressure of sewing up a place on the US
Olympic team, which will be announced Monday; Venus and Davenport
were guaranteed two of the three singles berths, but Serena failed
to leapfrog Monica Seles in the WTA rankings for the last one, and
her only hope now is that coach Billie Jean King picks her for
doubles.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that Venus might spurn an invitation
to Sydney for the Games in September if Serena isn't chosen. She
didn't address that issue, but she did explain her sense of sibling
obligation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always the big sister,'' she said. ``I always take care of
Serena, no matter what. I always make the decisions. I'm always a
role model for Serena.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, she was a model of determination Thursday, overcoming
25 unforced errors, while Serena epitomized inconsistency,
committing 36. She and Venus engaged in the occasional
scintillating rally of which they're capable. But Serena couldn't
keep up with her elder. She displayed her self-disgust by dropping
her racket one time and bouncing it another. The problem was that
she couldn't bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   There were four breaks in the first set, and three went to
Venus. Serena seemed on the verge of asserting herself when she
broke Venus in the first game of the second set. But she squandered
two chances to virtually clinch the set by breaking to 4-1, instead
allowing Venus to close the gap to 3-2 after two deuces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't play well today,'' said Serena. ``I didn't feel
it. I'm very disappointed in the way I performed.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in the crunch. After letting Venus off the hook, she
allowed her to get back on track by hitting a two-hand backhand
into the net, thus getting broken to 4-4. The sisters held serve to
6-6, and Serena surged to a 3-1 edge in the tiebreaker. But she
didn't manage another point, and when she double-faulted to give
Venus the match, the protagonists almost froze over the abrupt
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Serena lowered her head and seemed to be crying, although she
said emphatically, ``Tears weren't coming down my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the two slowly walked to the net for the congratulatory
handshake and conciliatory embrace, and quickly left the court to
Davenport and Dokic.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't on it for long. Trading early breaks, including the
point that clinched the first set, Davenport needed only 50 minutes
to handle her unseeded 17-year-old opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The champion has about the most balanced perspective on the
tour, and she didn't begrudge the Williamses the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was pretty exceptional, two sisters playing in a
semifinal,'' said Davenport, the No. 2 seed. ``By no means should
myself playing Dokic overshadow that. I mean, that's pretty
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Unique, in fact. One wit in the stands expressed it early in the
match when he yelled, ``Go, Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just what they wanted to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
