<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RUSCHA-RETROSPECTIVE-     07-06 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSCHA-RETROSPECTIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: A LIFETIME OF WELL-CHOSEN WORDS AND QUIRKY MATERIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Calif., Fla., Ill., Texas, England)   By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During the summer of 1956, after graduating from
high school, Ed Ruscha left his home in Oklahoma City, hopped into
his 1950 Ford and headed west on Route 66 for Los Angeles, where he
was going to become a commercial artist.
</P>
<P>
   His timing was good. An art scene was shaping up. Walter Hopps
and Ed Kienholz were about to open the Ferus Gallery. A group that
included John Altoon, Billy Al Bengston, Wallace Berman, Ed Moses,
Larry Bell, Craig Kauffman and Robert Irwin was soon to get
national attention. Within a few years, the new Los Angeles County
Museum of Art would open; the Pasadena Art Museum would be a place
to see new art, again thanks to Hopps, who went to work there; June
Wayne would start the Tamarind Lithography Workshop, which spawned
Gemini GEL, one of the country's best printmaking shops; and
Artforum magazine would get off the ground in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The art produced was eclectic, but the city came to be
associated with the kind of work that Ruscha exemplified. It was
cool, sly, deceptively mechanical-looking. It had a self-regarding,
matter-of-fact charisma. In his case especially, it was born of
laconic Western spaces, strip malls, highways and the Technicolor
movie. Increasingly it came to be about film, an art about art.
</P>
<P>
   If you can catch the traveling retrospective of Ruscha's 40-year
career, now here at the Hirshhorn Museum, you should do so.
Ruscha's scrutiny of the world is truly American, and his art
hovers tantalizingly on the edge of slapstick, with enough
intimation of melancholy to keep you guessing. Its rewards are not
exactly tactile or sensual, paint being used interchangeably with
eccentric materials like vanishing cream and blueberries as if they
were equally dubious propositions for art, but the results are more
than just cerebral.
</P>
<P>
   Ruscha navigates a pregnant space between Pop and Conceptual
art. You read the words he paints, his ironic titles, and see how
they mix with his images, and you're sure something is up, just not
always precisely what. A sleight-of-hand brand of humor is at work,
which derives both from a natural lightness of spirit and a refusal
to condescend or moralize. Jasper Johns and Andy Warhol are the
obvious names with which to reckon in his case, but Ruscha's
buoyancy separates him, creditably, and has kept him bobbing along
consistently through the decades.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar story is that he had one of those eureka moments
when he saw a reproduction of a Johns ``Target'' painting in a
magazine in 1957. It gave him the conviction that he didn't have to
splash paint around like the Abstract Expressionists to be a
serious artist. He went to art school to study commercial design
and got a job as a layout artist and graphic designer for a local
advertising agency, but he realized that he didn't want to do that
after all. He traveled in Europe, where he saw more works by Johns
and by Robert Rauschenberg in Paris, and on the way back he saw a
Roy Lichtenstein show in New York.
</P>
<P>
   His early pictures combined his diverse experiences differently.
His first mature paintings, nods to Johns, consisted of words:
``boss'' painted in big, greasy black capital letters on a muddy
brown backdrop, and ``ace,'' its letters made into even more of a
sculpture in relief. The self-aggrandizing irony of the titles
spoke for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Then came ``Large Trademark With Eight Spotlights,'' which
recreated the 20th Century Fox logo, with its roving spotlights, on
a big, horizontal canvas, as if on a wide screen. It was organized
in oblique-angle one-point perspective, the surface flat, opaque
and anonymous, unlike ``Boss'' or ``Ace.'' This would become
Ruscha's consistent mode: deadpan, sneakily enigmatic. In its smart
use of typefaces and lettering, it also exploited his commercial
training _ the towering T in ``The Mountain'' is an example. It was
attached to icons of Los Angeles and the West.
</P>
<P>
   So when he painted a Standard Oil gas station in the same format
as the 20th Century Fox logo, he was again glorifying a Western
symbol, this time of the highway, and now additionally implying the
experience of driving past it, one-point perspective creating a
cartoon effect of the station as if we were rushing past it in our
own 1950 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Ruscha described what he wanted: ``The image of a train that we
have from movies is from lower right to upper left; it is a force
of exaggeration that we've seen many times. It parallels the
concept of speed, going from nowhere to somewhere, nowhere to
everywhere. If you can get that into a painting, then there is a
sense of accomplishment. There's a kind of conviction in the
awkwardness of doing that that appealed to me.''
</P>
<P>
   You could say that the appeal of awkwardness became one of his
themes. The plain books of photographs he put together in the early
60s depicting gas stations, ordinary apartment buildings, swimming
pools and parking lots _ tremendously influential on younger
artists _ were snapshots of nowhere places, often
indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   But like the painting of the Standard Oil station, they can seem
awkwardly beautiful even as they raise the question, What's the
point? The images are numbered (34 parking lots; 26 gasoline
stations; 9 swimming pools), as if a meaning might be involved, or
is there no meaning? Maybe the images are just another way for
Ruscha to number pages in a book. You can't be sure.
</P>
<P>
   A conceptual game, but time has a way of lending even the most
conceptual and nondescript of these images a degree of nostalgia.
Works in the show like ``Noise, Pencil, Broken Pencil, Cheap
Western,'' with its reproduction of an old dime comic book, have a
retrospective charm that was presumably the reverse of their
original intent. Except that in his ambiguity, Ruscha leaves enough
room for us to shift our chairs around and get an occasional view
from the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia isn't bad, it turns out. With their simulation of
scratchy black-and-white films, Ruscha's recent paintings bask in
it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on top of that, there is an unexpected lyricism to the
best work. It derives partly from the sheer fluency of the
surfaces, the words and images as smooth as polished stones in a
clear stream, with the concomitant result that meaning flows over
them without sticking.
</P>
<P>
   A few of his word-pictures end up as not much more than coy
one-liners: ``ice'' in red-hot letters, ``space'' in comic-book
sci-fi typeface against an almost empty blue field, and a squiggly
``jelly.'' But sometimes his words floating in vast colored fields
or against Hollywood backdrops can take on a surprising aspect akin
to actors isolated on a stage. They can look remarkably vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   This is another source of the art's lyrical effect. Ruscha, like
Johns, is famous for untethering words from their moorings,
exploiting linguistic instability to imply an instability in our
grasp of experience generally. A different way of putting this is
to say that his words and images get to make themselves over in his
pictures. They are largely freed from the past and sent out into
the world with a fresh identity and maybe a chance at a few minutes
in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   It's a classic American dream. It also happens to be Ruscha's
story.
</P>
<P>
   The show travels to the Museum of Contemporary Art in Chicago
(Nov. 20 to Feb. 5, 2001), the Miami Art Museum (March 22, 2001, to
June 3, 2001), the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth, Texas, (July 1,
2001, to Sept. 30, 2001) and the Museum of Modern Art in Oxford,
England (Oct. 28, 2001, to Jan. 13, 2002).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
