u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      07-06 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE ART: $30.4 MILLION FOR SOUTH AFRICAN COLLECTION; 1 MILLIONTH
VISITOR FOR TATE MODERN; AND $10 MILLION DONATION FOR ISRAEL
MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A rare group of old master paintings, French furniture,
silver and sculptures that once belonged to Julius Wernher, a
diamond merchant who was a governor of the South African
conglomerate De Beers, sold at Christie's here on Wednesday night
for $30.4 million, twice its $15 million estimate.
</P>
<P>
   In a packed salesroom, dealers and collectors bid relentlessly
for the best of the art and objects housed for nearly a century at
the Wernher family's two homes: Bath House, Piccadilly, and Luton
Hoo, a stately home in Bedfordshire.
</P>
<P>
   A small group of old master paintings and several extraordinary
pieces of silver were the stars of the evening. While the buyers
were mainly dealers, Christie's executives said after the sale that
many were bidding on behalf of museums.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Blumka, a New York dealer, bought a rare piece of
silver, a late Gothic figure of St. Sebastian dated 1497 and
estimated at $1 million, for $2.9 million. Officials at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art confirmed Thursday that Blumka was
bidding for the Cloisters, which is part of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diana and Her Nymphs Hunting'' (c. 1636), an oil sketch by
Rubens from one of the famous series made for Philip IV of Spain to
display at the Torre de la Parada, his lodge near Madrid, sold for
$4.6 million, nearly three times its high estimate of $1.6 million.
Experts said the sketch was considered one of the best examples of
Rubens' Baroque period. It was bought by the Savings Bank of Madrid
for the Prado, Christie's confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hazlitt, Gooden &AMP; Fox, the London dealers, bought Titian's
``Portrait of Giacomo Doria'' (c. 1531) for $3.6 million, nearly
twice its $1.9 million estimate. Christie's confirmed that the
dealers bought it for the Ashmolean Museum at Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   Another top price was paid for ``Saturn Devouring His
Children,'' a bronze cast from a 17th-century model by Pietro
Francavilla. Estimated at $940,000 to $1.4 million, it was sold for
$1.6 million to Cyril Humphries. Humphries was sitting next to
Robert H. Smith, the celebrated bronze collector who is chairman of
the National Gallery of Art in Washington, and people at the sale
speculated that Humphries was buying the bronze for Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from Wednesday's sale will go to the Wernher heirs and
to maintaining Luton Hoo.
</P>
<P>
   THE TATE'S CROWDS
</P>
<P>
   Last week, only a month and a half after opening, the new $214
million Tate Modern welcomed its millionth visitor. By now, more
than 1,063,161 people have gone to see the giant renovated power
station in the regenerated Southwark section of London, the first
new national museum in Britain in 100 years and its first devoted
solely to modern art.
</P>
<P>
   Before the opening, officials at the Tate estimated attendance
for its first year at about two million. Now, they say, they are
now hoping for twice that figure.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds are bigger than the first Tate Gallery, now called
Tate Britain, across the Thames in Milbank, has ever seen. That
museum broke a record in 1996 during its Cezanne retrospective,
when it averaged about 14,000 visitors a day. The Tate Modern is
getting about 15,000 people a day, down from 24,000 in May.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is also far greater at the new museum than at the
Guggenheim Bilbao, the three-year-old museum in the Basque region
of Spain designed by the Los Angeles architect Frank O. Gehry. In
its first year, the Guggenheim Bilbao had about 1.4 million
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to go to London to see art from the Tate. The
institution has just begun its first online art program. ``It's a
way of extending the frame of the gallery,'' said Nicolas Serota,
director of all the Tate museums. ``It makes art accessible to
millions.''
</P>
<P>
   The first commissioned work in the program, ``Uncomfortable
Proximity,'' a Web art project by Harwood De Mongrel, a team of
British computer artists, can be seen on the Tate's Web site,
www.tate.org.uk. It looks similar to the Tate's Web site in layout
and design but has new images and texts. It is parallel to the
Tate's main Web site, emphasizing the difference between them.
</P>
<P>
   A second commissioned artwork, ``Le Match des Couleurs,'' by the
British sculptor and installation artist Simon Patterson, will go
online on Wednesday. It features a recording of Radio France 1's
football commentator, Eugene Sacomano, reading the football results
for all the teams that have ever played in the French Football
League. He gives each team a color based on the hexadecimal
equivalent color system, a system of specifying colors on the
Internet. Both works will be online until June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not unlike the video artists of the 1960s, there are some
practitioners working only in this field,'' Serota said. ``And
there are others like Simon Patterson, who migrate and explore art
online.''
</P>
<P>
   GIFT TO ISRAEL MUSEUM
</P>
<P>
   The Israel Museum in Jerusalem has been refurbishing and
renovating its galleries one by one with donations. The latest gift
_ $10 million from Andrea and Charles Bronfman, of the family that
is selling the Seagram Co. to Vivendi SA, a French conglomerate _
will be used to renovate and reinstall the wing housing the
archaeology collection, including some of the world's best biblical
Jewish, early Christian and Islamic antiquities.
</P>
<P>
   The wing was built in 1965, when the museum opened, with money
from Edgar and Charles Bronfman and their sisters, Baroness Minda
de Gunzburg and Phyllis Lambert, to honor the 70th birthday of
their father, Samuel Bronfman.
</P>
<P>
   Since the space has not been touched in 35 years, it can no
longer accommodate a growing collection of material from newly
excavated sites throughout Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, Charles Bronfman has been a visible player in
Israel, both in the business and cultural community,'' said James
Snyder, the museum director. ``He recognized that archaeology is
the true and most important cultural patrimony of Israel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
