<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4712 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CONVENTIONS-PROTEST-H     07-06 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTIONS-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROTESTERS PREPARE FOR POLITICAL CONVENTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Protesters who clashed with police during meetings
of international agencies in Seattle and Washington plan mass
marches and candlelight vigils during the Republican and Democratic
national conventions, organizers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Group leaders said they expect about 30,000 protesters to flood
the streets of Philadelphia and Los Angeles to draw attention to
what they see as the corporate takeover of U.S. politics and
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   Among the chanting crowds will be some of the same
building-climbing, turtle-costumed groups that disrupted last
fall's World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle and that
skirmished with police officers at the April gathering of the World
Bank and International Monetary Fund in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   However, unlike the demonstrations in Seattle and Washington,
the protests will not focus on globalization, which refers to the
trade and investment ties among countries that opponents say have
led to increased job competition with low-wage countries.
</P>
<P>
   That issue will be addressed, but demonstrators will focus
instead on domestic issues such as campaign finance reform, poverty
and police power, the organizers said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both political parties are bought and paid for by a small
number of corporations,'' said Margaret Prescod, an activist for
the R2D2 Coalition, a national network of organizations
coordinating the protests.
</P>
<P>
   Until politicians are accountable to ``working people,'' she
said, the political system will remain under the control of
corporations that donate millions of dollars to politicians and
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you're looking at the global economy or the U.S.
Congress, they're both being controlled by the same people,''
Prescod said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Convention begins July 31 and ends Aug.
3. The Democratic gathering runs from Aug. 14 through 17.
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizers insisted that their demonstrations would be
peaceful. But Cheri Honkala, an R2D2 activist working on the
Philadelphia demonstrations, warned, ``If we are prevented from
exercising our constitutional right to protest, we will use massive
civil disobedience.''
</P>
<P>
   One protest group, the Berkeley-based Ruckus Society, has opened
demonstrator boot camps near Malibu, Calif., and in central
Philadelphia. Recruits are learning how to form human blockades and
to drape banners from high-rise buildings. They will use colorful
costumes to convey their message.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the protesters' pledge to remain peaceful, Philadelphia
and Los Angeles police are preparing for Seattle-type protests.
With help from the Secret Service and FBI, both cities have set up
broad ``no-protest'' zones around the convention sites.
</P>
<P>
   The off-limits areas stretch for blocks. They will include a
single location _ beyond shouting distance of each convention hall
_ where demonstrators will be permitted to assemble in shifts under
heavy guard.
</P>
<P>
   Similar protest ``pits'' were used at the 1992 and 1996
conventions, and demonstrators reluctantly respected their
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, protest organizers say they will not give up the
streets. ``The pits are like prisons, and we don't intend to go
there,'' Prescod said.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, police intend to confine demonstrators to a
section of Franklin D. Roosevelt Park, across a boulevard and large
parking lot from the First Union Center, where Texas Gov. George W.
Bush's likely nomination is scheduled. Philadelphia has adopted an
ordinance that bars protesters from wearing masks while engaging in
``harassing'' behavior. Many protesters in Seattle who clashed with
police wore ski masks and hoods.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles pit is a parking lot a block away from the
downtown Staples Center, where the Democrats are expected to
nominate Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to ensure the city can function,'' said Los Angeles
police Cmdr. David Kalish. ``We have to be cognizant of what we
have learned from other cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Roland Lee, Philadelphia Police Department spokesman, said:
``We're going to protect people.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters in Philadelphia will kick off their demonstrations on
Sunday, July 30, calling for universal health care. The next day,
when the Republican convention officially starts, a march against
poverty will be held under the banner of ``Economic Human Rights.''
Other demonstrations with separate themes, still to be decided on,
will be held throughout the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles protests will begin on Sunday, Aug. 13, with a
march in support of death row inmate Mumia Abu Jamal, a
Philadelphia activist and journalist who was convicted of killing a
policeman. His supporters say he was framed.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, as the convention opens, the theme will be ``Human
needs, not corporate greed,'' and demonstrators will focus on
poverty. On Tuesday, the issues are to be racism and gay rights
under the banner, ``An injury to one is an injury to all.'' Police
brutality and the growth of prisons will be the subject of
Wednesday protests. On Thursday, as the convention ends, activists
are scheduled to focus on immigration and issues of global justice.
A candlelight vigil is scheduled to coincide with the Gore's
acceptance speech that night.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
