<HEADER>
A4713 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BUSINESS-BJT07-COX     07-06 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-BJT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Friday, July 7, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MILLIONAIRE _ Austin's recent spate of acquired companies has
left the rest of us wondering what it's like to be suddenly very
rich. How do these nouveau millionaires' lives change? Do they run
right out and buy cars? Toss in the hat for early retirement? Or
are they more conservative, knowing the money's just on paper?
Let's find a suddenly rich Austin techie and tell his/her rags to
riches story. (Gee, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MILLIONAIRESIDE _ Aa chat with financial advisors about what the
nouveau Austin millionaire should do with their moolah. Hint: it
doesn't involve mattresses. (Gee, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-GIANT-BASEBALLS _ Atlanta will be awash in baseballs this
weekend.ACVB officials plan to display about 100 giant baseballs at
Turner Field, Underground, Peachtree Center and Centennial Park. So
far, about 115 balls have been sold and sales are ``right on
track.'' (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving in Sports (s) category.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT _ While BellSouth ponders a renewed bid for Sprint, the
company keeps working to launch its wireless joint venture with SBC
by summer's end. But if Deutsche Telekom does bid for Sprint,
BellSouth is more likely to hold on to its wireless holdings and
make a play for Qwest. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DATA-STORAGE _ IBM Corp. and Compaq Corp. are joining forces in
an assault on the lucrative and growing market for data storage
that many see as the Holy Grail of the Internet for computer
companies. In a partnership valued at about $1 billion, IBM and
Compaq each will cross-sell a limited amount of the other's
products. Pletz, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   POTTER _ ATLANTA _ FedEx hopes the latest Harry Potter book will
work magic for its new home delivery unit. The Memphis-based
delivery giant has a special deal to deliver the first books for
Amazon.com starting Friday. It hopes the deliveries will raise the
profile of its new Home Delivery ground unit, aimed at competing
with Atlanta-based UPS. (Hirschman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   UPS _ ATLANTA _ Following report that UPS and wholesaler
AmericasMart have a deal in which AmericasMart will offer a UPS
credit card. Retailers using it would earn credit toward delivery
services. Its the latest product from UPS Capital Corp., the
delivery giant's new financial services arm. (Hirschman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 9:30 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
