<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4717 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER07-COX     07-06 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: A bash _ and a bashing
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush was quietly celebrating his 54th birthday today
with his family in Austin. But as he returned from a noontime jog,
staffers jumped out from behind bushes and a gazebo yelling,
``Surprise.'' About 300 workers from Bush's office and presidential
campaign threw him a party on the lawn, singing ``Happy Birthday''
and serving chocolate and white cakes decorated with ``Happy
Birthday Governor.'' In Washington, he got less-friendly greetings
from the Democratic National Committee, which poked fun at his
relationship with oil companies with a cake decorated with oil
pumps.
</P>
<P>
   AND THIS WEEK, IT'S TIGHTER AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Just a week after polls showed George W. Bush with double-digit
leads over Al Gore, the latest Fox News/Opinion Dynamics survey
shows a close race between the two. Forty-two percent of
respondents said they prefer Bush, while 37 percent like Gore.
Green Party candidate Ralph Nader pulled 7 percent and the Reform
Party's Pat Buchanan got 2 percent. That means there's 12 percent
out there still looking for a place to go.
</P>
<P>
   ONE FROM COLUMN A, ONE FROM _
</P>
<P>
   Three members of Congress _ one Hispanic, one female and one
black _ have been named to leadership roles for the Republican
convention in the hope of presenting an image of diversity. Reps.
Henry Bonilla of Texas, Jennifer Dunn of Washington and J.C. Watts
of Oklahoma will be deputy permanent chairmen of the convention
that begins July 31 in Philadelphia, and probably will have
speaking roles. Campaign officials for George W. Bush say the
convention will reflect the diversity Bush wants in the Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   VETTING FROM EVERYWHERE
</P>
<P>
   Being named a potential running mate can get nasty. Special
interest networks are beginning their own vetting process. And, if
the politician has voted ``wrong''or taken offending stands, the
offended groups begin a concerted discrediting drive. Sen. Evan
Bayh of Indiana is getting an early thumbs down from abortion
rights activists, who don't want him on the Democratic ticket. Bayh
considers himself strong on choice and women's rights, but once
made one vote against so-called partial birth abortions. On the
other side of the aisle, Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge's veep
campaign also is in trouble over the abortion issue, with Christian
conservatives threatening a defection to Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   SHORING UP MEDICARE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore went to a suburban Chicago senior citizens center today
to cap a weeklong focus on health care by contrasting his Medicare
proposal with a Bush plan that he dismissed as ``a piggy bank for
big tax cuts.'' Gore said he'll spend $339 billion over 10 years to
shore up Medicare, and said George W. Bush's plan offers ``not one
dime.'' Flipping through charts, Gore said the Bush Medicare plan
raises questions about the future of health care for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   SPEEDING UP IMMIGRATION
</P>
<P>
   In his third recent address to a major Hispanic organization,
George W. Bush on Wednesday portrayed the Immigration and
Naturalization Service as inefficient and vowed to change its
culture to improve services for new immigrants. Bush pledged $500
million in new spending to cut the average time needed to process
an immigration application to six months. Addressing the annual
convention of the National Council of La Raza in San Diego, Bush
said the process now takes between three and five years; the INS
claims the average time is 12 months. Al Gore addressed La Raza on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   GOP WOMEN STRONG IN VEEP POLL
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole and Christie Whitman rank with the strongest
potential candidates to be George W. Bush's running mate, a new
survey shows. Two men were judged the strongest GOP candidates for
vice president in the national poll by Intersurvey. But both of
them _ retired Gen. Colin Powell and Sen. John McCain _ have said
they don't want the job. The order of preference after Dole, the
former Red Cross president and presidential candidate, and Whitman,
the New Jersey governor, were Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge,
Tennessee Sen. Fred Thompson and Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating.
</P>
<P>
   BEWARE, THE TAX MEN ARE WATCHING
</P>
<P>
   The IRS issued an election-year warning that churches, charities
and many other tax-exempt organizations should not engage in
political fund-raising or activities encouraging support for or
opposition to any candidates. The organizations involved are exempt
from federal income taxes under section 501(c)(3) of the tax code.
Contributions made to organizations that lose their 501(c)(3)
status are not deductible by the donors on their income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   BUTT OUT, SAY DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco money is not welcome by the host committee that is
raising money for the Democratic convention in Los Angeles next
month. Committee head Noelia Rodriguez signed an agreement not to
accept or solicit donations from any tobacco company or its
subsidiaries. This comes as the committee is still $3 million to $4
million short of its fund-raising target of $35 million. ``We look
forward to showcasing Los Angeles as the largest smoke-free city in
the nation,'' Rodriguez said. Philip Morris, one of the nation's
largest tobacco companies, has given $250,000 to the Philadelphia
host committee for the Republican convention, which begins July 31.
</P>
<P>
   GOING DOWN SWINGING
</P>
<P>
   Jack E. Robinson III, the beleaguered Republican challenger to
Sen. Ted Kennedy, appealed a decision by the Massachusetts ballot
law commission that he fell short of the needed 10,000 qualifying
signatures because some of those he submitted had been forged and
some were printed upside down. Taking his case to the state's
highest court, he challenged the ruling that 129 signatures were
invalid. If the court upholds his removal from the ballot,
Massachusetts will lack a Republican candidate for a Senate seat
for what is believed the first time in the state's history.
</P>
<P>
   POLS CAN ALWAYS DO THE SIDESTEP
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, who once regaled audiences with his wooden version of
the Macarena, knows he's not a skilled dancer. But he told an
interviewer in Philadelphia that he'd like to get better at it.
Gore often used the Macarena, which became a trademark of the 1996
Democratic National Convention in Chicago, to poke fun at his
reputation for having a stiff personality. He often asked audiences
for silence so he could do the ``Al Gore version of the Macarena.''
Then he would stand rigid for several seconds before asking, ``Want
to see me do it again?'' When the interviewer reminded him that his
wife, Tipper, thinks he's a good dancer, he chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE OK, BUT IF GORE COMES CALLING _
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman (D-Conn.) plans to seek a third term,
saying he'll make education reform his top priority in the next six
years. In recent months, Lieberman has been mentioned as a possible
running mate for Al Gore, but said he doesn't expect to be asked.
However: ``Obviously, if that ever happened, I'd certainly think
about it, but to me, it's a nonevent.'' Lieberman, 58, upset
incumbent Lowell Weicker 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING LOCAL TV BACK INTO THE GAME
</P>
<P>
   As televised political coverage migrates away from broadcast
television to cable news networks, a new project is setting out to
convince local TV stations around the country that political
coverage can also be good television. With a $1.3 million grant
from the Pew Charitable Trusts, the Norman Lear Center at the
University of Southern California's Annenberg School for
Communication is creating Reliable Resources, a two-year program to
develop tools to help local TV stations beef up their political
coverage. The project hopes to persuade stations to increase the
quantity of their political stories, while focusing more on issues
and how they affect voters and less on the ``horse race.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
