<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-JFK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGIC ERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1978, an Air India 747 climbed smoothly out of Bombay into a
calm but hazy night sky and began the customary right turn.
Suddenly it rolled left until its wings were past vertical,
steadied momentarily, then rolled left again and plunged 213 people
into the Arabian Sea. Investigators said the central cause of the
crash was pilot error. The captain, a 22-year veteran, apparently
became disoriented in the starless darkness and felt he was still
banking right when the plane was already pitched far to the left.
Making two turns to the left, he flew the giant plane, nearly
upside down, into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   This is possible, according to aviation writer William
Langewiesche, because airplanes often bank in a way that
neutralizes gravitational forces, so there is no seat-of-the-pants
sensation. The Air India passengers may never have known there was
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The story is retold now because of the National Transportation
Safety Board's conclusion Thursday that the ``spatial
disorientation'' of John F. Kennedy Jr. was a probable cause of the
fatal flight last July 16 in which he, his wife, and her sister
died.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was criticized posthumously by some for attempting the
flight from New Jersey to Martha's Vineyard in the evening despite
only 310 hours of flying experience and no instrument rating.
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom comes easily at a distance. Kennedy doubtless should have
accepted the offer of a flight instructor to accompany him on July
16. And the risk increased when the trip, planned for daylight
hours, was delayed into the evening. Kennedy was responsible for
three lives, not just his own. Still, the weather was favorable,
and Kennedy had flown into the Vineyard dozens of times, including
at least five times at night with no instructor aboard, according
to the NTSB. There is every reason to think the flight would have
been uneventful had not haze obliterated the visual horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Experience might have made a difference, but disorientation has
caused numerous accidents, the Air India crash being especially
well documented.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB has determined that Kennedy's ``failure to maintain
control of the airplane'' was the probable cause of the crash. But
it is a story of three vibrant lives cut short in an accident that
deserves more sorrow than blame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
