<HEADLINE>
ULSTER FLASHPOINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the parade season comes to Portadown, Northern Ireland, the
Orange Order wears two uniforms _ one of black-suited and
bowler-hatted respectability and the other a T-shirted and
ski-masked thuggery exemplified this year by the terrorist Johnny
Adair. The Orange leadership in town needs to repudiate the
violence orchestrated by Adair and make an unequivocal commitment
to a peaceful resolution of the parades controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen, sectarian Protestants, say they merely want to
walk down the ``queen's highway,'' in this case the Garvaghy Road.
But Portadown sits on a faultline where the Protestant heartland
borders the South Armagh frontier. When Orangemen troop down the
road past Catholic homes, they personify an edgy Protestant
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholics might be willing to compromise, but the Orangemen
refuse to negotiate on the pretext that they will not deal with
Breandan MacCionnaith, spokesman for the residents and an Irish
Republican Army veteran imprisoned for trying to blow up the
British Legion hall in Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   The peace process is all about forgiveness and freedom for
political prisoners who no longer pose a threat to society.
MacCionnaith has been out of prison for 14 years and no longer
seeks to overthrow the government. Adair was released last
September and last month threatened to shoot Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA has done an effective job of keeping their killers in
check. When Adair interjected himself into the annual Portadown
controversy, the Orange Order did nothing to restrain him. Instead
they sanctioned a campaign that spread to Belfast, Adair's home
base, where Protestant mobs disrupted the city to an extent not
seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Orange leaders in Belfast are trying to find a solution,
but the local Orangemen have to step forward. In 1998, three boys
were killed 50 miles away because of Portadown-related violence;
last year, a woman was killed by a bomb in Portadown itself. The
Orangemen of Portadown should not wait for death to deescalate this
perennial and needless confrontation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
