<P>
   OHIO-JUDGE (Columbus, Ohio) _ Candidates for State Supreme Court
here are usually so unknown that contestants with familiar names
have often won because, political scientists say, voters thought
they were actually voting for someone they knew. But this year, at
least two candidates for Ohio Supreme Court _ and quite possibly
all seven members of the panel _ may soon be wishing for those days
of glorious obscurity. A boisterous, multimillion-dollar election
battle for one seat on the court is making two candidates household
names, while drawing uncomfortable attention to all seven members
of the rancorously divided court. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   BOLINAS-REVEALED (Bolinas, Calif.) _ It is the Howard Hughes of
towns. ``There is no reason to come to Bolinas,'' Vic Amoroso was
saying, following the conventional wisdom in this famously
reclusive place that no publicity is good publicity unless it's
bad. ``The beaches are dirty, the fire department is terrible, the
natives are hostile and have a tendency towards cannibalism.'' Long
known for its live-and-let-live attititude (except for visitors,
who they'd just as soon not let live) this spirited community of
surfers, poets, artists, writers, and aging mavericks about 30
miles up the coast from San Francisco, has reached a tipping point
of sorts. By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   LEE-NUKE (Los Angeles) _ Federal prosecutors say a scientist
accused of security breaches at the Los Alamos Nuclear Laboratory
once sought employment in seven different countries and was in
contact with a Chinese nuclear institution. By James Sterngold.
</P>
