<HEADER>
A4735 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-AMTRAK-REVAMP-BOS &LR;      07-06 0326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-REVAMP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMTRAK PLANS NEW LOOK, PASSENGER   GUARANTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACOB H. FRIES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To revitalize rail travel and achieve Congress-mandated
self-sufficiency by 2002, Amtrak is trying to change its image,
redesigning its brand logo, and offering riders an unconditional
satisfaction guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers who are unhappy with their ride _ regardless of the
reason _ will be entitled to a certificate good for free travel on
the national railway at the same cost, Amtrak officials said
Thursday. The offer began July 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want a second crack at pleasing passengers,'' said
Karina Van Veen, an Amtrak spokeswoman. We know not every trip is
going to be problem-free, but with this guarantee, we think we can
draw people who are tired of flight delays.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Veen said Amtrak is the only passenger transit provider to
offer such a guarantee. The program is modeled after Amtrak's Los
Angeles-to-Seattle ``Coast Starlight'' service, which has offered a
service guarantee for three years. In that time, only 17 passengers
out of 1.4 million requested a travel voucher, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Thursday's announcement, Amtrak unveiled its new logo
_ three parallel lines winding their way to a horizon. It replaces
the ``pointless arrow'' design, which had been Amtrak's trademark
since its creation in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Amtrak officials announced plans to add new
routes and to expand into package delivery. The high-speed ``Acela
Regional'' between Washington and Boston should be running by the
end of the summer, Van Veen said. It was originally scheduled to
begin at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak, formed by Congress from a collection of failing
passenger railroads, is subsidized by the federal government. If
Amtrak is able to become self-sufficient, it will be the only major
independent railway in the world, Van Veen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
