<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-SITE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY CHOSEN OVER SOUTH AFRICA FOR 2006 WORLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Africa's dreams of hosting soccer's World Cup for the first time
were dashed Thursday when FIFA, the international federation,
awarded the 2006 tournament to Germany over South Africa in a
surprise vote.
</P>
<P>
   Though FIFA president Sepp Blatter had declared that it was
Africa's time to host the planet's most popular sporting event
outside of the Olympics, the 24-man executive committee chose
Germany by a 12-11 margin with one abstention.
</P>
<P>
   The loss, termed ``a tragic blow for Africa'' by South African
president Thabo Mbeki, was a bitter setback to a continent that has
had its nose pressed to the soccer's window for seven decades while
the sport's quadrennial showcase was staged elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, which will be co-hosted by Japan and South Korea
in 2002, has been awarded 10 times to Europe, four times to South
America, and three times to North America, including the US in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it does have to be in Africa,'' Franz Beckenbauer, the
former Cup player and coach who headed the German bid, had conceded
before the vote. ``But it's a question of when. We have to ask, `Is
Africa ready?' Are they ready? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Africans insisted they were. They already had nine of
the 13 required stadia in place and had planned to expand FNB
Stadium in Johannesburg from 85,000 seats to 110,000. They had
Blatter's outspoken support. And after rival Brazil withdrew on
Monday, pledging its help, the South Africans thought they had the
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, which hosted the Cup in 1974, was a decided underdog in
the final weeks of campaigning since England was expected to split
the eight European votes. But when English hooligans rioted yet
again in Belgium during last month's European championships, it was
a killer blow to England's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most FIFA insiders felt history and geography would swing
the vote to Africa. Though Germany led, 10-6, after the first
ballot, South Africa drew even with 11 votes apiece after Morocco
was eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   When England followed, the South Africans thought they were
assured of victory. Had New Zealand's Charles Dempsey voted their
way, as the South Africans claimed he'd promised he would once
England was out of contention, the tally would have been 12-12 and
the tie would have been broken by Blatter. When Dempsey abstained,
Germany prevailed by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised,'' acknowledged Beckenbauer. ``I'm not prepared
for this because you can't be prepared for this. It was a very
close result. We'd hoped for this but we couldn't expect it. We are
very, very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was a huge emotional boost for Germany, whose famed
soccer team has dropped to Third World levels since the 1998 World
Cup. ``You are the soccer idiots of Europe,'' the newspaper Bild
mocked after the squad returned home winless and humiliated from
the European championships.
</P>
<P>
   As hosts, however, the Germans should put on a first-rate
tournament. Sixteen of their cities _ most notably Berlin, Munich,
Frankfurt, Hamburg, and Cologne _ already have suitable stadia,
plus one of Europe's best rail and highway systems. ``We will show
our guests in 2006 that Germany is a country open to the world and
hospitable,'' chancellor Gerhard Schroeder vowed Thursday in
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
