<HEADER>
A4738 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MILLIONSIDE-COX     07-06 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLIONSIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You've got the bucks, now what do you do with them?
 &HT;    By Robert W. Gee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - First they buy a Porsche Boxster or a Baja
performance boat.
</P>
<P>
   Or both.
</P>
<P>
   Then they call the financial planner.
</P>
<P>
   The wave of wealth that has washed over the Austin tech
community the past three years has set in motion a dizzying display
of consumption, from cars and boats to homes so large the owners
might not set foot in all the rooms in a year.
</P>
<P>
   But after all of that spending usually comes a propensity to
save, to plan for kids' college educations or early retirements or
the desire desire to travel.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Kozun and Daniel Tapia of Axa Advisors LLC., who count among
their clients dozens of tech millionaires as well as builders,
developers and restaurateurs who have gotten rich off of Austin's
hot economy, offer a five-step plan for the instant millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   1. Set goals. Kozun recommends a vacation away from all
electronic distractions, like radio, television and telephone to
assess short-term, mid-term and long-term goals. ``Imagine the life
you want to live,'' Kozun says. Among considerations might be trust
funds for children, charitable giving or life insurance. And for
some people, early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   2. Get your team together. Hire an accountant, a tax attorney
and a financial adviser. Ask friends and colleagues for referrals.
Interview several to find someone with whom you can communicate.
Don't rely on the Internet for investing advice.
</P>
<P>
   3. Talk with your new team to refine goals and priorities.
Consider three areas: income taxes (try paying as little as
possible while converting stock options to safer investments);
estate taxes (plan to avoid paying high estate taxes after death by
setting up charitable strategies or trusts); and investment
diversification (provide yourself with an income stream for the
rest of your life).
</P>
<P>
   Most tech millionaires, whether they work at Dell Computer Corp.
or
</P>
<P>
   Vignette Corp., became wealthy through company stock. An
oft-repeated refrain from financial advisers _ and one that's hard
for many millionaires to follow _ is to convert some of that stock
to more secure, long-term investments, like mutual funds or bonds.
``If you have stock options, you have sweat equity in that
company,'' Tapia says. An advisor can provide an unbiased, outside
opinion of how much company stock should be sold to meet financial
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be too loyal, Kozun says. ``Don't treat your stock options
and your company like your 12-year-old dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A stock isn't like a bank savings account,'' he says. ``It can
go up as high as possible _ as high as your imagination _ or it can
go to zero.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Stick to your guns. Implement your plan and reassess it as
tax laws change and important life events occur.
</P>
<P>
   5. Don't watch the market every day; go to your annual or
quarterly reviews with your financial adviser, and live well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4739 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MILLIONAIRE-COX     07-06 2486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLIONAIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Purple-haired,
 &HT;    regular guy millionaire Nate Hess lives just like you.
 &HT;    Except for the cars. And trips. And the $100,000 stereo.
 &HT;    By Robert W. Gee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - In many ways, Nate Hess is the same person he
always was. He still refuses to buy his coffee at Starbucks because
he says they're too big and powerful. He stays up late at weeknight
concerts in crowded, smoky clubs. His music tastes are eclectic as
ever: One night it's jazz, the next it's punk industrial. He never
watches television. He still dyes his hair purple and wears six
earrings in his right ear and two silver studs in his tongue. He
works 60-hour weeks.
</P>
<P>
   You might not know it if you saw him sitting in the back of the
Continental Club, sipping a Guinness, wearing purple Chuck Taylor
sneakers, black jeans and a gray T-shirt _ the same outfit he wore
to work _ but Nate Hess is a millionaire. Hang out with him for a
few days, and you'll get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the purple hair, he's not too different from the
thousands of other recently made Austin millionaires who are
leaving a permanent stamp on the landscape of Central Texas. He's
relatively young (37) and free-spending. He's a techie who got a
job at the right company at the right time and is now sitting on
stock worth enough to start thinking about early retirement. He's a
California transplant who loves Austin's mix of fine dining and
Bohemia, live music and Birkenstocks.
</P>
<P>
   He's having the time of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what they say, 'the older you are, the better life
becomes,' '' Hess says, smiling gently from behind his brown beard
as he lounges in his downtown loft, a Dave Brubeck vinyl record
playing on a new stereo system that cost him just shy of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hess is one of the 17,000 new millionaire households that have
sprouted in the Austin metropolitan area over the past five years.
The number of total households in the Austin area with at least $1
million in net worth, excluding the principle residence, rocketed
to 30,700 in 1999 from 13,700 in 1994, according to the Spectrem
Group, a New York research and consulting firm specializing in the
affluent market. In the nation, there are 7.1 million households
with more than $1 million in net worth.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, according to the company's calculations, 68 of every
1,000 households qualif-- for millionaire status. That's slightly
less than Dallas and Houston, both at 76 per 1,000. In the San
Jose, Calif., metropolitan area, which would include much of
Silicon Valley, 129 of every 1,000 households are worth at least $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   An even more revealing picture of the accretion of wealth in
Austin is the rise in the number of households worth at least $5
million: to 2,500 in 1999 from 360 in 1994, a seven-fold increase.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the stock market over the late 1990s and the growth
of the tech industry have helped fuel the accumulation of wealth.
Many of those who became rich watched as their stock options _ in
the beginning worthless contracts that represented partial
ownership in a private company _ turned into millions of dollars,
sometimes in a single opening day after an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the market's recent tumble, many of these
millionaires, including Hess, seem to be doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   Hess is employee No. 36 at Vignette Corp. In the Internet and
software start-up world, the earlier the employee starts the more
options that can be acquired , which can translate into greater
wealth. Despite the fact that Vignette stock has lost roughly half
its value since its peak of $100.63 in March, many, if not all, of
the 330 people who worked at Vignette before its February 1999
initial public offeringare still millionaires today. Vignette has
been Austin's most lucrative IPO. Since the opening day, shares in
Vignette have split three times, including a three-for-one split.
</P>
<P>
   Hess still owns about 85 to 90 percent of his Vignette stock,
even though he has the right to sell almost all. (At Vignette, as
at many tech companies, employees can exercise the options to own
company stock over a four-year period.)
</P>
<P>
   He won't say how many shares he owns or what he's worth. But he
explained his wealth this way: ``Every individual has an amount of
money beyond which adding additional money wouldn't matter ... For
some people, it might be $10 million. For others, it's $50 million.
For others, it's $100 million.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hess, whatever that number is, he has arrived, he says.So
why keep working?
</P>
<P>
   For one, that magic number inches upward the more he tastes the
millionaire lifestyle. He also hasn't been at Vignette a full four
years, the point at which he will own all his original stock
options. And he's sure the stock will rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Hess is happy as field technical director, a
position to which he was promoted last fall. Despite work weeks
that can stretch six days and 60 hours, he enjoys getting up in the
morning and heading into the office, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hess strikes a casual and carefree pose worth noting even in
Austin. The fastest he's moved in weeks was likely on a recent
Sunday afternoon when he scampered from his outdoor seat at Little
City Espresso Bar &AMP; Cafe across Congress Avenue to his Plymouth
Prowler convertible so that he could raise the top just as it
started to rain.
</P>
<P>
   The nouveau millionaire moved to Austin in early October from
Silicon Valley, where he was one of the first people hired in
Vignette's sales office.
</P>
<P>
   No more bargain hunting
</P>
<P>
   Idle chatter around the espresso machine at Vignette, which
sells software to help companies build and maintain Web commerce
sites, often turns to early retirement, to life on the beach. Some
already have called it quits. Co-founders Ross Garber, 33, and Neil
Webber, 38, left the company and are now involved with civic and
philanthropic projects. A sales manager recently left and is
building a ranch in Lake Tahoe, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say you get bored if you stop working,'' Hess
says. ``But I've never talked to anyone who's stopped working and
is bored. If you're bored not working, you were probably bored when
you were working.''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks about the possibility of spending his days reading,
writing, listening to music, teaching high school math,
volunteering and donating to charities. He hasn't given away much
of his money yet: just some stock to his parents and two brothers _
enough ``to make a difference in their lives,'' he says _ and cash
gifts to his alma mater, Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   But he's found plenty of ways to spend it.
</P>
<P>
   First there was the purple Lamborghini Diablo. When he paid for
it last fall, he was struck by how small he had to write on the
check to fit in the sale amount. Then he bought the custom-made
stereo and in April, the purple Plymouth Prowler, a 1930s-style
roadster, for which he paid $40,000. All together, it's a change
from the 1981 Chevette that he drove cross country in 1986 for his
first job out of college at Intel Corp. in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been vacations Last summer, on a whim, he flew
to Berlin to see three performances by Tom Waits, a gravelly voiced
songwriter who spins romantic tales of drifters and drunks. That,
after seeing Waits in five shows in Oakland, Calif., and Los
Angeles. ``He's one of my favorite musicians,'' Hess explains
matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the millionaire reserved a spot at Plaza Lofts, to be
built at Guadalupe and West Fifth streets. The units will range in
price from the high $200,000s to $2.3 million. It will be his first
home purchase.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, when Hess was married, supporting his first
wife and her three children from a previous marriage, he was
writing computer code for Campbell, Calif., start-up HAL Computer
Systems Inc., and living paycheck to paycheck. Hess remembers how
just a couple of years ago, he would price shop at bargain travel
Web sites to shave $20 off an airplane ticket. Now he doesn't think
twice about buying a ticket with a few days' notice, as he did two
weeks ago when he flew to California to see Bob Dylan and former
Grateful Dead bassist Phil Lesh in concert. He flew out with his
girlfriend, also a Vignette millionaire, and met up with an old
buddy, another millionaire who retired from Sun Microsystems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Hess attributes his financial success mostly to luck. Vignette
is his fifth start-up. Only one other gave him a substantial
pay-off from stock options _ ``on the order of annual salary kind
of money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He works hard like a school teacher works hard. He only happens
to have been rewarded in different ways. Just ask his girlfriend,
Lisa Stanley, 33, who went from making $30,000 as a high school
history teacher to becoming a millionaire at Vignette in less than
a year. She was hired in the sales department less than a week
before the IPO. ``Please, how lucky can I get?'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to make some money. I wanted some context, some
life experiences ... I never dreamed I'd be where I am now,''
Stanley says. She still rents an apartment in Northwest Austin but
is thinking of buying a house. ``It has to have a jacuzzi,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Hess, who signs his e-mail ``woodstock,'' after the Peanuts
character, and is typically esconced in his favorite color, purple,
prefers not to get philosophical about his sudden wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is a basketball player worth what they're paying him?'' he
asks. ``That's hard to say, but is the basketball player arguing?''
</P>
<P>
   Hess plainly justifies his new spending habits by explaining
that he's doing just as anyone else would do with millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it was buy the stereo you always wanted, get a couple
of cars, be able to travel more,'' he says. ``Other than that,
pretty much life's the same. I'm still a geek at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But life has changed for Nate Hess.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the prospects of retirement before age 40, the
weekend jaunts to music festivals (two in May) and the Sunday
drives in a car worth $155,000, there is the artwork: Three Marc
Chagall lithographs sit on his apartment floor still wrapped in
boxes from a San Francisco gallery. He gets calls from friends
looking for a little seed money for start-up ideas. He gave $25,000
to one friend and considerably more to another.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the bare refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Hess eats all of his meals in restaurants. For dinner, he has a
semi-regular rotation with Stanley at the upscale Gumbo's and Jean
Luc's French Bistro, both within a half block of his Brown Building
apartment at Eighth and Colorado streets, where he pays $1,800 a
month for a one-bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've cooked a meal since I've been here,'' he
explains while munching on chips at Guero's, waiting for an order
of shrimp fajitas. His last trip to the grocery store, as he
recalls, was in December when he picked up six bottles of Odwalla
brand juice, flowers, fruit and a bottle of wine.
</P>
<P>
   In his new life, Hess says, ``cost pretty much factors out.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he insists, there is logic behind his extravagances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to only spend money on stuff I enjoy,'' he says. ``For
me, I enjoy music. So if I'm flying to Berlin to see Tom Waits,
it's worth it. I'm not going to buy 88 pairs of shoes just because
I can.''
</P>
<P>
   The young and the rich
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Hess has not squandered his fortune on cars or
paintings or shrimp etouffee. But his spending follows a pattern of
the young tech millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants the toys to go along with it,'' says Ed Kozun,
a financial adviser for Axa Advisors LLC, which helps techies and
other millionaires manage their money. ``For somebody who comes
from a background of not having a lot of money and it's suddenly
thrust upon them, they want that Lexus or that house in Barton
Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin's new tech millionaire class comes from a handful of
companies that have either held successful IPOs - like Vignette's -
or have been acquired for a lot of money. Agere Inc. was purchased
in January by Lucent Technologies for $415 million, and Charles
Schwab Corp. paid $488 million for CyBerCorp.com Inc. in February
</P>
<P>
   Often, like Hess, the new millionaires are young and enjoy fast
cars and nights out on the town. They are building mansions in the
hills and piloting big boats on Lake Travis. Consider the net
effect on the everyman: a tighter real estate market, higher cost
of living, longer waits for tables at restaurants, larger wakes at
the lake, more philanthropic spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole town is full of rich people,'' says Daniel Tapia,
manager of the Austin office for Axa Advisors LLC, which plans to
hire eight more financial planners by the end of the year to meet
demand. ``They could be wearing sandals downstairs. You can't spot
them like (in) other towns.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite the stock market tumble in April and May _ no Austin
tech firm emerged unscathed from the so-called market correction _
many of these millionaires are still millionaires. For those who
hitched their wagon to the wrong start-up and are still in search
of their dot-com fortune, there will be more start-ups, more
venture capital to burn and more wealth to create.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start-up action tends to grow exponentially,'' says Kim
Butler, president of Greywolf Consulting, a high-tech recruiting
firm. ``This type of money creates more opportunities. You'll see
more angels and independent investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Correction, shmorrection, says Hess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those bubbles have burst,'' he says. ``There are
people at Vignette and other places who said, 'maybe I'll wait a
while to buy a house,' but you don't get the feeling that they've
changed their lifestyle because the stock went down.''
</P>
<P>
   An unscientific survey of conspicuous consumption in Austin
seems to support his thesis:
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one homes valued at $1 million or more were sold in the
Austin area in May, according to the Austin Board of Realtors.
That's 300 percent more than last year. There are about 135
$1-million homes currently on the market. Sales at Lexus of Austin,
which also sells BMWs, are up 25 percent from last year. Austin
Boats &AMP; Motors Inc. has sold at least 15 family-style deck boats _
the maritime version of the Suburban _ for $40,000 a pop since
January, most of them since the stock market fizzle. That's
compared to three sold last year. And South Austin Marine has moved
about 10 performance boats, which range in price from $200,000 to
$400,000, since March, mostly to techies, in a pace on par with
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for the high-end boat,'' says Kenneth Black,
one of the owners of South Austin Marine. ``Austin is just a
high-quality town. It's a Lexus/BMW/Mercedes town.''
</P>
<P>
   And a purple Lamborghini town.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Robert W. Gee at bgee(at)statesman.com 445-3643.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
