<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAB, ISRAELI LEADERS SET FOR TALKS FACE SKEPTICISM AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ As Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat prepare for next week's summit, they'll both
be carrying a lot of baggage.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders are saddled with popularity ratings that have
plummeted, internal political struggles that threaten their
leadership, and a generally exhausted population anxious about the
shape of the final peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The summit set to begin Tuesday at Camp David could be the
decisive moment in the endgame of the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   But even if President Clinton _ who analysts say is doggedly
determined to make this a crowning victory as his presidency _ can
help Barak and Arafat hammer out the details of a final agreement,
the two leaders must return to the more daunting task of selling
the deal to their constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Barak faces a fractious political coalition that was already
unraveling just hours after the announcement Tuesday of a summit.
Two key partners in his One Israel coalition, a Russian immigrant
party and the National Religious Party, announced they would pull
out of the coalition. That would strip Barak of his mandate, and
leave him with a 59-61 minority government in Israel's 120-member
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The defecting party leaders say they are opposed to the
concessions they expect Barak will make in returning land to the
Palestinians of the West Bank, which was captured by Israel in the
1967 Six Day War.
</P>
<P>
   And this kind of internal political battle over foreign policy
issues has been endemic not only to this peace process, but
throughout Israel's history. An observation by former Secretary of
State Henry Kissinger from the 1970s seems as applicable today as
it was then: ``Israel has no foreign policy, only a domestic
political system.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is struggling to control a restive Palestinian population
that has waited for six frustrating years for progress on
Palestinian self determination, the marking of borders of what is
expected to be an independent state, the return of refugees, and
the release of Palestinian prisoners held in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
   Unrest in the Palestinian ruled areas has flared dramatically in
recent months. Usually Arafat has been able to control such
violence, sometimes even use it as a bargaining tool in
negotiations, but Israeli military officials say lately he seems to
have lost control of the growing popular anger.
</P>
<P>
   After six years of grueling stops and starts in the peace
process, the Palestinians have full or partial control of about 40
percent of the West Bank. Israeli newspaper reports say that Barak
may now be moving toward giving back as much as 90 percent of the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   This would mean having to evacuate a number of Jewish
settlements _ a lighting rod issue among religious extremists and
far right elements of the Israeli political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   And as Barak leans toward movement on the peace process, the
political dangers that surround him increase. A June 30 Gallup poll
published in Israel's Maariv newspaper, showed that Barak would
lose an election to his more conservative predecessor Benjamin
Netanyahu. The poll said that if an election were held today, 36
percent would favor Barak and 44 percent Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's popularity rating, according to polls published in
Israeli press reports, show him at an all time low of about 35
percent. But, for Arafat who presides over a rubber-stamp
Palestinian Authority legislative council, the problem is less
severe for Barak, who must survive in a system that is much closer
to a Western-style democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders' weakened political positions stand in contrast
to the last time Camp David served as an historic venue for a
Middle East deal. That was in 1978, when President Jimmy Carter
brought Israeli Prime Minster Menachem Begin and Egyptian President
Anwar Sadat together to sign the first Israeli-Arab peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A key difference, analysts here point out, is that Begin and
Sadat were both confidently in control of their countries, and went
to the bargaining table with strong political backing.
</P>
<P>
   But even with solid support, peace makers always risk the danger
of extremists from within. Sadat was assassinated by a militant
Islamic group opposed to the peace deal. And Barak's mentor, former
Prime Miniser Yitzhak Rabin, was assassinated by a Jewish religious
extremist opposed to the framework agreement Rabin first signed in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of their relatively weaker positions or maybe as
a strategic move, both Barak and Arafat were busy Thursday trying
to lower expectations for next week's summit.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the chances for success, Barak told reporters,
``It is not possible to assess _ 50 percent, like the toss of a
coin.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said it was unlikely that
disputes over borders, the status of Jerusalem, the return of
refugees, and the fate of Israeli settlements in the West Bank
could be resolved in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   And he was already suggesting that more high-level meetings
would have to follow those that begin Tuesday in the Maryland
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of this moment in the peace process, when Clinton is
urging both sides to make the compromises necessary to end 52 years
of conflict, is that the two leaders actually could benefit
politically _ in the short-term _ by its failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success is danger, and failure is not,'' said Zeev Chafetz, a
columnist for the English-language weekly Jerusalem Report.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Barak stands tough he could return as a hero who stood up
to the enemy and rebuilt his coalition,'' said Chafetz. ``And the
pressures are there for Arafat. I think if he comes back with a
deal that is seen as a bad deal, he could face more internal
problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
