<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MEDICARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SLAMS BUSH-BACKED MEDICARE PLAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Democratic presidential contender Al Gore on Thursday
accused his GOP rival George W. Bush of backing a Medicare reform
plan that would force senior citizens into managed care and
financially starve teaching hospitals, nursing homes and other
health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   In an address at a suburban senior citizens' center, Gore tied
his Medicare attack to his latest campaign theme _ that he is the
populist candidate fighting against a Republican opponent favored
by powerful interests such as the drug industry and insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a series of charts, Gore contrasted his plan to
pump $339 billion from the projected federal budget surplus into
Medicare with the proposals advocated by Bush, which Gore said
would put ``not one dime'' more into the federal health insurance
program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not stressed health care in his presidential campaign
and only recently highlighted Medicare reform during a speech
largely devoted to Social Security privatization. The Texas
governor has said he supports a plan developed by a bipartisan
congressional panel that would curb the rising costs of the program
by letting seniors shop for a variety of private plans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said, however, that the Bush-backed plan, opposed by the
Clinton administration, would put limits on how much the government
would subsidize health insurance premiums, which would force many
beneficiaries into lower-cost managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would be financially coerced into joining an HMO,'' said
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidate said that he has earmarked $40 billion
of the surplus for health care providers such as teaching
hospitals, which have complained that they were hurt by a 1997
balanced budget agreement between Clinton and the GOP majority in
Congress. That budget pact helped extend the life of Medicare by
cutting reimbursement rates to health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   But a Bush spokesman responded that Gore had stood in the way of
ensuring the long-term future of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gore's charts and graphs can't hide the fact that the
Clinton-Gore administration opposed bipartisan Medicare reform and
submitted a budget to cut Medicare funding by $70 billion,'' said
Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aide Sarah Bianchi said that Gore did not agree with the
scope of the president's proposed budget cuts for Medicare, and
instead proposed $30 billion in reductions to come from rooting out
waste, fraud and abuse in the program.
</P>
<P>
   As he has all week, Gore spent the day hammering hard on the
populist theme.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore, like Bush, comes from a prominent political
family and is the product of elite private schools, he sought to
portray his GOP rival as out of touch with the average voter.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the seniors that ``in this election for president the
fundamental choice has to do with whose side are you on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am on your side,'' he said. ``I want to fight for the
people. The other side fights for the powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign responded by accusing Gore of ``attempting to
reinvent himself, this time as a class warfare warrior'' _ his
seventh campaign persona, by the Bush camp's count.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's campaign is focused on bringing people
together while Al Gore is trying to pit one group of Americans
against another,'' said Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   Gore continued trying to link Bush to the big drug companies, as
his campaign put out a release noting that Bush media consultant
Alex Castellanos was also working on a television ad blitz,
supported by the industry, attacking the Democrats' plan to
subsidize prescription drugs for the elderly. Gore has claimed that
the group, Citizens for a Better Medicare, is a front for the drug
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett said that while Bush employed Castellanos' firm,
National Media, to make media buys, Castellanos was not involved in
the creative side of the governor's advertising effort.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president later received a rousing reception from
members of the National Education Association, meeting in Chicago.
NEA, the largest teachers' union, has endorsed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He told the more than 12,000 participants at the NEA convention
that he supports increasing educational funding and accountability.
Gore also received cheers when he told them that he opposes private
school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF FILE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
