<HEADER>
A4746 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     07-06 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BITTERSWEET AFTERNOON FOR THE WILLIAMS SISTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The ice cream truck didn't pull into Centre Court
Thursday, and Little Sister Serena didn't get her treat.
</P>
<P>
   Close, but no Eskimo pie. No Wimbledon title shot. No step up to
No. 1 in the family tennis pecking order. Big Sister Venus says she
always ``took care of my little sister, saw that she got her ice
cream. You know, little sisters, the babies, they get what they
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Thursday afternoon, as clouds and sunshine mingled in an
array that could be called bittersweet, the adjective 20-year-old
Venus Williams applied to her 6-2, 7-6 (7-3), triumph in the
much-anticipated intramural collision. Not when Big Sister was
keeping the sweets to herself and dealing bitter blows.
</P>
<P>
   Of course no good humor man wheels his ice cream truck with the
music blaring onto the grounds of the staid All England Lawn Tennis
&AMP; Croquet Club. Confronting such a spectacle, the Duke of Kent,
president of the club, might hemorrhage in blue.
</P>
<P>
   But in considering the long and unlikely way the sisters have
come, from a deteriorating neighborhood and a cracked, lumpy hard
court to a semifinal on the plush lawn of Wimbledon, Venus says,
``Maybe Compton (Calif.) isn't the most desired place to live. Not
in the top 100. But I still miss the ice cream trucks that came
around to the court. They were the best. I spent all my allowance
on Eskimo pies, ice cream sandwiches and popsicles.'' Their daddy
wouldn't let them have sundaes: ``Too expensive in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Citizen Kane had his cherished sled called Rosebud. Maybe, for
these two millionaires, their Rosebud is an ice cream truck. London
bookmakers, and almost everybody else, made 18-year-old Little
Sister the favorite _ you got 11 if you put up 8 _ and even Venus
thought Serena, the US Open champ, deserved that role. But she
wasn't averse to taking the popsicle away from the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was fun!'' Venus exulted as she came off the court to the
cheers of 13,812 parishioners in the venerable tabernacle of
tennis. ``We put on a great show. I ran faster, served harder than
ever before.'' Her eyes glittered. She was high on making the
second major final of her life, almost three years after being
flattened by Martina Hingis in the first, the US Open. She had her
eye on Saturday and the champ, Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she'd showered and composed herself, Venus was
almost reserved at her press conference. She didn't want to give
even the slightest impression of great gladness at her sister's
great misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sad for Serena,'' she says, meaning it. They are as close
and important to each other as cards in a deck.
</P>
<P>
   Serena had wept and was sulking. `She takes losing harder than
Venus,'' says daddy, Richard Williams. ``It's almost like dying for
her. I congratulated Serena. hey both played good. But I had to get
her on the phone to her mama in Florida before she started to come
out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sibling rivalry goes back a distance _ remember Cain and Abel?
Although nobody got killed in Centre Court, there may have been
slight brain damage from which Serena will recover.
</P>
<P>
   Cain and Abel didn't draw much of a crowd. But what must it be
like to duel your sister with a bludgeon at 30 paces, trying to
slug her into submission in a full house, as the rest of the world
peers over your shoulder? This is not a picnic in the park. This is
common blood being let, and searing emotion overflowing, no matter
which way the contest goes.
</P>
<P>
   They'd done it four times at such way stations as Melbourne,
Rome, Key Biscayne, Fla., and Munich _ nothing as meaningful as
this one _ and it's going to happen many more times. Possibly they
can steel their psyches and treat each other on court as strangers.
Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   No semifinal at the Big W had stirred such great expectations
since Chris Evert made her debut here in 1972 and squared off
against the defending champion, Evonne Goolagong. Their initial
meeting lived up to the billing. Goolagong came from behind to win,
4-6, 6-3, 6-4, then lost her title to Billie Jean King.
</P>
<P>
   But that was well before the ogling that the world-roving eye of
TV gives everything. Serena and Venus bounded into everyone's
living room Thursday, heralding a new, bruising era. Though their
date with history lacked the suspense of Evert-Goolagong, the
sisters dabbed it with passages of brilliant firepower and superb
point-saving gallops across the paling green landscape that were
breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   Venus galloped quicker, swatted more effectively, played the
must-points with greater severity and command. She seized four of
five breakers, made nine of 11 against her melt like a fizzling
rocket pop.
</P>
<P>
   Serena's five-win pleasure cruise to the semis, averaging 50
minutes per, amounted to a mere 13 games lost, just one on serve.
That had influenced a lot of people, including the bookies, but she
was playing flopsies and mopsies. Venus had been fired and hardened
by her finest win, a 6-3, 4-6, 6-4, quarterfinal in 2:14 over No. 1
Hingis. That showed. She was ready to take care of Little Sister,
though not as tenderly as in the ice cream days.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a horrible way to lose,'' Venus says sympathetically of
the concluding point: Serena's last serve at 3-6 in the breaker
wobbled like a lame duck and flopped quietly into the net. It was
like getting hit in the face with an ice cream pie. ``I couldn't
believe it was over. So abrupt. I wanted to keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   And they will. This one may have ended with a whisper instead of
a bang, but there's an abundance of banging to come from the
flamethrowing sisters of no mercy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
