<SLUG> BC-CANADA-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMAL ATTACKS IN NORTH WOODS FRIGHTEN NATURE LOVERS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEBEC _ A killer bear prowling Quebec's outback is panicking
campers and frightening droves of nature lovers out of the north
woods. The animal has taken only one victim, but Canada's great
bear scare _ heightened by lurid media reports _ grew into broader
public alarm over marauding carnivores after a wolf reportedly
attacked campers in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Military patrols were dispatched into the forests north of this
historic walled city after one of Canada's leading female
biathletes was mauled to death Sunday on a popular hiking trail.
Traps baited with boiled molasses and rotted fish were set in hopes
of snaring the renegade bruin.
</P>
<P>
   A black bear was trapped Thursday, but officials said they will
not know if the creature is the killer until forensic examiners
compare its pawprints to those found around the woman's body. They
wll also use DNA tests. A bear caught earlier in the week was
released after investigators concluded that the 100-pound female
was ``too small, calm, and gentle'' to be the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Beth Miller, a 24-year-old athlete from Yellowknife,
Northwest Territories, was on a biathlon training run near the
Valcartier military base when she was attacked by what officials
deduce was a 200-pound male black bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``She defended herself and tried to escape,'' said Dr. Yvan
Turmel, the coroner who performed the autopsy. ``But the bear
attacked and attacked. She had no chance of getting away alive,
absolutely no chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Canada is teeming with bears, fatal attacks are rare.
The last in Quebec occurred in 1983, when a black bear slashed into
the tent of a 12-year-old boy and dragged him into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife officials guessed that the bear either is suffering
from a brain disease or was startled by Miller pounding down the
forest path.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her running motion may have frightened him,'' said Dick
Russell, a biologist with the Canadian Wildlife Service. ``He may
have attacked in what he considered self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's death by tooth and claw generated coast-to-coast
headlines and grim warnings from wildlife officials. The attack has
especially sown fear among the tens of thousands of backpackers,
canoeists, and other outdoors enthusiasts seeking adventure in
Canada's vast tracts of wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that girl got killed, we decided to fold the tent,''
said Ruth Greenberg of Cambridge, Mass., who with her husband and
two daughters, ages 11 and 13, quit a camping spot near the
Saguenay River for a hotel in Quebec's 17th century old town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look at the historic buildings and eat ice cream instead
of communing with nature,'' she said. ``I'll leave encounters with
wildlife to the National Geographic.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear grew this week after a kayaker camping on a remote
beach in British Columbia was badly bitten in an apparent attack by
a timber wolf. After fellow campers chased off the beast, Scott
Langevin, 23, was transported by speedboat from Vargas Island to a
hospital in Victoria, where surgeons made 50 stitches to close
gashes on his head.
</P>
<P>
   Game wardens landed Tuesday on the island and shot two wolves
while wildlife experts puzzled over the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Bear attacks are not uncommon, although seldom fatal: About 40
people were killed by black bears in Canada and the United States
during the 20th century, according to Minnesota's North American
Bear Center.
</P>
<P>
   Canada has an estimated 400,000 black bears, which inhabit every
province and territory except Prince Edward Island. They infest
garbage dumps and are a nuisance in many national and provincial
parks. Some communities in Quebec dump spoiled apples, fish
entrails, and other delectables in wilderness areas to entice the
creatures away from suburbs and shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   The species is found in New England, but usually sticks to the
backwoods of Vermont, New Hampshire, and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian athletes training in the outdoors frequently encounter
bears. Only two weeks before Miller was killed, a military officer
wheeling through the same section of woods on a mountain bike was
chased by a snarling bear.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was ranked among the top 10 Canadian women biathletes. A
biathlon is a grueling sporting event that combines target shooting
with cross-country skiing. She was expected to win a place on the
national team for the next Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bears are everywhere in Canada, it's part of our reality,''
said Olympic gold medal biathlon champion Myriam Bedard. ``There's
nothing more beautiful than training in nature. But there is
danger, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
