<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TRIXIE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIRKY `SCREWBALL NOIR' IS A FRESH, FIZZY TONIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B-  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine Gracie Allen playing private eye, trying to lay a Lauren
Bacall veneer of confidence and toughness over her priceless babble
of screwy punch lines. That's Emily Watson in Alan Rudolph's latest
genre bender, a ``screwball noir'' (by his definition) directed
with the quiet smoothness of a sophisticated romance.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange mix for another of Rudolph's shaggy-dog stories
but then he's carved a most improbable career out of offbeat,
updated little genre pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, the versatile British actress of ``Breaking the Waves''
and ``Hilary and Jackie,'' plays Trixie Zurbo, a malaprop-spewing,
gum-chewing security guard whose nonsensical barrage of mangled
cliches and jumbled jargon suggests an over-medicated Humphrey
Bogart reciting Raymond Chandler from memory.
</P>
<P>
   Sent to a rustic third-rate casino, she falls in with bad boy
Dex Lang (an endearingly smarmy Dermot Mulroney), a shaggy,
small-time, would-be hood who is completely unfazed by her
delirious diction. Before long he pulls her into a mystery
involving smarmy, double-talking Senator Avery (Nick Nolte, with a
plastic grin and groping hands reaching for every woman in sight);
boozy past-her-prime showgirl Dawn (Leslie Anne Warren); and a
blackmail scheme involving a secret sex tape.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Lane is patter perfect as a small-time entertainer,
nightly playing his vaudevillian heart out to a crowd of dozens and
drinking himself to oblivion, who becomes Trixie's worldly pal and
Rudolph's wounded commentator.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph delights in dumping cliches on their heads, and this is
no exception, but what makes ``Trixie'' so much fun is not his
little narrative surprises (and frankly this mystery is less
hard-boiled than over easy) but the offbeat richness of his
characters. He embraces their foibles and gives his performers room
to invest them with a passion, a sense of being, and a
vulnerability that hints at a well of depth under their skin, deep
style and B-movie dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   In its own, unassuming way, ``Trixie'' is about how nimble
tongues and educated vocabularies can be so much more deceitful and
obfuscating than the sincere fumblings of people like Trixie and
Dex.
</P>
<P>
   With its gliding cameras, air of mystery and throwback soft-rock
score, it's a bit like ``Choose Me'' cast with buffoons, but at 117
meandering minutes, it's a long road with too many side trips. By
journey's end, there's little payoff beyond the time spent with his
strange and unusual out-of-time characters.
</P>
<P>
   In a summer of cardboard figures in splashy spectacles, that
makes for a refreshing change, an intriguing, entertaining and
altogether sweetly mystifying misfire. In other words, another
quintessentially Alan Rudolph picture.
</P>
<P>
   Trixie. Directed and written by Alan Rudolph. Cast: Emily
Watson, Dermot Mulroney, Nick Nolte, Nathan Lane, Brittany Murphy,
Lesley Ann Warren, Will Patton. Sony Pictures Classics. 117
minutes. Rated R for language and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
