<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4759 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-06 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE AND WHAT'S HIS NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In picking a running mate, Vice President Al Gore
has two advantages over Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore gets to pick last, after he has assessed the political
impact of Bush's selection. And while neither candidate has deep
bench strength from which to choose, Gore, unlike Bush, does have a
standout possibility who would likely take the job: House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, veteran Democratic representative from
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   There are only two names that bring much to a Bush ticket: Gen.
Colin Powell and Sen. John McCain. Both are widely respected
moderates more popular with swing voters than Bush is. But Powell
has clanged the door shut on the vice presidency. McCain also says
he doesn't want it, but even if he did, Bush has sent hundreds of
signals that he doesn't want the independent, unpredictable
Arizonan.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond those two, Bush's alternatives are a pale, comparatively
undistinguished lot with as many liabilities as pluses.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore doesn't have a fat list from which to pick either, he
doesn't need it because Gephardt neatly fits the bill. Why look
elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has been playing hard to get, saying publicly that he
would prefer to be speaker, assuming the House goes Democratic. But
he has not bolted the door as Powell has, and the implication hangs
in the air that if Gore asked politely, the answer would be yes.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt and Gore have been rivals for power for several
decades. They ran against each other for the Democratic
presidential nomination in 1988. They are similar in temperament
and equally politically skilled. But they do not really like each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Their hostility reached a peak in 1997 after Gephardt became fed
up with President Clinton's failure to help congressional Democrats
during his 1996 re-election campaign. Gephardt denounced the
administration's balanced budget deal and the immigration and
welfare bills, and he succeeded in defeating the president's
fast-track trade initiative. Gephardt's ``new progressivism''
agenda, aimed at countering Clinton initiatives, made him the
darling of what was left of the party's liberal wing and set him up
for a possible presidential bid against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But stuff happens. Along the way Clinton fell from grace and
Gore consolidated his position as heir-apparent.
</P>
<P>
   So Gephardt went to Plan B, softening his criticism of the
Clinton administration and concentrating on electing a Democratic
House majority in 2000 with himself as its leader. He has since
been a team player except for his fights against international
trade agreements, which he lost.
</P>
<P>
   In the early reaction to Clinton's dalliance with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky, Gephardt _ whose own private life,
insofar as is known, is squeaky clean _ called the president's
behavior ``reprehensible.'' So did everyone else _ except Gore.
</P>
<P>
   As the impeachment process rolled on, however, Gephardt defended
the president, criticized GOP partisanship and led the
congressional drive to keep Democrats united behind the White
House. Since then, he has polished a strategy of partisan
confrontation, building a record of philosophical differences with
House Republicans on which Democrats can run in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout all this, Gephardt has kept a fairly low profile. He
is more of a work horse than a show horse.
</P>
<P>
   His relationship with Gore is now more comfortable than it used
to be. And Gore knows that if Gephardt joins the ticket, he will
understand how to stay in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt would bring more than brains to a Gore ticket. Their
partnership would symbolize the coming together of the two wings of
the Democratic Party, the centrists shaped by Clinton and the
party's traditional liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Union members would be reinvigorated and newly excited about
working for the ticket. Gephardt carried their water on the trade
issues against the administration, and although he lost, they will
not forget. His presence might also help to neutralize Ralph Nader,
the Green Party's presidential candidate, who is trying to appeal
to the unions.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt could also help Gore capture Missouri, a swing state
that might be influenced by having a favorite son on the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   And the minority leader's finances seem perfectly in order. No
quickie deals on cattle futures.
</P>
<P>
   The down side of this dream ticket? The goodie-two-shoes
Gephardt tends to be boring. And Gore all by himself has already
captured the boring kingdom crown.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, as a leader-in-waiting of the legislative branch,
would never be so undignified as to say publicly that he would take
the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But we remember Senate Majority Leader Lyndon Johnson, who had
his own presidential ambitions and vowed never to accept such a
lowly post. His mentor, House Speaker Sam Rayburn, told him, ``You
go home from the convention with something,'' and when John F.
Kennedy called, Johnson answered.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing for the country, too. Without Johnson to carry Texas,
Kennedy would never have been elected president. He won by only a
half a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
