   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-HIGHSCHOOL (Weaverville, Calif.) _ When it learned last
year that a private company was offering college-level Advanced
Placement courses over the Web, the lone high school in this remote
gold-rush town thought it had finally discovered a perfect way to
mine the genuine academic potential of the Internet. It took the
Clinton administration up on its pledge that there was educational
salvation in new technology, and that the Web could help the
poorest schools approximate the offerings of the wealthiest. But so
far the results here and elsewhere have been ragged, suggesting
that a computer can be a crude substitute for a live teacher,
particularly when the students are so young, the stakes for them
are so high and the technology is so new. By Jacques Steinberg.
(The story has moved in ``a'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-FAMILIES (New York) _ They fill the courtrooms and
hallways of the city's courthouses each day. In some cases they
arrive in force: siblings, children, friends, all there to show
support for a loved one. In other instances, they are women who
arrive alone, a solitary mother, wife or girlfriend there to
support a scorned defendant or bring to life a murder victim. They
are the families of accused criminals and crime victims, and they
are all in some form of mourning. They often display remarkable
grace and loyalty, but in just as many instances, those families
that show up show a more fallible side. Fights break out.
Relationships in the process of coming apart unravel completely in
public. Still, the families who fill the courthouses in ever
increasing numbers are not anonymous, and they very often have
impact _ great and modest _ in the outcomes of the trials they have
come to witness. By David Rohde. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.)
</P>
