u p BC-GORE-NYT &LR;      07-06 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE DEMANDS ANSWERS ON MEDICARE FROM BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Asking repeatedly ``whose side are you on,'' Vice
President Al Gore on Thursday drew a sharp contrast between his
Medicare proposals and those of Gov. George W. Bush, branding his
likely Republican opponent the candidate of powerful industries.
</P>
<P>
   Gore lectured with charts and graphs at a suburban senior
citizens' center, seeking to put the debate over the popular health
insurance program for the elderly at the forefront of the
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would devote $339 billion to shoring up the program
over the next decade and adding a new prescription drug benefit for
all Medicare beneficiaries. Bush, he charged, had allotted ``not
one dime in his proposal for extending, strengthening, adding to
Medicare. Not a penny.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and again Gore threw pointed and detailed questions at
Bush, who rarely talks about Medicare. The governor has put forward
broad principles _ but little detail _ for creating more
competition between private and public health plans to overhaul the
Medicare program for the retirement of the Baby Boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to controversial questions about Medicare on which Bush
has not provided specific answers, Gore asked whether Bush
supported raising the Medicare eligibility age, or raising Medicare
premiums, or sending more Medicare recipients to health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Medicare is important to you, these questions are something
you should know the answer to,'' Gore told the audience of the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also used a version of an old union organizing slogan about
choosing sides as he tried to frame the election. ``In this
election for president,'' Gore said, ``the fundamental choice has
to do with whose side are you on. I want to fight for the people,
the other side fights for the powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's why the big pharmaceutical companies,'' he said,
``are supporting Governor Bush. That's why the big oil companies
are supporting Governor Bush. That's why the big polluters are
supporting Governor Bush. That's why the HMO's and insurance
companies are supporting Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally Medicare is an issue that plays to the advantage
of Democrats. So far this year it has not had the prominence in the
presidential race that Social Security has had, even though experts
say that it faces the possibility of insolvency earlier than the
retirement program does. Medicare provides health insurance for 39
million Americans who are elderly or disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign in turn accused Gore of practicing the
politics of class warfare. ``Governor Bush's campaign is focused on
bringing people together, while Al Gore is trying to pit one group
of Americans against another,'' a spokesman for Bush, Ari
Fleischer, said Thursday. ``We always knew the latest version of Al
Gore the positive wouldn't last long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign also called Gore and President Clinton
obstacles to keeping Medicare solvent because last year all four of
Clinton's appointees to a bipartisan, 17-member group opposed its
chairman's ideas for overhauling the health care program. The
group, charged with finding a bipartisan solution to Medicare's
fiscal problems, was unable to agree on a final report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore's charts and graphs can't hide the fact that the
Clinton-Gore administration opposed bipartisan Medicare reform and
they submitted a budget to cut Medicare spending by $70 billion,''
said Bush's spokesman Dan Bartlett, pointing to some savings
Clinton had proposed for the program in his 2001 budget. He said
Bush would not support those reductions.
</P>
<P>
   But along with those savings, Clinton has also called for adding
an expensive new prescription drug program. Gore's slightly
different version of the prescription drug proposal would cost $255
billion over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the bipartisan commission, headed by Sen. John B.
Breaux, D-La., fell one vote short of the 11 needed to approve a
final report intended to forge a consensus on how to overhaul the
program. Ten commission members, eight Republicans and two
Democrats, voted for major changes that would convert Medicare into
an arena for competition among public and private health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has criticized the Clinton administration for opposing
Breaux's plan. And the Texas governor's broad concepts generally
mirror those of the majority on the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux had proposed that the government, instead of paying
separately for each medical service, offer a fixed amount of money
to each beneficiary. The beneficiary could use the money to buy
private health insurance, through a managed care plan, or to enroll
in the traditional fee-for-service Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed offering Medicare coverage of prescription
drugs as a new benefit, with the government paying for drugs for
people with incomes up to 35 percent above the official poverty
level. Health maintenance organizations and other private health
plans would have had to offer drug coverage to Medicare
beneficiaries, but they could charge extra.
</P>
<P>
   In other changes, Breaux's proposals would have gradually
increased the eligibility age to 67, from 65, charged higher
premiums to high-income people and required beneficiaries to pay 10
percent of the cost of home health care visits (there is no such
co-payment now).
</P>
<P>
   Gore has taken a different approach, shying away from the
efforts to turn more of the program over to private insurers. He
would use $40 billion of the surplus and $75 billion of savings in
interest payments from paying down debt to extend the life of the
program until 2030. He would create a $255 billion Medicare drug
program. He would also enact nearly $30 billion in savings.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the elderly Thursday that he had opposed the Medicare
commission's report because he felt it would raise the eligibility
age, lead to higher premiums and push more people into health
maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, Bush's spokesman, said the governor generally supports
the concepts of the Breaux commission. But he said Bush had not
said where he stood on the eligibility age, and did not believe the
plan would lead to premium increases.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not actually set out his own Medicare plan but instead
named six principles for change. He has said there should be no
increase in payroll taxes. And he wants Medicare to offer every
recipient a ``choice of plans including the option of purchasing a
plan that covers prescription drugs.'' He has said Medicare must
cover expenses for low-income elderly.
</P>
<P>
   His aides say he has earmarked $5 trillion over five years for
shoring up Social Security and Medicare, including providing some
kind of a prescription drug benefit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
