<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4789 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-INVESTORS-$AD     07-06 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-INVESTORS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MANAGED PERSONAL ACCOUNTS, A CHALLENGE TO TRADITIONAL FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By DANNY HAKIM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Hoelzen has not given up completely on mutual funds. He
still has a few Fidelity index funds, but he has sworn off actively
managed funds. These days, Hoelzen has four money managers buying
individual stocks for him, overseen by his own investment
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like cruise control on your car,'' said Hoelzen, 45, a
marketing consultant in Atlanta. ``You can drive if you want, or
you can put it on 70 and just sit there.'' Usually, he said, he
prefers to just sit there and leave it to the professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the managed account, which many people view as the latest
threat to the 76-year-old mutual fund industry. It used to be that
only a privileged few could afford their own money manager, but in
the last few years assets in privately managed accounts have
swelled. Credit, in part, a bull market that has more than doubled
the number of millionaire households since 1983, to five million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest growth area is the managed account area,'' said
John Sharry, president of the private-client group at Phoenix
Investment Partners, which manages $66 billion in mutual funds and
private and institutional accounts. Households with $1 million to
$5 million to invest are the fastest-growing group he tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Not that you have to be a millionaire to qualify for a managed
account. Today, private portfolio managers serve investors with as
little as $50,000, but typically look for at least $100,000 in
investable assets. One reason is that technology now allows a
single investment professional to manage, in some cases, tens of
thousands of individual accounts.
</P>
<P>
   These managed accounts, known in the industry as ``wraps,''
because the various fees are combined, reached $451.9 billion in
assets at the end of March, up from $160.7 billion at the end of
1996, according to Cerulli Associates, a consulting firm. One type
is the mutual fund wrap, in which a consultant advises clients on
how best to spread their investments across a slate of funds. But
such accounts make up only about a quarter of the wrap market.
Privately managed securities accounts, also known as consultant
wraps, make up 58 percent of the wrap market, or $262 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That figure, of course, is well behind the $7 trillion in mutual
funds. But consultant wraps are seen as enough of a draw to the
fund industry's richest clients that many fund companies are
joining the business by offering the services of their top
investment managers through managed-account programs run by third
parties. In return, the fund companies receive a portion of the
annual fee, averaging 2.25 percent, charged by wrap accounts. (By
comparison, the average annual fee charged by mutual funds is 1.60
percent.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in five years every major mutual fund company will
also have a line of individually managed accounts,'' said Leonard
Reinhart, chairman of the Lockwood Financial Group, a consulting
firm, at a recent industry briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Most consultant wraps work like this: Clients visit an
investment adviser, whether a big broker like Salomon Smith Barney
or a small independent. With the guidance of an investment
consultant, clients then pick among scores of investment managers
from different firms. Usually clients spread their money into
several accounts and asset classes and then leave much of the
monitoring and managing to the consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the average wrap investor has a net worth of about $1
million and invests in a mix of accounts for diversification. At
most big brokerage firms, minimums don't come much lower than
$100,000. But a new batch of Internet-based financial companies,
like WrapManager.com and PrivateAccounts.com, are offering lower
minimums and lower fees for private accounts, though usually
without the additional advice of investment consultants.
</P>
<P>
   All of the programs allow investors to make direct investments
in stocks, in contrast to mutual funds. This lets clients avoid
particular stocks that they may already hold in other accounts. In
the case of Hoelzen, a client of Phoenix Investment Partners, he
alerted his consultant that he had worked for 12 years at IBM and
already had a big position in the stock.
</P>
<P>
   But the chief consideration for many clients, including Hoelzen,
is taxes, or how best to avoid them. One drawback of mutual funds
cited by managed-account boosters is that investors sometimes foot
tax bills that are instigated by others. For instance, if a
hot-performing fund suffers withdrawals, investors who stay are
stuck with a larger tax burden as the fund sells assets to meet
redemptions. Another problem is that investors may buy into funds
that turn out to be tax traps, because they already have large
taxable capital gains on the books.
</P>
<P>
   Such issues do not affect managed accounts; wrap clients can
also take defensive measures, like selling losing positions in one
account to offset gains in others, thus reducing tax bills. About
10 percent to 15 percent of Merrill Lynch managed-account clients
order their money managers to take tax-related actions during the
year, said Alan Sislen, an executive at Merrill who oversees its
separate-accounts program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really believe that clients have the best chance of success
if they go into these very disciplined programs,'' Sislen said.
They certainly work for Merrill _ its private account business has
more than doubled, to $52.6 billion at the end of March from $27.3
billion at the end of 1998. By comparison, the firm's fund unit has
suffered nearly $2.8 billion in net withdrawals in just the first
four months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fund companies including Invesco, Munder Capital and Navellier
already offer the services of their managers through separate
account programs, and recently MFS Investments, Oppenheimer and
Pilgrim Baxter announced plans to enter the business.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the largest fund companies are noncommittal. While
Fidelity's brokerage unit offers separate account services, its
vaunted fund management team does not participate. A company
spokesman said Fidelity had no plans to introduce any such
services. Likewise, Janus Capital, one of the industry's hottest
money management firms, does not offer its management talent
through separate account programs. Nor does the Vanguard Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that you don't need separate accounts to get
diversification and tax efficiency,'' says Joel Dickson, a tax
expert at Vanguard. The firm's five tax-efficient funds, Dickson
says, are an alternative for clients sensitive to tax needs.
</P>
<P>
   But for Hoelzen, easy tax management is one of the best benefits
of his managed accounts. While he says he generally doesn't think
much about his accounts, he pays more attention in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, at the end of the year I'll ask them to sell every
loss position that's over $50,'' he says. ``You have considerable
control over your taxation, so I never get those checks with a huge
capital gains distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
