<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-BIG-BROTHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'BIG BROTHER' PROVES ANOTHER BIG HIT FOR CBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also TV-BROTHER-REVIEW, moved in `e' category.)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' was certainly big for CBS in its first broadcast
Wednesday night, scoring a higher rating for its first episode than
either of the two previous summer reality television hits, `'Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' on ABC and ``Survivor'' on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' pulled in 22.5 million viewers _ more than ABC
and NBC combined _ between 9 and 10 p.m, but the show did reveal
some signs that it may not have the kind of phenomenal appeal, at
least initially, that the other summer hits have demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``Who Wants To Be A Millionaire,'' looking to revive
some of its own phenomenal edge, returned from two weeks of repeats
last night with an edition that featured the crowning of yet
another million-dollar winner, the show's fifth. And ABC held a
news conference Thursday to reveal that yet another million-dollar
winner would turn up within the next week on ``Millionaire,'' the
show that started the current trend toward reality formats imported
from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' which throws 10 strangers together in a house
full of cameras, clearly benefited from being placed directly after
``Survivor'' Wednesday night. The tropical island adventure series
continued to smash every rating record for CBS in the summer. This
week ``Survivor'' reached its highest numbers ever among young
adult viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' impressively held onto most of those young
viewers and even improved on ``Survivor'' among viewers between the
ages of 18 and 34. But the show suffered falloff in terms of total
viewers during each quarter hour it was on, indicating some
possible boredom with the show.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Survivor'' the audience levels have consistently risen at
the half-hour mark every week. Last night ``Big Brother'' declined
by over a million viewers at the half-hour mark.
</P>
<P>
   Overall ``Survivor'' had a 15.1 rating (each rating point
represents just over a million homes) while ``Big Brother'' had a
13.9 rating.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers may have been expecting something different: the first
``Big Brother'' show was not typical of the usual format for the
series in that it filled most of the hour with feature profiles of
the 10 participants and spent very little time actually with them
inside the house they will share for the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   The show faced a bigger test Thursday night when it began on its
own at 8 as a half-hour show. This one was in its usual format: an
edited version of what takes place in the house over the group's
first two days together. ``Big Brother'' needs to keep up audience
interest levels because it will be on five nights a week through
September.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Millionaire'' meanwhile, a math teacher from Tennessee
named Kim Hunt won the big prize by knowing that Lesotho is a
land-locked country totally contained within another country. (The
other choices: Luxembourg, Mongolia and Burkina Faso.)
</P>
<P>
   He needed help from a friend on the $500,000 question: In the
1964 movie ``My Fair Lady,'' who dubbed the singing voice for the
character Eliza Doolittle? His friend knew it was Marni Nixon _ not
Julie Andrews, or Shirley Jones, or Roberta Peters.
</P>
<P>
   The executive producer of ``Millionaire,'' Michael Davies, said
Thursday that he decided to discuss the upcoming million-dollar
winners because ``rumors were rife'' about more contestants winning
the big prize.
</P>
<P>
   As for the fact that ABC held a news conference about
``Millionaire'' the same week CBS was starting ``Big Brother,''
Davies said he agreed to the idea somewhat reluctantly because he
certainly did not want any hint of implication that his show was
creating million-dollar winners to counter CBS's ratings surge this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had about 2 to 3 percent of our contestants win the
million and that seems about the right percentage,'' Davies said,
though he conceded that having two big winners in about a week
strains the statistics a bit. Defending the overall level of
questions the show is asking, Davies said, ``I feel clearly a
contestant has to have a fair chance at winning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' has been compared with ``Millionaire'' mainly
because ABC initially tried to use the game show to stunt the
ratings growth of the adventure series. But Davies has been
effusive in praising the CBS show.
</P>
<P>
   Regis Philbin, the host of ``Millionaire,'' joked Thursday that
when ``Survivor'' first beat ``Millionaire'' in the ratings, ``I
sobbed that night.''
</P>
<P>
   But he later said he had seen only one ``Survivor'' episode
``and all they were doing was throwing spears at a banana.'' He
said he decided, ``It's just not for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' continues to be especially successful with young
adult viewers, the audience that CBS has had most trouble reaching,
and the audience that many advertisers pay a premium to reach. It
was up 10 percent among viewers 18 to 34 and 12 percent among
viewers 18 to 49 from the previous week, and in both cases had more
of the viewers in those groups than all three other big broadcast
networks combined. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1941EDT &QL; 
