<HEADER>
A4794 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-BONDS-$ADV09-     07-06 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-BONDS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL SENDS A KIND OF HUSH OVER BOND FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By ABBY SCHULTZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do not be put off by how eye-glazingly abstruse the subject
sounds: A bill making its way through Congress to change how
government-sponsored agencies like Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae are
regulated could, if enacted, have some profound effects on the
portfolios of millions of ordinary investors.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the legislative details. The Main Street bottom line
is this: The agencies' bonds may stop being regarded as an almost
perfect equivalent to ultrasafe Treasury bonds at a time when the
supply of real McCoy Treasuries is contracting sharply. Such a
change would be hugely disruptive to bond mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   More than one-fifth of all assets in government bond funds _
$26.5 billion worth _ are actually Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac debt,
according to the most recent data from Morningstar Inc. Taxable
bond funds keep one-eighth of their assets, or $65.5 billion, in
these issues; pension funds and 401(k) plans also hold big chunks.
The two agencies' total outstanding debt of $908 billion has always
been treated as if it were entirely risk-free, since the Treasury
was sure to prevent any default.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rep. Richard Baker, R-La., is pushing a bill to put much
more distance between the agencies and the taxpayer. While it would
not push the agencies entirely from under the government's wing _
they would keep their exemptions from taxes and security
registration rules, for example _ the bill would call into question
the implicit government guarantee of their bonds that Wall Street
has always believed in. Without their special status embodied in
current law, the bonds may suddenly be off limits to many current
holders.
</P>
<P>
   Under current regulations, for example, banks can hold unlimited
amounts of the bonds. Government figures cited by Baker show that
more than 4,000 banking institutions have more money invested in
them than they have capital _ a concentration that would be
considered unacceptably risky if not for the agencies'
unimpeachable credit. No administration could permit a default, the
thinking has always been, if so many banks would be imperiled.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill calls on the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and
the Federal Reserve Board to study banks' agency bond holdings,
which totaled $210 billion in mid-1999, and to consider imposing
limits. If the banks are forced to reduce their holdings, or merely
to stop being active buyers, the bottom could fall out of the
agency bond market. Others, like money market funds, that may hold
only the safest, most liquid securities may also have to sell.
</P>
<P>
   If the selling trend develops, the ripple effects may be broad.
Banks and other holders forced to dump the bonds may have to
scramble to find enough Treasury securities to replace them,
heating up demand in an already tightening market. Meanwhile, as
agency bonds lose favor and their yields rise, they may crowd out
high-quality corporate issues or depress their prices.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Baker acknowledged that changes caused by his
bill, if imposed abruptly, could be disruptive; he said he would
recommend they be phased in over several years.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also repeal the Treasury's authority to buy up to
$2.25 billion in agency debt. This liquidity facility, as it is
known, was meant to ensure that the agencies could obtain funds in
a crunch. It has never been used, and may no longer be enough to
matter much in a crisis, but its symbolic importance is great.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies' top-of-the-scale credit ratings would not
immediately be threatened by the bill, according to officials at
the two big credit-rating agencies, Moody's Investors Service and
Standard &AMP; Poor's. And Baker said he believed that if the agencies
remained well managed, their ratings would stay high. Nonetheless,
the door to a future downgrade would be opened.
</P>
<P>
   Stanislas Rouyer, a senior analyst at Moody's, pointed out that
the agencies' standing grew out of the deep and intertwined
relationships with the government that the bill is intended to
curtail. And Michael DeStefano, who follows the agencies for
Standard &AMP; Poor's, said any signal from Congress that it intended
to expose the agencies to more market discipline could erode their
special status in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   A change in the agencies' credit ratings ``would roil the whole
fixed-income market,'' said Scott Mather, an executive vice
president of Pacific Investment Management, a money management
firm. ``There'd be so many portfolio readjustments,'' Mather added.
``There are a lot of high-quality funds that just own agency
debt.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if the bill passes, Mather said, a downgrade for the
agencies is very unlikely. ``They are just too big and too
important to have that happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Jeffers, a Fannie Mae spokesman, is concerned that the
bill jeopardizes the agencies' ability to raise capital cheaply and
to pass along savings to consumers through affordable mortgages.
``We don't think it makes any sense to isolate one of the many
tools Congress gave us,'' he said, ``because if you do, you are
quietly or unintentionally unraveling the whole mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the markets are sensitive to every twist and turn in the
legislation's progress. In March, when Treasury Under Secretary
Gary Gensler lent support at a subcommittee hearing to some aspects
of the legislation, including repeal of the liquidity facility,
prices fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The bill remains a long way from becoming law. Baker expects it
to be approved by the subcommittee he heads before the end of the
current term. But he does not see it moving much further until
after the election decides which party will control the next
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings on the bill, however, have put the agencies' status
in play, and have aired concerns that Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac
have grown too big and too concerned with profits, rather than
fulfilling a public mandate to keep home mortgage money plentiful
and affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the real goal is just to have Fannie and Freddie come
to the negotiating table,'' said Casey Colton, a bond fund manager
at American Century Investments. ``There is some concern that the
agencies believe that their mission is almost a manifest destiny to
control a huge portion of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
