<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4796 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-STRATEGIES-AR     07-06 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-STRATEGIES-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFLATING THE PROMISE OF FOREIGN DIVERSIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MARK HULBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On behalf of financial planners, academics, investment advisers
and self-anointed experts everywhere, I apologize. It appears that
much of what you have been told over the last 30 years about the
benefits of international diversification has been greatly
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, according to a new study, those benefits are less than
half as great as originally thought.
</P>
<P>
   The case for international diversification, having been
tirelessly repeated for decades, is now numbingly familiar _
especially to mutual fund investors, because funds have been the
preferred vehicle for achieving low-cost exposure to many foreign
equities. By allocating some of an equity portfolio to
international stocks, the argument goes, you can reduce risk
sharply without having to forfeit returns over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   Yadda, yadda, yadda. Indeed, diversification has come to be seen
as an insurance policy on your portfolio _ and one with no premium
to pay. The linchpin in the argument has always been the supposedly
low correlation between market movements in the United States and
those in foreign countries. When one of them is zigging, the theory
goes, there is a good chance the other is zagging. As a result, a
portfolio that combines domestic and international exposure should
be less volatile than one invested in only one or the other.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the linchpin has a major structural defect:
The world's major equity markets tend to become highly correlated
during major sell-offs. As a result, international diversification
falters just as investors need its much-promoted benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The defect went undetected for many years, and it is easy to see
why: When comparing the overall performance histories of U.S. and
foreign markets, the two indeed seem rather uncorrelated.
</P>
<P>
   The defect becomes evident only when the markets' good and bad
months are examined separately. That is the approach used by
authors of a new study _ Kirt Butler, an associate professor of
finance at Michigan State University and the author of
``Multinational Finance,'' a popular college textbook
(South-Western Publishing), and Domingo Castelo Joaquin, an
assistant professor of finance at Illinois State University.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate the importance of their findings, we must first
understand how to measure the correlation between two asset classes
of any kind. Researchers use what they call a correlation
coefficient, a number that ranges from ``+1,'' meaning that the two
assets have perfect, or complete, correlation, to ``-1,'' meaning
that they have perfect inverse correlation. A coefficient of zero
means no correlation whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   If U.S. and foreign markets tracked each other to the same
degree in rising markets as they did in declining markets, the
coefficient, of course, would remain the same. But that has not
been the case. The professors looked at U.S. stock market
performance, month by month, from January 1970 through June 1999,
then divided the results into three categories of equal size: The
months in which the market had the biggest relative declines
(compared with the previous month); the ``calm'' months, those in
which it rose or fell little; and the months in which it rose the
most.
</P>
<P>
   They found that during the months with big declines, the
correlation coefficient of American versus foreign stocks was 0.48,
more than twice as high as the 0.21 in months with big gains. Only
during calm periods was there essentially no correlation.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a low correlation between American and foreign
equities is generally seen when the market is quiet _ precisely
when an investor doesn't need downside protection. And during
bearish markets, when an investor most needs that insurance,
international diversification provides the least protection.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, investors would want the highest correlation during
bull markets in American stocks. That is because upside volatility
is something to be sought. But even though the correlation is
higher in rising markets than in calm ones, it is still less than
half that of declining markets.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I hope the professors' research makes journalists
stop writing about the mysterious failure of international
diversification during market corrections. Such reports have been
all too predictable in the last decade. The professors' findings
don't mean that geographical diversification is without merit _
only that it is not the free lunch that has long been advertised.
</P>
<P>
   So what does all this mean for investors who diversify
internationally? More risk, for one thing. Because world equities
have turned out to be more highly correlated in bear markets than
experts had believed, internationally diversified portfolios have
been far more volatile than predicted. That, in turn, leads to much
lower risk-adjusted performance for such portfolios _ more than 50
percent lower, in fact, according to the professors' calculations
of the Sharpe Ratio, which relates performance to volatility.
</P>
<P>
   That poses a problem for investors: If they still want to
achieve the risk reduction they thought they were getting through
international diversification, they must forfeit a chunk of their
expected profits. In other words, what used to look like a free
insurance policy turns out to carry a hefty premium.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, if investors don't want to reduce their expected
returns, they will have to incur significantly more risk than they
previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   The professors' findings do not justify the elimination of
international diversification. The approach still makes sense, but
with reduced expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The study should also have the effect of shifting the optimal
portfolio allocations among various foreign markets. That is
because different national markets are correlated to different
degrees in down markets.
</P>
<P>
   By this measure, allocations should be reduced most in Germany
and Japan _ markets that are most correlated to that of the United
States during sell-offs. For a more complete list of the
bear-market correlations, investors can see the study at Butler's
Web site at http://courses.bus.msu.edu/fi/fi860/.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
