<HEADER>
A4798 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-WIMBLEDON07-COX     07-06 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON07-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Venus wins, and Williams sisters return quickly to sibling roles
</P>
<P>
   By
</P>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ For a moment Thursday, Centre Court was
quiet and Serena and Venus Williams were still, their heads bowed
on opposite ends at the All England Club.
</P>
<P>
   Almost in slow motion, the sisters walked to the net and clasped
hands over it. They exchanged weak smiles. Not until Venus put her
arm around Serena did it become obvious who had won their historic
Wimbledon semifinal matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get out of here, Serena,'' Venus told her devastated
sister, who was near tears.
</P>
<P>
   As quickly as that, they returned to their sibling roles and
left tennis behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always the big sister,'' Venus said. ``I always take care
of Serena. No matter what I'm always worried about her.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus collected her things from her chair, then grabbed a few
items Serena had left behind. Venus finally acknowledged her
victory by waving to the crowd as she and Serena walked off the
court without signing autographs,
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really bitter, but someone had to move on,'' Venus said.
``It was either going to be me or Serena. In this instance, it was
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena, the younger of the Palm Beach Gardens sisters at 18,
double-faulted on match point and lost 6-2, 7-6 (7-3) to her
20-year-old sister.
</P>
<P>
   Serena built a 4-2 lead in the second set and had three chances
to go up 5-2. But she collapsed there, losing 11 straight points to
fall behind again. In the tiebreaker, Serena went ahead 3-1 but
didn't win another point.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome didn't surprise Richard Williams, who took a
``four-cigarette walk'' around Wimbledon village during his
daughters' match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena hates to lose more than anything in the world,'' he
said. ``That's the one thing I was a little worried about. I
noticed in practice she was tightening up. I think Serena wanted to
win too much.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an uncomfortable match between lifelong best friends who
love competition but still struggle with everything playing each
other entails _ the attention, the mental aspect, the family
undertones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult because the pressure was always on,''
Venus said.
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to the tennis: Serena's big serve, powerful
groundstrokes and ability to run down almost any ball. Venus
presented the same problems. The result was an error-filled match
with brief flashes of brilliance on long, all-court rallies.
</P>
<P>
   But the pressure was apparent everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Even the 13,812 fans, who had been hoping for outstanding
tennis, didn't know for which sister to cheer. The sisters didn't
seem to know how to act, rarely looking at each other and not
celebrating good shots.
</P>
<P>
   And the so-called friends box instead was filled with business
associates, a coach and two new acquaintances _ singers Dionne
Warwick and Gladys Knight _ although friend and former player Zina
Garrison was an exception.
</P>
<P>
   Mom Oracene Williams was home in Palm Beach Gardens, watching on
television because she was tired of traveling. Dad walked the
grounds before the match but left during it and returned afterward.
</P>
<P>
   He walked around Wimbledon with tabloid reporters trailing him
while he smoked, trying to forget that one of his two young
champions was eliminating the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a hard day for me,'' Richard Williams said. ``I
didn't go to sleep last night thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters tried to ask his opinion of the match and give him
updates. He held them off until it ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard Serena had tears in her eyes and I almost had tears in
mine for my baby,'' he said. ``She takes losing harder than Venus.
It's almost like dying for her. I congratulated Serena. They both
played good. But I had to get her on the phone to her mama in
Florida before she started to come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he raised them for this day, starting on the
public courts in Compton, Calif., before moving to Florida to have
them train at academies and eventually alone on the courts behind
their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at where they came from and where they are now,'' he
said. ``It's the greatest tennis court in the whole world. The
world is watching.''
</P>
<P>
   What the world saw raised questions with some about a ``fix'',
though many skeptics determined the occasion might have overwhelmed
the sisters _ leading to 36 unforced errors from Serena and 25 from
Venus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Venus was going to win the match, just for outside
reasons. But I don't think it was fixed at all,'' said Lindsay
Davenport, who defeated Jelena Dokic 6-4, 6-2 in the other
semifinal. ``It seemed like they were trying. Mentally, I think it
might be tougher for the younger one to beat the older one.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams had watched his daughters warm up on court
together Thursday morning and called their match just another step
on the road to his goal. That's something he shared with Venus and
Serena when he agreed to come to his first Wimbledon this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since you're asking me to go, I'll go,'' he told them. ``But
we're going to win the tournament. We are professionals. Play like
professionals. We didn't come to ring the bell. We came to take the
damn bell back to America.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
