s f BC-MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL     07-06 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW PORTS IN THOSE STORM-BATTERED INTERNATIONAL MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By VIVIAN MARINO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors who thought they could lessen their risk by
diversifying overseas found little solace last quarter in
international equity funds, many of which underperformed their
domestic counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The funds fell by an average of 6.28 percent for the period,
according to Morningstar Inc., compared with a decline of 2.91
percent for all stock funds in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A big reason was the 180-degree reversal of fortune for once-hot
technology stocks. Many of last year's stellar funds became this
year's laggards by loading up on high-priced foreign Internet and
telecommunications stocks that took a downturn during a highly
volatile period. Plenty of domestic funds did the same, of course,
but the problem was compounded for foreign funds by adverse
currency movements, particularly the euro's slide, that further
eroded their dollar-denominated returns.
</P>
<P>
   But a few international funds managed to beat the trend, mainly
by resisting dot-com temptations and sticking with undervalued
old-economy companies on the rebound. Among them were Pilgrim
International Value and Longleaf Partners International, which
invested primarily in middle- and large-cap stocks in Europe and
Japan, and RS Contrarian, which invested heavily in energy stocks
largely in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really looking through the trash that everyone else has
thrown out, trying to find undervalued companies run by people with
integrity,'' said Andrew McDermott, who helps run the Longleaf fund
along with Mason Hawkins of Southeastern Asset Management in
Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott and Hawkins, along with Charles Brandes, lead manager
of Pilgrim International and Andrew Pilara, a co-manager of RS
Contrarian, recently shared some of their stock-picking and
investment approaches for the quarter. They also discussed their
market outlooks for the remainder of the year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brandes, 57, who runs Brandes Investment Partners of San Diego,
submanager for Pilgrim International, says countries and industry
sectors do not matter when he chooses stocks for the $758 million
fund. ``Our secret is to buy good companies at bargain prices, no
matter where they happen to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That approach brought Pilgrim International a return of 7.46
percent in the second quarter and 28.23 percent for the last 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   Brandes said he is a student of the Benjamin Graham-David Dodd
value approach to investing, detailed in the 1930s: To buy stocks
that trade at below-market ratios of price to earnings but that are
poised to climb.
</P>
<P>
   For Brandes, that means holding very few technology shares,
which account for just 1.8 percent of the fund's assets. Instead,
the bulk of the portfolio last quarter was in financial services,
consumer staples, durable goods and industrial cyclicals, mainly in
Europe with smaller portions in Latin America, Japan and elsewhere
on the Pacific Rim.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest contributors to his fund's performance, according to
Brandes, included Alcatel, the French telecommunications equipment
maker; Mitsubishi Heavy Industries of Japan; and National Power,
the British electric utility. All three had good cash flow, and
their stock prices posted double-digit percentage gains in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, 31, and Hawkins, 52, echoed many of Brandes' views on
value. The bargain-hunting style, out of fashion in 1999, helped
the $300 million Longleaf International fund gain 10.11 percent for
the quarter, second best among international stock funds, and 14.05
percent for the last 12 months. But the Longleaf fund mixes in some
growth companies, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think we can separate value from growth,'' Hawkins
said. ``We care more about what value will build'' in a company.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott added: ``We don't have a quarterly strategy, and we
don't have an asset allocation strategy based on geography. We're
strictly bottom-up.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund's currency-hedging strategy also helped. The managers
match the expected foreign-currency earnings of their holdings with
short positions in those currencies, cushioning the fund from
exchange-rate fluctuations. ``It's one of the reasons our funds
held up in the second quarter,'' McDermott said. ``We don't take
foreign-currency risks.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also why the fund avoids investing in Latin America or
other emerging markets, where most currencies are too volatile to
hedge easily. The portfolio is concentrated instead in Europe and
Japan, and focuses on services, financial stocks, retailers and
industrial cyclicals.
</P>
<P>
   Among the fund's top performers, according to McDermott, were
Diageo, the giant British food and spirits company; Safeway P.L.C.,
the British supermarket chain; and Sampo Insurance of Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo, whose many brands include Burger King, Haagen-Dazs,
Guinness and Johnnie Walker, ``was selling at the cheapest price in
its history,'' McDermott noted.
</P>
<P>
   Pilara, 58, found a few low-priced gems last year for the $100
million RS Contrarian, run by Robertson Stephens of San Francisco,
and much of the payoff came during the last quarter. As energy
costs have risen sharply in the United States in recent months, so
have the fortunes of many oil and gas companies whose shares he
accumulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's bad for the consumer is good for us,'' said Pilara, who
joined the fund's founder, Paul Stephens, two years ago when the
fund was mired in losses. Since then, Pilara has helped revamp the
fund's investment strategy by reducing its heavy concentration in
beaten-down industries like metals mining.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about 45 percent of assets are in energy, with the
remainder scattered in basic materials, communications, industrial
cyclicals, technology and elsewhere. Most of the holdings are in
Canada and the United States, Pilara said.
</P>
<P>
   The fund suffered along with other contrarian funds in the glory
years of the bull market, but it is starting to see daylight again,
gaining 10.22 percent in the second quarter, the best of any
international stock fund tracked by Morningstar. It gained 15.46
percent over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Among its top performers last quarter, according to Pilara, were
EOG Resources of Houston; Ivanhoe Energy of Bakersfield, Calif.;
and Anderson Exploration and Encal Energy, both of Calgary,
Alberta. All are involved in the production of natural gas, which
has soared in price recently, tripling on the New York Mercantile
Exchange in the past year. ``Everyone is talking about gasoline,
but we think there's a bigger problem with natural gas,'' he said,
referring to the sharp rise in its price.
</P>
<P>
   Though the energy stocks don't quite fit the fund's out-of-favor
criteria, Pilara said he had no plans to sell them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a contrarian fund,'' he said, ``and we're looking for
some more straw hats in the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
