<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      07-06 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LONGITUDE': `WHEN' WILL TELL YOU `WHERE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``For so long `Longitude' was my weird little story that no one
was going to read,'' said Dava Sobel, in a press release promoting
the new television version of her book. ``For me there is a sense
of disbelief about it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobel's ``weird little story'' about the scientific quest to
measure longitude has become an unlikely cottage industry: Her
184-page book, bearing the imprint of a small publisher (Walker &AMP;
Co.), became an international best seller after it appeared in
1995. It has been translated into more than 20 languages. Two years
ago, PBS produced a documentary adaptation called ``Lost at Sea _
The Search for Longitude.''
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday at 8 p.m. Sobel _ a former science reporter for The
New York Times _ completes her tour in Wonderland when A&AMP;E presents
a four-hour dramatization of ``Longitude,'' starring very serious
actors: Jeremy Irons and Michael Gambon. The film surprises, much
as the book did, by taking what might seem a worthy but dull
subject and making it sparkle.
</P>
<P>
   Much credit goes to the director and writer, Charles Sturridge,
who managed to remain faithful to the story's spirit while
reinventing it for another medium. He hasn't committed cinematic
cosmetic surgery, falsifying for mere prettification. Rather, he
has found a way to translate Sobel's lapidarian prose and complex
intelligence into more easily recognizable drama, without
oversimplifying.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sobel, the director wraps the narrative around the story of
John Harrison, the 18th-century carpenter, clockmaker and musician
who spent most of his life _ and much of his son's _ trying to
solve the problem of longitude. Shortly into the movie, the
filmmakers borrow the book's colorful and tragic example of why a
solution was vital. There is a shipwreck, caused by a navigational
miscalculation. The camera scans broken bodies splayed on the rocky
shore, giving a visual jolt to the flesh-and-blood aspect of this
scientific quest.
</P>
<P>
   While sailors before Harrison's time theoretically understood
what longitude was (the distance traveled east and west from a
fixed point), no one could accurately measure it because nature
offered no obvious place for the prime meridien, the zero-degree
longitude line. This was different from latitude, the north-south
measurement, which had the equator as its zero point. Thus latitude
could be plotted by calculating the length of the day or the height
of the sun or observing guide stars. ``Child's play,'' wrote Sobel.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. You can enjoy the film version of ``Longitude''
even if you are an adult whose idea of child's play doesn't include
calculating latitude _ or even fully comprehending it _ much less
longitude. You just need to understand, even vaguely, Harrison's
breakthrough: He understood that measuring time accurately was the
key, while leading scientists of the day were certain that
astronomy held the answer.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers reduce Sobel's thorough explanation to a line:
``To tell one's longitude, you need to know the time aboard ship
and time at home port.'' In other words, you need a timepiece that
works at sea. It's not enough for a science exam, but plenty to
move the narrative along.
</P>
<P>
   Although the movie, even more than the book, concentrates on the
quest itself, it delivers an admirable amount of information about
18th-century science and politics, about the intricacies of early
watchmaking and even about the effect of centrifugal force on a
clock's accuracy. Heady stuff for a Sunday evening at home, yet in
this context, strangely moving.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers have also amplified the book's political
intrigues, underscored the relationship between Harrison and his
son William (played by Ian Hart) and added vivid scenes of
floggings, presumably to keep viewers alert and excited.
</P>
<P>
   To make the story more accessible, the writer-director Sturridge
gave one of Sobel's minor characters a starring role and then chose
a fine actor to fill it. Jeremy Irons plays Rupert Gould, the World
War I Royal Air Force veteran who rescued John Harrison's clocks
and history from oblivion. Gould's preoccupation, in turn, helped
him recover from a wartime nervous breakdown. With his soulful
voice and haunted intelligence, Irons beautifully conveys the
redemptive power of certain compulsions without overlooking what
can be ruinous in them.
</P>
<P>
   His exquisite neurosis makes a striking counterpoint to Michael
Gambon's earthy and barely combed Harrison, who always looks as
though something is unbuttoned somewhere. Gambon gives a vibrant
portrayal of a self-taught man for whom knowledge and intuition are
the same thing. He also doesn't separate the theoretical from the
practical. He wants to win the Longitude Prize (there actually was
one, the equivalent of $5 million today, because the British
government was so desperate to stop its ships from crashing into
rocks). But the money seems to be an excuse for him to continue
with his obsession.
</P>
<P>
   In Sobel's book, Harrison was at center stage and Gould occupied
slightly more than three pages, near the end. But Sturridge has the
two men share the spotlight. Gould is on-screen almost from the
beginning, acting as a narrator, and Harrison's legatee and alter
ego, even though they lived two centuries apart.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the constant shifts in time are confusing, as the
screen fills with period costumes and story lines from two
different epochs. Sometimes Sturridge seems to stretch the
parallels between the two lives (though, plausibly, the emotionally
unstable Gould might have become so absorbed in Harrison that he
began to see linkages everywhere).
</P>
<P>
   But in the main Sturridge deftly uses Gould to shine light on
Harrison's quixotic determination and to translate his
accomplishments for nonscientists. Gould did just this kind of
thing for the BBC, on radio programs aimed at children. Sturridge
uses one of these BBC broadcasts to give Gould the opportunity to
underscore the movie's central theme.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of explainer that, depending on language and
delivery, can either stop a picture cold or inspire a rush of
emotion, as complicated matters become clear. This speech works. In
the writing, Sturridge obtained elegant simplicity, and Irons
invests the words with enormous heart and meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as Gould, in a gentle voice, he tells the children
listening to close their eyes and think a thought no one has ever
thought before, without paying any attention to anyone else around
them. ``Most of us with our eyes closed just see the dark,'' he
says. ``But the artist or the scientist can sometimes see something
new, something never thought of before. It's these ideas that can
change our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Those intersecting lines on the globe will never look the same
again.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LONGITUDE'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Sunday on A&AMP;E
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Charles Sturridge and based on the Dava
Sobel book. Selwyn Roberts, producer; Peter Hannan, director of
photography. Original music by Geoffrey Burgon. An A&AMP;E/Granada
co-production. Pippa Scott and Antony Root, executive producers for
Granada. Delia Fine, executive producer for A&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   With: Michael Gambon (John Harrison), Jeremy Irons (Rupert
Gould), Ian Hart (William Harrison), Anna Chancellor (Muriel
Gould), Samuel West (Maskelyne); Gemma Jones (Elizabeth Harrison),
Brian Cox (Lord Morton), Barbara Leigh-Hunt (Dodo), Jonathan Coy
(Admiral Cloudisley) and Nicholas Rowe (King George III).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
