<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4806 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WIMBLEDONNOTES07-COX     07-06 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDONNOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England - It's hard to forget the image of Venus
Williams sitting under a black hood, morosely watching her younger
sister win the U.S. Open last year.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it's so easy to wonder if this round wasn't arranged,
if - because Serena Williams already has her first Grand Slam -
someone hadn't decided Venus' chance will come at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Watching only the tennis, that might seem possible. Each time
one broke a service game, the other broke back. Serena won just
2-of-11 break points and lost her serve four times after not having
lost it at all since the first round.
</P>
<P>
   John McEnroe, who called the match for the British Broadcasting
Corp., floated the theory of a ``fix'' earlier this week. Players
have hinted they think the Williamses matches involve more than
tennis. Even Chris Evert, who called the sisters' match for NBC,
said she hopes it's all about the stronger competitor when Venus
and Serena play.
</P>
<P>
   And Richard Williams has been so omnipresent, outspoken and
outrageous that it isn't hard to believe he could manipulate
anything, including the outcome of his daughters' matches.
Certainly convincing Serena to throw the match for her big sister
would be simple, right?
</P>
<P>
   But not if you watched Serena's face.
</P>
<P>
   She looked bewildered, uncomfortable and she wasn't having any
fun, the same way she looks whenever she loses. She made calls with
her fingers, screamed ``No'' more than once and sometimes seemed
overwhelmed by her sister's game.
</P>
<P>
   She entered the post-match news conference wearing a ballcap
pulled low on her face. Her answers were terse. When asked if it's
more emotional to lose to Venus, she said, ``I don't think so.
No.''
</P>
<P>
   And her main feeling at the moment? ``I don't know,'' she
sighed. ``I lost in the semifinals of Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Venus' U.S. Open devastation all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Staging the match would be one thing. Staging the devastation is
a different story.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, pointing out that both he and Evert played siblings
during their careers, had a different take after the match, saying
he didn't think anything had been ``fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anytime people get out on a Centre Court at Wimbledon
things can happen that you don't want to happen,'' McEnroe said.
``I can only imagine it's got to be very, very strange to be out
there. I don't care how many times they tell you it's another day
in the park.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, Venus couldn't have been happier or more
talkative. She described her protective role as big sister, her
sadness for her sister and how she wished they'd met in the final
instead of the semifinal. ``It would have been a lot more joyous,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She complimented Serena's game, saying she played so well
because Serena pushed her, and explained how the loss feels for
Serena.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a real competitor, probably even more than I am when it
comes to losing,'' Venus said. ``She hates to lose. So that really
hurts her deep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an arena like the Roman Empire,'' Richard Williams said
after the match. ``Where one person had the right to die and one
person had the right to live.''
</P>
<P>
   He has the match on tape and expects he'll eventually watch it.
But first, he'll concentrate on helping Venus win her first Grand
Slam, not to mention getting both sisters a doubles title. They
play Anna Kournikova and Natasha Zvereva in the semifinal today.
</P>
<P>
   Their eccentric father makes defeating second seed and defending
champion Lindsay Davenport sound easy, an issue of mind over
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Venus' party,'' he said. ``She didn't invite Lindsay to
it. Lindsay will get the same whipping Serena got.''
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: E.T. Dumas, a longtime coach of Venus and Serena,
had been talking with Venus for the past few days when she asked
him Monday to grab his rackets and join her at Wimbledon. Dumas
flew home to West Palm Beach and Wednesday night hopped a flight
from Miami to London. He showed up at the practice courts before
Venus and Serena played, but Richard was working with the girls and
told him to ``go get something to eat.'' Dumas, who worked
extensively with Serena before her U.S. Open title, expects to work
with Venus today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
