<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS SURVIVES BATTLE OF THE SISTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ An unblinking Serena Williams watched her
final serve of the day as it crashed into the net and died in the
grass. Too stunned at the blunt end of the semifinal spectacle
Thursday, she hesitated to move, frozen in a worn patch on the
baseline.
</P>
<P>
   A double fault on match point. Once the reality of it nudged
her, Serena Williams pressed her fingers against her eyes to dam
her emotions and walked in the direction of her subdued big sister.
On the scoreboard in the corner, V. Williams had defeated S.
Williams, 6-2, 7-6 (3) to advance to the finals of Wimbledon, where
Lindsay Davenport will await on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday wasn't a celebratory moment for Venus Williams,
just the end to an awkward day. Before they exited beneath an
uneasy applause on Center Court, Venus Williams slung her racket
bag over her shoulder and then hovered over her crestfallen little
sister. She put her arm around Serena, helped her gather a few
items on the court, and whispered, ``Let's get out of here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always the big sister,'' said Venus Williams, who smiled
but remained restrained after advancing to her first final of a
Grand Slam since her 1997 appearance at the U.S. Open. ``I always
take care of Serena, no matter what. I always make the decisions.
I'm always a role model for Serena. I'm the big sister. I always
worry about her.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams dismissed the idea that this loss hurt worse
than another, but she appeared uncommonly crushed just moments
after the match. Glancing up from beneath a blue cap pulled low on
her forehead, Serena's eyes looked puffy and her voice shook when
she tried to explain what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected to play a lot better than I did today,'' she said.
``It was my goal to do better in this tournament, but that's OK.
I'm only 18. Venus is 20. I have a lot of years ahead of me.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Serena was the one many picked to win. She was the
sister with the sharper serve, the one with a more precise game.
She was the one who had grabbed a Grand Slam first, the one who
left her older sister's self-esteem in a puddle after winning the
U.S. Open. Thursday, Venus Williams was the one who left Serena in
shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a younger sister, and that's the way it is when you're
younger,'' Venus Williams said. ``You always get your way. Anyone
who has had a younger sibling knows that. When they don't get their
way, mom and dad step in and say, `Give her the ice cream.' As an
older sister or the older brother, you roll with the punches.''
</P>
<P>
   As unnatural as it seemed, Venus Williams had to take the match
from Serena. True to her nature, Venus remained cool and
unflustered from the outset. While Serena Williams desperately
tried to coax out her killer instinct by shaking her fists,
pounding her racket and smacking her thigh, Venus calmly pressed
onward with fewer mistakes. Of the 40 unforced errors made by
Serena Williams, too many came on pivotal points. Out of 11
break-point opportunities, she converted only twice. Venus Williams
converted 4 of 5.
</P>
<P>
   Serena held a 4-2 lead in the second set, but failed to convert
three break points on her sister's next serve. On all three
chances, Serena Williams lost control of a wobbly forehand. That
was just the beginning of trouble. Over the next three games,
Serena lost 11 straight points. Suddenly, Venus Williams led, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Venus' last five matches, she didn't serve that well,''
Serena Williams said. ``That's the one thing I was counting on. But
she decided she was going to serve well today.''
</P>
<P>
   The tiebreaker proved it. When Venus Williams needed her serve,
she summoned it on cue. With a 4-3 lead, Williams unwound her
sinewy frame and lashed a 121 mph serve at her compact little
sister. Although Serena was able to muscle the blast back, Venus
Williams took the short ball and zipped it across the net at an
unreturnable angle.
</P>
<P>
   Through a fortnight marked with 50-minute matches, straight-set
victories and just one break of serve, Serena couldn't come up with
the same perfection against her sister. Her serve deserted her. On
match point, Serena Williams served her sixth double fault of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never double fault,'' said Serena Williams. ``Usually, I'll
play a tough three-set match and I'll hit one double fault the
whole match. Today, I don't know. I hit a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   That last double fault only underscored the anti-climactic
nature of the match. It was built up like a prizefight. For two
days, every element of the sisters' rise was explored, from their
days on the cracked courts of Compton, Calif., to the new home
Venus and Serena Williams just purchased. Through it all, Richard
Williams _ master storyteller, and eccentric architect of his
daughters' rise _ beamed with pride as he told every anecdote.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't around for what unfolded at Center Court. In the
private box next to the court, family friends like Gladys Knight
sat to cheer Venus and Serena on. The sisters' mother was in
Florida, and their father was taking a long walk. For most of the
day, Richard Williams strolled around the neighborhoods within the
two-mile radius of the All-England Club. He didn't watch a single
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too difficult to watch,'' said Richard Williams, who
made his way to the grounds once the 1-hour-27-minute match was
over. ``I didn't see the point of it. There was a lot going through
my head. It was too difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The matchup was too strange. The way the sisters mirrored each
other's style _ bludgeoning the balls from the baseline, tracking
down every angle with their speed _ there was an element of
strategy missing. They knew each other's game almost too well.
Although there were riveting rallies, punctuated by mesmerizing
power, the match was pockmarked by too many errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena and Venus both appeared nervous and didn't look happy
to be there,'' said John McEnroe after he called the match for the
BBC. ``There was no way for them to be totally comfortable. I don't
care how many times they say it, it wasn't just another day in the
park.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The crowd's response was unusual, as well. They were conflicted
by the circumstance. Not understanding which sister to applaud, not
knowing when a cheer would be insensitive, the spectators remained
hushed for most of the match. Once it ended, there was just a
gentle ovation. Nothing too raucous.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams wouldn't have wanted a big fuss. She wasn't in
the mood to celebrate beating her little sister. It wasn't the
right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really bitter,'' Venus Williams said. ``But someone had
to move on. It was either going to be me or Serena. In this
instance, it was me.''
</P>
<P>
   Next time, it could be Serena. Is there a family plan for the
sisters to alternate? In the end, there was scant evidence to
support the conspiracy theories. Upon match point, it was hard to
imagine Serena Williams manufacturing such a stunned and dispirited
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena is a real competitor, probably even more than what I am
as far as when it comes to losing,'' Venus Williams said. ``She
hates to lose. So that really hurts deep.''
</P>
<P>
   When she saw Serena hurt Thursday, the big sister knew just what
to say: ``Let's get out of here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
