<HEADLINE>
VERIZON GETS COMPETITIVE, CUTS PRICE OF DSL SERVICE 20% 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic marked its transformation to Verizon
Communications Thursday with a gift for its high-speed Internet
customers: a 20 percent cut in the price of its basic home digital
subscriber line service.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon, formed from the merger of Bell Atlantic and GTE, said
both current and future customers for its 640-kilobit-per-second
service will now pay $40 a month instead of $50, as under previous
plans, plus $100 for a modem.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 reduction makes DSL more competitive with cable modem
services such as AT&AMP;T Broadband, which holds a big lead over
Verizon DSL in several of the 31 states where Verizon has a
landline presence.
</P>
<P>
   However, the maximum 640 kilobit download speed is still only 40
percent as fast as the maximum offered by AT&AMP;T Broadband, and DSL
is unavailable to people who live more than about two miles from a
phone company ``central office'' outfitted with the requisite gear.
Roughly half of Massachusetts central offices have been upgraded
for DSL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a quality product, and for $10 more, you get
twice the speed,'' said AT&AMP;T spokesman Richard D. Jenkinson. In
Massachusetts and New Hampshire, the 1.5-megabit AT&AMP;T RoadRunner
service can be had for as low as $30 a month for people who buy the
modem rather than renting and also take cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   The DSL price cut announcement capped a day of nationwide
festivities launching the new Verizon brand name, which combines
companies that employ 260,000 people around the world and becomes
the largest local US phone company ahead of SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The name comes from a combination of the word ``horizon'' with
``veritas,'' the Latin word for truth.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon officials said their service area includes 16.5 million
households that potentially could receive DSL, of whom barely 1
percent are estimated by industry analysts to have the service now.
</P>
<P>
   The company's local landline reach combines the Bell Atlantic
Maine-to-Virginia base with GTE's scattered local franchises in 28
states. Key GTE local service areas include metropolitan areas of
Dallas, Los Angeles, Tampa, Raleigh-Durham, N.C., and Seattle and
the state of Hawaii and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   GTE and Bell Atlantic have also spun out their wireless
properties into Verzion Wireless, which covers 96 of the top 100 US
markets and has 29 million wireless and paging customers.
</P>
<P>
   In a Boston interview Thursday, Verizon vice chairman and
copresident Michael T. Masin said the company expects to take
several steps to close ``small gaps in our domestic footprint,''
which could include efforts to lease other Baby Bells' lines to
compete with them for local residential and business service.
</P>
<P>
   As a condition of federal approval for the merger, GTE had to
spin off most of its stake in Genuity of Burlington, Mass., the
former GTE Internetworking, a top Internet backbone carrier.
</P>
<P>
   However, Masin said, ``We think within two or three years
Genuity will be back in the fold of the Verizon family.'' To be
allowed to take back majority control of Genuity, Verizon must get
approval to be a long-distance phone carrier throughout the former
Bell Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year Bell Atlantic cleared that hurdle in New York
state and quickly grabbed nearly 1 million long-distance customers.
Last week federal regulators approved SBC as a long-distance
carrier in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Masin said he believes those steps have laid out a clear road
map for how Baby Bells must open their networks for local
competition to get approval as long-distance carriers. ``We think
we will do it'' in all Bell states ``within two to three years, and
we think the next one to do it will be Massachusetts'' before
year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon shares closed down 62.5 cents at $58.8125 in New York
Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
