<HEADER>
A4813 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-PERFORMANCE-$     07-06 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PERFORMANCE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND THE LOSERS WERE ... JUST ABOUT EVERYONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mutual fund investors received a painful reminder last quarter
that there is a third way.
</P>
<P>
   In the long-running debate between fund managers who search for
cheap stocks and those who chase the fastest-growing companies,
neither side had any reason to cheer. The growth funds that
dominated for most of the long bull market for stocks flamed out,
but their value-seeking counterparts did not exactly soar from
their ash piles. A checking account turned out to be a better place
to stash cash than either broad category of stock fund.
</P>
<P>
   In a quarter when the average fund that invests in large growth
companies was down 5.2 percent, the typical large value fund was
was off 1.9 percent. As a group, value funds outperformed the
overall market for a change, but it would be difficult to build a
celebration on their meager return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're breaking out the Champagne and saying,
`We're doing better than growth,''' said Michael Lipper, chairman
of Lipper Inc. ``They outperformed on a relative basis. The
question is, will value outperform on an absolute basis
sufficiently well to make it attractive? They're not going to get
new assets off these numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he noted, a few value-oriented fund managers, including
Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. and Wanger Asset Management, agreed to
be acquired in the last few weeks, signaling that some big fund
companies saw growth prospects in value.
</P>
<P>
   Among investors, there were long faces all around as the average
U.S. diversified stock fund lost 3.1 percent of its value in the
second quarter after gaining more than 7 percent in the first
quarter. For the six months, the average stock fund was up 3.7
percent, a pace that is substantially off the historical return of
large stocks, 11 percent or so annually since 1926. And it pales in
comparison with the 19 percent annualized gain that the average
stock fund has racked up during the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Many funds that have led the pack for years stumbled during the
quarter, as technology stocks fell back to earth. Several funds
that had annualized gains of more than 35 percent over the last
five years lost more than 10 percent in the quarter, including
Fidelity New Millennium, RS Emerging Growth and Janus Twenty.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest losers among large funds were those with the
heaviest concentrations of technology stocks, especially shares of
Internet-based start-ups. Putnam OTC Emerging Growth, which raised
its technology position to 70 percent in 1999 and rose 125 percent
that year, lost 21.2 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three worst-performing stock funds in the quarter had
the word ``Internet'' in their names. The fund at the bottom of the
list was the Jacob Internet fund, managed since its December
introduction by Ryan Jacob, who previously managed the quarter's
third-worst performer, the Kinetics Internet fund. Jacobs' new fund
lost about 37 percent of its value in the quarter and is down
slightly more for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Staying far away from Internet companies and most technology
stocks was the key to success for many of the best-performing
funds. The biggest gains were in funds that focus on the riskiest
or most conservative of sectors. The 11 stock funds that gained
more than 20 percent in the quarter specialize in health care
stocks, especially biotechnology, or natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   The favored sectors of 1999, technology and telecommunications,
fell to the bottom of the rankings last quarter. Funds that
specialized in them lost more than 11 percent, on average. Between
those extremes were financial funds, which were down 1.5 percent
for the quarter, and utilities funds, which lost 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the Longleaf funds, managed by Southeastern Asset Management
of Memphis, an aversion to hot, new things and an unswerving
devotion to classic value investing paid off after a long wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not changed the way we do things for the 26 years that
we've operated,'' said Mason Hawkins, a co-manager of the $3.2
billion Longleaf Partners fund, which gained more than 8 percent in
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Helped by buyouts of two companies it owned, Nabisco Holdings
and the Pioneer Group, Longleaf Partners gained almost 10 percent
in the quarter, ending a string of three losing quarters and making
it the top performer among mid-capitalization value funds. Hawkins
described the rebound as an inevitable market recognition of the
bargains in the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest contribution came from its No. 1 holding, Waste
Management, the garbage-hauling company. With new management
tackling the company's accounting and computer problems, Hawkins
said, the stock rose 39 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In past quarters, of course, some investors left value funds
like Longleaf's and chased the fast performance gains logged by
growth funds like those managed by Janus Capital in Denver. But the
flow has not reversed as once-hot funds have absorbed investment
losses in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The stronger showing by value funds ``gives some substance to
the value people who have this price discipline,'' Lipper said.
But, he said, he doubts that value funds will continue to
outperform simply because they own cheap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are not cheap enough yet to bring out the arbitragers
and the raiders on any sort of mass basis,'' he said. Having money
spread around the world only compounded the woes of fund investors
last quarter. Every foreign stock fund category was a loser.
</P>
<P>
   International stock funds lost 6.3 percent, on average, breaking
a string of six quarterly gains. As a group, their return over the
past year of 25.8 percent, on average, was still better than the
19.2 percent for the typical diversified domestic stock fund.
</P>
<P>
   Several international funds hung on to 12-month gains of more
than 100 percent even though they dropped 13 percent or more last
quarter. Among them were Driehaus European Opportunity, BlackRock
International Small Cap Equity institutional shares and T. Rowe
Price International Discovery. Janus Overseas, with more than $10
billion in assets and an annual return of more than 30 percent for
five years, dropped 11.4 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best-performing international funds in the quarter
were more conservative portfolios that specialize in finding
undervalued companies or in buying stocks related to gold or other
precious metals. Many of the worst-performing international stock
funds specialize in companies in Japan and other Asia-Pacific
countries. Among international stock funds with at least $1 billion
in assets, the worst return was a 18.9 percent loss from Putnam
International New Opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Europe was the least inhospitable region. Funds that specialize
in European stocks lost 5.9 percent, on average, but managed to
post a 37.5 percent gain over the past year. Diversified
emerging-markets funds dropped 11.7 percent, while Japanese-stock
funds lost 11 percent and funds that buy Latin American stocks lost
6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among bond funds, emerging markets were the worst place to be.
The typical emerging-markets bond portfolio lost 1.2 percent. Most
other categories of bond funds had positive returns, except for
high-yield _ or junk _ bond funds, which lost 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most bond funds are showing positive numbers but not great
positive numbers,'' Lipper said. As interest rates rose, he said,
investors started to worry about the credit quality of some of the
bonds in riskier portfolios, especially those backed by mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Although some convertible bond funds had 12-month gains of 25 to
40 percent through June 30, many of those suffered losses in the
quarter. One standout for the quarter, however, was the $81 million
Victory Convertible Securities fund, which gained 5.7 percent, and
15.6 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the worst-performing bond funds in the quarter and
almost all of the worst performers over the last year fell in the
high-yield category. The PaineWebber High-Income fund lost more
than 10 percent last quarter and almost 16 percent over the last 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal bond funds cooled a bit after a hot first quarter,
gaining just 1.1 percent, on average. The best recent returns among
big muni funds were from the $1.50 billion Vanguard California
Insured Long-Term Tax-Exempt and the $1.39 billion Vanguard
California Intermediate-Term Tax-Exempt, both of which gained 1.8
percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
