<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-MAZDA-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL SUV TO FILL A BIG GAP 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Imagine being a man of the '90s and not having a
single pair of khaki Dockers in your closet. Mazda found itself
similarly naked in recent years; without a sport utility vehicle,
it was missing out on the hottest auto fashion trend of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda had, in fact, offered a sport utility, the Navajo, but
dropped it in 1994. At a time when buyers were clamoring for four
doors, the Navajo came with only two. It was, in fact, essentially
a two-door Ford Explorer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Mazda receives another sport utility from Ford, and
this one may have a brighter future. The Tribute is similar in many
respects to another new SUV, the Ford Escape, and along with the
Escape it has the potential to be best in class in a booming
segment of the car market.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of small sport utilities, or ``cute utes,'' have more than
doubled in the last four years, and further growth is expected both
in the United States and overseas. The Honda CR-V currently leads
the pack in sales, followed by the Toyota RAV4.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ford and Mazda recognized that they needed a small sport
utility and initially went their separate ways. Ford looked at
borrowing the underlying platform of the Contour and Mystique
sedans; Mazda considered the foundation of the MPV minivan and the
626 sedan.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the two brands _ Mazda is controlled by the Ford
Motor Co. _ came together. Mazda staff members took the lead role,
developing an entirely new platform that borrows little from
existing vehicles. Designed and engineered in Japan, the Tribute is
built at a Ford assembly plant near Kansas City, Mo. Production
capacity is a sizable 250,000 Tributes and Escapes a year, with
Mazda taking about 40,000 for the American market; it will also
build a right-hand-drive version in Japan. Ford will split the rest
of the production between the United States and 167 overseas
markets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aimed at young singles, couples and small families on budgets,
the Tribute, along with the Escape, jumps to the head of the class,
at least for now, in size, refinement and substance. The four-door,
five-passenger Tribute is smaller than the former Navajo and
current Explorer but almost a half-foot longer than the current
Jeep Cherokee. The Tribute and Escape are the first of a new wave
of cute utes that are slightly larger and more substantive. The
next RAV4, due this fall, is larger than the vehicle it replaces;
the next-generation CR-V will bulk up; and even the Cherokee grows
when it is redesigned for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Escape looks a little like a shrunken Explorer, and it has
the same outdoorsy style. Mazda aims for a more elegant appearance;
in fashion terms, the Tribute is gray flannel trousers while the
Escape, with its rugged-looking front fascia and plastic lower-body
trim, would be blue jeans. None of the exterior pieces are shared
except for the roof, windshield and side door glass.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same story inside; the two vehicles share few visible
components. The Tribute's dashboard and radio are similar to those
of the Mazda MPV minivan; the Escape has the black-on-white-dial
gauges of some Explorers. In keeping with its refined image, the
Tribute test vehicle (a top-line ES) came with leather seats, a
six-way power driver's seat and an excellent optional sound system,
a 190-watt, 7-speaker radio with cassette player and six-CD
changer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its compact exterior, the Tribute is surprisingly roomy
inside. Ford and Mazda say the pair have the most space in their
class. My passengers certainly had plenty of headroom and
sufficient legroom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was also loads of room for belongings. The rear cargo area
has 33 cubic feet of space, more if the seats are folded down. The
cargo bay is tall enough to carry bicycles upright and wide enough
to transport plywood. The large rear opening and low vehicle height
make it easy to load bulky items. I hauled a fully assembled
computer desk inside the Tribute. The temporary spare tire is
hidden beneath the cargo floor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tribute rides on a new unit-body platform. Its carlike
architecture delivers several advantages over sport utilities built
from truck components. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting in and out is easy, thanks to a low floor height,
generous door openings and beefy grab handles. With less weight
than in truck-style utilities, the handling is more nimble and
carlike and the fuel efficiency is better. The base DX model has a
2-liter, 130-horsepower 4-cylinder that comes only with a
five-speed manual transmission. It has an economy rating of up to
28 mpg.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-liter V-6, rated at 200 horsepower and paired only with a
four-speed automatic transmission, is likely to be more popular. It
comes on the ES and the medium-trim LX and is one of few V-6s
offered in small sport utilities. Its fuel economy is rated at 18
mpg. in the city and 24 on the highway, with or without four-wheel
drive. The V-6 versions, when outfitted with the optional towing
package, can haul up to 3,500 pounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I didn't haul anything, but the gold ES was plenty quick
accelerating from stoplights and passing on the freeway. Equipped
with a four-wheel independent suspension _ most SUV's still use
relatively unsophisticated live axles _ the Tribute maneuvers
around corners and rides smoothly like a car. It competently hugged
corners at higher speeds than I expected, yet kept passengers
upright and comfortable without much body roll. But more sound
deadening material would have been noise; the amount of road noise
coming through the floor reminded me of a truck.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from exterior appearance and interior appointments, the
Tribute rides and handles slightly differently than the Escape.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda advertising has positioned the Tribute as the sport
utility with a sports car soul. Commercials feature a Tribute
driving a slalom course around black Miata roadsters. The Tribute
does have slightly tighter handling and steering than the Escape,
but the differences are quite subtle.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its refined appearance, the Tribute is capable of
driving on muddy, rutted roads or over snowy pavement. All three
trim levels can be equipped with a new on-demand four-wheel-drive
system. In normal conditions, the Tribute operates in front-wheel
drive. When the system detects a loss of traction, the
four-wheel-drive system hydraulically transfers up to half of the
power to the rear wheels. A dashboard switch allows the driver to
lock the system in four-wheel drive on slippery roads. All the
shifting of power occurs seamlessly. There is no low range for
heavy towing.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribute's safety features include standard dual front air
bags and a new child-seat-latch system that will be required by law
next year. Side air bags and antilock brakes come as a $495 option
package.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribute starts at $17,520, about $600 less than the base
Escape. The LX starts at $19,655, about $1,680 less than the
comparable Escape. Fully equipped models will run around $25,000.
Mazda's pricing is more aggressive than Ford's in an attempt to
lure potential buyers into showrooms that had been devoid of sport
utilities. Now Mazda has the goods, and they are priced to sell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
