<P>
   BUSH-HISPANICS (Austin, Texas) _ In press conference noting
George W. Bush's 54th birthday, members of an organization of
Hispanic Democrats send him two birthday wishes _ removal of Reyn
Archer as Texas' state health director and support for confirmation
of Enrique Moreno to a federal appeals court. The group also gives
the Republican presidential hopeful bus fare to visit rural housing
developments for the poor. By JULIE MASON.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-MEDICARE (Chicago) _ Vice President Al Gore accuses
Republican rival George W. Bush of backing a Medicare reform plan
that would force senior citizens into managed care and financially
starve teaching hospitals, nursing homes and other health care
providers. By BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTIONS-PROTEST (Washington) _ Protesters who clashed with
police during meetings of international agencies in Seattle and
Washington plan mass marches and candlelight vigils during the
Republican and Democratic national conventions. Both nominating
sessions are expected to attract demonstrators who advocate
environmental, civil rights and anti-corporate causes. By MARK
HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-LAND (Undated) _ The Alabama-Coushatta Indian tribe has
prevailed in a 17-year legal fight with the federal government over
ownership rights to 2.85 million acres of East Texas pine forest.
Similar claims with some 20 tribes have been settled around the
nation. By JAMES KIMBERLY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-PAINT (Houston) _ The Houston school district has sued
the nation's biggest paint companies, seeking the huge sums of
money it will take to get rid of lead paint in their schools.
Similar suits have been brought by other cities, including
Philadelphia and New York, and have failed. By BILL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ In picking a running mate, Al Gore
has two advantages over George W. Bush. Gore gets to pick last,
after he has assessed the political impact of Bush's selection. And
unlike Bush, Gore has a standout possibility _ House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, who would likely take the offer. By MARIANNE
MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
