<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOU WISH UPON A CAR: NEW MODELS AT DISNEYLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Throngs of drivers, including some never
before behind the wheel, are lining up here to test three new
automobiles that arrived late last month amid a promotional blitz
comparable to a new-product introduction by Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   These vehicles, unavailable in dealer showrooms, do come with a
price tag: The $41 cost of admission to the Magic Kingdom at
Disneyland. The fresh body styles are replacing what might be
called a classic, a vaguely Ferrari-like roadster that puttered
around the ``freeways'' of the Autopia attraction unchanged for 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   The three new models _ one is like a mini-SUV, another vaguely
resembles a Volkswagen Beetle and the third is a Euro-styled sports
car _ are part of a remake of the Tomorrowland attraction,
sponsored for the first time by the Chevron Corp. The oil company
joins a long list of corporate sponsors at Disneyland. For Chevron,
the Autopia alliance was a natural extension of its own marketing
efforts; its television ads featuring animated talking cars.
</P>
<P>
   Since freeway driving is no longer a novelty, especially in
Southern California, Autopia is now intended as a ride through an
automotive fantasy world; statues in the ``park'' are
representations of historic autos.
</P>
<P>
   The fanciful body styles of the new cars are supposed to convey
a distinct personality, Weckerlin said. ``They are unique and
Disneyesque, not ones you'd necessarily see on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the two-seaters posed some design challenges. Besides
size constraints for the seat and headrest, the shell had to fit
over the old car's chassis, whose design had been perfected over 13
years of trial and error. ``We finally figured out how to build an
Autopia car to last forever,'' said Bob Gurr, the original
designer. ``We didn't want to mess with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the cars accommodate both children and adults, the
designer of the new models, Jason Hulst, had to wrestle with
proportions to get the right sense of scale. ``It's hard to make a
car look good when a child is in it,'' Gurr said. Just as
real-world car design is intended to convey a buyer's personality,
the Autopia cars are also less serious and more image-conscious.
</P>
<P>
   Although Disneyland is an icon of American culture, Detroit is
not about to mimic these designs, said Gaylord Eckles, an
industrial design instructor at the Art Center College of Design in
Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   And he had a suggestion of his own: ``If Disney can do
animatronic figures, why not have the cars really animated with
moving lips?''
</P>
<P>
   He did like the color-shifting paint of the sports car, a
special effect first used in 1996 on a limited-edition Ford Mustang
Cobra. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
