<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, July 7, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Larry Johnson on the national-foreign desk at (206)
448-8035.
</P>
<P>
   EPA-WATER (Undated) _ Congress has quietly moved to scuttle a
federal program to clean up pollution in 40 percent of the nation's
lakes, streams, bays and rivers. In a provision slipped into an
appopriations bill in the middle of the night by members of both
parties, Congress told the Environmental Protection Agency to stop
working on rules to regulate pollution that flows off farm fields,
dairy operations, hog farms and similar operations.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert McClure. (Story will move in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   DUNN-CONVENTION (Seattle) _ Rep. Jennifer Dunn is named one of
three co-chairs of next month's Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia, an appointment that signals George W. Bush's
determination to put a new face on the GOP. Dunn will share duties
with Texas Rep. Henry Bonilla, an Hispanic, and Oklahoma Rep. J.C.
Watts, the only African American Republican member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CHO (Undated) _ Korean American comedian Margaret Cho made
headlines in 1994 by jumping from a successful stand-up career to
fronting America's first Asian-cast sitcom ``All-American Girl.''
Cho hit the depths of depression when it was canceled in its first
season. Her concert film, ``I'm the One That I Want'' is a kind of
comic healing, a hilarious yet pointed self-affirmation.
</P>
<P>
   By Sean Axmaker. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-KID (Undated) _ Last summer, Bruce Willis played on the
softer side of his persona in ``The Sixth Sense,'' which came out
of nowhere and both thrilled and moved audiences. Don't expect a
return engagement in 2000. Willis retunes the heartstrings for Walt
Disney's ``The Kid,'' a cloying family comedy as distinctive as a
TV movie, but this time he's off-key.
</P>
<P>
   By Sean Axmaker. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SCARY (Undated) _ If the baddest of the Farrelly brothers'
bad-taste gags has you in stitches, then this is the movie for you.
For almost 90 minutes, director Keenen Ivory Wayans tries to meld
the pop-culture parodies of ``Airplane!'' and its ilk with jokes so
crude and outrageously raunchy that even Jim Carrey would think
twice.
</P>
<P>
   By Sean Axmaker. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TRIXIE (Undated) _ Imagine Gracie Allen playing private
eye, trying to lay a Lauren Bacall veneer of confidence and
toughness over her priceless babble of screwy punch lines. That's
Emily Watson in Alan Rudolph's latest genre bender, a ``screwball
noir'' (by his definition) directed with the quiet smoothness of a
sophisticated romance.
</P>
<P>
   By Sean Axmaker. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-LONGITUDE _ The coldly cynical will see A&AMP;E's decision to air
``Longitude'' in a four-hour block as a crass attempt to persuade
the bum-weary masses to order the film from A&AMP;E Home Video instead
of sitting in front of the television from 8 to midnight Sunday.
But if A&AMP;E makes a little money on video orders for ``Longitude,''
who am I to complain? Especially if they pour the money into other
productions of such elegance and splendor.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Laura Vecsey column on the
pleasant surprise of Spokane tennis player Jan-Michael Gambill,
whom Pete Sampras calls the future of American men's tennis.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Anaheim, Calif.) _ Seattle Mariners at Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   By John Hickey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
