<HEADER>
A4819 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-GAS-TAX-REDUCTION-$AD     07-06 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-TAX-REDUCTION-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW BEST TO DEDUCT THE HIGH COST OF GASOLINE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 9) 
 By STACY KRAVETZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite recent signs of easing, high prices at the gas pump
continue to stir political debate. They may also change the
calculus for another, more personal question: Which method should
taxpayers use when figuring deductions for business mileage: The
standard rate or the actual-expense version?
</P>
<P>
   It is a decision that should be revisited whenever any of the
relevant elements change, experts say. For the self-employed, the
choice is especially important, though even employees who are
reimbursed for their mileage can deduct expenses in excess of the
reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   Business mileage refers to any driving done for work excluding a
commute to and from the office _ trips to see clients, to
courthouses or to meetings, for example.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the standard mileage rate, or the business expense
allowed by the Internal Revenue Service for each mile driven for
business, has generally ticked up steadily but slowly, mirroring
cost-of-living adjustments. The rate is a calculation of the
average driver's auto-related expenses, including lease payments,
depreciation, interest payments, insurance, gasoline, repairs and
maintenance costs. The rationale is that while gas prices and other
expenses may fluctuate, they have a relatively small impact on the
overall cost of driving.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean, however, that the standard mileage rate
reflects the cost of driving for any individual driver. People who
live in large cities, for example, spend more on insurance, while
those who finance expensive cars pay more interest. And as gasoline
prices climbed this year, Midwesterners paid higher prices than
others. But everyone who chooses this method of accounting gets the
same standard rate, though some small items, like parking and
tolls, can be added.
</P>
<P>
   When the IRS lowered the standard mileage rate last year, from
32.5 cents a mile to 31 cents as of April 1, it was a blow to those
who thought the rate was already too low. And with pump prices up
markedly since then, the actual-expense method bears extra
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We calculate it both ways for our clients and invariably 99
percent of the time the actual expense provides a better tax
deduction than the mileage rate they give you,'' said Howard
Leitner, a partner at the accounting firm Leitner, Zander,
Sniderman &AMP; Co. in Los Angeles. ``With rising gas prices, if you
were on the border of whether you should take actual or standard,
it will push you over to the actual-expense side.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the main benefit of using the standard rate is its
simplicity. A taxpayer need keep records only of the miles driven
for business in a given year.
</P>
<P>
   But when should savings trump ease? The only way to know the
difference between the standard rate and actual expenses is to run
the numbers. The calculation will include the number of business
miles driven in a year and the amount spent on gasoline and other
allowable costs for the portion of driving that relates to
business.
</P>
<P>
   The standard rate is based on average car expenses, with an
estimate for gasoline costs based on prices in the previous year _
currently, about $1.50 a gallon. This hardly does justice to prices
spiking upward of $2.50 a gallon, as they did recently in many
Midwestern cities. For a car that gets 20 miles to the gallon, a
$1-a-gallon jump in gas prices means an increase of 5 cents a mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could look at it as the IRS cheating you by 5 cents a
mile,'' said Gordon Klein, a tax lawyer and a lecturer at the
Anderson School at the University of California at Los Angeles.
``It could add up.''
</P>
<P>
   For people who barely use their cars for business or who have
extremely low car expenses, the extra effort of collecting receipts
and calculating expenses will generally not produce enough savings
to justify the work. Similarly, employees whose companies reimburse
their business mileage may not receive a big benefit, because they
can deduct only the actual expenses above the amount they are
reimbursed. Most employers pay for mileage at the IRS standard
rate. In addition, the IRS does not let employees claim the
interest portion of car payments as an auto expense, so their
allowable ``actual expenses'' will be lower than those for the
self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   Accountants say the differences in savings tend to be biggest
for people who are self-employed or who lease cars, or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're self-employed, it's a real issue because you're not
getting anything if you don't take it on your tax return,'' said
David Green, a partner in the personal financial services practice
at PricewaterhouseCoopers in Los Angeles. When they itemize, the
self-employed may claim the interest portion of their car payments
as an expense, along with all other annual costs of driving for
business.
</P>
<P>
   Say a self-employed woman has a $35,000 car that is used 50
percent of the time for business. She can deduct actual expenses
totaling 50 percent of her gasoline, insurance, interest and
maintenance expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The car was financed at an interest rate of 8.49 percent, is
driven a total of 12,000 miles in a year and gets 25 miles to the
gallon in a metropolitan area where gasoline costs $1.75 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The business half of the expenses includes $750 for insurance,
$1,374 for interest, $420 for gasoline and $250 for maintenance.
The IRS also considers depreciation an expense, though it is capped
for all cars, no matter their cost, and is set at a different
amount for each subsequent year of use.
</P>
<P>
   For cars first used for business in 1999, the cap that year was
$3,060. (The cap for cars first used in 2000 has not yet been set.)
In the example, that means a maximum of $1,530 (or 50 percent of
$3,060) could be included as an expense. In this case, the driver
would be allowed $1,530 for depreciation, bringing her total
allowable expenses to $4,324.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the standard mileage rate of 31 cents a mile would
let her deduct only $1,860.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between the calculations, of course, grows as fuel
efficiency drops or as the price of gasoline jumps. Say the car in
the example was a gas-guzzler, getting 15 miles to the gallon in a
city where gas prices have risen to $2.50 a gallon. The vehicle's
annual fuel costs would jump to $1,000, from $420, and total
expenses would rise to $4,904, from $4,324. But the standard
mileage rate would still allow for just $1,860.
</P>
<P>
   Big differences are also seen in the computations for leased
cars. While there are no interest expenses or depreciation
involved, lease payments may be included in the actual-expense
calculation. So if that same gas-guzzler were leased, with annual
payments of $3,800, the total actual expenses would be $5,800.
</P>
<P>
   If doing the extra math makes sense, remember that choosing the
actual-expense method the first year a car is used for business
obligates you to continue with it as long as you have that car. (If
you choose the standard rate the first year, you may be able to
switch to actual expenses in later years.)
</P>
<P>
   True, itemizing expenses can be an ordeal. But the tax savings
gained through using the actual-expense method may, among other
things, be one small way to feel better about the pain at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
