<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHINA-U.S.-WORKERS-AR     07-06 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-WORKERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPORTING JOBS TO CHINA, ALONG WITH GOODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA, Okla. _ American business is rushing into China, and
Marilyn C. Grant, a 56-year-old widow who drives a forklift for a
fishing reel company, is being left behind.
</P>
<P>
   The Zebco Corp., Grant's employer, began moving much of its
fishing reel production to China at the end of June, just a few
weeks after the House passed a measure that would end Cold War
restrictions on trade with China. Most of Zebco's 240 workers will
eventually lose their jobs, and Grant, who has worked at the
company's stone headquarters plant in Tulsa for 25 years, expects
to be one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this only happened to other people, and now it's
about to happen to me,'' Grant said. ``We're just another company
moving over there.''
</P>
<P>
   In promoting permanent normal trade relations with China, which
the House approved in late May and the Senate is expected to vote
on in late July, President Clinton predicted an ``almost
incalculable'' increase in exports of U.S. goods to China. But the
move also seems likely to encourage exports of some U.S. jobs.
</P>
<P>
   China agreed to open its markets in order to join the World
Trade Organization and to get permanent trading rights in the
United States. That should make it easier to sell American-made
products there. But as China modernizes and loosens controls, its
lure as a manufacturing base, which has been growing since the
early 1980s, is also proving irresistible to many multinationals.
For every jumbo jet that Boeing sells to China, it seems, a Zebco
sends a production line there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Trade is not a zero-sum ``you win, I lose'' game, and most
economists say that even if some people lose their jobs, the United
States reaps advantages from trade _ like greater productivity,
higher corporate profits and cheaper spincast reels. But if people
are celebrating these diffuse benefits, they are not partying as
much as Zebco's workers are seething.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our government just handed our jobs to a communist country,''
said Brenda McCoy, 50, a Zebco assembly-line veteran who wore a
T-shirt to work that bears an image of two Chinese police officers
choking a Chinese labor activist. ``It just makes you feel angry
and helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese claim to have invented the modern fishing device
more than a millennium ago by spooling line onto wicker reels. But
it was the Zero Hour Bomb Co. of Tulsa that invented and patented
the spincast reel 50 years ago, with line spinning off the end of a
stationary spool and remaining, famously, backlash free.
</P>
<P>
   Now called Zebco, the company is a classic American success
story. Its nearly fool-proof reels helped make fishing perhaps the
nation's most popular leisure activity. They carry a ``Made in
America with Pride'' logo.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the last decade, as it had to fight competitors who paid
much lower hourly wages to workers in Asia, Zebco remained the
dominant fishing tackle brand. Though Zebco once tested production
in Mexico, it pulled back when its Tulsa workers proved they could
produce more reels in less time with fewer defects.
</P>
<P>
   The dike finally gave way this year, however. With most of
Zebco's competitors having already set up fishing tackle plants in
China, allowing them to undercut Zebco's prices at Wal-Marts
everywhere, Zebco began exploring a year ago the possibility of
moving its own lines to China. The company found that it could
commission Chinese factories to produce and deliver reels to the
United States for a third less than it could make them at home,
company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Zebco decided to make most of its low-end reels at factories in
China. For now, it will continue to produce more expensive reels in
Tulsa, though union officials say the company has put them on
notice that it is searching for further ways to lower labor costs,
including the possibility of shifting the remaining reels to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made valiant efforts to keep production in the United
States,'' said Kathryn J. Chieger, vice president for corporate and
investor relations at the Brunswick Corp., Zebco's parent company,
in Lake Forest, Ill. ``We just had a flood of product coming from
Asia at prices we could not meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the layoffs, which began June 27, left Zebco's
unionized workers, who are mostly women, perplexed and angry.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a dimly lit Transport Union Workers hall, the air
soured by cigarette smoke and the tables stacked with copies of
protest literature that workers distributed at a recent anti-China
trade demonstration, Kristie L. Cater said she had expected to
retire in the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept telling us we were members of the Zebco family,''
she said with angry sarcasm. ``I guess they just forgot about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As assembly-line factory jobs go, Zebco offers ordinary pay but
solid benefits, including Christmas gifts of stock certificates.
Workers returned the loyalty. Turnover was low. Some workers also
became avid anglers, showing off Zebco's reels at bass and crappie
fishing tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   For Linda Allen, 41, an assembly-line supervisor since 1976,
work was literally a family affair: Her mother and grandmother
preceded her in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Those ties started to unravel last year. When company executives
visited Qingdao, a city in northeastern China, to inspect
factories, word leaked out. Then, this year, the company pushed
assembly-line workers to raise their output by at least 10 percent
a month, and China became a cattle prod.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we don't get quota, it is another day closer to China
taking our jobs,'' read a Feb. 3 memorandum from the company that
was circulated among employees. ``So today China won by 45
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Chieger, of Zebco, said such memos were intended to show workers
what they were ``up against'' in terms of competitors that had
factories in China.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the shop floor fell into stunned silence one March
afternoon when the president of the company read a brief statement
as first-shift workers finished their day. Zebco was moving some
production to China. Many of those listening would lose their jobs.
Zebco reels no longer commanded an ``adequate profit,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation offended Grant, the widow who drives a Zebco
forklift.
</P>
<P>
   Grant has gray hair and delicate manners. As she speaks, her
eyes dart about the living room of her A-frame house, which is
decorated with porcelain figurines and homemade quilts. Only her
strong shoulders reveal the heavy lifting she does each day as a
Zebco receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have never said they don't make a profit,'' she said.
``It's that word `adequate.' They're going over to China because of
greed.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years from retirement, she said she had begun looking
for a new job. Tulsa's economy is relatively strong, and she found
one prospect. But if she got the job _ she worries that a touch of
arthritis might hurt her chances _ she would lose her
quarter-century seniority and $1.50 of her $10.63 hourly wage, she
said, money she needs to make payments on her secondhand Jeep.
</P>
<P>
   Cater, 37, a mother of two, said that after she learned of her
layoff on the assembly line, she told her 17-year-old daughter to
check out community colleges in Tulsa; the higher priced Colorado
school she had been considering was now out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some savings put away, but that's going to disappear,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   At least in theory, the recent steps China has taken to open its
markets should be good for U.S. factory workers and farmers by
making it easier for companies to export goods to that nation.
</P>
<P>
   But as union leaders argued when they tried unsuccessfully to
block the China trade bill in the House, many leading U.S.
companies are like Zebco: They often want to save money by
producing in China _ often exporting back to the United States _
rather than making goods here to sell in China.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been losing manufacturing jobs for
decades, of course, and dire warnings about the hollowing out of
the economy seem a little hyperbolic during the longest expansion
in the nation's history. Most economists believe that the trade
boom of the last decade _ more exports, cheaper imports and the
reallocation of jobs to more productive parts of the economy _
forms a central pillar of the 1990s expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, although the Clinton administration often touted
exports as the headline benefit of broadening trade with China, the
real advantage for U.S. companies is probably enhanced rights of
investment and ownership there. Phone, Internet, bank and insurance
companies can buy larger stakes in Chinese counterparts and set up
operations in more cities under the terms of China's entry to the
World Trade Organization. Most companies try to crack the difficult
China market by setting up local operations, often using those
plants as export production bases as well.
</P>
<P>
   That means that the push into China is not limited to low-wage
assemblers. Cisco, Intel, Eastman Kodak and Motorola are among the
multinational companies that have lobbied Congress to grant China
permanent normal trade relations even as they have expanded their
manufacturing operations in China, according to a survey by the
U.S. Business and Industry Council, which has been critical of
Clinton administration trade policies.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, exports to China will probably grow. But the volume of
imports is expected to grow even faster. The U.S. International
Trade Commission, a government agency, predicts that American
exports will increase 10 percent a year if China opens its markets
as promised. But it also sees China's appeal as a manufacturing
base rising fast, bolstering China's exports to the United States
by 7 percent annually. Since imports from China already exceed
exports to China by a wide margin, the gaping $62 billion trade
deficit is likely to widen rather than contract.
</P>
<P>
   The way many workers see it, America loses.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the United States was better off with cheaper
fishing reels or job security for Zebco workers, Grant reflected
for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People might like buying things cheaper,'' she said. ``But
there's a price. They're going to wake up one day and find that
nothing's made here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
