u f BC-RAYTHEON-TEST-BOS &LR;      07-06 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-TEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON HOPES RIDE ANTI-MISSILE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an anti-missile test Friday night, the Pentagon and its
contractors will try to knock down an incoming dummy warhead _ and
perhaps a few of their critics.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will be the third in a series of shoot-down tests for
the National Missile Defense program, which has posted a mixed
record in previous tryouts and generated much doubt among academics
and foreign-policy experts.
</P>
<P>
   If fully deployed, the program could be worth about $8 billion
to Raytheon Co. But even one Raytheon board member thinks the
system isn't ready for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the current issue of Foreign Policy, former CIA
director John Deutch, a Raytheon director, and two co-authors state
that no matter what the outcome of the test, the anti-missile
technology is ``not mature enough for the United States to make a
confident deployment decision this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Adminstration has said it will do just that,
however, promising to signal when to begin full-scale construction
of the system. By current estimates, the effort could cost as much
as $60 billion by 2015, creating a network of up to 250
interceptors to counter threats from rogue nations like North
Korea. That country could have missiles of its own by 2005, the
soonest a basic missile defense system could be ready, the Pentagon
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Some doubt Clinton will commit to a firm construction schedule
before leaving office. One concern of critics is whether deployment
would violate the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. Republican
George W. Bush has called for scrapping the treaty and building an
extensive missile defense, while administration officials and Vice
President Al Gore hope Russia will negotiate amendments to permit a
limited program.
</P>
<P>
   Deutch and others say the military should pursue an alternative
weapons strategy to shoot down enemy missiles just after they are
launched rather than on their way to a target.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pentagon says its existing strategy is the most
practical, and the latest test launch will show how well its
interceptor rockets will work with new radar systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have the technology? That remains to be determined,''
Secretary of Defense William Cohen said this week. ``That's one of
the reasons we have to await the outcome of the next test.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial is scheduled to begin between 10 p.m. Friday and 2
a.m. Saturday. Plans call for the target, a Minuteman II
intercontintental ballastic missile, to be launched from Vandenberg
Air Force Base, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later an interceptor missile carrying a
Raytheon-built ``kill vehicle'' will be launched from Kwajalein
Atoll in the central Pacific Ocean. Ten minutes after that, the
kill vehicle is meant to locate the incoming dummy warhead, then
ram it at a combined speed of 12,000 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is daunting. In a test in January the kill vehicle
missed its target because of problems with infra-red guidance
sensors. The vehicle hit its mark in an earlier test last October,
but only after overcoming software-programming errors.
</P>
<P>
   Last month a panel chaired by retired Air Force general Larry
Welch called the chances of developing and fielding a limited
system by 2005 a ``high risk.'' The panel found no reason to adjust
the decision-schedule, however, but others disagree. Last month, US
Sen. John F. Kerry urged Clinton to delay the deployment decision
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have grave concerns that we are sacrificing careful
technical development of this system in order to meet an artificial
deadline,'' Kerry said in a speech.
</P>
<P>
   One area of dispute has been whether the system is able to
distinguish real warheads from decoys that enemy missiles might
also release.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Postol, professor at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, contends the Pentagon has rigged its tests to ensure
the kill vehicles ignore decoys. Pentagon officials say Postol's
claims are based on data from old tests, but they won't discuss its
new procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon works on the missile-defense program under contract to
Boeing Co. Raytheon's work includes the kill vehicle, software
upgrades to some existing radar stations, and a short-wavelength
radar system meant to pick out fine details of enemy warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say it's too soon to provide estimates for how
any new work would affect its profits or revenue. Government and
industry sources cite some public figures for guidance: fully
deployed, the missile defense program could include 250 kill
vehicles, at about $15 million apiece; six radar upgrades at
perhaps $100 million apiece; and, nine X-band radars, at around
$450 million each.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon produces the kill vehicles in Arizona, while most of
Raytheon's radar work would occur at its plants near Andover, Mass.
One of the radar facilites to be upgraded would be at the Cape Cod
Air Force Station, in Sagamore, Mass. Raytheon's headquarters is in
Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the views of Deutch, its board member, Raytheon says
everything is on track. ``Our job is to prove that the technology
is available to support a positive deployment decision this year,''
said company spokesman Dave Shea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
