<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SBC-TEXAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PHONE COMPANY TO BEGIN LONG-DISTANCE SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SBC Communications plans to announce Friday the long-distance
rates it will charge in Texas, the second state, after New York, in
which a local phone company will also offer long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Monday, SBC will offer long-distance plans to
individual and corporate customers that will compete with service
offered by companies like WorldCom, AT&AMP;T and Sprint. Verizon
Communications, the former Bell Atlantic, entered the long-distance
market in New York at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative in Texas is part of a trend to allow consumers to
buy long-distance service from the regional Bell companies created
by the breakup of AT&AMP;T in the 1980s. Under the Telecommunications
Act of 1996, the Bells were allowed to seek regulatory approval for
long-distance service state by state. SBC received approval last
week from the Federal Communications Commission for service in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're encouraged to see greater competition with the likes of
SBC moving into long distance,'' said Susan Grant, vice president
for public policy at the National Consumers League in Washington.
``But this type of thing can be a blessing or a curse, because so
many choices can be bewildering.''
</P>
<P>
   SBC, based in San Antonio, said it will announce a basic rate of
9 cents a minute for in-state and out-of-state calls anytime, with
no monthly fee. For customers who choose services like call waiting
or caller ID, SBC will offer a flat rate of 6 cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, SBC will take advantage of the demographics of
Texas, a state with a large Hispanic population, and cater some
services to people who make frequent calls to Mexico. For instance,
under one plan, calls to border towns in Mexico will cost 13 cents
a minute, while calls to Mexico City will cost 34 cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our understanding from talking with our customers is that
clarity, savings and one-stop shopping are very strong incentives
to choose our plans,'' said David Cole, president for consumer
markets at the Southwestern Bell unit of SBC.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said customers choosing one of SBC's basic plans could
save money because the average per-minute long-distance charge in
Texas is more than 20 cents a minute. Nationwide, long-distance
rates are about 20 cents a minute, according to the Gartner Group,
a telecommunications research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an innovative step, something we all expected and
hoped for with the Bells entering the long-distance arena,'' said
Jeffrey Kagan, an independent telecommunications industry analyst.
``It is much more exciting than Bell Atlantic's timid,
plain-vanilla-envelope entry into long distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bell Atlantic did not offer any flat-rate plans when it
introduced long-distance service in New York, the company is
estimated to have signed up nearly a million long-distance
customers, which translates into about $250 million a year in
revenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
