<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4834 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-SPRINT07-COX     07-06 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth continues to wait for answers
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The high-stakes alliance that will meld the wireless
units of BellSouth and SBC Communications to take on national
players is still waiting for answers to some important questions.
</P>
<P>
   First and most important: Will BellSouth decide to renew its bid
to purchase Sprint?
</P>
<P>
   If it does, BellSouth would expect that a purchase would mean
ditching either Sprint's national wireless business or BellSouth's
own wireless unit, which has amassed about 6 million subscribers,
nearly all in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Indications are that if Deutsche Telekom makes an offer for
Sprint, BellSouth likely will not.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave BellSouth to pursue other potential targets
like Qwest Communications, which has no national wireless presence.
And certainly BellSouth officials are preparing for the launch of
the joint venture with SBC as if that is the basket into which they
will throw all their domestic wireless eggs.
</P>
<P>
   So if BellSouth is going to follow through, it must fill in some
blanks.
</P>
<P>
   No chief executive has been named for the wireless unit. No
headquarters city has been named. And in fact, no name has been
given to the venture itself. And while the companies talked of
launching service later this year, no date is going to be set until
those other questions are answered.
</P>
<P>
   But some kind of answer should come soon if the new venture is
to have a shot at the lucrative late-year holiday consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, announced in April, silenced critics of BellSouth who
had wondered how the company could survive with just a regional
wireless offering. But with the SBC arrangement, BellSouth will go
from an offering nearly limited to its nine-state region to one
that is nearly national: The joint venture will create a wireless
unit with revenues of $10.2 billion and 16.2 million phone
subscribers in 32 states.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the companies plan to add to that, perhaps by buying
licenses, perhaps through alliances.
</P>
<P>
   But no question, the still-unnamed venture will start with
enough bulk to be taken seriously. BellSouth and SBC together will
form the second-largest carrier behind only Verizon, a joint
venture of Bell Atlantic, GTE and Vodafone AirTouch that boasts 24
million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   SBC and its Chief Executive Edward Whitacre Jr. have an industry
reputation for being voracious in seeking markets and for playing
hardball in deals and alliances. But BellSouth's CEO, Duane
Ackerman, is friendly with Whitacre and BellSouth believes it has
forged a deal in which it will not be out-muscled.
</P>
<P>
   SBC and BellSouth will share control, although as the bigger
partner, SBC will own the majority of the venture. The two
companies have agreed to split representation on the board and
among top executives, with the top exec coming from neither SBC or
BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   But since that announcement, officials have been mum.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most high-profile possible candidates for the top job
at the new company is Andrew Sukawaty, who resigned recently as
chief executive of Sprint's wireless unit. As for locations, the
initial agreement had called for picking a headquarters that was
outside the turf of both SBC and BellSouth. The theory on a chief
executive has followed that same template: Find someone who is from
neither company.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all that is moot if BellSouth sells its wireless unit
to SBC and strolls away from the joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth had made a run at Sprint in October. After being
outbid by WorldCom, BellSouth went seeking other ways to improve
its position, and has since announced plans to deliver television
via satellite, to launch a tracking stock for its Latin American
investments and to forge the joint venture with SBC.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, the Justice Department moved to block the merger
of the Sprint-WorldCom merger. The companies _ especially WorldCom
_ struggled to resuscitate their agreement, but now appear ready to
announce the deal's demise.
</P>
<P>
   Then, both will be free to entertain other offers.
</P>
<P>
   And both are expected to seek partners. Deutsche Telekom seems
most interested in Sprint as a giant prize moving it closer to its
plan goal of becoming a global provider. WorldCom conceivably could
also be game _ but only for a huge hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Most probably, WorldCom must decide whether to jettison its
consumer offerings and focus on businesses.
</P>
<P>
   If WorldCom does still want wireless, WorldCom must choose
between very expensive targets with national presence like Nextel
or VoiceStream and those with more limited scope like Powertel or
Alltel.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4835 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ASSESS-     07-06 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ASSESS-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: FACING A SUMMIT MEETING WITH LITTLE TO LOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ There is a go-for-broke quality to the Israeli and
American approach to the coming Camp David summit meeting, which
starts Tuesday with the stated goal of ending a 52-year-old,
blood-steeped conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Palestinians, whose participation is more reluctant,
there is at best an aspiration that the three-way meeting will
serve as a stopgap to keep alive the stalemated peace effort so
that a partial deal can be achieved by September.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak will arrive in Maryland as a weakened
Israeli leader with one thing on his mind: to push the peace effort
with the Palestinians to a conclusion before he loses his grip on
power. Battered by the right over his peace moves and by the left
over his concessions to the religious parties, he will try to rise
above the partisan politics that, with two parties poised to quit
his coalition, is about to cost him his parliamentary majority.
</P>
<P>
   Barak will seek to forge the framework of a final peace deal
with the Palestinians on the basis of what he considers a directive
from the Israeli people, who, as he often notes, overwhelming
elected him last year on a platform of peacemaking. And if he
fails, he said Thursday, he will have given it his best effort in
the face of a keen potential for the conflict to disintegrate
``into Belfast or Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, President Clinton appears to have decided that he
cannot make things worse by forcing the parties into an endgame,
since no summit meeting and a failed summit meeting have the same
potential outcome: violence. If the chemistry of the moment
produces a breakthrough in the peace effort, the accomplishment is
a substantial one. If not, the risk to the American president is
minimal; he, too, will have given it his best shot.
</P>
<P>
   But the Palestinians' leader, Yasser Arafat, whose lifelong
struggle rests on this effort, will approach Camp David far more
skeptically and cautiously than the other two leaders. He will take
part against the counsel of his senior advisers, who think the
groundwork has not been laid for a compromise on any major issue.
</P>
<P>
   Of mixed mind, Arafat is saying that he is going to Maryland
only because he cannot refuse an invitation from Clinton. But he is
also betting that if peace negotiations are to work, he stands to
gain the most at a high-stakes summit meeting presided over by this
American president, with whom he has forged a bond. At any rate,
weighing the alternative _ a unilateral declaration of statehood,
which is bound to be accompanied by renewed violence, an Israeli
annexation of West Bank land and complications for Arafat's
international acceptance _ he is willing to gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Like Anwar el-Sadat, before the last Middle East peace gathering
at Camp David, in 1978, Arafat needs to deliver some kind of
victory to his weary people, many of whom, for all their talk of
sacrifice, would prefer not to spill much more blood.
</P>
<P>
   Having proclaimed and disclaimed previous deadlines for
establishing a state, Arafat and the Palestinian leadership this
week tied the Palestinian fate to a new one, Sept. 13. This one
will be harder to ignore if he is to retain his credibility; it
marks the formal end of the interim peacemaking period, which was
extended from May 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But the chief economic adviser to Arafat, Mohammed Rachid, who
will accompany him to Maryland, said Thursday night that the
Palestinians would willingly bypass the deadline if they were
engaged in serious negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   And many experts think the Palestinian people, who would prefer
a real state to a nominal one, could be persuaded to endure yet
another postponement if they saw any tangible progress _ like a
substantial transfer of West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are pragmatic and they'll accept a bird in the
hand,'' said Ghassan Khatib, a Palestinian political analyst who
has done extensive polling on attitudes toward peace. ``There is a
growing minority that rejects the peace process, but it is not a
majority, and there is no alternative. There is no other game. The
peace process is becoming a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   A cartoon in the Palestinian newspaper Al Quds Thursday showed
the spirit of the meeting as a whirlwind blowing out the candle of
the Palestinian declaration of independence.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli military analysts paint a different picture. In a
briefing for foreign reporters Thursday, a senior military officer
in the West Bank said Arafat had introduced a ``struggle
consciousness'' to accompany the negotiations. He said Arafat
wanted to achieve independence ``through friction and blood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules of the game are low-intensity conflict accompanying
the diplomatic process with the threat of terrorism in the
background,'' the senior officer said. ``Arafat wants to appear as
both the pyromaniac and the fireman.''
</P>
<P>
   One could be whipsawed by the surface contradictions here
Thursday between the bounding optimism of Israeli doves and the
thick skepticism of Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving a meeting with Arafat in Gaza City Thursday, Yossi
Beilin, Israel's justice minister, expressed unconditional faith in
the eventuality of a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that all the leaders will go to Camp David and
come back empty-handed,'' he said. ``We are going to make peace.
And after all these years, we will have to compromise, both sides,
to find solutions and come back home and tell our kids that they
will not have to take part in the wars we took part in.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Abu Ala, speaker of the Palestinian legislature and
a senior negotiator, said he did not think the summit meeting would
achieve any of its aims. ``It is clear that Barak is trying to
escape from negotiations and jump to a summit because he thinks he
can force deals,'' he said. ``But if he thinks that he can give us
some land on which to declare a Palestinian state and then we will
forget the other issues, then he's living in a dream world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachid, a relatively unideological and pragmatic adviser, spoke
more practically about what could be achieved. He said that, in
Israeli style and on an Israeli scale, the Palestinians would ask
the Americans for $40 billion in aid to accompany a peace treaty.
Most of that would go toward refugee aid, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also that the Israelis were overly focused on the percentage
of the West Bank they would transfer to the Palestinians. He noted
that Barak, who started out talking about turning over 50 percent
of the land, had increased his offer most recently to 88 percent _
78 percent now and 10 percent over time. But Rachid said the
Palestinians wanted the Israelis to stop thinking of it as their
land to give away and to start accepting the principle that the
Palestinians have a rightful claim to the West Bank. That, he
suggested, would make the Palestinians more flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is unlikely to travel to Washington with his most
hard-line ministers because they are expected to quit before he
leaves. Interior Minister Natan Sharansky, who leads a small
Russian immigrant party, has said he will tender his resignation on
Sunday, and Housing Minister Yitzhak Levy, who leads the National
Religious Party, is prepared to step down too. Eli Yishai, leader
of the rigorously Orthodox Shas Party, is undecided about whether
he will travel with the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is expected to be accompanied by Foreign Minister David
Levy, Internal Security Minister Shlomo Ben Ami and Attorney
General Elyakim Rubenstein and his security advisers _ Danny Yatom,
Haim Mendel-Shaked and Zvi Stauber. Yossi Sarid, who heads the
leftist Meretz Party, and Transportation Minister Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak may join them, too.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's delegation will include Abu Ala; Rachid; the senior
negotiators Abu Mazen and Saeb Erekat; Mohammed Dahlan, a security
chief; and others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
