<HEADER>
A4841 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CRANBERRY-HARVEST-BOS     07-06 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRANBERRY-HARVEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO ORDER 15 PERCENT CUT IN CRANBERRY MARKETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal government plans to make cranberry growers cut the
amount of fruit they bring to market by roughly 15 percent below
historical levels, hoping to aid an industry reeling from
overproduction and sluggish demand.
</P>
<P>
   Urged on by Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc. of Lakeville, Mass. and
other big cranberry players, the US Department of Agriculture
issued a so-called marketing order to avert ``a potential for a
number of producers to go out of business,'' said USDA deputy
undersecretary Enrique Figueroa.
</P>
<P>
   Cranberries are Massachusetts' largest crop, with 1.8 million
barrels harvested each year. Some 14,000 acres of farmland are in
cranberry production, according to the state Department of Food and
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, reducing supply could mean that consumers will pay
higher prices, but the USDA said the impact of its marketing order
on consumers should be modest.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ocean Spray, which accounts for about 70 percent of
cranberry production, said it plans to lower some prices as it
looks to reduce its surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing order _ the first such order for cranberries in
nearly 30 years _ is set to go into effect next week, but that may
be too late for some growers to take steps to cut expenses on this
year's growing season.
</P>
<P>
   From the standpoint of planning a crop, ``April 1 would have
been the ideal date'' for a marketing order to have been issued,
said David Farrimond, executive director of the Cranberry Marketing
Committee, a part of the USDA.
</P>
<P>
   If an order had been issued in the spring, growers might have
been able to flood some of their bogs; when bogs are flooded early
in the season, they don't need to be pollinated, fertilized, and
treated with pesticides _ activities that incur expenses to
growers.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding bogs also can prevent cranberries from rotting on the
vine, something that can hurt future production.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday A.D. Makepeace Co. of Wareham, Mass., one of the
state's largest growers, indicated that it plans to flood some of
its bogs almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the USDA issue a marketing order so late in the growing
season? According to some observers, the USDA doesn't take such
dramatic steps unless there is an industry consensus. For many
months, there was much debate over whether a marketing order was
needed and how large it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Despite less than ideal timing, some in the industry believe
that a marketing order is better late than never.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray, for one, hailed the marketing order as an important
early step on the road to the industry's recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a huge help in fixing the supply side of the
problem,'' said Ocean Spray spokesman Chris Phillips. ``But it's up
to Ocean Spray to innovate and address the demand side of the
problem. (A marketing order) is far from the whole solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Don LeClair, a Norwell, Mass. grower, described the marketing
order as necessary short-term pain. Some sacrifices must be made
now to increase the chances of long-term survival, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was thinking of survival five years ago. In the
mid-1990s, the industry boomed. When a 100-pound barrel of
cranberries could fetch $60 and up, many growers scrambled to
increase acreage so they could take advantage of high prices.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 to 1999, the amount of North American acreage set
aside for growing cranberries rose by nearly 50 percent, according
to Ocean Spray.
</P>
<P>
   Because of increasing suburban development in the prime
cranberry growing areas of Massachusetts, local growers had little
room to expand. But growers in Wisconsin and Canada had wide open
spaces, and their acreage and production soared.
</P>
<P>
   Then the industry was hit by a double whammy. As growers
harvested bumper crops, demand softened. As a result of supply
exceeding demand, prices dropped to about $20 a barrel, and prices
could fall even further following the fall harvest.
</P>
<P>
   LeClair, the Norwell grower, said he needs to make $31 a barrel
for his cranberry operations to break even.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
