<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4843 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-COX     07-06 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong drops to 12th place
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOURS, France _ The initial escape from the pack for stage six
of the Tour de France started only nine miles into the 123-mile
race Thursday from the medieval town of Vitre to the more
metropolitan Tours.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Jacky Durand, who adores the thought of television
cameras following his every move, decided it wasn't too early to
make a break from the rest of the pack. Besides, Durand was on
familiar roads _ his hometown of Mayenne is near the route.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven other renegades quickly got in line behind Durand, a
bandana-wearing Frenchman. By day's end, nine of the initial 12
found themselves occupying spots in the overall top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Jalabert, who wore the yellow jersey for the past two
days, dropped to 10th. And America's Lance Armstrong, the defending
Tour de France champion, tumbled to 12th.
</P>
<P>
   The new leader is Telekom's Alberto Elli. The 36-year-old
Italian, the oldest rider in the Tour, was so thrilled with wearing
his first-ever ``les maillots jaunes'' that he lifted the collar of
his new yellow jersey to his face and kissed it.
</P>
<P>
   Elli is the third rider to wear the yellow jersey in six days.
That's one more leader than last year's race, when Jaan Kirisipuu
and Armstrong were the only two to sport yellow in the 21 stages.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of Thursday's stage was Rabobank's Leon Van Bon, who
picked up his second career Tour win. Markus Zberg, Van Bon's
teammate, was second. Eleven of the initial pack of 12, including
Elli, earned the same winning time of 4 hours, 28.06 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's odd Tour showing was a result of Team Once's lack of
defense for Jalabert's yellow jersey. No one from Once chased down
the breakaway riders in order to tire them enough to pull them back
to the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we preserved our chances of the overall
classification,'' Jalabert said.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the first week of the Tour has little bearing on
the eventual standings. The main contenders for the championship
are the riders who survive the first week of flat courses and
strive to distance themselves from the rest of the pack when the
race hits the difficult mountain stages in the Pyrenees and Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the outcome of Thursday's stage was a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attack was something we weren't planning for,'' Armstrong
said. ``Maybe it'll change the race a little. But I think the
favorites stay the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Elli, who started the day in 21st place, 2:11 out of first,
ended the stage with a 12-second overall lead over Fabrice Gougot.
Marc Wauters, another sprinter, was third, 1:17 out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   Jalabert was 5:40 behind Elli; Armstrong was 5:54. Both Jalabert
and Armstrong received the same time of 4 hours, 35.55 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Elli is a veteran of 11 Tours. However, his team strategy of
defending the jersey will be a unique one. Telekom's lead rider is
Jan Ullrich, who as the 1997 Tour winner figured to be Armstrong's
chief challenger this year. It's unlikely Ullrich will expend an
undue amount of energy helping Elli defend the jersey Ullrich
wants. The German rider also finished second in 1996 and 1998 but
did not ride last year because of a knee injury. He was 22nd after
Thursday, 6:37 behind Elli.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective is going to be to defend the jersey,'' Elli
said. ``And then in the mountains, I will try to pass it on to
Ullrich, who is more capable of keeping it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Livingston, a U.S. Postal Service teammate of Armstrong's,
said no one on his squad was that concerned about Thursday's change
in the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of us, we're OK,'' said Livingston, who is 24th
overall, 6:58 out of first. ``The makeup of the break was such
that, well they're great riders, but they're not really in
contention for the overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mountains will flip-flop everything. Maybe Telekom will
defend Elli one day, but their main objective is Ullrich.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin resident Chann McRae, who rides for Mapei, is 58th
overall.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Suzanne Halliburton at
shalliburton(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
