<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HUDSON-SHAKESPEARE-AR     07-06 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUDSON-SHAKESPEARE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE NATURE'S A STAGE, EVEN A PLAYER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT11 and 12 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARRISON, N.Y. _ In the theater it isn't always an encouraging
sign when the audience leaves humming the scenery. But at the
Hudson Valley Shakespeare Festival, it's all but inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, one of the best-kept theatrical secrets of summer
in the gentrified outer reaches of the New York metropolitan area,
is ensconced in the most lyrical of settings for open-air theater:
the grounds of the Boscobel Restoration, a historic house and
gardens on a promontory overlooking the Hudson River across from
West Point. The plays change each July and August, but the
magnificent backdrop is immutable. At sunset on performance nights,
the spectators take their seats in a yellow open-sided tent and
watch as the actors materialize in the distance, rising from behind
a bluff over the riverbank and making their way to the stage by way
of a manicured lawn bathed in a shimmering, late-day amber.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's an entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The festival's co-founder and longtime artistic director,
Terrence O'Brien, knows from long experience not to try to compete
too grandly with the landscape: the company's program notes the
contributions of designers of lighting, sound, costumes and
choreography. Notably missing: any mention of a set designer.
Nature got the job long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come here on some days and I think, `This is my office,'''
Stephen Paul Johnson says as he sits under an ancient shade tree on
the vast Boscobel lawn, taking a break from rehearsing ``Measure
for Measure,'' the festival's current offering, in which Johnson
plays Angelo, the lecherous villain. ``Our curtain goes up as the
sunlight starts to fade.''
</P>
<P>
   Theatrical fads inevitably fade, too, but Shakespeare alfresco,
it appears, is forever. From Lenox, Mass., where Shakespeare and
Company is in residence, to Central Park, where free Shakespeare is
such an entrenched institution that theatergoing New Yorkers seem
to claim tickets as a birthright, the summer months ring with the
sounds of 400-year-old soliloquies and sway to the rhythms of
iambic pentameter.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say classical theater in the great outdoors
doesn't have some obvious drawbacks; when nature doesn't cooperate,
the tortures can descend in an un-air-conditioned environment as
potently as the 12 plagues. ``Heat and bugs,'' O'Brien says,
enumerating two of the festival's most intrepid enemies. On
especially sultry nights, a lightheaded ticketbuyer or two have
been known to lose consciousness momentarily, and the squadrons of
mosquitoes will brazenly divebomb their targets through the most
heartbreaking moments in all of Shakespeare. The festival, in
response, has developed its own arsenal, a table laid with insect
sprays and lotions, and a new ventilation system that it says can
suck the hot air out of the tent every five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It does take a certain kind of resourcefulness to create art
under these circumstances, and the festival, now in its 14th
season, is used to squeezing every bit of advantage out of its
glorious surroundings. No one, of course, is getting rich doing
Elizabethan drama in a tent in Putnam County; the festival operates
on a relative shoestring. The budget for putting on two full-scale
productions, paying actors Equity scale, housing them at a local
college, renting the tent, leasing the grounds, printing the
programs and making the costumes is just under $600,000. The troupe
has almost no money for promotion, so it does not take out many
advertisements in the local papers, let alone film any of those
television commercials with the sappy post-show testimonials.
</P>
<P>
   OUT ON A LIMB
</P>
<P>
   What it does have is powerful word of mouth, helped along by
O'Brien's accessible and intelligent productions, many of which
have received favorable notices, including one this week by Ben
Brantley in The New York Times for the current production.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's ``Titus Andronicus,'' for example, was a daring
and controversial choice. The festival had built up an audience
over the years with safer fare like ``A Midsummer Night's Dream''
and ``As You Like It,'' but the director found in ``Titus'' an
intriguing parallel between its blood-soaked plot and the mechanics
of action-adventure movies. The violent denouement was played in
slow motion, a splatter scene in which the actors clutched spurting
bladders filled with a mixture of red food dye, chocolate syrup and
laundry detergent. Shakespeare, in other words, as a kind of hokier
version of ``Gladiator.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival is greatly aided, too, by those breathtaking vistas
of the Hudson, which put a visitor in mind of a hazy day on the
Rhine. There are, in fact, few pre-theater dinners more beguiling
than a picnic on the Boscobel grass, with a view clear down to the
Bear Mountain Bridge. (You can take your own meal or buy one of the
festival's, prepared in the kitchens of a nearby golf club.) The
combination has made it an ever more popular destination: last
year, a record 14,700 playgoers attended the festival's 45
performances of ``Twelfth Night'' and ``Titus.'' This season,
O'Brien and the festival's executive director, Susan Landstreet,
are hoping to do even better with 50 performances of ``Measure for
Measure'' and ``The Taming of the Shrew.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are no ``Lion King''-size paydays here. Even with
the record turnout, the festival finished last summer with exactly
zero dollars in the till. ``We took a bit of a bath,'' Landstreet
says, explaining that reviews for ``Titus'' were not published
until late in its run, so attendance at the early performances of
one of Shakespeare's obscurer plays was disappointing. The
festival's board came to the rescue with enough money to keep the
troupe afloat. But the experience pointed up how precarious staging
the classics becomes when a company of some ambition opts for
something other than the tried and true. Those bucolic country
roads can quickly become filled with potholes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   AN UNORTHODOX CHOICE
</P>
<P>
   It is a humid Saturday afternoon in late June at Boscobel, a
crucial day in the life of the Hudson Valley Shakespeare Festival.
In a few hours, ``Measure for Measure'' is to open, and like
``Titus'' the summer before, it is an unorthodox choice. (In
contrast, ``Shrew,'' the season's second offering, is ``selling
like hot cakes,'' Landstreet says.) The play tells the improbable
story of a man sentenced to death for fornication; his sister, a
novice in an abbey, pursued by a venomous lawman; and a noble duke
roaming his corrupted city in disguise. It veers wildly between
comedy and tragedy and has a thoroughly unconvincing happy ending
tacked on.
</P>
<P>
   Under the tent, O'Brien has Johnson, a festival veteran, and
Aidan Sullivan, a recent Juilliard graduate, in the key role of
Isabella, the novice, going over one of the play's most difficult
scenes, in which Angelo makes his sexual desire known to Isabella.
``That felt mechanical,'' Johnson says after hesitantly caressing
Sullivan. O'Brien, a lug of a guy in Bermuda shorts and sandals,
whispers something to the actors, and they try the scene again.
This time, Sullivan registers more revulsion, and the director
seems satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, who lives in Manhattan with his wife and two young
children, has been having at Shakespeare every summer since 1987,
when an actress friend, Melissa Stern Lourie, invited him to Putnam
to stage a benefit outdoor performance of ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream.'' It proved so popular that O'Brien and Stern _ who has
since left the troupe _ decided to found the festival, with the
help of a group of local supporters who formed a board. In its
second season the festival moved to Boscobel, an 18th-century
estate restored by a private foundation in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   MOONLIGHTING
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of feel like my job is as a divining rod, just to sit
there and see if what's going on is true or not,'' said O'Brien,
who is, in a sense, moonlighting in the countryside. His day job is
creating customized software, which seems about as far removed from
the forests of Arden, the courts of Vienna and the midsummer
fairies as one can get. ``Most of my clients think it's exciting,''
he said. ``But my cell phone does go off during rehearsals, and
it's `Hi, we ran out of disk space in the notes server.'''
</P>
<P>
   When you are a serious theater person, and you get to direct one
show a year (the ``Shrew,'' now in rehearsals, is being directed by
his colleague Nick Mangano), the emotional stakes can be pretty
high. O'Brien says he begins thinking about his production months
before the first actor is cast, and usually the initial ideas for
his interpretation come from music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I end up being very intuitive about these choices,'' he says.
``Suddenly a song will come to my mind, and I'll make a connection
between the lyric of the song and the play.'' For `Measure,' the
inspiration was, of all things, `Santa Baby,' a kitschy Eartha Kitt
song from the '50s. O'Brien's quirky linkage is incorporated into
the production in a highly visible way. The number, lip-synched by
Sullivan to Kitt's recording and accompanied by a vamping chorus of
actors, provides a stylish opening to the second act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The song is like a comic extreme of what's happening in the
play,'' O'Brien says, adding, ``I end up justifying the choice
intellectually, even though the choice was intuitive to begin
with.''
</P>
<P>
   `WEIRD LITTLE SETUP'
</P>
<P>
   If the tent is a fairly spartan affair _ 400 folding chairs on
risers arranged in a wide semicircle _ so are the actors' living
conditions. This year, the company consists of 11 Equity players,
who make $415 a week, and are put up in the dorms of Mount St. Mary
College in Newburgh, which charges the festival $9 an actor a
night, Landstreet said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave Kurt and me a double bed,'' Nance Williamson said
with a laugh, referring to her husband, Kurt Rhoads. They are what
you might call the festival's answer to the Lunts, having appeared
together as Beatrice and Benedick in ``Much Ado About Nothing'''
and, this summer, as Kate and Petruchio in ``Shrew.'' They have
attracted a following among Hudson Valley's audiences, which come
chiefly from Westchester, Putnam and Dutchess counties, though the
festival is looking for ways to increase its draw from Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Lunts live in the dorm like everyone else. ``When you first
hear about it, it's like, `Oh, no, there's a tent and bare grass
and a mud floor?'' said Rhoads, who is playing the duke in
``Measure'' and is in his sixth festival season here. ``The
ingredients are not for a very professional experience. But you
know, this environment, this weird little setup, is a great way to
tell a story.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien uses the vast Boscobel space in inspired ways to tell
the stories. There was the time, in ``Tartuffe,'' when he had the
actors arrive at the tent on a wagon, as if they were members of a
road company of the Comedie Francaise. And there are times when the
space uses them, as on the Fourth of July weekend last year, when
teen-agers setting off firecrackers nearby provided inadvertent
sound and lighting effects for ``Twelfth Night.'' A company member
had to explain to the audience that the celebration was not of the
festival's devising. Another evening, during ``Titus,'' the power
blew, and the cast performed with flashlights.
</P>
<P>
   On the opening night of ``Measure,'' the tent is packed with
people, not mosquitoes. O'Brien sits in a seat near the back, a
legal pad in his lap. There will be notes for the actors, a couple
more rehearsals, and O'Brien is in essence done for the year. It's
back to custom database applications, and thoughts of next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking very strongly about doing `Richard III,''' he
said. ``I'll latch onto something and just sort of daydream. I
picture what something might look like in that space.''
</P>
<P>
   And already, he's hearing music. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson Valley Shakespeare Festival is offering two comedies,
``Measure for Measure,'' and ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' in
repertory this season at the Boscobel Restoration, 1601 Route 9D,
Garrison, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend ``Measure for Measure'' will be presented at 8 p.m.
July 7 and 8 and 6 p.m. July 9. Tickets are $19 to $30 ($17 for
previews), with a 20 percent discount for students and the elderly
and a 50 percent discount for children 12 and younger for all but
Saturday night performances. Prepared picnics, $16 and $18, are
available by reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Other performances of ``Measure for Measure'' this season will
be July 12 to 16, 20, 22 to 23, 26 and 30. ``The Taming of the
Shrew'' will be presented on July 19, 21 and 27 to 29; Aug. 2 to 6,
9 to 13, 16 to 20 and 23 to 27.
</P>
<P>
   Information and reservations: (914) 265-9575.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
