<SLUG> BC-BLACKCHURCH-ELDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDERS URGES BLACK CHURCHES TO TEACH ABOUT SEXUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER WALSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sex talk in church is usually taboo, but it needs
to be a common topic of sermons and discussion, especially in black
churches, former surgeon general Joycelyn Elders said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you don't like talking about sex from the pulpit,''
Elders said in the keynote address at the National Black Religious
Summit on Sexuality. ``When we have a problem with education, we go
to the church. When we have a problem with racism, we go to the
church. We've got a crisis that requires crisis intervention. I'm
asking that the church get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-day summit, sponsored by the Black Church Initiative,
brought together about 600 ministers, church leaders, and health
professionals to address sexuality issues in the black church.
</P>
<P>
   Although almost all of the participants cheered in agreement
with Elders's message, which included teaching about birth control,
sexually transmitted diseases, and abortion, others thought she was
sending the wrong message to today's youth.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the Rev. Wesley Roberts of the People's Baptist
Church and president of the Black Ministerial Alliance of Greater
Boston said the church should only preach abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other places that can give them information about
birth control methods,'' he said in a phone interview. ``I think we
should be careful to not tell them that promiscuity is OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Glenn Campbell of the Central Congressional Church in
Boston, who is attending the summit, said he is trying to start sex
education programs in the Boston area, but it is not easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to get the black church to deal with the
issues,'' said Campbell after Elders's speech. ``It's not that we
don't want to, it's that we don't know how.''
</P>
<P>
   Elders, who was fired as surgeon general in 1994 after
suggesting sex education classes include information about
masterbation, said it is unrealistic to think teenagers will not
have sex just because they are told not to. ``The vows of
abstinence break far more easily than condoms,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the congregation, Elders said, need to play a key
role in encouraging sex education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preachers don't preach about it because the mothers in the
front row will want to throw them out of the church,'' she said.
``We don't want to talk about it in church because it says they did
something wrong. They're sinners. What good is church if it's not
going to save sinners?''
</P>
<P>
   Christhol McClain, a 16-year-old from Washington attending the
conference, said the church might be the only place where teens can
turn for information about sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't taught at home, it needs to be taught in the
church,'' McClain said. ``Kids are getting worse and worse, and we
need to do something about it. The church thinks you should keep
sex on the hush-up and it's not like that. Some kids don't know
anything about sex. If you don't tell them about it, they'll go out
and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elders, who is now a professor at the University of Arkansas
School of Medical Science, said teaching that premarital sex is
immoral needs to be put aside so sex education can take center
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to stop talking about morals and start teaching
responsibility,'' Elders said. ``Ignorance is not bliss. We've
tried it for a thousand years. It's not working so we need to try
education.''
</P>
<P>
   With more black teenagers getting pregnant and blacks accounting
for almost 50 percent of AIDS cases, black churches are the ideal
spot to start prevention and education measures, Elders said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to start talking about it where more black people go
than anywhere else _ that's the church,'' she said. ``It's time
that we as people of faith come out of the closets and serve that
God we talk about on Sundays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
