<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following
entertainment/arts and travel articles for release Sunday, July 9,
2000. The financial budget will follow. Note that this week's
financial budget includes the mutual fund report for the first half
of 2000, totaling 10 articles. If you have questions about stories,
call 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (moving in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VERMEER-OPERA (Amsterdam, the Netherlands) _ Peter Greenaway,
the British movie director, and Louis Andriessen, the Dutch
composer, are opening the Lincoln Center Festival 2000 with a new
opera, ``Writing to Vermeer.'' Focusing on two weeks in 1672 when
the painter Johannes Vermeer made a trip to The Hague, the creators
imagine that he received 18 fictional letters from women in his
life and sensed the crisis gripping the country as it prepared to
breach the country's dikes to hold off invasion by France. By Alan
Riding.
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-MUSIC (New York) _ The development of 12-tone composition
was one of the most invigorating occurrences of the 20th-century
music. Now two theories persist and conflict: Was there a tyranny
of the atonal composers who seized the intellectual high ground and
intimidated tonal composers or was it these modern composers who
were the beleagured minority? By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CIRCUS-LES-COLPORTEURS (Marseille, France) _ ``Filao'' from Les
Colporteurs, the French nouveau cirque, is the story of a French
aristocrat who becomes so disgusted with the world he climbs a tree
and stays there. The trapeze artists mix art forms and execute
their feats to music and with theatricality. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-DIAMOND (New York) _ Learn by doing: that is the premise
of the Diamond project, named after its principal donor, Irene
Diamond. Peter Martins, City Ballet's artistic director, initiated
this showcase for new choreography in 1992, repeated it in 1994 and
1997 and hit pay dirt with this spring's series. By Anna
Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-ULTIMA-VEZ _ (New York) _ When Wim Vandekeybus, the
Belgian choreographer, presented in New York from 1987 to 1991,
dancers ducked as others threw bricks at them, and the norm
consisted of flying bodies, confrontational games and erotic
aggressiveness. The 37-year-old choreographer warns the Lincoln
Center Festival says he no longer has to throw bricks to show
intense instinct. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-NOCHE-FLAMENCA (Madrid, Spain) _ In the gypsy quarter of
Madrid, Martin Santangelo rehearses five musicians and six flamenco
dancers for an American tour. This New Yorker has found a calling
in a 15th-century dance form. By Valerie Gladstone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SINGER-XMEN-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Bryan Singer's ``X-Men,'' based
on characters from the comic book series created by Stan Lee, is
one of the bigger extravaganzas of the summer. ``It's actually
about prejudice,'' said the 34-year-old filmmaker. By Bernard
Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   PODESWA-FIVESENSES-FILM (New York) _ Laura Winters interviews
Jeremy Podeswa, the Canadian filmmaker whose ``Five Senses'' will
open at the Lincoln Center Festival. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OZON-FILM (New York) _ The French director Francois Ozon has
made thrillers about homicidal house guests and high school
killers. In satire, he has explored the lighter sides of
cannibalism and incest. But his latest film tackles the horrors of
one couple's life. ``Water Drops on Burning Rocks'' is his screen
adaptation of a play written by Rainer Werner Fassbinder at the age
of 19. By Leslie Camhi.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION/RADIO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HAMBURG-RADIO (New York) _ Joan Hamburg speaks to listeners in
the warm, confidential manner women use when chatting with friends.
She dispenses tips on city living, interviews an entertainer or the
author of a book and then takes calls for an hour, keeping a
million and a half people _ mostly women over 30 _ listening. Her
audience, nearly twice the size of those for competing talk shows,
earns WOR in New York nearly $1 million a year in revenue, a
remarkable figure for a daytime show.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITE-SISTERS-RADIO (New York) _ The Satellite Sisters _
Liz, Julie, Monica, Sheila and Lian Dolan _ are WNYC Radio's rising
stars. What the Satellite Sisters do is get together for a
conference call. Liz is usually in New York, Lian is in Pasadena,
Calif., and Julie comes in via satellite from Bangkok. The other
two sisters _ Monica in Portland and Sheila in New York _ are also
sometimes on the line, depending on their schedules. By Anita
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-MUSIC-POP (New York) _ The composers, visionaries,
theorists, tinkerers and crackpots who invented electronic music
probably never imagined that by the end of the 20th century,
thousands of people would regularly turn out to hear electronic
music in clubs and that the futuristic sounds are now taken for
granted by anyone who tunes in a Top 40 radio station. By Jon
Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARCHITECTURE/ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-CENTER (New York) _ Herbert Muschamp, architecture
critic for The Times, evaluates David Child's design for the
Columbus Circle site and finds it ``vastly superior'' to earlier
versions.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOGRAPHY-SACCO (New York) _ Argentine artist Graciela Sacco
uses a heliography technique to place images on suitcases, Venetian
blinds, refrigerators and even postage stamps. In the current
exhibit at the Argentine Consulate here, visitors are confronted
by, among other things, small spoons hanging from a line. On each
spoon an open mouth has been heliographed. She has also hung a
series of clear plastic frames imprinted with the image of eyes as
if the art were looking at the visitor, not vice versa. By Lyle
Rexer.
</P>
<P>
   ROSLER-ART (New York) _ After stops in England, France, Austria
and Spain, ``Martha Rosler: Positions in the Life World'' makes its
only United States appearance in a joint presentation here by the
New Museum of Contemporary Art and the International Center of
Photography. By Michael Rush. &QL; 
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-GORT (Undated) _ Gort, in County Galway, is surrounded
by ancient monastic ruins and countryside that inspired poets. By
Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-IRELAND-BURREN (Undated) _ The dramatic limestone cliffs
of the Burren, on the seashore in County Clare, form a gray canvas
that is dappled with bright wildflowers in summer. By Lisa Fugard.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GASOLINE-PRICES (Undated) _ A random sampling of
destinations, including the nation's two most popular tourist
sites, Las Vegas and Orlando, Fla., found no appreciable falloff in
visitors because of the increase in gasoline prices. Yet Edwin
McDowell also found many indications that travelers are downsizing
vacations _ cutting short the number of days and number of miles
traveled _ to economize on gas.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Choosing phone service abroad: a
bewildering array of choices. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Ray Cormier answers questions about the
new United States Lines, tours of World War I sites in France and
where to hear church music in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Kiosks open at seven airports to rent
DVD players and movies; Hotel Savoy reopens in Florence, Italy;
Francis Gary Powers Jr. leads a Cold War tour; a hotel in St.
Thomas offers Nannies in Paradise so parents can have a night out
and rail service is completed for Sydney Airport.
</P>
