<P>
   EDITORS: We will move the following articles from The New York
Times mutual fund report for the first half of 2000. All will move
for release Sunday, July 9, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-FLOW (Undated) _ If technology remains the obsession of
American investors, where are money managers placing their bets
now? The answers can have all the longevity of a cast member on
``Survivor.'' To trace the path of new-economy investing, fast feet
and a good line of technospeak are required. By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-PERFORMANCE (Undated) _ In the long-running debate
between managers of funds that search for cheap stocks and those
that chase the fastest-growing companies, neither was an exultant
winner. The growth funds that had dominated for most of the long
bull market for stocks flamed out, but their value-seeking
counterparts did not exactly soar from their ash piles. An
interest-bearing checking account turned out to be a better place
to stash cash than either broad category of stock fund. By Patrick
McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL (Undated) _ Investors who thought they
could lessen their risk by diversifying overseas found little
solace last quarter in international equity funds, many of which
underperformed their domestic counterparts. By Vivian Marino.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-STRATEGIES (Undated) _ On behalf of financial planners,
academics, investment advisers and self-anointed experts
everywhere, I apologize. It appears that much of what you have been
told over the last 30 years about the benefits of international
diversification has been greatly exaggerated. In fact, according to
a new study, those benefits are less than half as great as
originally thought. By Mark Hulbert.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-ESSAY (Undated) _ Commentary: If you are like me, all
these fund family crests leave you cold. Granted, illustrating
something so fuzzy as an investment philosophy is no easy feat but
can't we do any better than a bunch of polygons, sailing vessels
and oak trees? By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-BONDS (Undated) _ Do not be put off by how eye-glazingly
abstruse the subject sounds: A bill making its way through Congress
to change how government-sponsored agencies like Freddie Mac and
Fannie Mae are regulated could, if enacted, have some profound
effects on the portfolios of millions of ordinary investors. By
Abby Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-INVESTORS (Undated) _ Meet the managed account, which
many people view as the latest threat to the 75-year-old mutual
fund industry. It used to be that only a privileged few could
afford their own money manager, but in the last few years assets in
privately managed accounts have swelled. Credit, in part, a bull
market that has more than doubled the number of millionaire
households since 1983, to five million. By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-JUNKBONDS (Undated) _ Remember junk bonds? It was the
play stuff of Michael Milken, mother's milk of the 1980s
leveraged-buyout craze and eventually a symbol of that decade's
decadence. In recent quarters, junk bonds have logged some of their
worst performance in almost a decade. By Kate Berry.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-MUNIS (Undated) _ For fixed-income investors, there
appears to be a lucrative silver lining in the cloud of rising
interest rates: buying opportunities among closed-end municipal
bond funds. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-RETIRE (Undated) _ Because saving for retirement had
become a crucial issue for Americans, The New York Times in 1993
asked five mutual-fund experts how they would invest a hypothetical
nest egg of $50,000 for someone who planned to retire in 20 years
or more. Each quarter since then, the five portfolios have been
reviewed and fine-tuned and their performances compared in these
pages. With results from the second quarter of 2000, the exercise
concludes, and the participants discuss what they, and investors,
have learned along the way. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-MANAGERS (Undated) _ There were swoons and rebounds, and
then more again of the same. But by the end of the second quarter,
the stock market had provided enough bad news to push every major
category of United States diversified equity funds into negative
territory for the period. Over all, domestic diversified stock
funds lost 4.3 percent. What funds managed to shine as stormy
weather lashed the markets? Generally, the winners owned shares in
companies in old-economy sectors, like oil and gas, as well as in
health care and some financial services. Managers of three
top-performing funds talked about the resurgence of
once-beaten-down sectors and what they expect from the stock market
during the remainder of the year. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
