<P>
   AT&AMP;T-FUTURE (Undated) _ On May 2, AT&AMP;T dropped its bomb on the
company's investors. AT&AMP;T said its operations would grow more
slowly and earn less this year than the company had previously led
investors to expect. The company's shares, which had closed that
Monday at $49, lost $7.0625, shaving more than $25 billion from
AT&AMP;T's market value. And the shares did not bounce back. They lost
more value the next day. And the day after that. And the day after
that. The pain continues. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SHOE-SALES (Undated) _ Despite the boom in consumer spending,
shoe sales have grown at a minuscule 1.8 percent a year for the
last decade, according to Footwear Marketing Insights, the
Nashville-based industry research arm. That is in keeping with
historical growth, but disappointing compared to the 1980s, when
fueled by the athletic craze, shoe consumption jumped about 6
percent a year. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ Weekly Wall Street commentary. By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COHEN-SULLIVAN-PROFILE (Undated) _ For more than 30 years,
Rodgin Cohen has been a sought-after counselor to chief executives
at the industry's largest financial institutions, including the
Bank of New York, First Union and Societe Generale, as well as an
adviser on some of this era's largest mergers. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED-HIGHTECH (Moorestown, N.J.) _ The locals call it ``the
cruiser in the cornfield.'' What looks like the top half of a Navy
vessel is actually a lab where the Lockheed Martin Corp. tests its
ability to knit together naval communications gear, sensors, radar,
and controls used to fire weapons. By Stan Crock.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Subject to come. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   BIZBOOKS (Undated) _ Off the Shelf: Citizen Coors: An American
Dynasty, by Dan Baum. By Alecia Swazy.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   GAS-TAX-DEDUCTION (Undated) _ High gas prices at the pump,
despite recent agreements to increase oil production, will surely
add to the political debate. They may also change the calculus on
another question: whether people who rack up business mileage
should use the standard rate or the actual-expense method when
calculating tax deductions. By Stacy Kravetz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Economic View: Topic to come. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   MY-MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ I am not a broker, a financial
adviser or even a day trader. Heck, I don't even own a single share
of stock outright. So why can't I stop watching CNBC? By Lynn
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER-BACKLASH (Berkeley, Calif.) _ College students who share
their music files on the Internet have been accused of stealing
copyrighted works, or at least of exhibiting questionable morality.
Ask the students in a college town like this one and they will beg
to differ. By Matthew Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABOUTCARS-MAZDA (Detroit) _ Next month Mazda introduces the
Tribute, and it has the makings to be best in class in a booming
segment of the car market. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-DISNEYLAND (Anaheim) _ Throngs of wanna-be drivers,
including some never before behind the wheel, are lining up here to
test-drive three new automobiles, rolled out late last month amid a
promotional blitz comparable to a new-product introduction by
Detroit. Yet these vehicles are unavailable in dealer showrooms,
though they do come with a price tag: the $41 cost of admission to
the Magic Kingdom at Disneyland. By Andrea Adelson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
