<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4852 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBO-GIANT-BASEBALLS-C     07-06 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GIANT-BASEBALLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball rolling out All-Star festivities
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Atlanta will be awash in baseballs this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials plan to roll out 100 giant baseballs as part
of a summer-long exhibit tied to Major League Baseball's All-Star
Game here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Colorfully decorated baseballs will be displayed around the
city, including Centennial Olympic Park, Underground Atlanta and
Turner Field. The promotion is similar to Cows on Parade, an
exhibit held in Chicago last year.
</P>
<P>
   Like in Chicago, at the end of the exhibit, the balls will be
auctioned, with proceeds going to the local arts community and
sports-related charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the launch, not the ending,'' said Bill Howard, vice
president of tourism and public relations for the Atlanta
Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, 115 baseballs have been sold, and there are commitments
for numerous others, Howard said. Initially, officials had hoped to
sell 500 baseballs, but production schedules and the amount of time
need to position the balls forced them to scale back to 300.
</P>
<P>
   Still ``if we can reach 300 we will have met all of our goals,''
Howard said. ``This is a very attainable goal. We're already a
third of the way there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-five percent of the balls have been designed by
professional artists. Somes are designated to represent Major
League Baseball teams, but others can be decorated how the buyer
chooses.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Atlanta Hilton &AMP; Towers has a
chocolate-covered baseball in the lobby of its hotel on Courtland
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of visitors,'' said Hilton General Manager
Dick Groves. ``There's a lot of picture-taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Today also marks the start of the John Hancock All-Star FanFest,
a baseball-themed interactive attraction at the Georgia World
Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're off to a great start,'' said Gary Stokan, president of
the Atlanta Sports Council.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star Game is expected to have an economic impact of $50
million.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials say landing the event helps bolster the city's
image in sporting events circles.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is one of four cities in the running for the 2005 Super
Bowl. Others are Miami, Oakland, Calif., and Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Stokan said the city also is making bids for ESPN's X Games in
2003 and 2004, the 2004 National Figure Skating Championship and
the Goodwill Games in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
