<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NOTES-N     07-06 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS MAY BE HURTING, BUT SO IS HIS OPPONENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TEN-WIMBLEDON) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Pete Sampras' latest injury has all but
been dusted for prints and sent to the lab. For more than a week,
he has described the tendinitis living inside of his lower left
shin, but it has been treated as an allegation and not a fact.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone believes Sampras is in pain. And if he is, no one
wants to hear about it from a six-time Wimbledon champion who has
tiptoed through five unseeded players on his way to another
non-threatening opponent in Friday's semifinal. The unassuming
Vladimir Voltchkov _ a penny-pinching qualifier who had to borrow
shorts and shoes during his extended stay at Wimbledon _ is the
only player in Sampras' way of reaching the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When players go out there and see Pete Sampras totally
dominate, it's aggravating to have him say he's not feeling
right,'' said John McEnroe, who is an analyst for NBC and the Davis
Cup captain. ``Pete talks about it, and it's like he's saying, `If
I lose, it's because of the injury. But by the way, I'm about to be
in the finals again.'''
</P>
<P>
   He could even make history. The injury has created diversion
from Sampras' chase of Roy Emerson's record even though he is in
pouncing position to win his 13th Grand Slam event. First, there is
Voltchkov. Next, Andre Agassi may await. But the second-seeded
Agassi has a far more treacherous path to the finals. He will play
the 12th-seeded Patrick Rafter, who is playing his best tennis
since shoulder surgery in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see Pat playing well,'' said Agassi, who leads
the head-to-head matchup with Rafter, 7-3, which includes his
semifinal victory here against the Aussie last year. ``I think he's
a great athlete with a lot to offer the sport of tennis. This is a
great arena to compete against him in because it's Wimbledon. He's
one of the best competitors out there, if not the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi also possesses untouchable desire. With his instincts and
quick hands, with his brainpower and fancy footwork, Agassi has
unveiled his magic over the fortnight. He escaped a five-set match
against Todd Martin in the second round, then dodged the atomic
serve of Mark Philippoussis in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 thing against Andre is that you have to serve
well,'' said Rafter, whose kick-serve can be problematic for
Agassi. ``And you've got to serve well all day. If you can do that,
you've got a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds for Voltchkov to advance are slim. But the smiling
22-year-old from Belarus doesn't seem flustered by the occasion,
just grateful for the chance to double his career winnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play Pete in the semifinals of Wimbledon, what else do you
wish for?'' said Voltchkov, who will make $193,000 for stepping on
the court. ``It's like a dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   The health of Sampras shouldn't be a factor. Although he hasn't
been practicing between matches, Sampras has been moving well on
the court, seemingly unencumbered by the pains viewed with
suspicion by other players. The acupuncture treatments seem to
help, but getting rest has been the best cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been different not practicing,'' Sampras said.
``Mentally, it's a little unsettling. I've been dealt this hand,
and there's not much I can do about it now; Just got to go out
there and try my best, just work through it. It's not ideal, but
I'll just go out there with a good frame of mind and et it go.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe Worried About Sampras
</P>
<P>
   John McEnroe's concerns about Sampras' injury extend beyond
Wimbledon. With a Davis Cup matchup in Spain just two weeks away,
the captain of the team doesn't know if Sampras will be available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the suspicion that there won't be good news at the end
of the day for Davis Cup,'' McEnroe said.
</P>
<P>
   Questions About TV Coverage
</P>
<P>
   Tennis fans were left wondering (and sputtering) about when they
would actually get to see the broadcast of the hot Wimbledon
women's semifinal between Venus and Serena Williams on NBC Thursday
afternoon. When NBC's four-hour taped broadcast of the matches
began at 1 p.m., the Williams sisters were nowhere to be seen.
Instead, NBC began its coverage with portions of Wednesday's men's
quarterfinal between Pete Sampras and Jan-Michael Gambill.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Sampras-Gambill a day-old offering whose result was
already known, but viewers were also left in the dark as to exactly
when coverage of the Williams-Williams semifinal would begin.
Viewers were told that the day's ``featured match between the
Williams sisters would be at the conclusion'' of the
Sampras-Gambill quarterfinal. But the problem was ``the
conclusion'' was a long time coming and tennis fans never knew when
it would be: the Williamses finally took Center Court on NBC around
3 p.m., some two hours after the broadcast began.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we were trying to do was have the largest audience for
the second match,'' Cameron Blanchard, director of communications
for NBC, said by telephone from London, ``and research indicates
that the larger audience is available later in the afternoon. We
wanted that match to be the Williams sisters because the match was
so highly anticipated and the sisters have been such a big story.''
</P>
<P>
   So, why not show the women's semifinal between Lindsay Davenport
and Jelena Dokic first? Blanchard said that TNT, which has worked
in tandem with NBC to bring Wimbledon 2000 to U.S. viewers, ``had
Davenport'' for its telecast later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chose Sampras-Gambill first,'' Blanchard said, ``because
many of our viewers hadn't seen it.'' But many of TNT's viewers had
seen it ... on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ SUSAN B. ADAMS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
