<HEADER>
A4860 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HENLEY-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      07-06 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HENLEY-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYING SOLO, HENLEY EYES THE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after July 9, 2000, by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, Eagles singer-drummer Don Henley famously
sang in ``Hotel California'' that ``you can check out anytime you
like but you can never leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the quintessential Southern California rocker did leave _
but it took the Northridge earthquake to push him out.
</P>
<P>
   Henley _ the voice and co-writer of such classics as ``Witchy
Woman,'' ``One of These Nights,'' ``Best of My Love,'' ``New Kid in
Town,'' ``Hotel California,'' ``Heartache Tonight,'' ``Desperado,''
``Sunset Grill'' and ``The Last Resort'' _ and his future wife
moved to Dallas after the 1994 quake destroyed the dream home he
designed.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Inside Job'' (Warner Bros.), his first album of new
material in 11 years, Henley writes of the peace and contentment
he's found since.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening line to the song ``Everything is Different Now,''
Henley, who appears Saturday and Sunday at Universal Amphitheatre,
sings: ``I hate to tell you this, but I'm very, very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Married in 1995 to Sharon Summerall, who like Henley is a Texas
native, the couple is raising three children. In 1990, Henley
founded the Walden Woods Project (www.walden.org), an environmental
preservation organization. And he and Eagles partner Glenn Frey
were recently inducted into the Songwriter's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Eagles, Henley shares in the biggest-selling
album ever in the U.S. The Eagles' ``Greatest Hits 1971-75'' passed
``Thriller'' for that honor.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Henley's best-selling new album contains plenty of
pointed social and political commentary, but there are also songs
celebrating the happy state of his home life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been inspiring,'' Henley, 53, says of his slow-lane life
today. ``I really believe I've rediscovered my better self. I feel
like I did when I was in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley, who won a Grammy Award in 1990 for his previous solo
disc, the 6-million-selling ``The End of the Innocence,''
originally came to Los Angeles in 1970 with his band, Shiloh,
before joining Linda Ronstadt's band and forming the Eagles in
1971.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, whose honeyed harmonies obscured the lyrics' dark
view of life in the Golden State, have since reunited for tours and
special events, including a date last New Year's Eve at Staples
Center that Henley calls ``one of the best shows we've ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   And we found that while talking with Henley by phone from his
home that is outspokenness isn't confined to his lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your take on the corporate mergers that have left few
major labels standing?
</P>
<P>
   A: To paraphrase Charles Dickens, it's the best of times and
worst of times. I'm deeply concerned with the corporatization of
America and the world in general. Everyday I see companies being
formed that in earlier times would be considered monopolies. And we
have a Congress now that is in the habit of looking the other way.
Anything goes. You can merge, conglomerate, globalize, and it's
frightening to me. I wake up in the morning and don't know who I
work for. It's particularly frightening in regards to the media
because things have been merged to the point where there are
serious conflicts of interest in terms of art and truth in
journalism. It isn't good for democracy, the decimation of truth,
art or culture.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You haven't spoken out about the forthcoming presidential
election. What's your take?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've sat this election out so far because I've been busy with
this album and my family. But (Vice President Al) Gore is the best
choice we have. I certainly think he's the best alternative. With
(Texas Gov. George W.) Bush, Texas is the most polluted state in
the union. It's surpassed Los Angeles as having the worst pollution
in the country. Texas is not only the most polluted but it's the
most pollution-producing state in the nation. So, I would much
prefer Gore on that front. Texas also has problems with its
education system. Texas has the highest teen pregnancy rate in the
U.S. and over a million kids who are hungry. Texas has serious air
quality and water problems. People need to look a little deeper
into the presidential race. Bush has a hands-off style of
governing. He's a non-interference kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: To change the subject, what are the chances of the Eagles
getting together again?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's 50-50. It changes week to week and month to month. I'm
currently concerned with my new record and touring behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You left the Geffen imprint before it was merged and
dismantled and you moved to Warners. What was behind the move?
</P>
<P>
   A: I saw the Geffen thing coming. I left happily because I
didn't think they were doing a very good job promoting my work. I
wanted out and I got out. I'm very happy at Warners. They had the
Eagles catalog by and large and some of my solo work. So Warners
always felt like home to me. And my manager Irving Azoff has his
own label there. I have longstanding relationships with some of the
people who remain there. Unfortunately, (longtime former Warners
execs) Mo Ostin and Lenny Waronker are gone, which was an enormous
mistake. But there are still some good people there and so far I'm
extremely pleased with the new record. The reception at Radio has
been tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have a new road band. What do you look for in touring
musicians?
</P>
<P>
   A: Musicianship is first with personality running a close second
since I'm going to have to spend a lot of time in close proximity
with these people. They should have a sense of humor, a level head
and they shouldn't have any substance abuse problems. They're all
funny, good looking, musically accomplished family men.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are your feelings on Napster?
</P>
<P>
   A: I take stealing very seriously. I don't care what kind of
spin they put on it, it's stealing plain and simple. Singers and
songwriters and recording artists should be compensated for their
work just like everyone else. I cannot fathom any kind of
justification for stealing the works of artists who depend on their
work for their livelihood. And whether an artist is wealthy or
poor, stealing is still stealing. And it's wrong. I haven't filed
suit against Napster, but I'll eventually be part of a class action
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the Internet itself?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Internet can be used for good such as education and the
decimation of news but it's also the repository for a lot of
garbage which is proved everyday by people like Jenny Jones and
Jerry Springer who are exploiting the problems of working class
people and degrading them at the same time. The same goes for the
Internet. It's an absolutely wonderful tool for communication, for
education, even for creating a certain type of community. But on
the other hand there's a tremdnous amount of litter along the
information highway. Any technology can be abused and will be.
Unfortunately, our lawmakers are sadly behind the curve and the law
has not kept up with the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the record industry still unfair in terms of contracts?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not as bad as it was then. But it still has a ways to go
in terms of fairness. Even if they give you a good contract, it's
hard to collect the money. You have to do regular audits and fight
every step of the way to get what's coming to you. It's a constant
struggle. You're never sure if you're getting what's coming to you.
</P>
<P>
   Q: One last thing. When you first heard those million-dollar
Eagles harmonies back in 1971, did you know the sound would take
off the way it did?
</P>
<P>
   A: I honestly didn't think of it in million-dollar terms. I was
young and filled with a sense of wonder and possibility. I was
mostly thinking about music and girls and not the money. I hoped to
make a living but I never expected our success would reach the
level it reached. I'm truly grateful for all that. But I don't like
to rest on my laurels. I'm more concerned with today and tomorrow. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
Who: Don Henley. &QL; 
Where: Universal Amphitheatre, 100 Universal City Plaza, Universal
City. &QL; 
When: 8:15 p.m. Saturday and Sunday. &QL; 
Tickets: $39.50 to $99.50. &QL; 
Information: (213) 480-3232.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
