<HEADER>
A4870 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     07-06 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR WOULD CRINGE AT THIS NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Sportswriters aren't a dying breed. They just
tend to dress nicer, diet, brush their teeth and care about
relationships more these days.
</P>
<P>
   And that's usually where the dilemma begins.
</P>
<P>
   As if anyone outside the profession cares, this low-lying branch
of the media is fighting a constant image problem.
</P>
<P>
   We already deal with the fact that athletes treat us as a
necessary evil, readers constantly ridicule us, and we're generally
not much use to anyone except friends looking for free tickets.
</P>
<P>
   We're kinda lovable losers. At least in our own minds.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't help when, in the same week, a sportswriter is
included in People Magazine's list of the top 100 most eligible
bachelors and Oscar Madison goes to the big press box buffet in the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   What message does this send out? We not only have to worry about
how we look, but how compatible we'd be with someone of the
opposite sex - and whether we believe Pete Rose belongs in the Hall
of Fame. There aren't enough hours in the day for all that.
Especially if there's a game going on.
</P>
<P>
   If everyone believed that Walter Matthau's cigar-smelling,
mustard- stained character from ``The Odd Couple'' was an
exaggeration of a typical sportswriter, all the better. Scribes
tend to relish the fact that they're traditionally cast off among
the undesirables, oblivious to those who actually have a life. They
can play in their own world, get paid for it, and don't have to
bother with anyone else. A professional fan, if you want to call
him one.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, they don't have to buy new clothes every season.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, probably the worst thing you can do to a bona fide
sportswriter is take their shirts to the cleaners and have them
pressed. Which makes us wonder why anyone would want to marry one.
</P>
<P>
   While the athletes they cover admit to giving it 110 percent on
the field, the sportswriters' divorce rate has to be in the same
percentile. Some make it, and God bless 'em. But those of us who've
made multiple trips to the license bureau only to have it later
revoked definitely make up for that.
</P>
<P>
   And we know who we are.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's Dan Lebatard, a 31-year-old sports columnist for
the Miami Herald, telling People Magazine that he's looking for a
gal who's good around kids, makes him laugh and isn't afraid of
getting soaked (since he enjoys river rafting). His ideal date is
``somewhere quiet.'' And he admits, ``I've never been in love.''
</P>
<P>
   This, friends, is today's sportswriter. More human. More aware
of others. More weight conscious. More domestic.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, no morons.
</P>
<P>
   So ends the Madison era, the character with character flaws,
sportswriters so comfortable with their career choice they can put
on whatever smelly clothes they so desire without the fear of
offending anyone, since they were wearing the same thing. And make
generally lousy money, offset by the fact ... well, at least
everyone else was in the same stinky boat.
</P>
<P>
   So, apparently, begins the Lebatard legacy - Gen X-tra
sensitive, where we care how we look to other people, maybe some
even hoping that a TV network picks up on their witty prose and
considers them camera-friendly enough to put on the air. Oh, right,
and give them more money.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a real sportswriter to do? Maybe it's like when Payne
Stewart used to wear the knickers when he played golf. There's got
to be a way to mesh the two - retain the charm of the job but move
into the 21st century without being displaced.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, how much does a good haircut go for these days?
</P>
<P>
   Getting it straight: NBC's coverage Thursday of the Williams
sisters' semifinals eventually aired in Los Angeles from 1 to 5
p.m. - two hours after the time block started. Not that it helps
for anyone who set their VCR or tuned in at 10 a.m., when NBC had
been showing Wimbledon all week, for the match that actually took
place several hours earlier (the result of which was specifically
not given on the KNBC Channel 4 news at 11 a.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Who would have awaken at 7 a.m. to watch this unique match live?
Seems by the phone calls we got in the office Thursday morning,
many.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but you forget. This is NBC. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
--You gotta see ``You Gotta See This!'' a new weekly sports version
of ``American's Funniest Videos'' produced and aired on Fox Sports
Net every Saturday night at 11:30! This week's installment includes
rodeo star Tuff Hedeman getting thrown from a bull and breaking
every bone in his face! No, really! &QL; 
--Starting with its coverage of the Home Run Derby on Monday (5
p.m.), ESPN, with the help of Major League Baseball, starts
offering a Spanish-language simulcast that includes graphics,
commercials and player interviews in Spanish. It'll be up to cable
systems that can accomodate the extra feed to find a channel to
give viewers for this service. &QL; 
--Channel 13 sports reporter Kenny Sargent has started a weekly
motor sports talk show (7-8 p.m. Sunday) on 97.1 KLSX-FM. &QL; 
--Highlights from Jim Rome's Cleveland ``World Tour'' stop airs
Wednesday (8 p.m.) on Fox Sports Net. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
--Unbridled bootlicking on the part of Fox Sports Net's L.A.
Regional News crew during its first week on the job. Obviously, the
scriptwriters have been trying inject a lot of rah-rahism instead
of results into the otherwise nicely formatted show, but is that
really going to fly around here? Calling the Dodgers ``our guys''
every other sentence should be a parody of how a local sportscast
goes, not something to imitate. The anchors should be renamed
Illiad and Odyssey - both creations of Homer. &QL; 
--What a surprise - Sports Illustrated baseball writer Jeff
Pearlman has hung another player out to dry. Just as the
unnecessary John Rocker story he wrote back in December set off
fireworks, Pearlman's cover piece on Toronto's David Wells has been
called ``a total joke'' by the pitcher because of how it focuses on
his weight and not so much on his ability. &QL; 
--``Hi, this is !racepay!Bill Walton!off! for Casa de Cadillac
...''
</P>
</TEXT>
