<HEADER>
A4875 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-LONGITUDE-REVIEW-LADN     07-06 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONGITUDE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REAL CLASSIC, BY ANY MEASURE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use on or after July 9, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
While the airwaves and films are populated with plenty of
whodunnits, the most compelling mysteries are cerebral. These
stories, however, rarely make for compelling viewing.
</P>
<P>
   But if you can tear yourself away from the reality-based show du
jour, ``Longitude'' on A&AMP;E is a handsomely mounted and absorbing
!ital!true story of the man who, after a lifetime struggle, solved
one of the greatest mysteries in history, creating a clock that
allowed sailors to know their position at sea. And while
``Longitude'' is four hours (it will be repeated), it's well worth
the time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1707, after a maritime disaster caused by an incorrect
calculation of a fleet's position (``guess'' is more appropriate,
since navigators had no way of really knowing then, using dead
reckoning and an unreliable method of computing knots), the British
Parliament offered a sum of 20,000 pounds (about $5 mil &QL; 
lion today) to anyone who could solve the problem of finding
longitude at sea.
</P>
<P>
   More than saving lives was at stake, though. Any nation that
could find an accurate method of navigation could rule the economy
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Taking up the challenge in 1730 was a Yorkshire carpenter named
John Harrison (Michael Gambon), a man with no formal education and
who had never been out to sea. Harrison, though, already had
fashioned a wooden clock that kept better time than the one in the
Royal Observatory.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a mere carpenter trying to solve a problem that had
stumped the best minds of the land didn't sit well with the
academic establishment at the time. While he did receive
encouragement from Edmund Halley (yes, that Halley), the Astronomer
Royal (John Wood), another famous scientist, Sir Isaac Newton,
prejudiced the board against the problem being solved by a
mechanical method.
</P>
<P>
   So even when Harrison almost succeeds his first time out with a
test at sea with his first device, he's met with resistance.
Eventually, though, he receives enough backing to continue his
work. Harrison, however, knows there is a flaw in his design.
</P>
<P>
   What occurs then is a nearly 50-year quest by the clockmaker, in
which he has to overcome both naysayers and his own doubts. For a
man obsessed with time, Harrison's own time meant little too him.
All of this came at a personal cost, including watching his son,
William, who he wanted to win the prize for so he grow up a
gentleman, grow instead into a middle-aged man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Longitude'' takes one great liberty with Dava Sobel's
critically acclaimed book in order to give the filmed version more
of a more dramatic reading. Rupert Gould, who is a minor character
in her book, becomes something of a parallel story in this version.
Gould is a World War I British Naval officer who becomes obsessed
with restoring Harrison's four clocks, which have fallen in
disrepair in the cellar of the Royal Observatory. There he asks
Frank Dyson, the current Astronomer Royal (Alec McCowen), if he can
put the clocks back into working order. Dyson agrees, but there is
no money involved and Gould must do it in his spare time.
</P>
<P>
   With Gould's mental health in an already fragile state and with
his wife unable to understand, Gould's obsession, like Harrison's,
takes its toll.
</P>
<P>
   The more interesting story, though, is Harrison's, whose
obstacles, including facing more rigorous class distinctions and
just plain ignorance, are external, rather than Gould's, which take
the form of inner demons. Harrison's fears stem more from his fears
that someone would steal his plans and cheat him out of his reward.
They were entirely unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   The story of ``Longitude'' is not an easy one to tell. Taking
place over a 50-year period, as one might expect, characters come
and go. And some of the more esoteric aspects of the tale are
smoothed over. But like Harrison's quest, the show ultimately
triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   Gambon is superb as Harrison, and Oscar-winner Irons has made a
living playing vulnerable Englishmen who must keep a stiff upper
lip. The cast is peppered with marvelous actors such as Wood,
McCowan, Barbara Leigh-Hunt as Gould's mother and Frank Finlay as
Admiral Wager.
</P>
<P>
   But the most credit should go to writer-director Charles
Sturridge, who get this unwieldy undertaking on course, making
reality (that's what history is, after all) entertaining. &QL; 
_______ &QL; 
The show: ``Longitude.'' &QL; 
What: the story of the man who invented a timepiece that allowed a
ships's longitude to be determined accurately. &QL; 
The stars: Jeremy Irons, Michael Gambon, Ian Hart. &QL; 
Where: A&AMP;E &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. and midnight. Repeating July 13, 8 p.m.; July 15, 1
and 8 p.m., July 16, 3 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
