<SLUG> BC-PATIENT-RIGHTS-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENTS' BILL SET TO BECOME CAMPAIGN ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ With uncertainty growing as to whether Congress
will pass legislation to define patients' rights, President Clinton
traveled outside Washington on Thursday to set the stage for
turning the issue into political ammunition for the Democrats
during the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an obligation in Washington to pass a strong patients'
bill of rights,'' Clinton said to dozens of health professionals
and other supporters at the University of Missouri campus here. He
praised a version of the bill that passed the House last year with
the support of Democrats and some Republicans, but criticized one
enacted by the Republican majority in the Senate, which he said
might be worse than not passing any bill.
</P>
<P>
   A patients' bill of rights would, for the first time, set
federal standards for private health insurance, notably health
maintenance organizations and other forms of managed care. For
decades, insurance has been regulated by the states.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional battle over a bill is hovering in the twilight
between compromise and breakdown. While continuing negotiations,
both sides are also looking ahead to carry the battle into the fall
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warmly praised Missouri's Democratic governor, Mel
Carnahan, who is running for the U.S. Senate. Carnahan, who stood
at Clinton's side along with a phalanx of white-coated health
professionals, backed a patients' bill of rights that became state
law in 1997. He hopes to unseat Sen. John Ashcroft, the Republican
incumbent who has resolutely supported his party's leaders in
pressing for a more limited version.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said in a statement Thursday that he had always
supported ``a real patients' bill of rights.'' Regarding the
president's remarks, he said that ``people have a right to expect
leadership to fix problems, not to fix blame.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two primary differences between the parties. The House
version supported by Clinton would cover people in every health
plan in the nation, an estimated 161 million subscribers. The
Republican Senate version would apply to those not already covered
by state laws, an estimated 56 million people.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the House version would make it easier for patients
to sue their HMOs and employers than the Senate bill would.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the assistant majority leader, has
argued that legislation making it easier to sue employers would
only discourage them from offering health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been my goal to send an enforceable, responsible
patients' bill of rights to the president this year,'' Nickles said
in a statement Thursday. ``But what I will not do is to pass a bill
that would cause employers to drop health insurance, dramatically
increase costs and force millions of Americans into the ranks of
the uninsured.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of which version of a patients' bill of rights is
preferable is likely to figure in several races in the fall. It has
already become an issue in Hillary Rodham Clinton's U.S. Senate
race in New York against Rep. Rick A. Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio voted against the bipartisan House version last year.
Lazio's spokesman said that the congressman ``has consistently
supported the Republican version, which is a patients' bill of
rights rather than a lawyer's right to bill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
