<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATA_STORAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IBM, Compaq jointly to offer data storage products
 &HT;    By John Pletz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - IBM Corp. and Compaq Corp. are joining forces in
an assault on the lucrative and growing market for Internet data
storage that many see as crucial for computer companies.
</P>
<P>
   IBM and Compaq will invest a combined $1 billion in a
partnership in which each company will cross-sell a limited amount
of the other's products rebadged under their own names.
</P>
<P>
   IBM brings the Shark, its high-end, mainframe storage product
line, while Compaq will chip in with StorageWorks, a Windows NT
offering. Compaq also will sell some systems-management software
made by Austin-based IBM subsidiary Tivoli Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Together, IBM and Compaq believe they can offer a top-to-bottom
package of products ranging from the low-end NT platform to the
proprietary, high-end Unix and mainframe platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq and IBM will compete fiercely on the software side of
things,'' said John McArthur, vice president of storage research at
research firm International Data Corp. ``Both think they've got
larger total market by making the software platform independent.''
</P>
<P>
   IDC projects that the market for storage products will be worth
$53 billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a ton of data out there on the Internet that has to be
stored,'' said Amir Ahari an analyst with U.S. Bancorp Piper
Jaffray in Menlo Park, Calif. ``All the catalogs, data collected
for purchases _ that's all storage. And that's where the growth is.
Storage is going to be the oxygen to companies.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM and Compaq will work together to make sure their products
are compatible, which is a key issue in storage. Companies
operating various systems want to be able to access data created or
stored on different platforms.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer Corp. made its only acquisition last fall, buying
ConvergeNet, to solve that same problem. Dell expects to begin
selling the ConvergeNet product in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   IBM and others are pushing for an open standard that allows
different platforms to work together. It's a further assault on
Massachusetts-based EMC Corp., the leader in storage products and
IBM's chief rival, which is pushing a proprietary solution with its
own hardware standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM is trying to build momentum, saying there's something else
besides EMC,'' Ahari said. ``IBM has an incentive to get out there
and build momentum for their products. It's huge (for Tivoli)
because Compaq has a huge installed base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq is second to none in the NT storage space, but Compaq
really needs to get the credibility to get into data centers.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Capellas, Compaq's chief executive, said he expects to
begin seeing ``significant'' revenue by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think IBM sees it that no matter what happens, they're going
to make money,'' Ahari said.
</P>
<P>
   It is the latest effort by IBM to partner with competitors. IBM
did its first partnership deal in March 1999 with Dell to license
technology from Big Blue. IBM later agreed to provide services to
Dell customers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it made technology deals with Dell, Cisco Systems,
EMC and others valued at $30 billion over five to seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago it was an idea that bordered on heresy, to open
the doors to our technology to our competitors,'' IBM spokesman
Randy Thompson said. ``The mission is to get IBM technology into
the marketplace as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact John Pletz at jpletz(at)statesman.com or
445-3601.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
