<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEN-TRIALS-AUSTIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tension at the fencing trials
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You won't need a knife, sabre, foil or epee to
cut the tension at the United States Olympic Fencing Trials in
Austin this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fencing is different from most other sports. We like to have
consistency. We have a series of Olympic trials,'' said Felicia
Zimmermann.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmermann and her younger sister Iris _ the Venus and Serena
Williams of fencing _ won't be in any cutthroat competition at the
convention center to make the Olympic squad. They, along with five
other fencers, already compose the U.S. Olympic team. The
Zimmermanns have done very well in international competitions, and
because U.S. fencers have scored better there, the importance of
the nationals for picking a team has lessened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still the nationals. I'd like to win,'' Felicia
Zimmermann said. ``But I just want to go in and have some fun. I'm
excited. I love Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   Iris, 19, and Felicia, 24, both fence in foil competition, which
is scheduled to start at 1 p.m. today. Also on the three-woman foil
team is Ann Marsh. According to Cindy Bent, a spokeswoman for the
United States Fencing Association, Erinn Smart already has enough
points to secure the alternate spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single one of us is strong. There's not one that's a
weak link. It's hard for anyone to figure us out, as we all have
different styles,'' Iris said.
</P>
<P>
   Women's foil, where the U.S. has a shot at winning a rare medal,
is the only U.S. fencing team that qualified for the Olympics.
Individuals that have earned a trip to Sydney to compete along with
the Zimmermann sisters are Keeth Smart and Ahki Spencer-El in men's
sabre, Cliff Bayer in men's foil, Arlene Stevens in women's epee
and Tamir Bloom in men's epee.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer is considered a medal threat, as is Iris Zimmermann. Last
year Iris became the first U.S. woman to capture a medal at the
World Championships when she tied for a bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Iris, however, will be sitting out the competition in Austin.
She's had knee problems for the past two years and is using this
time to get some rest and do some rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to watch my sister fence and cheer her on,'' Iris said.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters from upstate New York both attend Stanford but took
the year off to concentrate on the Olympics. Felicia is a little
more familiar with the Austin area. When the nationals were here
two years ago she got out to Antone's and some other spots. She
currently dates Sean McClain, a fencer from Round Rock who now
lives in the Rochester, N.Y., area.
</P>
<P>
   Felicia competed in the 1996 Olympics and is coming off an
encouraging finish in a World Cup event in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of my best results. It felt really good fencing,''
Felicia said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Iris, ``It will be really strange not to fence at
nationals, but I want to be there when they announce the Olympic
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition in the National Fencing Championships will conclude
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact John Maher at jmaher(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
