<HEADER>
A4904 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SCHOOLS-PAINT-HNS &LR;      07-06 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-PAINT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON SCHOOLS SUE MAKERS OF LEAD PAINT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL MURPHY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the cost of removing or treating lead paint in their
schools expected to cost millions, two Houston school districts are
suing the major companies that made lead paint.
</P>
<P>
   The suits, filed separately last week, are the first brought by
school districts nationwide, but are similar to pending ones by the
city of St. Louis, the state of Rhode Island and a California
county.
</P>
<P>
   The paint makers have defeated all such suits in the past. A
victory here or elsewhere could set a precedent and encourage other
cities and school districts to sue, lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   The suits hope to mimic the success of those against tobacco
makers in the past few years and asbestos makers in the late 1980s
and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Houston and Spring Branch school districts argue
that the companies are responsible for the lead paint even if it
was put on walls 30 or 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have applied somebody's product and it has to be removed
at exorbitant cost, we don't feel the taxpayers should have to pay
for the removal,'' Spring Branch Superintendent Hal Guthrie said.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the paint makers say they stopped putting lead in
interior paints in the 1950s and shouldn't be held responsible for
lead paint applied long before it was known to be unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've disseminated information and worked with public health
officials to make changes,'' said Alan Wheat, spokesman for a
number of companies being sued.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hardy, a lawyer for one of the companies, NL Industries,
said, ``I don't think manufacturers should be responsible for
products forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston suits are against DuPont, Glidden, Sherwin-Williams,
Atlantic Richfield, the Lead Industries Association, a trade group,
and several other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers reduced the lead in interior paints to under 1
percent in 1955, but continued to make lead paint for exteriors
until 1978, when the federal government banned it.
</P>
<P>
   The local suits contend that the manufacturers knew lead paint
was dangerous, especially to children, long before 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lead-paint industry knew as early as the 1900s that this
product could cause severe harm to people,'' the suits say. ``By
the 1930s and 1940s, the industry was fully aware of the harm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rhode Island suit filed last fall said industry memos show
that paint makers knew of lead paint's dangers in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   The districts are using the same law firms, Bracewell &AMP;
Patterson and Fleming &AMP; Associates, to bring virtually identical
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat, a former Missouri congressman, said paint makers helped
pay for studies in the 1940s and 1950s at Johns Hopkins and Harvard
universities that revealed lead paint's dangers and helped make the
findings known.
</P>
<P>
   Lead exposure can cause permanent brain, nervous system and
kidney damage in children, especially those under 4.
</P>
<P>
   Cases of lead poisoning have dropped dramatically since lead
paint was banned in 1978, but lead poisoning remains a national
problem.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, more than 7,400 children under age 7 had high lead
levels out of 53,000 screened since 1992, said Kathy Barton,
spokesman for the city Health and Human Services Department. The
children screened were mostly from inner-city neighborhoods where
most of the homes were built before 1960.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA now views lead paint removal or treatment as a priority,
said Ronald Scott, a lawyer representing the Houston and Spring
Branch districts.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie said Spring Branch sued because it is concerned that the
EPA will order districts to undertake expensive lead treatment
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty of our 37 campuses were built before 1980,'' Guthrie
said. ``We're talking about millions (of dollars).''
</P>
<P>
   In HISD, 213 out of 300 schools were built before 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The local suits are seeking money only to treat lead in schools.
St. Louis, Rhode Island and Santa Clara County in the San Jose,
Calif.,area are looking to recover money spent on treating lead
poisoning victims.
</P>
<P>
   Those costs include medical treatment and special ed classes and
lead treatment programs in homes.
</P>
<P>
   Suits against paint makers never have been successful.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia filed a class action suit on behalf of all cities
in the early 1990s, but it was dismissed because the statute of
limitations in Pennsylvania had long passed, said Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   Other suits have been been dismissed because the plaintiffs
couldn't identify which companies sold the paint needing removal.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia and other plaintiffs based their cases on a theory
called market-share liability, Hardy said.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that a huge paint maker should be found liable for
a certain percentage of damages based on past share of the lead
paint market. However, Hardy says, courts in many states have
rejected the theory because it could penalize companies not liable
for a particular problem.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, lawyer for the Houston and Spring Branch districts, said
it is unlikely he will bring a market-share case.
</P>
<P>
   He also said there is no statute of limitations on negligence
suits by schools and other government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Houston and Spring Branch officials said the suits don't mean
children in their school districts are at risk of getting lead
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Most lead paint has been painted over. It becomes a health
hazard only when a non-lead coat wears away, and lead paint falls
in chips or dust form, said the city's Barton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF FILE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
