u f BC-POTTER-COX     07-06 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FedEx delivering new Potter book tomorrow
 &HT;    By Dave Hirschman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FedEx Corp. is conjuring supernatural forces in its battle with
United Parcel Service for residential deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   The Memphis-based transportation company will deliver 250,000
copies Saturday of ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' the
fourth in a wildly popular series by J.K. Rowling about the
adventures of a magical orphan.
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile shipments are designed to showcase FedEx Home
Delivery _ a new service that FedEx is expanding to cover virtually
all U.S. households within 20 months.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, FedEx picked up thousands of Harry Potter books
from an Amazon.com warehouse in Henry County and began transporting
them to eager readers around the country. More than 300,000 have
been ordered via the Web site, and the publisher has printed 5.3
million so far.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an Amazon.com promotion, the first 250,000 buyers at
the site got free FedEx Saturday delivery. The two companies aren't
disclosing the financial terms of their deal, but for FedEx the
payoff is being associated with the Harry Potter craze.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project underscores our ability to handle a large number
of residential shipments with military precision,'' said Rodger
Marticke, executive vice president at FedEx Ground, a subsidiary
that includes the Home Delivery unit. ``It also draws attention to
the fact we deliver on Saturdays as a normal course of business.''
</P>
<P>
   FedEx Home Delivery will do about 50,000 book deliveries. FedEx
Express, the company's core next-morning delivery service, will
deliver 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at UPS, which handles more than 13 million packages
daily, said they could have accommodated the one-day surge in Harry
Potter shipments but didn't seek the contract because they saw no
reason to offer steep, promotional discounts.
</P>
<P>
   UPS is the dominant delivery firm for the publishing industry,
and company spokeswoman Susan Rosenberg said adolescent sorcerer
Harry Potter won't dislodge it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the primary shipper for Amazon, and we're the market
leader for shipping on behalf of the dot-com companies,'' Rosenberg
said. ``Amazon asked us if we were interested (in the Potter
promotion), and we decided it was something we didn't want to
pursue.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
