</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS takes on role of credit intermediary
 &HT;    By Dave Hirschman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to expand small package shipments generated online,
United Parcel Service's financial arm has begun offering credit
cards and lines of credit to businesses that buy products on
AmericasMart.com, the Atlanta-based companies announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bernabucci, president of UPS Capital Corp., said the
agreement is the first of many that will attempt to bridge the
online gaps between manufacturers, wholesalers and retailers. UPS
will pay manufacturers and wholesalers for their products as soon
as they are ordered, deliver them to retailers and collect
payments.
</P>
<P>
   The system is designed to eliminate the need for sellers to
extend credit or send packages C.O.D. It is not intended for
individual consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're investigating a number of opportunities in
business-to-business cards,'' Bernabucci said. ``We're looking at
offering similar programs for a variety of distinct networks.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS officials say their new product benefits Internet buyers and
sellers alike. Sellers will collect payments right away and won't
owe fees to credit card companies. Buyers will get reduced interest
rates and discounts on future purchases.
</P>
<P>
   UPS says it can afford to reduce interest rates and eliminate
fees because it already has relationships with more than 80 percent
of AmericasMart.com's clients. Also, each transaction creates
additional shipments for UPS' core transportation business.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Farrugia, chief executive at AmericasMart.com, said the
UPS agreement will make it easier for large and small companies to
close deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of manufacturers will only do business with buyers
that have established lines of credit,'' he said. ``Now, small
businesses will have access to those lines of credit through UPS.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrugia expects UPS credit cards to increase the volume of
business on AmericasMart.com, but he isn't sure how much. The
company, owned by AMC Inc., which is the sponsor of AmericasMart
Atlanta and its 17 annual trade shows, began trading on its Web
site Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
