<DOCNO> NYT20000706.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     07-06 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in
New York City. Running times and ratings of films are in
parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `THE ADVENTURES OF ROCKY AND BULLWINKLE,' starring Rene Russo,
Jason Alexander and Robert De Niro, with the voices of June Foray
and Keith Scott. Directed by Des McAnuff (PG, 88 minutes). Fans of
Jay Ward's old ``Rocky and Bullwinkle'' television show will enjoy
the first 10 minutes or so of this new movie, which employs the
show's characteristically flat animation and goofy humor to update
the biographies of the beloved flying squirrel, his antlered
sidekick and their enemies Boris, Natasha and Fearless Leader. But
the antic whimsy of the cartoon original is betrayed as the film
turns into a clunky, muddled stew of special effects, lame jokes
and labored attempts at satire. Rocky, Bullwinkle and a young FBI
agent save the world from Fearless Leader (De Niro), but who will
save it from misguided, overpriced and overhyped movies? (A.O.
Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `BUTTERFLY,' starring Fernando Fernan Gomez and Manuel Lozano.
Directed by Jose Luis Cuerda (R, 96 minutes). This gentle,
devastating new film, based on short stories by the Spanish writer
Manuel Rivas, tells the story of Moncho (Lozano), a sensitive young
boy coming of age in the months before the outbreak of the Spanish
Civil War. The movie touches on the usual excitements and mysteries
of childhood, but Moncho's relationship with his teacher, the
proudly Republican Don Gregorio, beautifully played by Fernan
Gomez, gives the story an unusual degree of pathos and political
complexity (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `CHICKEN RUN,' with the voices of Mel Gibson, Miranda Richardson
and Julia Sawalha. Directed by Peter Lord and Nick Park (G, 86
minutes). The first full-length feature from Aardman Animation is
immensely satisfying, a divinely relaxed and confident film that
credits youngsters' interest in a cartoon more substantial than the
standard bland musical. The movie employs modeled latex figures to
tell the story of a group of chickens desperate to escape from a
chicken farm before they are turned into pies. Nick Park, who also
directed the fabulous Wallace and Gromit shorts, transfers all of
the deftness and imagination of his shorter films into an artful
big-screen realization. And this briskly paced epic uses Lord's
continuing satirical take on British modesty and balmy superiority.
``Chicken Run'' parodies cultural touchstones from ``Stalag 17'' to
``Star Trek'' to the loose-cannon heroics of Gibson, the voice of
Rocky, the matinee-idol flying rooster who is asked to teach the
hens to fly. Finally, it shows that the hens can save themselves
through the pluck of Ginger (Sawalha) and doesn't make a big deal
of this (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `DINOSAUR,' with the voices of D.B. Sweeney, Alfre Woodard and
Ossie Davis. Directed by Ralph Zondag and Eric Leighton (PG, 90
minutes). Reputedly the most expensive animated feature ever made,
Disney's showcase of computer animation technology begins with a
breathtaking sequence, a visual and sonic extravaganza that the
rest of the movie never quite lives up to. The story, of a young
dinosaur raised by lemurs who must lead a herd of his fellow
reptiles to safety after an asteroid strikes the earth, is cobbled
from other Disney plots. But the effects _ the dinosaur's movements
and their nearly seamless insertion into real locations _ will
impress skeptical grown-ups. (The movie reportedly cost about $200
million.) Despite some potentially upsetting scenes of carnivorous
mayhem, the film will delight children (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `GETTING TO KNOW YOU,' starring Bebe Neuwirth, Heather Matarazzo
and Mark Weston. Directed by Lisanne Skyler (unrated, 91 minutes).
Adapting material by Joyce Carol Oates, Skyler conjures an alluring
tale of mistrust and hope by getting to the themes of
self-deception and betrayal that Oates characters often weave for
themselves. Stranded at a bus station, Judith (Matarazzo) and Jimmy
(Weston) spin tales about the people they see there and reveal
things about each other through their extemporaneous fictions.
Skyler gets standout performances, and her patience and skill are
revealed in small, satisfying ways throughout the film (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `GLADIATOR,' starring Russell Crowe, Joaquin Phoenix, Connie
Nielsen, Richard Harris and Oliver Reed. Directed by Ridley Scott
(R, 150 minutes). This movie is the answer to a question no one
bothered to ask: What would happen if someone decided to film the
imminent extreme football league as if it were a Chanel commercial?
Scott subjects action-packed bouts of mayhem and decapitation in
the Roman Colosseum to his glossy, inhuman directing style; it is
admirable but repellent. As the noble Roman general who ends up
fighting for his life, Crowe gives a performance with ball-of-fire
intensity suffused with a movie star's impatience. He holds the
movie together, such as it is (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `GONE IN 60 SECONDS,' starring Nicolas Cage, Giovanni Ribisi,
Angelina Jolie and Robert Duvall. Directed by Dominic Sena (PG-13,
119 minutes). A remake of a movie so insubstantial that its title
seems to refer to the length of time it would linger in memory.
Cage, who has gone prematurely blond, is the world's best car
thief, who is dragged out of his apparently lucrative go-cart
business and returns to auto theft to save the life of his brother
(Ribisi). With a magnetic cast of crooks and cops, it's mindless
hot-rodding entertainment for those who love car chases with
vintage autos, a film so glossy and impersonal that you will
sympathize more with the cars than the people (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `GROOVE,' starring Hamish Linklater, Lola Glaudini, Mackenzie
Firgens and Steve Van Wormer. Directed by Greg Harrison (R, 86
minutes). If you're nostalgic for chasing down a rave gig across
the city and arriving to find a pair of 16-year-olds discussing the
merits of drum and bass versus jungle, then this mostly knowing and
funny comedy is just the film for you. Even if you're not, its
seductive lack of pretension will win you over. ``Groove'' is a
comedy of moments, tracking a crowd through the ups and downs of
one night of pleasure at a rave. Harrison and his team do not try
to pretend that raves are anything new or dangerous. Rather,
they're an entrenched circuit with specific tribal complications,
and this genial picture captures them (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `ME, MYSELF AND IRENE,' starring Jim Carrey and Renee Zellweger.
Directed by Bobby Farrelly and Peter Farrelly (R, 100 minutes). If
``There's Something About Mary'' offended you with its callous
mockery of hair and pet care and its whimsical views of stalking
and serial killing, then this latest festival of vulgarity from the
Farrelly brothers will make you miserable. But ``Me, Myself and
Irene'' shares with their earlier movies a kind of dopey, boyish
sincerity and a good-natured sympathy for the underdog that may
prove capable of winning over even the dourest spirits. Carrey, in
one _ or is it two? _ of his most charming and repellent
performances, plays a Rhode Island state trooper with a split
personality and a giant crush on Irene, played with winning moxie
and plausible bewilderment by Zellweger (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `THE PATRIOT,' starring Mel Gibson. Directed by Roland Emmerich
(R, 158 minutes). A grueling Revolutionary War epic that, at more
than two and a half hours, seems to take place in real time. The
brutality and sentimentality are effective, though the film will
leave you feeling used as you exit the theater. This sort-of
prequel to Emmerich's ``Independence Day'' stars Gibson as a gentle
farmer who leads the Colonies in wresting freedom from the Brits,
using counterintuitive methods alarmingly similar to terrorism. His
anguished masculinity is brandished like a musket. The film's chief
asset is his relationship with the young actors playing his
children; it draws on the actor's real-life feeling about his own
large brood, and his work with them is stirring (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `THE PERFECT STORM,' starring George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg and
Diane Lane. Directed by Wolfgang Petersen (PG-13, 150 minutes.)
Impressive but monotonously redundant special effects smother the
human drama in this true story (adapted from Sebastian Junger's
best-selling book) of a group of swordfishermen battling ``the
storm of the century'' off Massachusetts in 1991. Clooney is the
ship's glowering, enigmatic captain, and Wahlberg and Lane are the
appealing lovebirds who lend the movie its stingy quotient of
warmth. The early scenes, which paint a romantic portrait of the
fisherman's life in Gloucester, Mass., promise a great deal, but
the movie becomes waterlogged once it leaves shore (Stephen
Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `PRAISE,' starring Peter Fenton and Sacha Horler. Directed by
John Curran (unrated, 98 minutes). A stunner about a doomed
relationship that's like Tennessee Williams with the ragged
heedlessness of post punk. Gordon (Fenton) is the epitome of
slacker, a slender do-nothing whose passivity is part of his wasted
charm. He attracts the sexually voracious Cynthia (Horler), whose
soft body is wracked with eczema. Though the movie feels aimless,
Curran lets the explicit detail spell out the compulsiveness of the
characters and uses jolts of humor to keep the squalor from lapsing
into unrelieved unpleasantness. Horler's tender and fearless
performance is just one of the elements that wiil stick with you
(Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `SHAFT,' starring Samuel L. Jackson, Vanessa Williams, Jeffrey
Wright, Christian Bale, Toni Collette and Richard Roundtree. A
sequel/remake to the 1971 semi-classic, starring the always
dependable Jackson. He's the nephew of the original Shaft
(Roundtree, who appears briefly), and this time, Shaft is a cop. He
leaves the force to track down a racist WASP murderer (Bale), who
joins forces with a drug dealer (the flamboyant and skillful
Wright) to eliminate the hero. This may be the least politically
correct movie in some time, and though it tries to convert
archetype into stereotype, it doesn't succeed. Watching the two
villains squabble for center stage is like watching Luciano
Pavarotti and Placido Domingo in a death match for the mike. But
Jackson comes out on top of this emptily entertaining hodgepodge of
retro and modern cliches (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `SUNSHINE,' starring Ralph Fiennes, Rachel Weisz, Jennifer Ehle,
Rosemary Harris and James Frian. Directed by Istvan Szabo (R, 180
minutes). In Szabo's tale of 20th-century Hungarian history,
Fiennes plays three members of a wealthy Jewish Budapest family _
grandfather, father and son _ who endure the corruption of the
Austro-Hungarian empire, the viciousness of fascism and the
brutality of communism. Fiennes' performances, and those of Ehle
and Harris (playing the same character at different stages of life)
help save the film from melodramatic excess. Even though much of
the story is crudely told, ``Sunshine'' is a serious, humane and
thought-provoking attempt to make sense of complicated and painful
historical experiences (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `TRIXIE,' starring Emily Watson and Nick Nolte. Directed by Alan
Rudolph (R, 117 minutes). In the self-billed ``screwball film
noir,'' Watson plays an undercover detective at a lakeside casino
investigating the murder of a third-rate lounge singer. Nolte is
the alcoholic, womanizing politician she suspects of the murder.
The director is wonderful with actors, and the fine supporting
cast, which includes Lesley Ann Warren, Will Patton and Nathan
Lane, fills in the movie's sleazy atmosphere. But the story neither
connects its narrative dots nor generates suspense, and the humor
(the title character is given to silly malapropisms) falls flat
(Holden).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
