<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MEXICO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL _ Be open to new Mexican leader's ideas
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vicente Fox's smashing election victory is splendid news for
Mexico politically, transfering the reins of government peacefully
there after 71 years of one-party domination. His presidency, which
won't start until December, could also be the start of something
good for Mexicans economically, with repercussions that could be
detectable in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of Fox's center-right agenda is raising living
standards for Mexico's 100 million people, 30 million of whom live
in extreme poverty. Fox has set ambitious goals for raising
education standards and for creating better-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But that will take time and resources, a crucial part of which
he hopes to secure by making Mexico more attractive to investors
from the United States, Canada and elsewhere. Strong selling points
in that effort will be his promised crackdown on corruption and his
commitment to build on the North American Free Trade Agreement,
which has increased trade between the United States and Mexico from
$80 billion to $200 billion in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the foreseeable future, many Mexicans will have to
look northward for work and for wages to sustain their families. In
yet-to-be-scheduled meetings with President Clinton and the two
major candidates to succeed him, George W. Bush and Al Gore, Fox is
sure to ask for a more generous, better regulated U.S. approach to
migrant labor, and they should hear him out.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond considering another amnesty for undocumented Mexicans
living above the border, U.S. officials should give serious thought
to raising the limit on permanent working permits to Mexicans, now
running at 65,000 a year, and negotiating broader guest-worker
agreements, both seasonal and sectoral.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of more systemized procedures ought to work both
ways. Employers should get a surer supply of labor at predictable
costs. Migrant workers are certain to prefer traveling northward
openly and safely for jobs of pre-set durations and wages to the
high-risk quests for work they undertake now.
</P>
<P>
   And how does Georgia fit in all this? A host of industries in
our full-employment state would have broken down without the influx
of Mexican and other Latino workers over the last 15 years. The
sooner the undocumented in that population have legal working
papers and can be here without fear of exposure or exploitation,
the better for all concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
