<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SISTERS FACE THE MOMENT OF TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TEN-WIMBLEDON, TEN-WIMBLEDON-NOTES) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Venus Williams was drenched with sweat. Her
signature braids, her one-piece tennis outfit, all dripping with
the effort of a grueling semifinal victory.
</P>
<P>
   She was walking off Center Court at the All England Club, where
she had achieved the greatest triumph of her career: She had
reached the women's championship round at Wimbledon, taken a huge
step closer to fulfilling a dream and the promise of an intriguing
career. She had came one step closer to winning her first Grand
Slam singles title at tennis' most hallowed address.
</P>
<P>
   There was one problem. Her success had come at the expense of
the person she loved more than anyone else in the world: she had
just beaten her little sister Serena, 6-2, 7-6 (3).
</P>
<P>
   When the match ended on a Serena double fault, the sisters both
looked at each other, frozen. They did not know how to react _
Serena to her sister's elation, Venus to her sister's
disappointment. So they both looked close to tears. There was no
Venus celebration, no fists pumped in the air. That was the most
distressing part of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Part of a fan's joy is sharing the triumph of the victor. Had
you tuned in after the final point and went merely by facial
expressions, you would have thought this was the first match in
history in which both players lost.
</P>
<P>
   For as long as I've watched the Williams sisters, it wasn't
until this moment I realized how close they really were.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to the semifinal, the
sister-versus-sister matchup had been hyped for good reason: It was
the first time two sisters had faced each other this deep into a
Grand Slam draw for more than 100 years. The fact that they were
soul sisters added spice.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the buildup, this match wasn't pretty. Intriguing,
yes. Riveting, yes. But far too intense to be called fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   For everybody who has a sister or a brother, this match may have
hit a nerve. It contained all of the elements of a sibling rivalry:
competition, empathy, envy and guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Zina Garrison, who reached the finals at Wimbledon a decade ago,
knew exactly what was taking place. She was the last
African-American woman to reach a Grand Slam final prior to the
Williams sisters, but before this match was even half over, you
knew this was not about pioneering; it was about family.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison, a mentor to Serena, said the younger sister had been
in awe of the older sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what _ win, lose or draw _ you're going to be the
little sister,'' she said. ``I know from being the youngest, no
matter what I accomplish, or what I do, my big sisters felt that
they could dominate me. It is a big factor.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that that was only part of what unfolded here. ``Today
Venus basically showed that she really wants this tournament,''
said Garrison, who attended the match. ``No matter who she played
today she would have won.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Venus said that during changeovers, she found herself
thinking about her sister. ``I'm sitting over there and I'm
thinking, `Does Serena have enough sports drink?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always taken care of Serena,'' she said. ``That's the way
it's always been. I'm the one doing the driving late at night when
we came home from school. I was always driving with her asleep. I'm
the big sister and that's the way it will always be.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus turned 20 last month; Serena will be 19 in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's really bitter,'' Venus said of winning. ``But
someone had to move on. It was either going to be me or Serena.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams said he tried to comfort his youngest child. He
said he told Serena: ``Just think of how many people would love to
be in your position today: you're on Center Court in the most
famous stadium in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't see the match, choosing to stay away. Yet he still
felt the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard she had tears in her eyes, I felt even sadder,''
he said of Serena. ``I almost had tears in my eyes for my baby.
It's been a tough day overall.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the sisters keep playing these stressful matches? Will the
sister-to-sister mathchups lose some of the edge? ``I think it will
become less spectacular,'' Venus said. ``Most of all, Serena and I
have to promise ourselves to start playing solid tennis every time
so that we can be No. 1 and No. 2, then meet in the finals. It will
be a natural thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And not to mention a relief. A victory should not be this
heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   Before they shook hands with the umpire, Venus put her arm
around her younger sister and whispered something. What she told
her sister framed the match, the day, the mood. Venus said: ``Let's
get out of here, Serena.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
