</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ECON-ART-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO VICTOR FACES CHOICES ON ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vicente Fox's 7-percentage-point margin of victory in Mexico's
presidential election has buoyed the spirits not just of Mexican
voters but of investors and business executives across North
America.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican peso strengthened immediately after the election,
the Mexican stock market rose to a three-month high before dropping
back a bit, and American investors generally were delighted _ not
necessarily because Fox won, but because the decisive way he won
kept Mexico calm and open for business. Many had feared turmoil
resulting from a very close election.
</P>
<P>
   But as people get used to the idea that Mexico's 71 years of
one-party rule are coming to an end, investors, analysts and
business leaders are beginning to ask just how Fox, a former
Coca-Cola executive, intends to handle his country's complex
economic issues. And there are questions whether, in the
interconnected global economy that he says he wants Mexico to
remain part of, he has much leeway at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``First there was this euphoria, then everybody was standing
around scratching their head,'' said John M. Bruton, executive vice
president of the American Chamber of Commerce in Mexico City.
``People of all classes voted for him because they think he can
change their situations. Now, managing expectations is going to be
Mr. Fox's greatest challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   So much of the campaign was focused on change for the sake of
change that other issues did not get much attention. There never
had been much distance between the economic platforms of the
principal candidates, and throughout the campaign Fox avoided
laying out a detailed program of economic reform. Instead, he
offered the standard campaign promises of increasing jobs,
promoting investment and producing economic growth that would help
the millions of Mexicans still living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has made it clear that he intends to stay the economic
course _ opening Mexico to the global economy and embracing free
market discipline _ set by previous administrations, but he has
made it equally clear that he is not happy with the way that many
Mexicans have been left behind.
</P>
<P>
   He supports an independent central bank, a free-floating
exchange rate and increased exports. He even said earlier this week
that the North American Free Trade Agreement should be amplified to
further integrate North America, perhaps with a common currency for
Mexico, the United States and Canada, ``20, 30 or 40 years from
now.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is facing many far more immediate issues, including the
millions of Mexicans who have never recovered the purchasing power
they had before the first of several end-of-administration crises
in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has a reputation as a pragmatist when it comes to business
and the economy. As governor of the small, central state of
Guanajuato, he initiated a program of providing micro loans for
very small businesses as a way of promoting entrepreneurship, a
program he intends to repeat on the national level. He has also
talked about copying Chile's program of providing tax relief for
companies that reinvest in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   One of Fox's first economic tasks will be to name an economic
cabinet that inspires investor confidence in a party that has never
run Mexico. He is said to be considering a treasury secretary who
might come from the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, known
as the PRI. One name being mentioned is Luis Tellez, the current
energy secretary and former chief of staff to President Ernesto
Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Fox must also prepare a federal budget that by law has to be
approved _ by a congress his party does not control _ within 15
days of his inauguration on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's chief economic adviser, Luis Ernesto Derbez, a former
World Bank official who is often mentioned as a possible Treasury
Secretary under Fox, told investors in New York on Thursday that
work had already started on that budget.
</P>
<P>
   Derbez said that Mexican political leaders had been asked to
outline budget priorities and that preliminary talks were under way
with the PRI, as well as the left leaning Party of the Democratic
Revolution, to gauge the limits of cooperation. Fox wants to name
his cabinet by the end of August and present a budget proposal by
the time the congress convenes on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts will be watching to see how Fox squares his campaign
promise to increase spending for education and social programs with
his pledge to decrease the current budget deficit by half. Derbez
said legislative initiatives would be introduced to close tax
loopholes. He also said the government would consider extending the
value added tax to medicine and food _ but only if there was a way
to soften the effect on the poor.
</P>
<P>
   John B. Chambers, deputy head of the sovereign ratings group at
Standard &AMP; Poor's, said his company's analysts would follow the
budget process and the fall legislative session in Mexico City for
clues to whether the major parties would cooperate or stumble into
gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Another rating company, Moody's Investors Services, upgraded
Mexico's debt to investment grade in early March, but Standard &AMP;
Poor's did not. This week, S&AMP;P affirmed its rating of one notch
below investment grade, with a positive outlook for an upgrade if
the new administration took care of some pending issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a question of how effective we think the Fox
administration is going to be in implementing the structural reform
agenda,'' Chambers said. ``Clues on that could come as early as the
fourth quarter of this year.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P says it will be watching for further strengthening of
Mexico's banking system and deregulation of the electricity and
petroleum sectors. The resignation of the company's chief Mexico
analyst last week will not affect the timing of any decision on a
ratings upgrade, Chambers said.
</P>
<P>
   The last three Mexican administrations ended with currency
devaluations and economic turmoil. Fears of another crisis
diminished with the strength of Fox's victory, and the continuing
strength of Mexico's economy. Jonathan E. Heath, a Mexican
economist who wrote a book on the causes of the
end-of-administration crises, believes most of the factors that
caused those earlier meltdowns _ a fixed exchange rate and an
oversized current accounts deficit, for example _ have been
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still the slim possibility of a shock that would be
caused by an assassination attempt on Fox,'' Heath said, ``but
barring something weird like that, the chances of another crisis
are very slim.`
</P>
<P>
   Rather than a meltdown, some investors are worried that the
post-election ecstasy could actually make Mexico's economy overheat
just as the U.S. economy begins to show signs of slowing down. The
first two days after the election, the Mexican stock market jumped
8.2 percent, but profit taking wiped away some of that gain,
leaving the market up 5.1 percent since the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumption, capital inflows, domestic investment, foreign
direct investment, all are increasing because of this injection of
confidence,'' said Jorge O. Mariscal, chief Latin American
investment strategist for Goldman Sachs. ``The thing to do now is
slow down the Mexican economy using fiscal and monetary means. Fox
needs to address that in the transition.''
</P>
<P>
   For him, Mariscal said, one incident best described the current
mood of excitement and uncertainty in Mexico. Just before the
election, a manufacturer in Mexico City who supported Fox loaded
barrels of fragrances on a pickup truck and drove around the city's
main highway. He wanted voters to know that the possibility of
change was so real they could smell it.
</P>
<P>
   But something went wrong: A barrel spilled onto the roadway, and
there was a multicar pileup.
</P>
<P>
   `Mexico,'' Mariscal said, ``still presents tremendous
challenges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
