A4914 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-DRUGSCOST-COX     07-06 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGSCOST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Congressman hopes to see dogfight over drug costs
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - National debate over rising prescription drugs
costs has the potential to become a real dogfight. At least an
Austin congressman hopes to make it one.
</P>
<P>
   Certain popular prescriptions cost far more for humans than for
animals, Democrat Lloyd Doggett said at a news conference Thursday
at the Humane Society-SPCA of Austin. Congress, he said, must help
make prescriptions drugs affordable to society's most vulnerable
members _ seniors on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogs, cats, horses, cattle get treated far better with
reference to the price of prescription drugs than do our seniors,''
Doggett said to a cacophony of barks and meows. ``If you don't have
prescription coverage as a senior, you're better off if you've got
four legs and a tail.''
</P>
<P>
   Doggett said that while uninsured children and families also pay
more for certain drugs he is focusing on Medicare recipients, who
generally do not receive drug coverage. Medicare is an issue in
Congress, and the elderly take more prescription drugs than the
young, he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 percent of those on Medicare, the federal health care
insurance program for people 65 and older and the disabled, lack
dependable private prescription drug coverage, Doggett's office
said.
</P>
<P>
   Drug manufacturers that seem to be charging what the market will
bear, not pharmacies, are at fault, Doggett said.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of pharmaceutical companies could not be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Doggett's office and staff to the Committee on Government Reform
surveyed pharmacies and Internet veterinary pharmacies to compare
drug costs. In Travis County, Doggett's staff found that a month's
supply of Lodine, a drug used to treat arthritis in humans and
dogs, cost $108.90 for humans and $37.80 for dogs, a 188 percent
difference.
</P>
<P>
   On average, Travis County seniors paid 113 percent more for five
common drugs that animals also use, Doggett's office found.
</P>
<P>
   Public Citizen, a consumer organization created by activist
Ralph Nader, now a presidential candidate, released a report
Thursday that said the prescription medicine industry is continuing
to fight Medicare drug coverage by stepping up contributions to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Doggett received $6,668 from drug industry political action
committees since 1993, a small amount in comparison to U.S. Rep.
Joe Barton, R-Texas, who was No. 1 among the Texas delegation with
$88,752 in donations, according to the Public citizen report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
