 PERSONALS: The Fairest Handbag of Them All 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The handbags of famous women _ but alas, not the queen _ are being
auctioned on eBay by Breast Cancer Care, a British cancer-support
charity. Among the goods and prices as of Thursday, July 6, with
six days of the auction left:
</P>
<P>
   A tiger-print purse donated by  &UR; Cherie Blair &LR; , wife of the prime
minister, lawyer and mother of four, was up to $498. The
description of this item says the purse ``shows a glamorous side''
of the donor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jerry Hall &LR; , whose glamorous side is already widely known,
donated a red and blue tote that's going for $1,085. The
description, for some reason or other, says that the donor's
favorite handbag (which is not for sale) is a 1950s Cartier
alligator purse ``with a real gold handle.'' The descriptive matter
also notes that Hall ``made the news recently with her decision to
remove all her clothes for her role as Mrs. Robinson in the stage
version of `The Graduate,' '' which ought to boost the value of the
handbag considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Blair and Hall purses are attracting small
change compared with the pick of the handbag litter, a black
Ferragamo donated by former Prime Minister  &UR; Margaret &LR; 
 &UR; Thatcher &LR;  and fetching $152,242. ``The first woman prime minister
and now a member of the House of Lords, Margaret Thatcher is one of
the most famous handbag owners of recent times,'' says the
description. ``It is she who was responsible for the press coining
the expression `handbagging' after observing the way she dealt with
her political opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BUTTONING UP THOSE LOOSE LIPS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Karen Hughes &LR; , who is head of  &UR; George W. Bush &LR; 's communications
team, has two deputies reading every media story written about her
boss. According to Washingtonian magazine, their task is to look
for comments attributed to ``unnamed campaign sources'' and then
contact the writers of those stories to try to find out who the
sources were.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign higher-ups told the magazine that Hughes had
scolded them for making unauthorized comments to reporters. ``It's
outrageous and bush league, pun intended,'' said one experienced
reporter. ``They're control freaks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; LOVE, HOLLYWOOD-STYLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A story on Hollywood's happiest couples in the August McCall's
magazine names  &UR; Meg Ryan  &LR; and  &UR; Dennis Quaid &LR; . ``He's the real
thing, a real guy,'' says the Mrs. ``She makes me laugh. She's got
good taste. She elevates my life,'' says the Mr.
</P>
<P>
   Official word came last week, obviously after the magazine went
to press, that the couple had separated. People magazine fills us
in:
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's been seen smooching and cuddling in public with
 &UR; Russell Crowe &LR; , with whom she stars in the forthcoming movie
``Proof of Life.'' And Quaid has been accused of pawing and
grabbing young women who have worked with him on such movies as
``Any Given Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no talk of divorce yet,'' Quaid's ex-wife,  &UR; P.J. &LR; 
 &UR; Soles &LR; , told People. ``I know Dennis would be extremely happy if
they resolved it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Alec Baldwin  &LR; told InStyle magazine about his top three hair
gels and about his 4-year-old daughter,  &UR; Ireland &LR; , who doesn't
hesitate to interrupt him, he said, when he's ``on the phone
talking to the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The  &UR; Duchess of York &LR;  has changed her mind about moving to
Switzerland, perhaps because the principal of the fancy Swiss
school her daughter &UR; Beatrice &LR;  was to attend was arrested and
charged with abusing his own children.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I live (in Europe) because the level of debate is so naive &LR; 
 &UR; in America. . . . The right wing wants their guns, the left wing &LR; 
 &UR; wants their criminals coddled and no one wants anyone punished. &LR; 
 &UR; America is a big, wild country where lots of bad things come to &LR; 
 &UR; pass, and from the minute my children were born I was determined &LR; 
 &UR; that they not grow up there. That's why we live in Europe. I &LR; 
 &UR; think that probably has something do with the fact that I am &LR; 
 &UR; perceived to be a smart-aleck. It's apparently why I made the &LR; 
 &UR; Movieline list of the most pretentious actors. That was quite a &LR; 
 &UR; happy day for me.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; John Malkovich &LR;  in Playboy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
