A4923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-STAMPS-C     07-06 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-STAMPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New stamps commemorate baseball greats
 &HT;    By Monique Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Pollack introduced himself and then began telling his
favorite Lou Gehrig stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, a lot of people don't know this, but he thought that
the gutsiest athletes in the world were ballerinas,'' said Pollack,
who is a family friend. ``And he had a great love for opera, but
back then if the baseball players knew that well, you know. Anyway,
he had to sneak in through the back with his collar up.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack laughed as he remembered the man he met while spending
his afternoons at the ballpark in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   It was at the ballpark that Gehrig and 19 others became the
legends of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   From Christy Mathewson to Jackie Robinson, the U.S. Postal
Service honored 20 major-leaguers Thursday with the first issue of
the Legends of Baseball commemorative postage stamps. An estimated
40,000 stamps were bought at the ceremony and officially go on sale
nationwide today.
</P>
<P>
   Family members and friends of the players honored attended the
event in International Plaza. More than 400 fans and stamp
collectors converged on the plaza to witness the Postal Service's
first collection dedicated to baseball.
</P>
<P>
   James Tolbert, USPS executive director of stamp services, said
the stamps honor not just what the men did in their sport but also
what they did in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a great president or politician to be
recognized,'' Tolbert said. ``We want to recognize people for their
dedication in any event and for their accomplishments and what they
did to make where they were a better place.''
</P>
<P>
   The 85-year-old Pollack said the stamps will help perpetuate the
lives of the players represented and allows people to see the human
side of the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gehrig's baseball statistics were unbelievable,'' he said,
``but this puts a human face to those statistics and now to future
athletes it can begin to mean something.''
</P>
<P>
   For the family of Josh Gibson, the stamp begins to recognize his
accomplishments in the Negro Leagues. Gibson died before he would
see Jackie Robinson break the color barrier in the major leagues in
1947.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only thought stamps and coins were for presidents,'' said
Josh Gibson Jr., 69. ``Now, here's my father, a black man, who
never played in the major leagues, and he's on a stamp. That's
special.''
</P>
<P>
   From the seven batting titles of Rogers Hornsby to the 511 wins
collected by Cy Young in 22 years, the collection brings together
the men who made baseball special in this country, said Hank Aaron,
the home-run king who was a guest of honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these men played before my time,'' Aaron said, ``but
every player in every era owes years of gratitude to them for truly
making baseball America's national pastime.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
