<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-TEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLAND RADAR BASE LINKED TO MISSILE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In advance of Friday night's critical missile
defense test over the Pacific Ocean, senior Pentagon officials have
quietly put together a construction plan for a $500 million radar
system in western Alaska, underscoring the momentum toward keeping
the project alive into the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   While the results of the test will play a factor in President
Clinton's decision this fall on deploying the missile-defense
system, Defense Department officials have strongly argued that the
president keep the project on track by building the start of a base
on Shemya Island, according to two people with first-hand knowledge
of the Pentagon's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to do the test and go ahead and pour the concrete
for the radars,'' said a former Defense Department official,
speaking on condition on anonymity. ``They can hold off on the full
deployment decision but still stick to the schedule for completing
the system by 2005.''
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton gave a limited go-ahead, an option strongly favored
by Defense Secretary William S. Cohen, the Pentagon would then
request bids for the ground-based radar system at the western edge
of the Aleutian Island chain.
</P>
<P>
   Barges could then carry the materials in March to a former Air
Force base on the island, just in time for Alaska's
April-to-September construction season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is such a narrow window in Alaska to do construction, to
scrape out the dirt, to pour concrete slabs, to mount radar,'' said
the former official. ``It still gives whoever makes the decision
next, (Texas Governor George W.) Bush or (Vice President Al) Gore,
the option of whether to go forward to build the system.''
</P>
<P>
   A US official, also speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed the Pentagon's plans, saying there was wide consensus
among the top ranks of the Defense Department to keep the project
on schedule until figuring out whether the technology can be
developed to hit incoming missiles more than 100 miles above the
earth.
</P>
<P>
   But such pro-missile defense bias in advance of the test, which
has been evident in past comments by US officials, has sparked
anger from a wide array of opponents, including Russia, China,
European allies, as well as US scientists, corporate leaders and
Nobel laureates.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 50 Nobel laureates this week signed a letter to
Clinton urging him to abandon the $60 billion project, saying it
``would offer little protection and would do grave harm to this
nation's core security interests.''
</P>
<P>
   But many in the administration have strongly argued that such a
system is needed to protect the country against an attack from a
hostile country or an accidental launch of a nuclear weapon aimed
at the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Several scientists, including Michael Mendillo, a professor of
astronomy and electrical and computer engineering at Boston
University, have found fault with the decision-making process.
Mendillo said the launch should be described as an experiment, not
a test, because the conditions are controlled.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise, scheduled to take place between 10 p.m. Friday and
2 a.m. Saturday EDT, involves firing a 63-foot rocket with a mock
warhead from Vandenberg Air Force Base, Calif. A balloon decoy will
be attached to it. About 15 minutes afterward, a 54-inch
``exoatmospheric kill vehicle'' is then set to be launched from
Kwajalein Atoll, about 4,300 miles away in the Pacific Ocean. It is
hoped the kill vehicle will guide itself into a collision with the
mock warhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you even thought a country was trying to attack us, you
wouldn't tell the adversary where you thought it was going to be,''
Mendillo said Thursday. ``It is such an affront to declare this a
test. No matter what happens, they will declare it a victory
because so much is invested in this.''
</P>
<P>
   In two previous tests, one ``kill vehicle'' hit the target,
while the other missed.
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant Colonel Rick Lehner, a spokesman for the Ballistic
Missile Defense Office, said if the president approved construction
of the radar system in Alaska, the building would have to start by
April ``to meet the 2005 deadline.'' Lehner reiterated that Clinton
would make the decision, not Pentagon planners.
</P>
<P>
   The former Air Force base, once home to 2,000 officers, is now
occupied by about 65 people working on other missions including a
weather station.
</P>
<P>
   The former Defense Department official said Pentagon lawyers
have extensively reviewed whether the start of building a radar
system would violate terms of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty. The lawyers believe it does not violate the terms because
the concrete pads could be used for several purposes. But the
lawyers have also written in their reports that Russian officials
could be expected to say it represented a violation, the former
official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test is seen as important, because it gives you more
data,'' said the former official. ``But the Pentagon is planning in
the meantime to go ahead and start the next phase.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
