<HEADLINE>
BUSH GETS SPECIAL BIRTHDAY `GIFTS' FROM HISPANIC TEXAS DEMOCRATS 
 
(INCL. TRIM INDICATORS) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ On the occasion of his 54th birthday, Gov. George W.
Bush on Thursday received from Tejano Democrats a gift of two
prepaid phone cards and a round-trip bus ticket to visit housing
developments for the poor on the Texas-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel he's not done enough for our people, like he claims
to,'' said Frumencio Reyes, vice chairman of the Texas Democratic
Party and a member of the Tejano Democrats of Harris County.
</P>
<P>
   As he campaigns for president, Bush is reaching out to Hispanic
organizations and voters, touting his record in Texas on issues of
concern to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes said his group hopes Bush will use one of the phone cards
to call on Texas' Republican U.S. senators, Phil Gramm and Kay
Bailey Hutchison, and ask them to rescind their opposition to El
Paso lawyer Enrique Moreno's appointment to the 5th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno was nominated by President Clinton to the New
Orleans-based court in September. His confirmation process stalled
after Hutchison and Gramm questioned his qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning last week, Bush said he would speak with both
senators to hear their concerns about Moreno, but stopped short of
saying he would intervene on Moreno's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to lobby this,'' Bush said at a campaign stop
in Michigan. ``I am going to find out what the facts are.''
</P>
<P>
   The second phone card is for Bush to use calling on Texas Health
Commissioner Dr. William ``Reyn'' Archer III to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, a 1997 Bush appointee, angered Hispanic groups by
linking Texas' high rate of teen-age pregnancy to Hispanic cultural
resistance to family planning. He later apologized, and Bush has
said he thinks Archer is doing ``a fine job.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus ticket to Pharr, Texas, would take Bush on his first
visit to the border area's (SET ITAL) colonias, (END ITAL) where
some 400,000 people, mostly Hispanic, live in substandard
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Bush has taken credit for improving
conditions in the (SET ITAL) colonias (END ITAL) and improving
access to health care coverage for the poor and uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our three gifts are designed to make the governor's birthday a
happy occasion for all Texans,'' Reyes said at a news conference in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``On today of all days, he should be in a good mood and
therefore willing to do the right thing on Enrique Moreno, Reyn
Archer, and the 400,000 people who live in (SET ITAL) colonias (END
ITAL),'' Reyes said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The two 60-minute phone cards and the bus ticket cost about $80.
Postage to the governor's post office box in Austin cost about $11.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Washington also gave Bush a birthday bashing, as
the Democratic National Committee poked fun at his relationship
with oil companies with a cake decorated with oil pumps.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The governor got more traditional and friendlier greetings at
home in Austin, as he returned to the Governor's Mansion from a
noontime jog. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Staffers jumped out from behind bushes and a gazebo yelling,
``Surprise!'' About 300 workers from Bush's office and presidential
campaign then threw him a party on the lawn, singing ``Happy
Birthday'' and serving cake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF FILE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
