<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BELL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REV. B. CLAYTON BELL SR., PRESBYTERIAN LEADER AND BILLY GRAHAM KIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. B. Clayton Bell Sr., a nationally known Presbyterian
church leader and the brother-in-law of evangelist Billy Graham,
died Tuesday in Montreat, N.C. He was 67.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Bell was minister-emeritus of Highland Park Presbyterian
Church in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service is scheduled for 3 p.m. Monday at the
Highland Park church, 3821 University Blvd., in Dallas. Private
burial will be handled by Sparkman-Hillcrest Funeral Home.
Memorials are asked to be made to the Bell Memorial Fund at
Highland Park Presbyterian.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Bell led the Highland Park congregation for more than 26
years before his retirement Jan. 31. He was known for his writings
and sermons on family life, moral and social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great man, and I know the Lord welcomed him home,''
said one of Rev. Bell's close friends, Bill Broocks, a retired
Dallas businessman and a major official in the governing body of
the 5,400-member Highland Park church, the third largest
congregation in the Presbyterian Church U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Bell, executive chairman of the board of Christianity
Today, was a founder of the Presbyterians for Renewal, a group
which urges a greater focus on spiritual life and evangelism. He
was also a national spokesman for the denomination's conservatives
who oppose ordination of gays or allowing same-sex union ceremonies
in the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Bell was a giant in our Presbyterian church's life,'' said
the Rev. Bob Thompson, pastor of Hemphill Presbyterian Church in
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, the Highland Park church was the denomination's
largest congregation. But a split occurred several years ago when
some members resisted the reunion of the northern and southern
branches of the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Bell favored remaining in the reunited denomination.
</P>
<P>
   He was the brother of Ruth Bell Graham, wife of the evangelist.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Bell was born in China, where his parents, the late Dr.
Nelson L. and Mrs. Virginia Bell, were medical missionaries for 25
years. He held a bachelor's degree from Wheaton College in Illinois
and a master's degree from Columbia Theological Seminary in
Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Bell's speaking schedule was full through 2002, his former
secretary, Diane Warner, said yesterday. He was in Montreat to
speak at the Presbyterian Retreat Center and spent July 4th with
the Graham family, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was planning on working with Billy Graham in one of his
upcoming crusades,'' Warner said. ``Also, he was looking forward to
taking a trip around the world, which the church had given him and
his wife as a retirement gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Peggy; two sons, the Rev. L. Nelson
Bell II of Tulsa, Okla., and Ben C. Bell of Dallas; two daughters,
Margaret Bell Lindstromand Virginia Lucille Bell Petty of Dallas;
and 10 grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
