u a BC-LEE-NUKE-NYT &LR;      07-06 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.M.)  
 U.S. NAMES SOME COUNTRIES SCIENTIST MIGHT HAVE TRIED TO HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After months of resisting, federal prosecutors
Thursday identified Australia, Switzerland, China and several other
countries as some of the nations that a scientist accused security
breaches at the Los Alamos National Laboratory might have been
trying to assist.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the scientist, Wen Ho Lee, immediately ridiculed
some entries on the list. ``These are not countries which anyone
other than the prosecutors have identified as presenting any kind
of nuclear threat to the United States,'' Mark Holscher, one of the
lawyers, said.
</P>
<P>
   But the filing, which came only after U.S. District Judge James
A. Parker ordered it, did reinforce a government theory that Lee
might have improperly downloaded the vast trove of secret weapons
data because he wanted to enhance his job prospects with a foreign
agency after being told by the laboratory in the early 1990s that
he might be laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers flatly rejected the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing Thursday, the government said that in about 1993,
Lee wrote letters to institutions in Australia, France, Germany,
Hong Kong, Singapore, Switzerland and Taiwan seeking employment.
</P>
<P>
   The government also stated that at one time Lee had made contact
with officials from the Institute of Applied Physics and
Computational Mathematics in China, though it did not provide a
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Chavez, a spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney's office in
Albuquerque, N.M., where the case is being heard, said that
prosecutors would not comment beyond the three-page document.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, Lee's lawyers have demanded that the prosecutors
provide a so-called bill of particulars, specifying which countries
the government believed Lee was trying to assist.
</P>
<P>
   Those details are important, because Lee is charged not just
with improperly downloading the data, but doing so with the
intention of aiding a foreign country and harming the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   George A. Stamboulidis, the assistant U.S. attorney who is
leading the prosecution, in his filing Thursday left the government
maximum flexibility by keeping its case against Lee vague.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that Lee had not necessarily decided which country he
intended to assist when he downloaded the weapons data.
Stamboulidis also contended that the government needed to prove
only that Lee intended to harm the United States and not
necessarily that he intended to provide an advantage to another
country.
</P>
<P>
   Stamboulidis also said that the government could add names to
the list in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who is 60, was originally the subject of a sweeping
investigation because of concerns that he might have given China
the secret to developing a miniaturized American warhead known as
the W-88. Because of those concerns, he was fired from his job in
March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But when Lee was indicted on 59 felony counts in December, it
was not for espionage. Instead, he faces charges that he had
improperly downloaded the data from a secure to an unsecure
computer, then placed the information on portable computer tapes.
Seven of those tapes have never been recovered, though Lee has said
that, in keeping with lab policy, he destroyed them.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers have not disputed that he received a notice saying
he might be laid off, or that he contacted some institutions about
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   They have said, though, that Lee's contact with the scientific
institute in China was an official trip paid for and sponsored by
the laboratory. And they rejected the idea that any downloading Lee
did had anything to do with improving his job prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the most noteworthy thing about this is that after all
those months investigating him and seven months after indicting
him, they still don't have a theory on what he was doing or who he
was trying to help,'' Nancy Hollander, another lawyer for Lee,
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
