<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNN-CONVENTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNN NAMED ONE OF THREE CO-CHAIRS OF GOP CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Rep. Jennifer Dunn was named Thursday as one of three
co-chairs to preside over evening sessions of next month's
Republican National Convention, an appointment that backers say
signals presidential candidate George W. Bush's resolve to put a
new outward face on his party.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn will share duties in Philadelphia with Texas Rep. Henry
Bonilla, an Hispanic, and Oklahoma Rep. J.C. Watts, the lone
African American Republican member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some symbolism in it, showing the soft side of the
conservative image,'' Dunn said. While she, Bonilla and Watts
``obviously look like representatives of different groups,'' Dunn
added, the three work well together in the House.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert was tapped as permanent chairman of
the convention. Hastert is likely to preside at the Republicans'
morning sessions. Dunn, Bonilla and Watts will be at the podium
during evening sessions which are part of TV networks' scaled-back
convention coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively high-profile role for Dunn is a signal that
Washington would assume an importance in a Bush administration
``more than it has had for any previous Republican president,''
Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., said Thursday. Gorton has emerged as a
prominent adviser to the Texas governor on environmental, forest
and salmon issues.
</P>
<P>
   Chairing a convention once brought national notoriety, such as
when House Majority leader Carl Albert wielded a gavel that
silenced reformist and anti-war Democrats at the party's tumultuous
1968 convention in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Although today's conventions are carefully scripted, Dunn is
likely to be seen sharing the podium with such prime-time GOP
speakers as retired Gen. Colin Powell, Arizona Sen. John McCain and
former cabinet officer Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn has risen in the Republican Party due to two skills, a
formidable prowess at fund-raising and the ability to put a kinder
face on House Republicans' policies than the party's male leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn was an early, enthusiastic supporter of Newt Gingrich, who
in 1995 became the first GOP House speaker in 40 years. She signed
on equally early with the George W. Bush campaign. She has served
as one of the ``Pioneers,'' the fund-raisers who last year
committed themselves to raise at least $100,000 apiece for the
Texan's race for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Dunns estimates that she has raised $300,000 for Bush, plus an
equal amount for the Republican National Committee, during
appearances around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn headed the Washington state primary campaign in which Bush
defeated McCain, even though Washington, with its deep reservoir of
independent voters, was a prime target for the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, Bonilla and Virginia Gov. James Gillmore also have been
tapped for roles as principal spokespersons for the Republican
National Committee during the fall campaign. She has been working
closely on GOP fund-raising with former Texas Republican chairman
Fred Meyer, Bush's chief liaison with the party apparatus in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost a race for House majority leader, Dunn has been
frequently mentioned as a secretary of Commerce or U.S. Trade
Representative in a Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There you go again!'' Dunn said, borrowing an old Ronald
Reagan line, when asked about a prospective cabinet job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to be on the House Ways and Means Committee in
which we can pass tax cut proposals that will be signed, not
vetoed, by the president,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn became renowned as a GOP fund-raiser during the 1980s as
Washington state Republican chairman.
</P>
<P>
   She was also a strong conservative and Reagan loyalist who named
one of her sons for the former president. Dunn was the object of a
famous blooper by Reagan, when at a 1986 Spokane rally he
identified the GOP chairwoman as ``Dunn Jennifer.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn was elected to Congress in 1992. After women voters
rejected GOP presidential candidate Bob Dole in 1996, she helped
organize an extensive Republican study on how to win back women's
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have carried Washington in the 1988, 1992 and 1996
presidential elections. But Bush has made five visits to the state,
and held a five-point lead over Vice President Al Gore in a
Democrat-sponsored poll made public this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have turned,'' Dunn said Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
