A4945 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KEISSER-MEDIA-LAD     07-06 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-MEDIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSTAS HAS MUCH TO SAY IN NEW BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the end of 2000, Bob Costas will have packed a decade's worth
of work into the first year of a new century. There was his NBA
season work that concluded with him seeing almost as many Laker
games as Chick Hearn, and then Tuesday's All-Star date in Atlanta
on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   That will be followed by two months of Olympic study leading
into his 16 Days of Gory as NBC's prime time anchor during the 2000
Summer Olympics in Australia, and then back to the ballpark for
NBC's post season baseball coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But the ironic reality for Costas is that his best work of 2000
comes along another media avenue. His book ``Fair Ball: A Fan's
Case for Baseball,'' made the top ten on the New York Times book
list, among others, and it's been widely hailed as a well-written
prescription for some of the things that ail baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the book came from two sources. The issues he
wanted to talk about were too large for him to work between innings
of game telecasts or even as a guest on longer form radio and TV
shows. ``You can't flesh out some of these issues during a game,
nor should you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also had his fill of being characterized as a traditionalist
or purist -- a niche now considered as avant garde as a AARP
meeting, octogenarian division -- and having his comments
automatically categorized as the ranting of a baseball nut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to collect all this in one place where I could get
some ideas out there and leave no misunderstandings regharding what
they are,'' said Costas. ``Tradition is important, and it is more
important to baseball than any other sport. But it has too often
been characterized as keeping baseball the way it is, or was.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's not the point, or at least not his.
</P>
<P>
   The quick read (177 pages) touches a lot of points, but one
suggestion he makes stands tallest. At a time when one team can
near a $100 million salary roster and another can barely top out at
$10 million, Costas offers a revenue-redirecting concept that makes
sense.
</P>
<P>
   He believes teams should share their local TV revenue for games
they play on the road. Imagine how it would even out the financial
structure of the game if the Yankees, Cubs and Braves -- three
perfect examples -- had to share their TV revenue whenever they
play in Minnesota, Milwaukee and Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   It's a common sense solution that incorporates an established
revenue source that all teams want to keep growing. Two principals
of the NFL's success is a sharing of gate receipts and equal
sharing in TV revenue. It certainly beats the concept of a luxury
tax that forces the rich franchises to tithe to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic idea is to help balance the playing field so
everyone has a chance,'' Costas said. ``Not even necessarily an
equal chance, but at least a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can look back at baseball and see a time when teams like
Kansas City, Pittsburgh, Oakland, Minnesota and Cincinnati had a
chance, because they did win. But in the last six years or so,
things have changed to where there are a half-dozen teams with
absolutely no chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Costas said the response has been heartening. He's heard from
owners of large-market teams that think it's a good idea as well as
some baseball front office people. But officially, baseball has no
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they haven't had time to digest the ideas, or just don't
care,'' he said. ``A few people said it makes sense, and therefore
it will never happen, which is a pretty strong indictment of what's
troubling baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``My way is not the only way. Maybe someone within baseball has
a better idea. I just feel we've got to do something. The best
thing about the book is that I've had my say. I've had a chance to
state my case without someone else distorting the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the news: Costas will work the All-Star Game Tuesday (5
p.m.) with Joe Morgan ... ESPN has the Home Run Derby (5 p.m.) and
Celebrity Hitting Challenge ( 7 p.m.) on Monday ... Fox will air
both games of Saturday's ultra rare Yankees-Mets day-night, two
stadium doubleheader, but L.A. will just see half of it. Fox has
the early game at Shea at 10 a.m. -- not seen here because we'll
get the Angels-Rockies at 1 p.m.) -- and Fx the game at Yankee
Stadium at 5 p.m. ), and FX ... ESPN Classic has announced relaunch
effective July 10. One part of the ``relaunch'' is the addition of
segments from ESPN's award-winning SportsCentury top 50 athletes
series, usually as part of theme packages. There will also be a
nightly rerun of a classic ``Up Close'' segment with Roy Firestone
... Advanced programming note: HBO's ``When It Was a Game III''
airs on July 17 (10 p.m.) ... Fox Sports Net and Broadband Sports
have entered into an agreement to produce 26 episodes of a new
series entitles ``Beyond the Game.'' The hook here is that each
show will feature fresh interviews and never-before-available
footage. AthletesDirect.com is a division of Broadband Sports, and
the company has been stockpiling original content for several
years.
</P>
<P>
   The world according to me: Fox's new Regional Sports Report has
been on the air a week now, and it hasn't shown much improvement in
content or changing its ``we'' philosophy. Word is a representative
of former KTLA sports anchor Eddie Arnold, who knows all of the key
L.A. Sports people well, sought an interview for his client and
couldn't even get a call back ... NBC happily reports that it will
make around a $200 million profit on its telecast of the 2000
Olympic Games. Gee, with all this largesse, maybe NBC could share
the wealth with viewers and AIR AN EVENT OR TWO LIVE instead of
airing all 441 hours of coverage on three networks on a delayed
basis. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
