<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIADY-FUNDRAISING-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEA BARGAIN EYED IN PROBE OF CAMPAIGN DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Negotiations have intensified between federal
prosecutors and lawyers for James T. Riady, a friend of President
Clinton and a prominent Indonesian businessman whose large campaign
donations to Democrats have been scrutinized by investigators,
government officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After talks with the Justice Department's chief
political-finance prosecutor, Robert J. Conrad Jr., Riady has been
under pressure in recent days to accept a plea bargain, the
officials said. Conrad has been investigating Riady's activities in
connection with contributions made by employees of Lippo Group, the
Riady family conglomerate, in the 1992 and 1994 campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether Conrad has insisted that Riady plead
guilty to a felony or whether he might accept a lesser charge and
settle the case without a trial. But, the officials said, Riady is
unlikely to accept any deal unless it includes a provision that
would spare him a prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Riady's defense lawyer, Abbe D. Lowell, would not comment on the
matter Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of Riady heated up after John Huang, a
Democratic fund-raiser and former Lippo employee with close ties to
Riady, was sentenced in August 1999 to a year of probation in
exchange for his cooperation in the inquiry. Huang pleaded guilty
to engaging in a conspiracy to defraud the Federal Election
Commission by arranging for Lippo employees to be reimbursed for
campaign contributions in the 1992 and 1994 campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Huang, in an appearance before a House committee investigating
campaign finance issues, testified that he knew of no wrongdoing by
Clinton or Vice President Al Gore. Huang said Riady told him about
a 10-minute limousine ride that Riady shared with President Clinton
in the 1992 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   During the limousine ride, according to Huang's account, Riady
promised to raise $1 million for the campaign. Huang said Riady
told him that Clinton had been surprised by the offer. Riady had
been a friend of the president since Riady's days as a trainee at a
Little Rock investment bank when Clinton was governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Huang recalled Riady saying later that his approach to political
giving was, ``If you are going to do something, don't do it
small.'' Clinton has said that he knew of nothing improper about
the donations made by Riady and other members of his family.
</P>
<P>
   Riady and his wife, Aileen, contributed $520,525 to the
Democrats in 1992, election commission records show. Lippo and its
employees gave the Democrats an additional $115,000 in 1992.
Members of the Riady family also made large donations to state
Democratic parties in 1992.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Later, in September 1994, Clinton, Riady and Huang were seen in
a White House videotape taken at a White House radio address, a
weekly event that important supporters were sometimes invited to
attend. After the address, Clinton is seen conferring with Riady
and Huang. Little can be heard of their conversation, although
Clinton at one point is heard to say, ``important issues,'' and at
another time says, ``I think it will be big.''
</P>
<P>
   In times of trouble, the Riady family stepped in to help other
Clinton associates. After Webster Hubbell left a high-ranking post
at the Justice Department in 1994 in a dispute over billing records
at his former Little Rock law firm, a Riady family company paid
Hubbell a $100,000 consulting fee.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, the former Whitewater prosecutor, investigated
whether such fees totaling more than $500,000, from several firms,
amounted to payments to buy Hubbell's silence about his knowledge
of the activities of Clinton and his wife, Hillary. Hubbell denied
that the payments were hush money.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Riady told an interviewer that he had tired
of the life of a high-flying entrepreneur and longed for a quieter
life in school or at a Christian ministry. In the interview with
Asia Inc. magazine, he said the Asian financial crisis had been a
trying experience because of bank runs and riots in Indonesia in
which one of the family's shopping malls was set on fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
