<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, JULY 7 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-RACE-SPORTS-NYT (moved on Saturday, July 2) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, July 2,
about a white quarterback at the historically black Southern
University in Louisiana misstated the number of colleges in the top
division in college football. That grouping, known as Division I-A,
comprises 114 institutions, not 500. (Southern plays in the next
division, I-AA.)
</P>
<P>
   The article also misstated the educational record of Jackie
Robinson. He attended U.C.L.A. but did not graduate.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-MOYNIHAN-FARM-NYT (moved on Friday, June 30) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, June 30,
about the decision by Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan and his wife,
Elizabeth, to sell their upstate farm misstated Mr. Moynihan's
birthplace. He was born in Tulsa, Okla., not the Hell's Kitchen
section of Manhattan. He moved to New York with his family when he
was a child.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-POWER-SHORTFALL (moved on Sunday, July 2) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 2,
about the challenge of maintaining a reliable flow of electricity
to meet the needs of the computerized economy miscalculated the
amount of time that a user would be without electricity if the
power supply were 99.99999999 percent reliable. It would be 0.0032
second a year, not 32 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The article also described  &UR; cobi &LR; FuelCell Energy &UR; coei &LR; 
incorrectly. The company, which changed its name last September,
was founded in 1969 as the Energy Research Corporation. It is not a
start-up company. A chart with the article provided an outdated
list of the company's products; it spun off its battery business as
 &UR; cobi &LR; Evercel &UR; coei &LR;  Inc. last year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT (moved on Monday, July 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 3,
about the effects of aging and exercise on blood vessels
misidentified one substance involved in keeping blood vessels
healthy. It is nitric oxide, not nitrous oxide.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-ABOUT.COM-NYT (moved on Wednesday, July 5) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, July 5,
about people who operate web sites for About.com omitted the given
name of the company's senior vice president for content. She is
Linda Osborne.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
