<HEADLINE>
DODGERTOWN AGREEMENT NEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The Los Angeles Dodgers are close to agreeing on a
deal that will keep Dodgertown their spring training home for the
next 20 years, officials familiar with the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and representatives from Vero Beach, Fla., and
Indian River County fine-tuned a proposal last week that includes a
major overhaul of Dodgertown, the club's spring training home since
1948. It will include a small town center and renovations to
workout areas and improvements to Holman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement could be made by the end of next week, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even see where Las Vegas is an option anymore for the
Dodgers,'' said an official involved in the process. ``I think the
window of opportunity there passed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers insist they remain interested in Las Vegas, but
interest from many of the other clubs involved has dwindled
considerably since Florida Gov. Jeb Bush signed a bill that
allocates as much as $2.5 million per year to spring training
facilities owned by local municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers and Dodgers were made the point teams in the
process of a six-team complex in Las Vegas. The Dodgers would only
do the deal with six teams, but only the Rangers remain excited
about it. Houston, Baltimore, Toronto and Tampa Bay are all
planning on returning to Florida for the long-term, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still actively pursuing our other options, including
Las Vegas,'' Dodgers senior vice president Derrick Hall said.
``We're in contact and continually negotiating with the other teams
involved in Las Vegas, as we continue to deal with the local
government in Florida as we approach a finalized plan.''
</P>
<P>
   It is conceivable Las Vegas could make a late run and overwhelm
the Dodgers, but the chance of that was termed ``a million-to-one
shot'' by an official.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have a hard deadline this month of making a decision
because of the way the funding bill was written in Florida. In
order for sites to get funding, the facility must be owned by the
municipality. The Dodgers own Dodgertown and will sell it back to
Vero Beach and Indian River County and lease it for $1 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Vero Beach and Indian River County have until Oct. 1 to apply
for funding.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo, Perez drop appeals: Dodgers outfielder F.P.
Santangelo and left-hander Carlos Perez each informed the players
association they were dropping their appeals and will serve their
five-game suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Perez will begin serving his five-game suspension July 16 and
Santangelo will serve his five-game suspension July 22. The Dodgers
players weren't enthralled with the idea of going to Atlanta to
have their appeals heard by commissioner Bud Selig, but the major
factor in dropping the suspensions was the likelihood Selig would
overturn it.
</P>
<P>
   However, left fielder Gary Sheffield plans to go through with
his appeal of a five-game suspension, which is tentatively set to
be heard Tuesday before the All-Star Game. And the players
association is behind Sheffield and believe he can have his
suspension reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great deal of sympathy for Gary,'' said Gene Orza,
associate general counsel of the players association. ``I've
watched the film more after the hearings (June 21) in Houston. The
conclusion that Sheffield was acting as anything more than a
peacemaker is absurd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
