<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIANS-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN INVESTMENT FUND, NO LONGER SECRET, WILL CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ After mounting pressure from Western
governments whose philanthropy keeps the Palestinian Authority
afloat, Yasser Arafat's government has divulged details of its
long-hidden investment portfolio, and now says that its next step
will be to dismantle the fund entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The man who has been the keeper of Arafat's investment accounts,
Mohammed Rachid, said in a rare, on-the-record conversation with
journalists here Thursday night that he will preside over the
dissolution of the financial empire he methodically amassed at
Arafat's behest.
</P>
<P>
   Rachid, who had managed to keep himself and the Palestinian
government's business dealings shielded from public scrutiny for
years, pledged that the holdings would either be divested or
transferred to a new, publicly accountable Palestinian Investment
Fund by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   According to an audited statement sent to the International
Monetary Fund in June and published this month on the Palestinian
Authority's Web site, the holding company now boasts assets of $345
million, including $292 million in equity stakes in three dozen
companies. Its one-third share in an Israeli-patronized casino,
valued at $60 million, is its largest and most lucrative
investment.
</P>
<P>
   The liquidation of these holdings will not be entirely
voluntary, Rachid acknowledged Thursday. Western governments had
refused to continue subsidizing Palestinian budget deficits unless
all government revenues and expenditures were consolidated into a
single ``transparent'' budget account, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been hiding information,'' Rachid said. ``Maybe it
wasn't wise.'' But he said that this secrecy was evidence not of
corruption, but of inexperience in public administration and
Arafat's desire to protect profitable investments from his own
free-spending bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge difference between monopolies and
corruption,'' Rachid said, adding that it was unrealistic to expect
the emerging Palestinian state to conduct business ``like a small
Switzerland.''
</P>
<P>
   The investments were detailed last month in the audit. In that
report, Rachid's Palestinian Commercial Services Co., which is
owned by the Palestinian Authority but not supervised by its
legislature or finance ministry, was revealed to control large
minority stakes in a Jericho casino, a Ramallah Coca-Cola bottler,
a Bethlehem convention center and myriad other private businesses,
plus full ownership of a cement plant that had long enjoyed a
government-protected monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The company was also, until recently, the direct recipient of
sales taxes _ more than $500 million in the past two years alone _
collected by Israel but owed to the Palestinian Authority under the
1993 Oslo peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   The tax receipts had been deposited in a Tel Aviv bank account
controlled by Rachid and Arafat, a practice ended by Israel in
April after persistent complaints by the World Bank, the
International Monetary Fund and other institutions charged with
monitoring Palestinian finances. Some of the tax money was used by
Arafat for undisclosed official expenditures, but most went to the
Palestinian Commercial Services Co., according to Palestinian
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the major investments disclosed in the audited report,
like the casino and holdings in luxury hotels and the local
telecommunications monopolies, had been reported unofficially here.
But there were a few unexpected oddities, like small joint
investment funds with the government of Qatar and the Peres Peace
Center, a Tel Aviv foundation started by Shimon Peres, the former
Israeli prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The report also revealed that Rachid's company recently put $9
million into a small biotechnology company in London, Ontario,
Bioniche Life Sciences, its only disclosed investment outside the
Palestinian territories. The Palestinian Authority became the
second largest investor in the closely held Canadian company, and
Rachid, whose wife and children are Canadian citizens, was awarded
a seat on the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they decided to invest in the London area for personal
reasons,'' a spokeswoman for the Ontario company said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Rachid said Thursday that he has no personal financial interests
in businesses in which his government company invested.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 23 years working with Yasser Arafat, I carefully watch
myself,'' said Rachid, who joined the Palestinian Liberation
Organization while working as a journalist in Beirut. He followed
Arafat to Tunisia and, in 1994, to Gaza, becoming one of his
closest confidantes. Though he has no formal position in the
Palestinian hierarchy, Rachid is part of the 11-member negotiating
team headed for Camp David next week.
</P>
<P>
   Rachid and other Palestinian leaders characterize their budget
reforms as an essential prelude to the independence they hope to
secure in the peace talks. A sovereign Palestinian state will be
able to seek loans from the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund and put up guarantees for commercial bond issues _
but only if its books are in order, they say.
</P>
</TEXT>
