<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-PLATFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SELECT GROUP SPEAKS OUT ON THE DEMOCRATIC PLATFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Democratic Party opened public hearings on its
platform here Thursday with a tightly scripted display of party
unity, hearing from a parade of witnesses who endorsed Vice
President Al Gore's positions on almost every major campaign issue,
like gun control, the economy, health care, education and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   The daylong hearing provided further evidence that Gore, who
easily defeated former Sen. Bill Bradley in the primaries, will not
face the kind of bitter policy divisions that have bedeviled
Democratic presidential nominees of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials intend to release a draft of the platform
on Friday. And they made it clear that they expected it to be a
clear articulation of Gore's vision rather than the kind of
ideological treatise he might feel compelled to run away from.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that much of this is straight out of what he has
already had to say, what he has already proposed,'' Gov. James B.
Hunt Jr. of North Carolina, chairman of the platform drafting
committee, said Thursday. ``And I think he can run on it and win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are hoping that their unified front will give them
the appearance of greater party strength than the Republicans,
whose platform meetings continue to provide a forum for fierce
debate over abortion.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the trade issue was widely expected to be the
Democrats' platform equivalent of abortion. Many trade unions and
environmentalists, major components of the Democratic base, have
opposed the Clinton administration's position on global trade,
arguing that it has hurt the environment and siphoned jobs away
from American workers.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, trade was rarely mentioned. The one person
expected to raise the issue, Alan Reuther, legislative director for
the United Automobile Workers, did not show up. Democratic
officials said Reuther had a scheduling conflict.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few discordant notes was sounded by Amy Isaacs,
national director of Americans for Democratic Action, a liberal
group. Speaking on the trade issue, Isaacs said, ``Granting China
permanent normal trade relations is a step in the wrong direction,
we believe. As a nation, we must state clearly that profits over
people is untenable.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaacs added that ``liberals in the country are very uneasy''
with the nation's political drift. And she urged the people writing
the Democratic platform not to blur the distinctions between the
two major parties, a criticism often leveled at the Democrats by
Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Leigh Blek, a registered Republican from Orange County,
Calif., who helped organize the Million Mom March for gun control
earlier this year, typified their tone. Blek, without explicitly
endorsing Gore, complained that the leadership of the Republican
Party had not heard the voices of mothers who want stronger gun
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think in November, they are going to hear it,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said the committee was likely to face some
policy debates behind closed doors Thursday night as they hammered
out the final draft. For instance, labor officials are pushing for
stronger language defending the rights of workers to form unions.
They also want a clearer pledge of support for trade agreements
that protect the environment and workers' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the committee are also expected to push for a
more sweeping declaration of the party's support for ending
discrimination against gays and lesbians and a more powerful
condemnation of racially motivated violence.
</P>
<P>
   But those debates are expected play out on the fringes, not at
the heart, of the 10,000- to 20,000-word document.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for a fight here at all,'' said Gerry Shea,
a top official with the AFL-CIO, who is on the platform drafting
committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
