<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-FREE-RIDE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMTRAK IS OFFERING EVERY DISSATISFIED RIDER A FREE TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 8th graf, Amtrak estimates ..., to correct 2nd sentence,
if amtrak can `reduce' rate by 1 percentage point, sted `raise'
rate.) 
By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amtrak said Thursday that it would offer every
dissatisfied customer a free repeat trip, even if the problem was
not the railroad's fault.
</P>
<P>
   The new program is part of its campaign to build ridership and
revenues by reducing the number of disgruntled passengers, before
Congress cuts off operating subsidies in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``This grabs people's attention in the marketplace,'' said
George Warrington, president of Amtrak, who added that no other
national carrier had offered a similar program. This one is
retroactive to July 4.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak's reputation among potential passengers has historically
been poor, Warrington acknowledged, because of trains that are late
or in poor condition. He said the new program was intended to
demonstrate ``Amtrak's ability, desire and fixation about putting
guests at the center of everything we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also revealed a new logo, to replace the ``pointless
arrow,'' as it is known, that has served for the last 29 years. The
company plans to redesign waiting rooms, ticket booths, platform
displays and schedules themselves, to match.
</P>
<P>
   To exercise the new guarantee, Amtrak is asking its customers to
call their complaints to the attention of any employee. If the
employee cannot solve the problem Amtrak will issue coupons for
repeat travel.
</P>
<P>
   The company anticipates, for example, issuing coupons to people
for a problem with a seat or a sleeping compartment or to entire
train loads of passengers if a train is extremely late. Amtrak
promises to provide the free ride coupon even if the problem is an
ice storm, or derailment of another train. ``Regardless of fault,
in the end, it's Amtrak that's responsible,'' Warrington said
during a meeting with reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak estimates that for every 100 people who try the railroad
for the first time, 15 percent never ride again. If Amtrak can
reduce that rate by 1 percentage point, its revenues would rise by
$13 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad has also trained on-board personnel to help
passengers if a train is going to be late, by telephoning ahead to
relatives who were planning to pick them up at the station, for
example, or re-booking connections and hotel accommodations.
Company officials said they were taking cues from what travelers
expect from airlines under similar circumstances.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the last three years Amtrak has been offering a similar
satisfaction guarantee on a single train, the Coast Starlight,
which runs daily in each direction between Seattle and Los Angeles,
and has issued one coupon good for a free trip for each 107,000
passengers, Warrington said.
</P>
<P>
   But the railroad expects a much higher rate of complaints and
refunds on other trains. It has told its 25,000 employees that if
the rate of complaints runs better than one in 1,000 trips during
any month, each of them will get a bonus for that month equal to
the average price of an Amtrak ticket, which is now $50.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad said that ridership was up 7 percent in the last
four months compared with the previous year and that in June, for
the first time, it had revenues of $100 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Passenger loads on its four daily all-electric ``Acela
Regional'' trains running between Washington and Boston are up 40
percent over the older trains they replaced, the railroad said.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad intends to introduce its high-speed Acela service,
with a top speed of 150 mph, later this summer. That had been
scheduled for last year, but problems were found in testing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
