<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-AUTOMOBILE-ROW-2ND     07-06 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AUTOMOBILE-ROW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: the establishment.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, Ford owns another Kahn building, 787 11th Ave., between
54th and 55th Streets, completed in 1929 as the Packard Motor Car
Co. Service Building. The massiveness of this eight-story
industrial structure is relieved by vaguely Mayan gargoyles along
the parapet, giant rosettes and fluted pilasters. It is a
one-and-a-half-mile detour from the Broadway itinerary, but you can
always buy a car while you're there.
</P>
<P>
   A much shorter detour takes you to the former home of the
Automobile Club of America at 250 West 55th Street, a 12-story
buff-brick building just west of Broadway. Within an ornamental
niche above the second story, the legend ``ACA 1910'' can still be
faintly discerned.
</P>
<P>
   This structure was an annex to a far more sumptuous eight-story
clubhouse at 247 W. 54th St., built in 1907 and designed by Ernest
Flagg, the architect of the Scribner Building at 597 Fifth Avenue.
(The club moved out long ago, and the Beaux-Arts facade was
replaced by plain white brick. The structure is now the state Labor
Department Community Service Center.)
</P>
<P>
   Besides garage space for 350 cars, the Automobile Club offered
its members a 100-foot-long assembly hall modeled on the Chateau de
Cheverny in France; a grill room that could feed 300 hungry
motorists at a time; a billiard hall; a library; and accommodations
for chauffeurs. The 55th Street annex had space for 600 more cars
and a restaurant, barber shop and Turkish baths.
</P>
<P>
   The organization is now the Automobile Club of New York, an
affiliate of AAA, with headquarters in Garden City. But it
maintains a travel agency at 1881 Broadway, which was once the
Walter C. Martin Cadillac dealership. This Triple A branch on the
northwest corner of 62nd Street may be the last functioning vestige
of Automobile Row.
</P>
<P>
   Down 54th Street from the old Automobile Club is a nondescript
two-story structure at 1711 Broadway that was once a Reo Motor Car
dealership. Reo was founded by Ransom Eli Olds (that is, REO), who
also put his name on the Oldsmobile.
</P>
<P>
   Up ahead, gleaming like a frosted Gothic angel cake, is the
nine-story Argonaut Building, 224 West 57th Street, another
potential landmark. Festooned with decorative details _ lion's-head
brackets, grotesques and stars-and-stripes shields _ the structure
was designed by Francis Hatch Kimball to harmonize with the
Broadway Tabernacle church, which once stood next door at Broadway
and 56th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Kimball designed two harmonious structures in 1909:
the A.T. Demarest &AMP; Co. Building, at the southeast corner of
Broadway and 57th Street, and the Peerless Motor Car Co. Building,
an L-shaped affair that wrapped around the Demarest Building, with
facades on both Broadway and 57th Street.
</P>
<P>
   In the Demarest showroom were Renaults, known as ``the Pride of
France,'' and Italas from Turin. Peerless _ ``All That The Name
Implies'' _ was a celebrated luxury carmaker that reached the end
of its road in 1932, during the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling General Motors Corp. bought the Demarest and
Peerless Buildings in 1916 and combined them. A Cadillac dealership
remained on the ground floor for many years, in what is now a Duane
Reade drugstore. A remnant of the GM days is the word ``Corp.'' in
a rooftop sign.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors moved in 1927 to its own building, 1775 Broadway,
at the northwest corner of 57th Street, designed by Shreve &AMP; Lamb,
later the architects of the Empire State Building. This 26-story
tower rose atop the earlier three-story Colonnade Building by
William Welles Bosworth, seemingly supported by its mammoth,
trunklike Ionic columns. They now frame the windows of Coliseum
Books.
</P>
<P>
   With a series of setbacks, this powerfully spare composition
recalled the mesas of the Southwest _ if mesas had been topped by
electric General Motors signs. The building is now home to
Newsweek, and the sign now advertises the A&AMP;E ``Biography'' series.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, the Hearst Corp. acquired the Argonaut Building, where
it had been a tenant for many years. Cosmopolitan, Cosmo Girl,
Country Living, Popular Mechanics and Redbook are among the Hearst
magazines based there today.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has operated on and around Columbus Circle since 1895,
when William Randolph Hearst bought the Virginia Hotel at 59th
Street and turned it into the office of The New York Journal.
Today, Hearst's Esquire magazine is in the former Automobile Club
annex on 55th Street, and its Classic American Homes and Marie
Claire magazines are in the former United States Rubber Building.
(Its corporate headquarters, at Eighth Avenue and 57th Street, are
only a block from Automobile Row.)
</P>
<P>
   The 20-story tower built in 1912 for United States Rubber, the
forerunner of Uniroyal, is the cynosure of Automobile Row.
</P>
<P>
   Clad in Vermont marble and crowned with a broad copper cornice,
it meets the oblique intersection of Broadway and 58th Street with
a rounded prow, resembling a 275-foot stack of tires, and hovers
over Columbus Circle like an alabaster version of the Flatiron
Building.
</P>
<P>
   Carrere &AMP; Hastings, the architects of the New York Public
Library on Fifth Avenue, designed the building. They specified
rubber-tile floors and marble trim for the ground-floor United
States Tire showroom. Altered beyond recognition in 1959, this
space is now a branch of the HSBC Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The ornate elevator lobby was reclaimed in 1986 after an
associate in the architectural firm of Beyer Blinder Belle
discovered rosettes and a frieze above the modern dropped ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Raab, the chairwoman of the landmarks commission, said the
building was likely to be designated this fall. The owners are not
opposed, said their lawyer, Mark A. Levine of Herrick, Feinstein,
and are even planning to light the tower at night to show off its
architectural features. End of the Road
</P>
<P>
   Next door, at 1780 Broadway, is another potential landmark, the
12-story former B.F. Goodrich Co. Building, completed in 1909 and
designed by Howard Van Doren Shaw. Though not as exuberant as its
neighbor, the facade warrants a second look for its novel
combination of neo-Classical and Vienna Secessionist motifs
surrounding horizontal window bays worthy of the Chicago School of
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Carrere &AMP; Hastings and Shreve, Lamb &AMP; Blake designed the
26-story Fisk Building at 250 West 57th Street, on the southwest
corner of Broadway, which is now undergoing a $10 million, two-year
renovation by its owners, a partnership that includes Peter L.
Malkin. At least through the late 1930s, the building was
ornamented by the Fisk Rubber Co.'s trademark image: a sleepy young
boy in pajamas, candle in one hand and a tire slung over his
shoulder. ``Time to Re-tire?'' the sign asked.
</P>
<P>
   Donald B. Kaplan, who managed the building in the late 1970's,
recalls seeing the sign as a young boy. ``It was something I could
identify with because I wore Dr. Denton's, too,'' he said, ``though
we did not live by candlelight.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk was acquired by U.S. Rubber in 1939, but Malkin has no
plans to retire the name on the building. ``We just feel that the
name is known and has some marketing value,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Automobile Row lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
