<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4968 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-HORSERACING-COLUM     07-06 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSERACING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSES FROM ALL OVER MAKE GOLD RUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. -- There's a lot at stake in Sunday's
Hollywood Gold Cup. Prestige, a purse of $1 million, and points
that count toward NTRA series bonuses as high as $1.28 million.
</P>
<P>
   To look at the field, though, you'd think there must also be a
door prize for the horse who traveled the farthest to be here.
</P>
<P>
   That prize would go to Blueprint, the Irish-bred who arrived at
Hollywood Park last week after racing 18 times in England and
France. But others in the nine-horse field have come a long way,
too - notably David and Pleasant Breeze, New York-based horses who
come out of third- and seventh-place finishes in the Massachusetts
Handicap at Suffolk Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Horses have come from all over to challenge 9-5 favorite General
Challenge in the 61st running of the 1-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as it should be for a race of this stature,'' National
Thoroughbred Racing Association spokesman Eric Wing said after
entries were taken Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   That's as it should be, all right - but rarely is in major
California races. The Santa Anita Handicap hasn't had a horse ship
in from the East to win since New York's Royal Glint in 1976
(unless you count Maryland's Broad Brush, who ran in the Strub
Stakes, went home to train, then returned for the Big `Cap). The
Pacific Classic at Del Mar hasn't had a winner from out of state in
its nine-year history.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gold Cup is proving to be the exception. The past decade
saw Sultry Song (1992), Cigar (1995) and Skip Away (1998) ship and
win. And for 2000 you need a map as well as a copy of the Daily
Racing Form to handicap the race.
</P>
<P>
   Even supposedly Southern California-based horses seem to be just
dropping by for the Gold Cup - D. Wayne Lukas-trained Cat Thief
after running his past three races in Arkansas, Maryland and
Kentucky, and Bobby Frankel-trained Chester House after running his
past four in Florida, Louisiana, New York and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they just do a good job at Hollywood to sell the race
and entice us,'' said Jim Bond, the New York-based trainer of
Pleasant Breeze, a 5-year-old gelding who was second to Golden
Missile in the Pimlico Special two starts back.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than aggressive salesmanship by the racing office.
</P>
<P>
   The million-dollar purse helps. Then again, the Big 'Cap and the
Pacific Classic are million-dollar races, too.
</P>
<P>
   The California weather helps. By contrast, when the Big 'Cap is
run in March, it can be wet in Arcadia, no inducement for Eastern
horses encamped in sunny Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park's running surface helps. Del Mar's has come to be
known as unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think timing is everything. The Santa Anita Handicap is
toward the beginning of the year,'' Bond said, indicating that many
top horses aren't cranked up for intersectional showdowns in the
winter. ``This (summer) time of year is what you'd call a quiet
time.''
</P>
<P>
   There used to be a theory that it was harder for horses to ship
east to west than west to east. It was actually an old wives' tale
spread by Eastern trainers to explain their failures out here - and
Western horses' successes on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no logic to it,'' said Michael Hushion, trainer of
David, a 4-year-old colt making his second trip to California,
having lost a photo finish to Early Pioneer in the San Bernardino
at Santa Anita. ``Possibly (the explanation was that) California
talent was underrated.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrivals of David and Pleasant Breeze swelled the Gold Cup
field to the largest since nine horses chased Best Pal home in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   David, a son of Mt. Livermore owned by Calvin Klein Inc. CEO
Barry K. Schwartz and ridden by Aaron Gryder, is 12-1 on the
morning line. He'd be the first New York-bred to win the Gold Cup,
and the first California stakes winner for Hushion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's one of the premier races in the country,''
Hushion said. ``If you want to prove to everyone that he's a top
horse, and if you want him to have a future at stud, you've got to
run in these races. This horse doesn't seem to have any problem
shipping.''
</P>
<P>
   David will have run at a different track in seven consecutive
races.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant Breeze, listed at 20-1, can top that: The 5-year-old
gelding, a Kentucky-bred son of Pleasant Tap, is about to run at
his ninth different track in a row, covering eight states.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have 1999 Eclipse Award winner Jorge Chavez aboard again.
The jockey missed the Mass Cap with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm testing the waters out in California to see how strong
that (handicap) division is,'' said Bond, who has Behrens on the
East Coast. ``He (Pleasant Breeze) is a really good travel horse.
He's a horse you can put in a suitcase.''
</P>
<P>
   How do the Californians feel about the invasion?
</P>
<P>
   ``As a fan, it's nice to see everybody come in,'' said Richard
Mandella, who trains Gold Cup entrants Out of Mind (5-2) and Big
Ten (12-1). ``As a trainer, I'd like to see them and General
Challenge stay home.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend: The undercard will give the connections of some
Gold Cup horses a chance to make a big day bigger or earn
consolation, as the case may be.
</P>
<P>
   Mandella also has two horses, Lexicon and Expressionist, in the
$300,000 Triple Bend Handicap, Hollywood Park's biggest sprint
race. Mandella can equal Charlie Whittingham with a fourth Triple
Bend victory.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel and owner Juddmonte Farms, who have Chester House in the
Gold Cup, also entered Honest Lady in the $200,000 A Gleam Handicap
for fillies and mares. Chester House and Honest Lady have something
else in common: Both call Toussaud ``Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Record carryover: Upset wins Thursday by claimer A Lil Sweet
($14.60), first-time starter Tracy ($27.20) and front-running Lord
Sterling ($30.20) made the pick-six too difficult for the Hollywood
Park bettors for the second afternoon in a row, setting up a
carryover of $713,923 for tonight.
</P>
<P>
   It's the largest two-day carryover in Hollywood Park history. It
surpasses the record of $638,000 on May 16, 1999. That one led to a
total pool of more than $3 million, from which eight perfect
tickets paid $246,000.
</P>
<P>
   The pick-six on tonight's 7 o'clock card begins with the third
race. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid moved from No.6 to 2 and Behrens dropped from
No.2 to 3 in the NTRA media poll after the former beat the latter
in the Suburban Handicap Tuesday at Belmont Park. Golden Missile
remained No. 1. ... Preakness Stakes winner Red Bullet and Belmont
Stakes winner Commendable square off Sunday in the Dwyer at
Belmont. ... Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus returned Monday
to training with a gallop under exercise rider Andy Durnin at
Hollywood Park. His next start hasn't been set but the Nov. 4
Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs is expected to be his
climactic race. ... Hollywood Gold Cup winners will be honored
Sunday in a ceremony after the third race. Among those expected to
appear are jockey Johnny Longden (four winners, starting with Noor,
1950) and trainer Ross Brinson (Cover Up, 1947). Longden, 93, and
Brinson, 88, are the oldest living Gold Cup champions. ... Many of
the top Hollywood Park jockeys, as well as Kentucky-based Hall of
Famer Pat Day, are scheduled to sign autographs from 11 to 11:30
a.m. Sunday near the saddling paddock. Donations to the Jockeys'
Guild's disabled riders fund will be accepted. ... Hollywood Park
will have a ``For Women Only'' luncheon Saturday, July 15. An 11
a.m. Q&AMP;A and handicapping seminar with Hall of Fame ex-jockey Julie
Krone, trainer Jenine Sahadi, jockey agent Michelle Barsotti and TV
analyst Joanne Jones will precede a noon lunch. Reservations: (310)
419-1549. ... Thursday marked the 25th anniversary of Ruffian's
fatal breakdown in the battle-of-the-sexes match race against
Foolish Pleasure at Belmont Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
