Street in Manhattan. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW BEDFORD, Mass -- July 6, 2000 -- WHALE-BONES-BOS --
A giant blue whale that hadn't been seen on the East Coast for 100
years is now in the possession of the New Bedford Whaling Museum.
The 55-ton whale, which scientists believe was between four and six
years old when it was killed, had it's ribs, vertebrae and shoulder
broken, apparently upon impact with a tanker. Andrew Konnerth, a
biologist in the field of mammal skeleton rearticulation, worked
with his wife Jean to reassemble the blue whale skeleton. The
process, somewhat akin to constructing the world's largest jigsaw
puzzle, took more than a year. (Tom Herde/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BOSTON -- July 6, 2000 -- VAN-GOGH-PORTRAITS-1 --
Vincent Van Gogh, a 19th-century French painter lived a brief but
animated life despite being labeled antisocial. He had visions of
establishing an artists' colony in France, which led him to others
interested in the avant-garde movement. A detail from Vincent Van
Gogh's self-portrait from 1887, at the Museum of Fine Arts in
Boston. (Museum of Fine Arts, Boston/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) GARRISON, N.Y. -- July 6, 2000 -- HUDSON-SHAKESPEARE-2
-- The Hudson Valley Shakespeare Festival in Garrison, N.Y., is
currently based on the grounds of the Boscobel Restoration, a
historic house and gardens on a promontory overlooking the Hudson
River. The company's co-founder and longtime artistic director,
Terrence O'Brien, knows from long experience not to try to compete
too grandly with the landscape. O'Brien at an afternoon rehearsal.
(Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) GARRISON, N.Y. -- July 6, 2000 -- HUDSON-SHAKESPEARE-1
-- The Hudson Valley Shakespeare Festival in Garrison, N.Y., is one
of the best-kept theatrical secrets in the outer reaches of the New
York metropolitan area. Theatrical fads inevitably fade, but
Shakespeare alfresco, it appears, is forever. Paul Johnson plays
Angelo and Aidan Sullivan portrays Isabella in ``Measure for
Measure.'' (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MORROW, Ga -- July 6, 2000 -- AMAZON-REVIEWER-COX --
Attracting a book buyer to its website is a feat made easier when a
reader can get solid reviews from a reliable source. According to
the online bookstore, Amazon.com, the top book reviewers are
selected not only for the number of reviews they contribute, but
also for the number of votes they receive from readers rating the
helpfulness of the criticism. Harriet Klausner has been dubbed the
``No.1 Reviewer'' after receiving more than 5,000 ``helpful''
ratings from her fellow readers. (Phil Skinner/The Atlanta Journal
Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- July 6, 2000 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-4
-- Today, Pristina, Yugoslavia, Kosovo's capital, is a chaotic,
noisy town, its streets heaving with small traders, construction
work, sidewalk cafes and traffic jams. But the hubbub scarcely
speaks of a solution to Kosovo's many problems: a year after the
end of the war here, chaos and dislocation continue, manifested in
the doubling or even tripling of the population of this ramshackle
town, now home to more than half a million people. Mostly people
from the villages, they are refugees who have abandoned their
burned-out homes and have sought work and shelter in the capital.
Aerial of Pristina at night. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) GRABOVAC, Yugoslavia -- July 6, 2000 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-3
-- The war in the Kosovo province of Yugoslavia forced about
two-thirds of the province's 2 million people from their homes.
Hundreds of thousands remain displaced, living in tents and shacks
in villages, in drab and despondent refugee centers in towns, or
doubled up with relatives in cramped and unhealthy surroundings in
the cities, as many as 30 to an apartment. Dalip Zogjani, 51, and
his wife in the makeshift home he built in Grabovac. Grabovac, or
Grabofc as it is called in Albanian, is a small mining village
tucked into the hillside just 10 miles from Pristina. All but one
of its 47 houses were burnt by Serbian forces. (Andrew Testa/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LODJA, Yugoslavia -- July 6, 2000 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2 --
Kosovar Albanian children playing in ruins of the village of Lodja.
The village of 300 houses was destroyed by Serbian forces in 1998.
As more than 700,000 Kosovo Albanians flocked home from refugee
camps in six weeks last summer, or came down from their hiding
places in the hills, many seized Serb-owned houses here, forcing
Serbs and the Gypsies to flee. The war in the Kosovo province of
Yugoslavia forced about two-thirds of the province's 2 million
people from their homes. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) GRABOVAC, Yugoslavia -- July 6, 2000 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1
-- The war in the Kosovo province of Yugoslavia forced about
two-thirds of the province's 2 million people from their homes.
Banush Zogjani spent the Kosovo war living in the mountains and has
just returned to Grabovac and his badly damaged house. Only seven
of the 47 families who lived in Grabovac have returned, living in
tents and clearing away the rubble of broken tiles and glass. They
are busy digging their gardens and growing vegetables for the
winter. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) HOLLYWOOD -- July 6, 2000 -- TRAVEL-TOURISTS-LADN --
Mann's Chinese Theatre in Hollywood draws tourists as if it were a
shrine. This is what international travelers clamor for when they
visit Southern California, fascinated by the world of illusion in
the enetertainment industry. A tourist tries out Natalie Wood's
hand for size in front of Mann's Chinese Theatre. (David Crane/The
Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAYVILLE, N.Y. -- July 5, 2000 -- ELEMENTARY-GYM -- In
many elementary schools around the country, the emphasis is
increasingly on cooperation, not competition. The idea is to
nurture children's self-esteem and teach them more about how to
keep healthy than how to play team sports. Joanne Hamilton, a gym
teacher at Sunrise Drive Elementary School in Sayville, N.Y., since
1982, says ``the fewer discouraging experiences students have in
gym class, the more likely they are to continue exercising for the
rest of their lives.'' Students interacting in a class at Sunrise
Drive Elementary School. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times) Story
moved on 07/03/00
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- July 6, 2000 -- CIR-ABOUT.COM-2 --
About.com is a linked network of 700 Web sites. The content on each
site is created by people, who may or may not be professionals in
the fields they cover and who are not employees of About.com. A
conference held in Washington in June was a series of intimate
gatherings sponsored by the company and designed to focus on the
basics of the Web business. About.com webmasters, also known as
guides, discuss various ways to make money at the conference.
(Susana Raab/The New York Times) Story moved on 07/05/00
