u p BC-BRADLEY-GORE-480&AMP;ADD-     07-06 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-GORE-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY WILL OFFER SUPPORT TO GORE SOON, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Adds second byline; minor changes.) 
By JAMES DAO and ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ending months of silence, former Sen. Bill Bradley will appear
alongside Vice President Al Gore next week to voice what Democratic
officials described Thursday night as his ``enthusiastic support''
for the man who trounced him in the bitterly contested Democratic
presidential primaries last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Though details of the joint event were still being thrashed out,
the officials said the two men were expected to meet at a rally
next Thursday in Green Bay, Wis. Wisconsin is considered an
important swing state. The officials said the appearance might be
just the first of several joint events before the November
election.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance comes just as Gore is working hard to unify the
party in time for the Democratic National Convention next month,
the event many Democrats are counting on to give his campaign a
lift going into the home stretch this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Gore has been trying to energize the Democratic
base in his public appearances by attacking the oil and
pharmaceutical industries.
</P>
<P>
   Smoothing things over with Bradley would be an important step in
energizing the party, many Democrats say. A cloud of bitterness has
hung over the relationship between Gore and Bradley since Bradley
quit the race in March without having carried a single state. Some
Democrats contend that friction has hurt Gore's ability to present
a united front for the party.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was furious with what he considered Gore's dishonest
attacks on his campaign agenda, particularly his proposal for
universal health care. At the news conference where he announced
his withdrawal from the race, Bradley said he would support the
vice president, but refused to use the word ``endorse.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would not release the roughly 400 delegates he
had won until the party's convention, raising the possibility that
he might start some policy fights with the vice president's camp.
And he chided Gore for a hard-edged campaign style, a criticism the
Republicans have repeatedly echoed in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that he'll run a better campaign in the general
election,'' Bradley said of Gore at the time.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic official familiar with the current negotiations
said that Bradley will ``make it very clear that the vice president
has his enthusiastic support.'' The official said it was even
possible that Bradley would use the word ``endorse,'' though
Bradley is well-known for changing his mind on such tactical
matters at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's unequivocal support could help take the edge off
Republican assertions that Gore is a dirty fighter and dishonest
politician who will do or say whatever it takes to win. And because
Bradley received support from Republicans and independents, he
could help Gore woo swing voters who are likely to determine the
outcome in closely contested states.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Discussions about when Bradley would campaign with Gore had been
going on for several months, primarily between Tony Coelho, the
former head of the Gore campaign, and John Roos, a fund-raiser and
confidante to Bradley. William Daley, who replaced Coelho and had a
good relationship with Bradley, picked up the negotiations when
Coelho quit last month.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have also agreed on Bradley's role at the
convention, one official familiar with the negotiations said. The
official said Bradley will address the convention at a prominent,
possibly prime-time slot. The official would not say which day
Bradley would speak.
</P>
<P>
   With Gore starting to draw stark contrasts between himself and
his Republican rival, Gov. George W. Bush, this seemed like the
right time for the two former rivals to appear together, an aide to
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to ramp into the convention,'' he said. ``It's
a good time for all Democrats to come together and focus on the
task at hand. The differences between Gore and Bradley are
minuscule compared to the miles of differences between them and
George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The aide continued, ``Both Gore and Bradley were in favor of
improving our health care system and George W. Bush has not offered
anything of substance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
