<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MILOSEVIC-     07-06 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MILOSEVIC-405&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISED YUGOSLAV CONSTITUTION ALLOWS MILOSEVIC TO SEEK ANOTHER
TERM 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The Yugoslav Parliament approved
constitutional changes Thursday that allow the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic, to run for a new term and that diminish the
influence of Montenegro, Serbia's small sister republic.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, which the Parliament portrayed as strengthening
democracy, require the direct popular election of the Yugoslav
president and of the upper house of Parliament. They allow two
four-year terms for the president and raise the threshold for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The effect will be to give Milosevic a very good chance of
remaining in power past July of next year, when his current term
expires. Until Thursday, the federal president was elected by the
federal Parliament and could serve only one four-year term. And the
upper house of the federal Parliament was itself elected by the
Parliaments of the two republics, Serbia and Montenegro .
</P>
<P>
   The changes put the federal government, instead of the two
republics, in charge of organizing elections.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, under President Milo Djukanovic, has broken with
Milosevic and moved toward the West, and has vowed to hold a
referendum on independence. Thursday's changes make Milosevic's
plans for elections less dependent on Montenegro's consent and may
hasten Montenegro's risky effort to break away.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrin leaders expressed outrage at Thursday's votes. One
told The Associated Press, ``Yugoslavia was erased today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since this amounts to the constitution of a new country,
Montenegro is now forced into making inevitable moves,'' said
Miodrag Vukovic, a senior adviser to Djukanovic. ``In the next few
days, Montenegro will adopt laws which will wrap up its
independence in all fields.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic must call federal and municipal elections by the end
of this year, and he is likely to hold presidential elections at
the same time, while the opposition is bickering and the
independent media are under increasing pressure from the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Djukanovic decides that Montenegro should boycott the
federal elections, they will take place anyway, and Milosevic's
allies there, who attract at least 30 percent of the vote, will win
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's divided democratic opposition, most of which already
boycotts the Parliament and thus did not vote against the changes,
seemed caught by surprise, without a clear candidate to run against
Milosevic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The lower chamber passed the changes 95-7, while the vote in the
upper chamber was 27-0.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's debate, the Radical Party leader, Vojislav Seselj,
argued that direct elections were the rule in most modern
democratic states.
</P>
<P>
   But Vladeta Jankovic of the opposition Democratic Party of
Serbia told the lower house: ``The constitution is being changed
for the sake of just one man.'' He denounced the haste of the
voting, and said: ``It is shameful that we are agreeing to adapt
the constitution to one man, Slobodan Milosevic, who should rule
forever and move from one presidential armchair into another until
infinity.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has already been elected to two terms as Serbian
president, and when he could not run again under the constitution,
he became federal president, taking on sweeping powers not foreseen
for this putatively figurehead office.
</P>
<P>
   Now, reaching the constitutional limit for this job, Milosevic
has changed the constitution to allow two terms.
</P>
<P>
   But he has also challenged the democratic opposition to beat him
in a direct vote.
</P>
<P>
   While deeply unpopular in opinion polls, Milosevic is
nonetheless regarded by Serbs as better at his job than any of the
democratic leaders, who are considered ambitious and divided.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll done in early May for the National Democratic
Institute, some 38 percent of Serbs said that Milosevic ``may not
be perfect, but he's better than the opposition,'' and he remained
the most popular choice as leader of Serbia _ the only one whose
ratings were larger than the ``don't knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, only 14 to 18 percent of the people, in various polls,
think he is the best leader for Serbia. But his ratings are three
times higher than those for Vuk Draskovic, the leader of the
Serbian Renewal Movement, who gets about 6 percent, while the
Democratic Party leader, Zoran Djindjic, gets about 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dragoslav Avramovic, the former head of the Central Bank who
beat back Yugoslavia's inflation, gets about 8 percent, but he is
old and ill. Still, if the opposition could unite behind a single
candidate in a two-way race, a Milosevic victory would not be
guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   For Montenegro, which has about 600,000 people compared to
Serbia's 10 million, the changes undercut some of the artificial
protectins it received as Serbia's formal equal in the federal
structure. Given its tiny size, it is unlikely that a Montenegrin
could ever win election as federal president.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrin officials also complained that they were not
consulted on these changes.
</P>
<P>
   The republic's government and Parliament will meet on Friday,
when they are likely to refuse to recognize the legitimacy of what
happened Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
