<HEADLINE>
ITALY CONSIDERS PLANS TO FREE INMATES FROM BURSTING PRISONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ With 53,000 people in a prison system built for fewer
than 43,000, Italy now has its largest prison population since the
end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since members of the governing center-left coalition last
month began gingerly discussing easing conditions by freeing
thousands of prisoners under a general pardon or amnesty, prisons
across Italy have erupted in disturbances and protests, with
prisoners _ and sometimes the guards _ conducting strikes, burning
mattresses and going on hunger strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from inmates, guards and Pope John Paul II, the
Senate Judiciary Committee voted on Wednesday to examine five draft
proposals to free prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who intends to visit a Roman prison on Sunday on a
Holy Year day dedicated to prisoners, last week asked governments
worldwide for leniency toward inmates, saying, ``A reduction, even
a modest one, of the term of punishment would be for prisoners a
clear sign of sensitivity to their condition.'' The Vatican has
helped raise the expectations of Italian inmates and put pressure
on politicians, who are uncomfortable with a step that a majority
of Italians oppose.
</P>
<P>
   The center-right opposition, led by Silvio Berlusconi, the media
baron, has rejected suggestions that Parliament approve a general
pardon to ease prison conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition argues that the entire justice system needs a
rehauling and that dangerous criminals could be freed. Italians
generally have little faith in the judicial system, but they are
also increasingly concerned about crime. Polls suggest that most
Italians oppose an amnesty or pardon.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house of Parliament has 20 proposals, and the Senate
has five.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Prime Minister Giuliano Amato has not issued
its own bill. Instead, politicians have floated proposals.
</P>
<P>
   With national elections expected to be held in a year, the
battle has many layers beneath the pros and cons raised in public
debate. Berlusconi had a private meeting with Justice Minister
Piero Fassino last week on the issue. Afterward, Berlusconi
rejected the notion of a general pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, a general pardon would release prisoners who have less
than three years remaining on their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   But Berlusconi did not rule out an amnesty, which would release
prisoners under certain conditions, expunge their records and also
wipe out certain trials in progress. Some legal experts argue that
an amnesty would help unclog the backlog of court cases and be more
effective than a general pardon.
</P>
<P>
   But Berlusconi, who has had several convictions of accounting
fraud and bribery and who has been acquitted on appeal of several
convictions of accounting fraud and bribery, faces trials on other
charges of false accounting and could benefit personally _ and
politically _ from an amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   That has led center-left politicians to make sarcastic remarks
about Berlusconi's personal motives, as well as pious remarks about
the center-right opposition's failure to heed the pope's pleas.
</P>
<P>
   But Amato's center-left coalition is deeply divided and in
disarray. Many political experts and even members of his coalition
suspect that the Amato government could end up reaching an
agreement with the opposition to grant an amnesty, hoping to avert
a confidence vote that could force early elections, which the
center-left fears it would lose in its present frazzled state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
