<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PADRES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' BROWN DOMINATES PADRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ A year ago, Kevin Brown was treated horribly in San
Diego, and by San Diego. He was pummeled at Qualcomm Stadium in one
start, lost another one, and was dissed when it came to an All-Star
selection by Padres manager Bruce Bochy.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed a bit.
</P>
<P>
   In his final outing before the All-Star break, Brown was simply
overpowering. He tied a career high with 12 strikeouts, and Shawn
Green broke out of a miserable slump as the Los Angeles Dodgers
beat the Padres 9-3 in the series finale Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Brown (8-2) was so dominating he retired 10
straight. He also went a stretch in which nine of 10 outs he
recorded were via strikeout. And his next appearance most likely
will be in Tuesday's All-Star Game in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, I made two really bad pitches and they both
wound up in the seats,'' said Brown, named to the National League
All-Star squad Wednesday. ``It wound up not being an issue because
the guys behind me did such a great job of putting runs on the
board. We came back. We were down 2-0, and it started right away,
and we kept pushing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, if only Brown could get some help from the other starters,
the Dodgers could possibly put together a serious winning streak.
The last time a starter other than Brown won was Chan Ho Park, who
beat St. Louis on June 18.
</P>
<P>
   Brown allowed four hits and didn't walk a batter, but he did
make two mistakes that resulted in San Diego's runs. After a
five-minute delay in the first inning because of an ill-positioned
banner in center field, Brown allowed a two-run homer to Phil Nevin
after a single by Ryan Klesko. The other hits were a fifth-inning
double by Wiki Gonzalez and a seventh-inning homer by Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like when they got those hits, (Brown) turned it up
to another level and kept guys off balance,'' Dodgers left fielder
Gary Sheffield said. ``The ball, from what I was seeing, was moving
all over the place. He was jamming a lot of guys. Nobody was
getting a good swing off him, and when he's like that, it's just a
matter of time before we can score runs. He's going to shut the
game down.''
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Beltre gave the Dodgers a 3-2 lead with a two-run homer
in the fourth, and right fielder Shawn Green snapped out of his
funk with his first homer since June 23. Green added a double and
could have had a two-run triple in the eighth but for a scoring
decision that went against him.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Todd Hundley continued to work toward a huge offseason
deal with some team as his revitalization continued. Hundley, a
career .236 hitter entering the season, had three hits, including
his 17th homer, and drove in two runs to raise his average to .318.
</P>
<P>
   ``My swing, it just clicked,'' said Green, who was 5 for 41
entering the game. ``I've been trying all different things and
nothing worked. Finally, I was able to stay back. I was jumping at
the ball too much. I finally got the right thought that kicked in,
and it worked. It's been a frustrating few weeks. It's tough when
you get in a rut. You go through a list of things to try, and when
something finally works it's a big load off your mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
