<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-HAGELIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE FROM MAHARISHI U.
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.H., Iowa, Pa., Mass.)  By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His own press secretary concedes that he has an
unusual curriculum vitae for a presidential candidate. John Hagelin
is a quantum physicist who preaches the benefits of transcendental
meditation. He runs the physics department at an Iowa university
named for Maharishi Mahesh Yogi. As the presidential candidate of
the Natural Law Party in 1996, he won exactly 0.12 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   But John Hagelin is also the man standing between Pat Buchanan
and $12.6 million in federal matching funds, and that has made him
a suddenly attractive commodity to Reform Party members opposed to
Buchanan's social conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Only Hagelin and Buchanan are on the ballot in the Reform Party
primary, which began this week with the mailing of about 1 million
ballots to party supporters across the country. The winner will be
announced at the party's convention in August, and the winner's
campaign will receive the millions in matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who has spent months gathering ballot access
signatures from some 500,000 prospective voters, all of whom are
receiving ballots, would seem to have a lock on the nomination. But
his candidacy has roiled an already fractured party that everyone
from Donald Trump to Jesse Ventura has tried to lay claim to this
election season.
</P>
<P>
   And with Ross Perot, the party's founder, now declining to
challenge Buchanan for the nomination, Buchanan opponents have been
desperately casting about for an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin is it. On Thursday, the leaders of the Independence
Party, the Reform Party's New York incarnation, gathered at the
Grand Hyatt Hotel in Manhattan to express their support for him.
Among those attending was the avowed Marxist Lenora Fulani, herself
a former presidential candidate, who last year endorsed Buchanan,
only to break with him last month. On Thursday, Fulani called
Hagelin ``decent, principled, pro-populist,'' and Buchanan
divisive.
</P>
<P>
   Such characterizations aside, the two men could not be more
different. Where Buchanan is ebulliently brash, Hagelin is
soft-spoken and prone to flowery phrases like ``grass-roots
politics and the laws pertaining thereto.'' He emphasizes his
pedigree, peppering his literature with the phrase
``Harvard-trained,'' while Buchanan has fashioned himself
anti-establishmentarian.
</P>
<P>
   And while Buchanan has made opposition to free trade,
immigration and abortion the staples of his campaign, Hagelin
champions preventive medicine, criticizing what he calls a
``disease-care system''; advocates a moratorium on genetically
engineered foods, and has detailed plans for increasing crop yield;
and proposes using ``coherence groups'' of meditators to reduce
stress and crime in major cities.
</P>
<P>
   At the gathering Thursday, he talked of building a ``mainstream
political alternative.'' Buchanan's entrance into the Reform Party,
he said, has caused ``mass attrition,'' and there is a
``grass-roots brush fire waiting to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin, 46, was born in Pittsburgh, graduated from Dartmouth
College and earned master's and doctoral degrees from Harvard. He
lives in rural Fairfield, Iowa, where he works at the Maharishi
University of Management, which calls itself an institution
``utilizing the managing intelligence of Nature for professional
success and personal fulfillment.'' There he directs the physics
department as well as the Institute of Science, Technology and
Public Policy, which his campaign describes as a ``progressive
policy think tank.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin challenged Buchanan to three debates. But Brian Doherty,
Buchanan's spokesman, said again that he would not debate his
challenger unless Hagelin promised not to run as the Natural Law
nominee should he lose the Reform nomination. As to the assertion
of Hagelin and others that Buchanan was hurting the Reform Party,
Doherty said it was simply not true. ``The party was in shambles,''
Doherty said, ``and he's rebuilding it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
