<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online Business Exchanges May Raise Antitrust Issues  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As companies in nearly every industry rush to join
business-to-business exchanges on the Internet, regulators are
growing concerned that they will face a rash of new antitrust
questions for which they are not prepared.
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges create a place for companies in the same industry
to buy and sell goods, potentially saving millions of dollars. But
the sites, which can compile huge amounts of sensitive data and are
often jointly owned by corporate rivals, also create opportunities
for collusion and price-fixing that did not exist before, antitrust
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers Post Anemic Sales Rise
</P>
<P>
   Sales in stores open more than a year, a key figure for
measuring the health of the retail industry, rose by only 2.6
percent in June compared with figures in the period a year earlier.
Analysts said the numbers were in line with expectations that the
economy is losing steam. Consumers are spending less at all types
of stores, ranging from specialty apparel stores like the Gap to
discount stores like Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Rise in Technology Rebound
</P>
<P>
   Stocks closed mostly higher as Wall Street looked for bargains
in technology shares that were battered in the previous session.
The technology-laden Nasdaq composite index rose 97.47 points, or
2.5 percent, to 3,960.57. The Dow Jones industrial average edged
down 2.13 points, or 0.02 percent, to 10,481.47, cushioned by gains
in Intel and financial stocks. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index finished up 10.44 points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,456.67. The
yield on the 10-year note rose to 6.04 percent from 5.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak to Offer Riders Free Trips
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak said that it would offer every dissatisfied customer a
free repeat trip, even if the problem was not its fault. The new
program is part of Amtrak's campaign to build ridership and revenue
by reducing the number of disgruntled passengers before Congress
cuts off operating subsidies in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   SBC to Start Long Distance in Texas
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications plans to formally announce Friday the
long-distance rates it will charge in Texas, the second state after
New York in which a local phone company will also offer
long-distance service. SBC will charge a basic rate of 9 cents a
minute for in-state and out-of-state calls anytime, with no monthly
fee. It will also cater some services to people who make frequent
calls to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Gtech Warns on Profit; Chief Quits
</P>
<P>
   Gtech Holdings said that its two top executives had resigned and
that its revenue and earnings would fall short of expectations. The
lottery company said the departures of William Y. O'Connor,
chairman and chief executive, and Stephen P. Nowick, president and
chief financial officer, were a result of the board's
dissatisfaction with the unexpected announcement, Gtech's lagging
stock price and the poor handling of a computer flaw in Britain's
national lottery that recently came to light. Shares of Gtech fell
$2.9375, to $19.8125.
</P>
<P>
   Factory Orders Rose 4.1 Percent in May
</P>
<P>
   Factory orders rose 4.1 percent in May, the largest gain in
almost seven and a half years, suggesting that signs of a slowdown
in consumer demand are having only a limited effect on
manufacturers, a report showed. A separate report showed claims for
jobless benefits fell to the lowest level in five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   MTV Comedian to Pitch Right Guard
</P>
<P>
   Tom Green, the outrageous MTV comedian best known for stunts
like dropping a live mouse into his mouth, as he does in the hit
comedy film ``Road Trip,'' or snorkeling for change in a shopping
mall fountain, is being featured by Gillette in a television and
print campaign for Right Guard.
</P>
</TEXT>
