<HEADER>
A5109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     07-06 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: LOOKING TO THE PAST TO SECURE THE PRESENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Columbus had an easier time finding the new world than the
Yankees have had finding a fourth starter in their rotation.
Cracking the Japanese code in World War II was child's play, the
theory of relativity a snap.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Yankees, who get clubbed and knocked about with
regularity but amazingly remain afloat, like a rubber duck in a
bubble bath, sent the rookie Ed Yarnall to the mound in an attempt
to find another starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall was brought up from Columbus on Thursday, after a good
outing against Toledo, and was immediately named the starter
against the Orioles. Yarnall had been scheduled to be in the
starting rotation in spring training, but poor performances
relegated him to the bushes.
</P>
<P>
   From all accounts, Yarnall is an upstanding left-handed citizen
and, at age 24, may have a long and prosperous career in the major
leagues. Maybe one day we will visit his plaque in Cooperstown. But
he swiftly learned that Baltimore was not Toledo, on the map or at
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   As one fan, seated behind the Orioles' bench, noted with
impressive resonance at one point in the Baltimore half of the
second inning: ``What is this, batting practice?'' And then he
shouted to the Yankee manager: ``C'mon, Joe, get this stiff outta
there!''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, with the Yankees losing, 5-0, and the bases loaded
and still no outs, Joe Torre took the fan's advice. In came Ben
Ford. Out went Yarnall, to a chorus of boos. If you're going to
play Broadway, you'd better have a thick skin. And better stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Ford had auditioned for a starter's spot
but came up short. The first batter he faced Thursday, Mike
Bordick, doubled. ``Bring back Irabu!'' another fan shouted. Hideki
Irabu, the Japanese import who never lasted as a starting pitcher
with the Yankees, is but a painful memory to Bronx fans.
</P>
<P>
   When the inning was over, the Yankees were behind, 7-0. At this
point, a gloom settled over the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Just three weeks ago, the Yankees had brought up Jake Westbrook
from Columbus and had started him immediately. He got bombed, too,
lasting just two-thirds of an inning longer than Yarnall. He was
soon back in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Now, David Cone has struggled mightily this season and was
bumped from the starting rotation for the coming series against the
Mets. It was hoped he would be the fourth or at least fifth Yankee
starter, but the great competitor and longtime ace has a ballooned
ERA and hasn't won a game since the Coolidge administration. Is it
his arm, his head, or simply senescence? No one knows, not yet,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Yankees search, like coal miners with nail files,
for that helpful hurler, their bats are alive like the sound of
music.
</P>
<P>
   They came back with eight runs in the second inning, and five in
the fourth, took a 13-7 lead and went on to a 13-9 victory. The
bullpen, which has been dependable all year, saved the team again,
along with the likes of Derek Jeter, Paul O'Neill and Bernie
Williams _ each of whom homered, which is nothing new _ and David
Justice, who launched his first homer as a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, though they are only five games over .500, remained
neck and neck and neck with Toronto and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It was fortunate for the Yankees that the Baltimore pitchers,
particularly Sidney Ponson and Jason Johnson, seemed under the
impression that they were also were candidates for the Yankees'
rotation, and were pounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee search continues, and they have plucked, of all
people, Dwight Gooden. In recent years, Gooden, 35, has seen many
teams and better days.
</P>
<P>
   The former Met and Yankee and Indian and Astro and Devil Ray is
back in the Yankee organization, and has pitched in relief for the
Yankees' Tampa team in the Gulf Coast League. He was recalled
Thursday to pitch Saturday against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was recommended from down below,'' said Torre, after the
game, meaning that the Yankee scouts tapped ol' Doc.
</P>
<P>
   Did he feel comfortable with a guy who hasn't pitched in the
majors in two months? ``He's got experience,'' Torre said
tactfully, not appearing wildly enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden has pitched in two games in rookie league ball and given
up no runs in eight innings. But in the majors this year, he was
2-3 with Tampa Bay with a fat 6.63 ERA, and with Houston a no
decision in one appearance with a 9.00 ERA. Off of this, he seems
perfectly suited for the Yankees' rotation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
