<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-06 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DEODORANT-AD-COLUMN-N     07-06 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEODORANT-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: GILLETTE GOES TO EXTREME WITH ADS FEATURING TOM
GREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Green, the outrageous MTV comedian, is best known for stunts
like dropping a live mouse into his mouth, as he does in the hit
gross-out comedy film ``Road Trip,'' or snorkeling for change in a
shopping mall fountain.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the kind of guy typically embraced by corporate
America, right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette has introduced a television and print campaign using
Green to endorse Right Guard, a brand built over the last dozen
years on the imagery of big, burly jocks like Emmitt Smith, Charles
Barkley and Brett Favre. The Right Guard campaign, carrying the
theme ``Anything less would be uncivilized,'' has helped the brand
maintain its status as the leading deodorant-antiperspirant in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Has Gillette gone mad in choosing Green?
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of anti-establishment entertainment figures in a
variety of advertisements may be evidence of a shift in attitude
from earlier generations. The use of songs by popular bands like
the Red Hot Chili Peppers to advertise automobiles and Green's
serving simultaneously as celebrity pitchman and anarchistic
cable-television comedian suggest that today's fans do not view
such commercial activity as ``selling out.''
</P>
<P>
   The skinny Green _ seemingly the antithesis of an athlete _ was
actually carefully selected by Gillette to pitch a new product
called Right Guard Extreme Sport, developed with the
much-sought-after young male consumer in mind. Even the brand's
name capitalizes on a youthful trend _ the popularity of extreme
sports like bungee jumping, mountain biking and snowboarding. The
sports are definitely not in the mainstream _ which brings Gillette
to Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom stood out as a unique personality and often his character
is extreme,'' said Bernadette King, director of global business
management for antiperspirants and deodorants at Gillette in
Boston. ``He is free-spirited, high energy and always can make
people laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   In focus groups, Green came up as a person boys and young men
liked, King said, adding that additional research suggested to the
company that the best way to reach young men was through humor and
information they deemed useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really don't want to hear a product story, but they want
some product information,'' King said. ``They are saying, `Tell me,
give me a reason,' but they don't want to be bored to death and
they don't want anything too intense or too scientific.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the introductory campaign, like the comic, does not
take itself too seriously. The spots show Green, who is 28,
reporting as if live from Muscle Beach, where he appears to be
unleashing a trailer full of tigers on unsuspecting weight lifters
to create extreme conditions.
</P>
<P>
   As the tigers wreak havoc, Green mugs for the camera, claiming,
for example, to prove the product's effectiveness by rubbing
Extreme Sport on the forehead of a weight lifter trying to climb
over a chain-link fence while a tiger is pursuing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's great at shocking humor,'' said Al Merrin, executive
creative director at BBDO New York, the Right Guard agency, of
Green, who is in the midst of a well-publicized bout with cancer.
``There's a kind of sweetness about him; he gets away with the most
outrageous stuff. And the kids like it.''
</P>
<P>
   BBDO New York, part of the BBDO Worldwide unit of the Omnicom
Group, was looking for a new approach for the new product and
sought to avoid demonstrations of the drama and energy of extreme
sports, which have been commonplace in campaigns for brands aimed
at younger consumers like Mountain Dew, also produced by BBDO New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while extreme sports are popular as a backdrop for
advertising, celebrities of the sports have yet to be tapped by
corporate America, said Nova Lanktree, president of Lanktree Sports
Celebrity Network in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a lot of commercials, like car commercials, of wild
involvement between man and nature, but you don't see the face of
an extreme athlete _ they haven't emerged as stars and I don't know
why,'' Lanktree said. ``The sports are kind of wild, hip and fun _
very MTV, so I think you would get a lot of bang for your buck with
Tom Green if that's the audience you're targeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Right Guard has long been a top brand for Gillette, but its
sales, like those of the entire $1.7 billion
deodorant-antiperspirant category, are sluggish. Right Guard has a
9 percent share of the market, followed by Degree, made by
Unilever, with 8.7 percent, and Mennen Speed Stick, made by
Colgate-Palmolive, with 7.3 percent, according to Information
Resources Inc., a market research company.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette decided to go after the youth market mainly because of
its growth potential, King said, but it also recognized that boys
as young as 10 are interested in appearance and are a factor behind
the popularity of fragrances like Tommy. With that in mind, King
said, Extreme Sport is offered in light citrusy scents like Cool
Peak and Fresh Blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``In looking at the demographic trends, we saw a huge influx
coming of echo boomers,'' she added, referring to the so-called
Generation Y children of baby boomers. ``We want to make sure Right
Guard is their brand of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   But Right Guard is not alone. Speed Stick sponsors televised
coverage of the X Games and Gravity Sports. And last month, Mennen
reformulated and repositioned Speed Stick Ultimate to reach men
under 25, introducing fragrances like Glacier and Power Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Right Guard is not Green's first foray into advertising. Madison
Avenue was unusually swift in spotting Green, who only auditioned
for his MTV series in 1998. PepsiCo Inc. used Green in 1999,
shortly after his MTV show began, for a promotional campaign for
Pepsi One linked to the NCAA Championship tournament. Those
commercials, also created by BBDO New York, featured his antics in
visits to college campuses; they were well received, according to
executives at Pepsi-Cola, but Green no longer appears in ads for
the brand.
</P>
<P>
   The Right Guard Extreme Sport campaign is the first from BBDO
New York since the agency won the Right Guard brand account last
year from Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi in New York. Gillette plans to spend
$61 million in total marketing and advertising to introduce Right
Guard Extreme Sport in America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-06-00 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
