<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULES , WRITTEN AND UNWRITTEN , BROKEN OR NOT BROKEN , AT THE TOUR
DE FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOURS, France _ A controversial _ or maybe not so _ attack by 12
riders turned the Tour de France on its head Thursday, placing nine
supposed noncontenders high atop the overall standing and provoking
angry charges of not playing by the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it all on Jacky Durand, since everybody else probably
will.
</P>
<P>
   Was he the one who launched the attack when the man in the
yellow jersey, Laurent Jalabert, stopped at the side of the road to
urinate? Under the unwritten code of bicycle racing, which hardly
anyone has respected for years, riders are not supposed to speed
away in such a situation. (Nor are they free to do so when a leader
has crashed, although almost everybody does.)
</P>
<P>
   Leon Van Bon, a Dutch rider with the Rabobank team and the
winner of this sixth stage, denied that Jalabert had been betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four of us did attack, but when we realized that
Jalabert had stopped, we slowed down and were caught,'' Van Bon
said. ``We attacked again when he was back in the pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Bon was contradicted by the new man in the yellow jersey,
Alberto Elli, an Italian rider with Telekom. Poor Elli _ 13 years a
professional and the Tour's overall leader for the first time at
age 36, and the opening question he was asked in a news conference
was whether Jalabert had been in the bushes.
</P>
<P>
   Elli answered yes. He quickly added that he had not launched the
attack but had merely joined it. ``Somebody went off on the left
while Jalabert was stopped on the right,'' he said. ``Like a lot of
others, I joined the attack but I didn't start it.''
</P>
<P>
   A hard-working journeyman with some climbing talent, Elli is not
expected to hold the lead long. Nor are his companions expected to
remain in the upper reaches of the overall standing. But that is
just what was said in 1990 when a similar long breakaway left four
riders far ahead of the favorites, where some stayed for more than
two weeks of the three-week Tour.
</P>
<P>
   With Elli and eight of his 12 companions in the breakaway
ensconced atop the standing, Jalabert, a Frenchman with the ONCE
team, is now 10th, 5 minutes 40 seconds behind Elli. The other
major contenders are even further back, with Lance Armstrong, the
U.S. leader of the U.S. Postal Service team, in 12th place, 5:54
behind.
</P>
<P>
   In second place behind Elli by 12 seconds is the unsung Fabrice
Gougot, a Frenchman with Credit Agricole. Marc Waughters, a Belgian
with Rabobank, is third, 1:17 behind.
</P>
<P>
   Van Bon was clocked in 4:28.06 for the 198.5-kilometer
(123-mile) stage from the occasionally medieval town of Vitre to
the Loire Valley city of Tours in sunny and breezy weather. That
meant an average speed of 44 kilometers an hour (about 27 mph). The
main pack finished 7:49 behind, vaulting Elli from 21st place to
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Durand, a French dynamo with the Lotto team, was
suspected in the triumphant bolt at the 14th kilometer was his
habit of launching attacks anywhere at any time. This was a special
day for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allez Jacky.'' ``Allez Durand.'' ``Jacky Durand.'' ``Club
Supporters Jacky Durand.'' ``Allez Dudu.'' Durand's name and
nickname were writ large everywhere Thursday at the start in Vitre
because he is a native of the region, born and reared just outside
nearby Laval.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Durand needs no encouragement to attack. His
trademark is the long-distance breakaway, often solo, frequently
with a companion or two.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the tactic works _ he has won two French national
championships, two World Cup classics and three stages in the Tour
_ but more often it does not. Twice already in this 87th Tour,
which began Saturday, the Frenchman has stayed ahead of the pack
for long periods and then been caught.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was one of those days when he was not caught. No
sprinter though, Durand could do no better than 10th place when the
dozen riders finished and he now rests in sixth place over all,
3:27 behind Elli.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
