u i BC-BRITAIN-BLAIR-SON-NYT     07-06 0242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BLAIR-SON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDEST SON'S REVELS EMBARRASS BLAIR
</HEADLINE>
   (No byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Prime Minister Tony Blair, who has made a point of
keeping his four young children out of the news, was embarrassed
Thursday by front-page headlines reporting the arrest of his
16-year-old son Euan for drunkenness Wednesday night in downtown
London.
</P>
<P>
   Days ago, Blair called for strict measures against pub rioters
and drunken soccer hooligans. The police said they had arrested
Euan because they were concerned about his state.
</P>
<P>
   The police found him on the pavement in Leicester Square at 11
p.m. after he vomited and collapsed on an outing with friends
celebrating the end of exams. He was taken to Charing Cross police
station, where he gave a false name before his identity was
discovered, and officers from the prime minister's residence, were
sent to take him home.
</P>
<P>
   Blair issued a statement saying in part: ``Euan is very sorry
for the inconvenience he caused to the police, the state he was in,
and for the false statement he made. He is in no doubt of the
seriousness of it and the view that his parents take of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, Blair interrupted a speech to a convention
in Brighton to say: ``Well, being a prime minister can be a tough
job, but I always think being a parent is probably tougher.
Sometimes you don't always succeed, but the family to me is more
important than anything else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
