<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG RETAILERS SAY JUNE SALES WERE WEAK 
</HEADLINE>
   By KRUTI TRIVEDI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Squeezed by rising gasoline prices and discouraged by cool,
rainy weather, Americans put a brake on retail spending in June,
new figures showed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in stores open for more than a year, a crucial figure for
measuring the health of the retail industry, rose 2.6 percent for
the month compared with the period a year earlier, according to the
Goldman Sachs retail composite index. Except for March, when Easter
sales were delayed by a month, that is the lowest percentage
increase since September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As anemic as the numbers were, analysts said they were in line
with expectations that the economy was losing steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected to see a slowdown,'' said George Strachan, a
retail analyst at Goldman Sachs. ``The weather was bad. Fashion was
bad. Basically, it was a pretty bad month.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are not increasing their spending as much at all types
of stores, ranging from specialty apparel stores like the Gap to
discount stores like Kmart and department stores like Dayton
Hudson, a unit of Target.
</P>
<P>
   Much to the dismay of the merchants, consumers have shown an
increasing distaste throughout the year for buying clothes, in
particular. ``There's no question that apparel sales have slowed as
we've moved through the year,'' said Richard N. Baum, a retail
analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``We've seen a steady
deceleration in same-store sales. This month they were barely
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   In what could be another sign of a consumer slowdown, Federated
Department Stores, the parent company of the Macy's and
Bloomingdale chains, said its second-quarter earnings would be hurt
by credit card defaults at Fingerhut, its catalog arm. Fingerhut
sells merchandise mostly to lower-and middle-income Americans, and
credit troubles there could foreshadow more widespread consumer
woes.
</P>
<P>
   Even discount chains like Wal-Mart, Target and Kmart, which led
the booming growth last year, all reported moderate to poor sales
in June. Wal-Mart's sales increased 4.8 percent at stores open for
more than a year, but the rise was mostly a result of food sales,
analysts said. Target's discount stores reported growth of 2.1
percent, in large part because of difficulties with its women's
apparel business, a company spokeswoman said. Overall, Target's
sales rose 1.1 percent. Kmart fared the worst, showing a 1 percent
drop in sales, also because of problems with apparel, one analyst
said.
</P>
<P>
   Department stores and specialty stores also had difficulties.
There were widespread markdowns to get rid of excess inventory, and
analysts said such price cuts could eventually reduce profits.
</P>
<P>
   In the specialty retail sector, Gap Inc., which has been
struggling to get the fashion mix in its stores right for nearly
nine months, missed again in June as sales fell 2 percent. Sales at
the company's Old Navy division dropped by at least 7 percent, but
analysts said that was because Old Navy had phenomenal growth of
more than 30 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Gap also announced Thursday that it would miss earnings
estimates by 3 cents a share for the current quarter, but its
shares rose $3.75, to $33.625, because analysts expected the news
to be worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Limited, on the other hand, reported a 6 percent increase in
same-store sales, but its stock hardly moved. It continued to
benefit from its teenager-friendly Express division, analysts said,
but investors were less confident about the Structure and Lane
Bryant divisions, both of which reported decreasing sales.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few standouts in terms of sales. Neiman Marcus, for
example, pulled in more customers by having its annual men's sale
in June instead of May and by cutting back on its more moderately
priced lines. Its sales rose 17.3 percent. And Intimate Brands,
which reported a 9 percent sales increase, was bolstered by
lingerie sales at its Victoria's Secret Stores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
