<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-2006-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA LOSES TO GERMANY AS SITE FOR SOCCER'S 2006 WORLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for complete rewrite; note new byline.)   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a mild surprise, Germany was awarded the 2006 World Cup over
South Africa on Thursday as international soccer officials
apparently chose the certain success of the world's largest
sporting event in a European country over concerns of stability and
safety about post-apartheid South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Germany prevailed by one vote in a dramatic result that carried
much political soccer intrigue in Zurich, Switzerland, the home of
the sport's world governing body, known by its French initials as
FIFA. Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany said the victory
showed that his country was ``open to the world and hospitable'' a
half-century after Nazism and nearly three decades after the
slaying of Israeli athletes at the 1972 Summer Olympics in Munich.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, President Thabo Mbeki of South Africa called the
defeat ``a tragic day for Africa.'' Securing the World Cup was
being viewed as a way to help transform South Africa as it
continues to reshape itself from its recent past of
government-mandated racial separation by boosting national pride,
attracting hundreds of thousands of visitors and a billion
television viewers, adding several billions of dollars and more
than 100,000 jobs to the struggling economy and ameliorating the
concerns of skittish international investors. While rugby and
cricket are the national sports of white South Africans, soccer is
the sport of choice for the overwhelming black majority.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa had been host to the 1995 Rugby World Cup and the
1996 African Nations Cup soccer championships and believed it had
the necessary stadiums, infrastructure and technology to stage the
2006 World Cup. Instead, for the second time in three years, it was
denied a major international sporting event. In the fall of 1997,
Cape Town lost to Athens in its bid to be host of the 2004 Summer
Games as members of the International Olympic Committee voiced
concerns after Nelson Mandela left office as president of South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Alan I. Rothenberg, the past president of the U.S. Soccer
Federation who headed the FIFA committee that inspected the
countries bidding on the 2006 World Cup, said his group had ranked
Germany just ahead of South Africa in terms of preparedness.
Germany is an international soccer power, having won three World
Cups and three European titles, and it has Europe's strongest
economy. It also entered Thursday's voting with the firm backing of
the eight Europeans who are one-third of the 24-member FIFA
executive committee, whose main job is to award the World Cup. For
the 2002 World Cup, South Korea and Japan will be the co-hosts.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Brazil had withdrawn its candidacy and thrown its
support behind South Africa, reportedly in exchange for South
Africa's support of its bid for the 2010 World Cup. Joseph ``Sepp''
Blatter, the president of FIFA, had also thrown his public support
behind South Africa. England's chances disappeared with the
thuggish acts of hooliganism committed by its fans at the recently
completed European Championships held in Belgium and the
Netherlands. Morocco was never given a serious chance of winning
because the North African nation had a severe lack of necessary
stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say the vote was a mild surprise, not a shock,''
Rothenberg, who organized the most successful World Cup ever held,
in the United States in 1994, said by telephone from Zurich. ``We
felt for some time that it would come down to Germany or South
Africa and be very close.''
</P>
<P>
   Both countries were considered well qualified, Rothenberg said,
but increasing violence in South Africa appeared to make some
voters hesitant.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, nothing could be surer than having Germany or
any other major western European country hosting a World Cup,''
Rothenberg said. ``It's going to be enormously successful. South
Africa came down to people assessing in their heart that while they
may want it to go to South Africa, it is better to wait a while
longer. This new country is only six years old. Obviously it has
certain safety problems. We were satisfied after speaking with law
enforcement and security people that people would be safe going
there during the World Cup. We were satisfied; possibly other
people weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Thursday's voting was also affected by the
ubiquitous and complicated political intrigue that attends the
awarding of all major international sporting events. Three rounds
of polling were necessary before Germany prevailed with a majority
of votes from FIFA's executive committee. In the final round,
Germany prevailed by 12-11, with an unexplained abstention from
Charles Dempsey, a delegate from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   The South Africans claimed that Dempsey had reneged on a promise
to vote for them after England had been eliminated. His abstention
led to speculation that Blatter, FIFA's president, had orchestrated
the German victory behind the scenes even though he publicly
supported South Africa. Had Dempsey voted for South Africa, leaving
the result even at 12-12, Blatter would have been called upon to
break the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little bit sad that the executive committee had not
the courage to innovate,'' Blatter said. ``We have to trust Africa
and we have to take this decision. We have to take the risk,
otherwise they will never have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very strange, unfortunate,'' Rothenberg said of Dempsey's
abstention. ``He claimed he was under enormous pressure. So is
everyone on the committee. It's probably the single most important
thing you do as a member of the FIFA executive committee, vote on
the host of the World Cup. You make your vote and take the
consequences. Some like it or hate it, but that's life. You do the
right thing. I don't understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
