<SLUG> BC-GTECH-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: R.I.)  
 GTECH'S TOP TWO EXECUTIVES RESIGN AMID CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
  By GREG WINTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Gtech Holdings Corp., the world's largest lottery company,
said Thursday that its two top executives had resigned and that its
revenues would fall short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhode Island company said the departures of William Y.
O'Connor, chairman and chief executive, and Stephen P. Nowick,
president and chief financial officer, were a result of the board's
dissatisfaction with the unexpected revenue announcement, Gtech's
lagging stock price and the poor handling of a computer
miscalculation in Britain's national lottery that recently came to
light.
</P>
<P>
   W. Bruce Turner, a former gambling analyst who joined Gtech's
board last year, will step in as nonexecutive chairman. The company
said it had begun a search to fill the other positions.
</P>
<P>
   The company said revenue for the year would miss forecasts by
$15 million to $21.5 million. Two weeks ago, Gtech announced
first-quarter earnings that beat Wall Street's expectations by 12
percent, its best performance in more than a year. In speaking to
analysts and reporters then, executives gave no indication that a
revenue shortfall was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said news of the shortfall came as a surprise to the
board ``that we just learned about within the last few days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But forecasts are guesses, some of which are beyond your
control, some of which should not be out of your control,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said a recent decision by the Rhode Island Legislature to
cut fees for video lottery operators, a move that will deprive the
company of roughly $3 million this year, could not have been
anticipated. Nor could the company have foreseen a problem like
Colombia's postponement of its national lottery, which could cost
the company as much as $15 million in lost sales for the year.
</P>
<P>
   But Gtech also disclosed cost overruns for projects in Israel
and Australia. The company said it was seeking to determine the
extent of the overruns and whether they could have been avoided.
Gtech designs and sells computer systems for state-run lotteries,
and some analysts speculate that the miscalculated costs were a
result of inaccurate bids by the company.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the board's patience with O'Connor and Nowick
might have been stretched by their handling of other problems. In
May, Gtech came under scrutiny for a 1998 computer malfunction that
resulted in a miscount of the number of winners in Britain's
national lottery. The problem was fixed within a month, but neither
Gtech's board nor the company operating the lottery, Camelot, was
informed, Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   When he became chairman of Gtech in 1998, O'Connor was widely
viewed as a moral boost to a company that had become known for
ethical lapses. A co-founder, Guy B. Snowden, had resigned after a
British jury found he had committed libel against Richard Branson,
head of the Virgin Group. In addition to allegations that Snowden
tried to bribe Branson in connection with an effort to win a
contract to operate Britain's national lottery, Gtech had been
investigated for trying to influence politicians and lottery
officials in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor fired executives and installed a former FBI official to
oversee Gtech's compliance efforts. But while the moves helped
restore confidence in the company among potential customers, they
did little to lift its stock price, which fell from a high of $40
in 1998 to no higher than $26 over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Gtech's lackluster stock performance, despite its
relatively consistent earnings, is attributable to the slowdown in
new public lottery projects in the United States. With budget
surpluses across the country, few states have turned to lotteries
to generate revenue. Gtech already holds contracts with 28 of the
38 states that have lotteries, offering few opportunities for
sustainable growth, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, most of the company's efforts are now directed
overseas, where roughly half of all lotteries are not yet
automated.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Gtech fell $2.9375, to $19.8125, Thursday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
