<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PRICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE FINDS THE OLD TOUCH AS WOODS STARTS SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEMONT, Ill. _ In 1994, when Tiger Woods was still a teen-ager,
Nick Price was the best golfer in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Price won six tournaments in 1994, including the British Open
and the PGA Championship. Golf seemed easy to Price then, just as
it seems easy for Woods today. When Price played, he usually
contended. When he contended, he often won.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed for Price since his glory days. He has not won
a tournament since 1998, and at age 43, he sometimes wonders if he
will ever win again. That made Thursday's opening round of the
Advil Western Open special for Price. Tying the course record with
a 9-under 63 at Cog Hill Golf and Country Club, Price led by three
strokes over Jim Furyk (66), and by four strokes over Carl Paulson,
Steve Stricker, Stuart Appleby and Fred Couples.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Woods, playing his first tournament since winning the
U.S. Open, and his only tournament before the British Open later
this month, was at two under with an opening-round 70.
</P>
<P>
   While Woods struggled to find his putting stroke and squandered
birdie opportunities, Price was sharp. He shot a 30 on the front
nine and birdied eight of the first 11 holes. At that point, the
thought of shooting 59 crossed his mind. Instead, he settled for
the course record, which he shares with Jeff Sluman (1992), John
Adams (1993) and Dudley Hart (1998).
</P>
<P>
   Can Price play well enough for three more days to win the
tournament? He wasn't sure. But Thursday's round was a major
confidence lifter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed something like that because I've been floundering a
little bit,'' said Price, who is ranked No. 11 in the world but who
has not won since the FedEx St. Jude Classic in the summer of 1998.
``I got back on track today and had some good memories of times
gone by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between now and the next two years, I want to give it my best
shot, because at the end of next year I'll probably start slowing
down a bit. Realistically, not many guys have played well past 45,
and I'm 44 on my next birthday. So I better make the most of this
year and next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Price capitalized on superb iron shots that left him in prime
position for birdies. Six of Price's nine birdie putts were from
inside 10 feet. He made a 17-foot putt for birdie at No. 11. At
that point, Price was 8-under with seven holes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   If Price could have played the final seven holes at 5-under, he
would have shot 59, equaling the PGA Tour scoring record held by Al
Geiberger (1977), Chip Beck (1991) and David Duval (1999). Price
made par at No. 12, then barely saved par at No. 13, getting up and
down from a bunker. Price stopped thinking about a 59, but he made
one last birdie at No. 16, hitting a 7-iron approach shot that
stopped 18 inches from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Putting has been Price's nemesis in recent years, but he looked
solid on the greens Thursday. Price has fond memories of this
event, having won it in 1993 and in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through '93 and '94, when I was putting great, I could have
putted on peanut brittle, I would have made them,'' said Price, who
tied Woods for most tour victories during the 1990s (15). ``Golf is
like life. Sometimes things happen and you just can't explain them.
You question a lot of things when you're not playing well. It takes
you six, eight weeks to work into a slump. But it only takes one
good round to work out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods will begin Friday trying to chip away at Price's lead.
While Woods was fairly solid from tee to green, his putter acted as
if it were still on vacation. Woods missed potential birdie putts
from 10 feet at No. 10, from 12 feet at No. 13 and from 8 feet at
No. 18. Afterward he refused to blame his performance on being
rusty, or on letting down after winning the U.S. Open by 15 strokes
at Pebble Beach on June 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good, and I was ready to go from the first tee,'' said
Woods, the defending champion, who is attempting to win this event
for the third time in four years. ``Unfortunately, I just didn't
make enough putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods can make a seven-stroke deficit disappear quickly, and
Price is taking nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to get off to a good start, but there's a lot
of golf left,'' Price said. ``If I get in the hunt, I'll start
thinking about winning Sunday when I get to the back nine.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
