<HEADLINE>
NFL'S LANE SHOT DEAD IN HIS HOME; WIFE BEING QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indianapolis Colts running back Fred Lane was found dead in his
home outside Charlotte, N.C., Thursday afternoon. The police said
that it appeared that his wife had shot him.
</P>
<P>
   He was 24.
</P>
<P>
   The police released few details about the shooting of Lane, who
had been the Carolina Panthers' leading rusher before being traded
to the Colts in April. A police spokesman, Keith Bridges, said that
Lane's wife, Deidra, was being questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigation to this point has revealed that Deidra Lane
shot her husband during a domestic dispute,'' the police said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Chuck Johnson of the Charlotte-Mecklenburg Police
Department told The Associated Press: ``At this point there's no
arrest, there's no nothing. It's just an investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lane's father, Fred Lane Sr., said the couple had been
experiencing marital problems. Last March, Lane was named in a
domestic complaint filed by his wife. She said he had snatched a
necklace from her neck during an argument, causing her to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Lane's death comes at a time when the NFL has spent considerable
resources attempting to clean up its image and encouraging its
players to stay out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Lane was one of the most talented players in the short history
of the Carolina Panthers, having gained 2,004 yards with the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers suspended Lane for one game in 1998 after he made a
lewd gesture to fans during a game against the Jets at Giants
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Lane was indicted Wednesday by a grand jury in Jackson, Tenn.,
on misdemeanor drug charges related to an arrest Feb. 3. During
that incident, the police had found a loaded .22-caliber
assault-style rifle in the trunk of Lane's car after stopping him
for driving slowly on a side street. While searching Lane and three
passengers, officers found 1.3 grams of marijuana on Lane and 4
grams of marijuana on one of his passengers. Weapons charges
against Lane were eventually dropped.
</P>
<P>
   According to several NFL team executives, the Panthers had been
uncertain whether they could ever truly count on Lane, prompting
trade discussions with several teams, including the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams, those executives said, began their own background
investigations of Lane and ultimately shared the Panthers'
concerns, especially after hearing accusations that Lane had missed
at least one team flight and had been late or missed several team
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   While other teams decided not to trade for Lane, the Colts
thought they could rehabilitate his career. Lane was scheduled to
be the backup for the Pro Bowl runner Edgerrin James.
</P>
<P>
   His father said that Lane had spent the past few weeks in
Nashville, although he had visited in Charlotte briefly a week ago.
Lane flew from Tennessee to Charlotte on Thursday, just hours
before he was shot, his father said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These have been troubling times for the NFL and its players.
Another former Panther, Rae Carruth, the team's top 1997 draft
pick, faces a murder trial in the shooting of his pregnant wife.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Atlanta had accused the star Baltimore Ravens
linebacker Ray Lewis of complicity in the stabbing deaths of two
men after the Super Bowl. Lewis pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor
charge of lying to police investigators during his trial last
month, and murder and assault charges against him were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Player troubles away from the field were a major topic for NFL
owners at their winter and spring meetings. Concerned that its
image was being tarnished, the league expanded its violent crime
policy (now called the ``personal conduct policy'').
</P>
<P>
   The league now screens incoming players for potential problems
at the annual scouting combine.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be mandatory counseling for at-risk players as
well as the training of coaches by professional counselors to
identify those players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
