<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN: ON REMARRIAGE
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican affirmed its prohibition on Communion for Catholics
who have divorced and remarried, saying that many priests are too
lenient toward divorced parishioners. Remarried couples may receive
Communion, however, if they abstain from sex.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: PUZZLING TIGER DEATHS
</P>
<P>
   The government set up a team of experts to help investigate the
deaths of 10 tigers, including seven rare white tigers, in a zoo in
the eastern state of Orissa. Early post-mortem reports suggest that
they died of a parasitic infection, although suspicion has also
fallen on medication used to fight the infection.
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: EMERGENCY RULE EXTENDED
</P>
<P>
   Parliament approved the extension of a nationwide state of
emergency, giving security forces sweeping powers to arrest
suspects. The laws also give the government powers to impose the
censorship reordered by President Chandrika Kumaratunga last week
after the Supreme Court ruled that a previous censorship order was
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: FOOD POISONING
</P>
<P>
   The president of Japan's biggest dairy company said he would
resign after more than 11,300 people were afflicted with diarrhea
and vomiting after consuming bacteria-tainted milk. Government
investigators said workers at Snow Brand Milk Products Co.'s Osaka
plant failed to clean equipment properly.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: ELECTION CHALLENGE
</P>
<P>
   Charging that intimidation and vote-rigging may have skewed last
month's parliamentary balloting, the opposition Movement for
Democratic Change has decided to formally challenge the results in
28 of the 120 voting districts. Movement officials said the party
would file formal complaints with the High Court, requesting that
the results be thrown out. The Movement won 57 seats in the June
24-25 elections, the largest opposition win in 20 years, while the
governing party of President Robert Mugabe won 62.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: FARMS FOR SALE
</P>
<P>
   White farmers are offering to sell 400 more farms to President
Robert Mugabe's government for its black resettlement program,
bringing to 600 the number of farms made available to the
government this week. A farmers' representative said the government
did not need to pursue its land seizure plans because white farmers
were prepared to sell some of their land for a properly managed
resettlement program. Last month, the government published a list
of 804 white-owned farms it wants to seize.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: RESTIVE OFFICERS A junior military officer who
accused President Hugo Chavez of ``destroying Venezuela'' and
called for his resignation has been dismissed, and another who
criticized the president in a letter to his superiors is under
investigation. The videotaped statement by Capt. Luis Garcia, who
says he represents a ``patriotic junta'' within the military, came
as Chavez is seeking re-election this month and opposition groups
warn that discontent in the military is growing and could lead to a
coup.
</P>
<P>
   PERU: ADVICE REBUFFED
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto Fujimori said he had no intention of following
the advice of an Organization of American States mission that he
fire his intelligence chief, Vladimiro Montesinos. Montesinos is
blamed for directing a dirty tricks campaign against opposition
candidates in recent elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
