<SLUG> BC-JURORS-PAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GIVES JURORS A RAISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``n'' state news file.) 
 &HT;    By JASON KANDEL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A statewide raise in jury pay took effect this
week -- the first in more than four decades -- but does little to
adequately compensate jurors, court officials said, although it at
least recognizes their role in the justice system.
</P>
<P>
   One-day-service pay for jurors remains at $5 per day, but for
service beyond the first day, jurors will be paid $15 -- a whopping
$1.88 per hour for eight hours of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted,'' said Judge Jacqueline Connor, a Los Angeles
Superior Court judge based downtown, and co-chair of a jury task
force. ``But our goal is $40 a day, like the federal courts. This
is not the end of it. The money is not even close to being enough,
but this is an important statement of the symbolism in what they
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The pay increase, which took effect Monday, is one of several
ways in which the Judicial Council has been fighting to improve
jury service to encourage more participation.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Gomez, the Superior Court juror supervisor, was happy
when she heard the news but had hoped for a little more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be more delighted,'' she said. ``We really wanted
$40, but one step at a time, right?''
</P>
<P>
   This pay raise is just one of many recent improvements to
encourage participation. Some courts in the San Fernando Valley and
around Los Angeles County are already using the
one-day-or-one-trial rule, which allows jurors to serve on one
trial, or be called on one day and, if not chosen, dismissed.
Another plan in the works is to create opportunities for jurors to
ask questions of lawyers and judges.
</P>
<P>
   The raise was part of the 2000-2001 budget signed by Gov. Gray
Davis. The budget also provides for new court technology, a pay
increase for court interpreters, and improvements in court-based
programs for families and children. Judges will also get an 8.5
percent salary increase.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Ronald M. George, chairman of the Judicial
Council, praised the attempts to meet the needs of California's
courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Californians will benefit from the funding to increase the
pay of jurors, to modernize the courts, and to help the state
continue to attract and retain the finest jurists,'' he said. ``The
budget responds to many of the immediate needs of the courts and
provides support for long-term priorities set by the judicial
branch of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the provisions in the budget approval: certified and
registered court interpreters will get $265 a day; child and family
services will get $10 million; $506,000 was approved to establish a
three-year pilot program in which 10 civil departments in the Los
Angeles Superior Court downtown offices would be authorized to make
mandatory referrals of civil cases to mediation; $11.1 million for
half-year funding of 20 new trial court judgeships and 12 new
appellate judgeships; $56.4 million for court technology. Funding
was also provided to address negotiated salary increases for trial
court and court security personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Judicial Council will review the budget at its Aug. 25
meeting in San Francisco, where members will disburse funding.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
