<HEADER>
A5140 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-06 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS: A Change in Vacation Plans
</P>
<P>
   While political operatives and journalists fish for information
about the status of Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma in the
Republican vice presidential sweepstakes, Keating is actually set
to go fishing in Alaska next week. And it turns out that he was
supposed to have been accompanied by the man charged with helping
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas select a running mate, former Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney. A few days ago, Keating called Cheney and
offered to stay home, lest their trip set too many tongues to
wagging. But Cheney had already decided he was too busy to go. Even
so, the initial arrangements for the trip, made before Cheney had
assumed his role in the Bush campaign, demonstrated the many
connections and long friendship between Cheney and Keating. Cheney
has other Oklahoma ties: he is chief executive of Halliburton Co.,
a Texas-based energy company that has operations in Oklahoma, and
he was the national fund-raising chairman for the memorial in
Oklahoma City for the victims of the 1995 bombing there.
</P>
<P>
   THE CONVENTIONS: Diversity on the Dais
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to emphasize diversity, the Republican National
Committee has picked three members of Congress _ a Hispanic, an
African-American and a woman _ for leadership roles at the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia. They are Reps.
Henry Bonilla of Texas, J.C. Watts of Oklahoma and Jennifer Dunn of
Washington. Each will help preside over the convention and deliver
a speech. While the Bush campaign said Thursday that the
appointments symbolized Bush's desire for the party to become more
inclusive, the Gore campaign dismissed the appointments as being
more symbolic than substantial. Others named to leadership
positions are House Speaker Dennis Hastert, Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott and Gov. George Pataki of New York.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS: Collecting Cash
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee raised $60 million in the
first six months of the year, nearly half of it at a huge dinner
honoring President Clinton in May, a Democratic party official said
Thursday. The party had $30 million in the bank as of July 1, its
best cash position ever at this stage of a presidential race, the
official said. The Democrats raised $26 million in the first three
months of the year and $34 million from April to June. On May 24,
the party reaped $26.5 million at a single event _ a tribute to
Clinton orchestrated by Terry McAuliffe, the Democrats' most
prolific fund-raiser. The party has spent $12.5 million on
television advertisements pointing out differences with Republicans
on Social Security and prescription drug benefits for the elderly.
The Republicans have spent about $5 million so far on such issue
advertising.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE STATES: Primary Rules at Issue
</P>
<P>
   Citing a recent Supreme Court ruling, the head of the Democratic
Party in Washington State has threatened to go to court unless
state election rules are changed before the Sept. 19 primary to
prevent a ``blanket primary.'' Washington has long used such a
system, under which voters may choose any candidate for any party
in the primary and the top Democratic and Republican vote-getters
then face each other in a general election. But the Supreme Court
recently struck down such wide-open primaries in a ruling involving
California. Washington state's Democratic chairman, Paul Berendt,
asked the Washington secretary of state to create a new Democrat
ballot that does not ``contain the names of any candidate standing
for election as a nominee of any other political party or as an
independent.'' But Gary McIntosh, the state elections director,
said that the secretary of state lacked the authority to change the
system and that the old system would have to be used unless the
state Legislature intervened.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ No public events
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ Bridgeville and Burgettstown, Pa.
</P>
</TEXT>
