<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID COMMOTION, YANKS RALLY TO BEAT ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sunbaked afternoon at Yankee Stadium quickly
turned into a pitching barbecue. The left-hander Ed Yarnall, called
up from Columbus for Thursday's start, gave up five runs in the
first two innings on just 42 pitches. By the time the rookie
reliever Ben Ford stumbled out of the second inning, the Yankees
were trailing, 7-0, to the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. When the second inning finally ended, one hour 11
minutes after the first pitch of the game, the Yankees led, 8-7,
feasting on the four straight walks from the Orioles' starter,
Sidney Ponson, and getting a lift once again from Bernie Williams,
who extended his hitting streak to 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees then scored five more runs in the fourth inning and
rode out a 13-9 victory over the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Yankees storm into Shea Stadium for Friday night's
series opener against the Mets, having won four of five games,
Thursday's game showed that not even a fuel-injected offense can
hide the noise of a flat tire rumbling in their rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees devised two temporary plans to fix it. Before the
game, manager Joe Torre announced that he was placing a fragile and
struggling David Cone in the bullpen for safekeeping for the
four-game Mets series, moving up the Yankees' best pitcher, Andy
Pettitte, into what would have been Cone's start Sunday night at
Shea.
</P>
<P>
   And after the game, Torre dropped the bombshell that the Yankees
were calling up the 35-year-old Dwight Gooden from the rookie
league minors to pitch the first game of Saturday's doubleheader
against the Mets, marking the first time that Gooden will pitch
against the team on which he became famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's ever going to be an adrenaline flow, I don't think
there's going to be a problem getting up for the game,'' Torre said
of Gooden's return to Shea Stadium for the first time since 1994.
``It's familiar grounds to him, and hopefully it works on our
behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in talking about Gooden, Torre did not sound particularly
enthusiastic or comfortable. Gooden pitched for Torre and the
Yankees in 1996 and 1997, and after the Yankees then let him go,
Gooden took a swipe at the way Torre had used him. Now Gooden is
back, after a quick stint in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doc was recommended to us from down below and you have to go
on their recommendations, and we need a starter for Saturday after
last night and today,'' Torre said. The Yankees beat the Orioles,
12-6, Wednesday after building a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The struggling Ford was no longer considered a viable option for
a start Saturday. Nor was Jason Grimsley, who pitched in relief
Wednesday and Thursday, giving up two runs in each outing. The
rookie Jake Westbrook, who had two horrendous outings last month,
was unavailable because of a strained rib cage.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were out of alternatives, General Manager Brian
Cashman said. So they turned to Gooden, who has not pitched a major
league game in more than two months. He started the year with
Houston and was later picked up by Tampa Bay. Overall, he has a 2-3
record this season, with a 6.86 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden has thrown 12 strikeouts in two outings with the Yankees'
Gulf Coast League team in Florida since being acquired last month.
He has been tinkering with a new pitch, a cutter, to good results.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best choice,'' Cashman said. For now. ``I'm just
hoping for a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Torre, who described himself as ``a guy who isn't as
comfortable as he wants to be with our pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Yarnall showed his inexperience and nervousness within
the first minute, giving up a leadoff home run to Brady Anderson.
It was an omen for a long afternoon. ``I was struggling to get
ahead of guys,'' he said. ``I was worried too much about my stuff,
and when you do that, it unravels.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite trailing, 7-0, after an inning and a half, the
Yankees did not unravel.
</P>
<P>
   The big inning began inauspiciously, with Williams getting an
infield single on a ball that second baseman Mark Lewis didn't
field cleanly. Ponson then proceeded to crumble in startling
fashion, walking David Justice, Tino Martinez, Jorge Posada and
Scott Brosius in succession to force in two runs and leave the
bases loaded. A groundout by Jose Vizcaino scored one more run, and
a single by Chuck Knoblauch scored another to make the score 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles Manager Mike Hargrove then called for the right-hander
Jason Johnson, who is now 0-8 on the year, and he did nothing to
disprove his statistics. He promptly gave up a three-run homer to
Derek Jeter, the first batter he faced, that tied the score at 7-7.
Then Paul O'Neill swung at the next pitch and deposited it in the
seats for an 8-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, that lead did not appear safe. Mike Stanton
started the third and threw six pitches before managing to get a
strike across the plate. The crowd of 44,104 cheered when Stanton
got Luis Matos looking for the game's first strikeout, 74 minutes
after the first pitch. When Stanton left, three and two-thirds
innings later, he had allowed no runs on one hit. ``I knew I had to
come in and stop the bleeding,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees piled on more runs in the fourth, and they would
need them. Williams hit his 19th home run, a two-run,
opposite-field shot to left that put the Yankees up, 12-7. Even
Justice, who had had just two hits at the plate in six games since
becoming a Yankee, contributed, logging his first home run as a
Yankee and his 22nd of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
