<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BEGINS UPSTATE TOUR IN FAMILIAR SPOT, FOCUSING ON ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton returned Thursday to
an electronics plant that was the scene of an event during her
early days as a prospective Senate candidate last year. She talked
Thursday about reviving the economy in upstate New York and chose
this spot to begin a five-day tour throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton began her upstate campaign swing, her Republican
opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, was on the final legs of his trip. In a
meeting with about 100 workers at a Lockheed Martin electronics
plant and in speaking with reporters, she was quick to point out
the differences in her campaign tactics from those of Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got moderate talk on the trail and extreme rhetoric in
his mail,'' Clinton said. ``I just think it's hard to tell what he
means and where he is from day to day. I'm not going to respond to
his personal insults. I'm going to run a campaign on issues, not
insults.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Clinton reacted to a fund-raising letter sent to
voters this week by Lazio's campaign in which he attacked Clinton
and President Clinton for having ``embarrassed our country and
disgraced their powerful posts.'' Clinton, the letter states,
``covets power and control and thinks she should be dictating how
other people run their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has said he had not reviewed the fund-raising letter
before it was sent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking to reporters, said, ``It's hard for me to get
this straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week he was telling New Yorkers that he wasn't
responsible for his voting record,'' she said. ``And this week he's
telling us that he's not responsible for his fund-raising letters.
I think he ought to rename his bus. Instead of the Mainstream
Express, he ought to call it the Double-Talk Express.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news briefing outside a senior housing apartment
building in Syracuse Thursday, Lazio said he still had not seen the
letter and he continued to decline to specify what the president
and Clinton had done to embarrass the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can make a big distinction between a solicitation
letter for funds among your supporters and communicating with
commercials,'' Lazio said, referring to television advertisements
by Clinton's campaign that he has characterized as attack ads.
</P>
<P>
   At the plant, where electronic controls are made, Clinton met
with managers, took a tour and experienced simulated flying in a
military aircraft. Meeting with employees, she answered questions
on topics like transportation in the Southern Tier region of the
state and federal spending on research and development.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also attended a cookout with about 1,500 people in
Endicott, N.Y., sponsored by the Democratic Party organizations in
Broome, Tioga, Thompkins and Courtland counties. Her trip
throughout the region comes a year after she unofficially entered
the race for the U.S. Senate when she visited the farm of Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, whom she hopes to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   On this trip, however, Clinton is a full-fledged candidate and
her tour across the state's western half is focused on economic
issues. She has produced a pamphlet that is being distributed to
voters discussing various ideas, including tax credits for
investments in new technology and making high-speed Internet access
more widely available.
</P>
</TEXT>
