<HEADLINE>
NEW AMGEN FACILITY OK'D
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. _ The Food and Drug Administration gave
its approval Thursday to Amgen's manufacturing facility in
Longmont, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The 200,000-square-foot factory is approved to make Epogen,
Amgen's largest-selling drug, and Amgen officials said they intend
to seek the agency's approval to make NESP, Epogen's longer-dose
cousin, at the site as well.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen spokesman David Kaye said the company plans to transfer
its manufacture of Epogen to Longmont from its Thousand Oaks
headquarters, where the drug is now made.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen's Thousand Oaks manufacturing center also makes the same
substance for sale by Johnson &AMP; Johnson, which markets it as the
drug Procrit to cancer patients in the United States and worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of both products continue to grow, Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Thousand Oaks manufacturing operation will take
on the added duties of making some of the three drugs it hopes to
have approved for sale in coming months, Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building 6, where Epogen is now manufactured, is operating at
something like 15 times its original capacity. We have immediate
and future needs for additional manufacturing capacity,'' Kaye
said. ``We can triple the output that we currently have.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock analyst Douglas Christopher of Crowell Weedon &AMP; Co. said
the new factory will help Amgen achieve sales growth.
</P>
<P>
   Epogen brought in $1.76 billion in sales in 1999, and the
company predicts double-digit percentage growth this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say they'll come very close to -- if not surpass -- $2
billion (in Epogen sales) this year,'' Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   And once the FDA approves the sale of NESP, the company's
fortunes could rise further, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for NESP to open up the world to them, where
they're currently restricted from competing with J and J,''
Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   While some employees might voluntarily transfer from Thousand
Oaks to Longmont, the new factory is not a threat to local jobs.
The manufacturing activity will be transferred to other drugs as
they receive approval, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new manufacturing plant solidifies Amgen's future, said
Dennis Harp, analyst for Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason to expand into that facility was primarily to
provide commercial manufacturing for NESP,'' Harp said. ``It will
provide a commercial manufacturing facility for the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
