<SLUG> BC-SHOPLIFT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPLIFTERS BEWARE; NEW LAW MAKES REMOVING THEFT DETECTORS A
FELONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ If you can't beat
them, beat them some more.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas legislators seem to have taken that approach with a new
law intended to safeguard the electronic devices that stores attach
to merchandise to deter shoplifters.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-year-old Olathe, Kan., woman on Thursday became the first
person in Johnson County to be charged under the law, according to
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The law took effect July 1, making illicit removal of the theft
detection devices a felony. The law also makes it illegal to
possess a tool specifically designed to remove the theft detectors,
or to possess, make or sell bags coated with materials that prevent
the sensors from working.
</P>
<P>
   The devices trigger an alarm when someone tries to leave a store
without paying for merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Renee Adams was charged in Johnson County District
Court and appeared in court Thursday afternoon. She was released
from custody after posting a $1,000 personal recognizance bond and
was ordered to return to court July 13.
</P>
<P>
   Adams was arrested Wednesday after allegedly removing the
electronic detection devices from about $240 worth of clothing and
taking the merchandise from the Jones Store at Metcalf South
Shopping Center in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   The theft charge is a misdemeanor because it involves less than
$500 worth of property, but Adams is charged with a felony for
allegedly removing the theft-detection devices from the clothing. (
30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
