A5150 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-MOM-KAN &LR;      07-06 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN WHO TOOK HER TEEN DAUGHTER TO STATION CASINO IS CHARGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A woman who took her
16-year-old daughter to Station Casino Kansas City last month has
been charged by Clay County authorities with the misdemeanor crime
of permitting a minor to make a wager.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mother, Carla Jean Wilson, 41, of Ash Grove, Mo., near
Springfield, is well known at area casinos as a high roller. She
was charged with a class B misdemeanor that carries a penalty of up
to six months in the county jail and a fine of up to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Station is expected to be hit with a huge fine later this month
by the Missouri Gaming Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Casino regulators also said Thursday that they are investigating
at least one other area riverboat that is suspected of entertaining
the mother and daughter recently.
</P>
<P>
   Several Station employees who had contact with the girl have
been fired or disciplined, but casino executives would not disclose
how many employees were affected.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson did not return calls Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Her trial date has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   According to case documents, Wilson aided her daughter in
placing a wager in a blackjack game at Station on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   According to several sources with knowledge of the case, it
wasn't the only bet the girl placed that weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager, who is said to appear much older than 16,
presented false identification to casino employees during the
evening of June 9. Until Sunday morning, that fake ID fooled pit
bosses, bartenders, card dealers and others.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's age finally was challenged by a casino employee
Sunday morning, when the Gaming Commission was notified and an
investigation was opened.
</P>
<P>
   Based on previous incidents, Station officials can expect a huge
fine, or worse. Station's St. Charles, Mo., casino paid a $250,000
fine in 1997 after a woman and her 12-year-old daughter were caught
playing slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Meyer was fired by Station Casino Kansas City after it was
determined she issued the girl a player's card that allowed her to
enter the casino.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said Thursday that she hasn't found another job yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked working at the boat,'' she said. ``But I don't know if
want to go back into a situation like that again where these kids
can cost me my job again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so unfair to the (fired) employees,'' said Meyer, who
insisted she did everything she could to verify the young woman's
identification.
</P>
<P>
   John V. Finamore, Station's Midwest president, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``These employees were terminated for not doing their job,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He would not discuss details.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is the exception and not the rule,'' Finamore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minors who present false or altered identification to enter
the casino happens here every day. We card thousands of people on
Friday and Saturday night. I'm proud that we catch most of the
offenders before they even get on the boat.'' ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
